<HEADLINE>
KARIYA RETURNS TO ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Being the perfectionist that he is, Paul Kariya was
concerned with his performance upon his return to competitive
hockey Sunday versus Calgary at the Pond. The Mighty Ducks winger
was more concerned about that than taking his first hit in game
conditions since Gary Suter cross-checked him on Feb.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous, I wanted to get it over with,'' said
Kariya on Monday of his return. ``I got better each period. My
timing is still off, but that is to be expected, when you haven't
played in seven months.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rust, Kariya had nine shots on goal, scored an
empty-net goal and got an assist. He said he will need all six or
seven exhibition games in which he is expected to play to regain
his timing, but expects to be 100 percent by the time the regular
season begins on Oct.10 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya took hard several checks, including a blow to the head by
Calgary defenseman Sami Helenius, but said he ``felt fine'' and ``I
didn't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg said he didn't think about Kariya
getting hit until he actually was.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he took a couple of hits I watched to see if he was all
right, and he was,'' Hartsburg said. ``He has full medical
clearance and I don't think it will be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Fredrik Olausson, who missed the first week of
practice due to an enlarged spleen has received medical clearance
and has begun practicing with the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said Olausson will not play tonight against the Kings,
or Wednesday against Colorado. It's hoped he will be ready to play
either Saturday in Colorado or next Monday against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks and Kings will renew their Southland rivalry tonight
at the Great Western Forum, but Anaheim won't be heading down the
freeway with a full bus. Neither Teemu Selanne nor Kariya will play
in Inglewood. Both are scheduled to be back in the lineup on
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
