<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TRY TO RELAX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The three-game series against the Texas Rangers is
about the closest the Angels have been to playing in a playoff
series since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the Angels want the crowd into it to help raise
their level of play. On the other, the Angels are doing everything
they can to treat the games like any other games so they don't get
uptight.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I'll continue to do is make sure our guys stay
loose, manager Terry Collins said. ``I'll walk around and remind
them to relax and have fun, continue to plug along. I don't want
them to get caught up in all the pressure of `head-to-head'. If you
think this is tense, wait 'til you play in a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing the Angels keep reminding themselves is that no
matter what happens in the series with Texas, the division won't be
decided until the final four games of the season -- the Angels will
be in Oakland and Texas will be in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next seven days will be like the playoffs, center fielder
Jim Edmonds said. ``Even if we win two of three from Texas, we've
still got to win three of four in Oakland to solidify our place in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad started Monday's game even though his strained left
hamstring is not healed. Erstad ran from home to first and second
to home for Collins Monday afternoon and convinced him he was good
enough to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't play him ... We need him in the lineup, Collins
said. ``If I keep him out of the lineup the next three or four
days, we might not need him until March. I'm sitting here thinking
I may have to hold him out for the playoffs. But if we don't use
him, we may not get to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad said he didn't expect to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised, he said. ``When I went out there I was not
expecting to play. It actually hurts more now. I feel it when I
run, but it's not pulling, it's more like the feeling of a bruise.
The trainers said that's part of the natural progression of
healing.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Kreuter got his first start as an Angel in 1998 in the
club's biggest game of the season Monday night. With knuckleball
pitcher Steve Sparks' personal catcher Phil Nevin out with a
sprained ankle, Kreuter, acquired from the White Sox on Friday, got
the start.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter has caught knuckleballers before -- Dennis Springer last
season and Charlie Hough early in Kreuter's career.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Jim Edmonds has had a good September, hitting
.364 (24 for 66) with four homers and 17 RBIs going into Monday's
game. At times he has been the only Angel producing any offense.
And lately, he's playing defense like he did last season, when he
won his first Gold Glove. Edmonds made diving catches in key
situations both Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy's taking his game to another level, Collins said.
``That's what great players do. They have the ability to step up
their play.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said he rarely reads the newspaper, but last Friday he
read an article that noted he was the only Angel hitting during
their four-game losing streak. Later that day, a reporter asked his
about his hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone came and asked me about it ... he jinxed me, Edmonds
said. ``I had seven (bad) at-bats in a row after that. I'm not
talking about hitting anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Ken Hill threw a sideline workout Monday reported no
problems with his right elbow, which has been sore lately. Hill is
still slated to start Wednesday's game against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Paco Martin started at third base Monday instead of Troy Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things that went into that, Collins said.
``He's a good runner. And in a game like this I may have to do some
things with the bottom of the lineup. He can hit-and-run, bunt. And
he has good hands. I thought this would be a good day to play him.
</P>
</TEXT>
