<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPERSTOWN MAY NEED WHOLE NEW WING TO HOUSE 1998 HIGHLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He took the night off. So now Cal Ripken Jr. has put
his own historic stamp on the 1998 baseball season. He joins a
pretty cool club _ one that already had done enough to make this
season rival any as the best baseball has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Now, getting Ripken's No. 8 jersey from Baltimore to Cooperstown
should prove a little easier than the odyssey involved in
transporting Mark McGwire's stuff to the hallowed National Baseball
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   That is, it SHOULD be easier when Ripken decides to hand over
something by which the whole world can remember his awesome Iron
Man Streak, which ended Sunday at 2,632 consecutive games because
Ripken made The Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything from the record,'' Hall of Fame
spokesman John Ralph said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken has yet to present the Hall anything from that Sept. 6,
1995, night when he broke Lou Gehrig's consecutive game record of
2,130. So far, there is no indication about how or when Ripken will
satisfy the Hall's request to possess something from Ripken's last
game before he ended The Streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal has been very, how should I say this, patient in deciding
what he is going to do,'' Ralph said. ``We called the Orioles
(Sunday night) after Cal took himself out of the lineup and I spoke
to someone again. We're very hopeful, and Cal has always said he
will take care of us.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't this the summer of taking care of people? Hasn't every
bigger-than-life baseball god taken care of us, making this season
one that history should say outshines every other season?
</P>
<P>
   Probably the more-guarded and more-private Ripken now will be
moved to act swiftly on the Hall's behalf. It is tough not to be
inspired by the love and goodwill McGwire and Sammy Sosa have
inspired.
</P>
<P>
   After collecting every shred of clothing, leather and lumber
pertaining to McGwire's 62nd home run on Sept. 8 _ McGwire all but
stripped down to his underwear to make sure the Hall had what it
needed _ Hall of Fame president Donald C. Marr Jr. and executive
director of communications Jeffery Idelson were whisked 70 miles
from the airport in Albany, N.Y., to Cooperstown by police escort.
State troopers with lights flashing took McGwire's stuff to the
place where it will forever rest with stuff from Roger Maris and
Babe Ruth and Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the night before they left St. Louis, Jeff slept with
McGwire's bat in his bed at the hotel,'' Ralph said Monday, when
more phone calls and more jerseys were being sought to bolster the
Hall of Fame collection.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you are suffering the incredible and overwhelming
highs of this unbelievable baseball season, pity the poor folks
whose job it is to stock the Hall of Fame with historic
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph was with Sosa in Chicago when the Cubs outfielder became
the second this month to surpass Maris' 37-year-old record of 61
home runs in a season. He has spent a week with Sosa, and said Sosa
was very happy to have the Hall of Fame there with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the game, I went in to see him. He had just gotten
done saying he didn't really want to give up the bat, since he had
been hitting so well with it. But he did. He just kissed it a
number of times and then handed it over,'' Ralph said.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's bat _ now on display in a special ``Chasing Maris''
exhibit at the Hall _ sits in special company. A replica
old-fashioned scoreboard charts the homers day-by-day of McGwire,
Sosa, Ken Griffey Jr. and Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a private donor has loaned the Hall a uniform worn by
Maris at one point during the 1961 season, along with the bat and
ball from Maris' 61st homer.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's entire uniform is in glass, as are the bat, ball and
scorecard from Cardinals announcer Jack Buck. And the uniform that
McGwire's son, Matt, wore the day McGwire hit 62 also is featured
in Cooperstown now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked for that, since Mark and Matt have had such a special
relationship. We thought it was a neat human interest part of the
story,'' Ralph said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot of that going around this summer. Yankee
pitcher David Wells threw a no-hitter, so his cap went to the Hall
along with a Beanie Baby that was a giveaway at Yankee Stadium that
day.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the home run chase is getting down to the wire,
Hall of Fame representatives will go back out on the road to
collect more stuff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Mariners have been asked to send any of the
bats Griffey used to hit homers after No. 50, especially now that
Griffey has joined the elite company of players who hit 50 homers
and stole 20 bases. There will be a request for a bat or jersey
from Alex Rodriguez, who has become only the third player in
history to go 40/40 _ a feat now statistically more rare than
clocking 60 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Most important now for 1998, Ripken will have to ship something
off to the Hall. Ending The Streak might not have felt like lifting
a burden off Ripken's back. But lifting the No. 8 jersey off
Ripken's back and putting it into the Hall will forever put him in
the company of other fine men who, in 1998, gave baseball heart and
soul, and the shot at being the best season ever.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
