<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-HELLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING IS SORELY NEEDED BY RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tonight will be the most significant start
thus far in the professional career of Rangers right-hander Rick
Helling.
</P>
<P>
   The state of the American League West makes it so.
</P>
<P>
   Helling's state, though, remains in question before tonight's
crucial divisional game with the Angels at Edison International
Field of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who entered last night's games as one of only three
19-game winners in the American League, will likely pitch with
discomfort for the second time in as many starts.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old pitcher endured by far his worst performance
this season during his previous start Thursday against the Angels.
Helling, though, refused to use the injury _ stiffness and pain in
the upper left side of his back _ as an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   That will not change tonight, the Rangers' scheduled starter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't affect the way I pitch,'' said Helling, who will
attempt to become the Rangers' third 20-game winner during their
27-year existence. ``It's going to hurt. I know that. I'm just
going to have to pitch through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who recorded only four outs during Thursday's
appearance, surrendered six runs on seven hits and two walks during
the Rangers' 7-6 victory against the Angels at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Rangers might be that Helling (19-7, 4.54
earned-run average) experienced no major setbacks Saturday during
his bullpen session between starts with pitching coach Dick Bosman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boz said he threw the ball on his work day without any
problems,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``Well, I shouldn't
say that. It was with him, but he was able to make all of his
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling echoed the manager's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the same,'' Helling said. ``It hasn't gotten any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The status of Helling and right-hander Aaron Sele (18-11, 4.22)
serves as one of the primary reasons Oates chose to stay with a
five-man rotation during the season's final week.
</P>
<P>
   Oates last week acknowledged thoughts of removing right-hander
John Burkett from the rotation and pitching right-handers Helling,
Sele, Todd Stottlemyre and Esteban Loaiza on three days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   Helling and Sele, whom Oates described Friday as less than ``100
percent right now,'' made that option less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Helling and Sele have pitched 2081/3 and 2062/3 innings,
respectively. That represents single-season highs for both during
their professional careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a lot of guys struggling, tired and aching
this time of year,'' Oates said. ``That's part of being a
professional athlete. There are a lot of people aching when it
comes down to the end of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
