<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED TEAM REPLAYS 1996 SCENARIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After 156 games covering one of the hottest
summers in Texas history, you have every right to worry that the
Rangers, like a staggering marathon runner, have hit the wall a
week too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Check your memory bank: Weren't we agonizing over precisely the
same thing exactly two years ago, in this very stadium?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes history can be a cool, soothing hand on a fevered
brow. And if you're not running a raging temperature over this
pennant race, you're just not paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   There was a definite sense of haven't-we-been-here-before? as
the Rangers opened what manager Johnny Oates labeled ``the most
important regular-season series in this organization's history''
last night at Edison International Field.
</P>
<P>
   The deja vu crowd couldn't help but notice: The evening marked
the two-year anniversary of the day John Burkett won the most
important regular-season game in club history as the Rangers
snapped a five-game losing streak with a 7-1 victory against the
Angels on Sept. 21, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The stomach-churning skid, which included a four-game Seattle
sweep at the Kingdome, had seen the Mariners whittle the Rangers'
lead to a single game (and actually draw even in the loss column).
</P>
<P>
   Until Burkett's victory, and another by Ken Hill the following
day, there was serious concern over whether the Rangers had enough
gas left to finish the race after drawing out to a 10-game lead in
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   After winning two of three here in '96, the Rangers came home to
Texas to clinch their first-ever American League West championship
a few nights later.
</P>
<P>
   If the situations aren't exactly the same, they're close enough
to serve as a gentle, even comforting, reminder that Yogi's right:
It ain't over, till it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we tired?'' reliever John Wetteland echoed a question
before last night's game pitting two teams dead even in the
standings. ``You can ask every person in this room and get a
different answer. No, you'll probably get the same answer, but you
``should'' get a different answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a saying I like to use: You can be tired in November.''
</P>
<P>
   It becomes, Wetteland said, a matter of mind over body. Arms
ache, legs are dead, tortured muscles scream that they can work no
more. But there's a another game to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that this time of the season there are a lot of guys
tired, aching, hurting,'' Oates said. ``That's baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The infernal, baking heat of a Texas summer, however, might take
more of a toll than anyone realizes, Wetteland suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in Texas now for two years,'' Wetteland said,
``Nothing's like a Texas summer, I'll tell you that. Ain't nothing
like it. Some days are very, very difficult to get through
physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a tough road trip and you get home late and
have to show up early the next day to deal with a hundred-plus
degrees. All of a sudden it hits you. `What am I doing here? Gee
whiz, I'm exhausted.' Then you play the game and you see the
performance on the field and you understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not stuff I'm happy to admit. But when you see it and
it's happening before your very eyes in certain situations
consistently, you can't avoid what you see.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates has alluded to the fatigue he sees in his starting
pitchers, particularly Rick Helling and Aaron Sele, who have both
pitched more innings than at any time in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the fatigue you'd normally feel after 150-something
games,'' Sele said. ``You don't change anything. You don't reach
back for something extra. You just keep pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a lack of desire, Wetteland said. It's fatigue and that
can be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just takes an extra measure of mental discipline,'' he
said. ``You have to continue to apply yourself to the task. Don't
get caught up in the fact that your body feels like it can't do
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of how your body feels or how your mind feels when
you get to the park, prepare yourself for that day. You've got to
listen to your body and keep your finger on the pulse. This is a
long, long season, longer than any in sports, and sometimes you
just have to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, just when they looked as if they'd be pronounced
DOA by the time they got back to Texas, the Rangers found a
reservoir of energy and strength and finished the season with a
kick that left the Mariners eating their dust.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're faced with the same challenge. They can be tired in
November, and right now, that still seems like a long, long way
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
