<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE FAILS TO MAKE HIS CASE FOR THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a while, Andy Pettitte appeared to have found a
relaxation technique Monday night. He was as loose as Jell-O as he
settled into an easy rhythm, looking like a pitcher without a care
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Then the fifth inning hit him like a tension headache. And the
same Pettitte who has stressed over his performances for the last
six weeks _ wondering how safe his spot on the playoff rotation is
_ grew tight and ineffective when the first sign of trouble
disrupted him at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He could only look up at the night sky in disgust after giving
up a grand slam to Enrique Wilson, a substitute Cleveland player
who had just one home run on his major league resume. That was all
the ammunition the Indians and Charles Nagy (15-10) needed as they
defeated the Yankees, 4-1, and sent Pettitte to his fifth loss in
his last seven decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This was likely the last full start for Pettitte (16-11), who
may see only limited action in the Yankees' final game against
Tampa Bay on Sunday. While struggling for the last month, Pettitte
has been faced with questions about his role on the playoff roster.
He has had to ask himself what two pitchers manager Joe Torre will
decide to start behind David Wells and David Cone, with Pettitte,
Hideki Irabu and Orlando Hernandez to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   There was a look of concern on Pettitte's face this week when
Torre, who has admitted that he has been purposely vague about his
rotation intentions, acknowledged that Pettitte had a chance of
being left out. Before Monday night's game, Torre seemed to be
leaning in Pettitte's direction if for no other reason than his
playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy has done it more than Irabu has,'' Torre said. ``He has
more in the bank. He has done it in the post-season, winning some
big games for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm asked if there is a chance, there's always a
chance,'' Torre said when discussing the possibility that Pettitte
will be left out of the rotation. ``But don't make too much out of
my vagueness.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte could have erased the gray area with a solid outing.
But it was not a particularly reassuring evening for the
left-hander. He left the game down, 4-0, after 111 pitches and
seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   After working through four scoreless innings, Pettitte began to
unravel against some unlikely threats in the fifth inning. With one
out, he allowed Alex Ramirez to record his first major league hit,
which was followed by a single from the ninth batter in the
Indians' order, Elnar Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   Out of sorts, Pettitte threw a wild pitch in the dirt and
proceeded to walk Omar Vizquel to load the bases. Up stepped the
unassuming Wilson, a backup second baseman just up from the minor
leagues who has had three stints in the majors. Wilson sent
Pettitte's first pitch into a high arc just inside the right-field
foul pole for a grand slam that gave Cleveland a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte could only kick the dirt on the mound, look up and
shake his head in frustration. Once again, his stuff was failing
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want him to go out there and trust his stuff,'' Torre
said before the game. ``I do not want him putting this in a test
tube.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte has been inspecting everything, stressing over the
details of his mechanics for the last six weeks. Instead of letting
go of a poor outing he had against Kansas City on Aug. 9, he seemed
to obsess over it as he tried to figure out what went wrong that
day, when he gave up eight hits and four runs in five and
two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he began wrestling with his mechanics and
overthrowing. Trying too hard to do too much, he started gripping
the ball too tightly. Suddenly, his breaking ball was not breaking,
and batters were swatting away. The groove he had while going 12-5
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's earned run average has climbed from 3.54 before Aug.
9 to 4.30. Nothing has felt right for Pettitte of late. He lost two
consecutive starts in mid-August, picked up a victory despite
giving up five runs, and then was torn apart for six runs in two
innings against the Chicago White Sox on Sept. 5. Last week,
Pettitte's tumble continued when he gave up six runs in six innings
against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   His velocity has not been the issue, not when his fastball was
registering 93 miles an hour. If he could only relax.
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   Inside Pitch
</P>
<P>
   With a day off, Mets second baseman Carlos Baerga &UR;  &LR; was in the
Indians clubhouse to see his former teammates Monday ... Manager
Joe Torre &UR;  &LR; admitted he would be keeping close tabs on the game
between the Anaheim Angels and the Texas Rangers, but not
necessarily because the Yankees will play one of those teams in the
first round of the playoffs. ``Todd Stottlemyre's pitching for
Texas,'' Torre said referring to the son of Yankee pitching coach,
Mel Stottlemyre. ``It'll be tough if we play Texas. I told Mel to
remind his wife where the paycheck comes from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
