<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WHITMAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN CALLS ON CLINTON TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds list of Republican governors who have called for Clinton's
resignation, graf 5; adds 2 grafs at end to expand Whitman
quotation.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-PERJURY,
CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-MONICA, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC,
CLINTON-WATCH-NY, CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA,
CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA,
CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) (JT) 
 By JULIA PRESTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After watching the videotape of President
Clinton's grand jury testimony on television Monday, Gov. Christie
Whitman of New Jersey called for him to resign, saying that ``his
disdain for the truth is a national disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement she gave in the midst of a five-day trade mission
that brought her to Mexico with 30 executives from top New Jersey
companies, Mrs. Whitman, a Republican, said that she was most
offended by Clinton's argument that his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky did not fit a narrow legal definition of sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard some of the definitions about what applied to
whom when, it was just mind-boggling,'' Whitman said. ``I don't
know what I can believe of what this president says now or in the
future about this or any other issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that she had reached a personal decision after
catching portions of the grand jury videotapes on television in her
hotel room and at the U.S. Embassy here. She said she did not
consult with other members of the Republican Party about her
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Although at least a dozen Republican members of Congress have
called for Clinton's resignation, so far only four other governors,
all Republicans, have done so: David Beasley of South Carolina,
Kirk Fordice of Mississippi, George Voinovich of Ohio and Terry
Branstad of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans have worried that it might hurt their chances
in the next presidential election if Vice President Al Gore, who
has remained largely on the sidelines of the Lewinsky scandal,
steps into Clinton's position now. But Whitman said the political
calculus around Gore was ``immaterial'' to her decision.
</P>
<P>
   She made no criticism of Kenneth Starr, the independent council
who has been accused by Clinton and his allies of conducting a
prurient investigation into the president's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is of the president's own making,'' she said. ``He could
have put this to rest seven months ago. But now we can't put this
genie back into the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, speaking shortly after meeting with Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo, said that being in Mexico gave her an acute sense
of how Clinton's authority as a world leader has been ``seriously
undermined'' by the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   She said that if Clinton did not resign, she hoped that Congress
would conduct swift impeachment proceedings. ``I want to see this
issue put behind us,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
