</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MACLEAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACLEAN IS HOPING HE'LL FIT IN WITH RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John MacLean and Bruce Driver began their National Hockey League
careers in 1983-84, and for more than a decade grew to prominence
with a New Jersey Devils franchise that became a league power and
won the Stanley Cup in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Driver, a defenseman, left the Devils after that championship
season and finished his career with three unfulfilling years as a
Ranger. In 1997-98, as the Blue Shirts floundered and missed the
playoffs, Driver became a scapegoat for hecklers in Madison Square
Garden and retired last summer at age 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when guys you started to play with are starting to
retire,'' said MacLean, who will turn 34 on Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean, a right wing, stayed with New Jersey until early last
season, when he was traded to San Jose after 26 games. He was the
Devils' leader in games, goals, assists and points. Having joined
the Rangers as a free agent last summer, MacLean will try to help
revive the rebuilding Rangers on even-strength shifts and on the
power play. Garden fans are likely to scrutinize him carefully.
Their treatment of MacLean could depend on both his individual
performance and the success of the team that used to be his chief
rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to be judged on my play,'' MacLean said. ``I'm
making the commitment to helping the Rangers win. Nothing's forever
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   These circumstances could be starkly evident this week when the
two teams play a home-and-home series of exhibition games. They
meet at the Garden Wednesday night and at the Meadowlands on
Saturday. When asked whether he was eager to get the reintroduction
over with, MacLean replied: ``Yeah, I think so. I'm aware of the
situation, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing him in the red, white and blue of the Rangers will be
difficult for some Devils fans who remember MacLean's role in
pivotal Devils moments. One came in the final game of the 1987-88
season when MacLean scored against Chicago to force overtime before
adding the winning goal at 2 minutes 21 seconds of the extra
session. The victory put the Devils into the playoffs for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Although he still lives in New Jersey and counts many Devils
among his friends, MacLean said the realities of the business
occurred to him this summer when talking with former teammates.
Things weren't quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny game,'' MacLean said. ``Once you're gone, you're
gone.'' Another former teammate, defenseman Ken Daneyko, is likely
to be targeting MacLean for hard checks. ``I'm sure he will be,''
MacLean said.
</P>
<P>
   With a smile, he added, ``Kenny looked for me in practice'' when
they were teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, former rivals become allies. When the Rangers and
Devils last met in the playoffs, in the second round during the
spring of 1997, MacLean swung his stick and broke a bone in the
wrist of New York's Niklas Sundstrom. That put Sundstrom out for
the rest of the playoffs and damaged the Rangers' chances of
upsetting Philadelphia in the third round. The Flyers eliminated
the Rangers in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologized,'' MacLean said, referring to Sundstrom. ``He's
comfortable. I'm comfortable. I felt terrible about it. We're over
that. When it all came down, I felt bad about it. It was an
unfortunate incident, something I'm not proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one new teammate made him feel welcome with a gracious
gesture. Through his career, MacLean has worn the No. 15 while
scoring 360 goals in 15 seasons. In Ranger colors, that number
belonged to Darren Langdon, who gave it to MacLean at the start of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unexpected,'' MacLean said. ``Darren gave it up.''
MacLean seemed grateful for the favor. ``I've had a lot of success
with that number,'' he said. ``Athletes tend to be superstitious.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first appearance as a Ranger at the Garden, in Sunday
night's 4-2 loss to Carolina, MacLean had no goals or assists. But
he looked comfortable on the power play, taking passes from Wayne
Gretzky and Brian Leetch that created scoring chances. As a
right-handed shooter, MacLean could be a crucial component of the
attack with the manpower advantage because a right-handed forward
can stand to the left side of the goal crease, which is smaller
this season, take passes from the right side and from behind the
goal line and one-time the shot without stopping the puck to tee it
up.
</P>
<P>
   At even strength, Ranger coach John Muckler wants an up-tempo
style of puck pressure in which his players will try to force
turnovers outside their blue line. The approach is radically
different from the Devils' style of waiting back passively in a
neutral-zone trap. Noting that MacLean scored 3 goals with the
Devils and 13 with the Sharks, Muckler suggested he might produce
more this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can score more than he did last year,'' Muckler said. ``He
won't be playing in Jersey. There was a disappointment there. He
didn't produce in the manner he could. He's an excellent checker,
but we want to use him in an offensive role.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0011 </DOCNO>
