<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRUGS-CHILDREN-640     09-22 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUGS-CHILDREN-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 CRACK'S EFFECT ON BABIES IS REAL, EXPERTS SAY, BUT REVERSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the first babies were born to crack addicts in
the mid-1980s, images of trembling infants with tubes up their
noses led to fears that such children were irreversibly damaged and
doomed to grow into violent misfits.
</P>
<P>
   The dire predictions failed to materialize by the early 1990s,
prompting a different conclusion: that cocaine causes no lingering
effects on children born to drug-addicted mothers. Instead, it was
asserted, whatever problems the children had could be attributed to
poverty and other environmental factors.
</P>
<P>
   Now many pediatricians and other child development specialists
who work with these children believe that the complex truth lies in
between.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run the risk of the pendulum swinging the other way and
saying, no, it's not cocaine, it's all the environment,'' said Dr.
Barry Lester, a professor of psychiatry and pediatrics at Brown
University School of Medicine. ``That would be a tremendous
disservice to thousands of children out there who need special
intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   While the specialists disagree about the extent and duration of
the damage caused to infants by cocaine, they do agree that early
intervention can help reverse any damage, whether it is caused by
drugs or bleak surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not doomed children,'' said Dr. Evelyn Davis, a
behavioral development pediatrician at Harlem Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   The studies of these children have been hindered by the mothers'
often rootless lives and the scattering of children into adoptive
and foster homes. But the lack of authoritative research has not
stopped one state, South Carolina, from prosecuting women for using
crack cocaine while pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is hardly academic for New York City, where crack
cocaine remains the most common street drug, and 15,371 newborns
tested positive for cocaine from 1988 to 1994, according to the
city Department of Health. They accounted for 1 percent of the
city's recorded births in 1994, down from a high of 2.3 percent of
the births in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute on Drug Abuse has estimated that in 1992,
45,000 women nationwide used cocaine during their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year or so, it has become clear that cocaine can
affect the developing brain,'' said Dr. Alan I. Leshner, the
institute's director.
</P>
<P>
   Leshner said the evidence emerged after researchers who tested
the effect of cocaine on laboratory animals compared notes with
clinicians who examine children for medical, learning and
behavioral disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The problems can be treated, Leshner said. ``We don't want to
stigmatize these kids as a lost cause, but at the same time we
should not ignore that some of them have serious problems that need
to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been difficult to isolate crack's effect on babies
exposed in the womb because mothers who use cocaine also often
ingest alcohol, marijuana or even heroin. Pregnant addicts also
tend not to eat properly or get prenatal care.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues alone, without cocaine, could cause children to
develop poorly,'' Lester said. ``What cocaine becomes is a form of
double jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture may become clearer within a few years, after the
National Institutes of Health completes a wide-ranging maternal
lifestyle study involving 1,400 children born to drug users.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, previous smaller studies have yielded sometimes
contradictory evidence. For example, Brown University School of
Medicine conducted a study in 1996 of 1- and 2-day-old babies of 57
mothers, 20 of whom smoked crack during pregnancy. The study found
that the cocaine left infants tense and jittery after the sound of
a rattle or bell, or, alternatively, lethargic and indifferent. But
the study found no proof that cocaine in the womb inflicted
hemorrhages, lesions or other physical damage to the infants'
brains.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another New York doctor, Daniel Neuspiel, followed 250 babies
exposed to cocaine, tracking them for three to six years at North
Central Bronx Hospital, before his program ran out of money. He
found that the newborns were irritable, showed a quicker heartbeat
and had trouble eating and sleeping, but he said these symptoms
wore off after 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't observed persistent problems related to
cocaine,'' said Neuspiel, now a pediatrician at Beth Israel Medical
Center. ``The only consistent findings I've seen have been more in
their growth _ reduced birth weight, premature labor, smaller head
circumference.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester, who maintains a computer database of published research,
drew a somewhat different conclusion. He cited a statistical
summary concluding that the IQs of children exposed before birth to
drugs like heroin and cocaine run an average 3.26 points lower than
those of other children. The disparity is doubled, he said, in
measuring the children's ability to understand and express
language.
</P>
<P>
   Some pediatricians who work with inner city children have
noticed similar problems. From 1987 to 1996, Davis saw 530 young
children at Harlem Hospital Center who were exposed to cocaine in
the womb. Nearly half the children were born prematurely, a
condition to which she attributed at least some of their abnormal
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Davis reported that a third of the children experienced sleep
disturbances, nearly two-thirds had delayed language skills and
slightly more than half had delayed motor skills. One-third also
suffered from hyperactivity and attention deficit disorder, and two
out of five displayed behavioral disturbances. Only 12 percent of
the children were still with their mothers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine does not ravage every pregnancy where it is detected,
any more than alcohol does, but there is evidence that it can cause
problems, said Dr. Herbert Kleber, an addiction psychiatrist who
served in the Office of National Drug Control Policy under the Bush
administration. He is now a cocaine researcher and a professor of
psychiatry at Columbia University's College of Physicians and
Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists generally agree that cocaine increases the risk of
premature birth. Dr. Farrokh Shahrivar, the chairman of neonatology
at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center and Beth Israel Medical
Center, has examined newborns after delivery for 30 years. ``The
devastating effect of crack causes premature labor, separation of
the placenta, higher morbidity and mortality, a low birth weight
and other problems related to prematurity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kleber cited numerous studies showing that cocaine distorts the
sensitivity of receptors in the brain. And the immaturity of a
fetus' central nervous system, he said, makes it more vulnerable to
chemicals than an adult's.
</P>
<P>
   The effects are real but subtle, Kleber said. ``They could be
worsened or improved by many environmental factors, but that's true
of many conditions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vulnerability of such children has prompted the intervention
of programs like Hale House in Harlem, which has provided a home
and treatment to more than 3,000 infants exposed to illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly do manifest problems,'' said Lorraine Hale, a
child development specialist who is president of Hale House. ``They
are cranky and, as they get older, their tendency is to get quite
moody.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hale has also marveled at their resilience. ``We thought
that the children would be a heck of a lot more damaged,'' she
said. ``We were pleasantly surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dreitzer Women and Children's Treatment Center in East
Harlem, which is run by Project Return, a drug rehabilitation
network, the debate has not been lost on the mothers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When Glenda C., a patient at Dreitzer, was pregnant and smoking
crack, she did not need a study to convince her that cocaine was
bad for her baby. ``I said, God, please encamp angels around my
unborn child,'' Glenda said. ``Every time I got a hit, I would
throw up. It was like she was rejecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her observations about her 17-month-old daughter echo the
sometimes ominous, sometimes heartening findings of the medical
studies. ``They say that babies whose mothers are using crack are
very sensitive and easily upset,'' she said. ``I notice that my
daughter is sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, she added, ``I look at all the kids around here and
most of them seem to be doing just fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
