<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FOSTER-PARENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW RESPECT FOR FOSTER PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   A federal district judge in New York City has taken an important
step toward recognizing the special relationship that exists
between long-term foster parents and children they are seeking to
adopt. The case stemmed from a caseworker's abrupt removal of a
4-year-old boy from the Bronx home of a foster mother who had cared
for him since he was a month old, and who was in the final stages
of the adoption process. The adoption was eventually approved, but
the foster mother sued anyway, arguing that her due process rights
had been violated when the city denied her a prompt hearing as well
as visitation rights.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kimba Wood agreed. Her 50-page opinion asserted a
``constitutionally protected liberty interest in the stability and
integrity'' of the relationship between the foster mother and
child, and found that the city had indeed violated the mother's
right to due process.
</P>
<P>
   Wood carefully applied her ruling to a relatively small class of
foster children whose birth parents' rights have already been
terminated, and to foster parents who have cared for their foster
children continuously for more than a year and who have agreed to
adopt them. But the decision sends a broader message of respect for
parental relationships that are often more important in a child's
life than biological bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
