<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HAVE EXCUSES, BUT THE GIANTS NEED THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Dallas Cowboys played the entire
game without their usual starting quarterback, Troy Aikman. They
played the second half without their best running back, Emmitt
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   At different times in Monday night's game against the Giants,
Deion Sanders, who scored two touchdowns in a virtuoso performance
as an offensive, defensive and punt-returning star, went to the
locker room because he was dehydrated. And Leon Lett, Dallas' best
defensive lineman, missed part of the game because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the Cowboys' excuses for playing poorly. But they
didn't need them.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who could use the excuses, played their worst game
since this time last year, when they opened the season by losing
three of their first four games.
</P>
<P>
   A dominating performance by the Cowboys Monday night in a 31-7
victory at Giants Stadium has temporarily shifted the balance of
power in the National Football Conference East.
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion Giants (1-2) have stumbled to an uneven,
skidding start. The Cowboys (2-1) have assumed the division lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first division loss for the Giants since 1996 and
ends a nine-game undefeated streak in the division. The Cowboys'
victory also makes them 6-0 against the Giants in Monday night
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense generated just 56 yards rushing while their
defense failed to create a turnover, or register a sack, and
allowed Dallas' quarterback, Jason Garrett, playing in place of the
injured Aikman, to complete 12 of 28 passes for 224 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' running attack, which the coaches had vowed to
improve this week, looked worse than ever. Fullback Charles Way was
the team's leading rusher with 26 yards on 9 carries.
</P>
<P>
   On third down, the Giants converted 4 of 16 attempts, continuing
their season-long struggle on third-down conversions.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 minutes and 25 seconds left in the fourth quarter,
Sanders intercepted Kanell and ran 71 yards for his second
touchdown of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell finished the game with 25 completions in 45 passing
attempts with 228 yards. He was intercepted twice.
</P>
<P>
   During the previous week of practice, the Cowboys worked on
including Sanders in the offense for the first time this season.
Sanders returned a punt for a touchdown in the second quarter, but
didn't have much impact from scrimmage offensively until the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After missing a portion of the second quarter because of
dehydration, Sanders, in one of the few times he was on the field
as a wide receiver, helped the Cowboys extend their 10-point
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders caught a 55-yard pass from Garrett, splitting the
Giants' defense as free safety Tito Wooten let Sanders get behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, running back Sherman Williams sliced through a
massive hole in the middle of the Giants' defense, dashing 18 yards
into the end zone for a 24-7 Dallas lead.
</P>
<P>
   All of the first-half scoring came in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, always dramatic, brought an end to a scoreless struggle
2:29 into the second quarter. His spectacular 59-yard punt return
for a touchdown gave the Cowboys a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders caught Brad Maynard's punt near the middle of the field
and initially broke left. Hemmed in by the Giants' pursuit, Sanders
reversed his field. He side-stepped in succession diving tackle
attempts by Greg Comella, Corey Widmer and Doug Colman.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the corner, Sanders received some good blocks from his
teammates as he headed up the sideline. Maynard was the last Giant
with a chance, though he was encircled by three Cowboys and never
got close to Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sanders' fourth punt return for a touchdown in the
National Football League and the 15th time he has scored on a
return of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:54 to play in the first half, the Giants finally showed
some life. A 36-yard touchdown pass from Kanell to Amani Toomer
tied the game and completed a nine-play Giants drive, their best of
the half.
</P>
<P>
   Twice on third down in this possession, the Giants kept their
drive alive _ Kanell finding Chris Calloway for a 14-yard pass
completion once and scrambling for 6 yards and a first down on
another third-down play.
</P>
<P>
   On the touchdown, Toomer burst past Dallas cornerback Kevin
Smith, making the catch at the goal line on a perfectly thrown pass
by Kanell. It was the high point of the Giants' night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys regained the lead a little more than a minute later.
Garrett, playing for the injured Troy Aikman, threw the ball deep
down the middle of the field for wide receiver Billy Davis. As
Davis caught the football, Wooten flung himself at Davis' head and
shoulders in an attempt to make a tackle. Wooten missed Davis
entirely, but did knock two other Giants defenders, Percy Ellsworth
and Phillippi Sparks, out of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Free of the Giants' secondary, Davis sliced down the heart of
the playing field for an 80-yard touchdown and a 14-7 Dallas lead.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-yard Richie Cunningham field goal with 7 seconds left in
the first half gave the Cowboys a 17-7 lead at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's kick was set up by a 19-yard pass interference
penalty on Sparks and a 10-yard completion from Garrett to Michael
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, like the Oakland Raiders a week ago, seemed
prepared for most of the Giants' bread-and-butter plays _ the runs
inside to Charles Way and the short passes out of the backfield to
Way and Barber. And there was little unpredictable about the
Giants' early play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   There was the occasional new play _ like a reverse run for
Toomer, with Toomer lofting a pass over the head of Ike Hilliard
along the sideline. But too often, the Giants ran for small gains
and passed underneath the Cowboys' deep coverage for equally modest
pick-ups. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS &LR;      09-22 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
It won't become an issue until the season is over, but it's a
question everyone who cares anything about the Astros is dying to
have answered.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Moises Alou staying or going?
</P>
<P>
   Because he was traded to the Astros after signing a multiyear
deal with the Florida Marlins, Alou has the right to demand a trade
at the end of the season. And if the Astros don't trade him, he
could become a free agent March 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rest easy, Astros fans. The team's star left fielder isn't
champing at the bit to get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Dominican (Republic) gets a franchise, I'd demand a
trade for sure,'' Alou wisecracked about his native country. ``But
as of now, I just want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   When last we checked, expanding into the Dominican was not on
baseball's agenda, so chances are good Alou will be sporting the
open-star logo on his cap next season. Nevertheless, his status
figures to be an issue after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something a lot of people have been asking me, and I
have to be real careful about what I say,'' said Alou, who leads
the Astros in home runs (38) and RBIs (122). ``Every day, I feel
different. The guys have treated me real well here, and I love
playing with these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the way they go about their business. It's really
been fun this year, and it's already September. It just seems like
two weeks ago when I was at the (horse racing) track in the
Dominican. Now, it's almost time to go back. That's the way it is
when you're having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like? Alou has realistic expectations of being the
key player on a World Series championship team for the second year
in a row. Last year, he was voted Most Valuable Player of the
Florida Marlins, who defeated the Cleveland Indians in the Fall
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Marlins owner H. Wayne Huizenga dismantled
the team for financial reasons. When Alou meets with Astros
management after this season, he will be looking for assurances
that owner Drayton McLane Jr. will continue to be committed to
putting a championship-caliber team on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McLane is a lot nicer guy than Mr. Huizenga,'' Alou said.
``(McLane) loves to win. He wants to be a champion. I don't think
he will stop trying. I haven't known him for that long, but if he
wins, I think he would want to do it again. He wants to be a
champion so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to talk after the season and see what happens. I
like it here, and I like it a lot. But we still have three weeks to
go _ more, hopefully _ and a lot of things can happen between now
and then. Winning is going to make a lot of difference in what I
do. If we win it all, I'll beg to come back to Houston. If we don't
(win it all), we'll talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see where this team is going. To me, it looks
pretty good. We have a new stadium coming, and I'm sure they would
like to go to the new stadium with a good team. Winning and having
a good team is something I'd like to see, if they want me to stay.
But I don't know if they're going to want me to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful the Astros would have traded pitching prospects
Oscar Henriquez, Manny Barrios and Mark Johnson if Alou weren't in
their long-range plans. The 32-year-old outfielder has three more
years and an additional $15 million on his contract, and the Astros
plan to see him patrolling left field in the new Ballpark at Union
Station, which is scheduled to open in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moises has been absolutely tremendous,'' general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said. ``We hope he will continue to be a part of this
ballclub. But now is not the time to comment on that situation,
because it's not an issue right now, certainly not on the eve of
the postseason. We're prepared to sit down after the postseason,
and if that situation presents itself, we'll address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou and his family have found Houston to their liking, and he
said he would not look forward to playing for a fourth team in four
years, although early speculation has linked him to Los Angeles if
the Dodgers can lure his father, Felipe, away from Montreal as
their manager.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, that's pure speculation. Alou is contractually
bound to the Astros for another three years, and he realizes they
don't have to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my choice (to demand a trade),'' Alou said. ``But they
have a choice, too. They can do whatever they want with me. I don't
know if they like my personality here, but if they don't, I feel
like I can get a job somewhere next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's personality seems to be more an issue for the fans and
media than for his teammates and employers, with whom he has gotten
along famously in his first Astros season. But those who make their
living thrusting notepads and cameras into Alou's face have done so
with mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that,'' Alou said. ``The press has to
understand that you're a human being and that sometimes you need
time to be alone and that you need time to be at your locker by
yourself. They need to understand that sometimes you didn't have a
good game, and there's no reason why you should be talking to the
press.
</P>
<P>
   ``That probably costs me a lot of (All-Star and MVP) votes, fans
and maybe even money. But my job here is to produce. If I'm doing a
good job, playing hard and we're winning, then I'm happy. I hate to
lose, and I hate it when we don't play the way we're supposed to
play. I hate when someone is scared to play or when someone doesn't
give 100 percent. I hate when we don't make the right moves.
There's a lot of things that I hate. No. 1 for me is my family.
After that, it's what I do here (on the baseball field). What
people think about me is way down there on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a flashy guy. I may not be a press favorite because of
my personality, but one thing I know is how to play, how to win and
how to get along with these guys, and that's very important. There
are a lot of things more important to me than earning fans. I know
I'm a good guy, and I know I'm a friendly guy, but a lot of people
have a different perspective about my personality and the way I am.
If you ask around and ask people in the game, they'll say positive
things about me.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Alou has positive opinions about returning to Houston,
and the Astros hope that's the way it stays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
