<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS THROTTLE ANGELS, 9-1, TAKE AL WEST LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates remains convinced
that pitching will determine the American League West title.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching, though, relies greatly on dependable defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that facet _ one of Oates' greater sources of concern the
past 25 weeks _ was the essential element of the Rangers' 9-1
victory against the Angels last night at Edison International Field
of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played almost flawlessly in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, the vastly superior defensive unit for the past 25
weeks, did not.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, save one fifth-inning error by center fielder Tom
Goodwin, made every play behind right-hander Todd Stottlemyre, who
pitched seven scoreless innings for his fifth victory in nine
decisions since being acquired July 31.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth consecutive start of seven innings or more for
Stottlemyre, who improved his earned-run average to 2.10 in four
September appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers will play the Angels tonight leading the
division by one game with six remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not change my stance: If we pitch well, we will win,''
Oates said. ``I've been saying that for six months now.''
</P>
<P>
   Superior defense cultivates well-pitched ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   Angels right-hander Steve Sparks (9-4) witnessed how detrimental
plays not made can be during his 32/3-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, whose .984 fielding percentage ranked behind only
the Orioles and Devil Rays before yesterday, gift-wrapped two and
perhaps as many as five runs before Sparks' premature departure.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' woes in the field began with a first-inning ground
ball that second baseman Randy Velarde misplayed, and it resulted
in the first of two unearned runs charged against Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore reached on Velarde's
one-out error and advanced to third and later scored on singles by
left fielder Rusty Greer and right fielder Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Chad Kreuter, whom the Angels acquired Saturday, joined
the defensive malaise in the second inning. Rangers first baseman
Lee Stevens led off the inning with a single and attempted to score
on a double to right-center field by third baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   The throw to the plate by Velarde appeared to be in time to
retire Stevens, but Kreuter failed to control the ball after
contact from the sliding runner. Zeile advanced to third as the
ball rolled away from Kreuter, and that proved costly. Sparks, who
relies on the knuckleball, issued a two-out wild pitch that allowed
Zeile to score the Rangers' second unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks contributed to the Angels' woes by failing to cover first
base on a poorly hit, fourth-inning ground ball by Zeile. Velarde
went into the hole to retrieve the ball, but Zeile beat the pitcher
to the bag for a one-out, infield single.
</P>
<P>
   The out not recorded was a significant contributor to the
Rangers' two-run fourth inning. Zeile advanced to third on a double
by shortstop Royce Clayton and scored on a sacrifice fly ball by
Goodwin that should have been the third out. Clayton scored on a
two-out single by Greer, and the Rangers never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ensures that the Rangers will leave Anaheim no worse
than one game behind the Angels before their four-game,
season-finale series against the Mariners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
