<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     09-22 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There are good times and bad times. There
is wartime and peacetime. There is big-time and small-time. There
is teatime and mealtime. But only one Prime Time. Praise the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   He has played both professional baseball and football. He has
partied like the devil from coast to coast and is now a helmeted,
traveling preacher in search of lost souls.
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders has found religion, and now he wants to show you
the path, whether you're searching or not.
</P>
<P>
   No more Neon Deion, he says. No more flocking to the bright
lights, only the one true light. Rather than challenge authority,
he now challenges all of us to make the same conversion. The former
wise guy who once allegedly tried to run down a parking-lot
security guard with a motorcycle now says he wants to be a role
model.
</P>
<P>
   You believe him or you don't. As with the presidential
deposition, there is no middle ground. You defend him or you detest
him, love him or loathe him. But you can never take your eyes off
him. Not when he's between the lines of any game he's playing.
</P>
<P>
   If Muhammad Ali was the one to introduce charisma and flash to
the world of sports, Prime Time is the leading practitioner of the
late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   See him point a finger straight up to the sky before dropping
back deep to settle under his first punt of the night early in the
first quarter Monday. See him run like a crazed mouse through a
maze after gathering in another punt early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   See Sanders start left and come almost nose-to-nose with a
couple of would-be tacklers. See him spin around on a dance step
niftier than Travolta and loop all the way to the right sideline.
See him make one, two, three men miss. See him cut back one more
time to the left and go all the way to the end zone, high-stepping
the final five yards of a 59-yard touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   See Sanders step in front of a Danny Kanell pass intended for
David Patten with 2:25 left in the fourth quarter and take it back
71 yards for another TD.
</P>
<P>
   If this was Monday Night Football, then it was prime time. If
that was a flash of sheer brilliance, then it was Prime Time.
</P>
<P>
   His special-teams coach, Joe Avezzano, dropped his jaw in
amazement. The New York Giants simply dropped to the turf dead,
dead, dead.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when the Cowboys played the entire game without
starting quarterback Troy Aikman and the second half without
running back Emmitt Smith, they needed true inspiration, divine or
otherwise. And it was Sanders who gave it to them.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning rod for controversy was the crackling bolt who
split the game wide open like an old tree trunk and lifted the
Cowboys to a 31-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   For a night, there was no need for the Cowboys to worry that
Aikman stood on the sidelines nursing a broken collarbone while
Jason Garrett made only his third start in the NFL. For a night,
the Cowboys could overlook the fact that Smith gained just 21 yards
on seven carries and had to retire at the half with a strained
right groin.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that may not change the Cowboys' entire season,
but it kept them from slipping over the edge. Garrett did his job
and didn't lose it. Sanders did his magic and stole it.
</P>
<P>
   It was desperation time. It was Prime Time, Rev. Gold Chain, the
man of the hour. He returns punts, catches passes, defends the
corner and makes interceptions. He can probably sing, dance and
carry a refrigerator on his back, too. After all, we saw him carry
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dreary contest of exchanged punts until Sanders grabbed
a line drive off the foot of Brad Maynard and went on a mad dash
through the minefield to give Dallas a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He strutted, he celebrated, and then he staggered to the
sidelines dehydrated and promptly vomited. He went to the locker
room at halftime, got an intravenous replenishment and came back
for more. And more.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders barely appeared in training camp, recovering from ankle
surgery and then a fractured rib. But apostles apparently don't
need training.
</P>
<P>
   On the second possession of the third quarter, he lined up at
wide receiver and split Giants Carlton Gray and Tito Wooten to make
a 55-yard catch and set up the Cowboys' third touchdown. Then, for
good measure, he picked off Kanell and ran that one back, too.
</P>
<P>
   He has 16 return touchdowns in his career _ eight interceptions,
four punts, three kickoffs and one fumble _ and has also caught
three TD passes and rushed for another score.
</P>
<P>
   He is larger than life and faster than a hummingbird's pulse. On
this night, he was the Cowboys' heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime. Big-time. Prime Time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
