<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7422 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-22 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING FOR THE MOMENT IN AL WEST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mark McGwire stayed home. Sammy Sosa had the day off.
Even Cal Ripken Jr. took a seat.
</P>
<P>
   And to clear the national stage completely, the New York Mets
and the Chicago Cubs took a one-night break from their second-place
race Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Warmup acts all, they knew it was time to step aside when this
season of magic and comedy shows finally presented a main event.
</P>
<P>
   In the year of the home run, the year of the runaway division
leader, the year of what Baseball Weekly mislabeled as ``Wildcard
Mania,'' the only thing missing was a game that really mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Angels and Texas Rangers played this one to break their
tie for first place in the American League West, and wouldn't Big
Mac have loved to be part of it?
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won 9-1 on a pleasantly cool night when Todd
Stottlemyre smoked the Angels and Steve Sparks' knuckleball fooled
only catcher Chad Kreuter, giving Texas a one-game lead with two
games left in the showdown series and six games left in the season.
A blowout, demoralizing for the losers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the brief time it was a ballgame, there were nine innings
worth of sweet little baseball moments, each sensation heightened
by the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin working Sparks to 3 and 2, as a leadoff hitter
should. Jim Edmonds running down Goodwin's opposite-alley drive a
step from the warning track. Randy Velarde kicking Mark McLemore's
grounder in an early sign of nerves. Rusty Greer's hit-and-run
grounder through the vacated shortstop hole. Juan Gonzalez's
grounder up the middle for his 155th RBI, breaking his
major-league-leading tie with Sosa. Darin Erstad's diving catch of
a Will Clark line drive, while partially screened by a runner,
saving at least one run.
</P>
<P>
   After all that, it was on to the bottom half of the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The shame is that only 33,487 watched, nearly 10,000 short of
capacity at Edison Field, where walk-up ticket sales totaled an
embarrassing 1,579. If you've loved the summer of '98 but you
couldn't get worked up over this, it turns out you're a home-runs
fan, not a baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   Worked up?
</P>
<P>
   Texas manager Johnny Oates called a team meeting, approximately
an annual event with him, to ``remind them to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a seven-game series to see who represents the AL West,''
Oates said. ``I wanted to tell them there's no execution Monday
morning if we don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Worked up?
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins was able to sleep for ``a couple of
hours'' Sunday night _ ``sporadically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to break my pattern,'' Collins said with a weak
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Worked up?
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, the young Angels first baseman who was in the lineup
Monday for the second time since he aggravated a hamstring injury
three weeks ago, tried to remember the last time he played in a
game this big. He came up with the '95 Orange Bowl, when Nebraska
beat Miami for the national title, and Erstad was the Cornhuskers'
punter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball?'' Erstad said. ``Probably never.''
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, a season is so full of sidebars and subplots,
sometimes it's hard to tell if they're the distractions or the
games are.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about analyzing yesterday's game and tomorrow's
matchup, getting over last week's injury and planning next week's
pitching rotation, erasing last year's disappointment and grooming
next year's rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in a while is it all about !ital!today!off!.
</P>
<P>
   As it was Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a lot of attention on this race,'' Collins
said in the dugout before the game. ``There's been attention on
McGwire, on Sammy, on Ripken. And that's as it should be. Those are
big stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guys (Angels) say, `We're overshadowed out here.' Well,
here's a great chance to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the insomnia, a manager's job actually gets easier
with the division on the line in the final week. He has only one
worry. Winning today.
</P>
<P>
   Why else was Erstad out there, a threat to reinjure himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him in our lineup,'' Collins said. ``If I wait three
or four days to put him in there, we may not need him until next
March. Every day I've been thinking, `Should I save him for the
playoffs?' Well, if we don't have him, we might not make the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   At last, a baseball moment measured in runs, not in feet.
</P>
<P>
   When he covered baseball for the Daily News (he's now with the
Detroit Free Press), John Lowe said he loved Opening Day best of
all because it was the one afternoon he could write not about
yesterday, not about tomorrow, but about !ital!the game!off!.
</P>
<P>
   John was half right. Some years you get a second Opening Day.
The Angels and the Rangers, as even in the standings as they were
April 1, played a second Opening Day on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can the Angels find midseason form in 20 hours? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
