<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE BUFFETS PUERTO RICO AND THE U.S. VIRGIN ISLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS lead and early grafs for late evening update; new info. on
increased number of fatalities.)   (af)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, P.R. _ Hurricane Georges roared into Puerto Rico and
the United States Virgin Islands on Monday, causing extensive
damage after leaving a trail of destruction in the smaller islands
of the northeastern Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 o'clock Monday night, the authorities were reporting that
two-thirds of Puerto Rico was without water and that fully half the
island had lost electrical power.
</P>
<P>
   A flash-flood warning was in effect throughout the island, home
to 3.8 million people, and there were reports of many building
collapses. Damage to buildings was extensive, particularly in San
Juan and elsewhere along the northeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   The eye of the storm, which the National Hurricane Center in
Miami has classified as the most powerful and menacing of the
season, was just west-southwest of San Juan late Monday evening,
and The Associated Press reported that five people had been killed
by the storm in Puerto Rico, three in a landslide outside San Juan
and two who suffered heart attacks in shelters. A sixth person was
reported missing in a separate landslide near San Juan. The AP said
the storm killed a woman in St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the weekend, the storm has been on a course that took it
diagonally across the full length of Puerto Rico. It has weakened
somewhat since Sunday morning, when it had maximum sustained winds
of 150 miles per hour, almost enough to make it a Category 5 storm,
the most dangerous on the Saffir-Simpson scale used to rank
hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, its peak winds had diminished to 110 mph,
making it a Category 2 storm. But it strengthened once more this
evening, intensifying to Category 3.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before the storm hit with all its fury, the
authorities here and in the Virgin Islands repeatedly warned
residents to remain indoors or, if their homes were in coastal
areas or made of flimsy material, to move to shelters. Twenty
thousand people took refuge in shelters here in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect there is going to be major damage, and some families
are going to have difficult days to come,'' Gov. Pedro Rossello
cautioned at midday as the first strong winds and rain were
beginning to be felt here.
</P>
<P>
   In the Virgin Islands, Gov. Roy Schneider had already imposed an
8 p.m. curfew and, like Rossello, asked President Clinton in
advance to declare a federal state of emergency so that disaster
relief could flow more rapidly once the storm passed. Advance teams
from the Federal Emergency Management Agency and the American Red
Cross were in place in both American territories, and FEMA had
organized a 62-member search-and-rescue team in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday afternoon, Rossello said that both
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki had called him and
offered New York's help in any cleanup and reconstruction. Puerto
Ricans living in the continental United States have also inquired
about providing assistance, he said, adding that a decision whether
the aid will be needed would be made only after he had assessed the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Leeward Islands, which suffered a direct hit by the
storm on Sunday night and early Monday, that process was already
under way. Initial reports said the islands hit the hardest
appeared to be Antigua and Barbados, St. Kitts and Nevis, both
independent countries; the British colony of Montserrat; and the
French overseas territory of Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   On all those islands, the authorities reported that buildings
had been ripped apart and power lines damaged. But as of
midafternoon, no fatalities had been reported anywhere along the
storm's west-northwesterly path.
</P>
<P>
   After traversing Puerto Rico, the storm is expected to hit the
northern coast of the Dominican Republic and Haiti, where hurricane
warnings are already in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Once the storm reaches the eastern tip of Cuba, however, its
course becomes less predictable. It is too early, they say, for
anyone's guard to be lowered, even along the United States' Gulf
Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
