<HEADER>
A7471 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOTAPE-ANALYSIS-SF     09-22 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOTAPE-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPE PROVIDES LITTLE AMMUNITION FOR CLINTON FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ For a man whose defense rests on the proposition
that she had sex with him but he did not have sex with her, he
could hardly have sounded more credible.
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's four hours of videotaped interrogation
before a grand jury and 3,183 pages of documents, released Monday
to the world, may have provided a low moment for the presidency and
his own career. But it did not provide the smoking gun his critics
hoped would turn the nation against him.
</P>
<P>
   He did not turn purple with rage. His nose did not grow longer.
In fact, the four-hour exercise seemed to reinforce the notion
promoted by the White House that the crisis that has gripped the
nation's capital for the past eight months is about little more
than sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen this four-year, $40 million investigation come
down to parsing the definition of sex,'' Clinton declared after
prosecutors tried repeatedly and futilely to get him to explain how
he could acknowledge ``inappropriate intimate contacts'' with
Lewinsky and yet deny ``sexual relations.''
</P>
<P>
   A quarter century ago, the release of White House tapes led
directly to the resignation of President Richard Nixon. Monday's
spectacle is unlikely to do anything but further polarize the
partisan debate in Congress over the appropriate course of action
and further darken the public's dim view of the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Those who watched television Monday saw an unfamiliar view of
the president. He rarely smiled. He coughed. He scratched his ears.
His makeup wore off, and the perspiration glistened on his forehead
and upper lip. He blinked uncomfortably as he alternately sipped
Diet Coke and ginger ale, and at times he appeared to be holding
back a seething rage.
</P>
<P>
   His answers were often evasive. He offered a definition of
``sexual relations'' that relied on who was doing the touching. He
explained away apparent inconsistencies with statements like ``it
depends on what the meaning of the word `is' is,'' and ``it depends
on how you define `alone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But there was little to convince Americans that the president
had endeavored to obstruct justice, abused his constitutional
authority or tampered with witnesses, as independent counsel
Kenneth Starr charged in his report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, those who watched the full 243 minutes of testimony saw
the most detailed, and perhaps most innocent-sounding explanation
yet from Clinton of why he lied to the American people for seven
months about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassing and personally painful thing, the truth
about my relationship with Ms. Lewinsky,'' he said, sounding like
any spouse caught in a web of adultery.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors off camera repeatedly pestered him about how he
could have sought to deceive, Clinton repeatedly stated the
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I want this to come out? No. Was I embarrassed about it?
Yes. Did I ask her to lie about it? No.''
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of questions, Clinton insisted that he did not perjure
himself January 17 when, during a deposition in the Paula Jones
litigation, he stated under oath that he did not have sexual
relations with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Jones' attorneys knew they had a ``bogus'' case,
and ``the real reason they were zeroing in on (Lewinsky) was . . .
no matter how uninvolved with Paula Jones, no matter how uninvolved
with sexual harassment, was so they could hurt me politically. . .
. They just thought they could take a wrecking ball to me and see
if they could do some damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing my best to be truthful,'' he said, asserting that
kissing and oral sex are not covered by the definition provided to
him by Jones' attorneys. ``I was not trying to be particularly
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   There were many moments of awkwardness and humiliation for the
president, some of which could provide devastating footage for GOP
television commercials this fall. But during four hours of
questions from off-camera interrogators, it is prosecutors who come
across as clueless about the working of an illicit affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tried, in fact, not to let anyone else know about this
relationship?'' a prosecutor asked accusingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, of course,'' said the president. ``I did what people do
when they do the wrong thing. I tried to do it where nobody else
was looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean he excluded his secretary, Betty Currie, and
others from intimate moments with Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to be an exhibitionist not to have tried to exclude
everyone else,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the secrecy that surrounded the testimony last month,
Clinton was clearly aware that his words would not remain private
for long. He repeatedly refused to detail the nature of his sexual
activity with Lewinsky, at one point alluding to the camera, and
saying that ``I am right to answer all the questions about perjury,
but not to say things which will be forever in the historic annals
of the United States because of this unprecedented videotape
(which) may be leaked at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's artful performance is unlikely to appease his
detractors, who will be able to seize on several tortured
explanations of his previous testimony. For example, prosecutors
referred to his attorney's statement during last January's
deposition in which he stated: ``Counsel is fully aware that Ms.
Lewinsky has filed, has an affidavit . . . saying that there is
absolutely no sex of any kind in any manner, shape or form, with
President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked on the videotape whether that statement was true, Clinton
said: ``It depends on what the meaning of the word `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean, prosecutors persisted, that because he was not
engaged in sexual activity with Lewinsky during the deposition,
that his attorney's statement was literally true.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Clinton said, ``I mean that at the time of the
deposition, it . . . was well beyond any point of improper contact.
So that anyone generally speaking in the present tense, saying
there is not an improper relationship, would be telling the truth
if that person said there was not, in the present tense, the
present tense encompassing many months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, concluding an explanation that may take
linguists _ let alone lawmakers _ weeks to dissect, ``is what I
meant by that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
