<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSTATE-CANCER-BUDGE     09-22 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-CANCER-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Sept. 22, 1998      EDITORS:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is the most diagnosed serious cancer in America;
it is the No. 2 cancer-killer of men; it kills African-American men
at nearly twice the rate for Caucasian men.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its lethality, prostate cancer gets far less federal
research funding than does AIDS or breast cancer. One reason is
that well-organized lobby groups push for funding for AIDS and
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer, on the other hand, has been surrounded by an
aura of awkward embarrassment, its victims hushed into silence by
the biologic reality that the prostate gland is at the center of
male sexuality. The veil of reticence is starting to lift, thanks
to the courageous efforts of famous prostate cancer patients like
Bob Dole and Norman Schwarzkopf, who have made it their personal
campaigns to alert the American public about this disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service and the San Antonio Express-News have
prepared a package of stories, photos and graphics examining
prostate cancer from the point of view of patients, physicians,
researchers and government funders.
</P>
<P>
   This package is for release Sept. 27, 28 and 29. The photos and
graphics are available on the Wieck Database.
</P>
<P>
   The key to surviving prostate cancer is early detection because
once the cancer spreads beyond the prostate gland _ a
golf-ball-sized organ located underneath the bladder _ a cure
becomes difficult, if not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Although detection tests are simple, many men don't get tested
or wait until it is too late.
</P>
<P>
   The following budget outlines a three-day series about the
disease. Our stories deal with the treatments, the sexual side
effects of treatments, the screening procedures, the plight of
African American men, the politics in Washington that stymie
prostate cancer research budgets and other elements of this deadly
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The principal writer for the series was Eric Rosenberg of the
Washington bureau of the Hearst Newspapers; Don Finley and David
Uhler of The Express-News also contributed stories.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics by Mark Blackwell of The Express-News; photos by Jerry
Lara of The Express-News and Eric Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about stories, please call Chuck Lewis at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about photos or graphics, please call
Hallie Paul at 210-250-3301.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: All slugs contain the prefix ``PCA,'' the medical
shorthand for prostate cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-RDP: Prostate cancer is the second-leading
cancer-killer of men, behind lung cancer, and the most common
non-skin cancer diagnosed in the United States today.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society estimates 184,500 men will be
diagnosed this year and 39,200 will die of the disease, a little
less than the number of deaths from breast cancer but about twice
as many deaths from AIDs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its toll and the prominence of some of its sufferers
(Bob Dole, Arnold Palmer, Michael Milken, Andy Grove), prostate
cancer has received little public attention or political focus. One
reason: Men don't like to talk about the disease, which often
affects sexual function and bladder control.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that although prostate cancer kills more people
than AIDs, research on prostate cancer gets only a fraction of the
federal research funding that goes to AIDS. This may be changing as
a result of an emerging grassroots lobbying effort coordinated by a
new private organization. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo: PCA-ROUNDUP.)
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBARS:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-RISK-FACTORS: While little for certain is known about what
causes prostate cancer, there are two groups of men who face high
risks of getting the disease: men over 65 years and
African-American men. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-BLACKS: For mysterious reasons, a perplexing racial element
haunts prostate cancer research. Mortality rates for black
Americans are more than twice as high as those for whites. In fact,
American blacks have the highest prostate cancer rate in the world.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo: PCA-BLACKS.)
</P>
<P>
   PCA-SEX: Several top researchers believe that the cancer, at
least in some cases, may be fomented by a sexually transmitted
disease found in nearly two out of three American men. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-DIAGNOSTIC-TEST: A simple blood test has revolutionized
prostate medicine by diagnosing thousands of new cases of prostate
cancer every year in men who have few, if any, other symptoms. The
prostate specific antigen (PSA) test makes it possible to detect
tumors before they become life-threatening. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-ANATOMY: graphic showing location of prostate, urethra,
seminal vesicles, bladder, rectum.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-CELLS: graphic/slide showing a cancerous prostate cell
versus a healthy one.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-MORTALITY-MAP: state-by-state mortality rates: ``Death rates
from prostate cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   PCA-RACE-MORT-INCID: mortality rates/incidence rates among
blacks, Hispanics, whites and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-RISING-NUMBERS: overall incidence rate graph from 1973
through 1995 and overall mortality rate graph from 1973-1995.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-VICTIMS-SURVIVORS: Graphic of well-known prostate cancer
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS: Prostate cancer victims face a confusing
array of treatment options, all carrying the risk of such side
effects as impotence or incontinence. Depending on whether the
cancer has spread beyond the gland, the options may include:
</P>
<P>
   - Removal of the prostate, a prostatectomy;
</P>
<P>
   _ External beam radiation;
</P>
<P>
   _ Seed radiation therapy;
</P>
<P>
   - Hormonal deprivation through castration;
</P>
<P>
   - Chemotherapy;
</P>
<P>
   _ Do nothing, the ``watchful waiting'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   We examine each treatment and include commentary from
specialists around the country and the personal experiences of
patients who have undergone the treatments. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos: PCA-TREATMENT1, PCA-TREATMENT2.)
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBARS:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-SURGERY: The surgery to remove the patient's prostate gland
gets underway in Operating Room No. 11 at Walter Reed Army Medical
Center in Washington, D.C., at 8:30 a.m. Surgeons make a vertical
incision about five inches long from below the man's navel to the
base of his penis. They slowly ``dissect down'' into the abdomen.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos: PCA-McLEOD and PCA-GLAND.)
</P>
<P>
   PCA-IMPOTENCY: The most common treatments for early-stage
prostate cancer _ surgery and radiation _ likely will reduce a
man's sexual potency. The treatments can pose a daunting choice
between normal sexual function and a potential cancer cure, between
quality of life and longevity. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo:PCA-IMPOTENCY.)
</P>
<P>
   PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY _ Gently, Dr. Michael Sarosdy slowly withdraws
a foot-long needle from between Jim King's legs. The hollow probe
leaves behind a tiny trail of radioactive pellets in the patient's
prostate gland. By DAVID UHLER.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo: PCA-KING.)
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-CHANCE-DIAG-DEATH: graphic showing prostate cancer risk
increases with age.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-SIDE-EFFECTS: graphic explaining current therapies for
dealing with potency side effects.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-GLOSSARY: glossary of important terms.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-IF-U-R-DIAGNOSED: Important questions and steps to take if
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Sept. 29:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-POLITICS: When Congress hands out medical research money,
cash flows to the projects demanded by the loudest and best
organized health lobby groups. The result: Federal research
spending on breast cancer and AIDS far exceeds spending on prostate
cancer research. That is starting to change, thanks to a
grass-roots lobbying effort across the country. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo: PCA-POLITICS.)
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBARS:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-RESEARCH: Research 25 years ago on sexually ambiguous
children led to the drug Proscar, used to treat prostate disease
and male baldness. Those studies identified a metabolite of
testosterone now being tested to find a drug to prevent prostate
cancer. By DON FINLEY.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-NEW-TREATMENTS: Scientists are developing an array of new
therapies for patients who fail frontline prostate cancer
treatments such as surgery, radiation, hormonal blockade and
chemotherapy. The National Cancer Institute identifies nearly 40
clinical trials underway for patients with recurrent prostate
cancer or prostate cancer that has spread beyond the gland. We
detail new prostate cancer treatments under study along with
contact phone numbers. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-MILITARY: Amid a network of laboratories on the campus of a
government medical school in Bethesda, Md., the U.S. military is
developing a one-of-a-kind tool in the war on prostate cancer: a
massive tissue and blood data base. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos: PCA-MILITARY1-4).
</P>
<P>
   GRAPHICS:
</P>
<P>
   PCA-RESEARCH DOLLARS: graphic of federal research dollar per
death caused by prostate cancer, breast cancer and AIDs; graphic of
federal research dollar per incidence of prostate cancer, breast
cancer and AIDs.
</P>
<P>
   PCA-FOR-MORE-INFO: listing of prostate cancer resources, book
titles, Internet sites, support groups, etc.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
