<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-PROSTATE-CANCER-R     09-22 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-PROSTATE-CANCER-RDP-2TAKES-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSTATE CANCER: THE MAN-KILLER THAT PEOPLE DON'T TALK ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Ralph Valle, the first clue came when he
started waking up several times during the night to urinate.
</P>
<P>
   He went to his physician who, after an exam, referred him to a
specialist. Several tests later, Valle got the bad news that
explained his problem: He had prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had a prostate, but I wasn't even sure what it did,''
Valle said, recalling his reaction back in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   After learning his options, Valle elected to have the cancerous
gland surgically removed. But during surgery, it became apparent to
the doctors that the malignancy had already spread.
</P>
<P>
   So Valle took the most drastic step possible to stop the cancer
from spreading. He had himself surgically castrated to halt the
production of testosterone, which is produced by the testes,
because that male hormone fuels prostate cancer growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to shock men. I tell them, `If you don't pay attention
to this disease early on, these are the things that can happen,'''
said Valle, 65, of Phoenix, Ariz., a Cuban-born manufacturing
executive.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 184,500 American men will get the news that they have
prostate cancer. Many will need to choose a treatment that may
lengthen their lives but that also may end their sexual function
and cause urinary incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of these newly diagnosed prostate cancer victims will
be over 65 years old. Most of the others will be in their 50s and
early 60s, at the peak of their working careers. A minority will be
in their 40s, although some major medical institutions are
reporting a spike in the number of younger men with prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we are seeing more younger patients with
aggressive disease in their 40s and 50s,'' said Dr. Howard Scher,
chief of genito-urinary oncology at the Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This year, some 39,200 American men, many in hospices or at home
and attached to morphine pumps, will die from a cancer that began
in a gland a little larger than a golf ball. The prostate gland,
nestled under the bladder adjacent to the rectum, produces the
seminal fluid that carries sperm.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer contained in the gland itself isn't fatal. Death
comes if the cancer spreads beyond the prostate to bone, lungs,
liver or brain.
</P>
<P>
   Next to highly curable forms of skin cancer, carcinoma of the
prostate will be the most diagnosed cancer in the United States
this year, according to the American Cancer Society. Nearly one in
six men will get the disease sometime in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas alone, an estimated 11,900 men this year will learn
that they have prostate cancer, according to American Cancer
Society statistics, and 2,500 will die from it. Like the national
trend, prostate cancer is expected to be the most diagnosed
malignancy in Texas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Most patients will die with the disease rather than from it
because prostate cancer usually is slow growing. Nonetheless, it is
the second leading cancer-killer of men after lung cancer, killing
in 1995 about 24.9 percent of men who got it, a death rate similar
to breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For mysterious reasons, there is a perplexing racial element to
the cancer. Mortality rates for black Americans with prostate
cancer are more than twice as high as those for whites. Researchers
speculate that this may be caused by a combination of genetics,
diet and a reluctance to get medical checkups.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics compiled by the National Cancer
Institute, 150.3 non-Hispanic white men per 100,000 and 104.4
Hispanic men per 100,000 developed prostate cancer from 1990
through 1995 compared with 224.3 black men per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, 55 African American men per 100,000 died
from the cancer, while the disease claimed the lives of 24.1
non-Hispanic whites per 100,000 and 16.8 Hispanics per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the number of prostate cancer diagnoses has skyrocketed
over the last 20 years. Medical scientists say the main reason is
the growing use of a new diagnostic tool known as the prostate
specific antigen (PSA) blood test.
</P>
<P>
   A contributing factor is that men are living longer _ and
prostate cancer afflicts older men more than younger men.
</P>
<P>
   The average life expectancy of a non-Hispanic white American
male is almost 80 years, and the average diagnosis of prostate
cancer is around 65 years. As a result, men are now being diagnosed
15 to 20 years before their life expectancy is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are around longer for the cancer to develop and spread,''
said Dr. William Catalona, director of urologic surgery at
Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of better early detection and longer life
expectancy has made prostate cancer ``a very significant
health-care problem,'' said Catalona.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer rates have more than doubled between 1973 and
1995 _ from 64.2 men per 100,000 to 137.2 men per 100,000,
according to the National Cancer Institute. The mortality rate
during the same period has shot up more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the PSA test, about 58 percent of new cases this year
will be caught in the early stages when the disease hasn't spread
beyond the prostate and the men are potentially curable. However, a
cure is not certain even under the best conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The most favorable scenario for a newly diagnosed patient is
that the disease is confined to the prostate, which is then either
surgically removed or radiated. Both treatments commonly result in
impotence or reduced sexual potency and urinary incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   However, in about 20 percent to 30 percent of cases where a
cancerous prostate gland is surgically removed, it later turns out
that cancer cells had escaped into the body before the surgery. The
result: The surgeon who ``got it all'' actually didn't _ and the
patient later develops the cancer elsewhere in the body.
</P>
<P>
   This stubbornness is why prostate cancer victims swapping
treatment experiences in Internet chat rooms have nicknamed the
disease ``the beast.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not grow as fast as breast cancer, but it is
relentless,'' said Dr. Michael Manyak, chief of urology at George
Washington University in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that when confined to the prostate and treated,
five-year survival statistics are 100 percent. And over the past 20
years, the survival rate for all stages of the cancer combined has
risen from 67 percent to 89 percent, thanks to early detection and
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Survival starts to fall off after five years. According to the
American Cancer Society's most recent data, 67 percent of all men
diagnosed with the cancer survive 10 years while 50 percent survive
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Early detection is imperative. By the time symptoms appear _
like Ralph Valle's frequent urination during the night, painful
urination or pelvic pain _ the cancer may have already spread
outside the gland, making it difficult, if not impossible, to cure.
If the disease spreads to the bones, death usually results within
18 months to two years.
</P>
<P>
   And death does not come peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prostate cancer has the tragic distinction of being a death
often protracted, always associated with severe pain, debilitation
and psychological distress, and a death for which no effective
intervention now exists,'' wrote Drs. Andrew Von Eschenbach and
Christopher Wood of the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston, two
top prostate cancer researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no cure for prostate cancer, once systemic
progression beyond the gland has occurred,'' they said in a 17-page
``Agenda for Prostate Cancer Research.''
</P>
<P>
   Men have been famously reluctant to talk about prostate cancer,
mainly because the disease and its treatments often curtail sexual
and urinary function. It's simply too embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to a support group for guys, men say, `What's your
PSA ... and how about those Mets?' There's no feelings or concerns
expressed,'' said Jerry Donohue, a prostate cancer patient from
Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   That's beginning to change, thanks to publicity campaigns by
well-known prostate cancer patients. People like Bob Dole, Norman
Schwarzkopf, Andy Grove and Michael Milken have told the public
about their own experiences with the disease in an effort to
encourage more men to get tested.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and Randy
``Duke'' Cunningham, R-Calif., who in August had his cancerous
prostate removed, held a press conference in front of the U.S.
Capitol to urge men to get tested for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as breast cancer is something every woman should know
about ... similarly, men I think should learn from Sen. Dole and
from Congressman Cunningham, that if you will take the preventive
steps, if you will do the screening, if you will worry about
wellness, you will live longer, and you will live healthier,''
Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the touchy reticence surrounding the disease is
that men have been absent from the political wars that determine
federal funding for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have not been organized into groups like the women have
been,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, the chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee and a prostate cancer survivor.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Federal funding for prostate cancer research has
been dramatically less than funding for such other killers as AIDS
or breast cancer. Breast cancer kills about the same number of
American women annually as prostate cancer kills of American men.
</P>
<P>
   From this flows the reality that, compared to other major killer
diseases, less is known about prostate cancer. As a result, medical
practitioners disagree over such basic issues as which treatment is
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast cancer is a pretty clean shot _ there is pretty much a
consensus about how to treat it,'' said Dr. Harold Freeman,
President Clinton's top cancer adviser. ``Prostate cancer is not
the same. You get diagnosed and can get treated in very different
ways according to which way you decide to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Because prostate cancer often is slow-growing _ a man who is
diagnosed today may not face a life-threatening predicament for
years, if ever _ doctors may recommend that elderly patients do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   This approach _ known as ``watchful waiting'' _ means monitoring
the disease until it becomes dangerous. Quite often, the patient
will die of something else.
</P>
<P>
   The general rule of thumb among prostate specialists is that if
the man has a life expectancy of at least 10 years at diagnosis and
the cancer is suspected of being organ-confined, physicians will
try to cure the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking in the background will be such effects as impotence,
incontinence and scarring of the rectum.
</P>
<P>
   As Dr. Mark Litwin, of the UCLA Medical Center, puts it: ``Once
prostate cancer is diagnosed and treated, the patient's life is
necessarily and permanently altered.''
</P>
<P>
   The message from patients like Valle is that men should seek out
as much information as possible about their disease and the side
effects of treatments so they can make the best treatment
decisions. Valle regularly swaps information with other patients in
Internet discussion groups dedicated to prostate cancer. Each case
is different, each cancer has its own unique complexities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that my survival is directly proportional to my
involvement in learning what the hell is happening inside me,''
said Valle. ``You are going to make decisions critical to your life
and you need all the tools.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
