r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-RISK-FACTORS-$ADV     09-22 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-RISK-FACTORS-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS AT RISK FOR PROSTATE CANCER? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While medical researchers haven't identified the causes of
prostate cancer, statistics show two groups of men face high risks
of getting the disease: men over 65 years and African-American men.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are studying other possible risk factors as well.
Here is a rundown:
</P>
<P>
   _ Age.
</P>
<P>
   Age is the most important risk factor for prostate cancer. Men
over 65 are at the biggest risk. By the time he reaches 50, a man
has a 30 percent chance of having the cancer. The risk increases
exponentially with age. But not all prostate cancer turns lethal
and not all prostate cancer requires medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Race.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans have the highest prostate cancer mortality
rates of any ethnic group in the world. Researchers believe this
may result from a combination of factors, including diet and a
greater likelihood of carrying an inherited strain of the cancer
carried through the Hereditary Prostate Cancer gene, or HPC-1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Family history.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies indicate that men with a strong family history of
the disease are twice or three times more likely to get prostate
cancer than are men without such a history.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have located the first gene associated with
hereditary forms of prostate cancer. The gene is known as HPC-1.
About 10 percent of new cases may be the result of inherited
factors, according to the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Geography.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is common throughout North America and Northwestern
Europe but is rare in Asia, parts of Africa and South America.
Norway and Switzerland have the highest prostate cancer death
rates, while the United States is ranked No. 11. Japan,
Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan are among the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Diet.
</P>
<P>
   Diet is a major suspected risk factor. A diet high in animal fat
may nearly double the risk of prostate cancer, while consumption of
lycopene, an anti-oxidant found in tomato products, may decrease
the risks, according to studies in the Journal of the National
Cancer Institute and the Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a recent medical study from Harvard University has
determined that the mineral selenium may help prevent advanced
prostate cancer. Small amounts of selenium are found in meats,
fish, grains, dairy products and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Heavy metal exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Overexposure to the element cadmium may promote prostate cancer
in some men. Cadmium inhibits the metabolism of zinc, which is a
fundamental requirement for normal cell division. The prostate
contains the highest levels of zinc of all the organs in the body,
and cancerous prostates contain less zinc than healthy ones.
</P>
<P>
   Men who work in making batteries, paint and cigarettes, among
other industries, risk cadmium overexposure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists know for certain that the male hormone testosterone
fuels the cancer once it is sparked. But whether testosterone
actually ignites the disease is still an open question and is
currently under study.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sexually transmitted virus.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers believe that the human papillomavirus, the same
disease that has been linked to cervical and penis cancer, plays a
role in prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Cigarette smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston suspect
that smoking may make prostate cancer tumors behave more
aggressively causing them to spread and turn lethal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
