r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-BLACKS-$ADV27-HNS Sept.27) &LR;    09-22 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-BLACKS-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN-AMERICAN MEN HAVE THE HIGHEST RISK OF PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Harry Harris, a retired federal government worker
from Silver Spring, Md., was diagnosed eight years ago with
prostate cancer at age 69.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, a blood test detected the cancer in its early stages
and Harris _ an African American _ opted for surgery to remove the
gland. The procedure left him with curtailed sexual function, a
common side effect of surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still alive today, but I know a lot of people who had the
cancer and are dead,'' said Harris, who is beating the terrible
odds that African-American men face when it comes to prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For mysterious and complex reasons, African-American men have
the highest rate of prostate cancer of any ethnic or racial group
anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are bleak.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics compiled by the National Cancer
Institute, 150.3 non-Hispanic white men per 100,000 and 104.4
Hispanic men per 100,000 developed prostate cancer from 1990
through 1995. By comparison, 224.3 black men per 100,000 developed
the disease in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Over the period, 55 African-American men per 100,000 died from
the cancer, while the disease claimed the lives of 24.1
non-Hispanic whites per 100,000 and 16.8 Hispanics per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Korean-American men had the lowest rates of the disease _ 24.2
per 100,000, while Chinese-American men had the lowest mortality
rates _ 6.6 deaths per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers baffle cancer researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Could the differences be explained by factors such as diet,
behavior or environment? Or on a biological level, is prostate
cancer more aggressive in African American men?
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists focused on the possibility that African-American
men have poorer health care and thus might not have their prostate
cancers detected in a timely way.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of equal access to health care has long been suspected as a
contributing factor to high cancer rates among African American men
and women.
</P>
<P>
   An American Medical Association report released in the early
1990s continues to reverberate today. ``Access to basic medical
care for all of our inhabitants is still not a reality in this
country,'' the report found. ``There are many reasons for this, not
the least of which is long-standing, systematic, institutionalized
racial discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA found access to be lacking particularly among African
Americans and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   To test the access theory, Dr. Judd Moul, a urologist and
director of the U.S. military's Center for Prostate Disease
Research, studied the records of active duty and retired military
men, all of whom were eligible for the same level of medical
attention through the military. He found the same huge gap between
African-American men and non-blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Moul sums up the mystery: ``So why are blacks affected so much?
Is it biology, behavior or a combination of both?''
</P>
<P>
   He speculates that a piece of the puzzle centers around
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though black men may have equal access to health care,
they might not have been availing themselves of it,'' Moul said.
``It could be behavioral, even among black military beneficiaries
who might not want to go to a doctor for a check up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Isaac Powell, an African-American urologist at Wayne State
University, found evidence supporting a behavioral link; many black
men he studied in the Detroit area were reluctant to undergo the
digital rectal exam, a frontline test used to detect prostate
tumors.
</P>
<P>
   The men had a mistrust of the medical establishment that
curtailed the frequency of medical check ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some differences in attitudes towards the health
care system in African Americans that may be more of a barrier than
in Caucasians,'' said Powell, who had his own cancerous prostate
removed last year. ``One of those happens to be concerns about
getting the kind of care their white counterparts would get.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell believes several factors are at the root of the prostate
cancer statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think some are biological, some may be genetic, some may be
environmental factors impacting on the genes, such as a high-fat
diet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell and a team of mainly African-American researchers are
zeroing in on hereditary factors.
</P>
<P>
   Inherited prostate cancer _ prostate cancer that strikes
numerous members in the same family _ accounts for about 1 in 10
cases, according to the National Cancer Institute. Alterations in
what is known as the HPC-1 gene are suspected of causing one-third
of these.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have determined that African Americans are twice as
likely to carry the HPC-1 gene, the first known hereditary prostate
cancer gene.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, scientists discovered a chemical signpost for the gene
along the long arm of chromosome No. 1 that they believe resides
very close to HPC-1. Powell and his group are trying to determine
the exact location of the gene.
</P>
<P>
   Once identified, the gene will provide insight into the
progression of prostate cancer and help doctors determine who is
more likely to develop aggressive strains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have families that have a hereditary component, the
men are more likely to die from it'' because hereditary prostate
cancer usually is very aggressive, said Sally Weinrich, a professor
of nursing and a prostate cancer researcher at the University of
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Powell is studying black families with four or more family
members who have prostate cancer. The study _ focused in Detroit,
Chicago, Washington, D.C., New York City, Houston, Atlanta and the
state of South Carolina _ is funded by the National Human Genome
Research Institute, Howard University and the National Cancer
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the HPC-1 gene, blacks may also have another
genetic risk. Scientists at Boston's Dana-Farber Cancer Institute
are focusing on the androgen receptor gene _ a gene closely
connected with testosterone, the male sex hormone that fuels the
growth of both healthy and cancerous prostate cells.
</P>
<P>
   The gene directs cells within the prostate to make a protein,
which in turn stimulates cells to grow and divide when testosterone
attaches to the protein.
</P>
<P>
   All men have this gene, but for some inexplicable reason, black
men have shorter versions of a key component called the CAG
repeats. The letters stand for the nucleic-acid bases cytosine,
adenine and guanine.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter variation of the CAG repeats is associated with more
aggressive prostate cancer and malignancy at a younger age.
</P>
<P>
   While researchers continue to seek the biologic reasons for the
sharply higher risks facing African-American men, the American
Cancer Society is urging black men to seek prostate cancer
screening starting at age 40, 10 years sooner than for other men.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to lowering the age for more intensive testing, Moul
thinks physicians should lower the threshold in black men for
acceptable levels of prostate specific antigen, a protein that can
signal the presence of cancer. The protein is measured in the blood
by the widely used prostate specific antigen test (PSA).
</P>
<P>
   For example, a PSA test showing more than 4 nanograms of the
protein per milliliter of blood of a man 40 to 50 years old would
make many doctors suspicious. They might then perform a biopsy of
the prostate, the next level of diagnostic procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Moul believes black men with PSA readings of 2 or more nanograms
should get a biopsy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's top cancer adviser says more aggressive
screening of black men is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern in the black community, in particular the poor
community, is that people will get screened and not be properly
counseled about the possible risks and benefits of having different
kinds of treatments,'' said Dr. Harold Freeman, chairman of the
president's cancer advisory panel and director of surgery at New
York City's Harlem Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``For affluent Americans who get prostate cancer, most would
receive proper counseling and learn about all approaches. They
wouldn't just jump into surgery,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the worrisome statistics for black men, there are
success stories if the cancer is caught in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a death sentence if you act on it in a timely
fashion,'' said Harry Harris. His advice to black men: ``Do
something about it. Don't wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
