<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-SEX-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE A LINK BETWEEN SEX AND PROSTATE CANCER? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a cruel, frightening scientific fact: The male
sex hormone testosterone that fuels sexual desire also fuels
prostate cancer cells and nurtures them into a life-threatening
malignancy.
</P>
<P>
   Eunuchs _ men who lack testes and thus cannot produce
testosterone _ don't get prostate cancer. In fact, castration is a
common treatment to slow the march of prostate cancer by shutting
down the production of testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much a hormonally dependent cancer, at least in
the beginning,'' said Dr. Wael Sakr, associate professor of
pathology at Wayne State University School of Medicine in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   While scientists agree that testosterone helps the cancer grow,
there is no proof that the hormone causes the disease in the first
place, according to Sakr and Dr. Gabriel Haas, chairman of the
department of urology at the State University of New York Health
Science Center in Syracuse, N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   While clear medical sleuths have established clear associations
between prostate cancer and such demographic factors as age or
race, the precise causes of prostate cancer continue to elude
detection;
</P>
<P>
   Haas is exploring one controversial theory about a cause of
prostate cancer. This theory holds that a common sexually
transmitted disease _ the human papillomavirus (HPV) _ infects
prostate cells and in some men ignites the disease, which is then
fueled by the hormone.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, known as HPV, already has been linked to cervical and
penis cancer and may play a role in ovarian cancer and in prostate
cancer, said Haas, who has spent nearly 15 years exploring the
origins of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Haas says the HPV theory also helps explain why eunuchs don't
get prostate cancer. These men would have no exposure to the virus
because they are impotent.
</P>
<P>
   It may also explain why another study found that men with
vasectomies have a higher risk of developing the cancer. Once they
are sterile, these men may have unprotected sex and thus a greater
chance of contracting the virus, Haas said.
</P>
<P>
   The HPV theory was strengthened last year when a National Cancer
Institute study found that men infected with HPV in their youth
were five times more likely to develop prostate cancer in their 50s
and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``HPV may start a chain of events that later translates into
prostate cancer,'' said Dr. Charles Rabkin, an NCI epidemiologist
who led the study.
</P>
<P>
   A separate study published last spring by Swedish-led
researchers found more evidence of a possible link. The study of
Finnish men found that those infected with the virus were 2.6 times
more likely to get prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who subscribe to the HPV theory caution that not all
men who carry the virus get prostate cancer, and not all men who
have prostate cancer have the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virus data is tantalizing, but I would not expect it to be
associated with all cases of prostate cancer,'' said Rabkin.
</P>
<P>
   According to the theory, the virus inserts its deadly genetic
material into the chromosomes of healthy prostate cells. In many
cases, the body's immune system will kill the infected cells or the
cells will die naturally or will repair themselves and become
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But if some infected cells survive, they could turn into
prostate cancer, said Haas. ``Those cells will grow and proliferate
and develop into what we regard as a malignancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Once triggered, prostate cancer cells, like healthy prostate
cells, require male sex hormones to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need both _ the virus to initiate the (start of the
cancer) and you need testosterone to keep those virus-infected
cells alive and proliferating,'' said Haas.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers will continue to study the virus over the next few
years, hoping to prove a conclusive link.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important area of research because if we can
get a handle on it, we will be able to start good preventative
measures,'' said Haas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
