</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-DIAGNOSTIC-TEST-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PSA TEST HAS REVOLUTIONIZED PROSTATE MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A simple blood test has revolutionized prostate
medicine by diagnosing thousands of new cases of prostate cancer
every year in men who have few, if any, outward symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Before the prostate-specific antigen (PSA) test came into
widespread use in the early 1990s, an examining physician would
rely on a finger exam _ a digital rectal examination (DRE) _ to
feel for prostate tumors through the wall of the rectum. This
technique meant that most men were diagnosed in the later stages of
the disease when a cure is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The PSA test makes it possible to detect tumors before they grow
so large that they can be felt during a DRE.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 million PSA blood tests are performed annually,
according to Dr. William Catalona, director of urologic surgery at
Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis and one of
the inventors of the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now seeing earlier and earlier tumors,'' said Catalona.
</P>
<P>
   The test measures a protein produced by epithelial cells within
the prostate. A healthy man should have virtually undetectable
levels of the protein. However, more of these cells are produced
when the body is fighting off a prostate infection, thereby
increasing the protein level. Similarly, the protein level may
shoot up if the epithelial cells turn malignant and, as cancers do,
multiply out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elevated PSA is related to an abnormal proliferation of
certain prostate cells, epithelial only, whether benign or
malignant,'' said Dr. Michael Manyak, chairman of the urology
department at George Washington University Medical Center in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The protein seeps into the blood and thus can be detected in a
blood test.
</P>
<P>
   Results under 4 nanograms per milliliter (ng/ml) are considered
normal, while those over 10 ng/ml suggest a problem. Values between
4 and 10 are borderline.
</P>
<P>
   If the test result is 10 or higher and the patient is not
elderly, doctors will recommend more sophisticated diagnostic
tests, including a six-needle biopsy of the prostate. Urologists
may recommend biopsies for borderline PSA readings, depending on
the results of the DRE, what an ultrasound scan of the gland
reveals, how fast the PSA level is rising and the patient's age.
</P>
<P>
   The PSA test misses about 25 percent of cancers, so a normal PSA
can give false reassurance that cancer is not present. The test
also may provide high readings for such non-cancerous conditions as
enlargement of the prostate or a common prostate infection known as
prostatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Because the PSA test can't distinguish between cancer and benign
afflictions, many men with a high PSA will not have cancer when
biopsied. The PSA also can't distinguish between slow-growing and
fast-moving cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, researchers are developing more accurate tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Food and Drug Administration in March approved a new test
for patients with abnormal PSA readings.
</P>
<P>
   While the traditional PSA test measures the protein when it is
bound chemically to the compound alpa1-antichymotrypsin or
alpha2-macroglobulin, the new test measures levels of ``free'' PSA,
not bound to these substances.
</P>
<P>
   Men with prostate cancer have less ``free PSA'' than men who
have benign conditions. The lower the percentage of free PSA, the
higher the likelihood of cancer. The test's manufacturers claim it
could eliminate 120,000 needless biopsies a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pacific Northwest Cancer Foundation in Seattle is
developing a blood test based on the PSA that will help determine
whether a cancer is aggressive and life threatening or only growing
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center and the Howard
Hughes Medical Institute in New York are researching whether the
presence of a certain protein in the blood called p27 signals
aggressive cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., is working on a new test
that measures a protein similar to PSA called human glandular
kallikrein 2, or HK2. Researchers believe that HK2 measurements
will tell doctors which men with borderline PSA values actually
have cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Catalona said that in the near future doctors routinely will use
several blood tests to help diagnose cancer.
</P>
<P>
   When it was first introduced in 1986, the PSA test was designed
to help doctors monitor patients already battling the cancer
because a climbing PSA typically signals resurgent disease and the
need to change treatments.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, doctors were using the test, along with a
DRE, to diagnose new prostate cancer cases, and by 1994 the Food
and Drug Administration gave its official stamp of approval.
</P>
<P>
   The test was developed by scientists led by Catalona and Dr.
Gerald Murphy of the Pacific Northwest Cancer Foundation. At the
time, both were working at the Roswell Park Cancer Institute in
Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Managed health care plans such as health maintenance
organizations usually will cover the $80 blood test if the patient
is over age 50, or a member of a high-risk group, such as an
African American, or has a strong family history of prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been this way.
</P>
<P>
   A prostate cancer advocacy organization, the Baltimore-based
American Foundation for Urologic Disease, is going state-by-state
asking lawmakers to enact legislation requiring health-care
providers to pay for PSA tests and DRE exams.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, only three states had such a requirement. Now
15 states do and more are on the way. In contrast, nearly all
states require providers to pay for annual mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken us one state at a time,'' said M. Brooke Moran, the
foundation's director of government affairs. ``We are doing this
because some men are having difficulty getting the tests. What we
want is for men not to have to push for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 0936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS     09-22 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS-3TAKES-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSTATE CANCER VICTIMS FACE CONFUSING TREATMENT OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Sept. 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prostate cancer victims face a confusing array of
treatment options, all carrying the risk of such side effects as
impotence or incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   Patients complain that it's often difficult getting an objective
recommendation from medical experts because each physician tends to
champion his or her own speciality.
</P>
<P>
   A urologist might urge surgical removal of the gland; a
radiologist might promote radiation or radioactive ``seed''
implants; and an oncologist might prefer drugs to shut off hormones
feeding the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Choices are becoming even more complex as doctors refine new
treatments such as cryosurgery (freezing of the prostate gland) and
various combinations of treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Medical practioners are trying to determine which treatment is
best, but each new medical study seems to raise more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, a study published this month in the Journal of
the American Medical Association found that patients with
fast-moving prostate cancer lived longer when treated with either
surgery or traditional radiation, rather than seed implants _ an
increasingly popular treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The same study found that men with early-stage cancer fared well
regardless of which treatment they received.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the information out there is very confusing,'' said
Derek Durst, a 50-year-old real estate agent and teacher from San
Francisco, who was diagnosed with prostate cancer in February.
</P>
<P>
   Durst wants to avoid surgical removal of his prostate _ a
radical prostatectomy _ but he's uncertain whether to select
radioactive seed implants or several treatments in sequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I do a combination of hormonal blockade, then seeds and
then radiation?'' he wonders. ``It's very difficult to make a
choice. You have to become your own case manager.''
</P>
<P>
   David Evans, a retired diplomat in Washington, D.C., said that
soon after he was diagnosed in 1992 at age 56, ``I quickly found
out that in prostate cancer the patient bears an overwhelming
responsibility for deciding on his treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc Garnick, an oncologist and internist on the faculty at
the Harvard Medical School, said some cases are ``absolutely black
and white about what needs to get done. The rest of the patients
fit into the bulk of the bell-shaped curve where any one of a
variety of treatment options is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Shipley, the head of genito-urinary radiation
oncology at the Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, advises
patients to interview experienced physicians and learn all they can
about the disease and its treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men should hear various points of view from credible sources,
particularly about the side effects, and get a fair story of the
success rates and then select what suits them best,'' Shipley said.
</P>
<P>
   The bed-rock principles guiding physicians and patients are that
a man can be cured if the disease is caught early and is confined
to the prostate; if not, a cure is less likely, though the disease
may be kept at bay for several years.
</P>
<P>
   For many older men, a cure may not be necessary because they
will die of other causes before the prostate cancer turns lethal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes it complicated,'' said Dr. Howard Scher,
chief of genito-urinary oncology at the Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in New York. ``The major issue is to determine what
the risk of the disease is for the individual patient.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cure'' is a word prostate specialists use cautiously. Some
contend that a successful treatment strategy is to keep the cancer
under control for long periods. In other words, to manage it like a
chronic illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two clocks ticking: your prostate clock and your
life clock,'' said Dr. Alan Partin, a urologist at Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore. ``If I can keep your prostate clock just
behind your life clock, we've cured you, and it may not involve
cutting the prostate out in all men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A cure in prostate cancer means that we are going to allow you
to get to be a very old man and die of something other than
prostate cancer,'' Partin said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, prostate cancer is discovered through a digital
rectal exam and a blood test that measures the amount of prostate
specific antigen (PSA).
</P>
<P>
   For most men who are not elderly, a PSA reading above 10
nanograms per milliliter (ng/ml) will lead the physician to
recommend more sophisticated and expensive diagnostic procedures.
Depending on the man's age and the doctor's policy, a PSA reading
in the borderline zone of 4 to 10 ng/ml also may trigger additional
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Those tests typically include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A six-needle biopsy of the prostate. This will confirm whether
cancer is present in the gland. If it is, the biopsy is graded by a
pathologist on a scale known as the Gleason score. In general,
Gleason scores of 2 to 4 indicate less dangerous tumors in their
early stages, while scores of 8 to 10 indicate aggressive cancers.
Values of 5 to 7 are borderline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ultrasound and MRI scans of the prostate, and a CT scan of the
surrounding pelvic area;
</P>
<P>
   _ A nuclear medicine bone scan to determine if the cancer has
spread to the skeleton, a favorite resting ground for prostate
cancer outside the gland.
</P>
<P>
   _ Surgery to determine if the cancer has spread beyond the gland
to nearby pelvic lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   _ A DNA ploidy analysis that helps assess how fast prostate
cells are growing.
</P>
<P>
   Based on these tests, the physician computes the probability
that the disease is confined to the organ and assigns a code to the
results. A T1 or T2 cancer means the doctor believes the disease is
confined to the prostate, while a T3 or T4 cancer means the cancer
has spread to surrounding tissue.
</P>
<P>
   An N+ tumor means the cancer has spread beyond the gland to
lymph nodes and an M+ cancer, the most advanced stage, indicates
that the cancer has migrated to bones or distant organs.
</P>
<P>
   This ``staging'' of the cancer is not 100 percent accurate,
Shipley points out. Many men who are believed to have
organ-confined disease actually have cancer that has spread outside
the gland.
</P>
<P>
   If the cancer is confined to the gland, surgery or some form of
radiation are the most common treatments and can effectively cure
the patient. Both treatments are particularly effective against
small tumors with Gleason scores of 6 or less and PSA values under
10 ng/ml.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to surgery or radiation, doctors may use drugs to
temporarily halt the body's production of testosterone in order to
shrink the tumors, a procedure known as neoadjuvant hormonal
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   If the cancer has escaped the prostate and migrated into
surrounding tissue, lymph nodes, seminal vesicles or bone, surgery
typically is ruled out because it doesn't do any good to remove the
gland.
</P>
<P>
   About 29 percent of all prostate cancer cases each year are
diagnosed in these more advanced stages when a cure is less likely
and treatment options more ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see a 45-year-old man with a very aggressive tumor, and
I know from the first day I meet him that he will not be curable by
surgery or radiation and will need an alternative,'' said Scher.
</P>
<P>
   For these men, depending upon the spread of the disease,
radiation may be aimed at the gland and the surrounding area, not
as a cure but because radiation can kick the tumor into remission.
</P>
<P>
   Men with advanced disease often are treated to shut down their
testosterone, the cancer's main fuel supply. But cutting off the
hormone supply is a temporary measure. Eventually, when it enters
the most lethal stage the cancer transforms from a disease
dependent on male sex hormones for growth to a cancer that will
grow even when hormones are not present.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, further down the treatment trail is chemotherapy;
in the past toxins haven't been very effective in knocking out
prostate cancer but new progress is being reported.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the major treatment options facing the prostate cancer
patient:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RADICAL PROSTATECTOMY:
</P>
<P>
   The surgical removal of the prostate, a radical prostatectomy,
is the most common treatment for early-stage prostate cancer. The
patient must weigh his chance for a cure against incontinence and
impotence.
</P>
<P>
   The operation usually requires several days in the hospital and
weeks of recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   Patients have varying experiences.
</P>
<P>
   J. William Gadzuk, of Potomac, Md., a physicist for the National
Institute of Standards and Technology, had the operation nearly
four years ago at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, one of the
pioneering institutions for prostate surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole surgical thing was remarkably unremarkable,'' Gadzuk
said. ``I didn't have a lot of discomfort or a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gadzuk said he was left with sexual dysfunction, even
though Johns Hopkins surgeons have developed a technique to protect
the erection nerves located near the gland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has not been as successful as one might have gathered
from the hype,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Author Michael Koorda in his book ``Man to Man'' described a
difficult and often painful recovery after surgery at the same
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Urologists say a patient is a good surgical candidate if he is
under age 70, in good health, with the cancer confined to his gland
and if he can deal with the possible side effects.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RADIATION:
</P>
<P>
   There is little or no pain associated with radiation. However,
impotence, incontinence and even bowel scarring are possible side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Another downside is that there are limits to how much radiation
can be focused on the same area. Too much radiation can kill
healthy tissue by damaging blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer patient Carl Silverstein, of Monticello, N.Y.,
opted for radiation over surgery when he was diagnosed in 1995. A
semi-retired lawyer for the Sullivan County legal aid society,
Silverstein, 69, felt his chances of avoiding incontinence and
impotence were better with radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein underwent 37 radiation sessions, each lasting 5 to
10 minutes, over seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they didn't tell me I was having radiation, I'd think it
was a fraud. It was painless,'' Silverstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in Silverstein's case, the radiation didn't kill
the cancer. After his PSA started to climb again indicating
resurgent cancer, doctors put him on drugs to eliminate his body's
testosterone production.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stephenson, of Chestnut Hill, Mass., a retired executive
with Dupont Co., is a radiation success story. He was diagnosed 14
years ago at age 69 and underwent about the same number of sessions
as Silverstein. His cancer, however, has been in remission ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't say that I'm cured, but I've been extremely
fortunate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRACHYTHERAPY OR SEED IMPLANTS:
</P>
<P>
   Tiny radioactive implants, no bigger than a rye seed and
injected directly into the prostate through the perineum, are an
increasingly popular treatment for early-stage cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure was tried since the 1950s without much success.
</P>
<P>
   After being refined in recent years, seed therapy is coming back
strong. Patient survival statistics are promising, and some doctors
believe it will soon become as common as surgery or beam radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds, which remain permanently embedded, deliver a
radioactive dose inside the gland for up to a year, burning out the
prostate, and, hopefully, the cancer with it. A major benefit is
that seed implants are much less invasive than surgery, requiring
perhaps an overnight stay in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   As with traditional radiation and surgery, the seeds may impair
a man's continence and potency. Some patients require corrective
surgery to the rectum or urethra after treatment.
</P>
<P>
   If the seeds irritate the urethra, which carries urine from the
bladder to the penis and runs through the prostate gland, the
patient often feels the need to urinate.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Marfyaic, from Gettysburg, Pa., a former government worker,
was 59 when he was diagnosed six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I selected seeds because it was much less invasive and was a
relatively new treatment,'' he said. ``It still has drawbacks. The
urgency to urinate becomes part of your life. You start planning
your activities around where the nearest bathroom is.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HORMONE THERAPY:
</P>
<P>
   If prostate cancer spreads beyond the gland, a man usually is
considered incurable. In order to slow the disease, doctors focus
on therapies to rob the cancer of testosterone, which fuels cancer
growth.
</P>
<P>
   This can be done through surgical castration to remove the
testes _ which produce testosterone _ or through chemical
castration by using powerful drugs to block hormone production.
</P>
<P>
   Shutting down testosterone doesn't keep the cancer at bay
forever because the disease eventually finds other substances in
the body to feed it.
</P>
<P>
   David Evans, the retired diplomat, initially had radiation, but
the cancer returned two years later and doctors said castration was
essential for survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was more difficult than the first diagnosis,'' Evans
said. ``Once it's out of the prostate, then you know it's incurable
and you're facing a really serious fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans chose chemical castration over surgical removal of his
testicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least there is a hope that if a magic bullet is found, I
can go back. It's reversible. That's a big psychological
difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Valle, of Phoenix, Ariz., opted for surgical castration,
known as an orchiectomy, after the cancer spread. Valle and his
wife were concerned that chemical castration might not be as
effective in blocking hormone production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put everything down on paper, and I went through a decision-
making process,'' said Valle, a manufacturing executive who was
diagnosed six years ago at age 59. ``I concluded that I am fighting
for my life here. `Right or wrong,' I said, `I'm going with the
orchiectomy.' It was very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The side effects from either treatment can be extreme, including
total loss of sexual desire, facial hair loss, weight gain,
emotional swings and hot flashes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRYOSURGERY:
</P>
<P>
   While not yet in widespread use, this procedure injects liquid
nitrogen, chilled to temperatures minus-320 degrees Fahrenheit,
into the prostate to freeze cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   Budson Ellsworth, from Downey, Calif., chose cryosurgery over
other treatments after he was diagnosed in 1993 at age 55 with
extensive prostate cancer because he felt it offered more hope and
less risk.
</P>
<P>
   In the procedure, a doctor was guided by a rectal ultrasound
probe as he injected the liquid nitrogen through the perineum,
turning Ellsworth's prostate into an ice ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cryosurgery is much less invasive than a radical prostatectomy,
but the side effects in Ellsworth's case were just as severe. He
ended up impotent because the entire gland had to be frozen due to
the extent of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, the cancer spread to his pelvic lymph nodes and he
began hormone therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say that in cases where the tumors are small, the
procedure produces minimal side effects. While there is a limit to
the amount of radiation a person can withstand, cryosurgery
patients can be re-treated if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEMOTHERAPY:
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, chemical toxins were the last-resort defense
against prostate cancer because chemotherapy had little effect
shrinking tumors or extending life.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors now are having better results using chemotherapy in new
combinations, with hormone blocking drugs and with other compounds
when other treatments fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, for a patient with advanced disease, they'd
give him hormonal treatments and then he'd die. Now there are
numerous strategies,'' said Dr. Kenneth Pienta, director of
genito-urinary oncology at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In one such strategy, four drugs _ Adriamycin, Ketoconazole,
Vinblastine, and Estramustine _ are administered during a two-month
period. Compared with traditional chemo, the combinations are
better able to target and kill prostate cancer cells while
minimizing damage to healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   Pienta says some patients survive up to two years on the
combined chemotherapies. ``The potential for the prostate cancer
death rate to go down a lot over the next five years is quite
high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also are examining the use of new chemotherapy
combinations as a frontline treatment for early-stage prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While researchers are trying to make the drugs more tolerable,
the side effects can be severe, including hair loss, vomiting and
lowered blood counts that make the body vulnerable to infection.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WATCHFUL WAITING:
</P>
<P>
   Because prostate cancer is often slow-growing, some physicians
may advise elderly men or those with a life expectancy of less than
10 years due to other illnesses to do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption here is that the patient won't be cured of the
disease and will likely die with it rather than from it. Under the
``watchful waiting'' approach, the physician may recommend
non-curative treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to these men, usually in their upper 70s, `Look, you've
got prostate cancer. But it's not time yet to pull the trigger. Why
bother with the side effects of treatments?''' said Shipley.
</P>
<P>
   Watchful waiting is not advisable for men under 65 with
non-aggressive tumors that are potentially curable.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Marfyaic chose to wait two and one-half years after being
diagnosed with early-stage prostate cancer. He then settled on
radioactive seed therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was slow growing and I figured I had time to make a
decision'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Garnick believes watchful waiting is risky for men like
Marfyaic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that such patients should be treated with curative
intent rather than observed. The latter practice potentially allows
the cancer to grow, metastasize and become incurable,'' Garnick
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 0941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-SURGERY-$ADV28-HN     09-22 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-SURGERY-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RADICAL PROSTATECTOMY: UP CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Sept. 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The operation to remove the patient's prostate
gland gets underway in Operating Room No. 11 at Walter Reed Army
Medical Center at 8:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons make a vertical incision about five inches long
from below the man's navel to the base of his penis. Then, they
slowly dissect down into the abdomen, cutting through layers of
skin, fat and muscle. Retractors on each side of the abdominal wall
expand the field of vision to reveal the goal nestled beneath the
bladder and next to the rectum: a cancerous prostate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David McLeod, 63, an Army colonel, wants to remove the gland
in an effort to cure the man of a disease that will kill 39,200
American men this year.
</P>
<P>
   The patient, a 51-year-old non-commissioned Army officer, is
under anesthesia and connected to the gadgetry of modern medical
technology. His lungs rise and fall to the clicking of a respirator
while a web of tubes carry fluids to the veins in his arms.
</P>
<P>
   One tube, red with blood, sucks liquid from the abdominal cavity
into a container to the side of the operating table. A blue linen
divider shields the patient's head from the heat of the surgical
lamps and provides the anesthesiologist with a separate work area.
The divider also blocks the surgeons' view of the patient's face.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod estimates he has performed over 1,000 of these operations
in his 14 years as chief of urology at Walter Reed, one of the
military's top medical centers. He has removed the cancerous
prostates of former Sen. Bob Dole and retired Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf, among other Washington notables.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney as well as a surgeon, McLeod, 63, is a Civil War
buff when he's not taking out prostates. A biography of the
Confederate general Stonewall Jackson sits on his desk near an
anatomical model of the gland.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the operating room is intense, as McLeod directs his
team with a surgical shorthand born of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reduce the odds of getting in trouble if you stay
focused,'' he tells a reporter. ``I like to approach it like I'm
going to make a parachute jump. It is stressful. I don't rest easy
until the prostate is over there,'' pointing to a stainless steel
table nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former GOP presidential nominee and Kansas senator,
chose McLeod for his prostatectomy, even though some top civilian
surgeons had invited him to be their patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Dr. McLeod and that he'd done a lot of operations, from
privates, to sergeants, to colonels, generals and foreign
dignitaries. I decided that he had the skills and he was interested
in me as a person, not just as a patient,'' Dole said recently,
recalling his Walter Reed surgery in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The surgical removal of the prostate _ a radical prostatectomy _
is the most common treatment for early-stage prostate cancer, but
not all men with cancerous prostates choose that remedy.
</P>
<P>
   If the Army patient didn't want surgery, he might have chosen
radiation, either external beam radiation or radioactive ``seeds''
implanted directly in the gland.
</P>
<P>
   This patient is a good surgical candidate. He is young and
generally healthy. Furthermore, McLeod believes the disease is
confined to the gland, though he won't know until pathologists
examine slices of the gland under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   The man was diagnosed by the PSA blood test and a finger exam of
the prostate through the rectum wall. Because the PSA was high, the
gland was biopsied by inserting needles through the rectum wall.
The biopsy showed cancer.
</P>
<P>
   To remove the prostate, surgeons have the choice of two routes,
either through the abdomen, known as a retropubic approach, or
through the perineum, the area between the anus and scrotum.
</P>
<P>
   The choice depends on which method the surgeon is most
comfortable with and whether the surgeon wants to remove pelvic
lymph nodes so they can be checked to find out if the cancer has
spread. The nodes are not taken out in the perineum method.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod, who does both procedures, chose the retropubic approach
for this operation because he wants to remove the lymph nodes for
study.
</P>
<P>
   In either operation, the patient's sexual potency is placed at
risk because the nerves controlling erections run in layers of
tissue alongside the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do all we can to save those nerves,'' McLeod
says.
</P>
<P>
   To remove the prostate, the erection nerves must be carefully
peeled back. But sometimes they are severed, either accidentally or
deliberately. The surgeon would cut into the nerves if he or she
determines that the cancer has spread beyond the gland and that it
would be best for the patient's overall survival to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible side effect is urinary incontinence. To remove
the prostate, the urethra _ a tube which carries urine from the
bladder through the prostate and to the penis _ must be snipped and
then reattached.
</P>
<P>
   A pale blue catheter inserted into the patient's penis and
extending toward the bladder helps McLeod, assisting surgeon Dr.
Pierce Irby and Dr. George Stackhouse, the chief urologic resident,
locate the urethra and trace it to the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   Because Walter Reed is a teaching hospital, a medical student
stands alongside Irby and observes the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   As McLeod reaches into the abdominal cavity, his entire gloved
hand seems lost inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small prostate,'' he tells the team, feeling the
normally smooth and rubbery organ for bumps that might indicate the
extent of disease.
</P>
<P>
   Though the gland is in reach, more than an hour is spent tying
off surrounding blood vessels to reduce blood loss. The surgeon
then teases back the tissue that contains the nerve bundles. At
times, as many as three pairs of hands are working in the cavity
that occasionally has to be cleared of oozing blood with a suction
tube and gauze pads.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, a prostatectomy would have been much
bloodier because surgeons lacked a full understanding of the blood
vessel anatomy in the pelvic region. A patient would donate blood
before the procedure for use in any transfusion to make up for
blood loss.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod manipulates the catheter and snips the urethra at one end
of the prostate. He carefully teases back more tissue and then
snips the urethra at the other end where it joins the bladder. He
then places a segment of the blue catheter through the holes in the
gland where the urethra entered and exited and clamps the ends
together. The gland _ now attached only to the back of the pelvic
wall _ looks like a bead on a string.
</P>
<P>
   The tubing allows him to move the prostate in several directions
as he separates it on all sides from tissue and blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours after the operation began, the prostate is out.
Also removed are the seminal vesicles, glands that produce some of
the seminal fluid, which are attached to the gland.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod examines the roundish red-purple organ, about two inches
across, under the glare of the operating room's lights. He's
optimistic the disease is confined to the gland, however he won't
know for sure until a pathologist later examines slivers of the
prostate under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   If the pathologist determines that the cancer microscopically
extends through the wall of the gland, the cancer may have spread,
making the patient's long-term prognosis less hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear to be outside the prostate,'' he says.
``We've probably made this man disease-free. I don't like to use
the word `cure' because there is no guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   McLeod says he has saved the erection nerve bundles, though he
concedes the operation most likely will take a toll on the
patient's sexual potency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many men never make it back to 100 percent. It's more like 70
percent,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   By noon the patient's urethra is reattached, the cavity is
irrigated with water and drained, and the medical assistants do one
more count to make sure all the equipment is accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The man's abdominal muscles are sewn up and the skin's incision
stapled shut. A catheter to carry urine from the bladder is
inserted and will remain for several days until the urethra heals,
while a tube is inserted in a tiny incision in the pelvic cavity to
drain blood.
</P>
<P>
   The anesthesia is reduced and the patient is transferred to a
recovery room.
</P>
<P>
   Irby checks into an adjoining operating room where he is
scheduled for another operation. McLeod is off to meet a patient
and discuss the pros and cons of Viagra, the impotence drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
