<SLUG> BC-PCA-IMPOTENCE-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL PROBLEMS ARE A COMMON SIDE-EFFECT OF TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Sept. 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The most common treatments for early-stage prostate
cancer _ surgery or radiation _ will likely reduce a man's sexual
potency.
</P>
<P>
   The treatments can pose a daunting choice between normal sexual
function and a potential cancer cure, between chances for a longer
life and the quality of that life.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Howard Waage, an insurance inspector from La
Selva Beach, Calif., who was diagnosed with prostate cancer two
years ago at age 49. He recalled being overwhelmed at learning how
many men had lost sexual function after they sought treatment. He
was shocked that some of those patients were considering penile
implants and impotence medication to restore at least some sexual
function.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first support meeting I went to they brought out vacuum
pumps and the like,'' Waage said. ``It just scared the heck out of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatments for prostate cancer tinker with an uniquely male
reproductive organ and the surrounding nerve clusters that control
erections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything vital to a man is down in that area,'' said Waage.
</P>
<P>
   Surgical removal of the prostate, a radical prostatectomy, is
the most common treatment for early stage cancer that has not
spread beyond the gland. The use of the procedure has increased
almost six-fold between 1984 and 1990, in part due to surgical
advances designed to protect the nerves surrounding the gland,
according to the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the improved ``nerve-sparing'' techniques, at least some
damage to the two nerve bundles controlling erections is common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very seldom do I see a patient who says, `My erections are as
good as they were before surgery,''' said Dr. David McLeod, a
surgeon and chief of urology at Walter Reed Army Medical Center in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod has removed the cancerous prostates of several U.S.
lawmakers, including then-Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kans., and Sens. Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska, and Richard Shelby, R-Ala., as well as that of
retired Army Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf.
</P>
<P>
   To show how easily the nerves can be damaged, McLeod moistened a
piece of toilet paper and placed it like a shroud around his
outstretched fist. The clinging tissue represented the nerve-rich
tissue and the fist represented the gland.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve bundles are not clearly defined cables, easily pushed
aside to gain access to the prostate. Rather, they are meshed
within the adjacent tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you want to do, in order to preserve the nerve bundles,
is you have to carefully peel the tissue off,'' McLeod said, gently
teasing back the wet toilet tissue from his fist.
</P>
<P>
   The nerves often are bruised in the process, which will not
cause permanent impotence. But if a surgeon believes the cancer may
have spread into surrounding tissue, one or two bundles may be
removed along with the cancerous gland.
</P>
<P>
   A man can retain some normal sexual function with one bundle
severed, but not when both are lost.
</P>
<P>
   Many men elect not to have this surgery because of the
potentially serious side effects.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Derek Durst, a 50-year-old real estate agent and
teacher from San Francisco, who was diagnosed with the cancer in
February, said he didn't want the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``A radical prostatectomy is out,'' said Durst. ``I think of it
as butchery. I'm just not convinced the nerve-sparing technique
even works that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Marfyaic, a former government worker from Gettysburg, Pa.,
was 59 years-old when he was diagnosed six years ago. But he turned
down surgery because he had recently remarried and didn't want to
impair his sexual function.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, I'm not ready to give up my sex life yet and I sure
don't want to wear a diaper,'' said Marfyaic, referring to urinary
incontinence, another possible side effect of surgery or radiation.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the younger the patient, the better the odds of
preserving sexual potency. However, doctors report varying success
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patrick Walsh, the chairman of the urology department at
Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, has reported some of the
best results: 91 percent of his patients under 50 years of age
remained potent after prostate removal, as did 75 percent of men 50
to 60 years-old and 25 percent of men over age 70. Walsh is one of
the developers of the nerve-sparing surgical technique.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by the Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston
reported far worse outcomes. Only 25 percent of patients there
claimed sexual potency one year following nerve-sparing surgery.
What's more, only 7 percent said they had erections that they
consider adequate for intercourse, according to the study published
in January in the Journal of Clinical Oncology.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts General doctors contend that their study is a
more honest examination of patient outcomes because it wasn't
conducted by the doctors treating the patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have observed patient reluctance to report problems to
their physicians,'' the study said. ``As a result, reports from
providers that accurately reflect what patients tell them may
document substantially fewer problems than patients report to
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible explanation is that patients in the
Massachusetts General study simply may have had more advanced
disease or worse pre-treatment erection function than patients at
Johns Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the question of surgical skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people weren't treated by doctors who were as expert in
doing the operations,'' Dr. Alan Partin, a urologist at Johns
Hopkins, said of the Mass General study. ``I do about 150 to 200
operations a year. In general, you've got to get a little better
doing that many.''
</P>
<P>
   External beam radiation to the prostate _ another common therapy
_ also can destroy the same erection nerves.
</P>
<P>
   About 67 percent of men treated at Massachusetts General
Hospital with radiation reported sexual potency after one year
following treatments, but only 33 percent said their erections were
sufficient for intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Marfyiac, who shares his experiences with men trying to make
treatment decisions, said the bottom line is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what treatment a man selects, there is a potential
side effect,'' he said. ``I can't guarantee that you'll have the
same functional ability that you had before. Life will change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
