<SLUG> BC-PCA-POLITICS-2TAKES-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSTATE CANCER ADVOCATES COMPLAIN THAT U.S. SKIMPS RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Sept. 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jerry Donohue, prostate cancer patient, is spending
what time he has left collecting signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, 62, of Bellmore, N.Y., leads an effort on Long Island
aimed at building grass-roots pressure on Congress to spend more
money for prostate cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   He's in a hurry because there's no treatment for him and
thousands like him. The cancer has invaded his bones where blood is
produced. His PSA, which measures a substance produced by prostate
cells, has risen to 2,700; a normal PSA reading is 4 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, who is married with three grown children, takes a daily
dose of morphine to numb his pain. If his health permits, he plans
to start experimental chemotherapy, a treatment in part made
possible by federal research dollars.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Donohue, an environmental engineer with a consulting
firm, has helped collect nearly 15,000 signatures on a petition
that asks President Clinton and Congress ``to commit to eradicating
prostate cancer, the leading form of cancer in men, by increasing
funding for research and making prostate cancer a national
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been at it for two years, standing at shopping malls,
chatting up his auto mechanic, his electrician, the plumber and
barber, going to cancer support groups, bending the ears of anyone
who will listen, sign the petition and pass it on.
</P>
<P>
   Many people consider the topic too embarrassing to discuss, much
less sign a petition demanding more government help fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   Men generally don't like to talk about the cancer and its
treatments, which can diminish sexual function and bladder control.
Donohue recalls with disbelief the reluctance even of men suffering
from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys say, `No, I don't want my name on anything. I don't
want to get involved,''' said Donohue. ``I say, `Let me get this
straight _ you've got prostate cancer and you don't want to sign?'
It's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Waage, a prostate cancer patient from La Selva Beach,
Calif., who attends several support groups prostate cancer victims,
agrees about the male inability to talk about such personal
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women can talk about stuff, but men have a hard time talking
about sexuality,'' said Waage.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassed _ and silent _ patient group is one explanation
for the relatively small federal investment in prostate cancer
research, even though the disease is the second leading cause of
cancer deaths among American men.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress hands out research money, cash flows to the
projects demanded by the loudest and best organized health lobby
groups. The result: Federal research spending on breast cancer and
AIDS far exceeds spending on prostate cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just not vocal enough,'' said Rep. Michael Bilirakis,
R-Fla., the chairman of the House Commerce health subcommittee,
referring to the prostate cancer lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason there is so much money spent on breast cancer is
that there is a tremendous breast cancer lobby,'' said Dr. Kenneth
Pienta, director of genito-urinary oncology at the University of
Michigan, one of the nation's top cancer research centers. ``The
AIDS people also have a great lobby and they receive a lot of
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer and prostate cancer killed about the same number
of Americans in 1997 _ 43,900 women and 41,800 men, respectively _
while about 14,000 people died from AIDs-related illnesses last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health (which includes the National
Cancer Institute) spent about $107,214 in AIDS research for every
AIDS-related death that year; $9,362 in breast cancer research for
every breast cancer death; and $2,512 in prostate cancer research
for every prostate cancer death.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 through 1997, the National Cancer Institute spent $371
million on prostate cancer research. By comparison, NCI spent
nearly $1.67 billion for breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers have steered away from investigating prostate
cancer because money is more plentiful for other kinds of work.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Cowan, a scientist at Technica Inc., a small Orlando,
Fla., start-up company developing a new generation of radiation
machinery, said he would like to do additional work on prostate
cancer partly because of a personal interest: His own cancerous
prostate was removed several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Cowan instead is focusing on breast cancer ``because there
is more money out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pienta makes the same point. ``We chase dollars as well as
anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal money makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   By subsidizing research or sponsoring clinical trials, the money
often translates into life-saving or life-extending therapies. Two
examples are the drug AZT for AIDs patients and new chemotherapies
for women with aggressive strains of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of prostate cancer cases is expected to continue to
rise faster than any other cancer during the remainder of this
decade, further increasing costs in an already stressed health care
system,'' warned the American Association for Cancer Research,
which represents 14,000 cancer researchers and publishes four
scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
