<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONSUMER COLUMN: You'll see in 3-D for years to come
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a game that requires 3-D glasses. The cheap, paper
ones that came with it are almost ruined. Do you know who sells
high-quality 3-D glasses?
</P>
<P>
   _Keith McLaughlin
</P>
<P>
   A: For 3-D glasses (one blue lens, one red lens) in a plastic or
rubber frame, contact Rainbow Symphony at (800) 821-5122 or Reel
3-D Enterprises at (310) 837-2368. Reel 3-D also sells clip-ons for
customers with prescription eyewear.
</P>
<P>
   Need a fast pair of paper 3-D glasses? Send $1 in a stamped,
self-addressed envelope to Dimension 3, 256 S. Robertson Blvd.,
Beverly Hills, Calif. 90211. This promotion is offered to help
people enjoy the company's 3-D Web site at www.dimension3d.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The builder for my house is using finger-jointed wood and I
am not happy with that. I asked if this is inferior to the normal
wood and they said it's actually better.
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, the reason for using finger-jointed wood is to
save money, not for structural superiority. What is your advice?
</P>
<P>
   _Teo Giang
</P>
<P>
   A:As the consumer, you may specify what materials are used in
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Some contractors prefer finger-jointed wood (shorter sections of
wood united by a curved joint) because it warps less and is
straighter than some stud lumber. Prices are similar. You are more
likely to see finger-jointed wood used in trim pieces that are to
be painted. Paint-grade, finger-jointed trim costs less than
stain-grade, plain lumber. (I have some at my house.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true there is an office or headquarters in Texas for
UFO followers or for people to get information on UFOs ?
</P>
<P>
   _Rudy Salazar
</P>
<P>
   A:You are looking for MUFON, the Mutual UFO Network, 103
Oldtowne Road, Seguin 78155-4099. This organization has been in
Seguin for 23 years as part of an international network of those
interested in unidentified flying objects.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Recently I visited a friend in a wealthy Austin area. All the
parking spots in front of his house were taken, so I parked in
front of his neighbor's house _ making sure it was not blocking
anything. There weren't any ``No Parking'' signs, nor was the house
on the corner.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned I found a note: ``Please DO NOT park your car in
front of OUR house.''
</P>
<P>
   Was I wrong, or was the neighbor out of line? My car is not an
eyesore. What are city rules regarding this matter?
</P>
<P>
   _S. Pratap
</P>
<P>
   A:Out of line, not to mention just plain rude (well, they did
say ``please'').
</P>
<P>
   Not blocking the driveway or sidewalk? No other place to park?
Absent ``No Parking'' signs? Not parking all-day, every day? The
note was uncalled for _ just be glad this is not your neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The resident does not own the street in front of the house.
``Parking on a public street cannot be restricted by homeowners,''
says Austin Police Department's Lolita Slagle.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Driving through a lightning storm, I saw a blinding flash to
my right and left. At the same instant, bands of hair on the top of
my head and my left arm were briefly drawn upward. I thought my car
was struck by lightning, but there was no thunderclap. Did I not
hear the thunder since I was at the point of origin for the sound
waves? Can you verify this effect?
</P>
<P>
   _Mike Keyes
</P>
<P>
   A:Lucky guy. A car is one of the safest places to be in a
lightning storm (metal, not fiberglass _ garage the Vette or the
ragtop if a storm brews).
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kithil, founder of the National Lightning Safety
Institute, says the thunder could have been too far away or been
dimmed by your radio or closed windows. Thunder is the ``acoustical
shock wave of the electrical event,'' Kithil said.
</P>
<P>
   You may not remember the thunder. Short-term memory loss is
characteristic of lightning victims (as is the hair-raising and
involuntary muscle spasm). The car's metal conducted the
electricity around you, although some was conveyed through the
steering wheel. It is a myth that the rubber tires ground you.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of Personal Lightning Safety Tips, check
austin360.com under my name, see the Safety Institute's Web site at
www.lightningsafety.com or send me a stamped, self-addressed
envelope.Q: I'm going to be Special Agent Dana Scully (from ``The
X-Files'') for Halloween. I'm a perfectionist, so I need an FBI
wallet ID and FBI ID tag. Can I find them in a costume shop?
</P>
<P>
   I'll also need a nice, reasonably priced dress suit. My mom
suggested Goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   _R.N.
</P>
<P>
   A:Your mom is right. Pick up a Scully suit at a thrift shop;
Goodwill, Sacks II or the Junior League Thrift Shop come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Costume shops sell rather than rent accessories. Lucy in
Disguise sells badges for less than $10. For the Real McCoy, try
places supplying public safety professionals, such as Gall's Inc.
at (800) 477-7766. Locally, visit GT Distributors, 5426 Guadalupe
St. or (800) 443-6283, which sells ID holders and wallets. Both
limit items sold to nonprofessionals.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I watch educational programs on archaeology. Many of these
programs are entertaining and informative. However, something
bothers me a bit about watching people and their artifacts being
dug up. So, when does grave robbery stop being desecration and
start being archaeology?
</P>
<P>
   _Scott Lewis
</P>
<P>
   A:Next time send me a controversial question _ like creationism
vs. evolution ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Grave robbing has nothing to do with archaeology,'' says UT
professor and director of the Texas Archaeological Research Lab Tom
Hester. In Texas, most excavations are done as salvage efforts _ a
highway coming through, land development, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Laws governing archeological digs vary from country to country
and, in the United States, from state to state. Attitudes also vary
from culture to culture. Here, for example, federal laws protect
the remains of Native Americans on federal or tribal lands.Although
the study of burial sites is controversial, Hester maintains
prehistoric bones have a story to tell (diet, disease, environment)
that cannot be otherwise obtained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digging up sites without scientific methods and goals is not
archaeology,'' continues Hester. ``Texas is plagued by those
digging up archaeological and burial sites for profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspect such activity? Contact the State Archaeologist, Patricia
Mercado-Allinger, at 463-6090.
</P>
<P>
   Q:In all my years I must have been told this but it went over my
head. Who buried the men who were killed at the Alamo? When and
where?
</P>
<P>
   _Louis Pabor
</P>
<P>
   A:The bodies of the Alamo defenders were burned, not buried, by
the Mexican army. One defender, Gregorio Esparza, was buried by his
brother Francisco, a member of Santa Anna's army who was not part
of the Alamo assault.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Mexican dead were buried; some corpses were put in
the San Antonio River, according to T.R. FehrenbachQ: My
grandfather was recently widowed and needs help.
</P>
<P>
   He and grandmother had a joint will, in which the survivor is
the sole heir.
</P>
<P>
   Does he need to file the will with the court house? I suggested
he ask the attorney who handled the will, but he says the attorney
will charge a fee to answer that question. Sounds strange, but
Granddaddy has very little money.
</P>
<P>
   _P.M.
</P>
<P>
   A:Attorney Lee Vanderburg of Barton and Vanderburg, P.C. says,
``Probate in Texas is simple and relatively inexpensive.'' It costs
$79 to file a will for probate in Titus County.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Titus County Clerk's office, the judge
presiding in probate matters allows individuals to come to court
pro se (without a lawyer) to probate a will if you have all the
necessary papers (an attorney can prepare the papers for a nominal
fee).
</P>
<P>
   If the only asset is a joint checking account with the right of
survivorship, then probate is not necessary, Vanderburg says. But
if your grandmother owned an interest in real property (a house?
land?) then a probated will provides a clean title trail for heirs
when your grandfather dies.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors: Did your grandmother have separate property
acquired before marriage? Descendants from a prior marriage?
</P>
<P>
   Your grandparents elected to draw up a will with an attorney.
Seems one more call would be worth it to put affairs in order.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Has Vince McMahon ever said, `` ... lllllet's get ready to
rrrrrumble'' on the television? If not, who says this?
</P>
<P>
   _S.R.S.
</P>
<P>
   A:Beefy wrestling promoter McMahon may have said it, but the man
behind the oft-quoted phrase is Philadelphia ring announcer Michael
Buffer. Buffer's trademark began about 15 years ago in the boxing
ring and has won him 15 minutes of bow-tied, golden-throated fame.
Q: We deposited $800 in cash after 3 p.m. on a Friday at
NationsBank and expected it would be processed and credited the
next business day, Monday. But the cash was not credited until
midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Three checks came in on Monday and bounced. We were charged. At
another bank, deposits are credited the next day, before checks are
subtracted, and this wouldn't have occurred. Can NationsBank
``hold'' cash deposits? Is there an agency to contact about this
apparent injustice?
</P>
<P>
   _C. T.
</P>
<P>
   A:Cutting it close. ``The bank is entirely within regulatory
standards,'' says Texas Bankers Association's Dawn Duplantier. No
law governs the order in which a bank must process deposits or
checks. NationsBanks regional executive Andy Elliott urges you to
contact the bank and see about recouping the bounced check fees.
Banking is a competitive industry, so shop around.
</P>
<P>
   To complain about nationally chartered banks, write to
Comptroller of the Currency, 1600 Lincoln Plaza, 500 N. Akard St.,
Dallas 75201-3394; for state-chartered banks, Department of
Banking, State of Texas, 2601 N. Lamar Blvd., Austin, 78705-4294.
</P>
<P>
   Q:When I was in New York, I read about repelling silverfish. You
place gum, still wrapped, in areas where you find silverfish. It
really worked. I can't remember what kind of gum. It was one of the
Wrigleys.
</P>
<P>
   _Gloria Eckstrom
</P>
<P>
   A:Spearmint.
</P>
<P>
   The Wrigley's folks have no data on this particular use.
(Wrigley's Spearmint was introduced in 1893.) But Joey Green, in
``Paint Your House with Powdered Milk,'' suggests that, when placed
near open packages of pasta, this flavor repels pests. Keep me
posted.
</P>
<P>
   Are you a twin by any chance? Wrigley's ad agency hires the
talent for the famous Doublemint commercials: BBDO/Chicago, 410
North Michigan Ave., Chicago, Ill. 60611. It's worth a shot!Q: I am
about to graduate with a degree in international relations and am
interested in a diplomatic service job. I am looking for the
addresses of Amnesty International and the United Nations to send
my resume.
</P>
<P>
   _Melee Morgan-Powell
</P>
<P>
   A:Here are some addresses _ electronic and otherwise _ for the
job hunt. Amnesty International recruits by country. To begin in
the United States, contact the organization by e-mail at
admin-us(at)aiusa.org or write to the regional office: 131 Ponce De
Leon Ave., NE, Suite 220, Atlanta, Ga. 30308.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is you are interested in the junior professional level
at the United Nations. Send your inquiry to: United Nations,
Examinations and Tests Section, Division for Staff Development and
Performance, Policy and Specialist Services, Office of Human
Resources Management, Room S-2590 , New York, N.Y. 10017.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROARReader Mary Miller reports hot water and
ammonia in the sink or bathtub soaks oven racks clean. Miller says
you need only four things to keep your home clean: bleach, ammonia,
vinegar and baking soda.
</P>
<P>
   What reads like a bill and looks like a bill but may not be a
bill? Some mailings readers have received from Time magazine. These
``bills'' or ``invoices'' are really subscription solicitations.
Last year the magazine agreed not to send such solicitations to
Texans. Send a copy of suspicious mailings to Assistant Attorney
General Arthur Weiss, Consumer Protection Division, P.O. Box 12548,
Austin 78711.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are always on the lookout for new ways to add meaning to
a wedding or a funeral service. How about releasing butterflies _
either individually or by the cage? Painted ladies and monarchs are
two of the species available (all native to Texas) from Traveling
Naturalists (474-9181). Individual butterflies come packaged in
envelopes with the honorees' names _ ready for release. (Before
long someone will want to release Barton Springs salamanders!)
</P>
