<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-POLITICS-2NDTAKE-     09-22 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-POLITICS-2NDTAKE-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON:scientific journals.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Therefore, increased funding today for prostate cancer
research would be a wise investment,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sheldon Marks, a urologist in Tucson, Ariz., and author of
the book ``Prostate &AMP; Cancer,'' angrily declares: ``Look at how
breast cancer devastates this country and look at the dollars spent
in research. And then look at prostate cancer and how it devastates
_ (but) it gets only a fraction of the money.''
</P>
<P>
   There are signs the federal government is awakening to the
problem, the most public of which is a new commemorative
first-class postage stamp to raise prostate cancer awareness.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is a growing willingness by prominent prostate cancer
victims to speak out about their disease.
</P>
<P>
   Public testimonials about the need for men to get tested have
come from such well-known prostate cancer survivors as former Sen.
Bob Dole, retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf, Sens. Richard Shelby,
R-Ala., and Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, golfing great Arnold Palmer, NFL
legend Len Dawson, Intel founder Andy Grove, and Michael Milken,
the junk bond king.
</P>
<P>
   The funding plight has now caught the attention of the White
House. Earlier this year, President Clinton devoted his weekly
radio address to prostate cancer and pledged more federal research
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``For far too long, too little was known about prostate cancer.
Too little was said about it, out of embarrassment and fear.
Because of this, too little was done about it, as precious research
dollars were spent on other problems,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Senate lawmakers are seeking to boost NIH's
annual prostate cancer budget to about $175 million, from this
year's $114 million. Prostate cancer research proponents also are
trying to get at least $40 million from the Pentagon's annual
budget, which funds over $100 million each year for breast cancer
research.
</P>
<P>
   But the task won't be easy. In the House, Speaker Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., has expressed concern about what he views as the
politicization of cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am opposed to getting into political health research, where
every group shows up with their banner, and their slogan, and their
calculations,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very politics that led AIDS to become a politically
desirable thing to do research in is wrong. It distorts the
research process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prostate funding levels likely won't be decided until later
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to boost federal research and raise the profile of
prostate cancer, a new lobbying group, the National Prostate Cancer
Coalition, opened its doors about two miles from the Capitol last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hedlund, the group's president, said government funding
barely makes a dent in what the organization thinks could be
fruitful research. With the help of top cancer researchers, the
group has identified $250 million in promising prostate cancer
research projects that the government and private industry turned
away last year because of a lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by money from pharmaceutical companies, the American
Cancer Society and Michael Milken, the group has hired Vin Weber, a
former Republican congressman from Minnesota, as its chief
lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   One of Weber's first duties was to help train 50 activists from
key congressional districts around the country on how to get
Congress to take note of the toll the disease takes on men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing for us to tell a member of Congress to do more
on prostate cancer,'' said Hedlund. ``But it's another thing for a
member to go back home and hear somebody say, `Why the hell aren't
you doing more on this?''
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer activists point to 1997 as a fateful year that
reinforced the need for a Washington presence when Congress voted
to delay until 2000 Medicare coverage for prostate cancer
screening.
</P>
<P>
   The delay comes with a price: As many as 24,000 men might die
who otherwise would have received screening and subsequent
treatment, according to the Baltimore-based American Urologic
Disease Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is unfair,'' said Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., who has
introduced legislation to cover screening starting this year.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of politics and disease advocacy worries
President Clinton's top cancer adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that's not quite right about developing
armies of people who are fighting for one disease,'' said Dr.
Harold Freeman, chairman of Clinton's cancer advisory panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are good things about political pressure, but on the
other hand, it would be better if the scientific world could move
in its own logical direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A cure for prostate cancer may come from other scientific
disciplines, such as molecular biology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But men like Jerry Donohue don't have time to wait and see if
Freeman is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make long-term plans,'' Donohue said. ``I take it as
it comes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
