<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Laugh meter'' isn't so funny, all of a sudden
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ I have an idea for a television game show.
I'll call it, ``Can You Top This?''
</P>
<P>
   The name is not new, I confess. It's stolen from an old radio
show I used to listen to when I was a kid. I loved it. Four or five
funny guys would get together once a week and tell jokes. One would
tell a story and then dare the others to tell a funnier one.
Winners were determined by audience response which was measured on
something called a ``laugh meter.''
</P>
<P>
   My show will be just as funny as ``Can You Top This?'' even
though the contestants won't be joking. Participants will be
limited to political candidates wishing to get a head start on the
campaign trail by artlessly confessing all of their past sins
before their opponents can dig up something on them. Great idea,
huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen,'' the moderator will begin, ``our first
guest tonight is running for
</P>
<P>
   office in Ogden, Utah. Let's welcome Lewis Lackluster.''
Applause as Lewis adjusts his
</P>
<P>
   hangdog look and shambles into the bulletproof glass booth.
``All right, Lewis,'' the unctuous emcee will drone, ``it's
confession time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans,'' Lewie begins, pulling a well-fingered
list from his breast pocket,
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 38 sins to confess - 29 more than my opponent who would
have you believe he's
</P>
<P>
   the biggest sinner in the county. Why folks, I was sinning
before that boy was born. I wasn't hardly out of knee pants before
I was pilfering penny candy from the corner store. By the time I
was twelve, I was drinking beer, and smoking behind the barn....''
Lewie babbles on, each successive sin a little more lurid than the
one before until finally the audience interrupts with an audible
groan, indicating they're unable to endure any more.
</P>
<P>
   The moderator signals Lewie that his time is up. ``Great job,
Lewie,'' he exults. Your audience gross-out time is a near record.
Now you have 30 seconds for contrition.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously a drained and broken man, Lewie manages to squeeze out
a tear as he promises that if folks will vote for him they have his
word he'll go and sin no more.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the possibilities here. No ugly surprises ten or twelve
years down the road. Past
</P>
<P>
   sins in all of their disgusting detail will have been publicly
atoned for in advance, thereby
</P>
<P>
   precluding the need for special prosecutors, costly
inquisitions, and nose jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And for all of the wannabes who find themselves a little light
on the tote board of sins, the show's producers will supply a
listing of the top two hundred in order to provide contestants with
a multiple choice situation wherein they can order sin like Chinese
food _ one from column A and two from column B.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe we could even work a deal for future sins _
lame duck specials for
</P>
<P>
   the guy on the way out. Three adulteries and two perjuries, with
residuals going to the
</P>
<P>
   officeholder-elect.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Americans, I'm sick of what's going on in Washington.
I'm up to here with lies and deception, particularly when I wasn't
particularly concerned with our president's moral dilemma in the
first place. My feelings were: Okay, he's in, but soon he'll be out
and it'll all be over. Let history deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   But the beat goes on and now Americans are being held captive in
a world of contrition,
</P>
<P>
   confession, and rampant speculation. I don't know how you feel
about it, but my ``laugh meter'' is just about pegged out. Worst of
all, I hate watching Newt Gingrich pretend he isn't loving every
minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
