<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-TERMPAPER23-COX     09-22 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-TERMPAPER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Using Web term papers nets students bad grades
 &HT;    By Kevin Tankersley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's midnight, and that research paper is due at 8 a.m. Yes, it
was assigned a month ago, but there just hasn't been time to work
on it much. Not with football games and volleyball matches and
church and work. And no, there's no way to do research, take notes
and write the thing in eight hours. Hmmm, let's see what can be
found on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Do a search for ``term paper'' and ``research paper.'' Well,
there are several sites that charge money for an already-written
paper. But look here. Site after site after site offering up papers
. . . for free! That'll work. Let's see, download, clean it up a
little, fill in the pertinent info: Name, date, class, prof's name.
All set now, and with a few hours to spare.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is already an F,'' Baylor University lecturer Robert
Darden said as he marked the second page of a seven-page paper
titled ``Three Important Qualities of Christ's Life.'' The paper
was downloaded from a Web site dubbed Phree School. Darden's
comments in the margin of the paper suggested problems with it from
the first sentence: ``Ever since Jesus was born, he has always been
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Specifics?'' Darden questioned, and wrote notes asking about
attribution for the statement. Another sentence _ ``He had flesh
which is matter'' _ was marked ``unclear'' by Darden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not follow research paper format,'' Darden said.
``It's filled with high school (type) errors.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, ads have run in the back of Rolling Stone and other
magazines geared toward the young, offering ``Term Paper
Assistance'' and ``Research Help.'' Send in $15 or $20 and in a few
days you could receive a research paper. Of course, those papers
are ``for research purposes only,'' the companies always state.
</P>
<P>
   Those advertisements are still in place, but like most every
other industry, it also has a presence on the Internet. A search
effort will bring forth dozens of sites, some from students and
other scholars who have posted papers on personal Web sites. Not
for anyone else to copy, print and turn in but to show what sort of
work they are doing in their particular fields.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, however, are loaded with papers to be downloaded,
once again for ``research purposes only,'' most sites read. But for
a student waiting until the last minute to begin work on a project,
the temptation to turn the paper in as one's own could be strong.
But according to some local educators, that would not be a bright
idea.
</P>
<P>
   A notice at the Phree School site
(http://members.aol.com/dagunman/ phree.html) says the
administrator of the site takes ``no responsibility for your use of
any information posted on this page.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail interview requests for this article to Web masters of a
couple of term-paper related sites were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Darden, who said he teaches his students the mechanics of
researching a paper, more so than the grammar aspect of writing,
was not impressed with the sample paper's research or writing
style. Darden knows of what he speaks in doing research. He has
written 25 books, one of which _ Berdache, a horror novel set in
East Texas _ took seven years of research.
</P>
<P>
   Students in Darden's classes are free to use either traditional
library sources or the Internet as resources for writing papers.
But finding already-written papers to download would be a near
impossibility. Darden assigns topics of research papers _ ``They're
not going to come to me with a topic,'' he said _ that are fairly
obscure, such as religious beliefs of the indigenous tribes of
Vietnam, or the role of correspondents for Harper's Weekly during
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The process of research also precludes students from coming to
class with a completed paper on the due date. Students must turn in
work along the way, such as an outline and thesis statement,
materials typically not available on the free papers floating about
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The process is much the same for the research papers that Pat
Waterman's students write in advanced placement English classes at
Midway High School, though her students have a bit more leeway in
subject selection.
</P>
<P>
   Waterman, who is in her 13th year at Midway, creates a graph
with a timeline down the left side and suggested topic areas along
the top. Students then are free to choose a topic, such as
politics, crime, fine arts or sports, from a particular era and
write about that. All sources for Midway papers must be from the
school library, which is not connected to the Internet, which rules
that out as a source.
</P>
<P>
   Waterman said students are limited to using library sources so
teachers can find cited works if a question arises when the paper
is being graded.
</P>
<P>
   Waterman gives her students a calendar listing dates that
certain materials pertaining to the paper are due. The papers are
researched over a three-week period. Students pick a broad topic
during the first week. In the second week, they narrow down the
topic and present 15 note cards or pieces of photocopied
information that will be used in the paper. The final paper is due
at the end of the third week. Just as in Darden's class at Baylor,
there are deadlines along the way; handing in a completed paper
with no supporting material is out of the question. Not that
students haven't tried to bluff their way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspected one student three or four years ago,'' Waterman
said. ``She had not met any of the deadlines but showed up with a
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   That student received a zero on the paper, which is typically
about 25 percent of the student's grade during a six-week grading
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can make 'em or break 'em,'' Waterman said.
</P>
<P>
   While for Midway students the 'Net is verboten _ especially
those sites with papers ready to download _ Dr. Lynn Waller shows
off those sites to his students at McLennan Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take them to SchoolSucks (www.schoolsucks.com) and let them
know I'm aware of those resources that are out there,'' said
Waller, who teaches freshman composition and technical
communications at the school. ``I show them how they could easily
cheat, and the legal reasons'' they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Those legal ramifications could include the involvement of the
FBI if interstate telephone lines are used for the transmission of
bogus term papers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides legal problems, students caught turning in papers that
are not their own work face disciplinary action, from receiving no
credit for the paper to expulsion from the school, Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   Waller critiqued a three-page paper on Charles Dickens' A Tale
of Two Cities, and said it was ``poorly written,'' and would not be
considered college-level material. The paper came from CyberEssays
(www.cyberessays.com).
</P>
<P>
   Midway's Waterman said the content of the same report ``looks
like someone paraphrased the Cliffs Notes'' of the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no thesis statement,'' she said. ``It's just a summary
of the novel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Waller is not against using the 'Net for classwork. This
semester he is teaching an Internet-based English composition
class, where students never meet in a traditional classroom, but do
all of the work via e-mail and Internet chat rooms created for the
class. While some of Waller's students use the computers on the MCC
campus, one student is taking the class from Hong Kong, with
intentions of transferring the credit hours to Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
