<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-BEATABLE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux, Braves looking beatable
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greg Maddux is missing his targets by inches. To the Atlanta
Braves, he might as well be missing by a mile.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' ace has struggled since the All-Star break, making a
typically nerve-wracking September even more unsettling for
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who begin a quick two-game series tonight at Pro
Player Stadium against the Florida Marlins, have won their division
in each of the past seven seasons, including this one. But they've
won the World Series only once (1995).
</P>
<P>
   If they're to win it this year, they'll need their pitching
staff _ and especially Maddux _ at full strength. Since the break,
Maddux is 5-7 with a 3.28 ERA and there are whispers around
baseball that something is wrong with his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux says he knows what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been inconsistent with my location, and that's my whole
game,'' he said. ``My arm feels fine, and I'm throwing all my
pitches fine, just not always in the right spots.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the key. What makes Maddux dominant is his ability to
throw high-80-mph fastballs on the corners with good movement.
Lately, the pitches that for years have tailed away from hitters
and nicked the outside corners are staying over the plate and
becoming hittable. And the pitches that used to tail in on hitters
and catch the slightest bit of the plate at the last possible
moment have been staying out of the strike zone, becoming walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been fine mechanically, just a little bit off,'' Braves
pitching coach Leo Mazzone said. ``With Greg, it's not something
that can't be corrected. As long as we get it figured out in time
for the playoffs, he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves in general have some things to figure out heading
into the playoffs _ like can they live up to another 100-win season
by not collapsing. They've been beaten in the post-season by teams
good enough to compete with them and driven enough to beat them.
The Phillies in 1993. The Yankees in 1996. The Marlins in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't throw the switch on in the playoffs,'' Braves
infielder Ozzie Guillen said. ``In the playoffs, we're going to
have 2-1 games, 3-2 games, close games. We've got to do the little
things to win those.''
</P>
<P>
   But right now, some pretty big things are looking troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right-hander John Smoltz is 11-1 with a 2.41 ERA since the
All-Star break, but he's got a nagging elbow problem and won't make
another start until the playoffs because he ``doesn't want to risk
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta's bench and bullpen, traditional post-season Achilles'
heels, are no better than last year, when the Marlins beat the
Braves late in NLCS games, or the year before when the Yankees did
the same in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   _ And there's Maddux. Even if there's nothing wrong with his
arm, problems with his location won't get him or his team far if
he's matched against Randy Johnson and the Houston Astros in a
crucial game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on pure talent, this team is the best team I've ever
been on,'' said Tom Glavine, whose 20 wins lead the major leagues.
``Sometimes, since it's such a long season, you can start taking
things lightly, start not feeling any urgency. We need to realize
we won't always just be able to turn it on because we want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially against Houston and San Diego, division champions
with regular-season credentials as solid as Atlanta's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, there was maybe one other team along with us,''
Glavine said. ``Now, all three division winners are about even.
It's going to be a tough road, but if we play the way we played in
April, not many teams will be able to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
