<HEADLINE>
ANTI-BALDNESS DRUG IS STUDIED FOR USE AGAINST PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Sept. 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DON FINLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Almost 25 years ago, doctors published an account
of a rare genetic disorder among some children in the Dominican
Republic. The children were born sexually ``ambiguous,'' but
developed as normal males after puberty.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican Republic research ``eventually led to the
discovery that the prostate actually is present in male and female
fetuses early in development, but it requires androgen stimulation
for it to develop,'' said Dr. Ian Thompson, chief of surgery at
Brooks Air Force Base and clinical director of the national study.
</P>
<P>
   That observation led to the understanding that 5
alpha-reductase, a metabolite of testosterone, the male sex
hormone, leads to the development of the prostate in males.
</P>
<P>
   Even as adults, the men with the genetic disorder could not
properly make 5 alpha-reductase. They had a small prostate gland
throughout life, did not develop benign prostate enlargement or
prostate cancer. Nor did they develop male pattern baldness or
acne.
</P>
<P>
   Research into that phenomenon eventually led to the drug
Proscar, used to treat prostate disease and male-pattern baldness.
The drug also is being studied in more than 1,500 healthy San
Antonio men to see if it will prevent prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Prostate Cancer Prevention Trial is a seven-year study of
18,882 men across the country. San Antonio has the largest pool of
volunteers, with the Brooke Army Medical Center and Wilford Hall
Medical Center participating.
</P>
<P>
   If the drug is shown to prevent prostate cancer with minimum
side effects, it will provide doctors and patients with a powerful
tool against the second deadliest cancer killer of men.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio researchers also are looking for the genes
responsible for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio familial prostate cancer study has enrolled 28
families, each with two or more members with early onset of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The study was originally designed to focus on Mexican-American
families, but only two have enrolled, said Dr. Rosemarie Plaetke,
assistant professor of cellular and structural biology at the
University of Texas Health Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often we have Mexican-American prostate cancer patients who
want to participate. However, willingness of relatives to be
enrolled in the study is low,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers are working on developing new therapies _ or
improving existing ones _ for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Sarosdy, a local urologist, is looking at an
alternative drug for patients after they've undergone primary
treatment for their cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sarosdy is exploring whether high doses of a single drug,
Casodex, can be effective with fewer side effects such as muscle
wasting, loss of muscle mass and bone demineralization.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other drugs, Casodex doesn't interfere with the
production of the male hormone testosterone, but blocks it from
interacting with cancer cells within the prostate, Sarosdy said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is also trying to determine whether interrupting
long-term hormone therapy might actually improve outcome for
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need hormonal therapy you start it and it continues
forever with metastatic disease,'' Thompson said. ``There are side
effects from that _ osteoporosis, anemia, mood changes. My old
professor told me it takes the wind out of your sails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have evidence that you don't need to do it continuously,
that it can be intermittent. It may have all sorts of benefits to
the patient in terms of side effects of treatment. And there are
some data that suggests it may be actually beneficial at reducing
the development of hormone-resistant prostate cancer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
