</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PANTHERS-WORRELL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Distractive Worrell attracts Panthers fans
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an unlikely scenario, but if the Florida Panthers ever
decide to assign right winger Peter Worrell to an East Coast Hockey
League team, fans of the Pensacola Sky Pilots would love to have
him.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 4,194 that watched the Panthers battle the
expansion Nashville Predators to a 4-4 tie at the Pensacola Civic
Center on a recent night grew increasingly enamored of the
6-foot-7, 225-pound enforcer as the game went on, chanting
``Worr-ell, Worr-ell,'' cheering every time he took the ice and
booing every time he departed.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell gained their affection by playing his usual aggressive
game, pounding Predators tough guy Dennis Lambert in a pair of
fights and generally distracting his opponents with crushing hits
at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter did a good job,'' Florida coach Terry Murray said after
Worrell's tactics had helped the Panthers take over the game in the
third period and rally to tie. ``If we got that kind of game from
him on a game-to-game basis, we couldn't ask for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very intense, he's good in the locker room and he brings
energy. He played smart at the end. They took some runs at him and
paid for it with a couple of penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Panthers (0-1-1), who have yet to work on special teams
in training camp, had any real success on their power play _ they
finished just 2-of-14 _ they could have gained a split of the
weekend series.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell, 21, understands his role. After amassing 462 minutes in
penalties last season _ including 153 in his 19 games with Florida
_ he knows that the more he can get opponents to focus on him
instead of their game, the more successful he becomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're more worried about trying to get back at me, that
gives us a chance to get back in the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell felt he had played poorly in Florida's 4-2 loss to the
Predators a night earlier in Huntsville, Ala., and was determined
to redeem himself. After spending the final month of the season
with the Panthers last spring, he's hoping to stick around from the
start this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to show I deserve to be here, and to get more ice
time,'' he said. His skating, which has always been a shortcoming,
is much improved, though his stick work and lateral mobility remain
below par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rate my camp as so-so so far. I haven't been bad, but I
haven't been at my best either. Hopefully this will get me back on
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Difference of opinion: Goaltender Kirk McLean didn't think his
performance Sunday _ in which he gave up four goals on 23 shots _
was as disappointing as Murray did.
</P>
<P>
   All four goals came from long range and two or three of them
seemed preventable, prompting Murray to say, ``Kirk has got to stop
those.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean's response: ``I felt pretty good; they were pretty good
shots. . . . For the first time out, I felt pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Right winger Dino Ciccarelli sprained his ankle
Monday, the first on-ice injury of training camp. He is expected to
miss 1-2 weeks. . . . The Panthers assigned 10 players to
minor-league affiliates, leaving 36 players in camp. Forwards
Andrew Long, Curtis Doell, Herbert Vasiljevs, Tero Lehtera, Dave
Duerden, Mike Brown and Craig Ferguson, defensemen Lance Ward and
Joey Teterenko and goaltender Denis Khloptonov.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
