</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CARS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    End of an era: Last downtown auto dealership packs up for the
suburbs
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Before there was a Motor Mile, back when U.S.
183 was considered in the far reaches of Austin, before Austinites
had ever heard of a car named KIA, downtown was the place to car
shop.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, East Fifth Street, Texas, was lined with
dealers that sold Cadillacs and Chandlers, Indiana Trucks and
Studebakers. In recent years, downtown was home to such dealers as
McMorris Ford, Covert Buick and Capitol Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they've all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   After 47 years at 501 N. Lamar Blvd., Capitol moved its sales
lot to a new 26-acre dealership last month on the south end of the
Motor Mile on Interstate 35 near William Cannon Drive. Capitol's
service department will move this week and the parts department
will follow in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Although Land Rover Austin opened a dealership on West Fifth
Street last fall several blocks west of the city's central business
district, and a few other used car dealers are still downtown,
Capitol was the last dealership in the city's urban core.
</P>
<P>
   In Capitol's place will be Austin Marketplace, a 425,000
square-foot retail, entertainment and office complex. Developers
are hoping to break ground on the project by mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Capitol signals the end of an era _ a time when
families drove in rather than out of Austin's central city to look
at shiny new cars.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is like downtowns around the United States _ cities in
the midst of revitalization. Car dealers are moving away from the
central city, faced with skyrocketing downtown land values and the
lure of the growing suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a trend that excites downtown boosters who think
pedestrian-filled streets and fancy shops are better than car lots
when it comes to revitalizing the city's core.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, auto dealerships have been replaced by some of the most
celebrated additions to the southwest edge of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods Market and Book People at Sixth Street and Lamar
Boulevard took the place of Capitol's truck sales lot. Advertising
company GSD&AMP;M headquarters next door used to be McMorris Ford.
Developer Whit Hanks has converted Capitol Chevrolet's body shop on
the northwest corner of West Fifth Street and North Lamar Boulevard
into high-end stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``These projects are going to be a big plus for downtown,''
Charles Betts, executive director of the Downtown Austin Alliance,
said of Austin Marketplace and the office project.
</P>
<P>
   Betts said the changing downtown landscape is a natural
progression. While land in the suburbs can be purchased for less
than $10 a square foot, downtown costs can run $40 a square foot,
Betts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As property values have risen, it justifies more intense
development downtown,'' Betts said. ``It's a matter of economics.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first auto dealers to leave Austin's downtown was
Henna Chevrolet, which moved to Interstate 35 more than 30 years
ago. Dodge, Pontiac and Cadillac-Oldsmobile dealerships left
downtown soon afterward for large lots along U.S. 183.
</P>
<P>
   When real estate prices north of downtown rose in the early
1980s, South Austin's Motor Mile gained popularity, with pioneers
like Hendrix GMC Trucks, Leif Johnson's trucks and John Roberts
Subaru. By 1986, it had been joined by dealerships selling Honda,
Pontiac, Audi-Porsche, Volkswageon, Dodge, BMW and Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-September, Covert's Buick, Saturn and Isuzu dealers
completed its move from West Fifth Street to 11750 Research Blvd.
in North Austin. An Austin developer plans to build an office
complex in its place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't vacated the land, our tax bill would have forced
us to,'' said William Cromwell, president and general manager of
Capitol Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   The property tax on the land rose nearly 70 percent during the
past year, he said. He estimated that the land's valuation has
risen by 500 percent in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't economically feasible for us to be there anymore,''
Cromwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the dealership's downtown service business was still
good, sales had fallen off _ a trend Cromwell attributes to the
traffic congestion of the area and the allure of clusters of
dealerships along I-35 and U.S. 183. Downtown, he said, just wasn't
convenient anymore for most people. ``It was time to move,''
Cromwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Betts said he is excited about the new projects slated
for downtown, he says he will miss the convenience of dropping his
two Chevrolets at Capitol to be serviced. He could walk six blocks
from the dealership to his downtown office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Capitol will have a good shuttle service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
