r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THORNDALE-HAZING23-CO     09-22 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THORNDALE-HAZING23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thorndale students apologize to victim
 &HT;    By Dylan Rivera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMERON _ Four Thorndale High School students admitted in
juvenile court recently that they attacked a classmate in a
football hazing ritual last October that divided a small town and
fed a growing feud over the prosecutor's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The students confessed in court that they used a plastic
soda-type bottle to commit an act of ``physical brutality'' against
a classmate that ``subjected him to shame, humiliation and extreme
mental stress. . .for the purpose of being initiated into junior
varsity football.'' The attack occurred in an athletics weight
room.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of a plea bargain, each of the teens _ Paul
Bernstein, Cole Chapman, R. J. Sandoval and Jerry Young, all 15, _
stood and apologized publicly to Joshua Bonney, the student they
had attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't mean to hurt you,'' Bernstein said in court.
``We hope you can move past this. We all feel sorry about this.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the boys stood nervously and made similar
statements. ``I'm sorry for what we did and we didn't mean to hurt
you,'' Sandoval said.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Bonney, the 15-year-old victim, said in an interview
after the hearing that he had been through ``hell'' at the hands of
high school bullies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think that because they're bigger than everybody on the
football team that they think they're going to have privileges,''
Joshua Bonney said. He said the attack was not hazing: ``It doesn't
happen to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonney said he was happy that the case was settled but would
have preferred a harsher penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the defendants nor their attorneys would comment after
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The final charge was a compromise that stopped short of accusing
the teens of sodomizing Bonney and reduced a felony to a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   While the four teens, all of whom have been high school football
players, were originally charged with sexual assault, they admitted
to a Class B misdemeanor charge of hazing in a plea bargain that
was negotiated all weekend and until the last minute Monday
morning. They each will perform 80 hours of community service,
serve one year of probation, and pay the victim's counseling fees
up to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   They are also required to refrain from contact with Bonney and
not have any adverse contact with two other teens who were to be
witnesses in a trial.
</P>
<P>
   If the teens violate the probation, Lance could sentence them to
incarceration in a Texas Youth Commission facility until they turn
21.
</P>
<P>
   Lance sternly lectured the boys, threatening harsher punishment
if they violate their probations.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told the youths it would have been better if they had
broken the victim's legs ``because dignity and self-respect are a
lot slower in the healing process.''
</P>
<P>
   It was originally alleged that another teen was the victim of an
attempted sexual assault, but that issue did not come up Monday.
Lewis said later that the second victim declined to prosecute
because testifying would have caused too much distress.
</P>
<P>
   The Thorndale case landed in and was fodder for a bitter feud
over control of the courthouse in Milam County. State District
Judge Charles Lance, who presided in the case, and juvenile
officials who were investigating it publicly criticized County and
District Attorney Hollis Lewis Jr. for the 10-month delay before
charges were filed in August. One probation officer cited the
Thorndale case among several allegations in a removal suit he filed
against Lewis in June.
</P>
<P>
   In previous court cases, Lance had found that Lewis lied to the
court and committed other misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis denies those charges and says he is being run out of the
county on exaggerated and false accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, there were no outward signs of conflict between Lance
and Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Myra Bonney, Joshua's mother, said she was glad to have closure
in the case. She said she wanted to seek a conviction of sexual
assault, but after seeing her son try to practice his testimony in
the courtroom this weekend, she was convinced the lesser charge
would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was willing to stand up and say what happened to him in
front of everyone but we came up here a couple times and I saw what
he was going through and I'm not going to do that,'' Myra Bonney
said. ``He's been through enough. We had to relocate; my kids are
in another school now. These kids have no idea what they've done to
my family.'' Joshua now attends Granger High School.
</P>
<P>
   Thorndale Superintendent Wayne Calhoun said Monday's actions
would provide needed closure to a community that had been shocked
by the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the community's reaction to the allegations, Calhoun
said, ``While it's possible they could have understood or believed
boys doing hazing, the sexual assault seemed to outrageous that it
was difficult for them to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said the community and school district have been
unfairly criticized for their handling of the case. In the wake of
the incident last year, school officials studied their disciplinary
procedures, called for closer supervision of students in
non-classroom settings and encouraged other students to come
forward with complaints, Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   Myra Bonney said she hoped that both sets of teens would be able
to go on with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of pain here and on the other side and
hopefully they've learned their lesson,'' Myra Bonney said.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Dillenberger, the chief Milam County juvenile probation
officer who had criticized Lewis in writing for delays in the case,
said Monday that the plea bargain could be helpful for all
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's important for them to apologize because it
helps them understand that they did do something wrong and for the
victim to hear that in court, I think it's very healing,''
Dillenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
