<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVREVIEW-CLINTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Was Clinton tape good TV? Only for insomniacs
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had to be one of the most surreal moments television has ever
produced.
</P>
<P>
   A visibly angry, finger-waving President Clinton answering
intimate _ and sometimes salacious _ grand jury questions about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the usually unflappable Clinton swallowing hard after
pointed questions or downing water and Diet Coke like a near-dying
man lost in the Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   ABC commentator and former White House communications director
George Stephanopoulos admitted the president looked ``scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow ABC analyst Cokie Roberts remarked she felt sorry for a
beleaguered Clinton, adding that, ``You feel like he's a little boy
before the principal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' said ABC's Sam Donaldson, ``breathtaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, Sam? I'd say it was more of a Bore. All those racy
inquiries were sandwiched in between mostly insomnia-curing
legalese.
</P>
<P>
   If viewers were smart, they skipped the four-hour inquisition
and waited for CNN's highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 9:25 a.m., ABC, CBS, NBC and C-SPAN began airing
Clinton's videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   While the big three networks (ABC, CBS, NBC) took pains to tell
viewers that much of the testimony was sexually graphic, only NBC
had the guts to cut away when those moments actually arrived.
Instead, NBC showed interviews and a portion of Clinton's speech
before the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   CBS switched from airing the testimony live to a 10-second
delay.
</P>
<P>
   ABC used a five-second delay to give producers time to stop
before airing inappropriate language. But in the first 2 1/2 hours,
it ran the testimony unedited.
</P>
<P>
   CNN periodically ran a graphic on the screen under Clinton:
``Warning: Testimony may contain explicit details.'' The other
networks used similar warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, only WPTV-Channel 5 didn't air Clinton's entire
testimony. The station cut away to air its regularly scheduled noon
newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got pretty graphic,'' explains Todd Woolman, Channel 5's
news director. ``Our network was cutting away because they felt it
was too graphic, so we felt we might as well put on our local
news.''
</P>
<P>
   WPEC-Channel 12, however, chose to stick with Clinton's entire
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where once you're in it, you almost
have an obligation to stay in it,'' said Don Colee, Channel 12's
programming director. ``At that point, to go in and selectively
censor, I don't think that would've been a good thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as expected, local TV stations received a number of
calls from angry viewers complaining the testimony didn't belong on
TV. Parents and Jewish viewers were especially irked because Monday
was Rosh Hashana and kids were off from school.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1 p.m., Colee said Channel 12 received close to 70 calls
from angry viewers. Woolman said Channel 5 got a similar number of
calls. But I bet many of those same people who complained about the
testimony, were probably watching it.
</P>
<P>
   People mostly wanted to know if their favorite daytime soaps
were going to be pre-empted and why the stations were airing
Clinton's testimony in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying, `Take this stupid stuff off TV,' '' Colee
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to escape into fantasy with their soaps,'' said
one Channel 5 staffer.
</P>
<P>
   Soaps?
</P>
<P>
   Who needs soaps when you have a clearly embarrassed president
talking about a steamy affair with a young, misguided intern?
</P>
<P>
   But that's one real-life TV soap I _ and the rest of the country
_ don't ever want to see again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
