<SLUG> BC-FBC-LONGHORNS-GOAL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Next goal for Horns: beat Owls, win state
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Rice up next and the meat of the Big 12
South schedule looming ahead, the push starts now toward the Texas
Longhorns' primary goal.
</P>
<P>
   Win state.
</P>
<P>
   If that's in terms that the Horns' defense can easily
understand, it's only a coincidence, although it's no surprise,
with the two-deep littered with players only a year or two out of
high school and getting younger every week.
</P>
<P>
   At his weekly press conference Monday, Coach Mack Brown praised
two freshmen _ end Jermain Anderson and cornerback Ervis Hill _ and
indicated they will compete for starting spots this week in
practice. Brown also said backup tight end Mike Jones, a redshirt
freshman who has not caught a pass this season, will start working
at defensive end as the Horns continue to search for answers at
their most problematic spot in the front seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play people according to how they do in practice,'' Brown
said. ``Whoever produces more will play more. We'll make changes,
if we need to make them, on Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   The part-time move of Jones, who will continue to play offense
in short-yardage and two-tight end sets, was the only change Brown
spelled out Monday, but he hinted at others.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, he said the Horns may work in some of the younger
players to improve performance. Clearly he's speaking of the
offensive line, where sophomore Leonard Davis played much of the
second half at both tackles, freshman Mike Williams came in on the
last series at tackle and Antwan Kirk-Hughes would have seen more
action had he not been weakened by a throat problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't give Ricky Williams a chance,'' Brown said of the
lack of running room for the Horns' Heisman Trophy candidate.
According to UT statistics, Williams gained 69 yards after contact
_ 26 of those just getting back to the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, undersized at 6-foot-3-inches, 218 pounds, sacked
Kansas State quarterback Michael Bishop once, had two tackles for
loss and picked off a shovel pass that was inexplicably ruled an
incompletion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made plays that guys who've been out there a lot longer did
not make,'' said Brown, who indicated that Anderson's lack of size
is one of the reasons he hasn't cracked the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he liked the position Hill had on Wildcats receiver
Darnell McDonald's touchdown catches, and lauded the diminutive
freshman for blocking a point-after attempt late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hill will battle sophomore Joe Walker, who was frequently
victimized in the KSU game before being taken out and targeted for
confidence rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think Joe's trying too hard,'' Brown said. ``I really
think he's pressing. We took him out to let him relax. Joe's a good
football player and we need to get him back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones follows in the footsteps of J.J. Kelly, who was the backup
tight end last year before being moved in the spring to defensive
end, where he's starting on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 6-5, 250 and can run,'' Brown said. ``Derek Lewis is
playing so well at tight end, (Jones) isn't getting any snaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Horns will deal with Jones' move by using
redshirt freshman Chad Irwin as Lewis' backup or utilizing more
three-wide receiver sets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
