<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON2     09-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson: No mirrors this time
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ This is different.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the fool's gold that glittered after fast starts in
Jimmy Johnson's first two years as the Miami Dolphins' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   This stuff _ a shiny 3-0 mined from a muddy 21-0 victory against
the Pittsburgh Steelers _ is real.
</P>
<P>
   That was Johnson's analysis after having a day to examine the
three-game gem he now holds in his hands _ and will continue to
hold for two weeks until the Dolphins resume play against the New
York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the high assessment?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing things that win games offensively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother re-reading that sentence. Yes, he said offensively.
Never mind that the Dolphins are 3-0 primarily because they have
given up an NFL-best average of 7.3 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Johnson feels that this start won't fade like it did
in his first two years _ in 1996, 3-0 turned into 8-8; in 1997, 2-0
turned into 9-7 _ is because of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy and optimistic and on and on,'' Johnson said of
his first two years. ``But I've said all along, I never have been
comfortable with our approach offensively. . . . I thought there
were going to be games when we were going to have interceptions. I
thought there were going to be games when we were going to have bad
weather. And I thought there were going to be games when we were
not on target with the passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   This season the offense has hardly been productive. In fact, the
defense has scored two of Miami's seven touchdowns _ interception
returns by cornerback Terrell Buckley and linebacker Zach Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it has done what Johnson wanted most. It has avoided
mistakes. It has run time off the clock with a lead.
</P>
<P>
   Take Dan Marino's numbers. Most of the attention has been on how
Marino has thrown for only 407 yards _ the lowest three-game total
of his 16-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins point out that for the first time in Marino's
career, he has not thrown an interception in the first three games
of a season. And Johnson has referred repeatedly to Marino's
quarterback rating, which now is nearly 26 points higher than after
three games last season (87.0-61.3).
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, I think we're on schedule,'' Johnson said.
``We're nowhere close to where we're going to be in the next few
weeks. But we are doing some critical things in that we are
protecting the passer, we are protecting the football and we are
running the football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins have averaged 121 yards rushing. And, perhaps more
importantly, they have been able to run in the fourth quarter. Of
35 offensive plays in three fourth quarters, only seven were
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Against Pittsburgh, the Dolphins walked onto the field after
half time, looked at the scoreboard (14-0) and the sky (rain) and
went on to pass only three times in the final two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions and the score dictated that,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what would have happened if the conditions and score
dictated that last year, Johnson said, ``We wouldn't have made any
first downs.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Johnson said, is the beauty of a game built on the run: It
has a better shot at surviving late-season games in snow and nasty
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can run the ball; I don't care what kind of weather it
is,'' he said. ``That wind can blow as hard as it wants to blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added several times that the offense has a long way to
go. His point, though, was that he doesn't believe the offense is
this weak link that will drag down this season. To the contrary, he
believes it will help win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to get better,'' he said. ``There are going
be some games we're going to have a tough time running the ball and
we're going to throw for a lot of yards. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, he can savor that his team is 3-0 _ and that he
doesn't have that nagging feeling that it's only a matter of time
before people start uncovering blemishes in the gem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
