r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GRILLED-DOLPHINS2     09-22 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GRILLED-DOLPHINS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson: More media, more pressure
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Jimmy Johnson plopped down in a chair for his
day-after meeting with the newspaper reporters who cover the Miami
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ready for the weekly grilling,'' he said with a laugh.
``What've we got?''
</P>
<P>
   Before taking any questions, the unusually relaxed Johnson
(being 3-0 heading into a bye week will do that) steered the
conversation toward the pressure of being an NFL head coach in 1998
and how, because of increased media coverage, it is different than
when he took charge of the Dallas Cowboys in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is so competitive now, there is so much
visibility,'' he said. ``Even though we understand that's what pays
our salary and that's what creates interest and that's why the
stadiums are full, there is so much abuse on every decision, on
every head coach in this league. There is pressure on 30 guys.
Doesn't make any difference if you're 3-0 or 0-3.''
</P>
<P>
   After rattling off some of the changes that have made the
coverage even more intense _ from the growth of talk radio to
nightly NFL segments on ESPN to the Internet _ Johnson made an
admission.
</P>
<P>
   He said that coaches do indeed pay attention to what is being
said and written about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a coach pays attention to the media _ which most of us do,
and the ones who say they don't are lying _ it's going to create
some pressure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, of course, spent two years on the other side of the
camera, working for Fox as a studio analyst before taking the
Dolphins job.
</P>
<P>
   Has that helped him deal with the pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he said. ``But everybody likes to be patted on the
back. Everybody likes to have people saying they've done wonderful
things. Nobody likes to be criticized when it's incorrect. That's
the one that really gets to you.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, even if they're right, sometimes you don't like to be
criticized there, either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This season, despite the 3-0 start, Johnson has had to deal with
plenty of second-guessing. About the new offense. About the
decision to use the first-round pick to draft a running back. About
the way he has pushed injured players to be on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accept it,'' Johnson said of the pressure. ``We know if we
didn't have this we wouldn't be paid the money we're paid. We
wouldn't have the ratings on TV we have. . . . But when you look at
the role of the head coach, it's a lot different than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Another quarterback in the mix: The Dolphins plan to work out a
quarterback today for the practice squad. Although Johnson wouldn't
disclose who the player is, he did give the reason for the
potential addition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may need another arm the next couple weeks,'' he said.
``We'd like to rest some of the arms we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Erickson, who was expected to be the Dolphins' backup
quarterback this season, has been bothered by pain in his right
elbow since early in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Game ball for the boss: Johnson gave Dolphins owner Wayne
Huizenga a game ball after the victory against the Steelers ``just
because of the support he's given us.'' He also gave a belated game
ball to linebacker Zach Thomas. Thomas wasn't among those handed a
ball in the locker room after the game, but by Monday Johnson had
decided he deserved one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He completely dominated the third quarter and the start of the
fourth quarter,'' he said. ``He made play after play. He had one of
the better games he's had here. I think Zach is playing better
right now than he's ever played as a pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who received game balls: The entire defensive coaching
staff; offensive linemen Mark Dixon and Richmond Webb; cornerback
Sam Madison, receiver O.J. McDuffie; and Nate Jacquet and Bernie
Parmalee for special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
