<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWPROFS-CLINTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Law professors give Clinton ``B'' on testimony
 &HT;    By John Keilman and Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the halls of academe, President Clinton's performance before
the Kenneth Starr grand jury rated less than an A but better than
an F.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he came off that bad,'' said Susan Brenner, a
University of Dayton law professor and author of the legal text,
``Federal Grand Jury.'' Overall, she said, the president's civil
tone will probably impress much of the public, but it's likely his
lawyerly jousting over definitions of what constitutes sex will
continue to be a turn-off.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in law and communications were analyzing the president's
responses to questions about his sex life, and even his body
language as he fenced with prosecutors. Like much of the public,
they came away with a mixed review of the president's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Funso Oluyitan, a communications professor at Wilberforce
University, had one of his classes watch part of the testimony
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   His view: The tape's strongest contribution to the mountain of
evidence before Congress is to reveal Clinton's palpable
embarrassment. Oluyitan noticed the president blushing on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great sympathy for him,'' the professor said. ``It is
very serious to see a man of such power ... quizzed in front of a
jury like that.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton's evasive manner roused Oluyitan's suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some questions (to which) he probably knows the
answers, but he cannot give them,'' he said. ``On many occasions, I
noticed how he went into this lapse of memory.''
</P>
<P>
   After a classroom discussion, though, Oluyitan said the tape
didn't seem to change many students' minds. Those who thought
Clinton should remain in office kept their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   While many have called the Monica Lewinsky scandal a national
embarrassment, Oluyitan, originally from Nigeria, said it actually
offers proof of America's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the freedom that allows the system to put the
president on the spot,'' he said. ``This is the kind of thing you
might never find in the developing countries.''
</P>
<P>
   James Sayer, chairman of Wright State University's
Communications Department, watched about two hours of Clinton's
testimony, and pronounced it an entertaining spectacle not to the
president's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchanges between the president and the special prosecutor
and others over what constituted sexual relations bordered on the
absurd,'' he said. ``It was funny...No one looks good in that kind
of exchange. And the president looked horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, though, that he does not expect the tape's release to
change public opinion a great deal. Those who already dislike the
president will likely watch a great deal of the testimony, he said,
while those who support him will watch very little.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably one of the best shows ever seen in a premiere
week,'' he said, ``...(but) I hope to hell there's not a sequel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
