</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-CLINTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media calls nation to unwilling jury duty
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The media are taking a lashing from a large part of the American
public for its long-running and uncomfortably detailed coverage of
the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal. But newspapers, TV networks and cable
news stations have no choice but to call the nation to an unwilling
jury duty, according to media ethicists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entirely appropriate that Congress and the media be
putting this information out there, because in any event, the
public will be the ultimate judge in this case,'' said Richard
Noyes, political studies director for the Center for Media and
Public Affairs, a nonprofit, nonpartisan media watchdog based in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Noyes said he believes most of the media have acted responsibly
in their coverage, even though the lurid details and sheer volume
of the coverage have unleashed a media backlash. About 40 percent
of readers and viewers feel there has been excessive coverage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindi Hughes, a freelance writer in Austin, Texas, is one of
them. She recently dispatched e-mails to friends and relatives all
over the country, urging them to cancel their newspaper
subscriptions and boycott TV for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just gone too far,'' she said by phone Monday. ``It's
almost like the media have become this propaganda machine for
people who want to see Clinton go.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported receiving hundreds of calls Monday about its
broadcast of the president's grand jury testimony ``with reactions
all across the map,'' CNN spokesman Steve Hayworth said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said CNN polls show that many viewers are conflicted
about the coverage. Although nearly half the public said it would
watch the grand jury testimony, only 37 percent said that Congress
should release it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News received a handful of angry calls and
letters after it printed a special section last week with excerpts
from the Starr report, editor Jeff Bruce said. The decision to run
the excerpts, which were heavily edited for offensive content, was
a tough one even though it was in the best interest of readers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say it caused me concern as a parent,'' he said. The
graphic nature of the allegations against the president have forced
newspapers ``to address issues today that normally wouldn't find
their way into a family business. It's a tricky business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Steele, director of ethics for the Poynter Institute for
Media Studies in Florida, said he thinks the media overall have
done a poor job of explaining the rationale of its coverage to
readers and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we are not very good at is explaining the
how and why of what we do,'' he said. ``We should be much better at
that, not to cover our bets, but to be accountable and open to the
public. If we do that, I think people will disagree with us
respectfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
