<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDENTS-CLINTON23-CO     09-22 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-CLINTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students' reactions to testimony mixed
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell, Bob Batz, Benjamin Kline, Brandon
Peterson and Scott Elliott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While some Miami Valley TV viewers ignored the airing of
President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony, others who
were curious about the historic event tuned in from a variety of
places.
</P>
<P>
   On at least one Miami Valley college campus, TV viewers were
riveted to the screen. About two dozen people gathered in the lobby
of Wright State University's Allyn Hall and quietly watched the
four-hour testimony.
</P>
<P>
   WSU student Jason Lansdale, 21, of Kettering,who worked for
Clinton's Ohio campaign in 1992 and 1996 was among those gathered
in Allyn Hall. Lansdale, a senior majoring in political science,
said the president appeared defensive and very nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone would be under that kind of pressure,''
Lansdale said, adding he believes Clinton will survive this
``Republican smear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He always does well at his worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sears store in the Dayton Mall, a trickle of shoppers
passing through the electronics department stopped just briefly to
watch Clinton before moving along.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Hockwalt, who sells televisions, has seen large crowds
drawn to the TVs like moths to light when the O.J. Simpson verdict
was read and for coverage of Princess Diana's death. But Clinton's
testimony did not attract that same level of interest, Hockwalt
said. In fact, several shoppers remarked they were tired of
watching it.
</P>
<P>
   Hockwalt, who voted for Bob Dole in 1996, said ``from what I
heard on TV, I didn't see he handled himself badly at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Beavercreek resident Amir Guirguis said, after watching the
Clinton testimony on television on Monday, he's holding onto his
convictions about the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a liar,'' Guirguis said. ``The video shows that he is
trying to play with words and if he is a man, he will step down as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the seven TV sets at Fricker's in Kettering was
tuned to the Clinton testimony at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy watching that set asked us if it was OK to change
the channel, we said 'sure' and when he did, nobody complained,'' a
waitress said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tickets Pub and Eatery in Fairborn, David Bloomfield, 38,
struggled to view the testimony on an elevated television screen
behind the table where he ate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's handling himself the best he can. You can see
he's aggravated and frustrated with it. You can see that very
clearly on his face,'' said Boomfield, a Chillicothe resident who
commutes 160 miles daily to his job at Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomfield called the Independent Counsel's probe ``a waste of
our money'' and an invasion into the president's private life.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas D. Williams, 42, of Bellefontaine, who dined at Damon's
in Fairborn for lunch said Congressional efforts to regulate sexual
content on the Internet were weakened by lawmakers' decision s to
release the Starr report and Clinton's videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody would open their closet doors, everybody would be
out of job,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens at Heartland of Kettering on Wilmington Pike
were unimpressed by the televised Clinton testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Heartland resident Phyllis Blake, 75, said she was upset that
she missed her favorite morning show, Sally Jessy Raphael , but she
left her television set on and watched the videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like the same old questions, worded a different
way,'' Blake said. ``I think (Clinton) is all right. I think he has
done a good job for the country. As for this (sex scandal), I think
he's about the same as any other man.''
</P>
<P>
   Resident Lorean Whaley, 80, said she began watching her
television set at 7 a.m. waiting to be shocked by Clinton's
testimony, but she wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like it was going to be much worse than it was,''
the retired nurse said of the taped testimony. ``I was just glued
to the TV. I wanted to know what they were going to say. But I
think (Ken) Starr is just trying to murder Clinton politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois Pendegrass, who classifies herself as a ``die-hard black
Democrat,'' said she thinks Clinton is guilty but didn't think the
video needed to be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown up folks already know what happened. . .he's guilty and
we didn't need a video to show that,'' Pendegrass said. ``This
turned into a political game.''
</P>
<P>
   Angulic Wallace, of Morrow, has heard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew what he was going to say,'' said Wallace, who was
unloading her groceries at the Kroger in Lebanon. ``I'm tired of
hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and her father, Don, had watched some of the tapes
Monday morning. She believes that if Hillary Clinton can accept the
president's actions, the rest of the country ought to do likewise.
If investigators find Clinton committed perjury, then prosecute
him. Otherwise, leave him alone, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Robbins, retired pastor of the Bethel AME Church in
Lebanon, said he was surprised officials decided to televise the
videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who had not watched the tapes, doesn't believe it was
right to televise the testimony because of the message it sends to
young people.
</P>
<P>
   He also looks for the maelstrom of controversy around the
Clinton-Lewinsky affair to harm Democrats at all levels of
government. Clinton ought to resign rather than risk impeachment,
Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins does, however, see a positive side to the conflict. He
thinks Clinton's experience will encourage other people struggling
with temptation in their own lives to seek spiritual guidance
instead of giving in to it.
</P>
<P>
   Internet chat rooms also were hopping with commentary Monday
afternoon asjury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the president's backers said the tape showed prosecutors
were out to embarrass Clinton, while supporters said the tape
showed the president lied about his involvement with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
