<HEADLINE>
NEW TREATMENTS ON THE WAY FOR ADVANCED DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Sept. 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scientists are developing an array of new therapies
for patients who fail frontline prostate cancer treatments such as
surgery, radiation, hormonal blockade and chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute's database identifies nearly 40
clinical trials underway for patients with recurrent prostate
cancer or prostate cancer that has spread beyond the gland.
</P>
<P>
   Each clinical trial has its own unique requirements. Some demand
that the patient have undergone only certain treatments prior to
receiving the experimental drug. Others won't allow men to
participate if they've had standard treatments within a certain
timeframe.
</P>
<P>
   Experimental treatments are not without risks. There is no
guarantee that they will work in humans, even though they have
shown promise in animals. And the treatments may have harmful side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some new prostate cancer treatments under study
along with contact phone numbers. For a more complete listing,
check the Internet web address for the National Cancer Institute's
clinical trials division (http://cancertrials.nih.nci.gov) or
CapCure, Michael Milken's prostate cancer research organization
(http://www.capcure.org).
</P>
<P>
   Before considering a new treatment that has not been FDA
approved, consult your physician.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancer cell destruction vaccine: Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in New York is developing a vaccine that will induce
prostate cancer cells to commit the cellular equivalent of suicide.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 800-525-2225.
</P>
<P>
   _ Immunotherapy: The Pacific Northwest Cancer Foundation in
Seattle is developing a vaccine to jump-start the body's immune
system to attack prostate cancer cells. Researchers take a sampling
of a patient's blood, then isolate and multiply immune system foot
soldiers known as dendritic cells.
</P>
<P>
   These are injected back into the patient where they spark the
production of cancer-killing cells, which then travel throughout
the body hunting down prostate cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 1-800-MED-INFO.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starving the cancer: The University of California at San
Francisco is developing an antibody to disrupt blood vessel flow to
prostate cancer cells. The idea is that lacking blood, the
malignancy will slow or stop growing.
</P>
<P>
   For information call 415-885-7331.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gene Therapy: Researchers at George Washington University in
Washington, D.C., have discovered that prostate cells lacking the
uteroglobin protein are likely to have a rapidly advancing cancer.
Still about 18 months away from human trials, scientists are
devising a treatment to inject the protein back into cells in an
effort to slow the spread.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancer-Killing Virus: Researchers at the University of
California at San Francisco and John Hopkins University in
Baltimore are creating a new kind of genetically altered virus to
seek out and kill prostate cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   For information call UCSF at 415-885-7331 or Johns Hopkins at
410-955-8964.
</P>
<P>
   _ Metastatic treatments: When it spreads and enters the lethal
stages, prostate cancer typically travels to bone where it grows
and kills the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Wisconsin (608-263-7107),
University of Virginia (804-243-6188) and M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center in Houston (800-392-1611) are developing treatments to halt
this deadly migratory pattern.
</P>
<P>
   _ New chemotherapies: Chemotherapy is a last resort because
prostate cancer usually doesn't respond to toxins. But scientists
are making strides combining toxins, hormonal blockade drugs and
other compounds. Compared with traditional chemo, the combination
is better able to target and kill prostate cancer cells while
minimizing damage to healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   Several institutions are spearheading the new treatments,
including M.D. Anderson Cancer Center (800-392-1611), the
University of Michigan (800-865-1125) and Memorial Sloan Kettering
(800-525-2225).
</P>
<P>
   _ Alternative remedies: PC Spes, a mixture of chemical compounds
extracted from several Chinese herbs, is one of the most
talked-about alternative treatments for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment, which is designed to cause prostate cancer cells
to self-destruct, is receiving serious attention at the University
of California at San Francisco, which is scheduled to begin a
clinical trial on it.
</P>
<P>
   For more information call the treatment's Brea, Calif.-based
distributor, Botanic Lab, at 800-242-5555.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
