<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOYNER-OBIT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joyner's track shoes sit still
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the height of her popularity, former track star Florence
Griffith Joyner commanded the attention of everyone in her
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask LaVonna Martin-Floreal, 31, a 1984 Trotwood-Madison
graduate. Martin-Floreal, who won the silver medal in the 100-meter
hurdles in the 1992 Olympics, remembered everyone marvelling at
Griffth Joyner as she entered a welcoming party for Olympians in
Japan, shortly before the 1988 Seoul Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was wearing a Kimono (Japanese dress),'' said
Martin-Floreal, a 1988 Olympian. ``As soon as she walked in the
door, everybody stopped. They were just captivated by her.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin-Floreal was reminiscing about Griffith Joyner after
finding out she had died of an apparent heart seizure September 21
in Mission Viejo, Calif., at the age of 38. Griffith Joyner won
three gold medals in the '88 Olympics - in the 400-meter relay, 100
meters and 200 meters. She holds the world records in the 100 and
200.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, Martin-Floreal and her parents Lefty
and Brenda Martin had formed a casual friendship with Griffith
Joyner after first meeting her at the 1984 Olympic Trials in
Indianapolis. All of them agreed her athletic ability was matched
by her graciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very sad for me,'' Brenda Martin said. ``She was a
very nice person and easy to talk to. She sent me a shirt in 1990
that said, ``To Mrs. Martin, love, Florence Griffith Joyner.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thankful and grateful that she took the time to think
about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefty Martin, the University of Dayton track coach, said
Griffith Joyner leaves a legacy that will be hard to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that she won three gold medals, is a Hall of Famer
and is the fastest woman in history, her legacy is she leaves
everyone trying to better what she did,'' he said. ``She set the
standard for women in sprints.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sprinter at UCLA in the early '80s, she wasn't quite the
runner she would become in the late '80s. But it wasn't through
lack of effort, said Morehouse athletic director Josh Culbreath.
</P>
<P>
   Culbreath - Central State University's track coach from 88-96 -
remembers watching Griffith Joyner workout at UCLA and in Santa
Monica. He also saw her at functions for the Jesse Owens
Foundation, for which Culbreath is a board member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched her when she was an average runner and she trained
so hard and I watched her grow,'' Culbreath said. ``She was such a
dedicated individual, it's such a great loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
