<SLUG> BC-PCA-MILITARY-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILITARY IS BUILDING A REPUTATION IN PROSTATE CANCER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Sept. 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ The U.S. military is developing a one-of-a-kind
tool in the war on prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Department of Defense's Center for Prostate
Disease Research are building the nation's most complete computer
database of prostate cancer tissue and blood samples culled from a
wide variety of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, nobody in the private sector has really been able to
put together a nationwide, multi-center database with a
standardized system to collect tissues,'' said Dr. Judd Moul, a
urologist and director of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1994, the database will be filled with donated samples
of tissue and blood collected from men at 10 Army, Air Force and
Navy hospitals in San Antonio, San Diego and Dayton, Ohio, and
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers hope to collect samples from more than 30,000
men over the next five years. Currently, information on 7,000
patients, mainly military retirees with an average age of 66 years,
has been entered in the database.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue samples from cancerous prostates are shipped to
Washington, D.C., where they are catalogued by scientists at the
Armed Forces Institute of Pathology. The samples then are sent
here, about 20 minutes away, for genetic study.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers plan to track the patients for 20 years, assess the
survival benefits of various prostate cancer treatments _ surgery,
radiation, hormonal blockade or others _ and record such side
effects as impotence or urinary incontinence. The military assures
confidentiality for the men.
</P>
<P>
   Its size, broad representation of minority men and its national
focus likely will make the database the leading American collection
of information on prostate cancer when completed.
</P>
<P>
   This database may help researchers get to the bottom of a vexing
problem: Why do black men have a much greater chance of getting and
dying from the disease? It will enable researchers to compare the
size and grade of tumors in the prostate glands of black and white
men.
</P>
<P>
   With an annual budget of about $1 million, the center also is
developing a comprehensive prostate cancer care clinic 20 minutes
away at Walter Reed Medical Center in Washington, D.C., that will
serve as a model throughout the military health-care system. The
facility will be completed by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a prototype, and we would like to emulate it at San
Antonio for the middle of the country, and one at San Diego for the
West Coast,'' Moul said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone eligible for military health care can go to the centers
for a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The center's 30 researchers, working at a laboratory at the
Uniformed Services University of Health Sciences in suburban
Washington, believe they have located a new gene linked to prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very prostate-specific gene. This is something that
is very new,'' said Dr. Shiv Srivastava, a molecular biologist and
the military center's lead researcher.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists are focusing on other areas of research. For
example, they are trying to understand at the genetic level the
deadly metamorphosis of the disease once it escapes the prostate
gland _ from a cancer dependent for growth on male sex hormones to
a cancer that will grow and kill its host even when a man's hormone
production is stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which was created by Congress and opened its doors
five years ago to manage cooperative research efforts in the
military, is drawing praise from civilian doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are perpetually working,'' said Dr. Sheldon Marks, a
urologist in Tucson, Ariz., and author of the book ``Prostate &AMP;
Cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where a lot of the new research is going to come
from,'' Marks said.
</P>
</TEXT>
