<HEADER>
A7689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     09-22 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR REPORT VIOLATES `HARMFUL TO MINORS' LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 17, Republican members of the U.S. House began fiddling
around with another version of the unconstitutional Communications
Decency Act _ call it ``Son of CDA.'' The bill (HR 3783) would make
it illegal to post material that is ``harmful to minors'' on the
Internet. The legislators didn't seem to notice their
inconsistency: Only days before, these same House GOP members voted
to put Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr's graphic sex report on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A person who violates ``Son of CDA'' can be fined $50,000 and
spend six months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Any Web site that carries advertising or charges for access is
subject to this law. Most online newspapers carry advertising, as
do a vast number of other Web pages. Many of the Web sites that
posted the Starr report carry advertising. A few specialized sites
charge for access.
</P>
<P>
   According to HR 3783, ``The term `material that is harmful to
minors' means any communication, picture, image, graphic image
file, article, recording, writing, or other matter of any kind that
(ii) depicts, describes, or represents, in a patently offensive way
with respect to what is suitable for minors, an actual or simulated
sexual act or sexual contact, actual or simulated normal or
perverted sexual acts, or a lewd exhibition of the genitals ...''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's sex report certainly fits that definition. If ``Son of
CDA'' were already the law, members of the U.S. House who voted for
posting the report on the Internet could be brought up on charges
of trafficking in material that is harmful to minors.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the House reflect America's hypocritical notions
about sex _ my sexual behavior is right and good, yours is
perverse.
</P>
<P>
   According to the bill, it depends upon who is putting the
material on the World Wide Web and for what reason. HR 3783
contains an exception: The material isn't considered harmful if _
it has political value for minors.
</P>
<P>
   So if 10-year-old Jane clicks on the Starr report, obviously its
political value far outweighs its sleazy obsession with sex.
</P>
<P>
   Would an ordinary citizen be immune to prosecution if he were to
post snapshots and descriptions of Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho,
in her former adulterous relationship? Or details of the affair
involving Republican Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana? Or motel photos of
Illinois Republican Rep. Henry Hyde and his ``friend'' during their
four-year liaison? Would the political value outweigh the sleaze?
</P>
<P>
   Barry Steinhardt, president of the Electronic Frontier
Foundation, is quoted in a Sept. 17 email release stating that the
Starr report ``has been blocked by most filtering programs and that
several Internet service providers have ordered their users to take
down mirror sites of the report.'' Steinhardt argues that although
the Starr report is important, the fact that it is being blocked by
filtering software programs indicates that it ``would not pass the
legislation's `harmful to minors' test.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Starr report with its lascivious details should
doom any sweeping legislation aimed at prohibiting sexual speech on
the Internet. Congress can't have it both ways. If Congress is
allowed to post patently offensive sexual materials, so is the
ordinary citizen.
</P>
<P>
   HR 3783 would criminalize speech that is protected by the First
Amendment. It has the same problem that the Communications Decency
Act did. Most Web sites are accessible to anyone on the Internet
without a charge and without age verification necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The technology for verifying the age of someone who wants to
access a Web site is extraordinarily expensive. If the Internet
were limited to only those sites which could afford verifying
technology, most of the best sites on the World Wide Web would
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   In Reno vs. ACLU, a unanimous U.S. Supreme Court struck CDA down
as unconstitutional because it prohibited the protected speech of
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The court said that the government cannot require speakers on
the Internet to distinguish between adults and minors.
</P>
<P>
   HR 3783 will fail for the same reasons that CDA did.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress passes this law, it will cost civil liberties
organizations more than $1 million to challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Oxley, R-Ohio, and the bill's 58 other co-sponsors
should have to repay these legal costs out of their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that would drive the Supreme Court's decision home: The
government cannot limit adult speech to that of a child's _ anymore
than Starr could have written his report on Clinton at a child's
level of language and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-21-98 1009EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
