<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Sept. 22, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PANEL (San Francisco) _ In the realm of the ordinary, it
was extraordinary _ an unvarnished view of a president in trouble.
Like the rest of the nation, a panel of four San Franciscans
watched it unfold Monday. They came away unconvinced about calls
for impeachment but deeply pained by what they saw. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLL (San Francisco) _ A majority of voters back a
statewide measure that would allow expanded gambling at Indian
reservations in California despite a barrage of expensive
television ads against it, according to a San Francisco Examiner
poll. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIDEO (San Francisco) _ The Clinton grand jury testimony
has become a hot commodity, as video stores, book publishers and
retail Web sites geared up to sell the commander in chief's
sensational testimony. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUN-FLOJO (San Francisco) _ What is a legacy? Is it shiny purple
leotards, sparkling fingernails, a snappy nickname and cascading
curls? Is it glittering medals, blazing world records, a jog with
the President and a dream-starved neighborhood that watched one of
its children soar into history? By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PAIN-THERAPY (Albany, N.Y.) _ A growing group of patients and
doctors, including former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, swear by
prolotherapy as a way to fight pain. Here's how it works: A trained
prolotherapist injects an irritant solution into damaged ligaments
and tendons. The theory is that such injections, usually a sugar or
salt solution, are helpful because they prompt the body's
inflammation response or the process by which we heal. By SYLVIA
WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ After all the build-up about
President Clinton's four hours of videotaped testimony before the
Starr grand jury, now we know the truth: Bill Clinton is a cad. It
doesn't depend on what the meaning of ``is'' is. He is a cad, and
always was. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
