<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-MALCOLM-MCDOWELL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDOWELL PLAYS THE DARK SIDE OF FANTASY ISLAND  
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 With color slide and black and white photo of Malcolm McDowell in
``Fantasy Island.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``It's a very interesting part _ rather dark with great
emotional variety. I get to do it every week. I get paid for it and
we're shooting it in Hawaii. What the hell else is there to talk
about, really?''
 &HT;    What indeed?
 &HT;    Malcolm McDowell, the young English rebel of such classic films
as ``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971), ``If'' (1968), ``O Lucky Man''
(1973) and ``Britannia Hospital'' (1982) is 55 now. Silver haired,
slim, just right to step into the white shoes of ``Fantasy
Island'''s Mr. Roarke. The show debuts on ABC Sept. 26.
 &HT;    Remember Roarke (Ricardo Montalban) in the l978-l984 series
welcoming guests to his tropical island with his sidekick Tattoo
(Herve Villechaize)?
 &HT;    Well they're reviving the concept but with a few differences,
starting with Roarke. When McDowell's Roarke is getting dressed,
riffling through a wardrobe full of white suits, he selects the
only black one. This is not the smiling, charming, benevolent
Montalban version anymore.
 &HT;    ``He's much darker and edgier,'' grins McDowell, ``not
saccharine, not pontificating.''
 &HT;    McDowell says his first reaction to stepping onto the new island
was one of horror and he had to be persuaded to look at a script.
``I took the part because it was dark. I liked the producer's sort
of 'Men in Black' approach to it.''
 &HT;    Travelers to this ``Fantasy Island'' will first pass through a
mysterious travel agency run by a couple of veteran actors _
``Picket Fences''' Fyvush Finkel and movie great Sylvia Sydney.
Then on to the island where their fantasies will be fulfilled
though they may not always like it.
 &HT;    The old Roarke made sure his guests had a pleasant time.
McDowell's Roarke believes firmly in the old saying: ``Be careful
what you wish for _ you may get it.''
 &HT;    He's attended by a strange concierge and a bellhop played by
Louis Lombardi (``Natural Born Killers'') and ``Frasier'''s Edward
Hibbert, both of whom keep dropping clues that they are on the
island to pay for their sins. Their female colleague Ariel played
by ``Twin Peak'''s Madchen Amick can morph into any female form to
fulfill any fantasy.
 &HT;    Is the island really the afterlife, as some think?
 &HT;    ``We're all dead, yeah,'' laughs McDowell collapsing in an easy
chair in a bungalow suite at in the Pasadena Ritz. ``But they make
the afterlife seem quite palatable, with these gorgeous babes
coming out of the water waving at the camera.''
 &HT;    But do Roarke and his crew inhabit heaven or hell? ``When I show
it to friends in Europe,'' says McDowell, ``they see Roarke as God.
When I show it to Americans they think he's the Devil. What do you
think that says about the two cultures?''
 &HT;    Married to his third wife Kelly, McDowell has two teenage
children from his marriage to Mary Steenburgen, now Mrs. Ted
Danson. He lives in homes in Los Angeles, the Ojai Valley (50 miles
north of L.A.) and in Tuscany.
 &HT;    A slightly sinister air is notably absent in person but has
served him well in his long career. He's made over 70 movies, some
of them among the greatest British movies ever made. And he's been
kept busier than most of the screen's nice guys.
 &HT;    Just by casting him as Roarke the producers are sending a
message about the kind of show this will be. ``Of course this
Roarke is malevolent,'' says McDowell, ``There are no boundaries
and so many layers to him. Somewhere there is a glimmer of
something, but God knows how deep or locked away it is. He is
all-knowing, all-seeing. He is this Machiavellian character.''
 &HT;    The original ``Fantasy Island'' was made cheaply in and around
Los Angeles, but this one is first cabin all the way. The pilot was
shot on three Hawaiian Islands. Not a bad place to go to work every
day.
 &HT;    And if McDowell ever gets to fulfill his own fantasy, the actor
has one all lined up and ready to fly:
 &HT;    ``When I was in my early teens, I lived near a race track in
England. And they had the British Grand Prix. My heroes were
drivers like Stirling Moss and Mike Hawthorne. So my fantasy would
be to be in a 1950s race car in a race with those great champions
and beat them.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
