A7729 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     09-22 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROVERB SAVED ... IS A PROVERB REWRITTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is one fault with old sayings, it's that they're, well
... old.
</P>
<P>
   While modernization is not always an improvement, one has to
admire the courage of an unidentified first-grade teacher who asked
her students to rewrite the second half of the following well-known
proverbs:
</P>
<P>
   As You Shall Make Your Bed, So Shall You ... Mess It Up
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably true, and a possible explanation as to why
first-graders are so reluctant to make their beds in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Better To Be Safe Than ... To Punch A Fifth Grader
</P>
<P>
   Also undeniably true. Better to hire a sixth-grader to do it for
you.
</P>
<P>
   Strike While The ... Bug Is Close
</P>
<P>
   The heel of a shoe would probably suffice for all except Florida
bugs, which require something heavier, like an anvil.
</P>
<P>
   You Can Lead A Horse To Water But ... How?
</P>
<P>
   Good question. But a better question might be, Why? Given the
temperamental nature of horses, it's probably best to let them find
water on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Don't Bite The Hand That ... Looks Dirty
</P>
<P>
   Nor the foot, knee, elbow or head, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   No News Is ... Impossible
</P>
<P>
   Brother, isn't that the truth. In fact, the problem with the
news nowadays is that the impossible has become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   You Can't Teach An Old Dog ... New Math
</P>
<P>
   Nor would it be wise to try, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Love All, Trust ... Me
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's epitaph, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   The Pen Is Mightier Than The ... Pigs
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about this one, especially if the pigs have been
elected to high office. Time will tell, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   An Idle Mind Is ... The Best Way To Relax
</P>
<P>
   I can certainly vouch for that, but we'd probably better not let
this get around as we already have too many idle minds as it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's Always Darkest Before ... Daylight Savings Time
</P>
<P>
   The best argument I've heard yet for year-'round Daylight
Savings Time.
</P>
<P>
   A Miss Is As Good As A ... Mr.
</P>
<P>
   Feminism knows no age limits, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Never Underestimate The Power Of ... Termites
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that this first-grader's dad owns a pest control
company? Either that or the kid has a great future in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A Penny Saved Is ... Not Much
</P>
<P>
   But save 1,000 pennies and ... well, you still don't have much.
</P>
<P>
   Laugh And The Whole World Laughs With You, Cry And ... You Have
To Blow Your Nose
</P>
<P>
   Which could cause the world to laugh even harder. Either way,
it's a good argument for carrying a handkerchief with you at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   Where There's Smoke, There's ... Pollution
</P>
<P>
   Is the EPA aware of this?
</P>
<P>
   Children Should Be Seen And Not ... Spanked Or Grounded
</P>
<P>
   Or deprived of sugary cereals, electronic video games, Nike
footwear and designer jeans.
</P>
<P>
   You Get Out Of Something What You ... See Pictured On The Box
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes not even that.
</P>
<P>
   If You Lie Down With The Dogs, You'll ... Stink In The Morning
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, probably, but think about the poor dogs.
</P>
<P>
   There Is No Fool Like ... Aunt Eddie
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Uncle Bob's no bright light, either.
</P>
<P>
   When The Blind Leadeth The Blind ... Get Out Of The Way
</P>
<P>
   The most astute commentary on American politics I have read in a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
