<SLUG> BC-STARR-CLINTON-PROBE-FOUR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHADOW BILL CLINTON CAN'T SHAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MICHAEL WINERIP  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 NOTE: Full-length article (8,700 words) available on request  
 &HT;     (NOTE: Editors _ This is Part IV in a four-part series.)
 &HT;    .............................................
 &HT;    Another prosecutor might have formed a different perspective on
an American president who lied about sex in a dismissed civil suit.
 &HT;    Another prosecutor could have ended the Monica Lewinsky inquiry
long ago.
 &HT;    James McKay, the Democratic independent counsel who in 1987
began investigating Republican Attorney General Meese III _ and
opted to avoid the political trauma of a trial for the nation's top
law-enforcement officer _ says that not prosecuting is one of the
hardest decisions a prosecutor makes.
 &HT;    Even within Starr's own office, there was dissent among seasoned
prosecutors over how hard to pursue the Lewinsky investigation. Two
of Starr's assistants, Michael Emmick and Bruce Udolf, argued for
accepting Lewinsky's first proffer in January, then running a swift
investigation and turning a report over to Congress in 60 days.
 &HT;    In typical Starr fashion, these issues were debated endlessly.
Over time, Starr sided with other assistants _ two of his deputies,
Robert Bittman, whom Starr affectionately calls Bulldog, and Jackie
Bennett, known among fellow prosecutors as the office expert on the
president's sex life long before anyone had heard of Lewinsky.
Ultimately, Starr opted for an investigation that would turn up
every last fact.
 &HT;    He fought up to the Supreme Court to get Clinton's Secret
Service guards to testify, up to the Supreme Court trying to get
hold of the notes of the lawyer for the late Vince Foster. Starr
pushed normal prosecutorial practices to the limit by calling
Lewinsky's mother before the grand jury.
 &HT;    It all reflected a big change in Starr. At some point, the
reserved appellate lawyer decided he would do whatever it took
within the limits of the law to squeeze people for his
investigations. He had come to realize that the White House was
going to do what defense lawyers almost always do during criminal
investigations: delay, stall, buy time.
 &HT;    What was the turning point for Starr? His assistant prosecutors
cannot pinpoint it, and who knows if even Starr can. This much is
clear: By the time Lewinsky appeared on the scene, he was poised
for an all-out assault. As to whether he was overzealous and
irresponsible or was simply ``becoming a prosecutor,'' as Rusty
Hardin, his former colleague at the beginning of the Whitewater
investigation believes _ that will depend on what is in his final
report.
 &HT;    What we do know is that Starr was willing to drive on when so
many other prosecutors would have stopped.
 &HT;    Part of the reason is Starr's legal temperament. All his
professional life, before reaching a decision, he has doggedly
pursued every last fact. His friends say it over and over: ``Ken is
determined that no one will defeat him by outworking him.''
 &HT;    As solicitor general in the Bush administration, the first case
he argued before the Supreme Court was an old-fashioned
civil-rights matter left over from the Carter era that forced the
City of Yonkers to remedy past discrimination by racially balancing
its public housing and schools. That couldn't have been a case
Starr had much political sympathy for, and yet his aides remember
his exhaustive preparation.
 &HT;    When he lost, says Robert Shapiro, a former deputy solicitor
general, ``Ken took it very hard.'' He hates to lose.
 &HT;    Starr also has a scholarly, at times pedantic, love for the law
and is genuinely offended that anyone, let alone the president of
the United States, would denigrate it. In his May ``Atticus Finch''
speech at the Charlotte, N.C., bar association, invoking the
beloved character in ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' Starr warned that
the single biggest problem facing lawyers today is ``loss of
respect for the truth.''
 &HT;    While Starr wants to be liked, he was also raised to have
confidence in his beliefs even if most people don't agree. A detail
such as a 19 percent approval rating in the polls isn't going to
deter Starr.
 &HT;    As for his career, he had little at stake anymore. When he tried
to leave the independent counsel's job in 1997 to be a dean at
Pepperdine University, he changed his mind a few days after the
announcement due to an uproar from the press and his prosecutors;
he couldn't escape. His great dream, the Supreme Court, had long
passed. His next most likely steps _ academia and corporate law _
are assured no matter how this investigation turns out.
 &HT;    Indeed, a senior partner at Kirkland &AMP; Ellis, Thomas Yannucci,
who is close to him, says that Starr, despite taking an unpaid
leave of absence from the firm in July, plans to return when this
is all over. In what may be the understatement of the year,
Yannucci says, ``Now that he's taken on his public duty, I don't
think he has the same view of public service.''
 &HT;    Did Starr come to hate the president _ did that drive him too?
The answer is probably yes, although not at first, and not until he
felt that the White House was stonewalling. I asked John Bates, a
deputy prosecutor from 1995 to 1997, whether Starr hates Clinton.
 &HT;    Bates was quiet a long time and then gave an answer so
convoluted that I stopped taking notes. I asked again, Did Starr
hate Clinton? ``I think Ken is very upset at how personal and
political the attacks on him, the office and others in the office
have become,'' he said.
 &HT;    Did moral outrage at Clinton's sexual escapades also fuel
Starr's investigation? Lawyers who have sat with him at meetings
when these details were discussed say they could tell that Starr
was offended.
 &HT;    But when asked for a single example, a single comment or
outburst, they could not provide one. They answered that it was
subtle, in the wrinkle of an eyebrow or a quiet grimace. They had
heard his deputies make lewd remarks, but not Starr; he was too
professional for that.
 &HT;    We do know that Starr was raised to take a hard line against
such behavior. When his mother was asked for this article what she
wanted Americans to think of her son, she answered, ``I want them
to think of a man who believes in doing right and a man who does
not cheat on his wife, like Clinton has on his wife.''
 &HT;    All this said, in the end Starr's motives no longer matter. That
is his victory, his measure of vindication. It no longer matters if
malicious right-wingers consorted with his office to lay a trap for
the president, if prudishness or ambition or even radio waves from
outer space drove Ken Starr. The president has admitted misleading
the American public. He lied. Through Starr's doggedness, his
relentless effort to amass every last fact, he has succeeded in
making his investigation about Bill Clinton, not about Ken Starr.
 &HT;    All Clinton's life, the man from Hope has relied on his brains,
his charm, his boyishness, his uncanny political instincts, his
superhuman energy to squeeze through tight spots. Not this time.
This time Starr built such a wall of facts that Clinton had no
place to go. On Aug. 17, 1998, at 10 p.m. Eastern Daylight Time,
Clinton hit that wall. It was not a pretty sight.
 &HT;    Which is not to say that Starr has scored his total and complete
victory. This may or may not turn out to be about obstructing
justice, but regardless, it is lots and lots about sex, and no one
wins when such private matters are made public.
 &HT;    All who became embroiled in the Lewinsky case _ the White House,
the press and the prosecutors, too _ dirtied themselves. When Starr
needed someone to show the American public that he was acting
fairly, he hired the Watergate hero Sam Dash as his ethics adviser.
Within Starr's office, Dash is referred to as ``our secret
weapon.''
 &HT;    A generation from now, if there is another president who needs
investigating, will the special prosecutor of that era hire Starr
as his secret weapon? Not likely.
 &HT;    Once Starr drops his report at Congress's door, the nation's
attention will be riveted on Clinton. It'll be (ital)just the
facts(end ital). People laughed at Starr when he once compared
himself to Sgt. Joe Friday, but it turns out he was right, he did
have something in common with the ``Dragnet'' cop.
 &HT;    In making the decision on what should be done with Bill Clinton
_ drop the matter? censure? impeachment? _ some in Congress will
choose along partisan lines, a few will look into their own
personal lives, but most will stick their fingers into the wind and
check the public-opinion polls. The citizenry will decide. Starr
has forced Americans to confront every last prurient fact, right
down to the presidential DNA.
 &HT;    There are those who will say that half the marriages in America
end in divorce, that if every spouse who lied about sex had to
confess on TV, the testimony would fill 500 cable channels for 500
years, that this is a matter between the Clintons and that what
Bill Clinton has already publicly admitted to is more than we would
ask of any other human being.
 &HT;    And there are those who will say it is shameful for a president
with Clinton's history to be arrogant enough to carry on a sexual
affair with a 21-year-old right in the White House, lie about it
and then take advantage of his good friends and aides by using them
to clean up his mess and cover his tracks.
 &HT;    Both conclusions are right, of course, and thanks to Starr,
during this era of relative peace and prosperity, some very painful
divisions will fracture the body politic before the matter is put
to rest.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Winerip is a staff writer for The New York Times
Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
