<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7802 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRIS-MATTHEWS-LEWINS     09-22 1879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-MATTHEWS-LEWINSKYGATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-LEWINSKY IS GRIST FOR THE 'HARDBALL' MILL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES TRAUB  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It's 3 p.m., Monday, Aug. 17. President Clinton is in the White
House Map Room, testifying, and Chris Matthews, the flaxen-haired,
pink-faced, know-it-all and occasionally unhinged host of
``Hardball With Chris Matthews,'' is sitting in his office in the
Washington quarters of CNBC, scarfing a basket of Wendy's fried
chicken.
 &HT;    For Matthews, this is the Day of Days _ to be equaled later, of
course, by Sept. 11, the day of the Starr report's release _ and in
his excitement he's spraying bits of biscuit on his tie.
 &HT;    ``Hardball'' is one of a half-dozen shows, mostly on cable, that
for the past seven months have been Monicamonicamonica. There's
``Rivera Live,'' also on CNBC; ``The Big Show'' and ``The News With
Brian Williams'' on MSNBC, and ``Hannity &AMP; Colmes'' and ``The Crier
Report'' on Fox News.
 &HT;    It's a Darwinian world out there, and in this jungle of passion
and diatribe, Chris Matthews is not about to end up as anybody's
lunch.
 &HT;    He calls Bill Clinton a liar about a hundred times a night, and
he mows down the defenders of the president foolish or desperate or
brave enough to appear on the show. There's an almost Rabelaisian
zest about Matthews: He lays about him with such indiscriminate
excitement that he flattens friend and foe alike. ``Hardball'' is
the most fervent of a fervent lot; it's also probably the most
entertaining.
 &HT;    Matthews, 52, is a political junkie of classic lineage. A
streetwise Catholic kid who grew up in Philadelphia, he was trained
by the Jesuit fathers at Holy Cross, served in the Peace Corps
(rather than Vietnam) and worked as a speech writer for Jimmy
Carter and as an aide and quotemeister for House Speaker Tip
O'Neill.
 &HT;    He now writes a newspaper column for The San Francisco Examiner
and has written a book about Capitol Hill (also called
``Hardball'') and a perfectly creditable book about the
relationship between Nixon and the Kennedys. He is a pol, a
moralist and a philosopher.
 &HT;    He has more theories than a Yale English professor; he has a
theory about why he talks fast, a theory about why he yells and, of
course, a theory about our obsessional interest in the president's
sex life. Matthews tends to keep talking until he's interrupted
(and beyond), so his theory is rather involved. It goes, in part,
as follows:
 &HT;    ``The great defining circus of our time was the Cold War, which
was the great gladiatorial spectacle, Us against Them, Us at home
against Us. Every great gladiatorial contest was part of this
wonderful, unbelievably stark, Manichaean struggle. And that went
away. The bad guys are gone. Now you have bread; you have bread
like you've never had it. Bill Clinton thought it was just about
bread, he was convinced it was bread _ give these people their
market, give them their Dow, give them their unemployment rate down
to 4, 3-1/2. Bread! But there's something missing, something we
need to have in our life, something gladiatorial, something
Kulturkampf, the big question, who we are, who's in, who's out,
who's right, who's wrong. Hey, O.J. came along. And Lady Di came
along for working women. That stunned me. That story was a Roman
candle: It only lasted a week and a half or two, but it was really
hot. Why do we have these things? We want to be tested. Think about
the Roman Empire, about the circuses of Nero. Think about a circus
as establishing a society's tests _ who's in, who's out, who's part
of us, who's not part of us, what kind of country do we want to
live in? I haven't figured this out yet, obviously. It's a great
metaphor.''
 &HT;    Or, possibly, it's an appalling metaphor that makes for great
TV. I asked Matthews if maybe the reason most Americans say they
want to hear less, not more, about Monica is that they don't want
their politics to be a circus.
 &HT;    ``Yeah,'' he conceded, with the air of a man accepting a premise
to rebut an inference. ``That's the way some people look at it.''
 &HT;    Several journalists who have appeared on the show told me that
they believe Matthews' assault on the president is dictated
strictly by ratings, not belief.
 &HT;    Matthews angrily denies this. Though he remains at least a
semi-chastened liberal, he also describes himself as something of a
William Bennett conservative who considers nonchalance toward the
president's sexual behavior to be a sign of loose cultural
moorings.
 &HT;    And yet, one of the great oddities of the Lewinsky affair is
that elites in the media and politics _ the very class that people
like Matthews accuse of waging a war against traditional American
values _ have been far more exercised about it than the citizens
whose views they claim to represent.
 &HT;    So if ordinary Americans are not clamoring for more Monica, who
is the ``we'' who need a Kulturkampf? Perhaps it's the media _ that
is, perhaps ``Hardball'' creates Monica, rather than the other way
around. The Cold War didn't need ``Meet the Press'' to grab the
nation's attention; but O.J. needed Geraldo, and Geraldo,
obviously, needed O.J.
 &HT;    The nexus between mega-event and talk show has grown ever
tighter since the hostage crisis created ``Nightline.'' Now it
seems naive to speak of such events as existing independently of
their coverage. The shows live from event to event, circus to
circus.
 &HT;    When Matthews' program was first shown in 1994, on the
short-lived America's Talking channel, it was called ``In-Depth,''
a name that already sounds quaint. In this feverish new world,
Monica was a godsend. No matter what Matthews says about ratings,
it was the scandal that persuaded CNBC to expand ``Hardball'' from
half an hour to an hour in March.
 &HT;    And after Monica? We'll have to have something else _ a new
cliffhanger, a new personal drama inflated to apocalyptic
proportions.
 &HT;    Talk about ``wonderful'' _ on the day of Days, CNBC decided to
air ``Hardball'' live rather than taped, in two segments, before
and after the president's 10 p.m. speech. Waiting to go on before
the speech, Matthews sat in his office, furiously scribbling
questions on blue cards.
 &HT;    A TV set in the corner showed a fixed image of the White House
entrance through which prosecutors were expected to exit _ tedium
laced with tension.
 &HT;    Matthews felt history floating in the atmosphere; he wanted to
be equal to the moment.
 &HT;    ``My goal for tonight,'' he told his staff, ``is three different
levels. We treat the moral, the legal and the political, and we ask
ourselves the right questions, as Roger Mudd did back in '74,''
during Mudd's post-mortem analysis of Richard Nixon's resignation
speech.
 &HT;    At 20 minutes till 8, Matthews took the elevator down to the
studio and seated himself at a crescent-shaped table. His guests
for the first hour included Stuart Taylor, the respected legal
journalist and a harsh critic of the president; Ron Nessen, the
former White House spokesman (for Gerald Ford); Marcia Clark, the
former O.J. prosecutor; and Elizabeth Holtzman and Dennis
DeConcini, former members of Congress.
 &HT;    The Monica shows have been a tremendous boon to former
everythings. The cable programs have so much air time to fill _
Matthews alone runs through 50 guests a week _ that they often have
to rely on people with only the kind of hypothetical expertise
conferred by resumes.
 &HT;    Matthews opened solemnly. The ultimate question, he said, was,
``Can the chief law-enforcement agent of the nation play with the
truth and still lead the nation?'' Then, with the magic words,
``Let's play hardball!'' the circus began.
 &HT;    Taylor said reports indicated that the president would admit in
his speech to ``some sort of sexual relationship'' with Lewinsky,
and that he had not been ``completely candid about it.''
 &HT;    Matthews jumped on him. ``Why do you use terms like 'some sort
of' and 'completely?'''
 &HT;    Taylor was on Matthews' side, but he had made the mistake of
stating the case in neutral terms. On ``Hardball'' there is no
middle. If you have trouble with that, you don't get invited back.
 &HT;    ``He lied,'' Taylor said, dropping the legalistic phrase. ``We
all know he lied.''
 &HT;    The gladiatorial combat that gives ``Hardball'' its faintly
sadistic appeal is not, interestingly, between the guests but
between the host and his guests. Matthews is a gleeful warrior, by
turns mocking, witty, high-minded and bullying. Even if he doesn't
know more than his guests, he can generally out-argue them; and
when he can't do that, he can just talk them into the ground.
 &HT;    Now he turned to Marcia Clark, in Los Angeles, and said, ``He's
now saying that the kind of sex he had with Monica Lewinsky did not
constitute sexual relations, and it seems to me by that definition,
Hugh Grant should be exonerated for what happened to him on the
Sunset Strip several months back, and every hooker that's picked up
on Broadway tonight for selling sex should be exonerated.''
 &HT;    Clark had battled wits with Johnnie Cochran, but Matthews
reduced her to an equivocal stammer.
 &HT;    By now, Matthews didn't need his guests at all. He turned to the
camera and shouted: ``I'd like to suggest that in every household
and every car pool and every barroom in America, and every party
you've been to in the past seven months, there's been somebody
who's spoken up for the president and said, 'I believe he didn't
have this relationship.' All of those people are part of the
recruited, commissioned and put-in-the-field army of Clinton liars.
He has made them all into liars ... and tonight he better come on
and apologize to those people.''
 &HT;    It was a majestic outburst, at least if you hate Clinton. If you
didn't, it was just plain menacing.
 &HT;    Then he cut to Elizabeth Holtzman in New York, a staunch
presidential defender, and reduced her to waving her hands and
saying, ``Chris ... Chris ... Chris'' as he buried her beneath a
torrent of words.
 &HT;    Afterwards, back in his office, Matthews looked out the window
and said: ``I got too emotional. What happened out there?''
 &HT;    What happened to restraint _ the whole rising-to-the-moment
thing? Matthews genuinely would like to give off light as well as
heat, but some combination of intellectual vanity, lack of table
manners and sheer passion does him in every time.
 &HT;    Of course, that's why he's on the air. If you want depth, you
can read a book.
 &HT;     c.1998 James Traub  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (James Traub is a contributing editor to The New York Times
Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
