<SLUG> BC-ANCIENT-CHINESE-MEDICINE-AND-MORE-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following two articles, which have been excerpted from
recent issues of Discover magazine, are available for one-shot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate. ALL THE ART IS FREE OF
CHARGE!
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ASK OUR SALES STAFF ABOUT SUBSCRIBING TO DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE.
Each week, clients receive two articles -- in both Spanish and
English -- plus eye-catching art to brighten their pages.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEEDLES AND NERVES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,500 words) &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES &QL; 
 &UR; By CATHERINE DOLD &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, physicist Zang-Hee Cho sought help from an
acupuncturist for relief from excruciating back pain. Initially,
Cho scoffed at the idea _ as an educated person, he says, he didn't
believe in acupuncture. But much to his surprise, it worked. How
could inserting needles into seemingly random points on the body
possibly affect human health? Read about Cho's subsequent study
involving this traditional Chinese medicine and a few student
volunteers in this feature from Discover magazine. Catherine Dold
is a free-lance writer who lives in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-WONDERS-OF-ACUPUNCTURE-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   SENT TO: category codes ``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general
news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN OCEAN OF SELTZER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (700 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ONE B&AMP;W SLIDE &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY A SVITIL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter's moon Europa continues to surprise scientists. First
there was evidence of an ocean beneath miles of ice. Now it appears
that the ocean is carbonated. Kathy A. Svitil is an associate
editor for Discover magazine.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-OCEAN-OF-SELTZER-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   SENT TO: category codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle
news.
</P>
