<P>
   &UR; NEEDLES AND NERVES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,500 words) &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES &QL; 
 &UR; By CATHERINE DOLD &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, physicist Zang-Hee Cho sought help from an
acupuncturist for relief from excruciating back pain. Initially,
Cho scoffed at the idea _ as an educated person, he says, he didn't
believe in acupuncture. But much to his surprise, it worked. How
could inserting needles into seemingly random points on the body
possibly affect human health? Read about Cho's subsequent study
involving this traditional Chinese medicine and a few student
volunteers in this feature from Discover magazine. Catherine Dold
is a free-lance writer who lives in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-WONDERS-OF-ACUPUNCTURE-NYTSF
