<HEADER>
A7882 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOBODY-AZR &LR;      09-22 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOBODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER CHILD MUSES ABOUT HIS MIXED HERI TAGE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
NOBODY'S SON: NOTES FROM AN AMERICAN LIFE 
Luis Alberto Urrea (University of Arizona Press; $19.95) 
 
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that home is where the heart is. But for those of us
who grew up on the border, easing back and forth between countries,
cultures and languages, the heart is often divided.
</P>
<P>
   Called by two directions, we are children of a blended world.
Our homes and hearts are defined by contrasts, clashes and separate
words that jumble together in a mixed identity overflowing border
limits.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alberto Urrea, author of ``Nobody's Son: Notes from an
American Life,'' is such a border child. He writes about the border
running through him, ``a barbed wire fence neatly bisecting my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Tijuana of an Anglo-American mother and a Mexican
father, Urrea was 3 when the family moved across the border to San
Diego. In his book, Urrea brings to life childhood memories and
sharp observations about his multiethnic identity in a collection
of essays, some previously published, that is powerful and
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Part-memoir, part-satire and part-essay, Urrea's book is as
undefinable as his transborder identity. In quick-bite, unconnected
chapters, he skips back and forth across the border to paint
colorful narratives of family history, boyhood vignettes and social
comentary that are at once funny, sad, tough and tender.
</P>
<P>
   His section on language sizzles. Satirizing the English-only
purists, Urrea points out the heavy borrowing of foreign words in
English:
</P>
<P>
   ``How will we get rid of all those pesky foreign words
debilitating the United States?'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Turkish words (like coffee). Those French words (like
maroon). Those Greek words (like cedar). Those Italian words (like
marinate). Those African words (like marimba).
</P>
<P>
   ``English! It's made up of all these untidy words, man . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I love words so much. Thank God so many people lent us theirs
or we'd be forced to point and grunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the book recount the joys and conflicts of
Urrea's divided household. He sifts through the cultural clashes in
vivid stories that sparkle with passion, wit and poetry.
</P>
<P>
   For Urrea, the conflict over identity and ethnicity began in his
own family. ``Why can't you be called Louis instead of Luis?'' his
mother, Phyllis, rants. ``Speak Spanish, pendejo!'' his father,
Alberto, shouts at the future Harvard professor of creative writing
who now is writer-in-residence at the University of Louisiana at
Lafeyette. The word loosely translates as ``good-for-nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most comic and beautiful chapters is about the home
of Urrea's surrogate parents, Mama Chayo and Abelino, his father's
tuna cannery co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   Urrea's recounting of the wonder and everyday magic of this
immigrant household is filled with delicious detail that lets a
reader savor the sights, sounds and smells as if watching the
stories unfold.
</P>
<P>
   For a book filled with delightful surprises, Urrea's final
chapter is anti-climactic. After eloquently painting scenes from
his divided upbringing, he ends without offering resolution for the
turbulence. The outcome, he implies, remains to be discovered and
defined.
</P>
<P>
   As close as he gets to tidying up is to paraphrase Thomas
Wolfe's ``You can't go home again.'' Urrea twist: ``Sometimes you
can't escape from home, no matter how far you go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's Son'' is the last book in a border trilogy that
begins with ``Across the Wire: Life and Hard Times on the Mexican
Border'' (1993), for which Urrea won the Christopher award. The
second book is ``By the Lake of Sleeping Children'' (1996). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR &LR;      09-22 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ATTORNEY SEES `NO SAFE PLACE' FICTION BECOME POLITICAL
REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Richard North Patterson set out to write his latest
novel, he asked some political consultants to help him solve a
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them OK, imagine that you've got this problem,''
Patterson says. ``Your candidate is running for his party's
nomination for president of the United States. There are seven days
left to go in the California primary. Suddenly, you find out that a
national news magazine is attempting to verify that two years
before, while still married, your candidate had an affair with a
reporter who has now been assigned to cover him. How do you kill
the story for the next seven days, and then what do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   He received some surprising responses. Do not, one of the
consultants told him, let the magazine's reporters near your guy
until the primary is over, and then make a firm denial. Find a
graceful way to lose the primary, another said, and your guy can
run again in four years when things have quieted down.
</P>
<P>
   These were some of the best political minds in the country, and
they were taking part in the political education of Patterson. They
were so honest with him _ because, he says, he wasn't a reporter
and they knew he wouldn't quote them _ that when sex and politics
made the real headlines more than a year later, Patterson felt as
if he could have written the script for what followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprised me how completely (begin itals) unsurprised (end
itals) I was by the performance of the Clinton spin machine and the
media around Lewinsky,'' he says. ``It went just about exactly as I
would have thought it would go. And before I undertook to write
``No Safe Place,'' I would have been absolutely astonished by it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No Safe Place'' (Knopf, $25.95) is a departure for Patterson,
51, an ex-attorney known for his legal thrillers (he quit his job
as a securities lawyer after his 1993 book, ``Degree of Guilt,''
made the bestseller lists). The plot, invented before Monica
Lewinsky ever set foot in the White House, is built around the
situation he took to the political wizards: In 2000, a decent but
flawed man named Kerry Kilcannon runs for the presidency and is
faced with a possible media frenzy over his one-time affair with a
reporter, a woman he still loves.
</P>
<P>
   Around the love story, Patterson builds an often unflattering
picture of politics today. There are Kilcannon's advisers, who meet
for blunt, no-holds-barred discussions on political strategy and
damage control. There is the press corps, a cadre of bored but
savvy people whose cynical humor and competitive sniping helps pass
the time between campaign stops. And there are the issues _ in this
case the big one is abortion, and all of the emotional arguments
that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't shrink at all from writing about it,'' Patterson
says. ``It would be gutless to write a novel about politics and not
try to deal with some of the most emotional issues. It's so
partisan that no one in politics feels safe admitting the moral
complexity of abortion as an issue. I wanted people to think about
how debased our dialogue around it has become. I expect to get
mail, and some of it will be angry. That's OK with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson says he has been interested in politics since he read
Allen Drury's ``Advise and Consent'' more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a majestic exploration of politics at the highest
level, with all its moral ambiguities,'' he says. ``I wanted to
write about what the world of high-stakes presidential politics was
like 40 years after Drury wrote that book. The environment has
changed entirely since then. It's much more savage, a much less
collegial world.''
</P>
<P>
   To write his book, Patterson needed entry to a culture that
seemed off-limits to a novelist with no political connections.
Then, out of the blue, he received a fan letter from former
President Bush, who wrote to say how much he had enjoyed ``Degree
of Guilt.'' Patterson seized the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that I was in touch with one of the four men in
America who'd had the remarkable experience of running for
president and winning,'' he says. ``To me, it's the most
excruciating, challenging, exhausting thing an American can do.
Candidates face endless invasions of privacy, constant scrutiny.
One mistake can wipe out years of effort in five minutes. Your
success and failure is all about (begin itals) you.'' (end itals)
</P>
<P>
   Patterson asked for Bush's help, and the former president put
him in touch with political strategists and helped him gain access
to the 1996 election campaign. He traveled in California with Bob
Dole, and met John McCain, whom Patterson calls ``one of the finest
people I know.'' He also at tended the Republican National
Convention, mingled with the press corps and tried to experience
every aspect of political campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   It was heady stuff for a writer of courtroom thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I write a book about the law, I know what I'm doing,'' he
says. ``I have a set of tools to work with, and I know how big the
project will be. But this one just kept getting bigger and bigger.
I finally decided just to go with it. I didn't plan to go to the
convention, but I had the chance so I went. I didn't know I was
going to get to travel with the campaigns, but I did. I didn't know
I would get access to the Secret Service, but I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was finally time to write, I had a huge organizational
problem. I cross-referenced a million things. I had an outline that
was probably two inches thick. It's the hardest I've ever worked on
a book.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a challenge to portray a politician's life and still
make his book entertaining, if not entirely realistic. By the time
he runs for president, Kerry Kilcannon has seen enough drama to
fill several lives _ he has survived an abusive father, a shooting
by the husband of one of his law clients, the assassination of his
brother (also a politician), and a bad marriage. Now, he is being
stalked by an anti-abortion zealot who holds a secret from
Kilcannon's past.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson does not apologize for any of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a school of fiction a while ago,'' he says. ``I call
it `New Yorker' fiction. The premise of a short story would be
something like guy gets up, guy brushes his teeth, guy tries to
figure out whether or not to leave the apartment, guy decides he
doesn't want to, and that's the end of the story. Bored my head
off. I like to write about people who want something, who engage
with the world. And things happen to those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson says he was not disillusioned by his political
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I distinguish between the good people in politics who strive
to remain good, and the system that works against them,'' he says.
``Same thing with the press. I think, however, that their world is
getting nastier and more brutish, and that the competition between
the proliferating media outlets means there will be a degradation
of standards. There's going to be more scandal reported on less
basis than ever before. I'm worried about that, and I think the
good people in the press are worried about it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the irreverent press corps he portrays in ``No
Safe Place''? Did he really see a frustrated reporter scribble a
question on a grapefruit and roll it up the aisle of a plane to the
evasive candidate secluded behind the first-class curtain?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't see it but I heard about it,'' Patterson says.
``I did, however, see people butt-surfing up the aisle on plastic
food trays. And I saw plenty of food fights.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
