<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7886 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      09-22 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ANNE FRANK &QL; 
 &UR; Melissa Muller (Metropolitan, $23)
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to resist this biography before you begin to read,
on the grounds that Anne Frank has told her own story,
sufficiently, eloquently and in her own way. But after a few pages
of Muller's book, you won't want to stop. She begins with the
arrest of the Frank family and the others who had hidden in a
warehouse annex for two years. In the surreal calm of that horrific
day, it's clear that Muller's chilling, omniscient narrative does
not compete with Anne's diary but enhances it. Later chapters
dealing with the more mundane elements of biography are no less
effective. Muller paraphrases entries that were omitted from
published versions of Anne's diary by Anne's father, who did not
want his unhappy marriage subjected to public scrutiny. That a
conflicted Otto Frank managed to keep them secret for so long is
another poignant element to Anne's story. As Muller points out, the
easiest way for Frank to hide the entries was to destroy them, but
he couldn't bring himself to do it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SAVING CHILDHOOD &QL; 
 &UR; Michael and Diane Medved (HarperCollins, $24)
</P>
<P>
   We should thank Ken Starr for turning in his Clinton/Lewinsky
opus (begin itals) after (end itals) the Medveds finished their
book. If he hadn't, they would have added it to their litany of
crimes against childhood, and the truth is that we just couldn't
take any more, not another word. The Medveds are disgusted _
drippingly, indignantly disgusted _ by everything from pushy
parents (as in the case of Jessica Dubroff, the girl who died in a
plane crash while trying to become the world's youngest
cross-country pilot, or of JonBenet Ramsey, not because she was
murdered but because she was in beauty pagents), to the media, to
kids' books (they even find fault with the ``Junior Girl Scout
Handbook''), to schools, to families that are anything but nuclear,
to peers who will lead your kids astray. They alternate these
tirades with anecdotes about their own ``precious'' children, who
seem to be the only ones in America being raised right. Do they
live on an island? In a convent? With this message _ that innocence
is under attack _ you'd think the authors would be preaching to the
converted. Instead, they spit venom, and make us run for cover.
We're glad they don't live next door. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; RENAISSANCE &QL; 
 &UR; Ruth Forman (Beacon, $18)
</P>
<P>
   Read only a few of Ruth Forman's poems and you'll hear the voice
that is behind all of them _ simple but wise, grave but joyous,
alive with language and, most of all, welcoming. She is young and
African-American, but her poems speak to universal things. Her
first book was ``We Are the Young Magicians.'' Forman will read her
work Tuesday at 7:30 p.m. at the YMCA of downtown Phoenix, 350 N.
First Ave., Phoenix. Her appearance is sponsored by The Writer's
Voice, which recently moved from its longtime location at the
Scottsdale/Paradise Valley YMCA in order to be more accessible to
most of its membership. The reading is open to the public. For
information, call 528-5543. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; REPORTING VIETNAM: AMERICAN JOURNALISM 1959-1975 &QL; 
 &UR; (Library of America, two volumes, $35 each)
</P>
<P>
   ``The guerrilla wore little, perhaps a simple peasant pajama
suit, perhaps only shorts. He was slim and wiry, and his face would
remind you of your interpreter or of that taxi driver who drove you
to My Tho. Only the haircut was different, very thin along the
sides, and very long on top and in front. It was a bad haircut, and
like the frailness of the uniform and the thin wallet with perhaps
only a few pictures of some peasant woman, it made the enemy
human.'' It was 1963, and David Halberstam was reporting from
Vietnam for The New York Times. This is a superb collection of
writing on American involvement there, by many of the journalists
who covered the war and events that led up to it, by others who
observed the tumult at home, and by some of the soldiers who
fought. Included are contributions by Peter Arnett, Tom Wolfe, Ward
S. Just, Neil Sheehan, Walter Cronkite, Seymour Hersh, Gloria
Emerson, Tom Buckley, Sydney Schanberg, Rudolph Rauch, Fox
Butterfield, Philip Caputo and many others. Daniel Lang's book
``Casualties of War'' is included in full, as is Michael Herr's
``Dispatches.'' Also here are John McCain's account of his years as
a prisoner of war, and letters written by pilot Jerry Shank to his
family until two days before he was killed in combat in March of
1964. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; N.C. WYETH &QL; 
 &UR; David Michaelis (Knopf, $40)
</P>
<P>
   ``A picture,'' said Newell Convers Wyeth, ``is the briefest
method known to communicate an idea to the human mind.'' As a child
he never read most of the stories that he would later illustrate _
``Robinson Crusoe,'' ``Treasure Island,'' ``Last of the Mohicans''
_ but he came to them soon enough. A teacher at an art school in
Boston evaluated the young Wyeth's drawing of a fox's head and
suggested that he might have a talent for illustration, at that
time a booming trade. ``I jumped at the straw,'' Wyeth later
remembered. He would ultimately call himself a failure, however,
for never achieving the career in fine art that would bless his
son, Andy, and grandson, Jamie. This first-rate biography has a big
price for the best of reasons: It includes color reproductions of
many of Wyeth's illustrations. But it also deals with the dark side
of Wyeth's life _ his compulsiveness, his depressions, his
relationship with his volatile daughter-in-law, Caroline, who was
32 years his junior. Michaelis bases his book on materials in the
Wyeth family archive and on extensive conversations with Jamie,
Betsy and Andrew Wyeth. &QL; 
(Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
