<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WHATWEKEEP-AZR &LR;      09-22 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WHATWEKEEP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVEL EXPLORES TANGLED WEB OF MOTHER-DAUGH TER RELATION SHIPS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
WHAT WE KEEP 
Elizabeth Berg, (Random House, $23) 
 
 By AMY CARLILE  
 THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever had a conversation like this with your mother? You:
``Remember when I bought those green platform shoes for the prom in
1978 and you said they were ugly?'' Her response: ``No. I never
liked those shoes but I wouldn't have said they were ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of you go on laughing about the styles of '70s and how they
are coming back into fashion, but in your mind you're sure she said
those shoes were ugly back in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   It's your perspective. Perspective is what we hold on to, what
we keep and use to form our lives. Having Mom call shoes ``ugly''
may be no big deal, especially 20 years later, but for whatever
reason it stuck in your brain. It's an occurrence that colors your
memory of the event and it's as valid as Mom's recollection.
</P>
<P>
   In her newest novel, ``What We Keep,'' Elizabeth Berg has deftly
captured the idea of perspective and how it shapes memory and
action. Plus, she's been brave enough to tackle perspective in the
most tender of relationships, the one between mothers and
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Every daughter knows the weight of a mother's influence. Every
mother knows the risk of having her words or glances taken out of
context. Each sidesteps the other in efforts to get along. The
beauty of Berg's story is that the issue of differing perspectives
is painfully real, but the pain is one of relief that the conflict
is finally acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny, the younger of two sisters, narrates the story of how she
and her sister, Sharla, ``lost'' their mother in the summer of
1958. As she flies across the country to meet up with Sharla and
reunite with their mother after not speaking to her in 35 years,
Ginny searches for clues as to why and how events happened.
</P>
<P>
   Berg sets up the family (there is a dad, too) as a very typical
'50s clan with all the stereotypes we want to believe about the
decade. Mom stays at home, Dad works. Kids hang out and watch grass
grow all summer. Life should be idyllic.
</P>
<P>
   But Mom is not quite Donna Reed. She's a good, attentive woman
who loves her husband and kids and goes through all the right
motions. She's also artistic, with an extraordinary talent for
drawing. On the negative side, the girls sense their mother is
uncomfortable in her role.
</P>
<P>
   That's the perspective of the girls, and, like most young
teenagers, they think they've got Mom all figured out. It's a
perspective that shapes the rest of the story as we learn of mom's
growing relationship and extended vacation with her new best
friend, next-door neighbor Jasmine.
</P>
<P>
   Then she divorces her husband and leaves her girls to develop a
separate life and nurture her artistic talents. To deal with this
huge blow, the girls refuse to accept any continuing relationship
with their mother. Eventually she stops trying.
</P>
<P>
   The girls weave a web around their hearts that protects them
from the memory of their mother. It also allows them to not forgive
her.
</P>
<P>
   Only decades later does Ginny allow herself to go back and see
life as it actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   In ``What We Keep,'' Berg allows us to acknowledge tough
questions about the mother/daughter relationship. What is it that
we ask of our mothers? What do they owe us? What do we owe them?
Why do we hold each other to such impossible standards?
</P>
<P>
   Her insight to this relationship is uncanny and her ability to
articulate the conflict without sounding whiny or caustic is to be
admired. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
