<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-LOVE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     09-22 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-LOVE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of IBM.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's more of a morale booster, in some respects,'' he says. He
paraphrases the typical one- or two-paragraph e-mail letter he
sends his wife: ```The weather here has been nice, Adam got two
hits last night and made a great play behind the plate. But they
lost.' Then, a few little tidbits about what's coming up for
tomorrow, and I'll tell her when a good time to call would be.'' He
gets the same kind of e-mail in return, since ``she's incredibly
busy,'' says Lorang. ```Got your note, hotter than hell here but
then again I haven't been out long enough. Thanks for the e-mail
and tell Adam better luck at the game next time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Couples say e-marriage correspondence tends to fall into one of
three general categories, representing a hierarchy of communication
needs. At the lowest level is domestic business. (As in: Have you
paid the mortgage, when are you coming home, have you fed the dog?)
At the next level is news exchange (itals)(``Tonight I am having 6
people over for dinner. Naturally, I have made spaghetti sauce, my
standard,''(unitals) as Maggie Huff-Rousselle wrote one day to her
husband.)
</P>
<P>
   At the deepest level is intimate, emotional e-mail communication
that, ideally, sustains the fabric of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Palmer to husband Joshua Rifkin:
</P>
<P>
   Hi _ as you know I'm a klutz and incompetent when it comes to
technology _ but I really wanted to let you know that I'm thinking
of you as I sit at my desk. This office is frigid _ 65F _ though I
have the thermostat up to 85!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Rifkin to Helen Palmer:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One good greeting deserves another. It's now 5.13 in the
morning on Thursday. Monday, still on English time, I also woke up
at about this time. Have fun reading this in the privacy of your
cold office, which I hope these words can warm up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But e-mail can be fraught with pitfalls, couples say. It is hard
to distinguish brevity from irritation. It's difficult, in e-mail,
to convey inflection.
</P>
<P>
   And without the reassurance of a daily presence, even
computer-aided separations can amplify insecurities and other
anxieties. (itals)``I hope you're not feeling so lonely that you'll
start a cyber affair,'' reads one Huff-Rousselle communication.
``You must have got my message about the frequent flyer miles, but
you didn't say anything back.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is ``cold in the way text is cold,'' says McLaughlin at
Harvard, who had a two-year e-mail relationship with a woman in
another city. ``It's no substitute for some of the other senses,
for being physically in the same place. A voice can convey passion
and emotion in a way that text just can't. There is an energy that
can be missing from e-mail, even if it's convincing in an
intellectual way.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why bicoastal couple Doug McCasland and Virginia Reuter
tend to sprinkle their e-mails with endearments _ ``as a sort of
replacement for an affectionate tone of voice,'' says Reuter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  McLaughlin believes there is a richness and value to e-mail
that hasn't yet been been widely appreciated. He and his
ex-girlfriend kept a journal of their e-mail letters, which they
eventually bound into a volume ``as a record of our relationship.
It was very moving,'' he says. ``It traces everything from the
giddiest early stages to the demise of the relationship in gory
detail, but beautifully so.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  E-mail, he believes, ``is qualitatively different from other
forms of communication _ better in some respects and shallower in
some,'' he says. ``It's no substitute for hearing the quiet voice
of the other person. But you can sit down and spend some time
writing out your thoughts carefully, and speak in a more considered
fashion. It is really quite powerful to receive a page of
beautifully expressed thoughts and reflections.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some believe that e-mail has the potential to be a
parallel mode of communication even for couples living in the same
city.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, an administrator at Tufts University, says she
frequently e-mails her husband during the working day to process
the minutiae of married life _ weekend plans, children's
appointments, and other details that they are too busy or tired to
deal with in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We depend on this. We get a lot of work done that way,'' said
the administrator, who asked not to use her name because she
e-mails from work. ``It's a tension for employees that you can be
audited and have all your messages thrown in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``You can see the power and uniqueness of e-mail,'' says
Sherry Turkle, who teaches the sociology of science at MIT and is
the author of ``Life On the Screen: Identity in the Age of the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it in people who live together and see each other often.
Sometimes they use it as a way to talk about something difficult to
raise. I've interviewed couples where they are literally in bed
next to each other, and one is sleeping and the other is writing an
e-mail to the spouse. ... It has the fantasy of instant
communication but with a little bit of distance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In the case of some commuting couples, of course, there can
be too much distance. Just ask Mainen, sender of that e-mail
bouquet. He got, by return e-mail, a message that hardly qualified
as a thank-you note:  &UR;  &LR; ``That was nice. I got some real ones from
Claudia.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon she logged off, permanently.
</P>
</TEXT>
