<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-22 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S NO. 1 CAD 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After all the buildup about President Clinton's
four hours of videotaped testimony before the Starr grand jury, now
we know the truth: Bill Clinton is a cad.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't depend on what the meaning of ``is'' is. He is a cad,
and always was.
</P>
<P>
   I watched all four hours and three minutes of the president's
testimony. The most shocking thing to me was his testimony about
his gifts to Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had given me a particularly nice book for Christmas, an
antique book on the presidency,'' Clinton said. ``I just thought I
ought to get up a few things and give them to her before she
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen to this master of the language. He thought he'd ``get
up'' a few things for her, perhaps pulling that $3 hat pin, $5 gold
brooch or $50 Rockettes blanket out of the drawer filled with the
gifts a president receives.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky sent a warm thank-you letter. Clinton sent her a note
saying, ``Hillary and I send our best wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is a cad. That leaves only the question of whether
being a cad is a high crime or misdemeanor, and if the Republicans
dare impeach him for it. They have more than their share of cads in
their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Already the right wing is beating the drums of culture wars.
It's Bill's boomer generation vs. middle America, according to Pat
Buchanan, who seems to have forgotten that Clinton went to Oxford,
not Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition has said that since so many people
support Clinton, there must be something wrong with their family
values. So I thought I'd give my family a call. They're Democrats,
and still have their values.
</P>
<P>
   ``As your mother, Robbie, I wouldn't let you watch this,'' said
my mother, a salt-of-the-earth New Englander.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad I didn't think of calling earlier and having her
write a note to my editor asking to have me excused.
</P>
<P>
   My father said he'd watched much of the tape while eating in the
``99'' restaurant in Mashpee, Mass., near their home on Cape Cod.
My mom had better things to do, like go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several TVs in the restaurant, and there must have
been 30 people in there, but nobody was watching it,'' my father
said. ``Every so often people would look up, but they'd say they
didn't understand what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   My dad and I could follow the tape because we'd done a lot of
homework. Besides, we're worried about what's happening to the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a tragedy that Bill Clinton has thrown his opponents
so much ammunition,'' my dad said. ``He's given new life to all
these awful people. ... You don't want the Christian Coalition
owning your life. They're a disgrace to Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to come from a truly religious family.
</P>
<P>
   Even though my father is a politics junkie, I doubt he would
have watched much Clinton testimony if he hadn't been at a
restaurant. He's a master with the remote, and would have found
``MASH'' reruns or played his tapes of old Red Sox games.
</P>
<P>
   That grand jury testimony was easily the most boring salacious
video ever made. But in a way, I'm glad I didn't get that note from
my mother and miss those four hours and three minutes of videotape.
It was interesting to hear what Kenneth Starr thought would shock
us.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't hear explicit language, as electronic stores like the
Circuit City in Concord, Calif., feared when they wouldn't allow
their TVs to be tuned to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the language was maddeningly inexplicit. Once-plain
words like ``alone,'' ``sex,'' ``affair'' and ``is'' turned out not
to mean anything, as Clinton twisted in his windiness.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't see a different Bill Clinton, as advertised. It was
the same articulate, media-wise Bill, but he had a grim, seething
quality, and clearly was afraid of stepping into a perjury trap.
</P>
<P>
   Was Clinton dodging the questions? You bet. Clinton even said he
had no interest in helping his legal enemies by doing a better job
of answering bad questions. Now that was honest.
</P>
<P>
   Was the Starr prosecution team a band of sex-obsessed
inquisitors? That's the way it seemed. By their tone and their
questions, they also seem obsessed with getting Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As my father said, ``The whole thing is degrading. The president
of the United States, a graduate of Yale Law School, has to be
interrogated about whether he knows what it means to be put under
oath.''
</P>
<P>
   It is degrading, and it is very bad family television. My family
watched Watergate, the Iran-contra hearings and Lyndon Johnson's
speech withdrawing from the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   All were important moments in TV. All involved presidents who
lied about big things, such as black-bag jobs on opponents and fake
torpedo boat attacks on American ships in the Gulf of Tonkin. Even
good old Dwight Eisenhower baldly lied about a spy plane being shot
down over the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Once we had presidents who lied operatically, and got away with
it. Now we have a president whose lies are as tinny as his
policies, and for that he's dragged through our living rooms by a
grand inquisitor.
</P>
<P>
   Who were these disembodied voices asking Clinton questions on
the tape? We never even saw the inquisitor's helpers asking the
questions. I can imagine what they looked like, though.
</P>
<P>
   They were running around naked, sticking out their tongues and
rolling around in mud.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it was the only thing left to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
