<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7909 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OVERAGE-STUDENTS-BOS &LR;      09-22 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERAGE-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SEEKS OPTIONS FOR ITS OLDER STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY   AND JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON - Boston High School student Michelle Kilgoe has learned
to ignore the taunts from classmates when she takes her seat: What
kind of 20-year-old is still in 12th grade?
</P>
<P>
   Kilgoe, a three-time dropout with a toddler, says she is
determined to finish school. To her, a General Equivalency Diploma
is ``nothing. So she, along with almost 2,500 other 19- to
23-year-olds, attends Boston public school classes with students as
much as eight years younger.
</P>
<P>
   Few of these older regular- or bilingual-education students ever
graduate. Most simply drift in and out of school until they become
too old and embarrassed to show up, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Some are there as a condition of parole or probation; others are
immigrants and may not even be literate in their own language.
Most, however, have simply been held back year after year. Almost
all need expensive services, such as counseling and intensive
academic help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down, a lot of these kids know they need to get a diploma
to succeed,'' said Boston High headmaster Thomas Hennessey. ``But
somewhere along the line they self-destruct. A lot of them stay
because their friends are here, they feel safe ... they are afraid
to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the high number of older students in Boston, School
Superintendent Thomas W. Payzant worries that money is being
misspent by trying to graduate some of them from a traditional high
school. He is organizing a task force to look at other ways to
educate the older students _ perhaps through ``bridge'' programs
that link to community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I worked in several large urban school districts,
I've never seen as many 19-, 20- and 21-year-olds in a district as
in Boston,'' said Payzant. ``Are these students best served in a
comprehensive high school?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year there were five high school sophomores in the city who
were 23 _ the age by which many adults have already graduated from
college. Altogether, there are almost 1,000 Boston public school
students age 20 or over _ and about 60 percent of them are still
not seniors.
</P>
<P>
   School officials can't simply push these students out the door
because the state, like most in the nation, has no age cap for high
school. The older students could attend adult education or GED
classes _ but many say they want to finish in a traditional high
school because the diploma means more.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a 26-year-old woman asked to be admitted to Brighton
High. School officials dissuaded her, but no law says she couldn't
go.
</P>
<P>
   Older students say they should be admired, not criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard sometimes. People say stuff,'' said Kilgoe in an
interview before her creative writing class at Boston High last
week. Most of her classmates are 17 and 18. Having little in common
with them, she keeps mostly to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've had so many chances. But I know a lot of kids who
don't even want to go to school. I'm determined to walk across that
stage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgoe was a junior at English High when she became pregnant at
age 18, 2 1/2 years ago. She dropped out and had the baby. After
that she attempted to start school at Boston High two other times,
but day care problems and a lack of motivation, among other things,
forced her out again, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgoe and most older students say they feel out of place in a
regular high school and spend as little time there as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard,'' said Claudio Brandao, a 19-year-old junior
at Boston High. Coming here from Cape Verde in 1991, he has dropped
out of school three times, each time to go back to Cape Verde. His
father wants him to quit school and get a job. But Brandao says he
needs a diploma to ``get a good job, to get into the Navy, for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The state does not track students by age and does not know how
many 19-, 20-, and 21-year-olds are still in high school statewide.
But the issue appears most acute in Boston. Superintendents
elsewhere say they have some older students, but the numbers are
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   School attendance in Massachusetts is compulsory from age 6 to
16, but it is up to local school committees to decide how long they
are willing to educate a child beyond that, according to the state
Department of Education. Few districts, if any, have an age cap.
And a 1990 state memorandum to school districts, underscoring the
federal law requiring school districts to educate special-needs
students at least until they turn 22, added that to deny schooling
to other older students would leave a district ``vulnerable to a
legal challenge by an aggrieved student.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, however, the number of older students represents a
major expense. On average, it costs $6,349 a year to educate a
regular-education student in Boston, and $1,000 more for a
bilingual student, meaning the cost this year of educating Boston's
2,459 students 19 and older who are not classified as special-needs
will be more than $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Older students say they are often embarrassed by their age and
want alternative programs, but not the equivalency diplomas that
lack the reputation of a regular high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Interim state Education Commissioner David Driscoll, like many
school administrators, said he would not support a cutoff age for
high school attendance. But he would like to see a variety of
alternatives for students who have a checkered academic history.
</P>
<P>
   Boston High's Hennessey agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest thing would be to get rid of these students,'' he
said. ``They will leave if you tell them to. But there is nothing
out there for them without a diploma other than dead-end stuff. So
we try to hold on to them as long as we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
