<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-STYMIED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENSHIP A DREAM DELAYED FOR IMMIGRANT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rakhil Shchuchinskaya fled the German siege of
Leningrad during World War II in a horse-drawn cart, lived in a
remote barracks after the war, did not attend synagogue for fear of
Soviet authorities, and was harassed because she is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Now this 67-year-old immigrant, a pediatrician in her homeland,
lives in a Brighton high-rise with views of the Back Bay and
Cambridge that are nearly as stunning as the success that her
family has fashioned in their adopted country.
</P>
<P>
   But Shchuchinskaya still lacks something that she says would
make her life complete _ American citizenship. Since she applied in
early 1997, the Immigration and Naturalization Service has asked
three times for fingerprints that must be cleared by the FBI before
she can be invited to take the Oath of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   The INS lost one pair of prints, never informed her of the
disappearance, and continued to request a new set despite
Shchuchinskaya's medically verified statement that she could not
produce good fingerprints because of a skin condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this country. I see it is very good,'' said
Shchuchinskaya, who immigrated to the United States in 1992 with
refugee status. ``I can live here and be happy. But I want to be
equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, sister, and brother-in-law have all become
citizens. Her nephew is an anesthesiologist on the North Shore; her
daughter an IBM employee in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know life; I understand they have much work,''
Shchuchinskaya said of the INS. ``But maybe they have to have more
clever people and try harder to help people.''
</P>
<P>
   Shchuchinskaya's wait comes at a time of record applications for
citizenship. Nearly 1.6 million such requests were received
nationwide in fiscal 1997, an increase of 29 percent over the
previous year, according to the Massachusetts Immigrant and Refugee
Advocacy Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston INS district, which encompasses much of New
England, there are 32,000 pending applications, according to
district director Steven J. Farquharson.
</P>
<P>
   That backlog means a prospective citizen here waits an average
of 16 months from filing to naturalization, Farquharson said. Add
to that delay a drastic change in the way fingerprints are
processed for the INS, and Shchuchinskaya's anxiety seems
well-founded, Farquharson said.
</P>
<P>
   As Shchuchinskaya.neared the five years of residency needed to
become a citizen, she submitted her application in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, the INS responded that her fingerprints were not
adequate. Shchuchinskaya submitted a new set with a doctor's letter
explaining that her eczema prevented high-quality prints.
</P>
<P>
   By February of this year, Shchuchinskaya had not heard back from
the INS. She appeared at the office to inquire about her status and
was told to place her question in a box. A subsequent INS letter
told Shchuchinskaya that her case was pending and to call in three
to four months.
</P>
<P>
   In June, when she checked back, the case was still declared
pending. Again, she was told to wait another 90 to 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   With this discouraging news, Shchuchinskaya's sister contacted
the FBI, which said its agents had never received the prints.
Another call to the INS office confirmed that they had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   A third set of fingerprints was forwarded in June. On Sept. 11,
Shchuchinskaya was informed that they had been received.
</P>
<P>
   Farquharson said he will give the case his personal attention.
All INS officers in Boston, he added, will be devoting at least two
months this fall exclusively to processing naturalization
applications.
</P>
<P>
   For Shchuchinskaya, the work cannot begin too soon. Although she
suffered religious insults and deprivation in her native St.
Petersburg, she is not satisfied merely to enjoy the comforts of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, I wasn't equal with other people,''
Shchuchinskaya said. ``Now, I want to be equal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
