<SLUG> BC-TEAM-LEAVES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTERSWEET BASEBALL: PITTSFIELD'S LOSS MAY BE BROOKLYN'S GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PITTSFIELD, Mass. _ Small things, like a perfectly executed
double steal, will be missed most. The crack of the bat. The
plastic, pigeon-scaring owls in the rafters. The delays as a fiery
sun sets in center field. Peanut shells on the worn floorboards of
the box seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's truly a magic here,'' said Kevin O'Hara of Pittsfield,
a zealous fan of the minor league Mets, who appear ready to pack
their bags for good. ``You're so close to the action that a good
pickpocket could lift the batting glove from the on-deck batter's
pants. The beauty and the memories that this little music box of a
park has brought to our lives will be sorely missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one years after Walter O'Malley's Dodgers abandoned Ebbets
Field for Los Angeles' Chavez Ravine, professional baseball is
poised to return to Brooklyn, N.Y., at the expense of this
down-on-its-luck city in the Berkshires.
</P>
<P>
   And the thought of an empty Wahconah Park _ Pittsfield's
79-year-old venerable ball yard with quirky dimensions and a rich
history _ is evoking emotions approaching those felt in Brooklyn in
1957 when the zany Dodgers turned out the lights and boarded the
train for the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like someone in your family died,'' said Marty Adler of
Brooklyn, who maintains a hall of fame to the Brooklyn Dodgers and
is jubilant at the idea of professional baseball on Coney Island.
``I feel sorry for Pittsfield because I know how they feel. I'm
sure there are people there who define their whole day on the
success of that team. And now their whole day is shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the team, but feel sorry for the fans they left
behind. But what are you going to do? What are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   What Pittsfield is doing is preparing for summer nights without
games against the Lowell Spinners, the Oneonta (N.Y.) Yankees, or
the Batavia (N.Y.) Muck Dogs _ sultry evenings when the beer garden
down the right-field line will be empty and the chance for free
pizza for everyone will no longer hinge on one fan's ability to
catch three consecutive pop flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably as enjoyable a baseball experience as a fan
could ask for,'' said Bill Mesick, vice president of the Pittsfield
Mets fan club. ``You're right there with the players. You can hear
the arguments with the umpire _ juicy words and all. This place is
historic. A lot of great players have played here. I wish they
would just jack that stadium up, renovate it, and put it right back
down again.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not going to happen. The team's owners have made it
plain that they need a new facility if they're going to stay here.
And there seems little chance of that happening. Pittsfield Mayor
Gerald S. Doyle Jr., through a spokesman, said the situation is out
of his control. He said he expects the team to honor its licensing
agreement, which calls for the team to play here at least through
the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani announced last week that his
city had reached a deal in principle with the Mets to move their
single-A minor league club from here to a new, $20 million stadium
to be built on the site of an abandoned amusement area on Coney
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is not final yet. The Yankees could reject the
move of a minor league team into their territory. But, club
officials say, it is increasingly likely that the Mets will depart
Wahconah Park after next year's season.
</P>
<P>
   William L. Gladstone, the minor league Mets president, said that
like the Dodgers, who were willing to stay in Brooklyn if they got
land for a new stadium, the Mets would like to stay here. But the
facilities _ spartan clubhouses, and insufficient lighting _ are
substandard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful old playing field and the scene is
beautifully bucolic,'' said Gladstone, a Brooklyn native who
purchased the team in 1992 for $850,000 with four other investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from a fan's point of view, it's not a comfortable
stadium. The bathroom facilities are pretty bad,'' he said.
``Still, it's a charming place to see a baseball game. We've shown
more loyalty to Pittsfield than any of our predecessors and some
people appreciated it, which doesn't mean they won't be mad as hell
when we leave _ or if we leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Mets' 10-year stay at Wahconah Park has made them
the longest hometown team since the Pittsfield Hillies ended their
17th season here in 1930. Since then, a succession of bush league
clubs have come and gone, wearing the uniforms of the Electrics,
the Indians, the Red Sox, the Senators, the Rangers, the Brewers,
and the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   From seats as close as 40 feet away from the action, fans
through the years have watched former Red Sox first baseman George
Scott send towering home runs over the center-field fence, whose
due-west orientation occasionally forces only-in-Pittsfield delays
at blinding sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, players such as Lou Gehrig, Rafael Palmeiro,
Mark Grace, and Greg Maddux have laced up their cleats in
Wahconah's dank locker rooms and thrilled the fans, who pay $2.75
for general admission and $1.25 for a snow cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's like going to Fenway Park on a smaller scale,''
said Jacko Furey, 60, a Pittsfield native and longtime Mets fan.
``It would be a big loss. I know the kids love it there. They get
to see the future stars. A lot of summer nights, it'll be empty
with no games to go to. Last year, I'll tell you, it was just great
when we took the championship. It's pure baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The team drew 84,323 fans this year, the most since 1992. The
tally makes it the sixth most popular of 14 teams in the New
York-Penn League. ``We offer a lot of charm,'' said team spokesman
Ethan Wilson. ``But charm can only go so far and last for only so
many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Pratt, pulling draughts at nearby Pepe's tavern, a
post-game hangout, said that if the Mets leave, it will be another
blow to a city that already has absorbed too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Electric pulled out about 10 years ago,'' said Pratt.
``Now we've got the PCB issue. The department store (the former
England Bros.) is empty. This was the only positive thing that we
had going here. It's going to be a void.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pittsfield is a baseball city, Pratt and his customers
insisted on a warm afternoon last week. And, like Brooklyn, they
will hunt for another franchise that will spark standing ovations
and affordable family entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to Pittsfield is not to give up hope and keep trying
to get another team,'' said Paul Montanaro of Brooklyn, a
long-suffering Dodger fan who is anxious for professional baseball
to return to his native Brooklyn. ``That's what we did all these
years and see what's happening now? We're back in the baseball
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
