<HEADER>
A7913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      09-22 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMMATE PERFORMER AWAITING HIS REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A deceiver Bill Clinton undoubtedly is and perhaps not a
deceiver alone but a perjurer as well, depending, of course, on the
many subtle shades of meaning that evidently attach themselves to
words like ``is'' and ``alone.''
</P>
<P>
   But semantic uncertainties aside, another thing was also clear
Monday in Clinton's videotaped testimony: MondayHe remains a
consummate political performer, capable of gaining an audience's
sympathy, even while trying to hide in a fog of cleverly chosen
words.
</P>
<P>
   In a situation unimaginably stressful, Clinton proved once again
that he is in a league of his own when playing to a larger
audience. And, as his own comments make clear, there's little doubt
that Clinton suspected that his testimony would eventually be made
public, even when he gave it on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the four-hour session, Clinton's answers were aimed
not so much at the prosecutors who have pursued him for years or
even the grand jury, but rather at the country itself.
</P>
<P>
   Forget all the spin from before the video's release about an
enraged president losing his temper, quarreling with his
inquisitors, ripping his microphone off, and abruptly demanding
breaks. For almost the entire four hours, Clinton hit just the
right notes: contrite, sorrowful, empathic, and eager for
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of making his own case, this was a far better
performance than the president's angry speech to the nation later
the same day, in which he lashed out at prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In word and tone, in body language and gesture, he seemed
occasionally ashamed, often apologetic, sometimes pained, annoyed,
reluctant.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall impression he conveyed was of a man making a
good-faith effort to answer questions, even while trying to salvage
a shred of personal dignity for himself and his family.
</P>
<P>
   There was no window into the angry inner psyche of a master
manipulator. Instead, what viewers saw was the Clinton they have
come to know, a man likable even as he misleads, someone many
Americans find appealing despite a long history of troubling
personal conduct. Despite a bout or two of finger-wagging and a
couple of flashes of anger, Clinton was polite even to his
inquisitors, treating them, in the main, more respectfully than
they treated him.
</P>
<P>
   He was disrespectful only to plain-spoken truth. But since
little by way of revelation came from his videotaped performance,
the effect was to let the president sugarcoat apparent (and in some
cases admitted) evasions, to plead a faulty memory, and to
interject explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton haters, of course, will have plenty of fuel for their
rage, while others now have proof for their long-held suspicions
about the evasiveness that seems to run to the core of his
character.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the president's much--remarked-upon ability to
compartmentalize his job and troubles and thus keep his calm under
fire. As Monday's videotaped testimony shows, what's truly
extraordinary is his ability to compartmentalize, categorize, and
qualify the truth.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many find it laughable that the president _ even as
he did not deny that Lewinsky performed oral sex on him _ could
still maintain that he had no ``sexual relations'' with her. The
same is true of his assertion that he tried to be truthful, though
not unnecessarily helpful, in denying a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky when deposed in the sexual-harassment lawsuit brought by
Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Equally incredible was his contention that Monica Lewinsky's
deposition, as paraphrased by Clinton lawyor Robert Bennett, could
have been entirely truthful in contending that ``there is
absolutely no sex of any kind in any manner, shape, or form, with
President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, actually, in the present tense, that's an accurate
statement,'' said Clinton. He later elaborated: ``It depends on
what the meaning of the word `is' means. If `is' means is, and
never has been, that's one thing. If it means there is none, that
was a completely true statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton displayed the same relativistic approach to truth when
prosecutors asked, ``Do you agree with me that the statement, `I
was never alone with her,' is incorrect? You were alone with Monica
Lewinsky, weren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, again, it depends on how you define alone,'' the
president replied.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went. But to what end?
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the airing of Clinton's four-hour testimony,
broadcast outlets periodically flashed the day's stock-market
fluctuations, as though the market was an EKG monitoring the
presidential pulse.
</P>
<P>
   In a way it is. The market, as it happens, dived as Clinton's
testimony began, but wound up ahead for the day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Content with the economy, Americans seem forgiving of their
tremendously talented, but terribly flawed, chief executive.
Indeed, polls show that despite what they now know about Clinton,
most Americans still approve of the job he is doing and hope he
remains in office.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think that anything that average voters saw Monday
will change their minds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
