<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPORTS NIGHT' SEEMS LIKE A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SPORTS NIGHT 
Starring: Josh Charles, Peter Krause, Felicity Huffman, Robert
Guillaume, Joshua Malina 
On: ABC 
Time: Tuesday at 9:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ABC introduced ``Sports Night'' to TV critics in July, the
network revealed that it hadn't yet opted to employ a laugh track
on the show, at the urging of writer and executive producer Aaron
Sorkin. The reason: This comedy, which goes behind the scenes of a
cable series similar to ESPN's ``SportsCenter,'' contains more
dramatic moments and fewer one-liners than most of TV's half-hour
sitcoms. Alas, convention and network risk-fear prevailed, and
``Sports Night'' arrives equipped with one of those metallic,
automatic, fascistic chuckle machines that undermines realism as it
commands you to find something funny.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, ``Sports Night'' survives the trills of artificial
laughter to emerge as one of the more promising new shows of the
fall season. Yes, it joins TV's already long list of
self-referential media sitcoms whose family tree goes back to ``The
Mary Tyler Moore Show.'' But with the guiding hand of Sorkin, whose
screenwriting credits include ``A Few Good Men'' and ``The American
President,'' ``Sports Night'' manages to distinguish itself with
aspirations to be like ``Broadcast News,'' the movie that blended
the ethics of the news business with the emotional toll that
deadline work takes on its employees. Minutes before airtime, the
hyped-up staffers of ``Sports Night'' are quipping excitedly; the
morning after they face loneliness, broken loyalties, and moral
self-loathing about the tabloidization of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The show revolves around the popular anchoring team of Dan
Rydell (Josh Charles) and Casey McCall (Peter Krause). In the
premiere show, McCall is depressed about his separation from his
wife and son, and his on-air performance is suffering. While the
boss and a network stiff prepare to fire him, Rydell and the show's
producer, Dana Whitaker (Felicity Huffman), protect him and try to
jolt him out of his funk. In the context of ``Sports Night,'' it
seems, anything less than consuming passion about the workplace is
unacceptable. Tonight, in a humorous sequence, Dana gives the
coveted assistant producer job to a neurotic sports nerd who knows
to the day precisely how long ``Sports Night'' has been on the air.
Like her, he's workaholic material.
</P>
<P>
   It's unusual, and refreshing, for the central characters on a
sitcom to be so engaged in their jobs. ``Sports Night'' does bring
their personal lives into play, and the professional relationships
are deeply personal, but the action stays in the newsroom. The
first two episodes occur entirely within the ``Sports Night''
studio _ a set that is well-used with the help of some confident
camera work.
</P>
<P>
   There are bugs that need to be worked out of ``Sports Night.''
While it moves without much clunkiness between the serious and the
silly, the dramatic moments are in need of fine tuning. In the
climactic scene when Casey calls his wife and asks her to wake up
their son to watch an inspirational sports event, the
sentimentality meter goes into the red. Sorkin and the other
writers will need to be militant about keeping out the schmaltz,
and sticking to the restrained or angry drama that does work, such
as when Dana accuses Casey of ``screwing up'' her show.
</P>
<P>
   For a new series, ``Sports Night'' already has a nicely
developed sense of ensemble and texture. Charles and Krause show a
natural chemistry as anchors and friends, and Robert Guillaume has
strong presence as the imposing executive producer. The most
appealing actor, though, is Huffman, who is dynamic as the
committed producer who only lives for airtime. She's got caffeine
running through her veins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
