<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FLOJO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HEAR THE TRUTH ABOUT FLOJO'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWENN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What is a legacy? Is it shiny purple leotards,
sparkling fingernails, a snappy nickname and cascading curls? Is it
glittering medals, blazing world records, a jog with the president
and a dream-starved neighborhood that watched one of its children
soar into history?
</P>
<P>
   Florence Griffith Joyner left all of that behind when she died
Monday morning at age 38 _ glory, glamour and a 7-year-old
daughter, too. But in dying far too soon, she might have left
something else, something that isn't as pretty or charming as the
woman herself, something that would be all too easy to bury with
her.
</P>
<P>
   If FloJo took performance-enhancing drugs, we need to know. Not
to sully her memory or label her a cheat, and certainly not to
blame her for her own death. We need to know because, if all the
rumors about her are true, she still can contribute something to
sports and to the youngsters who adored her. She can warn them, and
she can protect them.
</P>
<P>
   The innuendo about her will never vanish. No American Olympian
has ever been so strongly suspected of steroid use. When FloJo
obliterated world records in the 100- and 200-meter dashes in 1988,
she was 28 years old and astonishingly faster than she had been at
age 24. New, enormous muscles popped out from her thighs. Like her
male counterpart, Ben Johnson, she seemed too swift to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The drug testers in Seoul, ridiculed as ineffectual by most
competitors, somehow caught Johnson. FloJo never tested positive.
There was no scientific evidence against her. Her peers, though,
whispered constantly. Some talked out loud. In his autobiography,
Carl Lewis wrote: ``It was a common belief in the track world that
Florence had used drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to hear this now, not when her old neighbors from
Watts are remembering what she did for their community, when she
can't defend herself with another round of denials.
</P>
<P>
   But we have become too skilled at turning away from these
stories. We told Gwen Torrence to hush up in 1992, when she didn't
win an Olympic medal and accused her competitors of drug use.
Torrence chose the wrong time to complain, when her protest was all
about winning and losing. But now, with FloJo gone, we need to ask
questions, about health and safety instead of winning and losing,
about how much was risked for those brilliant moments in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   This generation has already turned on the radio and television
too many times to learn that a famous young athlete's heart has
stopped beating. Sergei Grinkov collapsed on the ice, Hank Gathers
and Reggie Lewis on the basketball court. FloJo might be just like
them, a sad and confounding mystery, allotted her 38 years by fate
and then taken randomly.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy is being performed, but it may not yield more than a
hint of what took FloJo. She might have had congenital heart
disease. She might have damaged her heart with steroids, or she
might have taken performance-enhancing drugs with no real
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have not established a clear link between steroid use
and long-term health problems. They suspect liver and heart damage,
but they can't ethically experiment on humans for confirmation.
They have to rely on scant anecdotal evidence, from the rare
athletes who have admitted to drug use or been caught. If FloJo
ingested banned substances, they need to hear the truth from anyone
close to her, anyone who would know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Courson, a former Pittsburgh Steeler lineman with heart
disease, has acknowledged taking steroids during his NFL career. He
has gone on a crusade against performance-enhancing drugs, giving
seminars in schools, trying to break through what he calls a
conspiracy of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Courson could be considered an unscrupulous cheat. He is, after
all, an admitted doper. But in anti-doping circles, he is
considered a beacon because he told the truth. The same could hold
for FloJo's memory, if she took drugs and a responsible confidant
tells her story with the best of intentions.
</P>
<P>
   And if FloJo took drugs, she was not alone. When news of her
death spread Monday, there should have been widespread fear in
baseball clubhouses, in football locker rooms ... Many athletes
should have started wondering: Could I be next?
</P>
<P>
   These last few months have been full of lessons about
performance-enhancing substances _ from the police crackdown at the
Tour de France to the revelation that Mark McGwire used a hormonal
supplement banned in some sports but allowed in baseball. In the
end, though, we brushed the lessons aside and waited for the happy
moments, to cheer for the sprint down the Champs-Elysees and for
Homer No. 62.
</P>
<P>
   But we could wake up to more and more news reports like the one
we heard Monday, that another star has passed away. The last 20
years have yielded a generation of athletes who turned their bodies
into lab experiments.
</P>
<P>
   If FloJo was one of them, it is disrespectful to her memory to
wait for this tragedy to fade away so that we can resume the
cheering. If there's any chance that sports stardom killed her, we
need to know, to prevent it from happening again and again. It
would be an awful way to remember her, but it would be more
valuable than world records or hot fashions. It would be a real
legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
