<HEADER>
A7932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-BOS &LR;      09-22 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHOY THERE, MICKEY! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would you or should you sail on a ship with mouse ears, rather
than some fanciful logo, emblazoned on its smokestacks?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world's newest cruise ship, the Disney Magic, the
first of a two-vessel fleet of the Disney Cruise Line.
</P>
<P>
   And it's pure Disney magic, everything you think a cruise should
be, with lots of fanciful touches and unexpected fun. The Magic
looks just like a grand ocean liner should, but even here Disney
shows off its imagination. Take those smokestacks: Only one is
real; the other hides the ESPN lounge, complete with stadium
seating for catching the latest in sports events with big- screen
action.
</P>
<P>
   As the Magic was getting under way from Port Canaveral, I took a
shortcut through the ESPN Skybox located within the fake funnel to
watch the sail-away festivities, only to bump into Minnie Mouse,
who then rubbed noses with me, took me into her arms, and danced to
the sounds of the band outside. How will I explain this to our
cats? And, although I know Mickey is a nice guy, I was glad to see
he was busy in an adjoining room waiting to greet the passengers on
this pre-maiden voyage sail. Mickey and Minnie were dressed in
their best sailing outfits.
</P>
<P>
   This is Disney's entry into the cruise market. And Disney is
promising innovations, a ``seamless'' vacation, and places for kids
and adults where neither should meet. A tall order. While my cruise
was less than seamless and had a few bugs, the Disney concept looks
like a winner, and should win converts to cruising. Already the
company says 60 percent of its passengers have never cruised
before. That's the magic of the Disney name.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Magic began sailing July 30, months after its planned
inaugural. The ship, Disney said, was not finished in time by the
Italian shipyard. Disney's vacation concept is to offer three- and
four-day cruises along with a three- or four-day vacation at Disney
World, about an hour's drive from Port Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   All the cruises sail to Disney's own private Bahamian island,
Castaway Cay; four-day cruises also call on Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's idea for a seamless vacation is to have guests check
into Disney World, where they receive a ``World'' card that is used
to open the booked resort room, as a credit card for all purchases
in Disney World, and as identification. After the resort stay,
guests are bused to Port Canaveral to Disney's own terminal, where
there is no check-in; passengers just walk aboard the ship, showing
their cards. On board, the same card is keyed to open the stateroom
door, again be used for purchases, and to be identification on
leaving or entering the ship at port.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the ships of the day, which seem somewhat boxy,
the Magic looks the way a ship should. Entering, you find no huge
atrium but rather a somewhat plain lobby, similar to what one might
find on a grand ocean liner of the past. The largest dining room,
Lumiere's, also has the feel of one of the queens of the '30s and
'40s. Even the piano lounge, Sessions, has that feel.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you will not find on board is a casino. That's not
part of the Disney image, a spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney magic works wonders in its staterooms, lounges,
showroom, entertainment, children's facilities, innovative dining,
and on its private isle. Disney's island outdoes other cruise lines
not only in its facilities but, especially, because the Magic docks
at the island. On other cruise lines, one must tender in to the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Staterooms on the ship are well thought out, particularly for
families. All have extra space, allowing families of five to share
a room. Many rooms can be booked with an adjoining stateroom. All
have an innovative two baths; one has a shower/tub and sink, the
other a toilet and sink. Many staterooms have private balconies.
</P>
<P>
   While the ship is keyed to families, those without kids should
find enjoyment away from the younger set. Many lounges and one
dining room are for adults only. No kids. Adults will find a
night-time show area with a comedy club, a rock/ country lounge,
and other entertainment. A reservations-only Italian restaurant,
Palo, is found topside, with a sweeping ocean view, and it's just
for adults. There are also an adult pool and a marvelous spa and
salon. One can indulge in facials or therapies, using water or
aroma. If you're into fitness, there are plenty of programs
available; if you're looking to get fit, a personal trainer is
available.
</P>
<P>
   Kids should have a ball aboard. Huge areas are set aside for
them. Disney will have up to 50 counselors on board to care for
them from early morning to late at night. The Oceaneer Club, with a
Captain Hook theme, is a lavish area for the 3-to-8 set. The
9-to-12 gang get the Oceaneer Lab, where computers galore are
available, and they can have fun with science projects. On the open
deck, youngsters have their own pool and play areas.
</P>
<P>
   Most cruise lines forget about teenagers. The reason is simple:
Teens like to do their own thing, don't want programmed activities.
I know this from watching my own children grow up on cruises. But
Disney is creative and offers Common Grounds, a lounge area just
for teenagers where they can meet other teens, enjoy a cappuccino
or mock cocktail. Should the teens want to do something, there are
counselors there to help organize games, pool parties, whatever. On
Castaway Cay, the teens have their own beach area.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovation Disney offers is rotating dinners. Each night
guests dine in a different dining room; even their waiters move
with them. The most enjoyable room is Animator's Palate, where
black-and-white cartoons burst into color.
</P>
<P>
   Disney outclasses its competitors also in its showroom. It is
the equal, if not better, than any Broadway playhouse. And the
shows are spectacular. One featured the magical moments from Disney
classics, another an original fantasy with raging seas and
fire-breathing dragons.
</P>
<P>
   While our cruise had its bugs, it was a pre-maiden voyage. We
found some dining lacking, especially breakfast and lunch buffets,
which offered far less in variety and quantity than other lines.
One show suddenly stopped when its computer-operated animated
dragon failed to move.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports of a lack of daytime activities for
adults, and complaints of not being able to book a spa treatment or
reservation at Palo. Disney has been working on these and other
problems, and by now should have them under control.
</P>
<P>
   The new line is headed by Arthur Rodney, who helped build
Crystal Cruises into a five-star line. Rodney brought along others
from Crystal, including a photogenic captain, Tom Forberg, who
proudly notes that the Magic is the most stable ship he's been on,
and that ``it looks like a ship.''
</P>
<P>
   One other complaint heard from many is that the Disney Magic is
expensive for families. Rates for a family of four would be between
$4,000 and $5,000 _ much higher than on a competitior such as
Carnival, Royal Caribbean or Premier. Disney stresses value, and in
this case there is no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Magic was built for family cruising, and its
facilities on land (Castaway Cay) and sea are first rate. Even its
international staff, while having some rough edges, is highly
enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the Disney Wonder, a sister vessel, will join the
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Magic is an 85,000 ton, 964 foot long vessel carrying
1,700 guests double occupancy (2,400 using extra berths in each
room).
</P>
<P>
   The ship offers three- and four-day cruises combined with a
three- or four-day stay at Disney World, about an hour from Port
Canaveral. The ship calls on Nassau and Disney's private island,
Castaway Cay. Disney's island is the only one where a cruise ship
can dock.
</P>
<P>
   Of its 875 staterooms, 73 percent are on the outside, 44 percent
of those with balconies.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has all the amenities of a floating resort (no casino,
however), along with separate adult and children's areas. Almost an
entire deck, 15,000 square feet is devoted to children's
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for a seven-day Walt Disney World and Magic cruise begin
at $1,295 a person. Rates depend on ship and resort accommodations
selected. For third, fourth or fifth guests sharing a room, rates
are $275 for child aged 2; $999 for children 3-17 and $1,199 for
adults 18 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The price includes round-trip air from most cities in the United
States and Canada; accommodations on land and sea; unlimited
admission to Disney World parks, ground transfers and more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
