<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI SUPPORT BY LABOR DECEPTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The labor unions that publicly declared their support
last week for Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, gives Attorney General
Scott Harshbarger more _ not less _ assurance that he has a solid
base of support within organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Cellucci and his supporters attempted to reap as much
political mileage as they possibly could with the endorsements of
Teamsters Local 25, Hotel and Restaurant Employees Local 26,
Service and Employees International Union Local 254, National
Association of Goverment Emoloyees (NAGE) and the New England
Council of Iron Workers.
</P>
<P>
   These endorsements reflect neither a defection nor a split among
unions. Rather, they reflect more of a splinter from organized
labor's large platform which has given its support, largely through
the key endorsement of the state AFL-CIO, to Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, these endorsements were not much of a surprise to
union activists supporting Harshbarger. They were expected.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Teamsters Local 25 was with the former Gov. Wiliam
Weld-Lt. Gov. Cellucci team since they were elected in 1990. In
addition, current Local 25 president, George Cashman, is a current
Weld appointee to the Massachusetts Port Authority's board of
directors and represents workers at the port authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel and Restaurant Employees union also has backed the
Weld-Cellucci team since 1990. Its president, Janice Loux, is a
Cellucci appointee to the MBTA board of directors, for which she
receives a $7,500 a year stipend. And the union's former president,
Dominic Bozzotto, has been recently appointed director of personnel
for the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority.
</P>
<P>
   As for SEIU Local 254, its president, Edward Sullivan, is an
appointee to the state's Workers Compensation Advisory Board and is
also a long-time Weld-Cellucci backer.
</P>
<P>
   Since NAGE did not back the Democratic gubernatorial candidate
in 1994, some union activists said they were not surprised that it
is backing Cellucci this year.
</P>
<P>
   While the New England Council of Ironworkers backs Cellucci, the
largest local in the council, Ironworkers Local 7 in South Boston,
has endorsed Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Cellucci's labor endorsements actually ring hollow
when compared to the unions that endorsed Harshbarger, including
the ones affiliated with the state AFL-CIO which gave its backing
in June to Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Harshbarger has received individual endorsements from
more than 30 unions representing 250,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Haynes, president of the state AFL-CIO said of
Cellucci's endorsements, it's the members of these unions who
actually do the voting in this election. When they compare the
records of Harshbarger and Cellucci, the membership will select
Harshbarger as the champion of working men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   What means even more good news for Harshbarger (bad news for
Cellucci), is that Harshbarger is gaining the support of the labor
unions that backed his rival in the Democratic primary, former
Congressman and Ambassador Brian Donnelly. Plumbers Local 12
recently wrote a letter of endorsement for Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Cellucci and his supporters try to portray the labor
endorsements as major defections, the fact is they are long-time
loyal Harshbarger supporters who represent merely a splinter from
the platform of organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it was labor that helped Harshbarger go over the 50
percent mark in voter support in a three-way primary race. And it
was labor's help that gave state Sen. Warren Tolman an eight-point
edge over unexpectedly strong rival Dorothy Kelly-Gay in the
Democratic primary for Lt. Governor.
</P>
<P>
   Strong union backing of state Sen. William Keating no doubt
contributed to his impressive victory in the three-way Democratic
primary race for Norfolk County district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   If labor had not been strongly behind the candidacy of state
Sen. Lois Pines in her race for attorney general, her loss in the
primary to Middlesex County DA Tom Reilly could have been far worse
due to her own political mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   As the overall results in the September primary demonstrate, and
what the November final will likely confirm, labor is back and
firmly behind the Democratic gubernatorial team of Scott
Harshbarger and Warren Tolman _ and there is no better confirmation
of this than the small number of expected labor endorsements that
went to Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
