<HEADER>
A7935 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-22 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE AND SOSA OFFER A RESPITE FROM THE NATION'S TROUBLES  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The majestic arc of a baseball sailing over a left
field fence doesn't hail a cure for cancer, the cessation of war or
the promise of true love for all of God's children.
</P>
<P>
   Its flight doesn't carry the meaning of what it is to be an
American or instructions on how to live a good life.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is the home run that remains the single most captivating
and breathtaking event in sports, a burst of explosion that lasts
for only seconds yet can reverberate for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Never before have two men provided so many memorable and
explosive moments in one season as have the St. Louis Cardinal's
Mark McGwire and the Chicago Cub's Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest home-run race in history has seen both men eclipse
Roger Maris' single-season home-run record. Neither Barry Sanders
pursuit of the NFL record for most yards rushing in a season or
Michael Jordan's assault on the NBA's single-season scoring record
so stopped the nation in its tracks and demanded its attention like
the McGwire-Sosa phenomenon has done.
</P>
<P>
   The cliche holds true that football may be America's passion but
baseball is still its pastime. For whatever reason, baseball has
always had the capacity to provide the nation with a respite,
however brief, from its troubles.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1941, as Europe was locked in war, the feats of
another pair of baseball players transfixed the nation with marks
that haven't been matched since _ Joe DiMmaggio's 56-game hitting
streak and Ted Williams' season ending batting average of .406.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the exploits of McGwire-Sosa have brought much
needed relief from the sexploits of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (Not that baseball has ever been perfect. The home-run chase
revived talk of asterisks. One should never have been attached to
Maris because he played a longer season than Babe Ruth and it's
silly to suggest that one should be applied to McGwire because of
his use of a legal but controversial nutritional supplement. But if
asterisks had to be used, they should be attached to every record
set before 1947, before Jackie Robinson changed the complexion of
the game and elevated baseball's talent level.)
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't simply the sheer athleticism and competition of
McGwire-Sosa that have so captivated and touched the nation; it's
also the grace and dignity with which both men carry themselves and
the respect and fondness they have for each other and the game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite different backgrounds, McGwire, a white Californian who
had a privileged childhood, and Sosa, a black Dominican who shined
shoes and sold fruit to help his mother, both men have embraced
each other and the record chase with affection.
</P>
<P>
   Embraces that have transformed each of them into icons. McGwire
finally realized the potential that was expected of him if he could
just stay healthy for an entire season while Sosa evolved from a
gifted, though little known, player into a superstar who is now a
household name.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the defining period of the season came last month when
the Cardinals and a slumping McGwire landed in Chicago for a
series. Sosa's playful and infectious personality rubbed off on and
loosened up McGwire for the final leg of the home-run derby. It was
as if Sosa reminded him that baseball was a game and he should be
having fun.
</P>
<P>
   No, we won't find any philosophical truths in home runs. But the
enthusiasm of Sosa, and now McGwire, reminds us that baseball is a
game and it's OK to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
