<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TAHITI-2TAKES-     09-22 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TAHITI-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAHITI CRUISE BRINGS A DREAM TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAPEETE, Tahiti _ Like so many others, I've dreamed of leaving
civilization behind and escaping to one of those island paradises
in the South Pacific. Living freely off the land, swimming in
azure-colored waters. No cares, no cash, no worries.
</P>
<P>
   Reality, unfortunately for me, always sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Blame James Michener, Robert Louis Stevenson, Herman Melville,
and Paul Gauguin for inspiring the dream. Their writings and
images, as well as those of others, have created this vision of
paradise in my mind _ and, I'm sure, in countless other minds.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, with the introduction of a new cruise ship
sailing in the lovely waters of the South Pacific and named for the
artist who has so beautifully captured the sensuous images of the
islands, it was time to mix a bit of reality with a lot of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first realities was that Papeete, Tahiti, is a long,
long way from Boston. Is paradise possible in just over a week's
vacation, and would it be worth it? The answer to both questions is
``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Paul Gauguin , a 320-passenger vessel, is as delightful and
casual as Polynesia itself. The vessel sails weekly from Papeete to
five of the islands of French Polynesia _ Huahine, Raiatea, Bora
Bora, and Moorea.
</P>
<P>
   The Gauguin is a small vessel that proves big on pleasure. It
looks the way a ship should, with a simple yet elegant interior
design. All the amenities one could ask for on a ship are aboard,
along with some surprises. When docked, the ship's stern lowers to
provide a sports platform from which one can water-ski, kayak, or
windsurf. The sports platform is also the place to borrow
snorkeling gear because every island visited is ideal for
snorkeling.
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans, reaching Tahiti requires a long, tedious
journey: six hours to Los Angeles, a two-hour layover, then a 7
1/2-hour flight to Papeete. When we arrived at 1 a.m. Tahiti time,
we were greeted by musicians and given small white flowers, which
we learned are to be worn behind the ear _ the right ear if you are
taken, left if available. On leaving the airport, we also received
leis.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hour was late and the trip long, Radisson-Seven
Seas Cruises made our journey as pleasant as possible, with a
waiting room at a nearby resort. In the morning, we awoke to a
beautiful scene overlooking lush gardens and a placid lagoon. There
was a breakfast and a buffet lunch to help while away the time
before boarding the ship later in the afternoon. The ship's
check-in was handled at the resort.
</P>
<P>
   We opted for an island tour that included two museum visits.
After all, this would be our only time on Tahiti. One museum
explains the history and geology of the islands of French
Polynesia, the other is dedicated to Gauguin. While there are only
three original Gauguins on display, the museum explains his life
and displays many reproductions of his works. The other museum
explains the volcanic nature of the islands, all surrounded by
shallow turquoise lagoons. Where fresh water flows from the
islands, there are breaks in the lagoon, allowing ships to pass
safely into port.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon, we boarded the ship in Papeete, were greeted
with champagne, then escorted to our rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The staterooms are spacious. Ours, like many others, had an
outside balcony where we'd enjoy our room-service full breakfast.
In the evening, the balcony would be a pleasant place to enjoy a
drink overlooking the tiny lights of whatever island we'd be near.
(The ship offers a stocked bar with complimentary liquors, beer,
and soft drinks in each stateroom.) All cabins have an outside
view, and 50 percent have balconies. Bathrooms are luxurious, done
in marble, and all have tubs.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has a casino, but local law doesn't allow the slot
machines to be used. Another curious local law requires that to use
the ship's gift shop, one must purchase a minimum of $50 worth of
goods. There is a small windowless gym, also a small spa operated
by Carita of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ship, there are reminders of French Polynesia,
from photos to a small gallery with art and artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, we found the Gauguin offers dining with style.
The ship's main dining room, L'Etoile, has open seating, and dining
was at our pleasure. The maitre d' offered us a choice of dining
alone or joining a larger table to meet other passengers. We chose
to dine alone. Other choices of meals are the open-air Grille and
Le Veranda, which alternates with French/Italian specialties. This
restaurant features a fixed menu that includes a sampling of
outstanding entrees and desserts from these two lands. While many
of the menus feature the creative cuisine of two-star Michelin chef
Jean-Pierre Vigato, owner/operator of Apicius restaurant in Paris,
the meals are international in scope.
</P>
<P>
   The Gauguin is French-built and operated by Radisson-Seven Seas
Cruises, which is making a very good name for itself in luxury
cruises. Besides the lure of French Polynesia, the reason we chose
the ship was because of the positive cruise we had aboard the
Radisson Diamond. While the service and food were on a par with the
Diamond, the Gauguin was at times affected by ocean currents
rolling with the waves, unlike the very stable twin-hulled Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   A nice touch both ships enjoy comes after dinner. With my rigid
diet, when asked about desert, I informed the waiter, ``Nothing.''
When others received their treats, a plate was placed before me
with ``Nothing'' inscribed in icing.
</P>
<P>
   Another enjoyable touch is the casual atmosphere of the ship. No
jackets or ties needed _ ever. The ship also has a no-tipping
policy and serves complimentary wine with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
