<HEADLINE>
A CHAT WITH A CLIPPER CAPTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``That's my real love,'' Uli Pruesse was telling us while
pointing at a painting of a clipper ship on the wall of the Wheel
Haus restaurant in Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod is known for its sea captains and their former homes,
many of which serve as delightful inns, but the last thing I was
expecting when entering the Wheel Haus was to meet a real sea
captain. Pruesse is a schooner captain on the Star Clipper, a
four-masted barquentine with five square sails on its formast.
</P>
<P>
   Once I saw the German dishes on the Wheel Haus menu, I was ready
to dine, but during the meal, I also feasted on the thought of
sailing on a genuine tall ship, one with historical ties to Boston.
Pruesse, who joined our table, owns the Wheel Haus with his wife,
Aleta. He hails from Hamburg, Germany, and has been sailing most of
his life. When Star Clipper came along, he couldn't resist the urge
to return to the sea. After all, he said, a sailor always has one
foot on land, one on sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Star Clipper is based on the designs of Donald McKay, the
masterful 19th-century clipper ship designer from East Boston.
McKay's vessels were known for their speed, an important factor
during Gold Rush days to get around Cape Horn with passengers and
cargo for the California gold fields.
</P>
<P>
   The modern-day version, Star Clipper and its sister vessel Star
Flyer, carry on that tradition, although with a lot more comfort
and fun than in Gold Rush days. The Star Clipper has 85 cabins,
each with a private bath and all the amenities. There are two
swimming pools, a dining room that fits all passengers, a library,
and a piano bar.
</P>
<P>
   The Clipper and Flyer sail to ports around the world, and one
ship is usually found in the Caribbean. Passengers can participate
in sailing the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Pruesse enthusiastically encourages passengers on his sails to
participate in steering, learning navigation, seamanship,
understanding the weather and skies, maybe even mastering the art
of knots.
</P>
<P>
   One sail Pruesse is particularly enthusiastic about is the April
17-24 Antigua Classic Yacht Regatta that includes competition for
the Tall Ships' World Peace Cup. The sail will include visits to
Tortola, St. Barts, and other isles, but will be in Antigua to
compete in the cup race. The race, which Pruesse and his friend Ken
Coombs started in 1988, has grown to become a world- class yachting
festival with tall ships of all sizes entering. The competition
includes races, knot tying, dinghy races, seamanship judging, and
the spirit of tradition. And, you can be on the Star Clipper for
its competition, picking up seamanship skills under the direction
of Captain Pruesse _ or just sit back and relax and enjoy the show.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected to participate in next year's race is HMS Rose,
which just happens to be sailing in the Boston area now.
</P>
<P>
   Star Clippers is building the world's largest clipper ship,
Royal Clipper, due to enter service late next year. The Royal
Clipper will be the second five-masted full-rigger vessel in
history, and for its inaugural season will offer seven- and 14-day
sails out of Barbados. For more information on sailing with Captain
Pruesse, write to Orleans Tours, 167 Route 6A, Orleans, MA 02653;
or telephone 508-255-7763.
</P>
<P>
   And should you stop by the Wheel Haus, you might even meet
another ``captain.'' Pruesse says Captain Stubing of the ``Love
Boat,'' Gavin McLeod, who lives nearby, stops in to chat and dine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
China in winter
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winter cruises on the Yangtze River are being offered by Regal
China Cruises. The cruises, November through April, are for three
days and travel to the Three Gorges. While other ships cease
operations during the winter as a result of changes in the water
level, Regal created a short round-trip itinerary that allows a
visit to the Three Gorges and the spectacular smaller gorges Wushan
and Bandong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Smoke free
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The world's first smoke-free cruise ship will begin sailing in
December. Carnival Cruise Lines' MS Paradise will feature a
completely nonsmoking environment. Guests and crew will enjoy a
smoke-free environment everywhere on the 2,040-passenger,
70,000-ton vessel, including open decks. ``The overwhelming
majority of adults do not smoke,'' said George Dessart, the
American Cancer Society's chairman of the board. ``They want a
vacation environment that is healthy and smoke-free _ especially
for their children. We hope Carnival's bold and innovative action
spurs others in the travel industry to follow their lead.'' The
$300 million vessel will sail from Miami beginning Dec. 6,
alternating between a eastern and western Caribbean route.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cigar cruise
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A seven-night cigar cruise is set for Oct. 3-10 aboard the
Celebrity Cruise Line Century. The cruise is sponsored by New
England Cigars Lifestyles magazine. Prices begin at $1,229 a
person. For information, call Four Winds Travel at 800-44-WINDS or,
in Boston, 781-397-7711.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Holiday cruises
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holland America Line is expanding its holiday cruises with new
ports of call and activities. On all its cruises, Holland America
decorates its ships in the splendor of the season, complete with a
Christmas tree and lights. Holiday favorites such as pheasant,
quail, and plum pudding will grace the table. There will be
caroling and a cork-popping gala on New Year's Eve. Catholic,
Protestant, and Jewish services will be conducted by on-board
clergy. Among new ports will be Puerto Quetzal, Guatemala, and Isla
de Margarita, Venezuela. And a 16-day Pacific Explorer Holiday will
feature Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sports afloat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If sports are your game, Norwegian Cruise Line is the place to
set your sails. Some of baseball's most notable players, past and
present, will be joining the annual Sports Afloat Baseball cruise
Nov. 29-Dec. 6 aboard the Norwegian Wind. Among Hall of Famers will
be Bob Feller, Enos ``Country'' Slaughter, and Harmon Killebrew;
current players will include Tyler Green, Denny Neagle, and Jason
Christiansen. Also on Dec. 5, the line's legendary Norway will be
the site of the first-ever Sports Illustrated Afloat cruise. Sports
fans will meet their heroes, past and present, and enjoy many
activities on the sail from Miami to the eastern Caribbean islands.
Among players participating will be Don Mattingly, Ozzie Smith,
Stan Mikita, John Havlicek, WNBA star and Olympic medalist Teresa
Weatherspoon, and track and field Olympians Florence Griffith
Joyner and Al Joyner. Guests will be able to also participate in
sports events with the stars. The cruise will also mark the
unveiling of the first Sports Illustrated Cafe, filled with
memorabilia, videos, and classic SI photography. NCL plans to
convert its existing Sports Bars on its other ships to SI Cafes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Africa savings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EuroCruises is cutting the price on its sail around Africa
aboard the Norwegian-registered Black Watch. The classic ship
features 90 percent of its cabins on the outside. The 68-day
cruise, which runs from Jan. 5 through March 14, can be done in
segments of 14 days. The ship also has a number of single cabins
available. Segment prices begin at $1,745 double and $1,770 single.
For information, call 800-688-3876.
</P>
<P>
   Orient Lines is offering a 50 percent savings for the second
passenger on two fall Africa cruise safaris. One cruise sails from
Athens to Africa via Egypt, the other from Mombasa to Cape Town.
Both include a free three-day Kenya safari.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Derby tickets
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free tickets to the 1999 Kentucky Derby and free round-trip air
fare for a river cruise to get you there are available for those
booking a category E or higher stateroom on the Mississippi Queen
by Oct. 24. The river cruise is from Memphis to Louisville April
24-May 2. The trip includes an onboard talk by horse racing
specialists, reserved infield seats to Churchill Downs, and a box
lunch for the race.
</P>
