u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-22 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEFENSE TAKES AWAY THE DEEP PASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After three games, the Patriots' defensive
statistics don't look as dominating as many had thought they would.
The Patriots are 14th overall in the league, 12th against the run,
and 18th against the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole feeling among the staff and the players is
that we need to be better,'' said defensive coordinator Steve
Sidwell. ``We need to be more consistent. We haven't been a good
team on third down. You have to be able to shut teams down on third
down. In most situations, we shot ourselves in the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has failed to stop 43.5 percent of opponents'
third-down conversion attempts. Only Indianapolis (48.8) and Denver
(43.9) are worse. In Sunday's 27-16 victory over the Oilers,
Tennessee converted half its chances (8 for 16).
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is that teams have been able to pick up the
Patriots' blitz packages since New England has built a reputation
as being a blitz-oriented defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand what teams are doing to us,'' said
Sidwell. ``They're fearing our pressure, so what they're doing is a
lot of play-passing. They're trying to block everything up and just
trying to make a short throw. The Oilers had thrown more deep balls
than any team I've seen in a long, long time but they just threw
away their deep passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the offshoots of being a team that pressures is they do
things to offset the pressure. And that kind of makes them a less
wide-open attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots managed only one sack; it seemed every time they
blitzed, the Oilers were ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so concerned about sacks,'' said Sidwell. ``What I am
concerned about is good rushes. With the three- or five-step drops
they were working with, we could have rushed 11 and had a couple of
guys come free and the ball would have been gone. That's the way
teams are choosing to play us. It makes it harder for them to get a
big play against us, but it makes it harder for us to get to them.
The ball is just gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams such as the Oilers and the Colts shut off their deep game
out of respect for the Patriots defense, realizing that (1) they
would have to beat Ty Law deep, and the way he is playing right
now, that can't happen; and (2) the quarterback would get eaten
alive if he had to make a seven-step drop. So opponents are content
to try to assert themselves on the ground and use the short passing
game to keep drives going.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's game plan, said Sidwell, ``was to try and do
anything they could to keep out of third-and-7 situations. They
started the game breaking all of their tendencies. On first down
they were throwing it. On second down they were running it and
trying to make it where they didn't have many third-and-longs. The
second third-and-long situation they had on the second drive _ the
one where they made the field goal _ we lined up and called a blitz
and we busted the blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got into the sub situation we had a couple of busts,
which gave them a couple of gifts. As a result, at the end of the
game when we got ahead, we got away from it and played basic
coverage in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell said the game plan was to pressure with the blitz on
third down and play basic coverage on the first two downs, but ``we
really didn't have as much success as we were hoping to have doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because quarterback Steve McNair was hard to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hard to finish off,'' said Sidwell. ``We had some
opportunities, but overall our guys did a good job doing that with
him. We're in a sitiation where you have to be able to finish that
guy, but that's not easy. He's a strong man. And he has some
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   On a positive note, added Sidwell, ``We had a couple of
outstanding plays. They ran three quarterback draws in that game.
We played those well. That's a dangerous play for (McNair) because
he had almost 700 yards last year. A lot of it came on the QB draw.
He converted a third-and-4 late when they were in their two-minute
situation and were trying to come back. But overall we did a good
job against draw.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight week, however, the defense allowed a
100-yard rusher. Eddie George hit 100 on the button.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's always concern,'' said Sidwell, ``but that's
a damn good back. He made us miss like most. We gave him a 27-yard
run where we missed a tackle. We're still making too many mistakes,
not fitting it together with our run defense. We should be and will
be more solid in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Another good sign was that the Patriots didn't get fatigued,
even in the heat and humidity on the field. The defense seemed to
get stronger late in the game, with Lawyer Milloy making a big
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most encouraging thing is that we had to make a play late
in the game and we were able to do it,'' said Sidwell. ``Our missed
tackles came early and I think our guys didn't go into this game
giving them as much respect as they should have. That's a good
team. I thought it was going to come down to the wire and that's
what ended up happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
