<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTNOTE TO A HORRID SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James S. Hirsch is a well-known Boston financial news reporter.
For three years, he covered mutual funds here with energy and
insight for The Wall Street Journal _ Fidelity Investments in
particular. Before that he worked in Houston and Pittsburgh, nine
years with the paper altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Then a routine assignment to cover the breaking news on the Mike
Barnicle story turned into a nightmare in August. Hirsh reported
that The New York Times Co. had ``declined to comment'' on The
Boston Globe's decision to reinstate Barnicle for a time. In fact,
Times Co. _ corporate parent to both the Times and the Globe _ that
day had issued a statement supporting ``the Globe's right to make
its own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Globe complained to a spokesperson for the
Times, who then complained to the Journal that Hirsch hadn't called
that day. Six days later Hirsch was fired. The severity of the
penalty raised eyebrows around town and in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch's explanation was that his failure to call the Times that
day was an error borne of a careless assumption: The Times twice
had declined to comment to him on Globe affairs in the recent past.
The statement a Journal spokesperson gave was this: ``There are
few, if any, more serious violations of journalistic norms than
knowingly printing a falsehood.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Journal editors apparently had come down hard on Hirsch
two months before the Barnicle mishap on a story of more
significance to the newspaper and its readers.
</P>
<P>
   It was May 21 that a front-page article appeared about
Massachusetts' Community Newspaper Co. under Hirsch's byline. It
was headlined ``Paper Tiger?/ Fidelity Tries to Build/ A Newspaper
Empire/ Delivers Only Losses/Mutual Fund Giant Spends/Big. But Some
Advertisers Aren't Buying Its Story/It Sees Better Times Ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   By most measures, it was an excellent story, confirming and
extending the conventional wisdom about the chain of Massachusetts
newspapers that a Fidelity unit had assembled in the early 1990s: a
business plan that had not yet worked as had been hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch reported that according to ``people familiar with its
books,'' Fidelity had spent about $150 million buying newspapers,
but that in 1997 the &UR;  &LR; company had lost about $5 million before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amorization, on revenues of about
$100 million. In the two previous years, the company had lost $22.6
million on the same basis, he &UR;  &LR; stated.
</P>
<P>
   The story had a certain critical edge that was difficult to
miss. It disparaged the lack of newspaper culture among the
Fidelity executives who ran the chain. It noted their inability to
sell much advertising space to Fidelity's investment side. It
concluded darkly that ``Fidelity's tolerance for CNC's struggles
isn't inexhaustible.'' It had, in other words, all the hallmarks of
a story facilitated, at least in part, by rivalry within the ranks
of the mutual fund giant, among whose investment side managers
Hirsch enjoyed a generally excellent reputation. (Community News is
an outgrowth of Fidelity's formerly small venture capital unit.)
The story could have benefitted Dow Jones' Ottaway newspaper
subsidiary as well.
</P>
<P>
   William R. Elfers, Community Newspaper's chief executive,
responded with a three-page letter to the managing editor of the
Journal, alleging a dozen errors. A month later, three corrections
appeared. None went to the heart of the story, but each had
slightly overstated the negative case.
</P>
<P>
   Readership was estimated to be 1.4 million, not ``about one
million.'' A majority of the 129 newspapers _ broadsheets, tabs and
advertising circulars _ had negative cash flow when they were
acquired, not positive. And of 37 employees who were laid off in
1997, only two were ad salespeople, not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that there were only three (corrections,)''
says Elfers. ``Still, how many times do you see that in a story?
Three gross errors, things that are not just wrong but damaging?''
</P>
<P>
   Did the Community News corrections influence the Journal's
decision to fire Hirsh over the Times' complaint? Dow Jones
declines to comment. So does Hirsch, though some friends insist the
Fidelity story played no part.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Journal, however, a good many heads are shaking.
Granted that the paper's news pages are prouder than any other of
their reputation for fairness and accuracy. But wouldn't a
two-month suspension have served just as well?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
