<HEADLINE>
EXPATRIATE FAMILIES GETTING MORE ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As global trade as grown, corporate America is doing a lot more
to prepare executives for overseas assignments and that means
responding to the needs of spouses and children.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Boston-based Gillette Co.
</P>
<P>
   After an executive is selected for overseas travel, Gillette
sends the employee and spouse overseas for a weeklong inspection
orientation visit designed to help the family look at schooling,
housing, and neighborhoods and help them iron out relocation
concerns before a permanent move is made, says Frank O'Connell,
director of global compensation for Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, meanwhile, Windham International, a consulting firm
that specializes in helping executives relocate abroad, says
revenue from executive relocation overseas now accounts for 42
percent of its sales revenue. The company assigns employees'
spouses and children advocates, or ``buddies'' who meet them at the
airport and serve as friends, confidantes and allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are even special programs for teens, and the
reason is that the whole success of the transfer depends on family
support. If the family isn't happy, the assignment won't last''
says Ilene Dolins, senior vice president of Windham, a privately
held firm.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when the Employee Relocation Council in Washington,
D.C., polled company executives to determine why foreign
assignments fail, few, if any, employers were paying attention to
relocation services or counseling for expatriate families.
</P>
<P>
   Not surpising, ERC's survey results revealed as much. It found
that the foreign assignments of more than 60 percent of US
employees had failed because spouses and family members were unable
to adjust to the move.
</P>
<P>
   Although current statistics are not available, specialists say
more companies are paying attention to the problem by focusing
attention on trailing spouses and children.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study of 400 international executives by Berlitz
International Inc. and the Virginia-based Institute for
International Human Resorces, the typical expatriate is male (84
percent), between 39 and 45, (57 percent), and married with a
spouse or family that will accompany him or her on assignment (82
percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often the spouse needs training more than the employee,''
says Michael McCallum, national director of business development
for Berlitz International Inc. ``Typically, the employee will have
a network of people to talk to. But the spouse is going to have to
keep the home together and negotiate outside the house on a daily
basis. If relocation fails, it is because a family member is
unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   To assist employees in the transition, Berlitz does
cross-cultural training and language instruction for the entire
family _ a significant change from the company's early reputation
as an international language institute that focused primarily on
offering instruction to the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Dolins recalls the story of an employee who returned home
abruptly after only one year, several months after his wife threw
up her hands and returned to the United States. Alone and
increasingly isolated, she grew resentful. ``His wife hopped a
plane after only two months abroad and now they are getting a
divorce,'' says Dolins. ``He felt the whole family fell apart
because of the assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Monterey International Institute in California, employers
pay a minimum of $9,000 for a six-week language bootcamp that
teaches the executive the host company's language and also prepares
his or her spouse, and children to live abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs companies a fortune to send someone overseas,'' says
Jeannie Watts, program manager for custom language services at the
Monterey institute. ``It is a much better investment if the
expatriate and his family are able to speak the language,
understand the culture and are not living in an Enlish speaking
ghetto where they cannot communicate with anyone, but people who
speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   Students refer to the courses as ``bootcamps'' because Monterey
suggests that executives divorce themselves from the firm, stay
away from the office, and disconnect the telephone during the six
weeks. Some are so committed to the process they stay in area
hotels. Others, typically executives from foreign countries who are
learning English, are placed in American host homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, there were fewer comapnies doing this,''
says Watts. Now, all types of companies are working internationally
to compete and they are asking for language and cultural
instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Watts, the most popular language program these days
is Chinese. Although the trend to study Russian has dropped, the
demand has picked up among oil companies with oil fields in
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, a lot of expatriates lived in English speaking
ghettos,'' says Watts. ``They connected in American schools in
foreign cities, and moved to American communities abroad. But they
did not always appreciate and enjoy their assignments because they
were really living in isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
