<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK STILL IN A HARD PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Times are such that even the slightest increase in business is
cause for joy at a local racetrack. Such is the case at Rockingham
Park, which concluded a 100-program meet Sunday with the overall
handle up 1 percent and attendance up 2 percent, reversing a recent
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased,'' said Rock vice president Ed Callahan.
``I think we ran a good program, averaging $87,000 a day in purses.
We had very good, competitive racing and we had a full barn area
all season. I thought racing director Bob DeStasio and racing
secretary Jim Pambianchi did a real nice job. Things went very,
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   As glad as management is to record modest gains, it knows all
too well that Rock, like Suffolk Downs, continues to be squeezed by
other gambling venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that we were up by more than 1 percent in June
and July, but when we got into the first and second week of August,
things began to tail off a little bit,'' said Callahan. ``The
differences this year from last were the introduction of a gambling
cruise boat from Gloucester and the opening of fair racing earlier
than usual this summer in Western Massachusetts, either of which
could have had an effect on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, when Foxwoods opened, we lost 40 percent of our
business. As far away as they are, the casinos in Connecticut hurt
us. With casino gambling coming closer, as with the boat, it has to
have some impact. And don't forget there is a casino in Montreal.
We lose as many people to the Montreal casino as we do to Foxwoods.
We are surrounded on all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock dearly would love to get video slot machines, as the
popular Lincoln Greyhound Park in Rhode Island features. The idea
of slot machines went nowhere in New Hampshire this year. However,
with the Granite State undergoing a rigorous debate over improving
education, Rock officials hope for a chance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislature, which is normaly out from June through
January, has had a number of special sessions on the education
issue, which has reached the constitutional stage, this fall, but
they have not looked into how to fund it,'' said Callahan. ``We are
hopeful that electronic gaming will receive the appropriate
consideration when funding is discussed. There is always a chance.
Whether it will be achieved or not is always a question.''
</P>
<P>
   Slots would be a home run for local racing, but there are other
things that government can do to help an industry that is so
heavily taxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant battle, it's tough, not just for ourselves,
but for the horsemen,'' said Callahan. ``The horsemen need better
purses to survive. The only way we have of doing better is to grow
the product. Give us the tools to keep it going, be it slots or
phone betting or whatever else. We are such a regulated industry
that we don't currently have the ability to fight our
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A horse shoo-in
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appears that justice has been served early this year, as Skip
Away, robbed of the Horse of the Year title in 1997, all but
clinched this year's top Eclipse Award with his convincing win over
a top field in the Woodward Stakes at Belmont Park last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Last time, enough Eclipse voters were fooled by Favorite Trick's
record (8 for 8) to vote him Horse of the Year, even though
2-year-olds run only against those their own age, don't carry
weight, and don't run past 9 furlongs. The only other 2-year-old
ever to win the award was Secretariat, which demonstrates how high
the bar should be for a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   But Skip Away, 7 for 7 this year and on a nine-race winning
streak overall, is about to become the first horse in history to go
over the $10 million mark in earnings and has little to fear this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else could you give him to do?,'' said Sonny Hine,
trainer of Skip Away, immediately following the Woodward. ``Even if
someone else wins the Breeders' Cup, it wouldn't be enough. He's
won five Grade I races this year (as well as a Grade II and a Grade
III), and carried all that weight (as much as 131 pounds). I don't
know who else it could be. I just don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-pressed conspiracy theorists could come up with only one
long shot scenario that would deny Skip Away. Awesome Again, a top
3-year-old in '97, started late this season but is 4 for 4,
including the Whitney and Saratoga Breeders' Cup. If Awesome Again
were to beat Skip Away in the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at
Belmont Oct. 10 and again in the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic
at Churchill Downs Nov. 7, he would end the year 6 for 6, with a
2-0 edge head to head. However, even that may not be enough to deny
the big gray, who has been racing hard since the Donn Handicap at
Gulfstream Park Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Byrne, who trains Awesome Again, knows that his charge must
defeat Skip Away twice to have any chance. It will be up to him and
owner Frank Stronach to come to the Jockey Club and throw down the
gauntlet. If they choose to go instead in the Hawthorne Gold Cup,
run the same day, the race for Horse of the Year is over,
regardless of what Skip Away does in his final two starts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Solid investment
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Thoroughbred Corp., headed by Prince Ahmed Salman, has
bought a ``substantial'' interest in Skip Away for breeding
purposes. The announcement was made after Skip Away's Woodward
tally by Rick Tronz, who will stand Skip Away at stud next year at
his Hopewell Farm in Midway, Ky. Thoroughbred Corp. also bought a
yearling who is a full brother to Skip Away at last week's
Keeneland September sales ... Rudy Baez won the Rock riding title
for the 10th time in 13 years with 112 victories, while Ron Dandy
won his second consecutive training title, saddling 46 winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was
used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
