<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN IS CONTENT WITH RUNNING DIFFERENT ROUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Terry Glenn knows people tend to worry about
him. That is especially true of the people who are paying him large
sums of money to play football. What they worry about is how what
he does affects how well he plays.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn tends to worry about himself, his sister, his young son,
and his God. He doesn't worry much about the people who are paying
him large sums of money to play football. What he worries about is
how what he does will affect the people he's responsible for. His
theory is that if he worries about them, that should end everyone
else's worries about him.
</P>
<P>
   If you think about it, that makes more sense than a demand he
perform supervised bench presses for $400 a week in the middle of
March, 1,000 miles from his young son. It makes sense because if he
takes care of his business, where he does it is not that important.
What's important is that he does it, although Glenn has learned not
everyone shares that point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a well-balanced family life the concern about me
might not be so much,'' Glenn said Monday while reflecting on why
he became the target of so many questions and concerns within the
Patriots organization over his decision to spend much of his time
conditioning himself alone rather than in New England's offseason
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I'm on my own and I think they feel I might be too
immature to take care of myself. That's what separates you from
being mature or immature, but if you have pride in yourself you'll
do all you can to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a little sister living with me. I have a son with my
name. They're my responsibility. They're my priority. If I do what
I have to do to take care of that priority it should take care of
the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Long into training camp whispers kept coming from inside the
organization that Glenn had not participated as the team had hoped
in its conditioning work. It was mentioned that he was coming off a
injury-plagued season that threatened to thwart his vast potential
if it became a pattern, and many wondered out loud if he'd
dedicated himself enough to the rigors of his job or if he even
recognized fully what those rigors were.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn read those comments. He heard the whispers. He is neither
blind nor deaf. Yet he walked his own road because he has been a
lonely traveler on that road for much of his life, alone since long
before he was a man.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's belief was Glenn needed to become stronger to
avoid injury because at 185 pounds he is slight by NFL standards.
While that might be true, Glenn thought back on the injuries that
cut his production to 27 catches after he pulled in 90 as a rookie
in 1996 and remembered how a diving Mark Montreuil had fallen
across the back of his legs in the season opener. He remembered
coming back on the bad ankle that resulted and scoring a touchdown
on his next reception before being sidelined for the better part of
the next three weeks because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Could their offseason program prevent a sprained ankle?
</P>
<P>
   He remembered catching 24 passes over the next six games,
including an explosive reminder of what his potential is when he
caught seven for 163 yards (23.3 yards per catch) against the
defending Super Bowl champion Packers before being poked in the eye
against the Vikings and pulling his hamstring a week later, an
injury that kept him out of five full games and for most of the
season-finale against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Would their offseason program prevent a poke in the eye? A
hamstring pull?
</P>
<P>
   Then he returned one last time, catching nine passes in two
playoff games, including five for 96 yards (19.2 yard average)
against Pittsburgh before he was slammed to the turf and broke his
collarbone, ending a season he'd rather forget.
</P>
<P>
   Would their offseason program prevent a broken collarbone?
</P>
<P>
   Some in the organization theorized it might, but Glenn doubted
it. If so, why did Garrison Hearst, one of the strongest backs in
the NFL, sustain the same collarbone injury? If so, why are so many
players sidelined with hamstring pulls every year?
</P>
<P>
   Yet Glenn tried, for a time, to adhere to the Patriots' wishes.
He showed up for the start of the conditioning regimen in
Foxborough, even though he feared some of what he was being asked
to do might slow him down.
</P>
<P>
   He did what they were asking but he wondered about it because
Glenn knows what got him into the NFL and made him a millionaire at
23 was not his strength. It was his speed, his hands and his
agility, not the ability to bench press a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, he believes it has been his decisions in life
that kept him afloat after the murder of his mother, the only
parent he ever really had, when he was 13. His decisions, not
others'. He believes in what Ralph Waldo Emerson once wrote about.
He believes in self-reliance. So he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   And then one day he went home. He went home for a lot of reasons
but he went home and brought out his orange cones and went to work.
He worked on his speed and his agility and, to a lesser degree, his
strength. He did what he thought was right and didn't do what he
thought wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to Smithfield, R.I., in July, he was light a few
thousand dollars in conditioning bonuses he hadn't earned by
choosing to stay closer to his son than to Patriot strength coach
Johnny Parker, but he was in shape. People in the organization
could whisper of their disappoiment at his choices, but no one
could say he wasn't ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   That was Glenn's first goal all along. To simply be able to
play. After three weeks he's played in 66 percent more games than
he was in this time a year ago and Sunday he was again the Terry
Glenn of 1996, the game-breaker everyone believes he can be.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn went 51 yards with one catch, making the right read
against a blitzing Oilers defense and adjusting a post pattern into
a short slant that turned into a long touchdown that won the game.
This would not have been his first bomb of the year had Drew
Bledsoe not overthrown him on at least two other occasions but that
doesn't concern him. At this stage, he's happy simply to be fit to
play.
</P>
<P>
   But to receive the blessing of fitness he had to work first. And
so he did. The way he does most things. Alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main focus was to get here in shape and be injury free for
the Monday night game (against Denver),'' Glenn said. ``Now it's to
get back to performing the way I did my rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the Lord wants me to be patient. I had two years
where things happened so fast that I got to believing what so many
people were saying because I thought those things, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have time to think about what I was doing. I started
to believe, like everyone else, that I could do so much. Too much.
God gave me a lot of success when I needed it. Now I believe He
thought it was time for other things to happen. The injuries
humbled me. It woke me up to some things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year wasn't a good year but it was a good thing. Before
that I was just riding along. Then the injuries came and things
changed. People said things about me. They doubted me the way
people always have.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I went away and worked on my own. I been doing things on my
own for the longest time. It's not that I don't need anybody or
won't listen to anybody. I just feel strongest on my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my team but I don't think about the organizaton first.
I think about my sister and my son first. I don't want to be on the
sidelines so my sister has to hear about her brother at her school.
I know the expectations for me are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some ideas what can help me and what can hurt me and I
felt some of the things I was being asked to do coming off my
shoulder injury would hurt me. But I also have respect for J.P.
(Parker). If I stayed here I would have done what they asked even
though I didn't agree with it, so I left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell them I felt they were hurting me. It's hard
for me to say no to people. I don't want to let people down. So I
had to get away and do it on my own. Do the things that got me
here. I did and I got to see my son all the time, too. If I'd
stayed in New England I wouldn't have gotten to see him. The fact
is conditioning is about doing it. If you don't, you'll pay. Not
just the team pays. You'll pay. So why wouldn't I do it where I
was?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I come back and read in Sports Illustrated that people
are disappointed with me. I don't like to feel I disappointed
anyone. I like to make people happy. But what were they
disappointed about? I was ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn thus far has stayed injury free and his 12 catches for 198
yards lead the team, as do his two touchdown receptions and
16.5-yards-per-catch average. Although he dropped two passes
against the Colts and one in Denver and was less than pleased about
it, he has done what he trained himself to do. He has stayed on the
field and showed Sunday that he remains the Patriots' most
dangerous weapon when he gets the ball in stride with room to run.
</P>
<P>
   But Terry Glenn is trying not to think too much about that, just
as he's trying not to fixate on a number that is haunting him. He
knows the 90 catches of his rookie year have become his measuring
stick in the eyes of those who worry about how he runs his life.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it is just a number, and frankly not one you often
reach, yet it has framed him and so he must face it the way he did
last year's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one sees 90 balls every year but guys like Jerry Rice and
Herman Moore,'' Glenn said. ``There's only a handful of guys who
ever did that. Once you've done it four or five times, then you can
talk about catching 90 balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to stay on the field. I'm happy just to have
the opportunity to drop balls after last year because if I'm not on
the field I can't even do that. I don't take for granted any more
that I can be out there, but I know what it takes to get me going.
I know how to get the best out of me and I know if I do that they
won't have to worry about Terry Glenn any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is going to tell everything. Days go by. Weeks go by.
Months go by. I made a choice to go home and get ready on my own. I
made a choice to be near my son and do my work. That's how you open
the maturity door. If I do a good job this year, maybe there won't
be a question next time about me. Right now people will say what
they want, but if I handle my business they won't have nothing to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but look at Terry run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
