<HEADLINE>
NOW'S SUPPORT OF CLINTON DOES DISSERVICE TO WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ You can't blame the National Organization for
Women for taking a stance in defense of President Clinton. The
group has an agenda to protect.
</P>
<P>
   But NOW loses me when it declares that Clinton's behavior was
not sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Monica Lewinsky went beyond tacky when she showed Clinton
the straps to her thong underwear. But Clinton was not compelled to
follow her lead.
</P>
<P>
   As leader of the free world, he more than any chief executive
should have known better than to diddle with a White House intern,
no less one who was just a few years older than his own daughter.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't far behind most people ready to chastise Lewinsky for
her naivete. Or was it cunning and manipulation?
</P>
<P>
   As I read excerpts of the report compiled by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr, it has been difficult to discern the difference. But
as psychologists, Lewinsky's friends and other observers have
dissected the report, Clinton's paramour emerges as an emotionally
immature, starstruck young woman who got in over her head.
</P>
<P>
   My annoyance with NOW's position notwithstanding, Lewinsky is no
victim, at least not in the sense with which a woman I'll call Mary
is most familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the women I work with, they're true victims,'' Mary
says. ``They're ... black and blue. They've had horrendous acts
committed against them. They have huge obstacles to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to advocate for them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lewinsky is a tragic figure. ``I don't want to discount
her pain and victimization,'' Mary says.
</P>
<P>
   Mary works with women who've been abused by their partners. She
also voted for Clinton. More so than many other women who count
themselves among Clinton's supporters, her competing loyalties have
brought her to an uncertain crossroads as the president's crisis
surely brought NOW.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an advocate for women, it is a real dilemma,'' she says.
``I want to be objective. I don't want to assume the woman is
necessary always in the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Lewinsky's behavior, as she detailed it to the grand
jury, doesn't make it easy for Mary and others who might allow her
a sympathetic view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sympathy for Monica Lewinsky because she was immature
and she was young,'' Mary says. ``But she, to me, was the pursuer
and aggressor in the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the bigger louse. After observing the president and
studying his history, Mary is convinced he's a user, if not abuser,
of women. So am I.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not hitting them,'' she points out, ``but there are many
ways to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the `grown-up' in this,'' Mary adds. ``He had the
power.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of it all is Clinton's impressive record of appointing
women and minorities to positions of responsibility throughout his
administration, a record NOW undoubtedly wants to protect. But at
what cost? Will NOW and other Clinton supporters simply avert their
eyes when it's just too painful to watch?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a contradiction,'' Mary says. ``The very man who
helps them turns around and uses them for his own personal gain.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``A person who does that is a real user of people.''
The more I see of this nation's president, the more I'm sadly
convinced she's right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
