<HEADLINE>
COACHING CHANGES ARE AFOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Major League Soccer general managers are attempting to
achieve dramatic effects with coaching changes, they are
succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Fusion made a most timely change when they replaced
Cacho Cordoba with Ivo Wortmann, the Revolution a most spontaneous
change when Walter Zenga took over for Thomas Rongen. And the
MetroStars might top everyone with Monday's announcement that
Velibor (Bora) Milutinovic will replace Alfonso Mondelo.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic was to arrive in New York last night to begin
preparing for the final regular-season game, Saturday night against
the Revolution at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There is a theory about changing horses in midstream, but it
does not apply to the MetroStars, who qualified for the playoffs
under Mondelo. A recent slump that included a 5-0 loss to D.C.
United indicates that Mondelo might have taken this team as far as
he could, and it was time to go to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bora has a reputation of being the best to coach a team where
it's going into a tournament,'' MetroStars general manager Charlie
Stillitano said. ``And let's face it, we're going into a
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic developed that reputation on the national team
level, with Costa Rica, Mexico, and the United States. But then, he
had several weeks or years to develop a strategy. For the MLS
playoffs, Milutinovic has until a Sept. 30 visit to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   This might seem almost like a capricious move, but it gives a
indication about the competitive intentions of MLS teams.
Stillitano's brother, Leo, made a similarly ruthless decision in
Miami in late July, and the team has prospered. Zenga was offered
the Revolution position after the team honored him at halftime Aug.
22; his hiring revived the team's credibility but was too late to
salvage playoff chances.
</P>
<P>
   Since the league's budget limits the impact of big-name player
signings, these coaching moves have been excellent generators of
publicity, the most effective means of transcending borders.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, these changes are all likely to produce
positive on-field results.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars have gone this route before with Carlos Queiroz
and Carlos Alberto Parreira. This time, the strategy could work
because (a) expectations are realistic, and (b) the MetroStars have
sufficient personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars' essential problems have stemmed from an identity
crisis relating to the enormous success of the New York Cosmos in
the '70s and '80s. They are members of a league with modest means
attempting to attain cosmic standards.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic and Zenga are popular figures globally, and they
also will attract attention from quarters outside soccer. They have
infectious personalities and, like Wortmann, enormous reputations.
Though Milutinovic is a coaching gypsy, he has much to prove after
his experience with Nigeria in the World Cup ended with a
humiliating loss to Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona survives
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona survived a difficult week with ties at Manchester
United (3-3) in the Champions League and Real Madrid (2-2) in the
Spanish League. The Real Madrid-Barcelona game featured Dutch
coaches Guus Hiddink and Louis Van Gaal and only seven Spanish
players. There were six Dutchmen and four Brazilians, though
Roberto Carlos was suspended for Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of those Brazilians will play for the national team
when coach Wanderley Luxemburgo makes his debut against Yugoslavia
in the northern city of Sao Luis tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's attack will be based on the midfield play of
Barcelona's Rivaldo, who played for Luxemburgo with Palmeiras.
Holdovers from the second-place World Cup team include defender
Cafu (Roma) and midfielders Denilson (Real Betis), Emerson (Bayer
Leverkusen), and Rivaldo. The strikers are Brazil-based Marcelinho
Carioca (Corinthians), Christian (Internacional), and Fabio Junior
and Muller (Cruzeiro).
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo's first two games with Inter since his mysterious
no-show in the World Cup final were uninspiring. Real Madrid
humbled Inter, 2-0, in the Champions League, then Ronaldo scored on
a penalty kick in a 1-0 Serie A win over Piacenza.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A loaded Arsenal
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United is among the world's most famous and valuable
teams, but Arsenal is the best team in England.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenal, which won the league and cup double last season, took a
3-0 victory over Manchester United Sunday on goals by Tony Adams,
Frenchman Nicholas Anelka, and Swede Ljungberg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two are honored
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only two US players were named to the International Federation
of Football History and Statistics CONCACAF team of the century _
San Jose striker Eric Wynalda and the late Adelino ``Billy''
Gonsalves, a Fall River native who was the US' top player in the
1930 and '34 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Gonsalves, whose parents emigrated from the Madeira Islands, was
among the most sought-after American players of his time. He
refused offers in Brazil after the '30 World Cup in Uruguay, where
the US finished in third place, and played with the top teams in
the American Soccer League.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists for the CONCACAF player of the century award are
the late Luis ``El Pirata'' Fuente, Carlos Hermosillo of the Los
Angeles Galaxy, and Hugo Sanchez, five-time scoring champion in
Spain with Real Madrid and formerly with the San Diego Sockers of
the North American Soccer League and Dallas Burn of the MLS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
