<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE BIG EAST, THINGS ARE LOOKING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The doomsayers are gone _ for now, at least. Instead of talking
about the future, Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese is talking
about the present and the immediate past, which includes some
impressive nonconference wins, at least one team worthy of Top 10
consideration, and five of eight teams receiving poll votes.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to the Big East?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've been saying all along, it's cyclical,'' said
Tranghese Monday. ``We've got some teams who can play, some teams
who are getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese feels good about his league, and he should. Miami,
despite its self-destructive loss to Virginia Tech Saturday, is
getting better. Syracuse is a last-second loss to Tennessee _ one
that looks better after Tennesse's victory over Florida _ away from
a Top 5 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia and Virginia Tech are solid teams that should have
good and perhaps even great years, and Pittsburgh and Boston
College are moving up rather than down.
</P>
<P>
   Only Temple and Rutgers have failed to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around and you can see improvement all around,'' said
Tranghese. ``At BC, (Tom O'Brien's) handprints are all over, and
the same thing has happened at Pittsburgh, where Walt Harris has
made them much better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if they had to pick a Heisman winner right now, I'm not
sure if (Syracuse quarterback) Donovan McNabb wouldn't win it or be
right there.''
</P>
<P>
   All this optimism from a man who was running a league that most
thought was on life-support a year ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago we had all the same questions but we didn't have
any answers,'' said Tranghese. ``It's still early yet, but if you
look around the country, I think we're doing all right. The ACC is
struggling somewhat and the Big Ten after Ohio State is having some
problems. I think we can go out and play with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese deserves as much credit as anyone for the turnaround.
His message to the coaches and athletic directors was go out and
play good teams. Which most, if not all, of the Big East schools
have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three things can happen when you play people,'' said
Tranghese. ``You can win, you can get killed, or you can lose in a
competitive game.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, all of those have happened. Ohio State beat up West
Virginia, but the Buckeyes are No. 1, and have been living up to
that ranking. Syracuse has lost a close big game and won a big
game, falling to Tennessee and beating Michigan. BC has beaten
average to below-average teams, and Pittsburgh has been competitive
(it lost, 20-13, to Penn State Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we have some programs who over the
long run have had some success and they're getting better,'' said
Tranghese.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A busy man
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miami linebacker Dan Morgan is turning into a big-time stud. The
sophomore had 15 tackles against Virginia Tech Saturday night, the
third consecutive game in which he has had 14 or more ... Although
Pittsburgh lost, the atmosphere at Pitt Stadium had a big-game feel
to it. The crowd of 56,743 was the largest home crowd for the
Panthers since 1989 ... Rutgers had better beat Army Saturday
because it could be the Scarlet Knights' only good opportunity for
a Division 1 win this season. A loss surely will seal coach Terry
Shea's fate (if it hasn't already been sealed) ... Here's the
meaningless stat of the year. In its 70-14 loss, Rutgers topped
Syracuse in passing yardage, 174-164 ... Syracuse (and North
Andover) fullback Rob Konrad's three touchdowns against Rutgers
matched his total from last season ... The 70 points scored by the
Orangemen were the most ever in a Big East game and the second-most
by a conference team overall ... Give credit to Virginia Tech. The
Hokies not only hung in for a 27-20 overtime win but also limited
the potent Miami rushing attack to 37 yards. The Hokies have beaten
Miami four straight times _ the first team to do that since Notre
Dame from 1977-80 ... Miami has a tough stretch beginning with
Saturday's game against UCLA. Three of the Hurricanes' next four
opponents are in the Top 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
