<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVES' LOSSES DON'T LOOK GOOD ON PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you think your investment portfolio has taken a few lumps
this summer?
</P>
<P>
   Average investors suffered setbacks in their mutual funds and
brokerage accounts as global financial jitters squeezed the stock
market. But if misery loves company, we found it with lots of zeros
attached in the portfolios of some of the state's richest business
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Several chief executives, with giant financial stakes in the
companies they lead, have lost hundreds of millions of dollars on
paper between the time the stock market reached its peak July 17
and last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They all remain fabulously wealthy and could easily recover
their paper losses if the market changed course. But the dimensions
of their short-term setbacks are mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Peter Nicholas and John Abele, the billionaire
cofounders of Boston Scientific Corp., a Natick, Mass. instrument
company. On paper, Nicholas and his family lost an estimated $387
million since July 17. Abele and his family suffered estimated
paper losses of about $366 million.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is software executive Alan Trefler, the chief
executive of Pegasystems Inc., who, with his wife, Pam, has made
large and high-profile donations to Boston public schools. Trefler,
who owns 75 percent of the shares in his publicly traded company,
suffered a $255 million setback on paper since July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Among nine executives, selected because of their large, publicly
disclosed stock holdings, seven of them have lost money since the
July market top. Four have suffered paper losses over the last 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   The results, which do not reflect other investments or assets
executives may own, are based on stock holdings reported in the
latest proxies issued by their companies. Several extremely wealthy
executives at private companies, such as Fidelity Investments
chairman Edward Johnson III and his daughter, Abigail Johnson, are
not included on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Desite the daunting dollars involved in the paper losses, many
of the setbacks are well within the percentage declines suffered in
the overall market during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index declined in price by 14 percent
since July 17 and the Nasdaq index lost 17.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicholas and Abele only lost 15 percent in the value of
their Boston Scientific stock and those holdings have actually
appreciated by more than $50 million apiece over the last 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Amos Hostetter, who made a fortune in cable television, suffered
a paper loss of $126 million in his holdings of MediaOne Group
stock. But that decline represented less than a 5 percent decline
in value. Hostetter's stake has actually appreciated by nearly $1.4
billion over the last 12 months, to an estimated total of $2.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But other paper losses have cut deeper. Trefler's interest in
Pegasystems has shed 40 percent since July 17 and is off nearly 45
percent in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Paper losses of about $132 million suffered by Reebok
International chief Paul Fireman and his wife, Phyllis, since July
17 represented a 48 percent decline. Reebok shares have plunged by
70 percent over the last year, cutting the Fireman holdings by $348
million.
</P>
<P>
   Losses of $83 million for Abraham Gosman and his two sons are
calculated over three public companies in which they own
substantial stakes. A recent, sharp rally in one of those
companies, Carematrix Corp., actually trimmed the losses.
Carematrix stock has jumped by more than $10 per share to 23 7/8 in
the last six days.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's summertime blues did not cost everyone money.
Stock held by former EMC chief Richard Egan and his wife actually
appreciated by $5 million during the summer to $380 million. The
Egans' stock gained about $142 million over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest winner of all was a local native who does most
of his business in New York now. Viacom Inc. chief Sumner
Redstone's shares appreciated by $186 million since July 17 alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Viacom stock is actually owned by National Amusements Inc.
of Dedham, Mass., which counts Redstone as its controlling
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   That Viacom stock, which had struggled for two years, has nearly
doubled in the last 12 months and boosted Redstone's stake by more
than $3 billion to a total of $6.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Street Research &AMP; Management is giving you another chance
to get in on its Aurora Fund _ if you dare. The company said the
$400 million small-cap fund, closed last year, will reopen to new
investors on Oct. 1 and remain open until Dec. 31 or until assets
reach $750 million, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora is one of a number of small-cap funds that have announced
they are reopening amid an expectation of a rebound in these
stocks. That hasn't happened yet: The Russell 2000, a good
benchmark for small caps, was down 17.1 percent this year through
Friday; Aurora was down 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
