<HEADLINE>
SHE NEVER SAID, `THANK YOU' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this year of the Titanic, the stories seem to never stop. Two
recent books are filled with tales about the doomed ship, the
people who survived, and those who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   One of those storytellers was a forgotten survivor _ forgotten
until decades after the 1912 tragedy, when she delivered her
written recollections to ship historian John Maxtone-Graham. He, in
turn, has annotated and published them as ``Titanic Survivor'': The
Newly Discovered Memoirs of Violet Jessop Who Survived Both the
Titanic and Britannic Disasters'' (Sheridan Press, $23.95). Here is
one tale about Jessop, who was an ocean liner stewardess, that
Maxtone-Graham related as a guest speaker aboard the Grand Princess
cruise ship:
</P>
<P>
   After making it to a lifeboat, Jessop was given a baby to hold,
and she cradled that child in her arms all through that long and
awful night. Once aboard the rescue ship Carpathia, the baby was
returned to her mother _ who never once said ``thank you'' to
Jessop during the three-day voyage to New York. And that was the
end of that ... almost. Many years later, retired and living in
rural England, Jessop got a phone call at 3 a.m. A woman asked,
``Is this Violet Jessop who was a stewardess on the Titanic and
brought a baby to the (rescue) ship?'' ``Yes,'' said Jessop. The
caller laughed, said, ``I was that baby!'' and hung up. When Jessop
related this, she was told that perhaps the call was a joke. How
could it be, she replied: Until then, she had never told anyone
about the child she cradled at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Another source for Titanic lore is Logan Marshall, whose
original 1912 book, ``The Sinking of the Titanic,'' was published
within weeks of the disaster that killed more than 1,500. The book
has been abridged and edited for modern readers by Bruce M. Caplan
and republished by Seattle Miracle Press (paperback, $12.95).
According to Marshall's account, the ship was on fire from the
moment it left Southampton, and that probably contributed to the
disaster. And what's this about women and children first? Marshall
reports men being shot on deck as they attempted to board
lifeboats. Yet, there was also remarkable calm as the end neared,
and Caplan has a theory about that, which he shared with us: ``Sure
there was panic in the end, but people like Astor, Guggenheim, and
Straus (Mr. and Mrs.) were very calm. My theory is that most people
in 1912 took opiates (which were legal then) with them when they
went on an ocean voyage. They didn't have the wonderful drugs that
we have today, and if the seas became rough, opiates would be their
main salvation!! My theory is that when most of the people realized
that the ship was going down, and there was no hope of rescue, they
took an opiate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``The boat sank _ get over it!'' _ T-shirt spoofing the
Titanic craze.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Snappy slogan: &LR;  ``Titanic _ the Artifact Exhibition,'' at the World
Trade Center in Boston through Nov. 1, has added the recently
recovered 16-ton section of the ship's outer hull to the exhibit.
Thus, the exhibitors proclaim, ``It's a Hull New Show!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  If you are on a companionway aboard ship, where are
you? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  The term ``liner,'' as in ocean liner, orginated
because ships went in a line from Point A to Point B.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a phrase: &LR;  Getting sick over the side of a ship's rail was once
known as ``paying tribute to Neptune.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Calling all trios: &LR;  To celebrate the launch of the Sea Princess _
the 77,000-ton sister ship to the Sun Princess and Dawn Princess _
Princess Cruises has launched a ``Sea to Sea Search for Terrific
Trios.'' The Pointer Sisters, a legendary trio themselves, will
help pick the most talented threesomes from among 20 national
finalists. Trios can be dancers, singers, musicians, jugglers,
magicians, or just about anything else. Those 20 finalists (who can
be amateurs or professionals) will receive an all-expense paid trip
to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., during the week of Dec. 15 to participate
in Sea Princess inaugural festivities. The grand-prize threesome
will win a seven-day Princess Caribbean cruise. Contestants should
submit a video performance no more than five minutes long (on
half-inch VHS tape), along with a 100-word statement about why
their trio is terrific and their name, address, phone number, ages,
and a photo. Send it all to Sea to Sea Search for Terrific Trios,
c/o Porter Novelli, 220 East 42nd St., 8th Floor, New York, NY
10017. Entries must be postmarked by Oct. 7. For more information,
call toll-free 877-SEA-TRIOS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Canine cruisers: &LR;  Cunard's Queen Elizabeth II lays claim to being
the only cruise ship that permits dogs on board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Water music: &LR;  Harvey Robbins is taking to the sea again, on two
Boston-to-Bermuda cruises aboard the Norwegian Majesty. Robbins, a
New England concert producer best known for his ``Royalty of
Doo-Wopp'' shows, will host an oldies but goodies theme cruise,
complete with stars from the '50s and '60s, May 23-30. Then, May
30-June 7, he'll present an Irish theme cruise with Frank Ryan and
the Celtic Clan. And June 27-July 4, he'll have a singles party
cruise, with lots of music for dancing. More information or
reservations, which are limited, are available by calling Robbins
at 978-256-6472.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; More water music: &LR;  Norwegian Cruise Lines' SS Norway will celebrate
the birth of Elvis Presley with a special weeklong Caribbean cruise
beginning Jan. 2. Performers will include original Elvis band
members, Elvis tribute singers, comedians, and even the
world-famous Flying Elvi skydivers. Prices start at $1,047, some of
which will go to the charitable Elvis Presley Foundation. For more
information, call 800-667-4523 or visit www.callawaycruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mickey style:  &LR; Lifeboats on the Disney Magic cruise ship resemble
the boat in ``Steamboat Willie,'' the 1928 cartoon that launched
Mickey Mouse on his voyage of fame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Citizen of the sea:  &LR; So what happens if a baby is born at sea? The
tyke will have three choices of citizenship: that of his parents,
that of the country nearest the longitude and latitude where the
birth occurred, or that of the country of the ship's registration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; How old? &LR;  The belief persists among many that most cruisegoers are
elderly, but that's just not so. According to the Cruise Lines
International Association, 34 percent are ages 25 to 29; 35 percent
are 40 to 59; and 31 percent are 60 or older. And Royal Caribbean
International notes that one in five of its passengers is either a
child or an adult accompanying a child.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  You are on a flight of stairs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
