<HEADLINE>
NANTUCKET: FESTIVE IN THE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nantucket in the fall is special. Not only are there off-season
values in inns but the weather is fine and the island is festive.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders point out that unlike the short-lived fall foliage
displays of northern New England, Nantucket's distinctive autumn
palette of rare wildflowers, bayberies, beach plums, and scub oak
flourishes well into November.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen find October and November perfect for striped bass and
bluefish.
</P>
<P>
   The island also celebrates with a Cranberry Harvest Festival,
Oct. 16-18. In October, the island's vast cranberry bogs (before it
was divided, the Milestone Bog was the largest in the world) are
flooded, and millions of wine-red berries bob to the surface. It is
then the harvest begins. On Harvest Weekend, visitors are open to
the public to watch the harvest take place.
</P>
<P>
   For information about accommodations, call 508-228-0925 and ask
about midweek values and Getaway Packages. The island is easily
reached by airplane or ferry. One-hour high-speed ferry service is
also available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Foliage train
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four one-day Leaf Peer express train service from Portland to
Bethel, Maine, will be offered Sept. 26 and 27 and Oct. 10 and 11.
Great Train Escapes, a Seattle-based tour operator, has relocated a
luxury train from the West Coast to catch the Maine foliage. The
scenic one-day outings will take riders to Sunday River for brunch
and a chairlift ride to the mountain top for sweeping foliage
views. For information on the service, call 800-895-2554.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Foliage hot lines
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For nationwide foliage updates from the US Forest Service, call
800-354-4595.
</P>
<P>
   For individual states, call:
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut: 800-CT-BOUND.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware: 800-441-8846.
</P>
<P>
   Maine: 888-MAINE-45.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland: 800-532-8371.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts: 800-227-MASS.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire: 800-258-3608 or 800-262-6660.
</P>
<P>
   New York: 800-CALL-NYS.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina: Western mountains, 800-921-9698.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania: Poconos region, 717-421-5565.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont: 802-828-3239.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia: Shenandoah Valley, 800-434-LEAF; Skyline
Drive/Shenandoah National Park, 540-999-3500; Virginia portion of
Blue Ridge Parkway, 828-298-0398.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Internet foliage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another way to check on foliage is through the Internet and
services such as Expedia. Expedia offers a one-stop source for trip
planning with detailed maps and weather forecasts, along with
advice on making the most of this season's foliage. For those
taking off on a foliage or other outing, Expedia is offering anyone
purchasing a Northwest or Continental ticket through the service a
$99 companion award certificate to use with their next Expedia
purchase of a ticket on one of those airlines. Check out
www.expedia.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Susannah's quilts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most astonishing quilts in Old Sturbridge Village's
exhibition, ``Northern Comfort: New England's Early Quilts
1780-1850'' is composed of approximately 12,000 miniature pieces,
many only the size of a dime. The Quilt is believed to have been
created by Susannah Allen Anderson Howard of Ware, Mass.
Aesthetically, Susannah's miniature-pieced quilt also shows the
growth of an American quilting tradition, said Lynne Bassett, the
village's curator of textiles and fine arts. The quilt has a
central medallion design typical of English-style quilting, but
also layers of block-pieced bordrs that feature 15 designs. ``Her
quilt is a predecessor of the block-pieced quilting style that is
now recognizably American,'' said Bassett. The quilt is one of more
than 40 on display through Jan. 3. Old Sturbridge Village is
particularly beautiful in foliage season. The 1830s' village is in
Stuirbridge near the intersection of the Mass. Turnpike and
Interstate 84. For information, call 800-SEE-1830.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Exhibit passes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advance passes for ``Van Goghs: Masterpieces from the van Gogh
Museum, Amsterdam'' and ``Edo: The Art of Japan 1615-1868'' are now
available at the East Building of the National Gallery of Art in
Washington and through TicketMaster.
</P>
<P>
   The van Gogh exhibit, Oct. 4-Jan. 3, includes a loan of 70
paintings from the Amsterdam museum and comprises the largest
survey of the artist's career to be seen outside the Netherlands in
more than a quarter century. Daily passes will be required for the
show.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Edo'' Nov. 15-Feb. 15, passes will be required on
weekends, federal holidays, and busy days during the holiday
season. Free advance passes will be available at the museum with a
limit of six passes per person. A limited number of free passes
will also be available each day for both exhibits on a first-come
basis. Passes will also be available through TicketMaster
PhoneCharge for a $2.75 service fee per pass and a $1.25 handling
fee per order. Call 800-551-SEAT outside Washington, Baltimore, and
northern Virginia. For pass information on ``van Gogh,'' call
202-737-4215; for ``Edo,'' call 202-789-4999. The gallery's Web
site is www.nga.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beatles Museum
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only museum in the United States devoted to the Beatles has
opened in Virginia Beach, Va. McKee's Beatles Museum features wax
figures of the foursome, and memorabilia. For information, call
757-491-0491.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swiss World Airways, a new airline operating from Newark, is
offering half-price off the everyday price between Sept. 10 and 22.
The airline said it is the only nonstop service to Geneva. For the
sale period, first class tickets begin at $634, business class at
$334, and economy class at $84. All fares are one-way. The savings
will be given via a cash rebate check on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways now offers a low-fare service, MetroJet, from Boston.
The new service is to Tampa, Fla., and offers two daily round-trip
flights from Logan. Service out of Hartford will begin later.
MetroJet will offer a $97 one-way fare to Tampa with a 14-day
advance purchase. The lowest one-way walkup fare is $145. MetroJet
currently offers service out of 12 cities, including Manchester,
N.H., and Providence.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines is offering its BreakAAway fares for weekend
savings through Nov. 17. The fares range from $98 to $338 depending
upon destination. Flights leave on a Saturday, and return is the
following Monday or Tuesday. Also available are flights to Canada,
where the American dollar is buying more these days. Toronto is
$158 and Vancouver is $338. All fares are round-trip. Tickets must
be purchasd by Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways is offering fall fares that begin at just $399
for three nights in London. The packages, which include air fare
and accommodations for a three-night stay, are available for travel
between Oct. 1 and Dec. 12. Tickets are on sale through Nov. 20.
The lowest fares are for the period Nov. 1 through Dec. 12. Among
other fares are Paris, $429; Nice, $529; and Amsterdam, $489.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ultimate Experience
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While all Ritz-Carlton guests will receive special gifts and
amenities the evening of Dec. 31, 1999, one couple at each hotel
will enjoy the Ultimate Experience. They will stay in the best
suite, receive an 18-carat gold Bulgari Chrono watch for him, an
18-carat gold Bulgari Quadrato watch for her, a magnum of
Taittinger champagne with two Baccarat flutes in a gift box, a
Jaguar for the weekend, and many more amenities. The price for the
three-day package: just $100,000. Special entertainment is planned
at all Ritz-Carltons. In Boston, Peter Duchin will perform; in
Naples, Lou Rawls will be in concert; and at the Kapalua in Hawaii,
it's going to be the luau of a lifetime as guests dance barefoot in
ball gowns and tails. For a brochure detailing the Ritz-Carlton
Millennium Experience, call 800-241-3333.
</P>
