 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ After the video and the Starr documents,
the White House considers its options. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPUBS (Washington) _ How Republicans on the Hill view
their big decision on the documents. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REACT (Washington) _ Gauging the political landscape now
that the public and the professional politicians have had a chance
to absorb the impact of the additional Starr documents. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PANEL (Washington) _ It is up to the Rep. Hyde's
Judiciary Committee to take the next step. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV-RATINGS (Undated) _ The TV ratings for the broadcast
Monday of the president's testimony. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE (Appleton, Wis.) _ With the vice president: The
view from an official motorcade in the heartland. By Michael
Janofsky. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional action on the minimum wage
and bankruptcy bills. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-GEORGES (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ Hurricane Georges
pounded the Dominican Republic capital with powerful winds and
heavy downpours Tuesday after a deadly tear through Puerto Rico and
the Lesser Antilles.The hurricane killed three people in Puerto
Rico, rescue workers said. The storm had also killed three people
in the Leeward Islands. Tourists in the Florida Keys were urged to
leave today as the vulnerable island chain stepped up preparations
for the storm. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (New York) _ The Caribbean population in New York
watches and waits for news about the hurricane back home. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S. (Tarrytown, N.Y.) _ President Clinton meets with
Prime Minister Obuchi of Japan at a crucial moment in Japan's
banking crisis. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ASSEMBLY (United Nations) _ A parade of foreign leaders
address the U.N., including new Russian foreign minister. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-U.S. (New York) _ President Khatami of Iran meets the
press, talks about Iran-U.S. relations, Iran-Afghan relations, the
writer Salman Rushdie, other matters. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NUKE (Moscow) _ The U.S. and Russia agree on a deal to
turn former Soviet bomb plants into commercial sites. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Political and economic developments in Russia.
By Celestin Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Dublin, Ireland) _ The Irish prime minister
meets with head of the new Northern Ireland Assembly to try to
defuse the crisis over IRA disarmament. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   LESOTHO-COUP (Maseru, Lesotho) _ South African troops enter
Lesotho to quell coup attempt. At least 3 are killed. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-UNREST (Kuala Lumpur) _ Prime Minister Mahathir talks
about the turmoil in the country and the arrest of his deputy. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ The Asian economic crisis
has wrecked Indonesia's banking system, and as countries elsewhere
in the world grapple with their own banking problems, Indonesia's
halting efforts to clean up the mess are instructive. While it is
true that banking reform has been delayed by bureaucratic inertia
and a raft of other economic problems, the bigger problem may be
that, more than a year after its banks ran into such big trouble,
Indonesia still seems paralyzed by the enormity of the problem. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the industrial average was
down 42 points and the Nasdaq index was up 12 points. Overseas,
prices gained 1.4 percent in Tokyo and 2.8 percent in Hong Kong.
They rose 2.5 percent in Frankfurt, 2.2 percent in London, 1.8
percent in Brazil and 3 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was down 17/32 point at midday, with the
yield at 5.15 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Goldman Sachs reports earnings. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   UAL-APPOINT (New York) _ UAL's United Airlines names James
Goodwin, head of North American operations, as its new president
and chief operating officer, succeeding John Edwardson, who
resigned under union pressure last Friday. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly business travel column.
By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ The U.S. Commerce's undersecretary for
international trade criticizes China's efforts to open its markets.
By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich's ``Journal'' and Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties`';
details to come.
</P>
