<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIDEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SHOWTIME AS BUYERS PLUCK UP THE CLINTON TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Clinton grand jury testimony has become a
hot commodity, with video stores, book publishers and retail Web
sites scrambling to sell the president's videotaped testimony
before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deposition changed the course of history forever,'' said
Natalie Olinger, spokeswoman for MPI Home Video of Orland Park,
Ill. ``There has to be an easy-to-find access to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee on Monday released the taped
deposition, recorded in the White House map room Aug. 17 for the
grand jury investigating whether the president lied and abused his
power to cover up an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   MPI will ship 100,000 copies of its ``The Grand Jury Testimony
of William Jefferson Clinton'' cassette Wednesday to on-line and
retail video stores, including Tower Records and Borders Books.
</P>
<P>
   The video, which will arrive in stores Friday, carries the
following blurb on the back cover: ``WARNING: This program contains
strong language. Parental guidance is suggested.''
</P>
<P>
   Paperbacks of Clinton's grand jury testimony about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky also are being rushed out for
publication by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week before, several publishers came out with copies of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress that
contains allegations of perjury, abuse of power and obstruction of
justice that could lead to the impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Pocket Books, a division of Simon &AMP; Schuster, and PublicAffairs,
an independent publishing company, said Monday that they plan to
publish the transcript of the four hours of testimony under the
title ``The Starr Evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The video is already a best-selling item on the Amazon.Com Web
site, knocking Stephen King's latest novel, ``Bag of Bones,'' into
the No. 2 slot.
</P>
<P>
   At the Emeryville, Calif.-based Reel.com video retailing Web
site, the cassette came in at No. 3, behind ``Titanic'' and the
reissued Disney classic ``The Lady and the Tramp.''
</P>
<P>
   MPI made headlines earlier this year when it published ``Image
of an Assassination: A New Look at the Zapruder Film.'' That video
featured a digitally enhanced re-examination of the shooting of
President John F. Kennedy, and included more footage than had
previously been released. MPI sold 300,000 copies of that tape,
Olinger said, making it the company's best-selling documentary
title to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Jury'' will debut with a $14.95 price tag, though
Reel.Com, Amazon and many retail stores are discounting it to
$9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Olinger said the company obtained from the communications center
at the House of Representatives. There will be no commentary or
other content added to the tape, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting it straight,'' Olinger said. ``No spin will
be added.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, CNN, MSNBC and other news sites have recorded
record numbers of visitors viewing the Internet versions of the
president's deposition. The crush of viewers going on line slowed
the Internet down by a third, according to the Internet Traffic
Report, a Web site that monitors Net usage.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks, a Seattle-based company that distributes on-line
video viewers, said their traffic will exceed their last
record-setting event: The June 16 Net broadcast of a live birth
that garnered RealNetworks some 1.1 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers aren't in yet,'' RealNetworks spokesman Greg
Makuch said. ``But preliminary reports show that this Clinton
deposition will at least be double the birth thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Wainwright, the chief executive of Reel.com, said she
expected a burst of Clinton tape sales, then a quick fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's something that has legs,'' said Wainwright,
who said one reason the tape will be a best-seller is because of
its unprecedented portrayal of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Watergate, where no one was privy to information
that didn't come from a reporter,'' Wainwright said. ``Here you
have the most powerful man in the free world testifying under oath
right before your eyes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
