A8056 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALL-FASHION-FABRICS-     09-22 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-FABRICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT GOES? GLOBAL ACCENTS, GRAY FABRICS AND OTHER GREAT THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the little touches that make the clothes for fall current
and lively, give them individuality.
</P>
<P>
   Here are things to watch for:
</P>
<P>
   E is for ethnic looks. Embroidery from Asia or India. Patterns
and textures from the Middle East and Africa. String tie or frog
closures. Don't be surprised to find several cultures represented
in one garment.
</P>
<P>
   G is for gray. And we're not talking just gray flannel. Gray,
from pale to charcoal, is the neutral of the season. It's already a
best seller at The Bon Marche.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers may not trade their all-black wardrobes for it, but
gray is important to any fashion mix.
</P>
<P>
   What are the newest ways with gray? Ralph Lauren's gray flannel
jeans skirt, gray flannel Birkenstock clogs, or a sheer, shimmery
silver/gray evening dress.
</P>
<P>
   S is for sheen or sparkle. Crystal beads glimmer through dense
wools or synthetic poodle cloth. Even the sheerest fabrics appear
to be touched with gold or silver. Sequins and oversize paillettes
give added interest to patterned fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are a few beaded-all-over garments around, the
spare approach is most chic _ a tiny band of beads for accent, or
glimmer scattered randomly.
</P>
<P>
   H is for hoods. Expect to find hoods on everything from vests to
sweaters _ on sweaters that look like hooded sweat shirts, for
example _ and on coats. Hoods are age and gender blind.
</P>
<P>
   F is for furs. Fur cuffs, fur collars, fur jackets, fur coats,
even fur scarves and bags. Fur is flying this fall. Sometimes it's
dyed to match. Some of it's real. Some is frankly fake. The
luxurious feel, appearance and texture make fur most-wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Also look for:
</P>
<P>
   Animal prints, from spots to stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Colored/textured pantyhose. And don't be afraid to wear a color
that contrasts with the rest of a costume, like bright blue legs
with a gray tweed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Cashmere in any form.
</P>
<P>
   Bustles on skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Flats. Shoes haven't been this simple since Capezios took to the
streets in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Sheath dresses with matching coats. They look newer than
tailored suits.
</P>
<P>
   Padded vests, skirts, jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Turtlenecks on top.
</P>
<P>
   Handbags.
</P>
<P>
   Zip-front jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Knit dresses for day and evening.
</P>
<P>
   Suede shirtjackets.
</P>
<P>
   Cargo pants.
</P>
<P>
   Hats and caps, from cloches and fedoras to little knits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; tad-z
