<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JURY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PORTRAIT OF THE GRAND JURY: OPINIONATED, INVOLVED IN PROBE
 &HT;    840&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Crying tears of relief, Monica Lewinsky thanked the
grand jurors who had questioned, consoled and scolded her about the
most intimate details of her White House affair with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate all of your understanding for this situation and
your ability to open your heart and your mind and your soul,'' the
star witness told her anonymous, sympathetic inquisitors.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's nine-month
investigation of whether Clinton illegally covered up his
relationship with the former intern, the identities and activities
of the 23 federal grand jurors have remained shrouded in legal
secrecy. However, the panel's personality has begun to peek through
in the transcripts of testimony released by Congress and the
televised questioning of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Asking probing, informed questions, openly expressing its
opinions and pushing for answers, the grand jury is clearly not the
passive chorus for Starr's investigation that some outside legal
observers had supposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a longstanding investigation like this, a grand jury
becomes very proprietary about its role. The members take great
pride in their work and sometimes they have to be restrained by
prosecutors,'' said Joseph DiGenova, a former U.S. attorney and
independent counsel. ``They were the ones who asked the president
explicit questions about his sexual relationship with Miss
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the grand jurors asked the sort of questions that many
Americans who aren't lawyers or politicians would pose if they had
a chance. Why did Lewinsky save the semen-stained dress? Does she
still love the president? What does she think about Linda Tripp?
Why doesn't Clinton just give a full, straight answer about his
``inappropriate relationship'' with Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not uncommon for a grand jury to ask questions of a human
or personal nature,'' said Bruce Yannett, a New York attorney who
worked in the Office of Independent Counsel in the Iran-contra
investigation. ``They're supposed to be a reflection of the
community at large, and they often ask the kinds of questions a lay
person would ask.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This grand jury is made up almost entirely of African-American
women from the District of Columbia,'' said DiGenova. ``They play a
very active role, contrary to public belief.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the grand jury that summoned Lewinsky back for a second
day of testimony _ a session in which prosecutors posed very few
questions. From the opening moments _ when the witness asked, ``Can
you guys call me Monica?'' _ it was an occasion more akin to an
``Oprah'' show than a legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to let you know we're not here to judge you in any
way,'' one juror began. ``I think many of us feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica, none of us in this room are perfect,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   But, like much of the country, they were oh so curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``And today, Monica, do you still love the president?''
</P>
<P>
   She said she did until his televised speech in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you aware that he was having problems in his marriage?
Did this ever spill over in the time you were together?''
</P>
<P>
   That answer was redacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said the relationship was more than oral sex,'' asked a
juror. ``I mean, it wasn't like you went out on dates or anything
like that like normal people, so what more was it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we spent hours on the phone. It was emotional,'' Lewinsky
testified. ``We were very affectionate. ... We'd hold hands. We'd
smile a lot. We discussed a variety, you know, a wide range of
things. .. .There was a real component of a relationship to it. ...
I thought he had a beautiful soul.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jurors, more than almost everyone, knew the details of
the case. Their questions weren't all softballs. The jurors wanted
to know about the witness's proffer and her immunity deal, and
about the day she was confronted by FBI agents and found out that
her friend, Linda Tripp, had been secretly taping their telephone
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   They asked about her past relationship with another married man;
the timing of the retrieval of presidential gifts by Betty Currie,
Clinton's secretary; conversations with Vernon Jordan, and her
thoughts when ordered to give a deposition in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment trial.
</P>
<P>
   While understanding, they weren't always approving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a married man and it wasn't no secret of that fact,''
said one juror.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed to share Lewinsky's disdain for Tripp, but urged her
not to dwell on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that even though right now you feel a lot of
hate for Linda Tripp, but you need to move on and leave her where
she is because whatever goes around comes around,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is definitely going to have to give an account for what
she did, and you need to just go past here and don't keep her
because that's going to keep you out,'' advised another.
</P>
<P>
   And when it ended, the foreperson told the tearful witness: ``We
wanted to offer you a bouquet of good wishes that includes luck,
success, happiness and blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the questioning of Clinton, questions were relayed from the
grand jurors in the federal courthouse to members of Starr's team
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, the next series of questions are from the grand
jurors,'' said one attorney, Solomon Wisenberg. ``And let me tell
you that the grand jurors want you to be more specific about the
inappropriate conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The series of questions included: Is oral sex performed on you
within the definition (of sexual relations) as you understood it?
What is the legal basis of the president refusing to answer some
specific questions on sexual matters? Would kissing or touching the
breast or genitalia of another person constitute sexual relations
under the definition?
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's lawyers cut off the session after an agreed-upon
four hours, Jackie Bennett, another of Starr's associates, said,
``Mr. President, I am notified the grand jury still has unanswered
questions of you.''
</P>
<P>
   This intense interest and remaining questions by the grand
jurors could spell trouble for the Clinton administration, since
the investigation is still going on, said DiGenova. ``I expect
indictments will be coming out of this grand jury very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Yannett said it is impossible to predict whether
indictments are forthcoming. It is apparent though, he added, that
this grand jury ``is acutely aware of the importance of its work.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
