<HEADLINE>
DUAL PURPOSE IS AN ASSET FOR ARTISTS' FUNCTIONAL WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All art doesn't hang out or sit around waiting to be admired or
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Functional art practically begs to be included in life. It was
created to be beautiful or perhaps whimsical _ and useful.
</P>
<P>
   More people are buying into this art form _ one-of-a-kind lamps,
handmade rocking chairs, pottery thrown by an artist and other
items both user-friendly and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Handcrafted pottery can be found for a few dollars when Pottery
Northwest in Seattle has a yard sale. Blown glass by local artists
is available for $25 to $25,000 depending on the size of the item
and the reputation of the artist. Furniture prices are often
comparable to high-quality manufactured designs.
</P>
<P>
   Functional art has other advantages: It usually doesn't require
a large space, a frame, special lighting or an insurance policy
rider.
</P>
<P>
   Some art appears functional, but don't be fooled.
</P>
<P>
   A blown-glass cylinder by Dale Chihuly may look like a vase, and
could be used as one, but it isn't meant to be one, says Kate
Elliott, owner of Elliott Brown Gallery in Seattle's Fremont
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   You'd probably hesitate to put flowers _ or anything else _ in
something with a $44,000 price tag, but as Elliott quips, ``It does
hold water.''
</P>
<P>
   Chihuly's art may fall into the for-viewing-only category, but
there are plenty of blown-glass pieces by artists that are meant to
hold everything from flowers and fruits to chip dips and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Foster, owner of Foster/White Galleries in Seattle and
nearby Kirkland, says artists have historically made things with
dual purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Pottery is a prime example. Foster describes a platter by the
late George Tsutakawa _ an artist best known for his sculpture and
drawings _ as art that could be displayed or used for serving food.
</P>
<P>
   Foster says Tiffany lamps from the early 1900s were functional
art of that period. By the '20s, artists were making one-of-a-kind
pieces of furniture. In the '30s, pottery became an acceptable art
form.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the '70s that functional art began to assert
itself once again, when pottery flourished along with handcrafted
jewelry. Galleries began giving space to functional art, and the
line between functional and fine art began to blur.
</P>
<P>
   Foster/White Gallery staged a functional art show in the early
1980s _ a courageous move for the time. Foster says he met with
artists who showed at the gallery and asked them if they had any
ideas for a functional show. Artists could contribute whatever they
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show didn't affect their future work, but it did fire
their imaginations,'' Foster says today. Among the items _ an area
rug painted on Masonite, acrylic book ends, several small painted
tables and ceramics. The public loved it, Foster says. Art critics
were, to put it politely, critical.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are galleries devoted to functional art. And fine
art galleries often have some functional pieces to show. Artists _
especially those working in wood, glass and ceramics _ seem
comfortable in the duality of their works, Foster says.
</P>
<P>
   Foster cites Seattle artist Elaine Hanowell's fish lamps as
being ``truly art and truly functional.'' The painted paper lamps
on bamboo frames hang in the Dahlia Lounge restaurant in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He praises the finely crafted furniture by Viscount Linley _ the
British royal whose mother is Princess Margaret and aunt is Queen
Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   Linley, known for inlaid wood designs, has created an eyeglass
cabinet for Elton John and other pieces for serious collectors
around the world. His shows in American cities are treated as art
events.
</P>
<P>
   After discussing functional art at length, Foster leans back and
says, ``I don't think you can define functional art. There's a line
of aesthetic judgment. I'd be offended if I went to a party and
found a fine piece by a Pilchuck (glass) artist used to serve
popcorn. It's sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster says it helps to know why the artist conceived a piece.
Anne Hirondelle, for example, makes ceramic vessels that look like
tea or coffee pots, but they're not. They're sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   ``An embroidered potholder might be art to the creator, but is
it art?'' Foster questions. ``Some things are marginal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
