<P>
   THE CLINTON CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JURY _ WASHINGTON _ A portrait of the Starr grand jury,
which turns out to be both more activist and more sympathetic than
people had realized. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CANDIDATES _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton may or may
not escape impeachment, but the path to high office has been
drastically changed by his ordeal. Now that a mechanism exists to
extract politicians' secrets via private lawsuits, future
candidates for the White House _ and perhaps lower offices _ may
think twice before running. The result may be a process that places
a higher premium on purity than competence. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHARACTER _ WASHINGTON _ Using psychological theories
that attempt to describe how such traits as integrity, ambition,
the ability to relate to other people develop to make up a person's
character, a New York psychoanalyst and political scientist
concludes that as a child President Clinton was alternately adored
and neglected by his mother and gradually taught that rules and
restrictions don't matter _ at least not for him. Stanley Renshon,
in the book, ``High Hopes, the Clinton Presidency and the Politics
of Ambition,'' attempts to set forth a theory by which voters can
systematically evaluate the character of candidates for president.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   LAWPROFS-CLINTON _ In the halls of academe, President Clinton's
performance before the Kenneth Starr grand jury rated less than an
A but better than an F. Experts in law and communications were
analyzing the president's responses to questions about his sex
life. Like much of the public, they came away with a mixed review
of the president's performance. (Keilman/Bennish, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-CLINTON _ The media is taking a lashing from a large part
of the American public for its long-running and uncomfortably
detailed coverage of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal. But newspapers,
TV networks and cable news stations have no choice but to call the
nation to an unwilling jury duty, according to media ethicists.
(DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JAPAN _ TARRYTOWN, N.Y. _ President Clinton meets with
new Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi at Rockefeller Family
Estate for the first time. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-GEORGES _ MIAMI _ The latest developments on the
movements of, and destruction caused by Hurricane Georges. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hurricane Georges barrels
through the islands, we prepare and watch and wait and buy up water
and other items. Tourists are asked to leave the Keys. (McLachlin,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in the (a) general news category.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BINO _ Frank Cerabino's local column on Hurricane Georges.
(Cerabino, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in the (a) general news category.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-HAITI _ MIAMI _ Due to Hurricane Georges, Ted Turner,
Hillary Clinton and George Soros delayed their scheduled weekend
trip to Haiti. They were to visit clinics and give money. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   POLMONEY-COLOR _ WASHINGTON _ A disproportionately small part of
campaign contributions come from people of color, according to a
new study by Public Campign. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POLMONEY-DATA _ Comparison of contribution and income figures
from average ZIP codes with ZIP codes where most residents are
people of color.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ The federal government is moving
toward contracting for a new Patent Office building that critics
have dubbed the ``Taj Mahal,'' complete with plans for $250 shower
curtains. What's more, after 20 years and at least $1.3 billion in
costs, the building won't belong to the government because it's
being leased. Sponsors of the project have already defeated an
attempt to kill it in Congress. A Senate hearing on Wednesday may
move the project closer to reality. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLASS-ACT _ WASHINGTON _ A group of veterans, including the most
decorated soldier and former prisoner of war from Vietnam, rally at
the Capitol Tuesday to protest what they see as the government's
reneging on a promise to provide them health care for life. Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., and others likely to speak. (Nesmith, Cox
News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CARTER _ ATLANTA _ Jimmy Carter has his annual town hall meeting
at Emory University for students and faculty Tuesday. It is not
open to the public. During this forum, which is fairly informal,
Carter answers written questions from students. We go to seek if
anyone asks about the Clinton/Lewinsky scandal. (Kurylo, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NIEMAN-SUIT _ ATLANTA _ A woman who frequently shopped at Nieman
Marcus and went there one day and tried on some lingerie in the
dressing room, was taken by security guards after she left the
store and searched to determine whether she had stolen some items.
But she had not. The woman filed a federal civil rights lawsuit
against the department store. Verdict possible today. (Rankin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND _ The National Underground Railroad Freedom Center
in Cincinnati will make its public debut this weekend with the
start of its civil rights lecture series and the first presentation
of the International Freedom Conductor Award to civil rights
crusader Rosa Parks. By the time Ohio celebrates its bicentennial
in 2003, the Freedom Center's interactive museum will tell the
story of the Underground Railroad, the clandestine network of
abolitionists who harbored fleeing slaves in pre-Civil War America
during their escape to freedom in the north. (Joyce, Dayton Daily
News). 26. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WALK _ Like the thousands of slaves who reached Ohio on their
way to freedom in Canada, Anthony Cohen will have traveled almost
800 miles through forests and rivers by the time he reaches Dayton
on Nov. 4. Cohen, 34, is retracing the steps of those who escaped
the slavery on the Underground Railroad. Cohen, an Underground
Railroad historian, left Mobile, Ala., on Sept. 1 and is hiking
about 20 miles a day. He's due to arrive in Dayton Nov. 4, although
at this time has no specific activities planned to mark his arrival
(Joyce, Dayton Daily News). 8.5
</P>
<P>
   THORNDALE-HAZING _ CAMERON _ Four Thorndale High School students
admitted in juvenile court recently that they attacked a classmate
in a football hazing ritual last October. As a condition of a plea
bargain, each of the teens stood and apologized publicly to Joshua
Bonney, the student they had attacked. (Rivera, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT-MOLESTERS _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ A U.S. Border Patrol
agent who found a list of Florida sexual predators on the Internet
conceived the idea for the newest crackdown on criminal immigrants.
Any immigrant, legal or illegal, is already subject to deportation
if convicted of a felony sex crime. Now, Agent Michael Flanagan is
comparing the Internet's list of convicted child molesters with the
immigration service's data. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
