<P>
   NY-WINE-TASTING (New York) _ All over the New York City,
sandwiched between the dry cleaners and the shoe repair shops, are
wine stores, and on Saturday afternoons, many of them are opening
bottles of Spanish riojas, or California chardonnays, or Australian
syrahs and pouring them, free of charge, for anyone who takes the
trouble to stop in. In San Francisco, the hedonistic Saturday has
become a ritual, as cars stream across the Golden Gate bridge and
speed toward the vineyards of Napa and Sonoma. New York does not
have the vineyards, but it does have the wine stores, dozens and
dozens of them, and shrewd customers, after making a few phone
calls and drawing up a little list, can map out a personal wine
trail, as I did on a recent Saturday afternoon. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FRENCH-PIZZA (New York) _ Even though the French influence is
everywhere in New York's culinary world, a few foods that are
common in France have managed to escape the city's dragnet and
remain almost unknown here. The French pizza is one stunning
example. Yes, pizza. Although it is most often known as a
pissaladiere, it is what it is: a round flat bread, crisp on the
bottom, flavorful on top, rustic and yet urbane. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
