<HEADLINE>
HEM AND HER: HERE'S THE LONG VIEW OF THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long skirts with sweaters were epidemic on U.S. and European
runways when fall '98 fashions were unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   Show after show opened with a model wearing a slim, ankle-length
or longer skirt topped with one or two sweaters _ big and bulky,
short and tight or perhaps a twin set.
</P>
<P>
   So numerous were these long styles, it seemed a foregone
conclusion that they'd be sweeping onto sidewalks, and into
classrooms, workplaces and parties come fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ankle-length styles are already seen on Seattle streets _ young
women striding out in their latest fall gear the minute there's a
cloud in the sky. Miniskirts, however, are still giving them
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be long skirts in every closet? Will they become a
classroom classic, a workday uniform or just another ingredient in
the fashion mix?
</P>
<P>
   Historically, long skirts with trains flourished in the late
1790s. A century later, women were wearing a flared ``Gibson Girl''
style.
</P>
<P>
   But will the 20th century _ the one that opened with long skirts
and went on to expose ankles, knees and thighs _ end back on a long
note?
</P>
<P>
   Carol Steele, Northwest fashion director for Nordstrom, hedges.
She calls ankle-length skirts ``an option . . . part of the relaxed
sportswear influence . . . sort of a new pant.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that long skirts were an important part of Donna Karan's
DKNY collection _ usually a sure sign that a fashion is going to be
a best seller _ Steele predicts long skirts will become even more
important as the holiday season approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Ahern, fashion coordinator for The Bon Marche, says
ankle-length skirts are in all departments in fabrics ranging from
wool to denim to silk. Who's buying? Customers under 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a younger, more creative customer,''
Ahern says. ``For those over 30, it's going to be a
fashion-conscious, avant-garde shopper'' who buys long.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Ann Taylor chain, says their customers
have let them know they want a variety of hemlines _ and they're
getting them. Skirt lengths in these stores will range from
midthigh to ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based image consultant Audrey Beaulac says skirts and
sweaters are the fall fashion statement, especially long skirts
with flattter shoes or boots.
</P>
<P>
   But realistically, hems will probably hang from top of the
kneecap to ankle, with most settling somewhere midknee, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulac points out that Nicole Miller was one of a very few
designers to feature above-knee skirts in her fall '98 collection.
But skirts aren't the only option this season.
</P>
<P>
   Pants are definitely part of the mix _ slim and straight to
slouchy trousers. They're also topped with sweaters _ often a
turtleneck. Sometimes they're shown with vests (especially furry
ones) or short, zipped jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulac believes this will be a season for dresses, both knit
and woven. Sheath dresses will be worn under coats and jackets. A
sheath, jacket, pants, skirt and shell top can form a complete
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Wool jersey dresses are already best sellers for the Geoffrey
Beene label. When Brian Millsap brought the Beene collection to
Ruth Hill in downtown Seattle last month, long skirts weren't part
of the picture. Long dresses, however, were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day dresses have really caught on this season,'' Millsap says,
as he shows ankle-length and midcalf jersey dresses that are
selling well throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Other dresses in the Beene collection end just above the knee _
especially little black cocktail dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Cropped jackets have long been staples in Beene's collections,
and other designers have picked up on the shorter looks for fall
'98. Short jackets look right with long skirts. So do close-to-the
body sweaters and twin sets.
</P>
<P>
   Beaulac warns that a maxi coat over a long skirt would be too
'70s. Ahern says a blazer makes a long skirt look matronly. And
stiletto heels with long skirts are a fashion disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Hemlines lower, with designer touches
</P>
<P>
   A sample of long skirts and tops from top designers, unveiled at
shows in New York:
</P>
<P>
   Designer Donna Karan quilted silk chiffon for a long, slim
skirt, then paired it with a hooded polar fleece vest in her DKNY
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the skirts shown were bias cut, sans waistbands, resting
on hip bones. Others were cut like a pair of jeans around the
waist, ending in a slim skirt instead of pants.
</P>
<P>
   Designers Yeohlee and Susan Lazar opened with long, wrap skirts.
Linda Allard, designer for the Ellen Tracy label, slashed a long
walking skirt to the thigh. Ralph Lauren showed a jeans skirt in
gray flannel, even a full, half-circle skirt.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Eisen put a stretch mohair sweater over an iridescent
chiffon skirt for late-day. Han Feng's evening styles include a red
velvet skirt with a red cable-knit sweater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
