r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PANEL-HNS &LR;      09-22 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PANEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO GROUP TROUBLED BY CLINTON'S PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the realm of the ordinary, it was
extraordinary _ an unvarnished view of a president in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With much of the rest of the nation, a panel of San Franciscans
saw it unfold Monday, watching on television at the San Francisco
Examiner at the request of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three hours of testimony by President Clinton,
they came away unconvinced about calls for impeachment but deeply
troubled by what they had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not his high point,'' said the Rev. Stephen Meriwether
of the San Francisco archdiocese, who said the scandal made him
pose ``the age-old question: Would you want to read minds? No.''
</P>
<P>
   For Meriwether, 45, and the others, the sordid details of
Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky were revealed in a surreal
setting: the president, at times fidgety, at times tenacious, at
times unsure, answering for his sex life on national television.
</P>
<P>
   It was fascinating and unsettling at the same time for this
mostly Democratic quartet, all of whom voted to elect Clinton two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the same token, I also elected Richard Nixon twice,''
Meriwether said.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the testimony, they rolled their eyes at the
dogged legal gymnastics Clinton engaged in to avoid admitting that
the young White House intern performed oral sex on him. They joked
about the gifts Clinton gave her _ all items he apparently
scrounged from his own office. They pondered the term ``reasonable
circumstances.'' They took in how many times Clinton sipped a drink
or coughed nervously. They argued about just what it all meant for
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself almost resenting him,'' said Don Young, 30,
director of broadcast programming at the National Asian American
Telecommunications Association. ``I know it's not all his fault,
but why do we have to put ourselves through this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man _ he's a big dog!'' said Toni Young, 35, a San
Francisco consumer rights advocate, who is not related to Don
Young. ``His thing is, `I'm a guy and I made some guy mistakes.'
He's not as contrite as I'd like him to be.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Toni Young said, ``He's a smart guy who says,
`I'm going to follow the rules you gave me.' Can I fault him? No.
The stakes are high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fabulous euphemisms!'' noted Rosemary Bacy, 66, of San
Francisco, about the contorted definitions of sexual relations she
heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encounters that were wrong ... inappropriate contact,
inappropriate sexual banter _ come now!'' Meriwether said.
</P>
<P>
   He also pronounced Clinton as being cheap to boot for not buying
any of the gifts he gave to Lewinsky, who lavished gifts on him.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's less than forthcoming behavior about the scandal
is entirely explainable, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one is so gauche as to ask about such intimate matters, one
should be expected to be lied to,'' Meriwether said. ``It was a
very natural reaction. It was embarrassing. He didn't want it to
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, doesn't make it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, he should come clean _ it'll all be better,''
Toni Young said.
</P>
<P>
   No political novices, the four dismissed as whining Clinton's
complaints that he was being grilled about the meaning of taking an
oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who has a (degree) from Yale School of Law. He
has a better understanding of the process than most,'' Toni Young
said. ``Stop with the persecution complex _ you're the leader of
the free world!''
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the panelists, Toni Young said she thought most
Americans are ``getting sick of the whole thing, unless they come
up with stronger charges stamped with perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to all the Whitewater and travel office
investigations?'' Bacy said. ``It's all vanished and we're left
with all this sex stuff. If the president's going to be impeached,
it should have to do with national security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
