<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS CALIFORNIANS SUPPORT INDIAN CASINO MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new poll shows that a slender majority of
California voters support a statewide measure that would allow
expanded gambling at Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks from the Nov. 3 election, 54 percent of voters
surveyed supported the initiative to allow tribal casinos to have
slot machines and high-stakes card games; 33 percent opposed it.
Thirteen percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of likely voters, conducted for the San Francisco
Examiner, also found majority support for Gov. Pete Wilson's
proposed education reform measure and a measure that would increase
the tax on cigarettes by 50 cents per pack to pay for early
childhood education programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the contests for statewide offices, the survey found that the
incumbent secretary of state, controller and insurance commissioner
enjoyed solid support. No candidate has established clear support
in the statewide races for lieutenant governor, attorney general
and treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were running a campaign, I wouldn't tell anyone to
relax,'' said Del Ali, pollster for Mason-Dixon Political/Media
Research, which conducted the poll for the Examiner. ``You can't
burn out because no one is focused on these races right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 812 registered voters in California was
conducted Sept. 14-16. All who participated said they regularly
voted in state elections. The poll has a margin of error of plus or
minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 5, the Indian gambling measure, is the most
vigorously contested of the 10 initiatives on the Nov. 3 ballot,
with the two opposing campaigns expected to spend at least $75
million, mostly on commercial advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes expect to spend $50 million, but political insiders
say the forces supporting Proposition 5 may top the record for a
statewide initiative campaign of $84 million spent by opponents of
Proposition 103, the auto insurance initiative voters passed in
1988. Opponents of the measure, funded largely by Las Vegas casino
and hotel operators, plan to spend close to $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have been sparring in TV commercials running for
weeks. The tribes argue the initiative is the only way to keep
their slot machines, which make up 75 percent of Indian casino
revenues. Under current state law, slot machines are illegal, and
federal authorities are battling in court to seize them.
</P>
<P>
   Indian gambling opponents, a coalition that includes labor, law
enforcement and religious and business groups as well as casino
interests, say the initiative allows for little state oversight of
casinos and would result in an expansion of gambling in California.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents admit the tribes gained an early advantage by starting
their ad campaign in May, before the measure even qualified for the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yes side has one message: sympathy for Indians. They've
pretty well established that message,'' said Frank Schubert,
manager for the No on 5 campaign. ``It's really our challenge to go
block by block and deliver our message. We're confident that when
we do that, we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, the poll showed that 70 percent of those
surveyed supported Wilson's education initiative, Proposition 8.
The measure would permanently cut elementary school class sizes,
create parent-teacher governing councils and require teachers to
take competence tests. Only 15 percent opposed Proposition 8, while
15 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also support Proposition 10, a measure sponsored by film
director Rob Reiner that would increase the tobacco tax to pay for
early childhood development programs. The survey found that 55
percent of those questioned said they support the measure; 33
percent were opposed and 12 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Voters supported, by a slimmer margin, Proposition 9, which
proposes giving electricity consumers a 20 percent rate reduction:
56 percent to 21 percent, with 23 percent still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Among the incumbent statewide officers: Democratic Controller
Kathleen Connell was favored over San Mateo County Supervisor Ruben
Barrales, a Republican, 56 percent to 29 percent; Republican
Secretary of State Bill Jones was supported by 50 percent to 32
percent for Democrat Michela Alioto; Republican Insurance
Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush received the support of 47 percent
to 27 percent for his Democratic opponent, Assemblywoman Diane
Martinez of Rosemead.
</P>
<P>
   In the nonpartisan school chief contest, Superintendent of
Schools Delaine Eastin, a Democrat, had the support of 41 percent
to 28 percent for Gloria Tuchman, a Santa Ana school teacher who
co-chaired the successful Proposition 227 campaign to end bilingual
education.
</P>
<P>
   In the open seat contests, Democratic Assemblyman Cruz
Bustamante, the former Assembly speaker, was supported by 42
percent to 35 percent over state Sen. Tim Leslie, R-Roseville, for
lieutenant governor; Deputy Attorney General Dave Stirling, a
Republican, received the support of 42 percent in the campaign for
attorney general to 37 percent for state Sen. Bill Lockyer,
D-Hayward, the former state Senate president pro tem; and in the
contest for treasurer, Democratic businessman Phil Angelides of
Sacramento and Republican Assemblyman Curt Pringle, a former
Assembly speaker of Garden Grove, each gained 34 percent support
with 32 percent undecided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8132 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-2TA Sept.   09-22 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-2TAKES-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIOACTIVE SEED THERAPY IS USED TO FIGHT PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday,
Sept. 28)   By DAVID UHLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ With gentle force, Dr. Michael Sarosdy slowly
withdraws a foot-long needle from between Jim King's legs. The
hollow probe leaves behind a tiny trail of radioactive pellets in
the prostate gland of the patient. He sleeps on his back on an
operating room table, his feet locked in stirrups.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's next?'' Sarosdy asks, putting aside the used needle.
Beth Walker, a radiation dosage expert, glances at her chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Charlie three to the base,'' she says. A nurse hands
Sarosdy another needle.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor turns and checks the alphanumeric coordinates on a
pinhole-dotted grid mounted on a stand, clamped close to the
patient at the end of the table. He finds the hole corresponding to
``big charlie'' _ the capital letter ``C'' at the top of the metal
grid _ and the number ``three'' along the left side.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate destination for the tip of this particular needle
is the ``base,'' the place where the prostate meets the bladder, a
spot about four inches inside Jim King.
</P>
<P>
   With latex-gloved hands, Sarosdy carefully inserts the needle
into the correct pinhole on the grid. Then he pushes it forward.
</P>
<P>
   As the minutes tick by in the operating room, the doctor, the
dosage expert and the nurse develop a rhythm, one that sounds like
a bizarre round of bingo or the board game ``Battleship.''
Location, needle, insert, withdraw. Sarosdy and his colleague, Dr.
Bradley Prestidge check their work on a nearby ultrasound monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has preloaded each hollow needle with a carefully
calculated number of radioactive pellets, usually called ``seeds.''
Each seed, about half the size of a grain of rice, contains
radioactive iodine encapsulated in titanium. The kill zone around
each seed is about the size of a marble.
</P>
<P>
   The medical team thinks it will take about 85 seeds to
neutralize the cancer in their patient's prostate and keep it from
spreading into the rest of his body.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors found Jim King's prostate cancer about a year ago. A
routine screening for military veterans exposed to Agent Orange,
the chemical defoliant used during the Vietnam War, revealed an
irregularity in Jim's blood work. A ``prostate specific antigen''
test, known as a PSA, detected a slightly elevated level of
prostate-produced protein.
</P>
<P>
   A biopsy, however, failed to confirm suspicions. Nine months
later, Jim's PSA was higher yet. Another biopsy confirmed the
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Jim, a 73-year-old retired command sergeant major with the U.S.
Army, is no stranger to doctors' offices and operating rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons, suspecting lung cancer, removed a lobe from his left
lung in 1972. Tests showed it had been attacked by cryptococcus, a
fungus Jim may have picked up overseas. Also on his medical chart:
A heart attack in 1984, an aortic aneurysm, arthritis, two TURPs _
trans-urethral resection of the prostate _ to help him urinate.
</P>
<P>
   And now prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting with his wife, Mary, in a lobby outside Sarosdy's
office, Jim faces his upcoming operation with the stoicism of a
long-time military man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not scared,'' says Jim, a native of Boerne, Texas. ``It's
just one of those things that's part of life. Almost all of us at
this age have some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The last couple of years, however, have been especially tough
for the King family, with medical battles on two fronts. Diagnosed
with breast cancer, Mary had a mastectomy and finished chemotherapy
just six months ago. She is scheduled for a cataract operation next
week. Today, however, all her thoughts are on Jim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Jim says, you have to live with whatever comes your
way,'' she says, with a gentle twang revealing a childhood spent in
Nashville. ``The man upstairs is the one who makes the big
decisions. ``Of course, Jim helps me because he's so upbeat. I
don't know what I'd do without him, to be perfectly honest. He's
always that way, 36 years he's been that way. He wakes up every
morning with a smile on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple met in the library at Fort Sam Houston. Jim was
divorced and on his way up through the military ranks. Mary, the
widowed wife of an Army pilot, was working as a librarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted a book,'' Jim recalls. Mary remembers it
differently: ``He was doing some flirting is what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim had two children. Mary had three. Together, they made a
family. Like many military families, they traveled and moved a lot:
Japan, Europe and several stateside posts. The children are grown
now and scattered around the U.S., with jobs and families and kids
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   For the last eight years, home for Jim and Mary has been a
comfortable three-bedroom condo off Vance Jackson Road, with a
garden off the back patio for the flowers Jim loves to grow. He
usually takes a brisk walk every morning on the winding streets of
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   At night, Mary sometimes joins him for a leisurely stroll.
Lately, she has noticed that her husband sleeps a little more than
usual, the only change since his prostate cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim never was a person who slept an hour more than he
should,'' she says. ``You know, in the military you get up with the
birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarosdy reviews Jim's medical history in his office before
seeing him in an examining room. A urologic cancer specialist, the
only one in private practice in San Antonio, Sarosdy has performed
about 60 radioactive seeds procedures, also known as brachytherapy,
in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our patient is a 73-year-old man,'' the doctor says, flipping
through Jim's chart. ``He had a bad heart attack a number of years
ago. He takes a number of medications. ``He's not a great candidate
for a big surgical procedure. Even though this will require some
form of an anesthetic, either a spinal or general, it's going to be
less of an insult on him than a surgical procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than 20 years as a surgeon, Sarosdy also has performed
dozens of operations to remove cancerous prostates. Possible side
effects of that surgery include incontinence and inability to
achieve erection.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering work in the radioactive seed procedure began about a
decade ago. The early seed implants were done by surgically
exposing the walnut-sized prostate and inserting the seeds
individually. Today, with special needles and ultrasound guidance,
the procedure still carries some risk of side effects, although
with less chance of them occurring.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of brachytherapy vs. prostatectomy still is
under debate in the medical world. Sarosdy, however, calls the
radioactive seed procedure ``the biggest important change'' in
prostate cancer treatment in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a change in direction,'' he says. ``It's a change in
toxicity of treatment. The length of time to convalesce is markedly
diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarosdy walks out of his office and into the lobby. After
greeting Mary, he escorts Jim into an examining room. The operation
is in two days. During previous visits, Sarosdy and other members
of the medical team poked and prodded their patient, looking for
problem areas and mapping out the planned seed placement.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sarosdy checks Jim's heart and lungs and runs over his
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, your prostate will look something like this when we
get through,'' the doctor says, snapping on the light of a view box
to show Jim an X-ray of a prostate filled with seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been over this,'' Sarosdy says, pointing to the
black-and-white image. ``Your bladder sits right up there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Umm,'' Jim grunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's where the seeds are going to be, in the prostate right
in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we hope it will look like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the cancer?'' Jim asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cancer in your case happens to be in the left apex. But we
do the entire prostate because there is about a 50-percent chance
that you've got cancer somewhere else in the prostate that we don't
know about. We want to make sure one of the others doesn't come
back to bother you.''
</P>
<P>
   When he leaves Sarosdy's office, Jim is all smiles. He pumps the
doctor's hand and says another physician told him ``you got the
best there is'' after learning Sarosdy and Dr. Prestidge were
treating him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was that?'' Sarosdy replies, grinning. ``I'll have to send
that guy a bottle of whiskey.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Mary go home to their routine and to wait. Mary talks to
a son who lives in San Antonio. He wants to take off from work and
sit with her at the hospital during the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't bother,'' she says. ``We've been through lots worse than
this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Jim also tells Mary to stay home. He'll drive
himself to Methodist Hospital for the early morning procedure and
park in the parking lot. Later, Mary can get a ride from a friend
to drive him home.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of Jim's operation, Mary awakens to the sound of a
car pulling out of their garage. It is 4:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jim is gone, on his way to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A big crowd has gathered in the cystology suite at Methodist
Hospital. Also known as ``cysto,'' the pastel-hued room reserved
for urology operations and procedures is named for the cystoscope
that urologists use to peer inside their patients' urinary tracts.
</P>
<P>
   The medical personnel includes Sarosdy and Prestidge, a former
U.S. Air Force radiation oncologist now at the Cancer Therapy &AMP;
Research Center who literally wrote the book on the radioactive
seeds procedure for the Department of Defense. A team of nurses
assists the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, the radiation dosage expert, has set up an aluminum box
with 28 needles, each loaded with several radioactive Iodine-125
pellets. The metal box absorbs their low-level radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wears surgical scrubs, booties and caps, along with
heavy lead aprons that will shield them from the radiation emitted
from occasional fluoroscope images. Since there is no incision, no
one wears a mask.
</P>
<P>
   Jim King is the star attraction. He lies on his back on the
operating table, his legs spread wide in stirrups in the
unflattering position most women are all too familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   Tubes in his nose and throat help Jim breathe. Most of his body
is draped in hospital linen. Anesthesiologist Russell Hern stands
near Jim's head, keeping an eye on vital signs with the help of a
bank of medical monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, Jim sleeps deeply. On the end of the operating
table, between Jim's legs, a special metal stand and carriage hold
the needle positioning guide and an ultrasound probe in place. Two
solid core needles inserted through Jim's perineum also help anchor
the mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   The theme song from the motion picture ``Excalibur''
triumphantly blares on the ``cysto'' sound system as the doctors
continue sowing radioactive seeds in Jim's prostate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what?'' Sarosdy asks, holding one of the loaded
needles in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Delta 3,'' Walker replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Delta 3 is really close to where the urethra is,'' warns
Prestidge, watching the needle's progress on an ultrasound monitor
as Sarosdy slides it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you know when I hit it,'' Sarosdy says, smiling. ``I
think not.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes just under an hour to put all the seeds into Jim's
prostate, a total of 85 pellets.
</P>
<P>
   Sarosdy uses a cystoscope to look for any misplaced seeds in
Jim's bladder. Because of the patient's previous TURP procedures,
the chances are good for a seed to have pushed through his urinary
tract's weakened walls.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors will flush out any loose seeds with water. Even if
they miss one, Jim will be able to pass it with his urine, probably
without feeling it. The sound of French horns and strings playing
the ``Pilgrims' Chorus'' from the opera ``Tannhauser'' fills the
room as Sarosdy pushes the scope into a plastic tube in Jim's
penis.
</P>
<P>
   The tip of the cystoscope has a lighted lens. The picture on the
TV monitor looks like the view from the front car on a roller
coaster, careening down a long, pink tunnel. Sarosdy twists the
scope around, catching glimpses of Jim's bladder and other
highlights of the urinary tract.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is looking good, Brad,'' Sarosdy says to Prestidge. ``No
seeds. I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't trust anything I say today,'' announces Jim's wife,
Mary, sitting in a surgery waiting room at Methodist Hospital.
``I'm on another planet right now.''
</P>
<P>
   She talks on and on about Jim and their life together. On the
night before his operation, Jim told Mary to ``dress up when you
pick me up at the hospital. I want to see a pretty girl when I wake
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary's blond hair is neatly coiffed, her makeup is on and she
wears a Kelly green dress. It brings out the color in her eyes. She
looks tired, however, and she hasn't eaten all morning. She rushed
to the hospital with a neighbor, Billie Mimms, right after Sarosdy
called with the news: Jim is fine. The procedure was a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thank God everything is all right,'' she says. ``Now, I
can breathe again. We've just got to get Jim home and get him well
again. Then we're going to be well for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is 1:45 p.m., four hours after Jim's operation, before
orderlies and nurses finally wheel him into a ``short stay'' room
where Mary can visit.
</P>
<P>
   Jim won't let Mary kiss him. He hasn't had a chance to brush his
teeth. She kisses two of her fingers and presses them to his lips.
Jim kisses them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's my pretty woman,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife at his side, Jim King drove home the day after his
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Mary King is recuperating after successful cataract surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
