<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUPCAKE-BOOK-REVIEW-N     09-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUPCAKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST, THERE ARE THE DOUGHNUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Preparing frostings and deep-fried foods are two of
my least favorite culinary tasks. But thanks to ``The Cupcake Cafe
Cookbook'' by Ann Warren and Joan Lilly (Doubleday, $25), there I
was, first heating and eventually discarding pounds of shortening
to make two batches of doughnuts, then up to my elbows in masses of
soft butter for buttercream.
</P>
<P>
   Decorative cakes strewn with bright buttercream blossoms like
wildflowers in a meadow are the signature of Cupcake Cafe, a little
place that has been on the corner of 39th Street and Ninth Avenue
for 10 years. But in the beginning, as the introduction to this
book explains, it was about doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Ann and Michael Warren, who had worked at the Well-Bred Loaf, a
big wholesale baker, wanted to start their own doughnut company.
They rented what had been a small down-at-the heels bakery and went
into business making not just doughnuts, but muffins and other
breakfast pastries, eventually adding home-style pies and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the help of Ms. Lilly, Ms. Warren's sister, there is a
book that begins with doughnuts, both yeast and cake. Ms. Warren's
efforts to recreate some favorite varieties sent me into the
kitchen to try the cake doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   First, the wheat-and-oat kind that were supposed to be like the
ones that Chock Full o'Nuts used to make but turned out to have
their own nut-rich identity.
</P>
<P>
   Then I moved on to the recipe for Long Island crullers, very
good, plump vanilla doughnuts that were nicely crusty on the
outside. Were they supposed to be Crutchley's Crullers, once a
Southampton, N.Y., icon?
</P>
<P>
   They came close, though I remember the ones from Crutchley's as
having a little less nutmeg. And the instructions did not suggest
frying the centers, or holes, which you could always buy at
Crutchley's.
</P>
<P>
   The tips on doughnut making in the beginning of the first
chapter refer mainly to using professional cutters and fryers, but
some of the information about proper pots and temperatures is for
home cooks. The recipes in the book are all rather basic _ and they
work _ so the pages in my copy will not remain pristine and
stain-free for long.
</P>
<P>
   Though tempted by the bran muffins sweetened with only a bit of
honey and the sticky buns riddled with nuts and raisins, I have
resisted these for the time being. I cut to the chase _ the
cupcakes.
</P>
<P>
   There are five basic cake recipes, which can be baked as either
layers or cupcakes. The dark, intense chocolate cake calls for a
rich batter, made with unsweetened chocolate and cocoa, white and
brown sugars, buttermilk and lots of butter and eggs. It was moist
and exceedingly chocolaty.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate and vanilla buttercreams topped with simple, nonfloral
but attractive rosettes added the finishing touch to mine. The
buttercream, made with sugar syrup and eggs, is the kind used by
professional bakers, not the shortcut combination of confectioners'
sugar and butter that is given in many cookbooks. Detailed formulas
are provided for tinting the plain buttercream.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of the book keeps you busy with frosting and
decorations. The authors advise plenty of practice on a cutting
board or counter top before attempting a special-occasion
extravaganza. One trick: Put the inscription on the cake before the
flowers, so if there's a blunder it can be easily erased.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions for fashioning various kinds of dazzling
flowers would have benefited by more step-by-step photographs of
exactly how each petal or leaf is made, how a lilac blossom differs
from a hydrangea and how to build the random bouquets that spill
over the Cupcake Cafe's cakes and that make them so distinctive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONG ISLAND CRULLERS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Cupcake Cafe Cookbook'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sifted all-purpose flour, plus flour for dusting
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces ({ stick) unsalted butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 pounds solid vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Sift together the flour, baking powder, nutmeg and salt in a
large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Beat the eggs, egg yolk and sugar until thick and light, then
gradually add the vanilla, melted butter and milk.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour the egg mixture into the bowl with the flour mixture,
and toss lightly with a large fork until all of the ingredients are
moistened and a soft dough can be formed.
</P>
<P>
   4. Refrigerate for 30 minutes. Roll or pat the chilled dough to
1-inch thickness on a lightly floured surface. Cut with a 2{- to
3-inch doughnut cutter.
</P>
<P>
   5. Melt shortening in a wok or a heavy 3- to 4-quart saucepan
(do not use a nonstick or enamel pot) over medium-high heat to a
depth of at least 2{ inches. Heat it to 365 degrees. Slip four or
five doughnuts into the hot fat, and fry them for about 2 minutes
on each side. Remove them with a spatula or slotted spoon, and
allow them to drain on paper towels. If desired, the centers can
also be fried.
</P>
<P>
   6. Dust the cooled doughnuts with sifted confectioners' sugar
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 18 doughnuts and 18 centers.
</P>
</TEXT>
