A8185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHARACTER23-C     09-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHARACTER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'PSYCHOBIOGRAPHER' OFFERS ANALYSIS OF CLINTON'S CHARACTER
 &HT;    330&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's unprecedented political
problems are the natural outgrowth of a psychology dominated by
exaggerated self-confidence and the notion that normal standards do
not apply to him, according to a political psychology researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Those traits - not compulsive behavior or ``sex addiction'' -
converged in Clinton's relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky and the controversy that now shakes the presidency,
says Stanley A. Renshon, a New York psychoanalyst and political
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who dislikes boundaries and a man who believes
he should not be held to them,'' Renshon said in an interview.
``This is one of the tragedies of this whole saga. What makes a man
take those chances that he doesn't need to take? The view that he
is entitled to have what he wants, when he wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Renshon thinks Clinton's intellect and a lifelong
habit of outsmarting his adversaries caused the president to
believe - and probably still believe - that he can get out of any
trouble he brings upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that he sits in the White House now, figuring a
way he can get by this. He is probably thinking, 'If I finish my
presidency and I did a lot of good things, in the long run this
other stuff won't matter.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to be one who thinks that without some strong
sanction, something that says no to this behavior, there'll only be
another experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1996 biography of Clinton, ``High Hopes: The Clinton
Presidency and the Politics of Ambition,'' Renshon used publicly
available information to develop a theory that attempts to describe
Clinton's character.
</P>
<P>
   The book received the American Political Science Association's
Richard Neustadt Award for the best book on the presidency and the
National Association for the Advancement of Psychoanalysis Gradiva
Award for Biography last year.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reissued in paperback by Routledge Press.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Renshon sees the president as a man whose character was formed
of three interconnected domains: ambition, integrity and
``relatedness,'' or the ability to interact with other persons.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that a childhood dominated by Clinton's capable and
self-indulgent mother, Virginia Kelley, produced a man with the
ability to invest himself in achieving an unbridled ambition but an
inability to adhere to a core of central values and ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``His moral compass is stuck on ambition,'' Renshon said.
</P>
<P>
   As to Clinton's ability to interact with other persons, Renshon
says that while the president is an unusually charming politician,
his charm is ``manipulative, rather than real.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, he believes Clinton has a self-esteem bordering on
hubris and can perceive little difference between the human being
he wants to be and the one he is.
</P>
<P>
   Biographical psychoanalysis is a controversial subject, with
many psychotherapists arguing that it is impossible to understand a
personality without intensive, one-on-one therapy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But Renshon, a practicing psychoanalyst who sees patients on a
daily basis and also teaches political science at the City
University of New York, says his work is simply a process of
collecting public facts and trying to make sense of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not magic,'' he said. ``I do what any scientist does.
I look at the evidence that his behavior generates and then I try
to make sense of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book, he relies heavily on information in books by
Washington Post reporters David Maraniss (''First in His Class: A
Biography of Bill Clinton'') and Bob Woodward (''The Agenda: Inside
the Clinton White House''), political writer Elizabeth Drew (''On
the Edge: The Clinton Presidency'') and Mrs. Kelley's
autobiography, ``Leading with My Heart: My Life.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has developed a voluminous file of newspaper and
magazine clippings, going back to Clinton's earliest appearance in
Arkansas politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that he's a man who's constantly had problems
with the difference between what he says and what he does,''
Renshon said. ``That is documented in many, many ways. That's fact.
It would be the intellectual equivalent of malpractice not to
recognize this pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
