<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CANDIDATES23-     09-22 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CANDIDATES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: IMPEACHMENT FEVER MAY INFECT PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGNS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton may or may not escape
impeachment, but the path to high office has been drastically
changed by his ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Now that a mechanism exists to extract politicians' secrets via
private lawsuits, future candidates for the White House _ and
perhaps lower offices _ may think twice before running.
</P>
<P>
   The result may be a process that places a higher premium on
moral purity than competence, as impeachment, or the threat of it,
threatens to evolve into just another weapon in the political
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The psychic cost of running for president has been escalating
for some time now,'' said Dennis Simon, a political science
professor at Southern Methodist University in Dallas. ``Now, it's
likely to increase so much that it's probably beginning to
discourage some people.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``politics of virtue'' that is rising from the possible
impeachment of Clinton is likely to give all but the purest some
pause before seeking the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, for example, has tried to slow
speculation about his political future even as he has continued to
top polls of Republicans' choices for the party's presidential
nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has enjoyed a wide zone of privacy as governor. But as a
presidential candidate, he probably will have to answer specific
questions he has refused to answer so far, such as the use of
illegal drugs and why he was once known as a ``major league
party-goer,'' as The New York Times recently described him.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri, the son and
grandson of ministers, is quickly establishing himself as the
favorite GOP son of the Christian Coalition with his ``Traditional
Values'' agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the front-runner is Vice President Al
Gore Jr., who, despite being tainted in recent investigations of
Clinton-Gore campaign fund-raising tactics, maintains a ``Boy
Scout'' reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a standard that presidents should be removed from
office only for acts that seriously harm the nation, a ``fitness
standard'' for being president is ``what's being worked out now''
as Congress moves toward impeachment hearings on Clinton, said
Gregory Wallance(cq), a New York lawyer who was a prosecutor in the
FBI's 1991 Abscam investigation of bribery in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress lowers the bar for what constitutes an impeachable
offense, it will ``almost certainly'' establish a fitness standard
for the next presidential election in which there is no privacy
zone, added Wallance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have never really decided about their presidents _
whether they can be human or they must be role models,'' said
Buckner Melton, a University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill law
professor who has been advising House Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., about the definition of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is impeached for what Melton views as largely private
actions, the next round of presidential candidates will run
campaigns promoting themselves as role models, he added.
</P>
<P>
   And it is unlikely that pre-election confessions will inoculate
candidates against invasions of privacy, said Simon. ``It's OK to
try, but any candidate who does that should still expect a lot of
stories about their private lives,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Melton said the increasing partisanship in Congress's treatment
of Clinton is ``a first sign'' that impeachment may eventually
become a political tool as common as attack TV ads or opposition
research. ``It depends on just how politicized this is going to
become,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Rebecca Brown, a constitutional scholar at Vanderbilt
University's law school, expressed concern that impeachment and
civil suits against sitting presidents could undermine the
constitutional election process.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, lawyers pursuing Paula Jones's civil sexual
harassment suit were able to question the president about former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Clinton's denial of a ``sexual
relationship'' has led Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr to
conclude that he committed perjury, possible grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Future zealots who lose an election will not have to wait
until the next election,'' she said. ``There's a process now where
they can undo the results of an election without having to wait.''
Even Clinton's resignation in the face of possible impeachment
would be ``an affront to the constitutional system,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
