<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH FIGS ARE TO RELISH, OR TO MAKE INTO ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af) 
By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can't say this about too many foods, but I can vividly
remember my first taste of a fresh fig. This is because I grew up
at a time when this plump, succulent fruit was sold almost
exclusively in its dried form.
</P>
<P>
   It took me 20-plus years of life to encounter a fresh fig, and
that was in Rome. In both appearance and taste it was unexpected
and spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Like chestnuts, fresh figs are so common in Mediterranean
countries that they are taken for granted _ there are places where
you can hardly give them away _ and yet I still encounter friends
and relatives who have never tried one.
</P>
<P>
   But now fresh figs are sold not only at fancy markets (where
they cost as much as $3 each), but also at sidewalk stands
throughout Manhattan (where the price runs to a more acceptable $2
a basket), at Italian grocery stores everywhere and even at many
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   And their season is now.
</P>
<P>
   While the best way to eat figs is out of hand _ few fruits are
as luxurious _ there are rewarding ways to employ them in the
kitchen. Add them to sauteed and braised dishes, especially those
made with dark, winey sauces, during the last few minutes of
cooking, and they contribute an element of delightfully sweet
surprise. And cooked figs become even juicier and more tender than
they are when raw.
</P>
<P>
   Figs add liquid to foods rather than absorb it. This tendency
reminded me of two other foods long associated with the
Mediterranean, the olive and the eggplant. Which, in turn, led me
to try treating the fig the way I often do those fruits _ mashing
them with a variety of herbs and spices and making a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   As I experimented with the fresh figs, I was thinking of
eggplant caponata and olive tapenade, both of which are moist,
highly seasoned all-purpose relishes.
</P>
<P>
   There are differences, of course: unlike caponata and tapenade,
fig relish does not make an especially good spread, or even a dip.
And although the herbs used with them are similar, fig relish
remains sweet.
</P>
<P>
   This fig relish really shines as an impromptu sauce. It is
especially successful on grilled swordfish or tuna, but nearly as
good with grilled or broiled chicken (especially dark meat), pork,
lamb or beef.
</P>
<P>
   Note that all of these foods contain some fat: combining the fig
relish with superlean meats or fish like boneless chicken or
flounder produces dishes that seem to lack substance.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is my favorite way to combine figs and seasonings,
but it is hardly the last word on the subject. Possible additions
and substitutions abound.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you can add a tiny amount (a quarter-teaspoon or
so) of minced garlic to the relish, or alternatively, crush a
garlic clove and let it sit in the mixture for a few minutes,
fishing it out just before serving. Add a teaspoon or more of
minced shallots _ or a couple of tablespoons of chopped olives or
anchovies. Lime or mild vinegar can be substituted for the lemon.
</P>
<P>
   You can also change the herbs: a teaspoon of minced thyme or
rosemary in place of the basil makes the relish considerably more
pungent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED SWORDFISH WITH FIG RELISH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh figs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced capers
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 lemon, minced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and fresh black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 large or 2 smaller swordfish steaks, a total of 1{ to 2 pounds
(tuna may be substituted)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped basil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Start a charcoal or wood fire or preheat a gas grill or the
broiler. The fire should be moderately hot, and the rack set about
4 inches from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Gently rinse and stem the figs; chop them into about \-inch
pieces, being sure to catch all the juice. Toss in a bowl with the
capers, lemon zest and juice, 2 tablespoons of the olive oil, salt
and pepper. Set aside while you cook the fish.
</P>
<P>
   3. Brush or rub the fish with the remaining oil, season it with
salt and pepper and grill it, turning once, for a total of 6 to 12
minutes. (Swordfish is done when firm and almost opaque throughout;
tuna can be cooked to any degree of doneness you like.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Just before serving, add the herbs to the fig relish; then
taste and adjust the seasonings. Serve the fish with the fig relish
spooned on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
