<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ The White House denounces the
independent counsel's decision to leave out of his impeachment
report Monica Lewinsky's statement that no one told her lie or
promised her a job in exchange for silence about her affair with
President Clinton. Meanwhile, national polls reflect support for
Clinton remaining in office. By BENNETT ROTH and NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEHOUSE-FISHBOWL (Washington) _ The Starr report and Monica
Lewinsky's grand jury testimony prove that 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue
might be the absolute worst place on the planet for a secret love
affair. Secret Service agents everywhere, watchful reporters, an
electronic locator recording the president's whereabouts, records
kept of every visitor. Where can lovers meet? By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE (Washington) _ The Senate votes 55-44 to kill an
effort to raise the minimum wage from $5.15 per hour to $6.15 by
2000, a measure pushed by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and
other Democrats who contend that the current wage is inadequate. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
