<HEADLINE>
BRIGANTE DEI BARBI: A HEARTY MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brigante dei Barbi, Fattoria dei Barbi, 1994, Tuscany. About
$42.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombini family, owners of the Fattoria dei Barbi, say this
wine was named for a local thief, or brigand, who satisfied his yen
for good food and wine by breaking into their cellars. His name was
Bruscone. No matter.
</P>
<P>
   The wine is a worthy companion to the great Barbi Brunellos and
can take its place among the Super-Tuscans, elite wines employing
nontraditional Tuscan grapes. The Brigante blend is 50 percent
sangiovese grosso, the grape of Brunello, and 50 percent merlot.
</P>
<P>
   The sangiovese spent 24 months in large oak casks; the merlot 14
months in French oak barrels. Brigante occupies a place behind the
three Barbi Brunellos and in front of a less expensive sangiovese
blend known as Brusco dei Barbi.
</P>
<P>
   Brigante is a rich, intense wine with a deep garnet color. It
should have a long life, but it can be enjoyed now and will go well
with hearty late-fall meals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      09-22 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUM ROLL, PLEASE, FOR THE 1995 BORDEAUX 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you plan to buy wine in the next few weeks, and you probably
do, as more wine is sold in the fourth quarter of the year than at
any other time, there is no question about what you should buy:
1995 Bordeaux. It is one of the better vintages of the waning
century.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some prices are incredible. The 1995 Chateaux Margaux and
Mouton-Rothschild are $300 to $350 a bottle, Lafite is around $250
and Petrus at least $1,000. Yes, for a single bottle. But so what?
That some new BMWs cost $90,000 doesn't seem to stop a lot of
people from enjoying Toyotas at $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, first-growth prices are for collectors and investors,
not for mere mortals who actually drink wine. For drinkers, there
are many good buys among the 1995 Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995s are big wines, which means they are dark in color,
rich in flavor and tannic. And yet, remarkably, many of them are
already good to drink.
</P>
<P>
   The writer A.J. Liebling once observed that a great wine has two
publics: one that likes it for its profound qualities as well as
its superficial ones, and another that likes it only because it is
easy to like.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will buy these beautifully balanced 1995s and
happily drink them up. Others will buy a few cases, try a bottle,
congratulate themselves on their astute purchase, then stash the
rest away for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the youthful appeal of these wines, they have the tannins
that will enable them to profit from the complexity that extra
aging gives. Either way, it will be hard to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 vintage in Bordeaux was uniformly good. This is not an
empty compliment. In some years _ 1997 appears to have been one of
them _ unpredictable weather patterns can cause one vineyard to
produce ripe healthy fruit while an adjoining one turns out grapes
that are immature and acidic.
</P>
<P>
   Buying wines from that kind of vintage is like walking through a
minefield: only an expert knows which way to go.
</P>
<P>
   The summer of 1995 was dry and hot in Bordeaux. There was rain
in September, but not enough to dilute the grapes. Merlot, the
principal grape in the right bank communities of St.-Emilion and
Pomerol, was particularly successful. Merlot ripens earlier than
cabernet, which means much of it was less affected by the autumn
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Parenthetically, the river banks referred to here are those of
the Garonne River, which rises in the Pyrenees, and its
continuation, the Gironde, into which it flows north into the
Atlantic. St.-Emilion and Pomerol are inland, hence to the east of
the river. Sauternes, Graves and the Medoc are on the left bank.
</P>
<P>
   Among the right bank 1995s worth considering are, first of all,
Chateau Figeac. This magnificent property in St.-Emilion has
produced some great wines, and this 1995 is one of the best in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the 50th anniversary of the chateau under the
ownership of the Manoncourt family. The wine is concentrated but
rounded and accessible, making it tempting to drink now. It is not
inexpensive, though, selling for $70.
</P>
<P>
   More appealing pricewise and still excellent is Chateau de
Sales, from Pomerol. This one would sell well just on its bouquet;
it is $25. Haut Corbin, from St.-Emilion, also $25, and La Cabanne,
from Pomerol, a few dollars less, are other worthy choices.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, from this part of the Bordeaux spectrum, there is
Chateau Monbousquet. A new owner, Gerard Perse, has changed the
wine's style. It is darker, richer and less accessible when young,
but gives every sign of having a great future. It needs a few years
in the bottle; $40.
</P>
<P>
   In the Medoc, on the left bank, the great star of the vintage is
Chateau Margaux. The people who rate wine by numbers are talking
unhesitatingly about 100 out of 100 for this one. At upward of $300
a bottle and $3,600 a case, most people are going to have to take
the critics' word.
</P>
<P>
   But Chateau Margaux also makes a second wine, mostly from
younger vines, called Pavillon Rouge. It goes for $60; in this
overheated market it is probably worth it. In a good year, any
Chateau Margaux will be a treat.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the commune of Margaux, Sacha Lichine has continued the
drive of his late father, Alexis, to improve Chateau
Prieure-Lichine. The 1995 promises to open into a beautifully
balanced wine in a year or two; it is about $30.
</P>
<P>
   Another praiseworthy Margaux is Chateau d'Angludet, nurtured and
restored by Peter A. Sichel, who died earlier this year. The 1995
is a surprisingly big wine, and a good buy at $25.
</P>
<P>
   One more excellent second wine is Les Fiefs de Lagrange, from
Chateau Lagrange in the commune of St.-Julien. It's not easy to
find a St.-Julien of this quality at this price, $20.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau d'Armailhac, adjacent to and owned by Chateau
Mouton-Rothschild, is a forward wine, good for drinking now. It is
intense, but soft on the finish. It is not the second wine of
Mouton, but a separate entity worth its price of $27 to $30.
</P>
<P>
   In St.-Estephe, the northernmost of the famous Medoc wine
communes, Chateau Phelan-Segur is a best buy. This property has
been renewed over the last six years, and the wine shows it.
</P>
<P>
   St.-Estephe wines are historically tougher and more tannic than
wines from the more southern communes. Phelan-Segur has good
structure and it will last, but its almost rustic quality sets it
apart from its neighbors. It is $27.
</P>
<P>
   These are only a handful of the good wines from 1995. Keep in
mind that the vintage was a good one across the board. At whatever
price you can afford, your chances of getting a good bottle are
excellent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
