<SLUG> BC-MULAN-OPERA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MULAN' COMES TO LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEESUN WEE 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Messages about ``girl power'' aside, Disney's
animated feature ``Mulan'' was decidedly cute. Think Mushu, the
jive-talking dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four months after the summer film release, there's an
opportunity to view a more authentic and serious representation of
the tale _ and you don't have to travel to China.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing Opera will perform ``Mulan, the Woman Warrior'' on
Oct. 24 at CSUN as a fund-raiser for the Northridge-based San
Fernando Valley Chinese Cultural Association.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mulan'' opera will star Shurui Yang, China's top opera
diva and a national heroine who &UR;  &LR; has performed with musical
legends, including Luciano Pavarotti.
</P>
<P>
   Yang, who lives in San Gabriel, said she hopes audience members
won't come anticipating a live Disney, fairy-tale version of Mulan
complete with Asian mysticism and a romantic interest.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ``Mulan'' opera will focus more on Mulan's humility
and her loyalty to her family and country. The legend of Mulan is
based on an ancient poem about a dutiful and brave girl who
disguises herself as a boy to replace her conscripted father in the
Chinese Imperial army.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with Chinese tradition, the Beijing Opera will feature
acrobatics and minimal dialogue, unlike European operas. But the
exaggerated gestures and props help tell the tale. And although the
opera will be presented in Chinese, don't worry, the story will be
spelled out for you in English in the opera's program.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is one of the Chinese cultural association's bigger
fund-raisers. The association also will host a fund-raising banquet
Friday at the Universal Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1971, the nonprofit organization promotes Chinese
culture and heritage and serves families in the San Fernando and
San Gabriel valleys. The group eventually hopes to establish a
proposed $6 million Chinese Heritage Center in the San Fernando
Valley. A site has not yet been selected.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing Opera also will perform ``Mulan'' at the Chao
Performing Center in El Monte on Oct. 18 &UR;  &LR; as another association
fund-raiser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8302 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-MUSIC-LADN     09-22 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING UP TO `SPEED'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; You've seen them on TV, those warm-and-fuzzy
commercials showing Greek fishermen doing spreadsheets on their
laptops, or Bedouin tribesmen miraculously tapping into the latest
cell phone technology.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Anderson has seen this sunny, corporatized vision of the
future, too. But she's not necessarily buying it. Though her
artistic career has been built around cutting-edge electronic
experimentation, Anderson today sounds a bit turned off by all this
talk of a digital brave new world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just was so sick of this incredibly teary version of the
future: `Everyone's plugged in, it's just going to be amazing,' ''
says the 49-year-old high-tech muse, speaking by phone from her
offices in Manhattan's TriBeCa district.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something that rang in the wrong way for me. There's
something a little too much about salesmanship. I thought, `There's
gotta be a catch here. What's really going on?' I mean, I actually
see it as one of the most successful marketing ploys of all time,
to convince people, especially Americans _ you know, it really
works very well on us because everybody's so terrified of falling
behind, we're so competitive. And the whole thing is like, `Unless
your web site's really cool, you're gonna fall behind.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling ambivalent about the shape of things to come is nothing
new for Anderson. When she first pierced the popular imagination,
in 1981, it was with her spooky electronic ode ``O Superman,'' in
which a mother's taped phone greeting morphs into an ominous
presentiment of military-industrial power-mongering.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she repeatedly has addressed technological themes
while partnering with such artistic innovators as musicians Nile
Rogers, Brian Eno, Peter Gabriel and current beau Lou Reed,
performance artist Spalding Gray and film directors Jonathan Demme
and Wim Wenders.
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual about Anderson's latest project, ``The Speed of
Darkness,'' isn't so much its content as its form. The 80-minute,
intermissionless work, which will have its L.A. premiere Friday at
UCLA's Royce Hall, uses only keyboards, violin and digital
processing equipment. Invoking three different settings _ a
theater, a mental hospital and a control room _ ``The Speed of
Darkness'' suggests how these places are fusing into a single
post-industrial techno-culture.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson performs solo on a near-empty stage, riffing about the
future of art and technology in her sing-songy voice, while
touching on cybersex, the Internet and the role coffee plays in
fueling visually overstimulated virtual environments.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her 1995 tour ``The Nerve Bible,'' a multimedia spectacle
that demanded 33 tons of equipment, ``The Speed of Darkness''
employs no minicams, video projections or animated cartoon
chorines. Anderson says the work's subject matter dictated its
stripped-down aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a choice about how it should look and feel, and what
control is,'' she explains. ``I thought, `I'll just do this in the
most simple way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like ``Laurie Anderson Unplugged''?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson demurs. ``Unplugged, you know, for me is like 50
plugs,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't like machines. I, unfortunately, love
them; I adore them. And I equally hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says she wrote ``The Speed of Darkness'' two years ago
as a diatribe about everyday life in the computer age. She expected
that her feelings would change and she'd become more enamored of
computers and the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she's become less interested, drawing a parallel
between the Internet and cable television: 30 million Web sites and
nothin' on. She also finds the digital aesthetic to be either too
``smooth and glitzy'' or else grainy and ``inherently ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I don't love low-res (resolution) stuff, I really do,
like, a great stray pencil drawing, you know, (or) a guitar solo
that's done on just the world's oldest, crummiest guitar but is so
heartfelt it's just amazing. You know, that stuff. But I think
there's so much temptation in digital stuff to make something that
has this corporate aesthetic, that it comes out looking real
heartless.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Anderson's hardly becoming a neo-Luddite. She has
released a CD-ROM and maintains her own Web page. Her beef, she
says, isn't with technology per se, but with its relentless
promotion as a panacea for uncertain times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that even compared to five years ago, certainly to 10,
people are so much more insecure about what they're going to be
doing. Their jobs are sort of, they do one thing for a while and
then that industry falls apart, or whatever. It didn't used to be
so precarious. And I blame that on speed, and on this incredible
sort of personal arms race people have gotten into.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wasn't surprised by a recently published study
indicating that people who spend large amounts of time on the
Internet are more likely to suffer from feelings of loneliness and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about staring at a rectangle in your room _
any rectangle,'' she says. ``I'm on a rampage against rectangles,
because the way they organize the world for you is so horrible. So,
all the projections that I'm doing are onto these really jagged
surfaces or three-dimensional things.''
</P>
<P>
   Her next project, ``Song and Stories From Moby Dick,'' may take
Anderson even further away from the late 20th century.
Co-commissioned by UCLA and co-directed by avant-garde mainstay
Anne Bogart, the piece is an idiosyncratic interpretation of Herman
Melville's mystic yarn about whaling and the nature of God.
Transposing its weirdly beautiful language into music has been ``a
struggle,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had forgotten how totally strange this thing is, I mean so,
so strange! I mean, all these images of enormous heads _ that's the
thing that just struck me when I read it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And this also is something where I'm going to be working with
actors. I've never done that before. So, it's totally terrifying to
me. It's opening in April. Every morning, I wake up in a cold
sweat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
