u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT &LR;      09-22 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SECRETS: LIGHTBULBS TO PLAYING CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knew that electric light bulbs could be used to mold
chocolate cups? Or that hotel shower caps can be used to cover
bowls in the refrigerator?
</P>
<P>
   No one could accuse Dining section readers of lacking in
resourcefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's column about unusual kitchen equipment used by chefs
(``Quick, Hide the Tools. Here Comes a Chef.'') included a request
for readers' own unconventional and ingenious tricks. The responses
flowed in a steady, lively stream.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few home cooks, it seems, who have been hitting the
hardware store and drugstore as hard as chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley B. Dickes uses the lightbulbs to mold chocolate cups as
follows. He oils a bulb _ 60, 75 or 100 watt, depending on the size
cup you want _ then dips it halfway into warm, melted chocolate and
stands it on wax paper. Once the chocolate cools, the bulb can
simply be lifted off.
</P>
<P>
   Nylon mesh paint strainers, Catherine Jones wrote, can be used
when making flavored broths or chai. She fills a stockpot with
water, fits the strainer _ which looks like a mesh sack with an
elastic opening _ over the rim of the pot and loads it with
vegetables and herbs or chai spices. (You may want to wash the bag
before you use it.)
</P>
<P>
   After cooking, she simply lifts out the strainer, and with it
the spices and vegetables. Phyllis Schondorf had a similar
alternative to cheesecloth: she uses a closed pierced spoon, the
kind normally used for steeping loose tea, for holding spices when
pickling or making soups.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Anchin has found a novel way to cut onions without tears.
No, she doesn't keep a piece of bread perched on her tongue or
breathe through her mouth. She wears a snorkel mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearing my snorkel mask,'' she wrote, ``I slice, chop and
grate, and my eyes never tear or burn.'' Never mind the odd view
into her kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most unusual idea came from Ratna Sarkar, who uses
playing cards to spread crepe batter thinly and evenly on a hot
griddle. ``Pour a ladleful of the batter on the griddle and quickly
spread with the edge of the card, using two semicircular sweeping
motions,'' she advised. ``Aces are particularly good.''
</P>
<P>
   Several readers integrated equipment used in their professions
into the kitchen. Dave Gibboni, a chemist, likes to use a
cone-shaped Erlenmeyer flask to steep saffron in hot water: after
all, it was designed so you can swirl a solution without spilling.
</P>
<P>
   He also favors a 10-inch-long, nickel-plated lab spatula, which
has a scoop at one end and a flat blade at the other, for removing
small amounts of dried spices and herbs from narrow-mouthed jars.
And he assured us, there are such places as discount lab equipment
houses where one can buy these things.
</P>
<P>
   Two readers recommended doctors' hemostats, or surgical clamps,
for removing pin bones from fish and for pulling ``boil in the
bag'' vegetables from boiling water. (Kitchen tongs work, too.)
</P>
<P>
   But cooking equipment makers, listen up: not all of your
products end up in the kitchen. On her first dig, Naomi Miller, an
archeologist, used a grapefruit knife to scrape away dirt from
delicate objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've also used little Italian gelato spoons to scoop up
charred plant remains,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The chemist who uses Erlenmeyer flasks in his kitchen takes bits
of his kitchen to the lab, too. He uses butcher's paper for
transferring powders and a wood-handled spatula, usually used for
flipping eggs, as a lab scoop.
</P>
<P>
   One reader relies on her hand-held beater to mix paint. You may
not want to eat whipped cream at her house.
</P>
<P>
   A few readers told me things that might make me want to decline
their dinner invitations. One man cooks salmon in his dishwasher.
Another reader wrote approvingly of her neighbor's practice of
drying salad on the spin cycle in her washing machine. Is it left
with an ever-so-slight scent of Tide?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
