<HEADER>
A8348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARD-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      09-22 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHARD, THE GLORY LIES IN THE GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARBARA KAFKA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Swiss Chard has a secret: it really is a type of beet. But while
the stars of the beet family _ the red beet and the Italian
red-and-white beet _ are valued primarily for their bulbous roots,
chard's glory is its magnificent greenery.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, every inch of its stems, ribs and leaves can be used in
a variety of dishes that seem just right for fall and winter
nights.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have known this for centuries. In Provence and on the
Ligurian coast of Italy, where the local dialects use the same
words for ``chard'' and ``beet,'' young stems and leaves are cut up
and sauteed like spinach, and larger plants are steamed or boiled
and dressed with a hollandaise sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Since chard is so versatile, it is a shame to waste any of it.
Leaves not used in a recipe can always be cut in strips and added
to bean or legume soups. Extra stems can be blanched and served
like asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of chard. Swiss chard is green with very
pale green to white stems and ribs. Ruby chard, has green leaves,
but red stems and ribs. Swiss chard is milder in taste, while ruby
chard's flavor is more beetlike.
</P>
<P>
   When chard is young, you can cook the leaves with their ribs,
which branch out into the leaf from the stem. But the ribs become
thicker and more fibrous in older, larger chard and take more time
to cook than the leaves, so it is best to separate the leaves from
the ribs before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Simply cut the leaf away from the central rib with a knife, or
hold the stem in one hand and with the other hand fold the leaf
over the rib and pull the leaf away from it.
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of chard on the stem can vary from 10 to 20 ounces.
Cooked leaves shrink; a pound cooks down to a cup. Stems stay
roughly the same size after cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The rich chard gratin given here should be made with the white
stems of green chard, both for looks and for a more elegant flavor.
The chard tart, typically Provencal, can be made with red or green
leaves or a combination of both.
</P>
<P>
   Sauteeing the stems of ruby chard in an anchovy and garlic paste
makes for a Mediterranean dish that is sweetened just a bit by
raisins. This dish looks nice served on colorful plates. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRUYERE CHARD GRATIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound white chard stems, trimmed and cut in }-inch pieces (4
cups)
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   8 grinds fresh black pepper
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated Gruyere cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter to grease pan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place rack in lowest level of oven. Heat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring 10 cups of water to a boil. Add chard stems. Cover
until water returns to a boil. Uncover, and cook for 10 minutes.
Strain in a colander, then run under cold water to refresh. Leave
stems in the colander for 10 to 15 minutes to drain.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, in a medium bowl, combine the eggs, cream, salt,
pepper and cheese. Add drained stems. Mash together by hand until
very well combined.
</P>
<P>
   4. Grease a 9-inch glass pie pan. Scrape mixture into pan with a
rubber spatula. Bake for 35 minutes, until top is golden brown.
Remove, and cool for 5 minutes. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RUBY CHARD STEMS AND ANCHOVY SAUTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ruby chard stems (leaves reserved), trimmed and cut
across into }-inch pieces (about 4 cups)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, smashed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 2-ounce can flat anchovy fillets, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pulp from a large tomato, peeled, seeded and chopped, or
canned whole tomatoes, drained, squeezed and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring 10 cups of water to a boil. Add chard stems. Cover
until water returns to a boil. Uncover, and cook for 10 to 12
minutes. Strain in a colander, reserving { cup of liquid. Run stems
under cold water to refresh. Leave in colander for 10 to 15 minutes
to drain. May be prepared 3 to 4 hours ahead up to this point.
</P>
<P>
   2. Soak raisins in reserved { cup liquid for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a mortar, crush garlic with the kosher salt to make a
paste. Add anchovies and fennel seed. Crush until fairly smooth.
Place raisins with liquid in a microwave oven, and cook for 1
minute, or simmer on top of stove until softened. Drain raisins.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a medium saucepan, combine olive oil with blanched stems,
garlic-anchovy paste, raisins, tomatoes and pepper. Cook over low
heat, stirring, until warm throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWISS CHARD TART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the pastry: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 \-ounce package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon canola oil, plus extra to oil 10-inch pastry ring
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups flour, plus extra for rolling out dough &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { pound Swiss or ruby chard leaves (reserve stems), washed,
dried and roughly chopped (about 8 cups)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice, cooked 8 minutes until barely firm
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 3{-ounce button fresh, soft goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   \ pound prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon milk or cream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. To make dough, sprinkle yeast over \ cup warm water and let
sit for 5 minutes. There should be some bubbling action after a few
minutes. If nothing happens, the yeast is old and should be
discarded. Combine remaining ingredients for pastry in a small
bowl. When ready, add the yeast-water mixture. Combine the two
mixtures. Turn out on a flat surface, and knead, just until
combined. If dough is too wet and sticky, add a little more flour.
Form dough into a ball, return to bowl, cover with a kitchen towel
and put in a warm place for 1 hour or until doubled in volume.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, make filling. In a food processor, pulse all the
ingredients for filling until well combined, scraping down the
sides of the bowl once or twice. Mixture should not be a puree, but
should have texture. Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   3. About 20 minutes before cooking the tart, place rack in the
center of oven. Heat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   4. Lightly oil a 10-inch pastry ring. Place it on a baking
sheet. Lightly oil the section of sheet enclosed by ring. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. Divide dough in half. Roll out bottom crust to a 12-inch
circle, using extra flour as needed. Twirl dough onto the rolling
pin, and set into the oiled ring. Tuck dough snugly into the ring.
Leave the dough edges up along sides of ring. Lightly prick dough
with a fork, so that it will not rise too much while cooking.
Spread the filling evenly over the dough.
</P>
<P>
   6. Roll second half of dough into a 10-inch circle. Place circle
on top of filling and smooth with fingers. Fold edges of first
crust over second to seal in filling. Trim flap to about \-inch
width, and remove any extra dough. Pat down gently with a fork to
make a firmer seal.
</P>
<P>
   7. For the glaze, beat egg with milk or cream (or water). Brush
glaze over crust. Using the sharp tip of a knife, make 3 slashes in
the crust to act as air vents. Cook for 40 minutes. Remove from
oven, and gently slide tart off onto a flat plate. Serve warm or at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 10-inch tart.
</P>
</TEXT>
