<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV29-     09-22 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BOY, ONE GIRL, TO GO PLEASE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday Sept. 29)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if there weren't enough choices to make in life, just in
cable channels and pizza toppings alone, now comes a way to select
a Mike or Molly.
</P>
<P>
   I know couples who can't agree from one day to the next what
color the new couch should be and cannot imagine them ever
committing to the sex of a child.
</P>
<P>
   What a responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Long before you get around to having children, you imagine
yourself with some cute little kid who will adore you forever, and
sometimes in your daydreams you see this as a boy child and
sometimes as a girl child. Depends on the mood, maybe even the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   And then you get pregnant and you dream even more and eventually
out pops one or the other, although many people opt to know ahead
and not wait for the big surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But even knowing in advance so you can croon ``Zelda'' to your
round belly is a lot different than placing your order for her
ahead, as is now scientifically possible through a newly tested
``sperm sorting'' technique.
</P>
<P>
   Even considering the notion gives some people the shivers. Ask
parents if they could have chosen their baby's sex would they and
what would it be, and they lower their voices as if the very
subject threatens the wonder of their beloved one in the Beastie
Boys T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   It's out of bounds for a lot of people to imagine. This is a
mystery they're not willing to tamper with. ``Isn't that what life
is all about - not knowing?'' said the father of a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   He likes the words of poet Khalil Gibran: ``Your children are
not your children. They are the sons and daughters of Life's
longing for itself. They come through you but not from you. And
though they are with you they do not belong to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say that gender selection will serve families who
carry a genetic disease that afflicts only one sex. This is
reasonable, but when they talk about helping couples who want
``family balance'' it begins to sound more like a designer baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``A boy for you and a girl for me'' is a nice line in an old
song, but to calculate such a perfect pairing sounds yuppie-driven,
like acquiring a Jeep to go with the town car.
</P>
<P>
   I understand wanting the experience of raising a daughter after
you've had a son, or vice versa, but part of wanting is hoping. And
then loving who you get.
</P>
<P>
   There's a couple in Southern California with three daughters who
decided to try one more time for a son. (``Trying for'' is
something that would disappear under high-tech baby selection, but
this couple decided to gamble the old-fashioned way.)
</P>
<P>
   They ended up with quadruplets. Four girls. Now a total of seven
girls. It sounds like an apocryphal story about stopping while
you're ahead, but it's true. I've seen family pictures and they all
look happy, though a bit dazed.
</P>
<P>
   How would you choose if you could? What if you were feeling
under pressure from the relatives to produce a specific gender?
What if you felt like being contrary?
</P>
<P>
   What if you voted boy/girl just because you thought that's what
your darling wanted?
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in recent memory in American culture when boy
babies were favored over girl babies. Of course, we all know this
is ludicrous, but discrimination still exists against girls in some
places.
</P>
<P>
   Like in China. What if a Chinese cultural preference for boys
was supported by a guaranteed boy baby technique? Would it become
an all male-nation? And then stop?
</P>
<P>
   There are so many things couples need to talk about before
deciding to become parents, why add one more issue?
</P>
<P>
   What if you had one of those partners whose natural response is
``I don't care, you decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Would you make a list of good and bad points, like you do when
trying to decide whether to buy in the country or the city?
</P>
<P>
   The perks are pretty much interchangeable now that we've
discovered that girls can toss the ball around and boys like to
cook. Daughter or son, equal value. Either one can become a doctor,
inherit the farm, run the family business and pass on the family
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so glad I didn't have that choice,'' said a mother of two
boys and a girl. Had it been up to her she thinks she might have
opted for all girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think with girls you'll have that bond, someone to hang
out with, the mother-daughter fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   But she says, ``I would have missed out on so much,'' including,
she says, ``the chance to raise evolved boys.'' As it turned out,
of her three children, the tightest bond today is with her younger
son.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't get nice surprises like that if you thought you
knew best and scheduled ahead.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for the Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
