<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-`NEWSRADIO'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN THERE BE LIFE AFTER DEATH FOR `NEWSRADIO'?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being forced to patch holes is never a comfortable place for
writers, producers and stars to be creatively, but what hasn't been
out of the ordinary for the cast and crew of ``NewsRadio''?
</P>
<P>
   This quirky workplace comedy about a struggling radio station is
well-known for a past colored with near-cancellation experiences
and last-minute reprieves, with bolting cast members and public
exchanges with network presidents over what producers considered
second-class treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as it moves into a fifth season without scene-stealing Phil
Hartman, the show must use the season premiere Wednesday to deliver
to its devotees a respectful cinematic eulogy while providing
newcomers with the essence of its irreverent style.
</P>
<P>
   Unaccepted departures always leave a creative team a bit puzzled
about how to proceed. But the shooting death of Hartman this year
severely altered the series' creative balance, and in light of
Khandi Alexander's departure last season, a question remains
whether it can regain its footing.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Lovitz, a close friend of Hartman's who worked with him on
``Saturday Night Live,'' will step in beginning next week as Max
Lewis, a painfully insecure and, they hope, very funny reporter.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wednesday's episode, written by creator Paul Simms, fans
will find the half-hour somewhat heartwarming, if not all that
funny or clever in light of the episode's delicate balance.
</P>
<P>
   They knew the character's absence had to be explained, so ``Bill
Moves On'' finds the saddened staffers of WNYX dealing with Bill's
(Hartman) sudden death of a heart attack while, of all things,
watching television. (What he was watching isn't explained.)
</P>
<P>
   Dave (Dave Foley), Matthew (Andy Dick), Lisa (Maury Tierney),
Beth (Vicki Lewis), Joe (Joe Rogan) and Jimmy (Stephen Root) are
seated at the station's conference table, heads bowed, trying to
steer clear of awkward silence.
</P>
<P>
   The episode unfolds with their reaction to Bill's death, hanging
mostly on Matthew, who is convinced that Bill is not dead but
either running a boat charter company in Afghanistan or teaching at
a scuba diving school in Nepal. Bill had always told the gullible
Matthew of this ``secret life'' he would one day lead.
</P>
<P>
   Near the episode's end, Alexander pops up, having flown in from
London. That's when Dave pulls out an envelope given to them by
Bill's lawyer, who was asked to do so if anything ever happened to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dave is reading this to you,'' Dave reads, ``I have either
been fired or passed away. Since my formidable talent would
preclude the former, I'd have to assume that the latter is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Each cast member reads aloud letters directed to them. Tears
flow. Jokes are flat and somewhat forced. Devotees won't care. The
episode fades as Bill's desk is ravaged by staffers and carried off
by two movers with Jimmy sitting on top of it. Bill's chair sits
alone, as the screen fades.
</P>
<P>
   Since milestones, like the death of a sitcom's key player,
usually get our attention, NBC expects a sizable audience for
Wednesday's episode and for next week's introduction of Lovitz.
</P>
<P>
   After that, ``NewsRadio'' will be on its own. The next few weeks
will be scrutinized by NBC. If the moderately rated series (No. 68
last season) can't sustain the additional audience it's likely to
receive, perhaps the plug needs to be pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Strange way of looking at it. But this is, after all,
television. Only so much mourning, and it's back to business as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
