<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLMONEY-COLOR23-COX     09-22 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-COLOR23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE AREAS DOMINATE POLITICAL GIVING, STUDY SAYS
 &HT;    570&AMP;add. With POLMONEY-DATA.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The vast majority of contributions to federal
candidates come from areas that are wealthy and white, says a study
to be released Wednesday by Public Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That could cause political neglect of the needs of minority
neighborhoods and communities, according to the Washington-based
nonpartisan group, which advocates public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's useful to have a study documenting what we already sensed
_ that the money comes from one place and the people of color live
in another,'' said Selena Walsh, director of policy and
communications for the League of United Latin American Citizens.
``Public Campaign's study shows why people in the community should
support campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The national study of contributions of $200 or more in 1995 and
1996 from every ZIP code with more than 1,000 residents shows:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the 2,479 ZIP codes where more than half the residents are
of Hispanic origin or black, Asian, American Indian or other racial
minorities, the average contribution per person to candidates for
the White House or Congress was $1.60.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the nation's average ZIP code, where 76 percent of the
residents are non-Hispanic whites, the per-person average was 61
times as high _ $97.79.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One out of every 1,250 people in minority-dominated ZIP codes
gave $200 or more. In the average ZIP code, the ratio was much
higher _ one out of every 416.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Only some of the difference was accounted for by income
levels, which averaged $9,046 per person in minority ZIP codes, but
$12,381 in the average ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 98.9 percent the 27,000 people in Georgia's 30314
ZIP code, in and around the Clark-Atlanta University Complex, are
African Americans. Only 12 gave $200 or more.
</P>
<P>
   But in the much wealthier 33480 ZIP code in Palm Beach, Fla.,
where nearly 96 percent are non-Hispanic whites, 816 of the 6,600
residents gave that much.
</P>
<P>
   One result could be that politicians will spend more time with
the people from Palm Beach than those from the Atlanta
neighborhood, Public Campaign maintains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawmakers (in tough races) no longer have the luxury to
talk to their one-time friends and neighbors about school safety
and child care and job security,'' says the study. ``Instead, they
have to shake hands at high-donor cocktail parties where they'll
hear about capital gains and inheritance taxes and the negative
impact of a minimum-wage hike.''
</P>
<P>
   William McNary , legislative director of Citizen Action of
Illinois, who helped coordinate the study, said Wednesday, ``The
study shows that campaign finance is just as segregated as many
other areas of society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that we in the disenfranchised communities must
move campaign finance reform beyond the do-gooder approach of good,
earnest, well-intentioned white liberals,'' McNary said. ``Getting
special interest money out of politics should be seen as a natural
extension of the political empowerment movement that got rid of the
poll tax and other financial barriers to participation.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's results are consistent with a study released earlier
by scholars from four universities who interviewed a sample of more
than 1,000 generous donors to federal parties and candidates. They
concluded that most big donors are rich, conservative men, and 95
percent of the donors are white.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``In a crude way, ZIP codes probably do capture different kinds
of communities,'' said political scientist John Green of the
University of Akron, who helped conduct the earlier study for the
Center for Responsive Politics. ``It's a geographic variation on a
position that others have taken: If money is a sources of access
and influence, then people with less money are going to have less
influence in political contexts where money counts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, people of color who live in heavily minority
neighborhoods have one advantage over those in neighborhoods with a
more even mix, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that they are concentrated in one community,
they can become visible to office-seekers who want their votes, and
get action on their concerns,'' Green said. While voter turnout is
dismal in most poor neighborhoods, ``you could probably make a case
that a hyper-mobilized community can have more influence than
others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
