<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      09-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAST PORK WITH POTATO-TURNIP GRATIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 This is the sixth of eight columns by Charlie Palmer, chef and
owner of Aureole in Manhattan. Judith Choate collaborated.  
 By CHARLIE PALMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I grew up on a dairy farm in central New York, and the first
cold snap still makes me yearn for the hearty, soulful foods of my
childhood. My mom had a stick-to-your-ribs approach to cooking _
which was fine by me and my six brothers and sisters _ and her
braised pork chops with mashed potatoes and cream gravy was one of
our favorite fall meals.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, pork was a different meat. Rich and fatty, it was
the sort of everyday food that rarely appeared on the menus of fine
restaurants. Today, hogs are being raised for more flavor and less
fat.
</P>
<P>
   And along with many other chefs, I now use pork in both hearty
and light dishes. Its tender texture lends the meat to a quick
roast or braise, and its mild flavor makes a good match for most
vegetables and a great variety of herbs and spices.
</P>
<P>
   In this dish, I moved only a little bit away from family
tradition by combining a simply roasted pork tenderloin with a
creamy French gratin.
</P>
<P>
   The leanness of this cut allowed me a bit of extravagance with
heavy cream and cheese. To liven things up, I added turnips to the
gratin for a contrast in taste and texture: cooked, the turnips
become lighter and add a sweet, astringent counterpoint to the soft
butteriness of the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   As a final bit of tinkering, I infused the cream with roasted
garlic for sweetness and depth.
</P>
<P>
   On the plate, the dish cries out for the color and balance of
fresh greens; try some sauteed kale or spinach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROAST TENDERLOIN OF PORK WITH POTATO-TURNIP GRATIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Butter for greasing dish
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves roasted garlic (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 pound potatoes, peeled and cut into [-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1 pound turnips, peeled and cut into [-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter at room temperature, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated Emmenthal cheese
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   3 pork tenderloins, 10 to 12 ounces each, well trimmed of all
fat and silver skin
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups chicken stock or low-sodium canned broth
</P>
<P>
   } cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   6 fresh thyme sprigs, for garnish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Lightly butter a round gratin dish, 10 by 2 inches. Preheat
oven to 425 degrees. Whisk roasted garlic into the heavy cream
until very well blended; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large mixing bowl, toss potato and turnip slices until
they are well combined. Using a clean kitchen towel, pat the slices
until they are very dry. Spread half the mixed potato and turnip
slices evenly across the bottom of the gratin dish. Sprinkle them
with 2 tablespoons of the butter, \ cup cheese and nutmeg to taste.
Repeat with the remaining potato and turnip slices, butter, cheese
and nutmeg to taste. Pour the garlic-flavored cream on top.
Sprinkle with bread crumbs. Bake until vegetables are tender and
the top is golden, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. While gratin is baking, prepare pork tenderloins: season pork
with salt and pepper to taste. In a large nonstick ovenproof saute
pan, heat canola oil over medium-high heat. Add tenderloins to pan,
and sear, turning frequently, until well browned on all sides,
about 6 minutes. Transfer tenderloins to a plate, and drain excess
oil from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   4. Return tenderloins to pan, and add stock, { cup of the wine,
1 teaspoon of the minced thyme and 1 teaspoon of the minced sage.
Stir to blend. Place saute pan in the oven (with the gratin). Roast
until an instant-read thermometer registers 150 degrees when
inserted into the thickest part of the meat, about 15 minutes; the
pork should be slightly pink in the center. Remove pan from oven,
and let pork rest 5 minutes. Transfer to a platter, and carve
crosswise into \-inch-thick slices. Cover loosely with foil, and
keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   5. Strain pan juices into a small saucepan, and skim off excess
grease; set aside. Place saute pan over high heat, and add
remaining \ cup of wine. Cook, stirring constantly, until pan is
deglazed, about 1 minute. Pour deglazing juices into pan juices.
Place saucepan over high heat, and bring to a boil. Lower heat, and
simmer about 3 minutes. Add remaining 1 teaspoon thyme, remaining 1
teaspoon sage and the parsley. Adjust salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   6. Cut six equal wedges of potato-turnip gratin, and place one
in the center of each of six warm dinner plates. Place three to
four slices of pork tenderloin around one side of the wedge on each
plate. Drizzle pan juices around plate. Garnish with a sprig of
thyme, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To roast garlic, trim the top third from a large head of
garlic. Rub the head with olive oil, wrap in foil and bake at 325
degrees until the cloves are soft, about 45 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
