<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ON TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's tortured videotaped testimony
before a grand jury about his sexual encounters was one of the most
disgraceful moments in the history of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But exposing it to the world on Monday changed nothing, really.
</P>
<P>
   We already knew more than we should about his strange, reckless
behavior with Monica Lewinsky. We already knew that the president
had a slippery way with words. We already knew that it is sex, not
Whitewater, that is Clinton's biggest vulnerability. We already
knew the independent counsel's office is obsessed with bringing him
down.
</P>
<P>
   And now that we've seen the president's contorted performance,
the impeachment process rolls obliviously along, responding only to
its own momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cannot stop it, no matter what he does or says, so long
as he occupies the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, trapped in the constitutional process, will not stop
it either. Whatever the ultimate public impact of releasing all the
gory details of the president's sexual encounters, the political
system demands that he be punished, in some way. Humiliation is not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency, no matter how temporarily diminished, will
survive this, as it has survived other traumas.
</P>
<P>
   But the survival of its occupant is another matter. His fate
depends upon a question that has no clear answer: Does a president
who is a lying lecher so demean the office that he deserves to be
impeached?
</P>
<P>
   The president's testimony was sufficiently nimble to allow him
to escape immediate political disaster. He was obviously
obfuscating, but his interrogators failed to nail him outright on
anything that might prove perjury or obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact he was asked only about women and not Whitewater or
other less titillating investigatory issues tends to confirm public
suspicion that this is not about serious crimes but merely about
sex.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he realized that the videotape was likely to
be made public, and he was accordingly cautious and controlled. He
did not reach the White House in the first place by being timid or
tongue-tied.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the simultaneous release of the written transcript
of Lewinsky's grand jury testimony helps the president against a
charge of suborning perjury, since she insists he neither asked her
to lie nor promised her a job in return for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   The voters are not clamoring for the president's removal. His
job approval rating actually went up after Monday's testimony, from
60 percent to 66 percent in the latest USA Today/CNN Gallup poll.
This is despite the fact he's not fooling anybody: 81 percent said
they thought he was lying when he claimed to believe his dalliance
with Lewinsky was not a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But that only briefly stalls what is going on here. He could tap
dance through Central Park to mass applause and still not shake the
legislative process initiated when independent counsel Kenneth
Starr sent his report advocating impeachment to Capitol Hill. All
Clinton has managed to do is live to fight again another day, and
the battles get tougher and tougher and harder and harder to
tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   What his testimony demonstrated is not pretty. It shows us that
Clintonspeak is an exercise in the use of language to create an
illusion, in order to conceal reality and mislead listeners. He
denied having sex ``as I define it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians have noted for years that Clinton habitually
says what he thinks they want to hear, but in such an opaque way
that he can later claim to be misunderstood if they are
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   This is a useful political talent and not quite the same thing
as directly lying. But it is basically dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   Now the House Judiciary Committee must decide: Does it amount to
perjury? If it meets that legal definition, is it an impeachable
crime?
</P>
<P>
   The core of the problem is that the answers will be slow in
coming. The House will soon release more Starr documents and is
likely to vote next week to authorize impeachment hearings,
probably to begin after the November elections. This could go on a
very long time.
</P>
<P>
   It is too much, already. We think and talk about nothing else.
We may even run out of new Monica jokes and begin repeating the old
ones. Clinton should resign and spare the country any more of this
shameful stuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
