<HEADER>
A8393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUDANINTRO20-COX     09-22 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDANINTRO20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't avert eyes from the horrors of famine in Sudan
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This story was different.
</P>
<P>
   And, after a morning spent in the grassland of southern Sudan,
amid the keening of the starving people, it came to me that I was
different, too.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, I was observing all I could, making notes and
gathering information. But my conduct so startled me that I took
out my notebook and wrote these words: ``I was not allowing myself
to make eye contact. It was more than language. It was more than
just the bloodshot eyes, covered with crawling flies. I didn't want
to look into their minds. I didn't want to feel what they felt.''
</P>
<P>
   I have seen dead people before _ stacked in the back of a truck
in Nicaragua, laid out in a hospital yard in the Dominican
Republic, incinerated by mobs in the streets of Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at dead people is one thing. Looking at dying people is
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to look into the eyes of a dying man and have no
answers for him, or of a mother whose daughter is dying in her arms
and mumble, ``Sorry, nothing I can do''?
</P>
<P>
   But if I wasn't there to try to understand the experience of the
Sudanese people, to understand what they as human beings were going
through, then I had come a long way for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I had to ask. I had to stop averting my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So recently I interviewed mothers of children who were weakened
by hunger, ravaged by disease, in danger of dying.
</P>
<P>
   I squatted in front of a woman preparing to bury her daughter
and asked how the little girl had died. My eyes searched out those
of a woman who had just buried her husband. I could never
understand, but I wanted her to know I was willing to try.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult work, a wrenching experience. I walked from the
burying field back toward the small United Nations camp where I had
pitched my tent. I was overheated, dehydrated and disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   I searched the sky for afternoon thunderclouds. I wanted nothing
so much as a cloudburst.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped, took out my notebook and wrote these words: ``Praying
for rain _ an end to the heat, an end to the thirst, an end to the
work of interviewing the dying and bereaved.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, in the U.N. camp, Yohannes Tecle, an Eritrean
UNICEF official, cooked up a pot of sticky rice. In the sauce, he
put pretty much everything he had left. I think there were peas in
there, and some tuna, and a melange of other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   I ate greedily. Then I slept.
</P>
<P>
   People have asked how anyone can eat in the midst of famine. I
can say only this: When you're hungry, you eat. When you're tired,
you sleep. The business of living goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing my two cups of rice with the 21,000 people clustered
around the village of Ajiep would have accomplished nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, I learned a woman a few feet from my tent died,
huddled under an empty grain bag, in the night's cold rain. I could
not have invited the population of southern Sudan into my tent.
</P>
<P>
   All I can do is carry on my work. These stories _ and, more
vividly, the stark and haunting photographs by Rich Addicks _ are
meant to show you as best we can what we saw in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't avert your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
