<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WINE-TASTING-ART-9     09-22 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WINE-TASTING-ART-955(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINE COUNTRY GROWS IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Schedule of wine tastings is at end of story.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the sixth day, New Yorkers do not rest. Saturday,
supposedly set aside for leisure, is the day for picking up the dry
cleaning, dropping off shoes for new soles, buying groceries and
taking the cat to the vet. It is a workday.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another Saturday out there, unknown to most New
Yorkers. All over the city, sandwiched between the dry cleaners and
the shoe-repair shops, are wine stores, and on Saturday afternoons
many of them are opening Spanish riojas, or California chardonnays,
or Australian shirazes, and pouring them, free of charge, for
anyone who takes the trouble to stop in.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the vinous Saturday has become a ritual, as
cars stream across the Golden Gate Bridge and head toward Napa and
Sonoma for a weekend of tasting. New York does not have the
vineyards, but it sure has the wine stores, dozens upon dozens of
them, and shrewd customers, after making a few phone calls and
drawing up a little list, can map out a personal wine trail, as I
did on a recent Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the wine-tasting season was just gathering steam
after the summer recess, the pickings were pretty attractive. To
kick things off, the Chelsea Wine Vault, in the Chelsea Market, was
offering three sparkling wines from Mionetta, a winery near Venice.
On a smarmily humid afternoon, a well-chilled prosecco hit the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the store, customers were lining up for red
and white Lillet, the French aperitif. The clock was ticking,
however. Skipping Lillet, I headed northward to Best Cellars on the
Upper East Side, which draws a crowd every Saturday afternoon, when
it pairs a wine with food. The wine du jour was a lush Alsatian
pinot blanc by Willm, matched with foie gras mousse spread on
triangles of toasted brioche. That, folks, is a deal.
</P>
<P>
   From Best Cellars it was barely 100 steps to Wright on Third
Avenue, where customers were being treated to a fume blanc,
cabernet sauvignon, chardonnay and merlot from Estancia, a
California winery. It was a useful trip, a chance to assemble a
profile of the winery at zero cost.
</P>
<P>
   Stop No. 4, at Acker Merrall &AMP; Condit on West 72nd Street, was a
must. A representative from Penfolds and Lindemans was presenting a
lineup of Australian chardonnays and cabernet-shiraz blends. The
ace up her sleeve was a bottle of Penfolds Grange, 1993 vintage _ a
$165 item that in real life I admire from a safe distance. Now,
instead of studying the label, I simply asked for a taste and, for
one thrilling moment, my palate lived beyond its means.
</P>
<P>
   The Grange encounter seemed like a fitting finale to a very
productive couple of hours. I had tasted wines that were new to me.
I had picked up interesting bits of information along the way. I
had emerged a better, more rounded human being. And the experience
had not cost me a dime.
</P>
<P>
   In a city of more than 7 million people, it might seem insane to
offer free drinks, but that's exactly what happens every weekend in
wine stores all over Manhattan. This civilized custom did not
become possible until five years ago, when the state Legislature
lifted the restriction that said stores could open only bottles of
New York state wine.
</P>
<P>
   Soon wineries and the wine merchants began capitalizing on a
splendid opportunity to show off their wares, get more traffic
flowing through the shops and sell more wine. For customers, the
free tastings offer a chance to learn a little and to test-drive a
bottle before taking it home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It educates our customers,'' Christopher Cree, a managing
partner of the Chelsea Wine Vault, said. ``The person who comes in
and has never tasted a prosecco has suddenly discovered a new area
of sparkling wines.''
</P>
<P>
   Wineries and their distributors use the tastings to grab the
attention of fickle consumers and to break through the marketplace
clutter. ``It's a great vehicle for introducing your product to
people who may not know about it,'' said Anne Marie Harrison, a
representative of Franciscan Wine Merchants, who was pouring
Estancia wines from California at Wright. ``This makes people feel
comfortable about spending the money for the wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Some stores feature a single wine, others lay out a selection.
Some highlight the wines of a single maker, while others establish
a theme, pouring, say, a selection of cabernets from different
makers. In many cases, a representative from the winery or the
company that distributes the wine is on hand to pour, answer
questions and observe consumer reactions to the product.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very low-key. Most shops simply place a handmade sign
in the front window, inviting one and all to step inside and sip a
little chardonnay, pinot grigio or syrah. But collectively, this
service adds up to an amazing variety of wines on offer, at a
variety of prices, from workaday Portuguese tintos to up-and-coming
Chileans to more-than-respectable Bordeaux and Burgundies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the action begins Friday night, as some wine shops,
especially ones in midtown, try to lure the after-work crowd, and
it picks up again on Saturday afternoon, with some shops getting
started as early as noon, but most doing their tastings between 3
and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing intimidating about the protocol. Like the
supermarket employees who hand out pizza puffs on a toothpick, the
winery representatives set up a small table, uncork their wines and
ask passing customers if they'd like to have a taste.
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is yes, they pour an ounce or two of wine in a
glass, or a plastic cup, briefly explain what's in the glass, and
wait for the customer to express an opinion or ask a question. No
question is too stupid. They are happy to talk all day about their
favorite subject.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
