<SLUG> BC-AMERICA-DATES-THE-PREZ-(HUMOR)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A COUNTRY IS DATING ITS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' humor feature _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted three times _ into
the ``l'' lifestyle news, ``k'' commentary and ``a'' national news
files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARILYN SUZANNE MILLER 
 c.1998 Marilyn Suzanne Miller  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As a single woman, I can't help but look at America's
relationship with President Clinton as being like certain dating
relationships I've had, where it gets to be ``all about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``all about him'' relationship starts off equal. (In
America's case, you give him your vote, he gives you women in the
cabinet, pro-choice policies, a Middle East peace process.)
</P>
<P>
   Things seem to go fine for, oh, six years until suddenly he gets
busy. He can't meet you someplace. He's at the office all the time.
He's having problems he can't explain. It's not about you, America
_ he needs his space.
</P>
<P>
   So then, for eight whole months America is hysterical and on the
phone with everyone else in America. America just doesn't ``get''
him.
</P>
<P>
   America quizzes him endlessly _ and when America does, he gets
peeved. So, except for the special prosecutor (who, frankly, I
would've liked to have in a few of my dating relationships), our
country is having exactly the same kind of affair I often do. It's
``all about him,'' and America is stuck sitting home alone night
after night eating ice cream and watching John Gibson on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   As a human woman, I don't like guys playing with my head. How
about a whole country's head? No wonder Americans are upset: We're
having a very dysfunctional relationship with whom? Not some guy _
the federal government! And most of us don't like to be hysterical
about the president of the United States all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, I find myself lying in bed, staring wistfully at the
ceiling, endlessly wondering if my president really cares about me,
or if he just wants to go down well in history.
</P>
<P>
   There's another element to this ``dating relationship'' many of
us are deluded about. As a country dating its president, America
seems to fit the mold of the ``trophy wife.'' I mean, in country
terms we're a hot number. The approval ratings for this president,
then, seem to be mostly about our desire to stay with him and go on
as a ``power couple.'' Young. Attractive. Well off. Nice GNP. (I
mean, so far, in the relationship.)
</P>
<P>
   I think America realizes that there are a lot of world leaders
whose calls we'd never even return let alone seriously discuss
impeaching! That's something to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Dating analogy aside, self-centeredness is what ticks off
Americans most _ not the sex, not Ken Starr (the poor man's Terry
Southern), not even the $40 million (which just would've been blown
on bombers or IRS forms or something just as stupid.) It's the
``All About Him'' presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is this president and the Congress, and the House (the
members of which also seem to have ``all about me'' relationships
with their constituents) have long ago spurned their ``significant
other'' (America) in favor of it being all, and endlessly, about
them (and Geraldo Rivera). It's their air time, their election
campaigns, their pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what. America doesn't want to be laughed at by
France, lectured by England or repeatedly stood up by you. How we
got into this relationship I don't know _ we certainly didn't meet
the federal government at a health club _ but it's assuredly got to
end. We can't take it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, it should be all about us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Marilyn Suzanne Miller has won three Emmy Awards for her
comedy writing.)
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
