<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WINE-TASTING-ART-2     09-22 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WINE-TASTING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: favorite subject.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the Chelsea Wine Vault, for example, Enore Ceola, a
representative from Mionetta, was stationed behind an upright wine
barrel, pouring his bubbly treats as customers lined up like kids
at a Good Humor truck. As he poured, he gently felt out his
audience. Did they know what prosecco was? Excellent! Did they know
the difference between frizzante and spumante? When brows furrowed,
Ceola explained: Frizzante has half the effervescence of spumante.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are good because they ask questions,'' he said.
``This is positive. Italians think they are supposed to know
everything about wine, so they won't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wright _ where an outside awning announced ``Wine Tasting
Today: Please Come In!'' _ Ms. Harrison and an assistant stood
behind a small table off to one side of the store and appealed to
customers as they strolled by. ``Would you like to try some wine
today?'' they asked.
</P>
<P>
   Warily, most customers accepted the invitation, and listened
politely as Ms. Harrison announced that the Wine Spectator had
recently given Estancia's fume blanc an 88 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the afternoon, Ms. Harrison had to fend off a couple
of wise guys who had apparently been doing some heavy tasting
already. ``Would you care for a dry white wine?'' she asked one of
them. Woozily, he said, ``I prefer a wet wine.'' (For the record,
most wine shops will indulge a repeat taste, but they are not
inclined to let customers put a foot up on the rail and plant
themselves for an afternoon of serious drinking.)
</P>
<P>
   Booze hounds form a very tiny minority of the free-tasting
population. The typical Estancia taster that day was more likely to
sip, and then tentatively offer an assessment, which, nine times
out of 10, was ``nice.'' A little like that 88 from the Wine
Spectator, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Some people felt obliged to be a little more creative. Sipping
the Estancia merlot, one customer looked toward the ceiling,
silently communed with his taste buds for a moment, and said,
``This tastes smoky, uh, smokyesque.''
</P>
<P>
   It made sense that Wright, a bargain hunter's wine store with a
youthful clientele, was offering the accessible, modestly priced
wines of Estancia, selling at the store at prices ranging from
$9.99 for the chardonnay to $15.99 for the merlot.
</P>
<P>
   At Acker Merrall, the wine presentations are geared toward a
more knowledgeable customer, and on Saturdays the store likes to
pop the cork on at least one big gun _ a Mouton-Rothschild from
Bordeaux, say, or Harlan Estate from the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular Saturday, the store was pairing two everyday
wines by Lindemans, Bin 65 chardonnay ($6.99) and Bin 45
cabernet-shiraz ($8.99), with Penfolds Padthaway chardonnay
($14.99) and Bin 389 cabernet-shiraz ($22.50). The legendary Grange
was a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word got out on the street,'' Patrick Boland, the store's
managing director, said. ``I think a lot of people organized their
day around the Grange.''
</P>
<P>
   Acker Merrall, more than most wine stores, fine-tunes its
tastings. On Friday nights, with an eye to the customer who wants
to grab a bottle for dinner, it pours one wine, usually under $25.
Saturdays are more ambitious. By keeping a sharp eye on customer
reactions, Boland said, he can develop a flavor profile for his
regulars and give them tips on wines they might like.
</P>
<P>
   Other wine stores have also tinkered with the basic tasting
format. Best Cellars, whose top price for a wine is $9.99, offers a
free tasting every night, featuring one wine that connects to a
weeklong theme. One week the store featured wines that would help
explain the role of tannins. Another week, the lesson was
fortification, or the addition of alcohol to wines like port and
sherry to arrest fermentation and provide extra backbone.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturdays, Best Cellars brings in a chef or cookbook author
and matches wine with food, a concept that draws as many as 300
customers from 2 to 4 p.m. The foie gras mousse, prepared by Scott
Snyder of the Astor Restaurant and Lounge, drew nicely. Past
offerings of Washington state oysters and caviar nearly touched off
a stampede.
</P>
<P>
   The Chelsea Wine Vault, in addition to weekend tastings, keeps
about 12 bottles at the ready on a copper-sheathed shelf near the
cash register, a kind of wine bar where customers can sample before
they buy. This may be the best deal in town. Recent offerings
included a Beringer white zinfandel ($6.99), an Argentine malbec
from Alto de Madrano ($8.99) and a single-vineyard zinfandel from
Hendry Ranch in the Napa Valley ($24.99).
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Wines and Spirits, in midtown, once teased its
customers by pouring a mystery wine from a brown bag with the
promise that anyone who could identify it would get the bottle
free. No one came up with the answer, and no wonder. It was a
rarity, a white wine from the tiny Provencal island of
Porquerolles, made from the obscure rolle grape.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping in a wine from Porquerolles may be cheating, but no one
complained, in conformity with the unwritten law of all such
tastings: No grousing allowed. If the wine is good, you call it
great. If it's mediocre, you say it's fine. You may even mean it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a rule of thumb,'' Boland of Acker Merrall said. ``All
wine tastes better when it's free.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
