<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-092     09-22 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-0923-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGES POUNDS DOMINICAN REPUBLIC, HAITI AS FLORIDA BRACES FOR
STORM
 &HT;    EDs: May need updating after 6 p.m . EDT.
 &HT;    With HURRICANE-HAITI-0923.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hurricane Georges pounded the island of Hispaniola,
shared by the Dominican Republic and Haiti, and pushed late Tuesday
toward Cuba and the U.S. mainland, distracting South Florida
residents who began preparing for the fury of this hurricane
season's deadliest storm.
</P>
<P>
   Packing winds of 120 mph at midday, Georges was expected to
devastate Hispaniola, home to 15 million people, many of whom live
in substandard housing.
</P>
<P>
   The formidable storm knocked out power and forced residents into
shelters across the densely populated Dominican Republic, where two
people were killed by downed electrical lines.
</P>
<P>
   Georges had paralyzed the Dominican Republic's capital of Santo
Domingo by mid-afternoon, where it flooded streets, uprooted trees,
and whisked away tin roofs and satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials expected a high death toll in Haiti due to
the unsafe living conditions of thousands of desperately poor
Haitians.
</P>
<P>
   In Haiti's capital of Port-au-Prince, which is surrounded by
slums, fragile communities of cardboard homes cling to slippery
hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``People die here even when we just get a heavy downpour, one
that's not even a tropical storm, so this could be catastrophic for
us,'' said Michelle Karshan, a spokeswoman for Haiti's President
Rene Preval.
</P>
<P>
   When Tropical Storm Gordon, a much weaker system than Georges,
struck Haiti in 1994, hundreds of people were killed in mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, forecasters predicted Georges could affect
southernmost Florida by late Thursday or early Friday. The National
Hurricane Center in Miami was expected to place parts of South
Florida under a hurricane watch late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Workers placed shutters over the windows at City Hall in Key
West, while authorities advised all visitors and non-residents of
the Florida Keys to evacuate the island chain who's only connection
to the mainland is a two-lane highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate most of the evacuations will occur on
Wednesday,'' said Billy Wagner, an official with the Monroe County
Emergency Management Service. ``Anyone who's got plans to visit the
Keys should postpone them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warnings were posted for Haiti, eastern Cuba, the
southwestern Bahamas and the Turks and Caicos islands, and a
hurricane watch was in effect in parts of Cuba and the Bahamas on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expected to issue a hurricane watch some time
Wednesday for South Florida, where residents packed the stores in
search of supplies such as batteries, flashlights and water.
</P>
<P>
   Georges was expected to weaken somewhat as it moved off the
shore of Hispaniola, but not below hurricane strength. As of 5 p.m.
EDT Tuesday, Georges had sustained winds of 110 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Still, forecasters at the National Hurricane Center predicted
that Georges would pack much less of a punch than Hurricane Andrew,
which caused billions of dollars in damage in densely populated
South Florida in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and early Tuesday, Georges wreaked havoc across the
northeast Caribbean, killing at least 10 people, mostly due to
mudslides and collapsed roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Boasting gusts of up to 130 mph, the hurricane dumped two feet
of water in the mountains of Puerto Rico, while bending palm trees
and flipping small aircraft like they were pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, all of the U.S. territory's 3.8 million people were
without power, and 80 percent of people were without running water,
while more than 25,000 people sought refuge in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The airport in San Juan, Puerto Rico was able to operate Tuesday
for relief flights, but remained closed to other traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting from ground zero,'' Puerto Rico's Gov. Pedro
Rossello said of recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin
Islands disaster areas, authorizing immediate release of federal
recovery aid. Scores of federal and Red Cross officials fanned
across the island to assess damage, expected to soar to hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In Antigua, the storm split open government-built houses and
ripped corrugated roofs off hundreds of other homes. In St. Croix,
winds shoved a 50-foot sailboat ashore and destroyed part of the
boardwalk. In St. Kitts, about 70 percent of the houses suffered
damage, as did the hospital, airport, and police station.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
