<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-HAITI-0923-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAITI PLAYS HOST TO GEORGES INSTEAD OF RICH AND FAMOUS
 &HT;    With HURRICANE-GEORGES-0923.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For Haiti, it was to be the delegation of its dreams.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the impoverished nation had planned to host first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, media mogul Ted Turner, investor
George Soros, and William Gates II, the father of America's richest
man, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the well-heeled notables have big bucks, and Haiti
desperately needs them.
</P>
<P>
   But now the ferocious Hurricane Georges has crashed the party
before it even began.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by the Clinton-organized, 75-member delegation --
officially dubbed ``Civil Society's Contribution to Democracy'' --
has been postponed to some time in October due to the storm,
according to Haitian government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought all of these people were going to come visit here,
Ted Turner and Hillary Clinton, and we were excited,'' said
Michelle Karshan, a spokeswoman for Haiti's President Rene Preval.
``These people were going to talk about giving money and support to
various projects in Haiti, which we really need.''
</P>
<P>
   David Harwood, a spokesman for the United Nations Foundation,
the Washington, D.C.-based charity created to designate U.N.
programs to receive Turner's funding, said Turner had planned to
send a foundation representative to Haiti, rather than go himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation has some activities going on that might relate
to Haiti and the Caribbean, and we wanted to talk about these,''
Harwood said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Clinton said she was not sure that the trip
would be postponed, adding that a final decision would be made by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's visit to Haiti would have been the first time
many of the delegation members, including Clinton, have visited the
country.
</P>
<P>
   However, Soros, the Hungarian-born international financier,
opened a foundation in Haiti last year -- the Knowledge and Freedom
Foundation -- to promote democracy and youth projects with a $2
million annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   The economy in this country of seven million people has
foundered since 1994, when a U.S.-led invasion ousted military
dictator Raoul Cedras and restored the democratically elected
Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Haiti's annual per-capita income is $250, about one-tenth
the average of Latin America and the Caribbean. Infant mortality is
almost twice the regional average, while malnutrition affects about
half of all children.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear exactly what the delegation planned to do during
its visit besides meet with non-governmental groups to discuss
judicial reform and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   But what was clear was that Haiti would be picking up a carpet
of debris left by Georges rather than rolling out a red carpet for
its much-anticipated guests.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
