<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-HOUSE-FISHBOWL-     09-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-HOUSE-FISHBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHITE HOUSE GOLDFISH BOWL IS A LOUSY PLACE FOR SECRET LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secret Service officers thought something fishy was
up at times when their radio crackled reports of President Clinton
moving toward the Oval Office just after Monica Lewinsky entered
through the White House gate.
</P>
<P>
   And moments after her departure, especially on weekends, Clinton
would return to the White House residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like clockwork,'' one officer said. Another
officer wanted to bar Lewinsky's entry but was told by a supervisor
it was none of his business whom the president saw.
</P>
<P>
   That was just one of dozens of instances documented by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr in which the electronic and human
eyes and ears of the White House recorded the comings and goings of
Clinton and his young lover.
</P>
<P>
   No agent, no official, no reporter, no electronic device ever
caught them in an erotic act. But Starr's enormous compilation of
evidence _ everything from second-by-second logs of the president's
movements to grand jury testimony of agents stationed outside the
Oval Office _ proves one thing: The White House is a goldfish bowl,
a lousy place to carry on an illicit love affair.
</P>
<P>
   If the serious possibility of impeachment were not at stake,
much of the evidence could form the basis of a zany Marx Brothers
movie or some other slapstick comedy of a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the two devised a cover story that Lewinsky was
delivering papers to the president when she visited him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal secretary, Betty Curry, dialed Lewinsky's
telephone number for Clinton so that the log of calls made through
White House telephone operators wouldn't show that the president
had dialed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton was nervous that detection literally was just
around the corner. On December 28, 1997, at their last face-to-face
meeting, Lewinsky noticed during a kiss that Clinton didn't have
his eyes closed. Instead, he was looking out the window of his
private study.
</P>
<P>
   When she complained that he wasn't being romantic, the president
said ``Well, I was just looking ... to make sure no one was out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had reason to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Without drawn curtains on windows leading out to the Rose
Garden, their trysts were fair game for Secret Service officers or
other White House personnel outside.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the sight through a window of a gardener made them retreat
from the study. Most of their encounters took place in a hallway
and bathroom, both windowless.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kept a door ajar so he could hear approaching footsteps,
Lewinsky testified. During one interlude, they were interrupted by
White House aide Harold Ickes, who was calling ``Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``jetted out into the Oval Office and I panicked,''
Lewinsky recalled. She hustled through a door leading to the
president's dining room and down the hall past the chief of staff's
office. In a phone call afterward, Clinton ``was a little upset
with me that I left,'' Lewinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their subterfuge, Lewinsky made a point of entering
the president's office suite through one door and exiting through
another door.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ``no (guard) would know how long I had been in there,''
Lewinsky told the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the agents' grand jury testimony, however, Lewinsky
was not fooling anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty commonly known that she did frequent the West
Wing on the weekends,'' former Secret Service officer Lewis Fox
testified. Another officer, William Ludtke III, saw her exit from
the pantry near the Oval Office looking startled.
</P>
<P>
   Another agent, William Bordley, reported stopping Lewinsky
outside the Oval Office because she lacked a White House pass.
Clinton opened the door and reassured the agent that her presence
there was OK. She went in.
</P>
<P>
   Still another agent, Robert Ferguson, recalled Clinton telling
him he was expecting ``some staffers,'' and watching as Lewinsky
arrived saying the ``president needs me.'' Ferguson rotated to a
position outside the Oval Office window and saw the two enter the
study where he couldn't see them.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky in particular wanted to avoid White House aides who
viewed her with suspicion. One of them, Clinton's personal aide
Stephen Goodin, was concerned over appearances and said Lewinsky
should not be alone with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   So during their meeting on Feb. 28, 1997, according to Lewinsky,
Currie chaperoned them to the study _ and then left the room.
</P>
<P>
   Another staffer, then-Deputy White House Chief of Staff Evelyn
Lieberman, chided Lewinsky for violating a policy forbidding
interns from hanging around the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky replied that she was no longer an intern.
</P>
<P>
   After an unidentified Secret Service agent told Lieberman that
Lewinsky was considered a ``nuisance,'' Lieberman ``decided to get
rid of her,'' according to Lieberman's grand jury testimony.
Lieberman quickly arranged for Lewinsky to transfer from the White
House to the Pentagon in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not put an end to the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In one now-infamous episode, Lewinsky arrived at the northwest
gate on Dec. 6, 1997, to deliver a letter and gifts to Clinton.
Currie had said Clinton was meeting with his lawyers and instructed
Lewinsky to wait.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting, she was informed by uniformed Secret Service
officers that Clinton actually had television personality Eleanor
Mondale in his office. Lewinsky stormed away in anger and called
Currie from a pay phone to complain about misinforming her.
</P>
<P>
   Currie then called the guards and chastisted them for revealing
that Clinton was seeing Mondale. Later, Clinton told the Secret
Service watch commander, Capt. Jeffrey Purdie, not to discuss the
incident. Purdie said Clinton told him: ``I hope you use your
discretion,'' Later, Purdie told his subordinates: ``Whatever just
happened didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, the Clinton administration fought a losing
battle to prevent Secret Service personnel from testifying. The
result, one former agent said, is to turn the White House into even
more of a goldfish bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been part of our culture not to talk about what
goes on,'' said Bob Snow, a former Secret Service agent and past
president of the retired Secret Service agents association. ``But
this is one step further in that `fishbowl' direction. In fact,
it's two or three steps beyond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
