<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-22 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE END OF THE RAINBOW, A POT OF PASTEL MUSHROOMS  
 ABRUZZI TO ZABAGLIONE  
 CHEDDAR IN CHEESECLOTH  
 SALMON FROM THE WILD  
 EAST SIDE PATISSERIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No dank forest glen could produce beautiful, frilly
oyster mushrooms in sherbet colors: delicate peach and lemon
yellow. These mushrooms, coming into markets now, are grown in
straw by Hopewell Organic Foods in West Grove, Pa., from spores
that originally came from Korea, where the colorful mushrooms are
prized.
</P>
<P>
   But once sauteed, their colors fade, like those purple string
beans that turn green when heated. The peach mushrooms become
salmon-beige and the yellows take on a grayish hue. The colors hold
better if they are blanched quickly in boiling water, drained and
tossed with a dressing to use in a salad. And they have an engaging
flavor, with a fruity, almost perfumed touch of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   The mushrooms are sold loose at Fairway, 2127 Broadway (74th
Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132d Street), for $9.78 a pound, or
in three-and-a-half-ounce packages for $3.29. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't know the difference between the amatriciana and arrabbiata
when you are in your favorite Italian trattoria? Help is on the
way. Not one but two dictionaries of Italian culinary terms have
been published in the last few months: ``Dictionary of Italian
Cuisine'' by Maureen B. Fant and Howard M. Isaacs (Ecco Press,
$27.50) and ``The Dictionary of Italian Food and Drink'' by John
Mariani (Broadway Books, $17 paperback).
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dictionary of Italian Cuisine'' has more entries,
extensive cross-referencing and hundreds of terms in regional
dialects. But the definitions are often not as detailed as in the
Mariani book, which also has some recipes, more explanation of the
cuisine of various regions and, for each entry, a guide to the
pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   Each book gives general pronunciation rules in its introduction,
and the Fant and Isaacs book has a handy English-Italian index.
Neither book will fit easily into your pocket, so you will have to
bone up before you dine out. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Shelburne (Vt.) Farms went back in time and started
wrapping some of its wheels of raw-milk Cheddar in cheesecloth,
instead of sealing them in wax, for aging. The cheese, above, is
dark ivory and firm but buttery, with a complex flavor at once
herbaceous and fruity. It has a sturdy, mottled rind the color of
concrete beneath its layer of cloth.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese, aged a little more than a year, is available on a
limited basis at Balducci's, 424 Avenue of the Americas (Ninth
Street), and at Murray's Cheese, 257 Bleecker Street (Cornelia
Street), for $18.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Pricey for Cheddar? ``Even though the cloth wrapping allows the
cheese to age faster than regular Cheddar, which is sealed in
Cryovac, then waxed before it is shipped, it is more
labor-intensive to make because you have to keep turning the wheels
and scrubbing the rind,'' said Elizabeth Skinner, who handles the
cheese marketing for Shelburne.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the cheese ages in the cellars of Major Farm in Putney,
Vt., but Shelburne Farms is building its own aging cellars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the dozen or so kinds of smoked salmon on the market, most
are made from farm-raised fish. But occasionally the leaner,
richer-tasting variety made from more muscular wild salmon is
available.
</P>
<P>
   Now through November, wild Scotch salmon imported by a company
called Sir John Wincroft will be available at a number of shops:
Todaro Brothers, 555 Second Avenue (30th Street), for $35.96 a
pound; Marche Madison, 931 Madison Avenue (74th Street), for $47.96
a pound; Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560 Broadway (Prince Street), $48 a pound;
Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third Avenue (71st Street), for $51.96 a
pound, and William Poll, 1051 Lexington Avenue (74th Street), for
$60 a pound. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cheap rent and spacious kitchen, a store on the
Bowery did not work out for Carolyn Giacolone, who opened Fina
Pastry there last year. So she closed the shop and reopened it as
Carolyn's, 1516 First Avenue (79th Street).
</P>
<P>
   The narrow, homey storefront has eight little tables, and the
kitchen is set up to allow her to offer soups and sandwiches in
addition to delicious apple- and prune-filled pastries, biscotti,
tarts, muffins and doughnuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
