<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, from the perspective of the weather satellite, an
impressive cluster of showers and thunderstorms associated with an
area of low pressure swirled over the western Gulf of Mexico. On
Wednesday, with steering winds blowing from east to west over the
region, the cluster of showers and storms will move inland to south
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, an expanding area of showers and thunderstorms
will affect parts of the southern Plains, particularly sections of
Kansas, as increasingly warm and moist air is drawn northward and
forced to rise over a thin layer of retreating cooler air.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms, some heavy, will erupt
over parts of Florida, with the most active storms likely to form
across central parts of the state. Localized street flooding is
likely.
</P>
<P>
   An autumnal air mass will build into the northeast states,
carried on brisk winds from the northwest that will average 15 to
25 mph. A few chilly showers will dampen extreme northwest New
England before migrating northeast to the Canadian Maritimes.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, sunshine will soften the chill of brisk Canadian
winds, though some fair-weather cumulus will develop over mountains
from the Poconos and Catskills of northeast Pennsylvania and
southern New York to the Green and White Mountains of Vermont and
New Hampshire. Frost is likely Wednesday night in mountain valleys
of the northeast states, with fog forming over river valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a few showers will escort a cool front across the
upper Middle West from the central Rockies to the northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Curious Comparison
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of similar intensity and path, Hurricane Georges has
been likened to Hurricane Hugo, which came ashore near Charleston,
S.C., on September, 21, 1989. On Monday (September 21), as
Hurricane Georges bore down on San Juan, Puerto Rico, 10.52 inches
of rain fell at Charleston, breaking the city's record rainfall for
the date. Curiously, Charleston's previous record for the date was
nearly 5 inches of rain with Hurricane Hugo. On Tuesday, in the
spirit of strange comparison, rain at San Juan, Puerto Rico,
tallied 5 inches as Hurricane Georges passed close to the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
