   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BAUMAN _ ROSWELL, N.M. _ First Mark McGwire, then Sammy
Sosa, caught and passed Babe Ruth and Roger Maris. But neither will
catch Joe Bauman. The real home run king of professional baseball
is 76 and retired in Roswell, N.M. Bauman hit 72 home runs in 1954
for the minor-league Roswell Rockets in the Longhorn League.
Bauman, who never played in the majors, also hit .400 and drove in
224 runs that season in 138 games. He made $4,000 _ good money for
the minors _ and also received a free ham for each homer. But the
real bonus came when fans passed money through the backstop fence
after each blow. He collected about $900 when he broke the minor
league record with homer No. 70. He bought a gas station in Roswell
and forgot about the big leagues. Then 32, he said he couldn't
afford to leave Roswell. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH LOCATOR MAP.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BAUMAN-BIO _ With stats.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BAUMAN-LIST _ Chart of all-time professional home run
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   JOYNER-OBIT _ At the height of her popularity, former track star
Florence Griffith Joyner commanded the attention of everyone in her
presence. Martin-Floreal was reminiscing about Griffith Joyner
after finding out she had died of an apparent heart seizure
September 21 in Mission Viejo, Calif., at the age of 38. (Lance,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CARS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Before there was a Motor Mile, back
when U.S. 183 was considered in the far reaches of Austin, before
Austinites had ever heard of a car named KIA, downtown was the
place to car shop. In the early 1900s, East Fifth Street, Texas,
was lined with dealers. Today, they've all but disappeared.
(Breyer, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON _ DAVIE, Fla. _ This stuff _ a shiny 3-0
mined from a muddy 21-0 victory against the Pittsburgh Steelers _
is real gold. That was Johnson's analysis after having a day to
examine the three-game gem he now holds in his hands _ and will
continue to hold for two weeks until the Dolphins resume play
against the New York Jets. (Woods, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GRILLED-DOLPHINS _ DAVIE, Fla. _ Jimmy Johnson plopped down
in a chair for his day-after meeting with the newspaper reporters
who cover the Miami Dolphins. Before taking any questions, the
unusually relaxed Johnson (being 3-0 heading into a bye week will
do that) steered the conversation toward the pressure of being an
NFL head coach in 1998 and how, because of increased media
coverage, it is different than when he took charge of the Dallas
Cowboys in 1989. (Woods, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MCCOY-COLUMN _ CINCINATTI, Ohio _ ``I sat out Sunday's game
because Cal sat out,'' Eddie Taubensee said with a laugh. ``Hey,
2,632 straight games? He deserves a day off. I can't imagine that.
On our team we see Barry Larkin and Bret Boone try to play every
day . . . but every day for 16 years? Wow.'' (McCoy, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LONGHORNS-GOAL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ With Rice up next and the
meat of the Big 12 South schedule looming ahead, the push starts
now toward the Texas Longhorns' primary goal. Win state. (Wangrin,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-BEATABLE _ Greg Maddux is missing his targets by
inches. To the Atlanta Braves, he might as well be missing by a
mile. The Braves, who begin a quick two-game series tonight at Pro
Player Stadium against the Florida Marlins, have won their division
in each of the past seven seasons, including this one. But they've
won the World Series only once (1995). (Graziano, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-PANTHERS-WORRELL _ It's an unlikely scenario, but if the
Florida Panthers ever decide to assign right winger Peter Worrell
to an East Coast Hockey League team, fans of the Pensacola Sky
Pilots would love to have him. (Biggane, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
