<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-JABBAR-COACHING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABDUL-JABBAR TO COACH AT ARIZONA RESERVATION SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Kareem Abdul-Jabbar has won championships. He set the
NBA's all-time scoring record. He fought Bruce Lee in the movies.
Now, he wants to coach.
</P>
<P>
   His first job?
</P>
<P>
   Alchesay High School.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Alchesay, a 3A school in Whiteriver that features a
6-foot-2 center and sits on the White Mountains Apache Reservation
in northeastern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar, who fell in love with the area the past three
years while doing research for a book on the buffalo soldier,
expressed interest this summer with the school and recently sent a
letter of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the school board approved Abdul-Jabbar to come on as
a volunteer assistant basketball coach under Raul Mendoza, who
guided the Falcons to the state championship game last season.
</P>
<P>
   The towering figure plans to leave his swank Beverly Hills,
Calif., home next month and lease a place on the reservation for
the basketball season, said Alchesay Principal Herve Dardis.
</P>
<P>
   The reservation, already a basketball hotbed, has been abuzz
since word came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody, all the players, the whole town, are excited,''
said senior guard Kyle Goklish, a returning starter. ``I think a
lot more kids will be coming out. He has a lot to offer us through
basketball and through life, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar could not be reached for comment. He is not
expected to stay beyond the basketball season, Dardis said.
</P>
<P>
   Dardis kept Abdul-Jabbar's interest in coaching at the school
quiet until this week, wanting to make sure the former Los Angeles
Lakers center was sincere on his promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met the guy once,'' Dardis said. ``I think he wants to
coach. I know he wants to help young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He mentioned to me he had a conversation with (retired Gen.)
Colin Powell on the need for people to serve as volunteers and help
young people. I think the seed was planted there.''
</P>
<P>
   But why Alchesay?
</P>
<P>
   Dardis said that Abdul-Jabbar has a friend who lives in the area
and did some research of the culture there for a non-fiction book.
He also was a guest speaker during a ribbon-cutting ceremony two
years ago for the opening of the school's activity center.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to coaching, Abdul-Jabbar will speak to classrooms
about the history of the culture he learned through his research,
Dardis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he will share more than just history,'' Dardis said.
``I'm sure he'll impact some kids on the lessons of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, Abdul-Jabbar was accused of assault and
arrested at a Toronto airport for possession of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't respond to that right now,'' Dardis said about
Abdul-Jabbar's run-ins with the law. ``I don't want to speak for
the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza said he met Abdul-Jabbar in July and found him to be
humble. He said they discussed basketball philosophies. They had
breakfast at a Whiteriver restaurant, which became something of a
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people saw him and started coming up to him,''
Mendoza said. ``People wanted his autograph. He had cards made with
his autograph on them and handed them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the parking lot, and people driving by were
stopping their cars to get a better look.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was polite about it, but I see we're probably going to have
to make some arrangements, some provisions, so this doesn't get too
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza's teams have traditionally played before packed
gymnasiums on the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Now?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not going to be there to see us,'' Mendoza said.
``They're going to be there to see him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
