<P>
   Y2K-SETTLEMENT _ ATLANTA _ An Atlanta company was involved in
what is being touted as America's first Y2K settlement. It was
$250,000. A Detroit-area grocer sued Tec America, an American
subsidiary of Tokyo Electric Co., part of Toshiba Group, for not
fixing a computer system that crashed whenever a credit card with
an expiration date of ``00'' was scanned. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-BELLSOUTH _ FCC gives the wireless cable operators
permission to provide interactive services, including Internet
access. We see what BellSouth thinks and how it will respond.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONVERGENCE _ NORCROSS, Ga. _ Convergence Corp., a small private
suburban Atlanta software developer, plays the software game,
turning up a timely product to enhance a new breed of digital cell
phones, as well as the text pagers such as ones now marketed by
BellSouth. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Surprise: Not all Y2K date problems need to be fixed. By
targeting only the critical date operations, a Waltham, Mass.,
company enables its customers to save money and quickly repair
mainframe software. (Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PAXNET _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Nielsen expects to put out
Paxson national numbers today. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post). 12.
</P>
<P>
   GRIEG _ Q: The builder for my house is using finger-jointed wood
and I am not happy with that. I asked if this is inferior to the
normal wood and they said it's actually better. In my opinion, the
reason for using finger-jointed wood is to save money, not for
structural superiority. What is your advice? And other
consumer-interest questions. (Grieg, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
