<HEADER>
A8525 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     09-22 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO THE BOTTOM OF `THE FULL MONTY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What's the story behind the expression ``the full monty''?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.H., Holden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Like the ``whole nine yards,'' ``monty'' is an expression
with more than a dozen poorly documented but plausible
explanations. The expression appears to have been coined in the
1980s, so the absence of a reliable history is even more puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   The expression means ``the whole thing,'' and one theory links
it to ``die volle Montur,'' a German phrase meaning ``full dress
uniform.'' Another describes it as a corruption of ``the full
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary's editor, Neil Fulton, a participant
in the Internet discussion group alt.usage.english, has researched
the phrase exhaustively. ``As a result,'' he writes, ``I am able to
state, categorically, definitively, and authoritatively, that I
don't know where it comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary researchers are asking the public for
help in finding evidence of the origin of ``the full monty,''
especially anything that predates 1986. If you can help, write to
Oxford English Dictionary, Oxford University Press, Great Clarendon
Street, Oxford OX2 6DP, or send an e-mail to oed3(at)oup.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My nephew was recently killed when a train at a crossing hit
his truck. Is there a group I could join that helps stop these
senseless accidents?
</P>
<P>
   _ E.W., Keller, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Operation Lifesaver is a national, nonprofit organization
that focuses on training people to speak on crossing safety, said
Marmie Edwards, vice president of communications for the group.
Last year, its 3,000 speakers gave presentations to 2 million
people at schools and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which has about 16,000 train crossings, ranks No. 1 among
states in these types of collisions. Last year, it recorded 54
deaths, 197 injuries and 421 collisions. Illinois was next, with
about half those numbers in collisions and deaths, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there were 461 crossing deaths last year, 3,865
collisions and 1,540 injuries. To contact Operation Lifesaver, call
(800) 537-6224; write to 1420 King St., Suite 401, Alexandria, VA
22314; or visit the World Wide Web site www.oli.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son-in-law told me my oleander plant is poisonous. Is that
true?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.W., Bedford, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Oleanders are extremely poisonous, according to information
provided by the Texas A&AMP;M University horticulture program. The
plant contains a deadly heart stimulant similar to the drug
digitalis.
</P>
<P>
   ``So powerful is this poison that a single leaf of an oleander
can kill a child,'' according to the program's report ``Poisonous
Plants and Plant Parts.'' ``Many people have died merely from
eating steaks speared on oleander twigs and roasted over a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about poisonous plants, write to the Texas
A&AMP;M University Horticulture Program, 202 Horticulture/Forest
Science Building, College Station, TX 77843-2134 or visit the World
Wide Web site aggie-horticulture.tamu.edu.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
