<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SQUASH-SOUP-ART-NYT &LR;      09-22 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SQUASH-SOUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUP WITH ENDLESS POSSIBILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE HAMLIN  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just how many squash soups can one city serve?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the number is infinite, as chefs, inspired no doubt
by the presently ubiquitous butternut squash, present variations on
this homey classic.
</P>
<P>
   Butternut squash _ the bisque-colored squash with orange flesh,
the tall one that stands straight up like a corseted bowling pin _
is easy to love. Unlike most other squashes, it doesn't require a
machete and Herculean strength to cut. The peel comes off easily
with a vegetable peeler, and it can be chopped with an ordinary
chef's knife.
</P>
<P>
   The fine-textured flesh is predictably rich and buttery, unlike
pumpkin or acorn squash, which can be stringy and bland. When
cooked with water, stock or cider, the flesh of the butternut melts
down to a rich mash. When pureed, it tastes like a meld of cream,
butter and squash.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious why chefs find squash soup irresistible. Who
wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   SQUASH AND CIDER SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 butternut squash, about 1 1/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups apple cider, approximately
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. With a vegetable peeler, peel the squash from top to bottom.
With a large, heavy knife, cut it in half lengthwise. Discard the
seeds. Cut the two halves in half lengthwise, and then cut across
to make large cubes. There should be about 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   2. Swirl olive oil in the bottom of a large, heavy pot. Add
onion and garlic, and cook slowly until soft, about 5 minutes. Add
squash cubes, stock and 1 cup of cider. Cover, and cook over medium
heat until the squash is very tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Uncover, remove pot from heat and let rest 10 minutes. In a
food processor, puree the mixture, in 2 batches if necessary.
Return the mixture to the pot, and whisk in up to 1 cup of the
remaining cider, thinning mixture to desired consistency. Season
well with salt and pepper. Heat again until very hot, divide into 6
soup bowls and serve. (Soup can be made in advance and frozen, or
refrigerated overnight and reheated before serving.)
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Just before it is served, the soup can be
embellished with a little dry mustard, cayenne pepper, sour cream,
yogurt or creme fraiche to taste. The soup can also be served in a
mug, with a cinnamon stick for stirring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0229 </DOCNO>
