<P>
   CLINTON-REPUBS (Washington) _ How Republicans on the Hill view
their big decision on the documents. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-GEORGES (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ Hurricane Georges
pounded the Dominican Republic capital with powerful winds and
heavy downpours Tuesday after a deadly tear through Puerto Rico and
the Lesser Antilles.The hurricane killed three people in Puerto
Rico, rescue workers said. The storm had also killed three people
in the Leeward Islands. Tourists in the Florida Keys were urged to
leave today as the vulnerable island chain stepped up preparations
for the storm. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LEBED (Krasnoyarsk) _ Russia's financial crisis has not
only rocked Moscow's political establishment. It has also stirred
many of Russia's farflung regions to set their own economic course
and establish price controls. A former general and the new governor
of Krasnoyarsk, Alexander Lebed has led the charge. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT-BAN (New York) _ Peanut butter is under attack at the
schoolhouse door. Cheap, nutritious, popular and traditional, it
has nonetheless taken its place on the list of substances _ like
asbestos and lead _ that send shivers down the spines of school
administrators. Prodded by activist parents warning of lethal
allergies, by the claims of some researchers that peanut allergies
are on the rise and, not least, by a fear of litigation, growing
numbers of public and private schools across the country, including
many of New York City's independent schools, have banned peanut
butter from their cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BUILDING-INSPECTORS (New York) _ Construction experts say
there are glaring problems with the city's 18-year-old effort to
require inspections and repairs of tall buildings. City officials
acknowledge that laws governing facade maintenance have long
allowed for ineffective, sometimes useless, inspections of many
buildings. And while the officials have made recent efforts to
strengthen the laws, inspection records and interviews with city
officials, engineers, architects and landlords indicate that
numerous problems exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
