<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-22 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: OLD NEW AMSTERDAM; MUSIC IN THE WINDY CITY;
SERPENTINE THESPIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What was Manhattan like long, long ago, before
skyscrapers, multimillion-dollar condos and co-ops and fast-food
outlets? The opportunity to see arrived Tuesday at the Museum of
the City of New York, where it will be exhibited from Saturday
through Nov. 29. It is a watercolor drawing believed to be the
oldest surviving visual representation of New York City. Made about
1650 and on loan from the Austrian National Library in Vienna, the
pen-and-ink sketch, 21 inches wide and 12.6 inches high, looks at
New Amsterdam from a point approximating the northern end of Nutten
(now Governors) Island at the entrance to the East River.
</P>
<P>
   The sketch, ``De Stadt Nieuw Amsterdam gelegen op het Eylandt
Manhattans in Niuew Nederlandt,'' is the centerpiece of a new
exhibition, ``New York Begins: A Rare Drawing of New Amsterdam,''
including maps and artifacts and a chance to learn what now stands
on the sites once occupied by the forts, taverns, warehouses,
churches and whipping post depicted by the 17th-century artist.
</P>
<P>
   Earful
</P>
<P>
   In the Windy City, woodwinds, brasses, stringed instruments and
all manner of music will vie with Sammy Sosa and the Cubs for
attention when the Chicago Symphony Orchestra ushers in a weekend
feast at Symphony Center beginning on Friday night, with the
opening of its 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Barenboim will lead works by Mozart, Haydn and
Tchaikovsky, with the mezzo-soprano Cecilia Bartoli as guest
soloist. Saturday brings the grand opening of the Eloise Martin
Center, known as Echo, the orchestra's new interactive
music-education environment in Symphony Center. And for 24 hours
starting at 7 p.m. on Saturday with a one-hour Chicago Symphony
concert, Marshall Field's Day of Music will offer free Dixieland,
classical, blues, flamenco, chamber, Irish and other music
throughout the center.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage Drama
</P>
<P>
   A crucial performer in the Royal National Theater's new
production of Shakespeare's ``Antony and Cleopatra'' has returned
to the bosom of the London company after a mysterious two-week
absence. Just as tickets for the show, starring Helen Mirren and
Alan Rickman and opening Oct. 20, were to go on sale, the missing
Cedric reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   He happens to be the sine qua non serpent used by Cleopatra for
her suicidal end. But Cedric, a California king snake asked to do a
stretch by impersonating a venomous asp, disappeared from his box
backstage at the Olivier Theater. On Saturday, Cedric shocked one
of the staff when he was seen slithering across the floor of the
theater's costume room. Taken into custody, Cedric was returned to
his quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The show goes on. All's well that end's well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
