<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES FALL AS YIELD LEVELS FALL TO HISTORIC LOWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of U.S. Treasury securities fell for the first
time in five days Tuesday despite weakness in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors may have been a little reluctant to buy
at current prices with yield levels, which move inversely to
prices, already at historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond's price fell 19/32 to 105 8/32. Its yield, rose
to 5.15 percent from 5.12 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last two months the bond market has derived
strength from the selloff in stocks, reflecting moves by investors
around the world to the relative safety of Treasury securities. So
it was considered unusual that both bonds and stocks fell Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts attributed the bond weakness to uncertainty over
what the Federal Reserve's policy-making committee will do at its
meeting next Tuesday. While speculation has increased that the
Federal Open Market Committee may move to lower rates, which could
help soothe anxiety in global markets, there is no obvious reason
for reduced rates in the United States, where the economy is
showing resilience.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said, ``At the very least, the FOMC will adopt a bias toward easing
at this meeting, but the probability of an actual easing at this
juncture has increased markedly and may well be more likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more emphatic in their prediction that the Fed would
move to ease rates. Philip Braverman, senior vice president and
chief economist at the DKB Securities (USA) Corp., said in his
latest market report that the Fed would take such a step because of
deepening distress in emerging markets, the threat of deflation in
the global economy and some signs of slowing economic growth in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Additional insight into the economy's performance will emerge
later this week when the Commerce Department releases a revision to
the second-quarter gross domestic product number, along with August
data for durable goods orders, personal income and consumer
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, whose ambiguous
remarks about interest rates last week contributed to a large
selloff in stocks, will be testifying Wednesday before the Senate
Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the Treasury will sell $15 billion of new
two-year notes, which by late Tuesday were being offered in
when-issued trading at a price to yield 4.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1759EDT &QL; 
