<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLOOD-BOOK-REVIEW-650     09-22 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-BOOK-REVIEW-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLOOD': A SCIENCE AND A BUSINESS, A SAVER AND A KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Douglas Starr points out early in this ``Epic History of
Medicine and Commerce'' that when human blood has been broken down
into derivative products, its market value is 1,600 times that of
refined petroleum: about $40 for a barrel of oil compared with
$67,000 for an equivalent quantity of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Blood, in other words, is not just a compelling, mystical symbol
of the spirit of life; it is a commodity and is medically
indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blood,'' Starr, the co-director of the Graduate Program in
Science Journalism at Boston University, has written a fascinating
history of blood, both as a challenge for scientific understanding
and as a product of global business.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific understanding, of course, had to come first, and some
of the most absorbing parts of Starr's story involve excursions
into medical history, when the role of blood in the body was
determined and the practice of transfusing it was invented.
</P>
<P>
   The tales of early experimenters, like Jean-Baptiste Denis of
France and the members of the Experimental Philosophy Club at
Oxford, are science history at a high and exciting level. Starr
covers the early experiments by which sick humans were transfused
with animal blood, explaining not only why such experiments were
bound to fail but why the early experimenters actually believed
they had achieved some success.
</P>
<P>
   These early transfusers were terribly wrong in their methods,
but Starr reminds us of the major contribution they made to
science. Before them, the human condition was believed to be a
matter of mysterious, semimagical humors, one of which was blood.
They determined that the body was a matter of ``chemicals, vessels
and pumps'' with blood _ previously deemed a kind of magical
substance _ a nutrient, a biological substance.
</P>
<P>
   Starr moves on to an equally riveting chapter on the practice of
bleeding, which endured for 2,500 years in the West despite the
fact that in almost every case it did more harm than good. His
portrait of Benjamin Rush, the American founding father whose
fanatical, blind devotion to bleeding as a cure-all killed many of
his patients, is a study in scientific obtuseness.
</P>
<P>
   What Starr calls ``the modern era of transfusion medicine''
began in 1908 with the work of a French researcher named Alexis
Carrel, who lived in New York. Carrel invented the technique of
taking blood from one person and putting it into another _
sometimes, when luck prevailed, saving lives.
</P>
<P>
   The principle that determined success or failure was, of course,
blood type, unknown to Carrel. It was discovered around the turn of
the century by a brilliant Viennese named Karl Landsteiner.
</P>
<P>
   Starr traces each of the scientific steps by which blood could
become a commodity, sketching in along the way some interesting
side implications, such as the early use of blood type in criminal
or paternity investigations and the historical significance of
hemophilia in Russian history. (It brought the mystic healer
Rasputin to the Romanov court.)
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of the volume is devoted to the second element in
the history of blood, its role as an increasingly important
international product that had to be collected, broken down into
its constituent parts, stored and sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every epoch, people had seen blood as more than it really
was _ more than a liquid or component of their body, but as a
reflection of their image and understanding of themselves,'' Starr
writes. He is speaking of the way World War II accelerated research
into the techniques of blood transfusion, so that a wounded soldier
was given blood he had donated months before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood, once held in religious regard, had been removed from a
man's circulatory system, separated, processed, freeze-dried,
packaged, shipped and reconstituted _ only to be injected into the
same individual in a completely different form several months later
and half a world away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starr tells all this in sprightly, vigorous fashion, smoothly
explaining the technical side of things, adding colorful
descriptions of a large international cast of characters here and
there. Sometimes he piles on a bit too much detail, as, for
example, when he describes the blood-bank system as it evolved in a
half-dozen countries. Still, the narrative generally moves briskly
as Starr recounts the full and sometimes very dark story.
</P>
<P>
   He tells, for example, of hideous experiments performed on
prisoners by Josef Mengele-like Japanese researchers during World
War II, and, in the late 1960s and '70s, the morally troubling
concentration of blood-collection centers in poor countries like
Nicaragua, which became a source of blood products for the rich,
industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   Vast profits were made by a new sort of entrepreneur, the
international blood broker. In Nicaragua, this global economic
system, in which the bodies of the poor were a kind of raw material
for the rich, became a focus of revolutionary anger against the
dictator Anastasio Somoza Debayle.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr foreshadows his story, and then ends it with the most
troubling episode in the history of blood as a commodity: the
spread of the AIDS virus in contaminated blood. His foreshadowing
has to do with the sensational 1992 trial of four French
bureaucrats, three of whom were convicted of failing to stop the
use of HIV-contaminated blood products in thousands of
transfusions. Starr's history of this incident is a gripping piece
of reporting.
</P>
<P>
   He stresses the French illusion that, because their
blood-collection system was based entirely on voluntary, unpaid
donations, the supply was safe. And even when that illusion died,
the failure to adopt sterilization techniques and the unwillingness
to destroy valuable stocks of available blood ``condemned thousands
of French citizens to AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time, in other words, blood became a dubious commodity,
one that killed as well as saved, until effective steps were taken
to ensure the safety of the product. The efforts to do that mark a
final chapter in a rich story admirably told in this book.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BLOOD'
</P>
<P>
   An Epic History of Medicine and Commerce
</P>
<P>
   By Douglas Starr
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 441 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $27.50
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
