<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JAPAN-0923-CO     09-22 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JAPAN-0923-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WARNS OBUCHI THAT JAPAN MUST TAKE ACTION TO SHORE UP
ECONOMY
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Concerned that Japan's listless economy could deepen
the global economic crisis, President Clinton warned Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi on Tuesday that ''swift and effective
action,'' is needed to clean up the tsunami of bad debt washing
over Japan's banking system.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the U.S. trade deficit with Japan mushrooming, Clinton
asked Obuchi to develop, within two weeks, a plan for opening five
key sectors of the economy -- telecommunications, pharmaceuticals,
energy, housing and construction -- to increased imports
competition.
</P>
<P>
   In their first meeting since Obuchi took office in July, Clinton
sought publicly to assure the Japanese of the premium the United
States places on its relationship with Japan, where more than
40,000 U.S. troops, pilots and sailors are based to help safeguard
U.S. security interests in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton invited Obuchi to a state visit at the White House
sometime early next year, Obuchi accepted, and administration aides
said they were working on a date.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States has no more important relationship in the
world than our relationship with Japan,'' Clinton told reporters
during a break in three hours of summitry with Obuchi. ''We are
very interested in deepening our partnership in the security area,
in the political area and in doing what we can economically
together to restore growth in the world and to stabilize the world
financial situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, over coffee, green tea and lunch,
Clinton delivered a tough message to Obuchi, Japan's sixth prime
minister since Clinton took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With Japan's major banks lumbering under an estimated $1
trillion in bad debts, Clinton told Obuchi that ''swift and
effective action,'' is needed to restore health to the system so
that lending, the lifeblood of economic growth, can resume, said
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, in his comments, stressed the urgency of swift
and effective action to stimulate domestic demand-led growth,''
said Summers, who was in the meetings, ``and strengthen the
financial system in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Obuchi made it clear that it was his intention
to take appropriate measures to secure an early turnaround in the
Japanese economy,'' Summers added.
</P>
<P>
   He said the infusion of public money is essential, meaning that
Japanese taxpayers should be prepared to pay billions of dollars to
help shore up debt-ridden banks.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said such public funding should be carefully structured
so that it's not simple ''bailouts to shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether public money should be used to bail out
banks has roiled the Japanese political system this week. Over the
past few days, a compromise bailout plan potentially involving
hundreds of billions of dollars came unglued after opposition
parties in Tokyo's Diet, or parliament, withdrew their support.
</P>
<P>
   Raising another area of political contention for Japan, Clinton
called on Obuchi to institute an aggressive combination of economic
reforms aimed at increasing the access U.S. companies have to
Japan's market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sector-specific market openings, Clinton
requested that Obuchi develop a plan for increasing U.S. access to
Japanese government contracts for computers, medical technology and
telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barschesfsky said
deregulation and restructuring of Japan's economy was essential to,
not inimical to, the long-term health of Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''In addition to banking sector reform and substantial fiscal
stimulus, market opening and deregulation are critical,''
Barschesfsky told reporters. ''Not only to the global economy, but
also to the functioning of Japan's own's economy, which remains
terribly over-regulated and under-productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expressed his concern, aides said, about the ballooning
U.S.-Japan trade gap, on track to top $60 billion this year, in
Japan's favor. The gap is widening chiefly because the combination
of a sagging economy in Japan and a weakened yen have sharply
reduced Japanese demand for American goods.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. exports to Japan fell to $58.9 billion, a drop of nearly 12
percent as compared to last year's figures, during the first seven
months of the year, according to the Commerce Department. That
tumble translates into more than $6 billion in lost sales to U.S.
farmers, manufacturers and raw materials suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi replaced Ryutaro Hashimoto, who resigned last summer in
the wake of a major parliamentary defeat for the Liberal Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP has dominated the political system of post-war Japan and
promulgated the policies credited with leading the country from the
ashes of war to become the world's second-largest economic power.
The party suffered a stinging rebuke by voters, however, angry over
a languid Japanese economy that has been flat or contracting for
seven of the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
