<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'LL LOVE, HONOR AND OBEY, BUT NOT RIGHT AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dating game. The mating game. The waiting game. I knew about
the first two stages of relationship development. It's that last
one that slipped through the cracks of my education about the
opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   The dating game was somehow both fun and frustrating. All those
hours debating what to wear, where to go, what to do, and what to
say. Along the way, I met some neat, interesting guys who are
successful and happily married today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I also met some incredibly strange, unpredictable fellows. I
don't know where they are today, and I don't care, either. Because
of the latter group, I highly recommend double-dating, at least in
the beginning. There's nothing more disconcerting than being alone
with your date, 30 miles from home, when he rolls his eyes to the
top of his head and asks you, ``Do you hear the voices, too? I hate
it when they sing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after sorting through the lily pads, you may just find a
prince. He's charming, funny, smart, good-looking, and he shares
your values. Your comfort level around him increases to the point
that you can gulp down your soda and burp in front of him without
dying of embarrassment. He stops washing his car and getting a
haircut before every date. Before you know it, wedding bells are
ringing, and your best friends give you high-fives as you stroll
down the aisle. And there he is, Mr. Wonderful, your new mate.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the waiting game starts.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, not right away. There's an adjustment period during the
honeymoon when you are both on your best behavior. You know, you
jump up every morning to brush your teeth and wash your face before
he wakes up. He runs errands with you and repairs stuff around the
house with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Then, slowly but surely, things start to change. You decide
you'd rather have a cup of coffee before you brush your teeth or
your hair. The pizza man no longer needs directions to your house,
and when he arrives, he calls you by your first name. Yes, the
honeymoon is over.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one day you say, ``Honey, would you take out the trash
for me?'' and he grunts in response but it's a positive kind of
grunt. A half-hour later, he's still watching the game and the
trash can is now overflowing because you've added that pizza box
and a wilted head of lettuce to an already large pile of refuse.
Annoyed, you finally decide to do it yourself. He doesn't protest.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is just waiting him out.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's hard. The grass is taller than the shrubbery. The
dripping sink annoys you. The cabinet falls on your foot every time
you open it. It's tempting just to do it yourself. Don't. If you
asked him to do it, and he gave a positive response. He will do it.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually.
</P>
<P>
   After umpteen arguments that all ended with, ``You just didn't
give me enough time. I said that I'd do it. What's the big rush
anyway? `Better Homes and Gardens' is not coming by today,'' I
finally learned my lesson. Just wait and wait and wait.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, sometime before never, he would take care of the
task. Sure enough, nothing bad would have happened in the meantime.
Neither `BH&AMP;G' nor my mother nor the yard patrol would have stopped
by and given us a citation. Friends have never dropped by and
complained that they had to jiggle the handle on the toilet to make
it stop running. In fact, contrary to my predictions, beanstalks
have never grown out of the trash can.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I know it's hard. Try to ignore it or make a list of all the
things that you've procrastinated about and do some of those while
you wait. Heck, if it's really killing you, just do it yourself.
But if you can, just wait. He'll do it.
</P>
<P>
   Someday.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. Call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in care of
the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington, TX
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
