<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLADDER-COX     09-22 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLADDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New therapy for bladder control gives women tool to fight
incontinence
 &HT;    By Amanda Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_A new treatment demonstrated Tuesday by a Georgia
company promises to help women control incontinence by merely
sitting in a special chair twice a week for eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Neocontrol Pelvic Floor Therapy System, developed by
Neotonus Inc. and Emory University(Ga.) and Georgia Tech
researchers, uses pulsed magnetic therapy to exercise and
strengthen pelvic muscles that control bladder function. It is
being made available first in Atlanta and will be rolled out
nationwide next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the majority of patients, it's a simple, safe and painless
treatment,'' said Dr. Niall Galloway, a urologist and director of
the Emory Continence Center. ``Our studies show it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway helped develop Neocontrol, which was approved by the
Food and Drug Administration in June, and the continence center is
treating 45 patients with the system.
</P>
<P>
   Neotonus will be licensing the system, manufactured at Design
and Manufacturing Services, to doctors' offices and treatment
centers, said Neotonus CEO and President Tony J. Morris. So far,
the treatment is available at 10 metro Atlanta sites. Some
insurance may cover the $1,200 to $1,500 treatment cost.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 percent of the 15 million Americans afflicted by
incontinence are women, and that's why Neotonus focused on them,
Morris said. Initial tests suggest the treatment also may help men
who've lost bladder control after prostate surgery, but so far the
treatment is approved only for women. The most common causes of
pelvic muscle weakness are childbirth, surgery, injury or hormonal
changes during menopause.
</P>
<P>
   With the Neocontrol system, women sit fully clothed for about 20
minutes twice a week in a chair that has magnetic technology
imbedded in the seat. Pulsating magnetic fields induce muscle
contractions in the pelvic floor to build strength. The patient
feels her muscles tighten, but experiences no pain.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment works much as Kegel exercises do. Those exercises,
developed in the 1950s by Dr. A.M. Kegel, involve contracting the
anal sphincter as you would to prevent a bowel movement or urine
flow. They must be repeated several times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the patients who need this (Kegel) treatment the most who
find it the most difficult to do,'' Galloway said. ``The Neocontrol
system helps them to understand how to work those muscles and keep
the problem from coming back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Treatments for incontinence include collagen injections to the
urethra, probes to provide electrical stimulation and surgery
called a vaginal repair, a $12,000-to-$15,000 operation that
involves tightening the muscles and ligaments of the pelvic floor.
</P>
<P>
   None of those procedures works for all women, and neither does
Neocontrol therapy. Galloway said it is inappropriate for women who
have metallic implants in their pelvic area, such as a hip
replacement, or for women who have cardiac pacemakers.
</P>
<P>
   In ongoing clinical trials involving 117 women in Cleveland,
Chicago, Philadelphia and Orlando, half of those who have completed
eight weeks of Neocontrol therapy reported being ``completely
dry.'' Eighty-three percent said they had seen ``significant
improvement'' in their incontinence.
</P>
<P>
   The therapy has won raves from patients who were helped in the
clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've regained my life in regard to sports and exercise,'' said
Penny Stockford, 45, an Orlando nurse who developed incontinence
after a hysterectomy and treatment for cancer. ``It's great not
having to be ever mindful that I have a leakage problem. It's a
wonderful feeling to be that free.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
