<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOUTHERN HAPPENINGS
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Panama City Beach, Fla. _ ``Aerial Circus'' Saturday and
Sunday features precision flying and aerobatics; a biplane flown
with a wingwalker; and an all-woman parachute team. Also, vintage
aircraft on display at Panama City-Bay County International
Airport. 1-800-722-3224.
</P>
<P>
   -- Columbia, Tenn. _ The 1998 Majestic Middle Tennessee Fall
Tours Friday through Sunday features eight antebellum homes along
with Civil War encampments, barbecue lunch and cemetery tour.
931-381-4822.
</P>
<P>
   -- Blackville, S.C. _ South Carolina's Agricultural Center
presents the ``Old Time Horse Farmers Gathering'' Friday and
Saturday at the Clemson Edisto Research and Education Center on
U.S. 78 between Blackville and Williston. Includes field work (hay
mowing, raking, bailing, plowing), farm life (apple pressing,
butter churning, quilting, etc.) and family fun (home cooking,
baked goods), plus old-fashioned produce stand, folk singers and
demonstrating crafters. 803-259-3350.
</P>
<P>
   -- Charleston, S.C. _ The Preservation Society of Charleston
hosts the 22nd Annual Fall Candlelight Tours of Homes and Gardens
through Oct. 24. Candlelight tours are 7-10 p.m.
Thursday-Saturdays; afternoon garden tours and teas are 2-5 p.m.
Sunday and Oct. 11. $30. 1-800-968-8175.
</P>
<P>
   -- Huntsville, Ala. _ Big Spring Jam brings 100 musical acts to
six outdoor stages at Big Spring Park Friday through Sunday. Rock,
country, jazz, big band and children's acts. 1-800-772-2348.
</P>
<P>
   -- Townsend, Tenn. _ The Townsend Heritage Festival and Old
Timers Day Friday through Sunday offers bluegrass music,
storytelling, Appalachian crafts and the beauty of the Great Smoky
Mountains. 1-800-525-6834, or http:
</P>
<P>
   //chamber.blount.tn.us/smokymvb.
</P>
<P>
   -- Asheville, N.C. _ Biltmore Estate presents the second annual
Michaelmas: An English Harvest Fair Saturday through Oct. 25
(weekends only). Arts and crafts, musical and theatrical
entertainment, children's activities, archery demonstrations, a
grape stomp and food and wine seminars. 1-800-323-6822.
</P>
<P>
   -- Macon , Ga._ The Peach State Jazz Festival Thursday through
Sunday features downtown performances by national, regional and
local jazz, blues, Latin and gospel artists, plus an artists market
and educational events at Mercer University. 1-877-337-8849.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ellijay , Ga._ Hillcrest Orchards will host the Third Annual
Apple Pickin' Jubilee Saturday and Sunday with live entertainment,
mountain barbecue, fried apple pies, homemade ice cream, apple
cider doughnuts and apple picking. 706-273-3838.
</P>
<P>
   -- Eatonton , Ga._ A Designer/Floral Showcase at Rosewood Bed &AMP;
Breakfast Saturday and Sunday benefits Habitat for Humanity Putnam.
706-485-9009.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tallulah Falls, Ga. _ Days for increased water flow through
Tallulah Gorge State Park will be Saturday and Sunday; and Oct. 7,
9, 14, 16, 21, 23 and 31. The aesthetic flow releases will be 200
cubic feet per second compared with 500 and 700 during whitewater
boating weekends. Hiking or rappelling into the gorge during
releases is prohibited; however, views are available from the rim
trail's overlooks. 706-754-7970 or http://www.gastateparks.org.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fisherville, Va. _ Virginia Mennonite Relief Sale Saturday is
an auction of handmade quilts, artwork and furniture, as well as
homemade preserves, bread, pies, and other baked goods. Augusta
Expoland, between Staunton and Waynesboro, off I-64.
http://home.rica.net/vmconf/relief
</P>
<P>
   /salehome.htm 540-434-9727.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gillsville, Ga. _ Hewell Family ``Turning &AMP; Burning''
Festival, sunup-5 p.m. Oct. 3, includes demonstrations of northeast
Georgia rural living (pottery-making, sorgum canning, wood carving,
blacksmithing, wagon and buggy rides), exhibits of farm equipment,
gospel and country music and food. 6035 Ga. 52, east of Gainsville.
770-869-3468.
</P>
<P>
   -- Natural Bridge, Va. _ The annual Natural Bridge Pioneer Arts
and Trades Fair Sept. 30-Oct. 4 features craftsmen dressed in
period costumes demonstrating crafts from the 18th and 19th
centuries. Also, storytellers and musicians. 1-800-533-1410.
</P>
<P>
   -- Balsam, N.C. _ Autumn Showcase at Balsam Mountain Inn through
Oct. 31 features works of 45 Haywood County artists. Work is
restocked twice a week. Free concerts Thursdays at 8:30 p.m.
feature Mountain Aire String Band, Oct. 1 and 29; and the Dowden
Sisters, Oct. 8; the Reel Band, Oct. 15; and Anne Lough, Oct. 22.
828-456-9498.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
