A8582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CMA-COX     09-22 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMA-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   All eyes will be on the new ladies of country
</P>
<P>
   By Russ DeVault
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   The way Faith Hill sees it, she and the other women are more
than holding their own as it comes time for the 32nd Country Music
Association awards program tonight. ``We're selling records and
kicking the boys' butts,'' Hill says. ``We're the ones to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of country fans and pop music mainstreamers will indeed
be watching the women of country during the CBS telecast _ last
year's glitzy show drew an audience of 20.7 million and this year's
is expected to do equally well.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among the younger stars _ loomed over by Reba McEntire
just as the male contingent is by Garth Brooks _ are teen sensation
LeAnn Rimes, 33-year-old Shania Twain and Hill, 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reba, boy, is she big _ a major cottage industry,'' says Larry
Vallon, national talent buyer for Los Angeles-based Universal
Concerts. ``Then you have LeAnn who's set some sales records and
Shania is going through the ceiling. Faith is the next big thing.
She seems to have set up her career perfectly, coming along slowly
with no overnight success, which gives you staying power.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the pop-oriented Twain, the first ``country'' act seen on
MTV, Hill clearly reaches beyond the ``Stand By Your Man''
mentality once imposed upon Nashville's women. (She's married to
country star Tim McGraw.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel uncomfortable calling myself a star, but I consider
Shania a star,'' Hill says Tuesday, during a break in awards show
rehearsals Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shania puts out great albums, has a great image, great videos,
is a bit edgy, is selling out arenas and appeals to a wide
audience,'' says Hill, who's nominated for Female Vocalist of the
year, among other awards. Then, laughing, she admits, ``(I) always
think about it (reaching the same level of success as Twain). I'm
not to that place yet, but I hope to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The 32nd Annual Country Music Association Awards
</P>
<P>
   8 EDT, tonight on CBS, live from Nashville's Grand Ole Opry.
</P>
<P>
   -- Host: Vince Gill.
</P>
<P>
   -- Top nominees: George Strait (5), Garth Brooks, Faith Hill,
Patty Loveless, Tim McGraw (4 each), Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Martina
McBride, Steve Wariner (3 each).
</P>
<P>
   -- The big deal: An all-out producton number with Shania Twain
singing her new single, ``Honey, I'm Home,'' as more than 200
cheerleaders race from the lobby to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   -- Performers include: Garth Brooks, Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Dixie
Chicks, Faith Hill, Alan Jackson, Patty Loveless, Reba McEntire,
Tim McGraw, LeAnn Rimes, George Strait, Pam Tillis, Travis Tritt,
Shania Twain, the Wilkinsons, Mark Wills, Wynonna, Trisha Yearwood.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hall of Fame inductees: George Morgan, Elvis Presley, Tammy
Wynette, E.W. ``Bud'' Wendell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
