<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-MITCHELL-COX     09-22 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-MITCHELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN's 'Superwoman'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Almost 30 years ago, a very young Jeff Greenfield
strenuously warned a very young Pat Mitchell not to go into
television. It would, he said, ruin her life.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1969, and Mitchell and Greenfield were working on John
Lindsay's New York City mayoral campaign. Greenfield, now a senior
analyst at CNN, looks back and laughs at how wrong his advice was.
Pat Mitchell, 55, is now president of CNN Productions and Time Inc.
Television, one of the most powerful and respected women in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Her profile reaches an apex Sunday with the debut of ``Cold
War,'' the colossal 24-hour documentary that Ted Turner envisioned,
then turned over to Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Television didn't ruin Mitchell's life. It consumed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a schedule that would kill Superwoman,'' says Barbara
Pyle, CNN's globe-hopping CNN documentary maker. ``She literally
lives on the red-eye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I call her 'Bumper to Bumper,','' says Scott Seydel, the
Atlanta businessman she's been dating for three-plus years. ``Any
time she's got any space to sign up for something that looks
interesting, she will.'' She stood Seydel up on their first date,
when a last-minute schedule change sent her back to Hartsfield
International Airport, her home away from home.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, they're underplaying Mitchell's over-scheduling.
Last month, she flew to Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina, on four
hours' notice for ``NewsStand: CNN and Entertainment Weekly,'' the
newsmagazine she's in charge of. Glenn Close and Marisa Tomei were
doing a play there, and CNN couldn't find a last-minute
correspondent. So the network tapped Mitchell, who started out on
the air rather than in the executive suite (she used to sub for
Jane Pauley on ``Today'' in the late '80s). She also went to
Havana, Cuba, to tape a special on Fidel Castro that aired Sept.
13.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the promotional trips for ``Cold War'' and other
documentaries, business meetings at Time Warner in New York, the
charity boards such as Mikhail Gorbachev's international
environmental group Green Cross and the mentoring group Girls Inc.,
the Sundance Institute (she calls Robert Redford ``Bob,'' as all
his friends do).
</P>
<P>
   At least she's stopped flying to London every other week,
something she did for three years while ``Cold War'' was being
assembled there by executive producer Jeremy Isaacs (``The World at
War'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere in all that, I try to find a life,'' Mitchell says.
``My family describes me as a blur.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, she'll be in her office in the CNN Center a mere six
days.
</P>
<P>
   The office wall behind her desk is dominated by a huge movie
poster for ``Woman to Woman,'' a 1929 melodrama and also the title
of Mitchell's early-'80s syndicated talk show, a precursor of ``The
Oprah Winfrey Show.'' Orbiting the poster are photos of Mitchell
with Gorbachev, Castro, Hillary Clinton, on safari in Africa _ the
last a working vacation, as nearly all of Mitchell's vacations are,
with the exception of occasional fly-fishing or mountain hiking
getaways with Seydel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to think I'm a workaholic, but I probably fit a
lot of the descriptions,'' Mitchell says. ``I have the balance
issues that almost everyone has with a job like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if she fits the technical definition (of a
workaholic), but she's probably pushing the envelope,'' says her
son, Mark, 33, a CNN producer. ``But she enjoys her work. I think
there's a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rest of Mitchell's office is filled with Native
American art, which Mitchell started collecting as an undergraduate
at the University of Georgia in the early '60s. She had already
found herself drawn to it when she was told that her
great-grandmother was a Creek Cherokee who had passed as white.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell caught her travel bug early in life, as an Army brat.
``I went to three schools in the third grade,'' she says. ``I had
to adapt pretty early. I always had the wrong accent and I'd have
to start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, her family settled in Swainsboro, Georgia, and
Mitchell went on to UGA on a drama scholarship. A young marriage,
son Mark, a divorce, a master's degree in English and an
entry-level job with Look magazine right before it went out of
business, all led up to the Lindsay campaign, where she met
Greenfield, started producing TV ads, and got an offer to produce a
New York show called ``First Person.'' She took it despite
Greenfield's misgivings and has worked in television ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell got into television at exactly the right time, the
early '70s. Women were finally being ``allowed'' to be more than
weathergirls, and she reveled in the new atmosphere. In 1974,
WBZ-TV in Boston turned the station over for a day to Mitchell and
a few female co-workers for live interviews with Gloria Steinem,
Betty Friedan and Helen Reddy on ``Yes We Can Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Among women our age (50s), she's one of those who had to break
the ground,'' Pyle says.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Mitchell bounced between on-air interviewer on
``Today'' and ``Woman to Woman'' to behind-the-scenes producer.
``When I was a kid,'' says her son Mark, ``I always secretly hoped
she would be Barbara Walters, some famous interviewer.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was drawn more to making documentaries on issues that TV
didn't pay enough attention to: child labor laws, infant mortality,
female peace activists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, as an independent producer trying to raise funds for a
project titled ``A Century of Women,'' she was hired, unexpectedly,
to head TBS Productions, Turner's documentary unit. Jane Fonda, an
old acquaintence from California, was among those who urged her to
take the desk job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the reputation of being Ted's pet, his philanthropy,''
Mitchell says. ``We had value to Ted, but I wanted us to have value
as a business.''
</P>
<P>
   She set about balancing the do-good documentaries Turner loves _
on environmental concerns, Native Americans _ with the bottom line,
turning the documentary unit from a money-loser to a money-maker.
Her job titles, power and influence increased as TBS Productions
morphed into CNN Productions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   So here she sits today, with ``one of the best jobs in
television,'' more than 2 million frequent flyer miles on Delta
alone, an ongoing serious relationship with Seydel, a house on the
border between Virginia-Highland and Morningside with a backyard
pool she only got into four times over the summer because of her
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wears more hats than Bartholomew Cubbins,'' says Seydel,
referring to an old Dr. Seuss book, ``The 500 Hats of Bartholomew
Cubbins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way she is. But instead of taking them off, she's
piling them all on top of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PATRICIA EDENFIELD MITCHELL FILE
</P>
<P>
   -- Title: President of CNN Productions and Time Inc. Television
</P>
<P>
   -- Latest claim to fame: Overseeing ``Cold War,'' CNN's 24-hour
mega-documentary that debuts Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Born: Jan. 20, 1943, Statesboro
</P>
<P>
   -- Personal: One marriage, divorced. In a steady relationship
with Scott Seydel, an Atlanta businessman who owns a chemical
textile company (for stonewashing jeans, for example). One son,
Mark, 33, a CNN employee.
</P>
<P>
   -- Education: BA, MA, University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   -- Career: Writer, Look magazine, 1969-'70; political-media
strategist, '70-'71; WBZ-TV, Boston, '72-'77; host of ``Panorama,''
'77-'78; host of ``America Alive,'' '78-'79; co-host of ``Hour
Magazine,'' '79-'83; executive producer, host, ``Woman to Woman,''
'83-'84; executive producer, host, ``Woman to Woman'' segments on
``Today'' show, '84-'89; co-founder, VU Productions, '89-'92;
senior vice president, TBS Productions, '92-'94; president, TBS
Productions, '95-'97.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hobbies: Fly fishing, hiking, tennis, horseback riding.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
