<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-HILTONHEAD-CO     09-22 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-HILTONHEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall for Hilton Head
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD, S.C._There is something about a fall beach vacation
that feels a little like rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Wading into the surf long after most regular folks have locked
away their sandals and buckled back into jobs. Playing tennis at
the precise hour most parents are picking up the kids from the bus
stop. Sipping a cool drink at a sunset-backlit cafe and
contemplating an obscenely late dinner, not a care in the world
about homework or school lunches or the morning commute.
</P>
<P>
   Few places celebrate this off-season spirit as well as Hilton
Head, S.C. Anyone within a day's drive knows the best time to hit
this Lowcountry haven is the fall _ just before warmer temperatures
head south for the winter and after hotels and attractions drop
their high-season rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Labor Day, it's real low-key here,'' says Niveen Corish,
a 33-year-old Georgian who makes frequent weekend jaunts to the
family's Sea Pines Plantation condo with husband John and
7-year-old son Trevor. ``Crowds thin out and it's much more
relaxed. Even when we go to the beach it's a different experience.
There are more families with small children, not as many teenagers
and no crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   Marti Fulton, who grew up on Hilton Head and now lives in
Alpharetta, Georgia says that with her son, Jordan, 8, in school,
it's hard for her and her husband, Steven, to break away for a
quick retreat. But the rewards are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there on Thanksgiving two years ago and it was 75
degrees,'' said Fulton, 42, a marketing consultant with the
Communigraphix Studio of Alpharetta. ``The air has that good crisp
feel, and it's good beach weather because it's not oppressively hot
and the water stays warm. Plus it's easy to get (tennis) court time
and into restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   To help you plan an escape, here's a list of Hilton Head best
bets for fall, which begins today.
</P>
<P>
   A shore thing
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Head's best feature may be the 12 miles of sugar-white
beaches that skirt the shoe-shaped island. At South Carolina's
southernmost tip, the semitropical barrier island's shoreline is
warmed year-round by the Gulf Stream. Average temperatures remain
in the 70s well into November, with October's average a
beach-friendly 77 degrees and the Atlantic a comfortable 75.
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels and resorts fold the cost of beach access and
parking into the bill. Two popular public beaches with restrooms
and other amenities are Folly Field Beach off Matthews Drive,
mid-island on the coast, and the expansive Coligny Beach, at the
southern end of the island off North Forest Road.
</P>
<P>
   The play's the thing
</P>
<P>
   With more public golf courses than even a fanatic could sample
in a month's time (40-plus) the island is a duffer's paradise. Most
courses are open year-round with holes bordering the ocean, winding
around coastal lagoons or through woodlands. The Harbour Town Golf
Links at Sea Pines, site of the MCI Classic-Heritage of Golf
Tournament on the PGA tour, is well-known for its 18th hole
overlooking Calibogue Sound and the island's lighthouse
(843-842-8484). The Palmetto Dunes resort, mid-island, also
features a number of award-winning courses named after their
designers: Arthur Hills, George Fazio and Robert Trent Jones
(843-785-1138).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, miniature golf courses dot the island. Legendary
Golf (900 William Hilton Parkway, 843-686-3399) offers two 18-hole
mini courses _ one for kids and a second for serious players
looking to work on their short game while entertaining the family.
``We get the guys who walk in right off the golf course with
vendettas, looking to settle the score with their buddies here,''
says manager Robert Brown. ``This isn't just a place for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Legendary Golf is open daily: $6.50, nine holes; $8.50, 18
($4.50 for kids under 9). Other mini courses: Island Putt &AMP; Drive
(U.S. 278 at Folly Field Road, 843-842-9990) and Main Street Golf &AMP;
Games (4101 Main Street, 843-689-3866).
</P>
<P>
   Harbour Town
</P>
<P>
   There's no better way to get into the vacation spirit than a
visit to this charming waterfront square anchoring Sea Pines
Plantation at the island's southern tip. Hard by a marina and
steepled at one end by a candy-striped lighthouse, Harbour Town is
a quaint collection of boutiques, galleries and cafes. Take in the
night air on a wooden rocking chair on one of the open-air public
porches, or treat yourself to a cool drink _ and the kids to
homemade ice cream _ under the center's Liberty Tree.
</P>
<P>
   You can also give the kids a workout at a new playground at the
square, or lead them up winding stairs of the Harbour Town
lighthouse, which affords a commanding view from the upper deck.
There's a variety of family concerts and activities, including an
occasional performance by singer-songwriter Gregg Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Harbour Town also features many high-end antiques and home decor
shops, but hard-core shoppers may also want to visit the Hilton
Head Factory Stores (U.S. 278), featuring more than 75 outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Come sail away
</P>
<P>
   Interested in natural history? Try a pleasure sail or a dolphin
cruise. Sonny Compher has been leading 90-minute eco-tours for 14
years on large and small boats, departing from Broad Creek Marina
($12 for adults; $9 for kids, 843-681-2522).
</P>
<P>
   A combination tour guide and environmental educator, Compher
likes to salt his cruises with tales of island history, while
pointing out the occasional bottle-nose dolphin, manatee, gator or
waterfront celebrity villa. The boats are covered, so rain isn't a
problem. ``September and October are great times to get out on the
water,'' says Compher, 58, whose tours conclude with an examination
of a crab net he keeps dockside _ usually teeming with shrimp,
crabs, even a small shark now and then. You can also choose among
dozens of other tours, on yachts, large boats, even kayaks. A good
place to weigh the choices _ from eco-tours to deep-sea fishing
outfits to sunset yacht cruises _ is at the Hilton Head Island
Chamber of Commerce Welcome Center on U.S. 278, on the way into
town.
</P>
<P>
   Riding along
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Head has several stables that offer fine guided tours
with a mare's eye view of the island's natural beauty. Some have
special kids' packages and pony rides, allowing parents and young
environmentalists to venture into the woods year-round to check out
majestic moss-draped live oaks, pines, magnolias and palmettos. The
forests and nearby marshes are havens for deer, pelican, great blue
heron and more than 100 other bird species.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton Stables, at the Sea Pines Equestrian Center (190
Greenwood Drive) has more than 70 horses. The stables offer pony
rides ($5) for children 7 and older, riding lessons ($40) for ages
5 and up, and scenic 90-minute tours (adults: $30) through a
600-acre forest preserve. Information: 843-671-2586.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis everyone?
</P>
<P>
   With 300 courts, Hilton Head may have more tennis options per
square mile than any place in the nation. Sea Pines Racquet Club at
Harbour Town and Van Der Meer Tennis Center offer kids', women's
and juniors' programs through the fall and rent court space by the
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Court time at Sea Pines (843-363-4495), featuring 25 clay and
five hard-surface courts, is $16 per hour for walk-ons, and club
managers tailor lessons and clinics to families' needs. At Van Der
Meer (800-845-6138), court time is $15 per hour for walk-ons (hard
and clay outdoor courts) and one-hour private lessons for kids
start at $35. Van Der Meer also has four covered courts ($20 per
hour) for use in wet weather.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Accommodations: Options range from expensive home, condo and
villa rentals (fetching thousands by the week) to hotel and motel
rooms that go for less than $100 per night. Sea Pines Plantation is
a good choice if you're seeking an all-in-one experience, with
beaches, pools, tennis, golf, restaurants, shopping and playgrounds
a short walk or bike ride away. Fall rates range from $200 per
night (down from $235 in summer) for a two-bedroom condo
overlooking the Harbour Town Yacht Basin (four-night minimum) to
$125 ($165 in summer) for a similar facility a 10-minute drive away
(800-732-7463).
</P>
<P>
   -- Eating out: The island has 200 restaurants of every stripe.
Our favorite was the Crazy Crab in Harbour Town (843-363-2722),
with its fine seafood at family-friendly prices. Crabby Nick's
(U.S. 278, 843-842-2425) is also a hit with families, with magic
shows between the under-$10 meals. Giusseppi's Pizza &AMP; Pasta
(Shelter Cove, 843-785-4144) serves up classic New York-style pies
and pitchers of beer at affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: Hilton Head Chamber of Commerce, 1-800-523-3373.
On the Web: http://www.hiltonheadisland.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
