<HEADER>
A8588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWSRADIO-COX     09-22 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSRADIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season Premire of ``Newsradio'' devoted entirely to Hartman
character
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the writing done for all the television shows premiering
this week, probably none was harder than the task assigned to Paul
Simms. After the murder of Phil Hartman by his wife in May, Simms,
the series creator, had to open this season of ``NewsRadio'' with a
farewell to Bill McNeal, Hartman's character.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman was more than just a cast member of ``NewsRadio''; he
was a mentor to the other players, most of whom were younger. So
it's fitting that rather than just write McNeal out with a few
lines of dialogue, the season premiere is devoted entirely to
McNeal's death and reactions to it.
</P>
<P>
   TV series have had to say hasty goodbyes before to actors who
have unexpectedly died, notably Michael Conrad (Sgt. Phil ``Let's
be careful out there'' Esterhaus on ``Hills Street Blues'') and
Nicholas Colasanto (Coach on ``Cheers''). But Hartman's death
merits an entire episode that is respectful without being maudlin,
and pretty funny given the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The season opens with the cast members returning from McNeal's
funeral; we're told he died of a heart attack. Instantly, the
employees of WNYX are ``reassuring'' news director Dave Nelson
(Dave Foley) about his boring, two-hour eulogy: ``It was totally,
uh, comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a little bit of play off the idea of not speaking ill of
the dead, though McNeal, the station's news anchor, was a
self-centered, pompous control freak with a mean streak. It's what
made him funny within these sitcom walls; in real life, McNeal
would have been unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   And we're reminded toward the end of how unbearable he could be
when the staffers get hand-written notes from McNeal, each written
in advance with the instruction that it be delivered in the event
of his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Lisa,'' the one to newswriter Lisa Miller begins, ``I'm
sorry I was so obsessed with seeing you naked.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the Bill McNeal we loved to laugh at. He, and Hartman,
will be missed. Next week, Jon Lovitz joins the cast as a news
anchor who reportedly will be as obnoxious as McNeal was.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre coincidence, Hartman also had a guest-starring role
on last season's cliffhanger finale of ``3rd Rock From the Sun,''
which is resolved with the season premiere tonight (9 EDT on NBC).
His character had kidnapped Harry (French Stewart) and scenes from
that show will be seen in an opening montage. But the show then
moves off in a different direction so it was unnecessary to recast
Hartman's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsRadio''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   9:30 EDT, tonight on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
