</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will the title soon be ``Dharma, Greg, &AMP; baby''?
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're getting a baby. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' last season's break-out cute couple, come
roaring back tonight (8 o'clock EDT on ABC) without a hint of
sophomore slump. They're Lucy and Ricky for the '90s: she's zany
and unpredictable, he's the long-suffering straight man. When they
click, Jenna Elfman and Thomas Gibson are sexy, sweet and just plan
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they have a secret weapon: their in-laws. Her folks, Abby
(Mimi Kennedy) and Larry (Alan Rachins) are unreconstructed
hippies, while his, Kitty (Susan Sullivan) and Edward (Mitchell
Ryan) are country-clubbing blue bloods. When the four of them get
together, it's like oil and Evian.
</P>
<P>
   What ``D&AMP;G'' doesn't appear to need so early in its promising
life is a baby, the plot device that pretty much clobbered ``Murphy
Brown.'' But that's what they appear to be getting in the season
opener, with ``appear'' being the operative word. Dharma befriends
a supermarket cashier who's nine months pregnant and abandoned by
the baby's father. In her impulsiveness, she decides she and Greg
need to adopt the baby. Only Greg, the rational half, doesn't think
so.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to-ing and fro-ing, leading to an ambiguous,
to-be-continued ending. But getting there is enormous fun.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Headline goes here
</P>
<P>
   A new ``Law &AMP; Order'' season (its eighth), a new ``Law &AMP; Order''
character (its umpteenth). Some things never change. Abbie
Carmichael (Angie Harmon) is the striking, inventive, gloves-off,
hang-'em-all addition to the district attorney's office tonight (10
o'clock EDT, on NBC), leading the prosecution in an adopted baby's
death. But first she needs to lock horns with old-hand D.A. Jack
McCoy (Sam Waterson). ``I understand you're opening a children's
wing on death row,'' he barks when she arrests a 7-year-old for
murder. ``Thrilled to be working with you,'' she barks back.
This'll work. ``Law &AMP; Order'' knows what it does best and does it
week after week, year after year, and tonight is as reassuringly
twisty as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Drew Jubera, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
