<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANKWILLIAMS-RETROSPE     09-22 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANKWILLIAMS-RETROSPECTIVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANK WILLIAMS' TOTAL CAREER IN A BOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hank Williams Sr. would have been 75 last week (Sept. 17), so of
course it's time for Mercury Nashville to make some serious cash in
commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Tuesday's release of ``The Complete Hank
Williams,'' the all-time, smash-mouth, hands-down, end-all, be-all
of Hank Sr. boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Other sets have focused on single aspects of Hank's career, such
as blues, singles, radio, etc., but the only thing lacking here
would be, say, a two-minute outtake tape of a coughing fit during
some recording session.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big, big box, and it's comprehensive. Really. And at a
suggested list price of $170, who would expect less?
</P>
<P>
   The 225 tracks, on 10 CDs, include 53 previously unissued ones.
All of the MGM and early Sterling Records sessions are here, plus
130 nonsession and radio/television performances.
</P>
<P>
   There are cuts from the earliest Montgomery demos, the later
Shreveport sessions, Armed Forces Radio shows, the Health and
Happiness shows, and a live one from Hank's European concert tour,
with many special gems included.
</P>
<P>
   An August 1952 Nashville demo recording of ``Kaw-Liga'' has two
false starts as Hank tries to get the future classic down the way
he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Wells and Johnnie Wright join Hank on ``Dear Brother,'' an
unreleased 1948 demo recorded in Shreveport when all were on the
Louisiana Hayride.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest recording, a simulated radio performance from 1939
that was used to pitch the 17-year-old Hank to live radio
programmers, stands in stark contrast to his later works: ``Happy
Rovin' Cowboy'' would give rise to ``Weary Blues From Waitin' ''
and ``We're Getting Closer to the Grave Each Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank's spoken-word work was appealing without being ingratiating
or overly emotional. He had a gift for intimate conversation within
the confines of mass media. There are the ``Luke the Drifter''
recordings (''Be Careful of Stones That You Throw''), a radio
commercial for Hank's book ``How to Write Folk &AMP; Western Music to
Sell,'' and a two-minute radio apology to Washington, D.C., fans
for canceling a concert due to back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But the printed matter that accompanies the set becomes
ponderous. Two 150-page booklets are included, with 120 supposedly
rare photos, ads, posters, LP covers, charts and even handwritten
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   How much is too much? Well, pictures of Hank's guy stuff
(fishing tackle, phonograph, guns) don't add a lot and have a
cheesy, holy-relic feel. And the telegram from Hank's mom to his
sister has been reprinted ad nauseam: ``Come at once Hank is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   While Williams biographer Colin Escott's ``Notes on the Music''
is sometimes fascinating, especially the preface describing Hank's
era and the music industry as it was then, it is also long. The
quotes from modern-day stars are superfluous; who is going to say,
``actually, Hank Williams wasn't all that great''?
</P>
<P>
   Much simpler, and clearer, is a foldout time line of Hank's
life.
</P>
<P>
   A 2,500-word essay by Daniel Cooper is way, way over the top.
``His songs have proven vibrantly resistant to millennial
obsolescence,'' Cooper writes. In other words, they're timeless.
``... Williams, alone and in absentia, has had to absorb Americans'
need to localize psychic demolition. ...'' Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Part of Hank's greatness was that he was a much better writer
than either Escott, or Cooper, or this reviewer. Simple as it is,
``I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry'' never fails to demolish my psyche.
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins writes on country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call her at (817) 548-5565. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
