<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEASTS OF ALASKA BEST SEEN FROM INTERIOR OF BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENALI NATIONAL PARK, Alaska _ Half past 4 o'clock in the
morning is a disagreeable hour to begin a vacation day.
</P>
<P>
   But wild things start stirring early, and we had not come nearly
3,500 miles to lie in our beds while other folks were out
consorting with enormous fanged and horned brutes.
</P>
<P>
   So we stumbled erect and dragged on clothes. I fetched coffees
from the lodge's breakfast bar. And at the stroke of 6 we climbed
aboard a bus for an all-day excursion into this 6-million-acre park
and preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing the wildlife from a bus window may sound a bit effete,
but it minimizes vehicle traffic on the park's one access road.
What's more, there are creatures out here that _ unless you happen
to be a world-class sprinter _ are more prudently observed from a
machine than on foot.
</P>
<P>
   During our first week in other parts of the state, few beasts
except marine animals had shown themselves. But today, the
literature promised, would be different. And it was.
</P>
<P>
   Two things, especially, a traveler here hopes to see. One is a
grizzly bear. The other is Mt. McKinley, or Denali (``the high
one'') in the language of the native Athabascans _ at 20,320 feet
the tallest mountain in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Great mountains generate their own weather and often are
wreathed in clouds though the rest of the sky may be clear.
There've been only 20 days this summer, we're told, when the view
of McKinley wasn't all or partly obscured, and this day was no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   But with bears, said our driver-narrator, the chances were
better. There are between 200 and 300 grizzlies in the park. This
computes to about one bear every 38 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be making rest stops during the day,'' the driver said.
``From time to time, a bear will come through one of the rest
areas. If one approaches, get back on the bus in a quiet and
orderly way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the second stop, overlooking a broad valley, a bear did
appear, a solitary giant lumbering across the dry river bed just
below. You'd be astonished at how quietly, how orderly _ and how
(ital)fast(end ital) _ the bus seats filled up.
</P>
<P>
   And that was only the beginning. Before the outing ended, we'd
seen 494 square miles worth of grizzlies, no fewer than 13 of them.
A sow and her yearling cub came over a ridge and crossed just
behind us. The cub stopped to pick up an orange cone marking some
road repair. Then, pronouncing it unpalatable, he brushed it aside
and they ambled away.
</P>
<P>
   The richness of life there on the high tundra was amazing. My
notebook contains the tally.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the bears, no fewer than 19 caribou were seen, grazing
the wild meadows. And 34 white Dall sheep perched on grassy patches
among the severely up-slanted mountain faces.
</P>
<P>
   Also two cow moose with lugubrious snouts and no antlers; 14
willow ptarmigan adults, their plumage just starting to turn white,
with more scurring chicks than could be counted; one each of
Steller jays and black-billed magpies; two Arctic ground squirrels,
and one hoary marmot, clinging precariously to a gnarled branch
overhanging a sheer drop of hundreds of feet.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was a fine day of creature watching. And the box
lunches were tasty.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, after turning back toward the lodge, the driver
announced he would suspend his commentary in order to give full
attention to the road.
</P>
<P>
   It's good that he did because on the worst part, rounding
Polychrome Mountain, our bus now was in the outer lane, next to the
precipice. My seat was on that side, and on tight turns sometimes I
could see no gravel road at all _ only yawning emptiness and
certain death.
</P>
<P>
   I experienced a religious conversion, however, and thus was
able, barely, to prevent myself from fainting.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   The above are notes from yesterday. This afternoon we boarded a
domed train car on the elegant Midnight Sun Express for the 7-hour
ride back to Anchorage, and the start of the next phase of this
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Though we're traveling independently, we seem to have fallen in
with some large tour group composed mainly of older folks.
Excluding our daughters in their 20s, we are _ I grieve to admit _
far gone in adulthood ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   But these were (ital)senior(end ital) seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Stimulating beverages were available, and if you think the fun
stops at 80 you are badly mistaken. By the time we neared
Anchorage, some of those people were in full throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be arriving at the terminal soon,'' the hostess on the
car announced over the loudspeaker. ``Be sure to collect all your
belongings, and please be careful on the stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The stairway from the upper-level seating to the track-level
exit below was tricky, with tight turns.
</P>
<P>
   What the hostess meant to say, I'm sure, is that it would be a
shame for anyone to take a tumble with the trip so near its end.
</P>
<P>
   What she said instead _ no doubt an innocent slip _ was: ``We'd
hate for anyone to fall down the steps (ital)this late in life.(end
ital)''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody complained. There was no sign anyone even heard. The
folks behind us were calling for another round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
