<HEADLINE>
KFI PROMOTION A BELLRINGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; If you got a message at home from talk radio
KFI-AM (640) morning host Bill Handel, join the club.
</P>
<P>
   The station hit upon an unusual marketing scheme to publicize
Handel's daily 8 a.m. updates on President Clinton. About 200,000
area residents received a phone call from Handel.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Turner, KFI's marketing director, had heard of a company
that leaves mass messages on answering machines throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we had Bill record a personal message reminding people to
tune into his Clinton updates, and it got left on machines
throughout Los Angeles,'' Turner explained Tuesday. ``Bill's really
fired up about the Clinton situation. That's all he can talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Handel's auto-dialed message, he introduces himself, saying,
``Please listen tomorrow morning at 8 on KFI-AM (640). Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Handel said the response was ``pretty terrific. A lot of people
called complaining and screaming, of course. They don't call to say
they're happy with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said this was the first time he had heard of such a
promotion being used in radio. The messages were left several days
last week and Monday and Tuesday of this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've even had people calling the station to return Handel's
calls, saying, `I got your message. Thanks for calling,' '' Turner
said. ``And a lot of people said they were going to save the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDLY RIVALRY: They square off on the air, but competing talk
hosts Joe Crummey and Wayne Resnick share the spotlight tonight at
a West Hollywood club.
</P>
<P>
   KABC-AM's (790) Crummey and KFI's Resnick are longtime friends
and guitarists. They'll perform covers and original songs at 9 p.m.
at the Crooked Bar, below Coconut Teaszer (8121 Sunset Blvd., West
Hollywood).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like KFI and KABC are getting together,'' Crummey says.
</P>
<P>
   On the air, though, each host is promoting the event without
uttering the other's name, referring instead to a ``mystery
guest.''
</P>
<P>
   Crummey and Resnick, who met several years ago when both were
working at KFI, compete on their respective stations on Saturday
evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're wondering if people who flip back and forth have figured
it out,'' Crummey said. ``We don't want to mention each other on
the air, but we've remained buds over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Crummey said admission tonight is free ``if you mention either
Joe or Wayne at the door.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT STUFF: Local attorneys Ken Kahn and Gerald Wolfe are
tapped to host ``Ken and Jerry's Courtroom Deli'' at 11 p.m.
Sundays on KLSX-FM (97.1) ... Radio &AMP; Records mag hints Phoenix
morning mouth Supersnake being lured to L.A. ... KABC's newly hired
Al Rantel moved into the 12:15 p.m. slot Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
