<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN &LR;      09-22 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 A group based on friendship  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ It started with a Monday night tennis game.
The evenings always ended with dinner and discussions about work
and family.
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to another, and the women decided to create an
organization for business owners like themselves. While they
haven't ruled out including men, the Executive Exchange now has 14
female members.
</P>
<P>
   They are lawyers and architects, consultants and manufacturers,
married and single, in their 30s and their 50s, but all have
employees and are intentionally not in competing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really wanted and needed was my own advisory board,''
said Patricia Kane, managing principal of the Schuster Kane
Alliance Co., and one of the exchange's founding members. ``We're a
great resource, and we've also become good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in its third year, the members take turns arranging the
meetings, the food and the programs. They always follow the same
schedule: They begin with discussion about concerns they have at
work. The conversations range from when to implement pay raises and
how to encourage a difficult employee, to where to find a lawyer
and who knows a good nanny.
</P>
<P>
   The women then compile a list of questions for their guest, who
speaks during lunch. On a recent Friday, Judy Hohn, president and
owner of Serenity the Rejuvenating Day Spa, arranged for a speaker
on team building.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the meetings are never dull. Even with a
guest, they are sprinkled with laughter, questions and debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really good at challenging each other,'' said Kane.
``But confidentiality is one of the most important parts. What I
say here never leaves this room.''
</P>
<P>
   Tula Turner, president of Supreme Insulation, said she values
not only the camaraderie but the expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It validates you not only as a woman, but as a
businessperson,'' she said. ``You know that you're doing the right
things.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a time when these busy women can recharge their
batteries. They leave with answers and encouragement they often
can't get from employees, family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one place where people understand when I say
something,'' said Becky Blades, president of Blades and Associates,
a public relations firm. ``These people can all relate.''
</P>
<P>
   And the women also take the time for others. Each year they
collect money for a particular charity. This year it's Katy's
Place.
</P>
<P>
   Members have wondered if their model can be duplicated. I think
it can.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're at the top or starting out, we all need support,
friendship and nurturing. Let's follow their lead and duplicate a
good thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
