<SLUG> BC-MERCANTILE-BANK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MERCANTILE SUBSIDIARY IS BROKERING TAX CREDITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Mercantile Bank has launched an innovative way of
trading Missouri tax credits that finances historic renovations and
community development projects.
</P>
<P>
   Mercantile has created a subsidiary, the Missouri Tax Credit
Clearinghouse, that buys tax credits from nonprofit organizations
and community redevelopment projects, then sells them to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Governor project in Jefferson City, Mo., provides an
example of how the program works. The long-vacant hotel is being
restored as an office building.
</P>
<P>
   Through the clearinghouse, Mercantile is investing about $5
million in equity to pay for the renovations. The bank says it
doesn't need the tax credits associated with the investment and
will sell them next year to investors who can benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects that are benefiting from the program are the
Northland Lofts, in which the historic Bella Hess building in North
Kansas City, Mo., is being converted to a 152-unit apartment
building, and the recently restored Elms Resort &AMP; Spa in Excelsior
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bader, president of Mercantile's Community Development
Corp., which specializes in community-related projects requiring
special financing, said many people wanted to invest in community
development projects but didn't understand how tax credits work or
which projects are a good match for them.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she added, ``Some companies and nonprofits
have more tax credits than they can use. The Missouri Tax Credit
Clearinghouse brings them together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUILDING-WASTE23-COX     09-22 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDING-WASTE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOES CHARGE FEDERAL BUILDING WILL BE MORE COSTLY THAN ESTIMATED
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opponents plan to charge Wednesday that a proposed
2.1 million-square-foot Patent and Trademark Office headquarters
will cost more than the $1.3 billion estimated by the government
and could become a federal extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen buildings come and go for 30 years, and the same
mistakes are made,'' said Pete Sepp, an official with the National
Taxpayers Union who is scheduled to testify at a Senate hearing on
the controversial project. ``With this one, we have a chance to
make changes before the concrete is poured.''
</P>
<P>
   The building that has been dubbed by some a ``Taj Mahal''
because of amenities such as a sculpture garden and landscaped park
planned for the still-undetermined suburban Virginia site.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters point to government studies concluding that a new
consolidated complex would save $72 million over the costs of
remaining in 18 older buildings scattered in Arlington, Va., across
the Potomac River from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   However, opponents were set to fire back at Wednesday's hearing
with a new private study by the Arthur Andersen consulting firm
projecting that, rather than a saving money, the move would
increase costs by $47.7 million. The review was ordered by Charles
E. Smith, the current landlord, which is fighting to keep the
Patent and Trademark Office (PTO) in his buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The new study concluded that government estimates had not
anticipated cost overruns or delays that occur with most federal
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least, the Andersen study means more analysis is
necessary,'' Sepp said. ``If this much money is at stake, what's
the harm in taking a few more months to see if the option PTO wants
to pursue is the best one?''
</P>
<P>
   The new Patent headquarters has already cleared most of the
obstacles in Congress, with backing from Sen. John Warner, R-Va.,
whose transportation and infrastructure Subcommittee has set
Wednesday's hearing. The government schedule calls for a contract
to be awarded by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The project has been lampooned for lavish plans outlined in a
government study for furnishing the new headquarters. A list of
``budgeted furniture expenditures'' included $250 shower curtains,
$1,000 for a coat rack, $13,298 for a modular table, and $83 each
for waste baskets, not to mention cribs at $750 apiece and desks
costing as much as $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Patents and Trademarks Commissioner Bruce A. Lehman wrote Warner
recently that this list was a ``worst-case scenario'' and added,
``I personally assure you, we have never contemplated nor will we
spend $250 for a shower curtain, $750 for a crib, or $1,000 for a
coat rack.''
</P>
<P>
   His spokeswoman, Brigid(cq) Quinn said Tuesday that the cost for
the project would go no higher than $1.3 billion for rent plus $135
in relocation costs for the Patent office, whose work force is
expected to expand to 7,100 by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no unanticipated costs,'' she said, citing a
congressional ceiling for the project.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics are not convinced. ``Virtually every project has
some kind of ceiling on it, and those ceilings are full of holes,''
said Sepp, noting that NASA had a ceiling for the space station but
keeps asking Congress for additional funding.
</P>
<P>
   Critics often compare the Patent building to the recently
completed Ronald Reagan Office Building, a massive 3
million-square-foot structure down the street from Capitol Hill
that was first estimated to cost under $400 million. It came in at
$800 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan building has a distinct advantage, however. It was
built to last 200 years and is owned by the government. The
proposed PTO building would cost $1.3 billion in rent over 20
years, and after that, the government would have only an expired
lease.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the decision to lease instead of own, Quinn said it
was because of the way the federal government budgets. ``We'd spend
perhaps $700 million to build it, and it would have to be taken
from one year's budget,'' she said. ``The determination was made
that a long-term lease was the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
