<HEADER>
A8623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FASHIONS-LADN     09-22 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FASHIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARDROBE GOES WILD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Could Drew Carey replace Jerry Seinfeld as TV's
next trendsetter?
</P>
<P>
   Will women start copying the fashion stance of Mimi, now that
frizzy-haired Elaine is gone?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Carey was last seen as a lovable teddy bear kinda
guy with nerdy horn-rimmed glasses and a crew cut. But beginning
tonight he's a babe magnet.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit last week to the Burbank studios where ``The Drew
Carey Show'' is filmed, the Daily News discovered a new and
improved Drew who's as stylin' as a blue-collar guy from Cleveland
can get, from his surfer-blond hair and goatee to his sexy wire-rim
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Carey says the new look reflects his TV character's interest in
joining a band, but he admits he does like the look and wants to
keep it.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carey, ``This season I go a little crazy. It's my
rock 'n' roll thing, so I grow a beard and get new glasses _
they're by Matsuda _ which I think I may wear a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he chuckles, pauses and says, ``But I can't look sexy in
every show. I'm really a Gap kind of guy on and off the set. And in
an upcoming episode, I have an affair with Mimi (played by Kathy
Kinney), and even then I don't wear anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even a sexy bathrobe or bikini briefs?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I dropped my pants, all you'd see is green plaid Gap
boxers,'' he confides.
</P>
<P>
   Mimi, on the other hand, plans on major drama for her romantic
interlude. ``Maybe a hot pink negligee with marabou feathers and
leopard accents. You know, something sophisticated but colorful,''
says Kinney.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated? A character who wears circus tents trimmed with
sequins as office attire and applies eye shadow with a trowel?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand the character,'' says Kinney, who
rarely wears makeup and prefers the understated style of Armani in
real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mimi thinks she's beautiful like Elizabeth Taylor ... or
better. She wears bright colors and sequins, attracting men like
the bee is attracted to brightly colored flowers ... so she'd never
wear brown, black or navy except on the bottom of her shoes,''
Kinney explains.
</P>
<P>
   In the studio's wardrobe room, it's clear which side of the
closet is Mimi's. ``Drew Carey'' costume designer Julie Rhine says
the Mimi character loves color, ruffles, huge earrings, animal
prints, fake fur and real feathers, so she and her design team are
constantly creating new dresses and matching coats or scarves. Even
her wide size-9 shoes are custom made, whether they're lime green
leather or red-white-and-blue sequins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dressing Mimi is the biggest challenge of my job. I have to
constantly come up with new ideas so the wardrobe doesn't get
stale, because I think viewers do remember her outfits,'' says
Rhine. She adds that Mimi's fashion tastes are evolving, and this
season you'll see more international-looking costumes, including
some designs out of Chinese silk, instead of last year's '70s
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Is there ever going to be a major Mimi make-over?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. If you put her in jeans and a T-shirt, she wouldn't stand
out ... she wouldn't be Mimi,'' says the designer. According to
Rhine, Mimi would be unhappy in boring suits or twinsets, but she
loves ruffles, baby doll dresses with tiny purses, swing-dress
silhouettes and bias-cut skirts, as well as long vests with billowy
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto on the makeup. Makeup artist Robert Germain says Mimi's
trademark peacock blue eye shadow _ a blend of blues by M.A.C.,
Sebastian's Trucco, Make Up For Ever and La Femme _ will not be
washed off. However, he's seriously thinking of giving her a
different wig this season.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the Drew character is a lot easier. The sense of style
is very blue collar, exactly what Carey wears in real life. Even
the vintage ties the TV character wears to the office are modeled
after those the real Drew wore in his early stand-up comic days.
</P>
<P>
   The wardrobe is bought off the rack at local stores, says Rhine,
Places like Robinsons-May, Nordstrom, Macy's, Sears and the Gap
carry plenty of soft, muted colors in T-shirts, plaid shirts and
jackets, just the kind of look he likes.
</P>
<P>
   And the labels are what many men have in their own closet:
Cricketeer suits, Nordstrom's own label white dress shirts, Old
Navy sweat shirts, Wyn Spooner Hawaiian shirts and lumberjack plaid
shirts by Lemon &AMP; Soda. His shoes are from Thom McAnn in Cleveland,
and his wristwatch is often a Timex.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the new 'do and glasses, Carey will wear the same old
comfy clothes in upcoming episodes, including his boring brown
suits at the office and his his favorite Cleveland Indians jacket.
</P>
<P>
   But honestly, the man could use a little spiffing up.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mimi, who has no trouble telling people their faults, will
let him know that his tie is tied too short and that black shoes
and socks don't go with everything.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, just for laughs, she won't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ECON-ART-2N     09-22 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECON-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JAKARTA, Indonesia: down others. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And it has placed another 32 banks under the scrutiny of an
oversight body, the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the government took over Bank Central Asia,
Indonesia's largest private bank, which is controlled by Liem Sioe
Liong, an ethnic Chinese financier with close ties to Indonesia's
former president, Suharto. Liem is the patriarch of the Salim
family, which runs Indonesia's largest business group.
</P>
<P>
   (On Tuesday, the government reached an agreement with the Salim
group to acquire big stakes in its companies in return for
Jakarta's financial support for the bank.)
</P>
<P>
   BCA suffered a calamitous bank run last May, after the fierce
riots and looting in Jakarta, which were largely directed at
Chinese-owned businesses and led to the resignation of Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the relatively small number of banks under state
control, experts said the government was struggling. It has
installed executives from state-owned banks to run these banks. But
as analysts point out, being a midlevel manager at a stable state
bank is rather different from running an insolvent private bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like taking a guy who lives outside Chicago and suddenly
putting him in the jungle in Zaire without a compass,'' said
Fabrice Desmarescaux, a principal at Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton in
Jakarta who advises banks on revamping.
</P>
<P>
   The government is also moving slowly on another part of its
overhaul: carving out the bad loans of banks and placing them in an
asset management company, where they can be sold to private
investors. Such a company would function similarly to Resolution
Trust Co. in the United States, which disposed of the bad loans
from the savings and loan debacle of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Ramli said that the pace would quicken by the end of September,
when Indonesia is expected to pass a new banking law allowing the
government to begin selling the assets of banks to foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, the progress will depend on the willingness of
outsiders to hunt for diamonds in the wreckage. Peter Woicke, the
chief executive of J.P. Morgan Asia Pacific in Singapore, said,
``At this moment, it is very difficult to find foreign investors
willing to invest in Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the major impediments is Indonesia's social unrest, which
seems to be escalating again as people blame Habibie for widespread
food shortages. Indonesia's economic output is expected to shrink
by as much as 20 percent this year, compared with 1997. And its
currency, the rupiah, has not been able to rise above the important
psychological level of 10,000 to one U.S. dollar. That makes it all
but impossible for companies to repay their loans.
</P>
<P>
   For Bank Bali, survival means playing a waiting game. In a new
promotion, Bank Bali is encouraging customers to deposit U.S.
dollars. At the end of the maturity period, the bank pledges to
return the notes, plus 12 percent interest. The lure is that the
dollars will not be converted into rupiah _ a practice that had
discouraged people from depositing dollars since the rupiah seemed
only to fall in value. Rather than take a loss from an eroding
exchange rate, people had begun stashing dollars under mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   Such sales pitches seem to be working. After declining sharply
in the first several months of the crisis, Bank Bali's rupiah
deposits increased 10 percent from June to August, while its dollar
deposits rose 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bank Bali has also been forthright in disclosing the extent of
its bad loans. Firman said that far from doing harm, the candor had
bolstered the bank's credibility among customers. Other Indonesian
banks _ particularly those, like BCA, with ties to sprawling
conglomerates _ were more opaque about their liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its strengths, Ramli acknowledged that Bank Bali's
future was as perilous as that of its country. Another eruption of
mob violence could set off another round of bank runs _ this time,
hitting Bank Bali. It could also drive away investors who are just
starting to think again about Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   As an ethnic Chinese businessman, Ramli has more than financial
worries. After the riots in May, he spirited his family to
Singapore and then to Bali for three weeks to protect them from
anti-Chinese persecution. Now, Ramli said, he dreaded a new
outbreak of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Ramli said he did not feel hopeless. ``Indonesia will
always need banks,'' he said with a wry laugh. ``Indonesia may
disappear from the world scene. But as long as there are people
here, they'll need rupiah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
