 &HT;     DAVID-LETTERMAN ``LATE SHOW'' TOP TEN 
 &HT;     ``Favorite Games of Cal Ripken Jr.'s Career'' 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    10. Game 87
 &HT;    9. Game where he drilled Steinbrenner in the thorax with a foul
ball
 &HT;    8. Game number 666, because streak would not have been possible
without the help of his dark lord, Satan
 &HT;    7. All-Star Game 88 -- unforgettable half hour whirlpool with
Steve Sax
 &HT;    6. Any game where Hanson sang the National Anthem
 &HT;    5. Milwaukee 96: played entire game with open gunshot wound
 &HT;    4. 1985's ``Duran Duran Night'' when the great Simon LeBon
signed his bat
 &HT;    3. He cannot recall one game in particular at the present time
(number 3 is brought to you by President William Jefferson
Clinton).
 &HT;    2. June 8th, 1984 -- you should've seen the smokin' chick in the
first row.
 &HT;    1. The game when he finally got to sit his tired ass down
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     A PROVERB SAVED ... IS A PROVERB REWRITTEN  
 By DAVID GRIMES   Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   c.1998 N.Y.
<TEXT>
Times News Service &LR;  &QC;  If there is one fault with old sayings, it's
that they're, well ... old.
<P>
   While modernization is not always an improvement, one has to
admire the courage of an unidentified first-grade teacher who asked
her students to rewrite the second half of the following well-known
proverbs:
</P>
<P>
   As You Shall Make Your Bed, So Shall You ... Mess It Up
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably true, and a possible explanation as to why
first-graders are so reluctant to make their beds in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Better To Be Safe Than ... To Punch A Fifth Grader
</P>
<P>
   Also undeniably true. Better to hire a sixth-grader to do it for
you.
</P>
<P>
   Strike While The ... Bug Is Close
</P>
<P>
   The heel of a shoe would probably suffice for all except Florida
bugs, which require something heavier, like an anvil.
</P>
<P>
   You Can Lead A Horse To Water But ... How?
</P>
<P>
   Good question. But a better question might be, Why? Given the
temperamental nature of horses, it's probably best to let them find
water on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Don't Bite The Hand That ... Looks Dirty
</P>
<P>
   Nor the foot, knee, elbow or head, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   No News Is ... Impossible
</P>
<P>
   Brother, isn't that the truth. In fact, the problem with the
news nowadays is that the impossible has become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   You Can't Teach An Old Dog ... New Math
</P>
<P>
   Nor would it be wise to try, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Love All, Trust ... Me
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's epitaph, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   The Pen Is Mightier Than The ... Pigs
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about this one, especially if the pigs have been
elected to high office. Time will tell, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   An Idle Mind Is ... The Best Way To Relax
</P>
<P>
   I can certainly vouch for that, but we'd probably better not let
this get around as we already have too many idle minds as it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's Always Darkest Before ... Daylight Savings Time
</P>
<P>
   The best argument I've heard yet for year-'round Daylight
Savings Time.
</P>
<P>
   A Miss Is As Good As A ... Mr.
</P>
<P>
   Feminism knows no age limits, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Never Underestimate The Power Of ... Termites
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that this first-grader's dad owns a pest control
company? Either that or the kid has a great future in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A Penny Saved Is ... Not Much
</P>
<P>
   But save 1,000 pennies and ... well, you still don't have much.
</P>
<P>
   Laugh And The Whole World Laughs With You, Cry And ... You Have
To Blow Your Nose
</P>
<P>
   Which could cause the world to laugh even harder. Either way,
it's a good argument for carrying a handkerchief with you at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   Where There's Smoke, There's ... Pollution
</P>
<P>
   Is the EPA aware of this?
</P>
<P>
   Children Should Be Seen And Not ... Spanked Or Grounded
</P>
<P>
   Or deprived of sugary cereals, electronic video games, Nike
footwear and designer jeans.
</P>
<P>
   You Get Out Of Something What You ... See Pictured On The Box
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes not even that.
</P>
<P>
   If You Lie Down With The Dogs, You'll ... Stink In The Morning
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, probably, but think about the poor dogs.
</P>
<P>
   There Is No Fool Like ... Aunt Eddie
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Uncle Bob's no bright light, either.
</P>
<P>
   When The Blind Leadeth The Blind ... Get Out Of The Way
</P>
<P>
   The most astute commentary on American politics I have read in a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton says he knew Monica Lewinsky eventually would talk
about their relationship. Who'd know better that she had loose
lips?
</P>
<P>
   In his taped grand jury testimony, Mr. Clinton sipped lots of
pop and water. With his raspy voice, he probably was trying to
avoid any oral hex.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Clinton video tape, Congress released 3,183
pages of evidence. That works out to about one for each question
about sex the president was asked in his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   On the grand jury tape, Mr. Clinton says he had ``inappropriate
intimate contact'' with Monica Lewinsky. So remember: s-e-x is now
spelled i-i-c.
</P>
<P>
   What odd balance to this story. The president first gets well
known for his saxophone but later gets famous for his sexophone.
</P>
<P>
   While Mr. Clinton's grand jury testimony was first being
televised, he was giving a speech to the U.N. Which, we bet, was
full of diplomats wishing they were watching the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts thought Mr. Clinton came off looking better than
expected in the taped testimony. If nothing else, he'll at least
get a post-presidential talk show offer out of this.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other evidence released in the Lewinsky case was a
photo of the famous dress. We saw the picture and can confirm it
looks like a dress.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton said in his testimony that he wouldn't go into
specifics about his Lewinsky relationship ``in an effort to
preserve the dignity of the office I hold.'' Too late.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken's record of consecutive games played is remarkable,
but Aunt Ilse from Oelwein says she'd be (ital)really(end-ital)
impressed if he did it again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
