<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-REALITY (Washington) -- With the handpicked candidate of
the West conceding defeat to hardliners in last week's Bosnian
elections, Washington must now confront a new reality in the
fledgling country. By David L. Marcus. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CLINTON SCANDAL &LR;   &UR; (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) -- The White House tries to
negotiate a deal for President Clinton to testify before the House
Judiciary Committee in exchange for guarantees that the impeachment
process would either be expedited or even altered. By Brian
McGrory. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EVIDENCE (Washington) -- White House officials seize
upon omissions from the Starr report to show that the prosecutor
has presented a one-sided story. By Michael Kranish. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MA-TRIPLE-FATAL (Pembroke, Mass.) -- Three schoolgirls are
killed and another critically injured when their car hydroplanes on
a rain-slicked road and crashes into a pickup. The tragedy plunges
a small Catholic school into mourning. By Brian MacQuarrie. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-VOTE (Washington) -- The Senate is expected to pass a
bill that will make it more difficult to declare personal
bankruptcy. By Aaron Zitner. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-INTEL-LAYOFF (Undated) -- Intel is laying off 675 of 1,600
workers at the Hudson, Mass. plant where it makes Alpha chips. The
company is not reducing production but claims it can do the work
with fewer bodies. By Hiawatha Bray. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-WORKING (Undated) -- Federal poverty wage guidelines are an
inadequate measure of what working families need to live at
subsistence level, study says. By Kimberly Blanton. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-DEVILRAYS-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Peter May.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-BRUINS (Boston) _ It has reached ``take it or leave it''
time in the Jason Allison saga. By Nancy Marrapese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
