</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FEMA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEMA PREPARES FOR POSSIBLE GEORGES STRIKE IN FLORIDA
 &HT;    w/HURRICANE-GEORGES
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Spurred by weather predictions that Hurricane
Georges could descend upon Florida by Friday, Federal Emergency
Management Agency officials planned to mobilize experts Wednesday
to assess the region's needs in the event of a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   With relief efforts already under way for the hurricane-ravaged
Puerto Rico and Virgin Islands, FEMA officials will open a regional
operations center in Atlanta on Wednesday to help them remain in
contact with Florida officials.
</P>
<P>
   The center will allow Florida officials to keep FEMA
representatives updated on what resources might be needed in the
event of a disaster, said agency spokesman Marvin Davis. Such
resources would include energy, transportation, medical and
search-and-rescue needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anything they need, we will get it to them,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Davis said, the agency is cautious about sending in too
much aid too soon. Pointing out the unpredictable nature of
hurricanes, he said FEMA is waiting for a hurricane watch to be
issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything could happen,'' Davis said. ``It could make a turn
and hit Carolina for all we know. We don't want to put all our
resources in southern Florida and have it not hit.''
</P>
<P>
   When preparing Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands for Georges,
FEMA helped supply water, plastic sheeting, tarps, blankets, cots,
tents and other emergency materials. The agency also set up more
than 300 government shelters and deployed several medical and
search-and-rescue teams before the hurricane struck.
</P>
<P>
   Such a massive effort will likely not be needed in Florida
because, unlike Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands, many of the
necessary resources are already in place, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
