A8642 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-INTEL-LAYOFF-BOS &LR;      09-22 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-INTEL-LAYOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL TO CUT 675 JOBS AT BAY STATE PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nationwide wave of job cuts at computer chip giant Intel Corp.
has finally reached the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   About 675 manufacturing workers at Intel's Hudson, Mass.
chip-making plant will be laid off &UR;  &LR;  over the next year, but Intel
vows there will be no reduction in output at the plant, which
manufactures the advanced Alpha microprocessor chip and several
other product lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson plant employs 1,600 workers. Intel purchased the
facility from Digital Equipment Corp. for $700 million last year,
as partial settlement of a patent dispute between the two
companies. The settlement required Intel to manufacture Alpha chips
for Digital at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Digital has since been acquired by Houston-based Compaq Computer
Corp., but the Alpha deal is still in force. In fact, Compaq said
last week that it will begin using Alpha chips to power its
high-end Himalaya computer systems used by banks and
telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't change in any way our commitment to manufacture
Alpha under the agreement with Digital,'' said Intel spokesman Bill
Calder. ``What has changed is we think we can operate this
manufacturing facility more efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel has been on a nationwide efficiency drive this year, as it
contends with dramatic decreases in computer prices and competition
from chip making upstarts like Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and
Cyrix Inc. Computer makers are tapping a huge market for
ultralow-priced machines, and chips from AMD and Cyrix, with their
lower prices, are beginning to steal business from Intel's
premium-priced Pentium II line.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has responded by bringing out its own low-cost line of
chips called Celeron, and also by launching companywide efforts to
reduce costs, so the company can charge less for Pentium II chips
while still making a profit.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Intel vowed to cut its worldwide headcount of 65,000
by 3,000 workers this year, mostly by attrition. Even before then,
in January, Intel laid off about 1,100 workers at a chip plant in
Arizona. And in May, the company cut 600 more jobs by shutting a
plant in Washington state that made private-label computers for
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hudson plant, Intel is cutting back on employees who
actually make the chips _ process engineers, technicians, and
testers, among others. Product development and marketing workers
won't be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Like most chip plants, the Hudson facility runs 24 hours a day
on three shifts. The affected workers got the bad news Tuesday as
they reported for their shifts, but the actual layoffs won't begin
until January, with a second wave scheduled for next fall. Laid-off
workers will receive four months' pay, plus 1.25 weeks of pay for
each year of service with either Intel or Digital.
</P>
<P>
   To Argeo R. Cellucci Jr., chairman of Hudson's Economic
Development Commission and the father of Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci, the news came as a disappointment, but not a surprise.
``We don't like what happened but we knew this when Digital sold
out,'' said Cellucci. Digital's management had overstaffed the
plant, Cellucci said, and layoffs were inevitable under the new
owners.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci predicted the lost jobs would have little impact on
the region's economy, and that most workers would quickly find
other jobs in any case.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Blazar, executive assistant of the city of Hudson, said the
layoffs would mean lower sales for some businesses in the city. But
he added that the that as long as the plant continues operating &UR;  &LR; 
and contributes to the city's tax base, the overall effect of the
layoffs will be slight.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the Alpha processor, other products made at the
Hudson plant include StrongARM, a low-power processor chip designed
for portable electronic devices, and chips used in computer
networking devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
