<P>
   THE CLINTON CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JURY _ WASHINGTON _ A portrait of the Starr grand jury,
which turns out to be both more activist and more sympathetic than
people had realized. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CANDIDATES _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton may or may
not escape impeachment, but the path to high office has been
drastically changed by his ordeal. Now that a mechanism exists to
extract politicians' secrets via private lawsuits, future
candidates for the White House _ and perhaps lower offices _ may
think twice before running. The result may be a process that places
a higher premium on purity than competence. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHARACTER _ WASHINGTON _ Using psychological theories
that attempt to describe how such traits as integrity, ambition,
the ability to relate to other people develop to make up a person's
character, a New York psychoanalyst and political scientist
concludes that as a child President Clinton was alternately adored
and neglected by his mother and gradually taught that rules and
restrictions don't matter _ at least not for him. Stanley Renshon,
in the book, ``High Hopes, the Clinton Presidency and the Politics
of Ambition,'' attempts to set forth a theory by which voters can
systematically evaluate the character of candidates for president.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   LAWPROFS-CLINTON _ In the halls of academe, President Clinton's
performance before the Kenneth Starr grand jury rated less than an
A but better than an F. Experts in law and communications were
analyzing the president's responses to questions about his sex
life. Like much of the public, they came away with a mixed review
of the president's performance. (Keilman/Bennish, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-CLINTON _ The media is taking a lashing from a large part
of the American public for its long-running and uncomfortably
detailed coverage of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal. But newspapers,
TV networks and cable news stations have no choice but to call the
nation to an unwilling jury duty, according to media ethicists.
(DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JAPAN _ TARRYTOWN, N.Y. _ President Clinton meets with
new Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi at Rockefeller Family
Estate for the first time. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-GEORGES _ MIAMI _ HHurricane Georges' 120 mph winds
knocked out power and forced residents into shelters in the densely
populated Dominican Republic today, after plowing through Puerto
Rico and leaving at least eight dead in the northeast Caribbean.
Georges' powerful thunderstorms Monday left all of Puerto Rico
without electricity and 80 percent of its people without water. The
storm spawned tornadoes as it slowly ripped through the island of 4
million people, turning trees into missiles, flipping small planes,
exploding car windows and forcing tens of thousands into shelters.
Many areas, including the islands of Culebra and Vieques, had yet
to be heard from. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hurricane Georges barrels
through the islands, we prepare and watch and wait and buy up water
and other items. Tourists are asked to leave the Keys. (McLachlin,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
