<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS STRIKE FOR SAFE DELIVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Firefighters picketing for a new contract outside the
main station in Wellesley got a bonus they never expected Tuesday
morning when Peter Houde pulled into their driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's having a baby,'' the Wayland expectant father
yelled, as he jumped out of his Jeep. ``Do you have an ambulance?''
</P>
<P>
   In the back seat, Caroline Owen-Houde was in labor. &UR;  &LR; Already,
the top of the baby's head was protruding.
</P>
<P>
   The men broke out of their picket line and rushed to help. While
firefighters Mark Ritchey, Paul Delaney, and Lieutenant Joe Keough
tended to the mother, others alerted paramedics Gary Rogers and
Mike Doyle, who were stationed at the fire-house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will we make it to the hospital?'' the expectant father asked
anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' firefighters replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy smoke!'' said Houde, no pun intended.
</P>
<P>
   As Rogers checked on the mother, he became concerned. ``She was
almost too calm,'' he said. ``The baby's head was sticking out but
it didn't look like it was making any progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried that something might be wrong, they decided to transfer
the mother to a stretcher and head to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the jostling helped her along, because she delivered
right there on the stretcher in the ambulance'' before it even
pulled out of the driveway, Ritchey said.
</P>
<P>
   At Newton-Wellesley Hospital Tuesday afternoon, Christina
Elizabeth, 8 pounds, 5 ounces, and her mother were both doing well.
``I wanted a natural childbirth, but I didn't expect it to be quite
so natural!'' said Owen-Houde.
</P>
<P>
   Christina, the couple's first child and a real scene stealer,
had arrived on their eighth wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   For the firefighters, the delivery was ``a highlight of our
careers,'' Ritchey said. ``So often we deal with people who are
suffering after a fire. When you're able to bring a life into the
world like this, you feel really happy and proud.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the firefighters returned to their picket line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
