</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S POETS DON'T ECHO LONGFELLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No disrespect for modern poetry is intended when I say what many
others know, that poetry no longer connects with the body public.
</P>
<P>
   Those who compose poetry in English today, whether in our
country or across the Atlantic, write only for a small audience of
other poets. Recognition of today's poets is commensurate with the
negligible revenue derived from the sale of their ever-more-oblique
verse.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the poets starve. The gifted and canny ones obtain
lucrative grants or seats in universities as poets in residence,
often socking away six-figure incomes while teaching one course.
Yet few outside the hermetically sealed literary community know who
these poets are.
</P>
<P>
   Quite recently but no longer, in America they were such as
Robert Lowell, Elizabeth Bishop, John Berryman, Marianne Moore,
James Merrill and Amy Clampitt. They still are such veterans as
Archie Ammons, John Ashbery and W.D. Snodgrass; and the vaguely
established younger poets _ Edward Hirsch, Denis Johnson, Mary Jo
Salter, Diane Ackerman and scores of others at the same recognition
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Not any of these is as familiar to the general public as Sylvia
Plath, a growing legend because death (by her own hand) snuffed out
her exceptional promise.
</P>
<P>
   Not even such extraordinarily creative poets as William Carlos
Williams and Wallace Stevens became household names. The last such
may well have been Thomas Stearns Eliot. (In Joseph Heller's
``Catch-22,'' Pfc. Wintergreen says ``T.S. Eliot'' in response to a
rude question if any poet ever made money, and it sets off a panic
among the brass, who have no idea what T.S. Eliot may indicate.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Eliot may be seen as a demarcation point for the
intellectualization of verse. The poems of Edwin Arlington
Robinson, Robert Frost and Carl Sandburg never were mindless, but
common folk could understand and like them. They were the last
``people's poets'' in our country, along with Edna St. Vincent
Millay and Stephen Vincent Benet.
</P>
<P>
   In 19th-century America, poetry was consumed as readily as prose
by the workaday society. People who read the novels and tales of
James Fenimore Cooper and Nathaniel Hawthorne and Edgar Allen Poe
also read (and recited) poems by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow and
John Greenleaf Whittier and William Cullen Bryant and Oliver
Wendell Holmes; and by Walt Whitman and Sidney Lanier a little
later on.
</P>
<P>
   The saintly, folksy Whittier may have been the best-loved
American poet, but the most memorized one was Longfellow, here and
in an England that exalted him. Longfellow's reputation, like
Whittier's, is now somewhat diminished; but it is easy to
understand his tight grip on the imaginations of contemporary
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Narrative was the key to Longfellow's heavy vogue. He told
stories in verse, not only in distended romances such as
``Hiawatha'' and ``Evangeline,'' but in shorter,
ripe-for-memorizing verses such as ``The Village Blacksmith'' and
``The Children's Hour.'' By 1858, when Longfellow had attained his
peak of fame, his narrative poem ``The Courtship of Miles
Standish'' outsold every new American novel.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Allan Poe in critic raimant came down hard on Longfellow
as a plagiarist, citing the indebtedness of ``The Wreck of a
Hesperus'' to an old English ballad, among other pilferings. But
after Poe was safely entombed, Longfellow in 1855 duplicated in
``Hiawatha'' the quirky, unusual meter of the Finnish epic
``Kalevala''; and beginning in 1863, he borrowed the basic scheme
of Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales'' and the ``Decameron'' of
Boccaccio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tales of a Wayside Inn'' finds seven men exchanging stories in
an actual inn in Sudbury, Mass., near Boston. Each man tells three
stories, and of the total of 21, the first and best-known one is
Paul Revere's Ride, as familiar and exciting as it is historically
imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   But Longfellow is never quite a joke. Poets in search of an
audience may look to him and learn.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
