<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASS-ACT23-COX     09-22 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASS-ACT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VETERANS COMPLAIN THAT GOVERNMENT BROKE MEDICAL CARE PROMISE
 &HT;    Photos are now available in the National folder on the Cox
server.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small group of retired members of the U.S. armed
forces rallied outside the Capitol on Tuesday to insist that the
federal government keep what they contend is a broken promise of
free medical care for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were recruited with promises of lifetime care for
themselves and their dependents if they made careers of military
service, retired members of the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marines
are now told they are eligible for military medical care on a
``space available'' basis only.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we signed up that part of our contract was going
to be a life of trouble and war on foreign shores,'' said retired
Air Force Col. George (Bud) Day, wearing the Medal of Honor he won
during two terms as a prisoner-of-war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``But another part of our contract was that when we came to the
end of the line, we would have medical care for the rest of our
lives,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to fewer than 200 members of an impromptu organization
calling itself ``The Class Act Group,'' Day said the government
reneged on its part of the contract in 1956, when Congress passed
the Medical Care Act, imposing the ``space available'' condition on
medical care for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have admitted that even after passage of the
1956 law, recruiters continued for years to promise young men and
women free medical care in return for commitments to 20-year career
service.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends those promises do not constitute binding
contracts. Day, now a Fort Walton Beach, Fla., lawyer has filed a
class action lawsuit, seeking to force the Pentagon to honor the
recruiting pledges.
</P>
<P>
   The ``space available'' condition has become an issue in recent
years, as downsizing forced closure of many military hospitals.
This caused many retirees to find that space was no longer
available for them _ at a time when their own advancing years
caused them to become dependent on it.
</P>
<P>
   To receive any military medical care, they are forced to
purchase Tricare, the Defense Department's health care coverage
plan. And when they become eligible for Medicare, they no longer
can obtain Tricare.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on folding chairs at one end of the Washington Mall, an
area that routinely sees demonstrations attracting 100,000 people
or more, the small Class Act Group seemed dwarfed by the Capitol
and the monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing hearing aids and old medals, they vowed to keep up their
fight, while tourists strolled by.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was interrupted briefly by a summer downpour. Members
of the Class Act Group huddled under trees and against Capitol
walls until it was over, then continued their rally while they
waited, wet and determined, for members of Congress who had agreed
to meet with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to tell the government that you made a promise and
we carried out our part of the contract,'' Day said. ``It's time
you stepped up to yours.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
