<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY STATEMENT COULD HELP CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid the thousands of pages of evidence released by
the House Judiciary Committee is this line from Monica S.
Lewinsky's grand jury testimony: ``I would just like to say that no
one ever asked me to lie and I was never promised a job for my
silence.''
</P>
<P>
   From the White House point of view, that could turn out to be
one of the most important statements for President Clinton's
defense, undercutting allegations that he suborned perjury and
obstructed justice. But Lewinsky's statement was not quoted in the
original report by independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, although
it was paraphrased.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials Tuesday seized upon such omissions from
the Starr report to show that the prosecutor was presenting a
one-sided story.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that is abundantly clear...is how grossly unfair the
Starr report was in presenting a very one-sided account of the
evidence,'' White House spokesman Michael McCurry said. Starr
``found room for hundreds of salacious details that titillated this
country and embarrassed this country in the world...but it didn't
find room'' for a key quote that helped Clinton's case.
</P>
<P>
   The president's attorneys Tuesday wrote an angry letter to the
House Judiciary Committee, which is considering impeachment
proceedings, saying Starr's report ``significantly distorted''
Lewinsky's testimony and ``is stunning in its silence about
evidence that supports the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, written by Clinton's private lawyer David E. Kendall
and White House counsel Charles Ruff, continued, ``The decision by
Mr. Starr to specifically exclude Ms. Lewinsky's exculpatory
statements and express denials raises grave questions about the
fundamental fairness of the Starr referral.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that Starr didn't quote Lewinsky's statement,
that ``no one ever asked me to lie and I was never promised a job
for my silence,'' his report did paraphrase Lewinsky as saying
``the president never explicitly told her to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report then drew its own conclusion: Clinton and
Lewinsky ``both understood from their conversations that they would
continue their pattern of covering up and lying about the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be a classic case of the White House trying to find a
silver lining in the darkest storm clouds. The evidence released
Monday is filled with damaging statements and other material that
some Republicans say prove that Clinton committed impeachable
offenses. Indeed, the Starr report makes clear that prosecutors
believe Clinton and Lewinsky had an understanding that they would
deny having sexual relations. Even if Clinton never told Lewinsky
to lie, the prosecutors allege that lies occurred as a result of
the understanding.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Lewinsky was pressed by prosecutors on whether
the president encouraged her to lie, she put it this way: ``The
best way to explain how I feel what happened was, you know, no one
asked or encouraged me to lie, but no one discouraged me either.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, with so much focus on the evidence against Clinton,
White House allies have spent much of the last two days trying to
find something good for the president in the more than 3,000 pages
of evidence released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best news for Clinton is that Lewinsky, in her grand
jury testimony, expressed anger at early reports that someone at
the White House helped her write the so-called ``talking points.''
That is the document in which Lewinsky instructed her onetime
colleague Linda R. Tripp to say she did not know anything about an
inappropriate advance by Clinton toward Kathleen Willey, a former
White House volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky told the grand jury that she wrote the talking points
on her own, without help from Clinton or anyone else at the White
House, according to the following excerpts of her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Did you talk with anyone in an effort to get assistance
editing or writing or getting approval for what is in the talking
points?
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did you ever talk with the president about the talking
points?
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky: No.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Lewinsky is asked whether she talked with
Bruce Lindsey, the White House deputy counsel. Earlier this year,
some media reports suggested Lindsey helped Lewinsky write the
talking points or had done something else to help the president in
the Lewinsky case. But Lewinsky denied ever talking with him
substantively.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you ever talked to Bruce Lindsey?
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky: No. I may have said hello to him in the hall, but I _
but _ just in passing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky reportedly implied in secretly recorded conversations
with Tripp &UR;  &LR; that another Clinton friend, Vernon E. Jordan Jr., was
helping her get a job in order to keep her quiet. But Lewinsky told
the grand jury: ``I attributed things to Mr. Jordan that weren't
true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Tripp) that, you know, at various times, the President
and Mr. Jordan told me I had to lie,'' Lewinsky testified. ``That
wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, said
Tuesday that Starr excluded a lot of exculpatory, or exonerating,
evidence from his report that could help the president. Moreover,
Meehan said there is much more such evidence in the 16 boxes of
evidence yet to be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was a normal legal case, I think the prosecution would
be potentially cited by a judge for withholding exculpatory
evidence,'' said Meehan, a former prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what happens when you have a prosecutor with no limits
to budget and authority and leak out information that presents
their best case,'' Meehan said. ``They leaked everything they had
that reflected poorly on the president. I thought they would have
saved something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
