<HEADLINE>
WHITE NEIGHBORHOODS BIGGEST CAMPAIGN GIVERS, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The vast majority of campaign contributions comes
from neighborhoods that are populated predominantly by white
people, according to a report to be released today.
</P>
<P>
   The study, called ``The Color of Money,'' was conducted by
Public Campaign, a national citizens group that is pushing for
overhauling the campaign-finance system. A spokeswoman for the
group said that while the results were not surprising, this was the
first time a study has been done by zip codes and racial makeup.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, for example, 49 percent of the residents or
workers in one upper-income, mostly white zip code area _ 02110 in
downtown Boston _ made contributions, which totaled $1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, only 0.11 percent of the residents the state's 14
minority-dominated zip code areas made contributions totaling
$384,831, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Public Campaign said the calculations are based on 1995-96
campaign figures and census data. The group counted
African-Americans, Asian-Americans, Indian-Americans and Hispanics
as ``people of color,'' or minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of color are largely absent from what has become one of
the most crucial elements of the election process, namely, campaign
financing,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at 2,500 zip codes nationwide in which
minorities make up more than 50 percent of the population. In those
areas, only eight out of every 10,000 people give contributions of
$200 or more, the study said. By comparison, four of every 100
people in the top-giving zip codes gave such a contribution, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts said Tuesday that 80 percent of federal
campaign contributions come from about 0.50 percent of the
population. Thus, the finding by Public Campaign that most
contributions come from areas dominated by whites is ``certainly
what you'd expect,'' said George Pillsbury, director of the
Massachusetts Money in Politics project.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign contributors do not identify themselves by race, thus
making it impossible for Public Campaign to determine the race of
the specific donors in the various zip codes. But Public Campaign
officials noted that one recent survey of major 1996 contributors
found that 95 percent were white and 81 percent were male.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
