<SLUG> BC-TJX-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TJC COS. SAYS WARM WEATHER COULD TRIM CLOTHING SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of TJX Cos. fell nearly 16 percent Tuesday after the
offprice retailer warned Wall Street that unseasonably warm weather
in the country could hurt fall clothing sales.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of the Framingham, Mass. operator of such chains as
T.J. Maxx and Marshalls dropped 3 3/8 to close at 18 3/16 on the
New York Stock Exchange Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, TJX remains confident that it will beat its
third-quarter performance of last year, when it earned 31 cents per
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very comfortable with analysts's earnings estimates''
for this year's third quarter, said Sherry L. Lang, TJX's manager
of investor and government relations.
</P>
<P>
   TJX is expected to earn 37 cents per share for the quarter,
according to a poll of 11 analysts surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Going into September, TJX had projected that sales this month
would rise 3 percent at stores open at least a year, but
preliminary data suggest only a 1 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   September sales in the Northeast and Midwest have been hurt by
unseasonably warm weather, but in regions where the weather hasn't
been a factor, sales have been far stronger _ up a projected 8
percent on the West Coast, Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of recent volatility on Wall Street, investors have been
quick to react to any news that might affect a company, said
Raymond James analyst Michael T. Glover.
</P>
<P>
   Glover noted that several retailers have warned that
third-quarter results might not meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investor confidence is very vulnerable now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that TJX is ``modestly behind plan'' is in no way
``any reason to panic,'' Glover said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
