<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON FACES DECISION ON BRUINS' OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It has reached ``take it or leave it'' time in the
Jason Allison saga.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Bruins rejected a counterproposal put forth by
Allison and his representative, Bob Gerow. Tuesday the player who
led the Bruins in scoring last season turned down the club's latest
offer. Assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said there are
three offers on the table _ for a one-year deal, for a year plus an
option, and for three years. That's it, said O'Connell: He can take
his pick of those or take nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choices are 1, 2, or 3 or don't play for us,'' said
O'Connell. ``We don't feel there's any need to go any further. He
can pick the one with security, some security, or no security. We
feel we're giving him good options and the ability to make a good
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerow said he and Allison will now begin looking at other
opportunities _ namely, playing in the International League or
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those terms, I guess we're leaving it then,'' said Gerow.
``It would be nice if another team in the NHL would sign him to an
offer sheet or trade him, which Mike said they won't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Bruins' four unsigned Group 2 free agents, Allison is the
most important. Coach Pat Burns, who has remained silent on the
subject since camp opened, for the first time expressed his
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace Jason Allison; we can forget that,'' said
Burns. ``This guy proved a lot last year and was one of our top
centermen. I don't have anybody to replace him. We're going to have
to find a way to play around that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had somebody I could take in this lineup here and say,
`Now you do exactly what Jason Allison did last year,' I'd be
kidding myself and I'd be kidding the player. The guy accomplished
a lot, and we have to recognize that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating for us, but we have to turn the page and
continue going. I think it's going to be even more frustrating if
we ever do sign him a couple of days before the start of the season
and he hasn't had these intense workouts like everybody else. He's
going to be four, five steps behind everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed late last week that defenseman Kyle McLaren would
agree on a one-year deal, but that has fallen through. O'Connell
said the sides are divided by philosophy more than money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said O'Connell. ``We're not that
far apart.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said management has had no contact with the
representative for unsigned forward Anson Carter. Ted Donato, also
a Group 2 free agent, remains at home waiting to be traded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
