<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STRESSES `EFFECTIVE ACTION' TO SPUR RECESSION-WEARY JAPAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With economic turmoil spreading, President Clinton on
Tuesday pressed the new prime minister of Japan to spur growth and
shore up its banks with public money so the world's second-largest
economy can lead an Asian recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met at the Waldorf Astoria Hotel for three hours with
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Japan's sixth leader in six years.
</P>
<P>
   No concrete plan emerged from the session but Obuchi
acknowledged that actions by recession-weary Japan could have
``major implications on economies in Asia as well as the whole
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The president told reporters before the session that Japan faces
an ``increasingly complicated political situation'' because of its
politically divided Diet, the sole law-making authority. ``So they
have to work out what is politically possible,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The divided parliament in Japan has left financial reforms in
limbo even as the Asian recession spread across the Pacific Rim,
nearly capsizing Russia and edging toward Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton in recent days has stepped up calls for a coordinated
international plan to stave off a deepening economic downturn and
warned that the United States cannot remain immune. Western nations
repeatedly have pressured Japan to cut taxes to jumpstart economic
growth and to assist its financially troubled banks to help lead
the world out the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think steps we take in Japan to address the issue of (the)
financial system has very large implications worldwide,'' Obuchi
said. ``So I think with this understanding, I intend to make my
very best effort at addressing this issue. I am convinced that we
will be able to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Summers, Clinton's deputy treasury secretary, said
Clinton ``stressed the urgency of swift and effective action to
stimulate domestic demand-led growth and strengthen the financial
system in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said Obuchi assured Clinton that ``it was his intention
to take appropriate measures to secure an early turnaround in the
Japanese economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said Clinton also cited the United States' own history
to ``emphasize the need for the Japanese financial authorities to
infuse public money swiftly and in sufficient amounts into Japanese
banks to ensure they were able to continue lending on a strong and
sustainable basis.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said Clinton also
pressed for continued deregulation in the Japanese economy. She
said the U.S. this month will send Japan a list of steps it would
like to see taken in sectors such as telecommunications,
pharmaceutical, energy, housing and construction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Obuchi met privately for nearly one hour before
being joined by staff members for an extended two-hour session. The
initial meeting for tea was scheduled for only 10 minutes but ran
long as the two men struck up a friendly tone, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president invited Obuchi to come to Washington next year for
an official visit.
</P>
<P>
   The two met in a hotel suite at the Waldorf Astoria after foggy
weather canceled a planned meeting in nearby Terrytown at the
Rockefeller family estate.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi replaced Ryutaro Hashimoto two months ago amid a
political churning that left few people happy with his selection.
Obuchi even joked to Clinton about ``cold pizza,'' which was how he
was described, prompting Clinton to say he had cold pizza the night
before, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Obuchi also discussed North Korea's recent missile
launch, which they deemed a ``matter of serious concern.'' The
launch indicated that North Korea's multi-staged rocket has the
ability to hoist weapons at least as far as Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In his meeting with reporters Clinton was peppered by questions
about the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal, but he refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that I focus on what I'm doing for the
American people and that's what I intend to do,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
