<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS VOTE DOWN MINIMUM-WAGE INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., S.C., Fla., N.Y., Pa., Utah, Iowa, Vt.)  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans Tuesday killed any chance of
increasing the minimum wage this year, voting down a bill they said
would hurt small businesses because it would extract too much too
soon after the wage increase of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., the measure's
sponsor, was using the vote as a political trap to force them on
the record against a wage increase in an election year. Kennedy
ceded the point. ``It is a defining issue,'' he told reporters
after the vote. ``It ought to be an election issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have raised the minimum wage by 50 cents in
January and another 50 cents the following year, taking it to $6.15
an hour from $5.15 over two years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans expect any public-relations fallout from this vote
to be blunted in the next couple of weeks by their passage of a tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's vote was 55-44, with 53 Republicans and two Democrats
_ Ernest Hollings of South Carolina and Bob Graham of Florida _
voting against the wage increase. Forty-two Democrats and two
Republicans _ Alfonse D'Amato of New York and Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania, both up for re-election in heavily unionized states _
voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, who also voted for the 90-cent-an-hour wage increase
approved in 1996, has been careful to support an array of
consumer-related issues as he faces re-election this year. He has
courted labor unions, even if that has meant turning his back,
temporarily, on the business and banking interests that have
traditionally supported him and given him millions of dollars since
he became chairman of the Banking Committee in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard-working people are entitled to make a living wage,''
D'Amato said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said his bill would have raised wages for 12 million
Americans who worked 40 hours a week and still made only $10,700,
which is $2,900 below the poverty level for a family of three.
</P>
<P>
   In an impassioned speech on the Senate floor before the vote,
Kennedy characterized the issue as one of ``fairness, decency and
equity.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kennedy spoke, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, observed with
some amusement, ``I always enjoy listening to wealthy members of
Congress talk about how the minimum wage is going to benefit
society.'' He added, ``Some of us have actually worked for the
minimum wage in our lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans characterized the measure as a cynical move by
Kennedy, who, they said, had two motives: to make it appear that
Republicans opposed helping low-income families and to try,
procedurally, to kill a bill to overhaul the bankruptcy system,
which Kennedy strongly opposes. That bill, to which the minimum
wage issue was attached, is expected to pass the Senate on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who is pushing the bankruptcy
measure, urged his colleagues to defeat the minimum-wage increase
not on the merits but because of the danger it posed to his bill.
``This is a poison pill to destroy the bankruptcy-reform
legislation,'' Grassley warned.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, little groundwork had been laid to build public or
congressional support for a minimum-wage increase this year.
President Clinton mentioned it in his State of the Union address in
January, but as the Monica Lewinsky scandal began to engulf him, he
did little to follow up. This was in stark contrast to his actions
in 1996, when he twisted arms and triumphantly pushed through the
Republican-controlled Congress the first wage increase in six
years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued a statement Tuesday saying he was disappointed in
the vote. But virtually no one expected the measure to pass the
Senate, and House Democrats had not even bothered to introduce
corresponding legislation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With so little organized support for the bill, the multiple
business lobbyists who usually swarm around to defeat measures like
this had a fairly easy time disposing of this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can defeat a hike in the minimum wage six weeks
before an election, that's impressive,'' said R. Lee Culpepper, a
lobbyist for the National Restaurant Association, which represents
restaurant owners and had a deep stake in preventing the bill's
passage.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a room just off the Senate floor, Culpepper wore a
sticker on his lapel that said ``Too much too soon,'' an easily
digested message that many senators endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., made this point in the debate.
Noting that he had supported wage increases in the past, he said he
opposed this one because, combined with the 1996 increase, it would
raise the minimum wage by 45 percent in less than five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we raise the minimum wage,'' Jeffords argued, ``we make
it more difficult for these businesses to justify hiring
inexperienced, unskilled and untrained workers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
