   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT-BAN (New York) _ Peanut butter is under attack at the
schoolhouse door. Cheap, nutritious, popular and traditional, it
has nonetheless taken its place on the list of substances _ like
asbestos and lead _ that send shivers down the spines of school
administrators. Prodded by activist parents warning of lethal
allergies, by the claims of some researchers that peanut allergies
are on the rise and, not least, by a fear of litigation, growing
numbers of public and private schools across the country, including
many of New York City's independent schools, have banned peanut
butter from their cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LEBED (Krasnoyarsk) _ Russia's financial crisis has not
only rocked Moscow's political establishment. It has also stirred
many of Russia's farflung regions to set their own economic course
and establish price controls. A former general and the new governor
of Krasnoyarsk, Alexander Lebed has led the charge. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with RUSSIA-LEBED.
