<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-CHEFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AIRLINES TRYING TO SPICE UP AIRBORNE FARE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Story also moving in ``f'' financial category) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Although it's doubtful anyone will ever say, ``Oh
honey, what say we book a flight for dinner?'' Fort Worth-based
American Airlines is at least making an effort to improve the state
of airborne fare.
</P>
<P>
   The airline giant Tuesday opened its 10th Chef's Conclave, a
two-day gathering of 15 of America's premier cooks aimed at finding
ways to make air-cruiser cuisine tastier and healthier.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Britton, American's new director of food and beverage
services, agrees it is a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem: Try taking food that was prepared half a day
and a thousand miles away, keep it warm or cold, avoid turning it
into something resembling rubber, cardboard or mush, and serve it
with a smile at 35,000 feet to tired, cranky travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Many say that it's a miracle it's as good as it is, and many
food professionals would take the route of that Dallas-based
airline and say, ``Nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are keenly interested in generating a dialogue about what's
happening in the restaurant business and about larger trends about
eating in the United States and about what they see evolving in
food and food service,'' Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   From the conclave's start 10 years ago, the chefs' general
advice has been: Do only what can be done well. Keep it simple,
fresh and recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   But within that context, Britton said, the goal is to keep up
with trends, update menus, improve quality and service.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, he said, the chefs' input has led to healthier,
lighter meals, meatless entrees and more regional cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some suggestions from last year led to some new entrees in
first and business class across the Atlantic. Some of the chefs
worked quite intensely with us,'' Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Douglas, director of menus for American, said the airline
is looking at the possibility of giving passengers more choices of
food, such as salad bars and sandwich bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want more control,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for what the airline hopes to gain through this week's
conclave, Britton said it's a trade secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is really safe, reliable transportation,'' Britton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, as one of the top air carriers in the world there
is an expectation of good food and good service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There also is an expectation among our customers that we will
continue to try and get better. There is a higher expectation level
than with the so-called low-cost, low-fare carriers even if our
prices are competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton said American spends $10 to $20 per meal for domestic
first-class flights. It's a little higher for overseas flights, and
considerably less for meals in business class or in coach _ an area
the airline refers to as ``the main cabin.''
</P>
<P>
   Across all classes, the airline spends an average of $8 on food
and beverages for each passenger, Britton said. Other major
carriers typically spend $4 to $5 per passenger, and the nuts-only
carriers spend about 20 cents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs include Texas range-meisters Robert Del Grande of
Houston's Cafe Annie and the Dallas duo of Dean Fearing from The
Mansion on Turtle Creek and Stephan Pyles of Star Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The Left Coast/Southwestern contingent includes Alice Waters of
Chez Panisse in Berkeley, Calif.; Bradley Ogden of The Lark Creek
Inn in Larkspur, Calif.; Wolfgang Puck of Hollywood's Spago
Restaurant; and Mark Miller of the Coyote Cafe in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables include: Allen Susser of Allen's Restaurant in
Aventura, Fla.; Jasper White of Legal Sea Foods in Boston;
Chicagoans Nancy Barocci of Convito Italiano and Michael Foley of
Printer's Row; and the New York City medley of Larry Forgione of An
American Place, Douglas Rodriguez of Patria Restaurant and Jonathan
Waxman of Bryant Park Grill.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans' Paul Prudhomme of K-Paul's Louisiana Kitchen
provides the Cajun/Creole influence.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
