<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8731 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BP-AMOCO-NAT     09-22 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BP-AMOCO-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      SENATE SCRUTINIZES BP-AMOCO MERGER
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ron Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 22 -- Downtown Chicago, now the refining and
marketing home base of the Amoco Corporation, would retain the
American headquarters of one of the world's largest petroleum
companies if British Petroleum's proposed purchase of Amoco is
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Steven W. Percy, chairman and chief executive officer of BP
America, told a U.S. Senate subcommittee Tuesday that he expects
the deal to be approved by the end of this year -- allowing BP
America to close its offices in Cleveland as the new BP-Amoco
transfers its corporate offices to Chicago by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is expected to displace about 6,000 BP and Amoco
employees in more than 30 offices around the world, said George S.
Spindler, senior vice president of Amoco. About 1,000 BP employees
in the Cleveland area will lose their jobs, and offices in Houston
and London are expected to be the next hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing brought about mixed emotions in Ohio Republican Sen.
Mike DeWine, chairman of the Subcommittee on Antitrust, Business
Rights and Competition. While DeWine did not oppose the
acquisition, he expressed concerns about future petroleum mergers,
consumer choice, foreign policy issues, and the loss of a major
employer in his state's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The petroleum industry is one of the most important sectors of
our economy, both in terms of its economic impact and our national
security. Accordingly, it is the responsibility of Congress to
carefully monitor structural changes in this market to insure
consumers have as many choices as possible,'' DeWine explained.
``As a senator from Ohio ... I am particularly troubled by BP's
decision to move its corporate headquarters out of Cleveland.''
</P>
<P>
   Percy said BP is offering a severance package to its employees
in Cleveland that may be the best in the industry. The company is
also creating a $1 million economic development fund to stimulate
job growth in the city, and will make $2 million worth of
contributions to Cleveland community programs through the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine went on to discuss the trend of consolidation within all
levels of the petroleum industry, including exploration,
production, refining and retail. For example, Texaco and Shell have
consolidated their retail operations, and British Petroleum and
Mobil have an alliance in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As these companies consolidate, many are also beginning to
specialize on only one area of the industry. DeWine said the
BP-Amoco merger appears to be another step in the direction of that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine and Democrat Herb Kohl of Wisconsin, ranking member of
the committee sent a letter documenting their concerns to Federal
Trade Commission Chairman Robert Pitofsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned bout the possible impact of the proposed
BP-Amoco deal and its competitive implications for the petroleum
industry,'' DeWine and Kohl wrote. ``We are especially anxious
about its possible effect on local retail markets. Accordingly, we
urge you to give careful scrutiny to this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a spokesman for DeWine said the deal is expected to
approved.
</P>
<P>
   BP announced its $48-billion-dollar deal on August 11 -- which
would create the largest industrial merger in history. Once the
merger is completed, BP service stations throughout the U.S. would
be re-branded, making Amoco the national brand in this country for
BP Amoco. The new company will employ about 90,000 people worldwide
and about 40,000 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American shareholding could be as high as 50 percent when the
transaction closes, Percy said.
</P>
<P>
   The American branches of both companies are the descendants of
John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil trust in Cleveland, established
in 1870. By 1881, Rockefeller's empire controlled about 90 percent
of the petroleum industry in the United States. In 1911, the
Supreme Court forcibly separated Standard Oil into 34 separate
businesses, claiming it violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The largest fragment was Standard Oil of Ohio, or SOHIO, which
became BP America in 1987 when BP purchased it. Standard Oil of
Indiana became Amoco in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
