<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TV-RATINGS-NY     09-22 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BEATS THE SOAPS, GAMES AND TALKS ON DAYTIME TV
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL,
CLINTON-GORE) 
(jw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 22.5 million people watched the videotape of President
Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony when it was broadcast Monday
on the three major broadcast networks and three all-news cable
networks, according to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen estimated that for the hours from 9 a.m., when most
networks began their coverage, to 2 p.m., when the broadcasters
returned to normal soap operas, the sum of the average household
rating for all six networks was an 18.8, which translates into 18.6
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the cable networks, the daytime television average
last season was an 11.3 rating (about 11.1 million homes) for the
hours from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. The average for the three broadcast
networks was 13.0 Monday during the testimony hours.
</P>
<P>
   More people watched CBS News' coverage than any other. CBS had
an average rating for those hours of 5.2, while NBC averaged a 4.5
rating and ABC a 3.3 rating (each rating point represents 994,000
homes).
</P>
<P>
   Although NBC has the highest-rated show leading into the 9 a.m.
time slot, in ``Today,'' CBS has the highest daytime television
ratings generally, so it is possible that people who tuned in for
``The Price Is Right'' or ``The Young and the Restless'' at their
normal hours on CBS stayed tuned to that channel to watch Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cable networks, ratings were roughly nine times higher
than normal. CNN had about 4.1 million homes tuned in, MSNBC 1.1
million and Fox News Channel 650,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of the president's testimony gave CNN its highest-rated
day of the year, for the total day, and the rating for the time
period of the videotape itself was second only to the rating for
the prime-time telecast of Clinton's Aug. 17 speech to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   A comparable recent news event _ a lengthy daytime legal
proceeding of national interest _ was the second day of the O.J.
Simpson murder trial, in 1995 (ABC did not cover the first day).
That drew a combined three-network average of a 14.5 rating from
1:30 to 3 p.m. Eastern time (before the lunch break in the Los
Angeles-based trial) and a 15.0 rating from 4 to 6:30 p.m. Eastern
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
