<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRITERS-FILMS-2TAKES-     09-22 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITERS-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD LOVES WRITERS (IF THEY SUFFER)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Ivory boasts about the fact that in the many movies he has
made about authors, he has almost never shown one writing. ``I
never even for one second thought of him writing,'' said Ivory of
his latest character, the novelist James Jones, in the new film ``A
Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of the miserable outsider, an alcoholic tormented by
writer's block, facing a forbidding black Remington portable in a
seedy hotel room, is a commonplace of films about writers, and
Ivory has always strived to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is a long tradition of movies about writers, and
they present directors with a number of technical and artistic
challenges _ not the least of which is, how do you depict what is
essentially an interior, solitary, intellectual process in a visual
medium like film?
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in portraying a writer's life, Ivory said, is
that ``there is nothing to be seen.'' The typical writer's
activities are limited, at best. ``Would his eyes narrow, then he
leans forward?'' Ivory asked. ``Then he is not satisfied and he
tears it up?'' Or, ``There's some dramatic thing he witnesses? He
flies into action. He tears his hair out.'' Sometimes, for the sake
of action, the director shows the writer reading his work out loud
to people. ``My experience is writers would rather die than do
that,'' Ivory said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet directors are obviously drawn to these characters: There are
literally dozens of movies about writers, including ``The Life of
Emile Zola,'' ``Henry and June,'' ``Tom &AMP; Viv,'' ``Barton Fink,''
and ``The Shining.''
</P>
<P>
   And now there is ``Permanent Midnight,'' with Ben Stiller as a
heroin-addicted television writer. Woody Allen's latest comedy,
``Celebrity,'' which opened the New York Film Festival on Friday,
centers on a grasping, confused writer played by Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   Then, ``Shakespeare in Love,'' with a script by Mark Norman and
Tom Stoppard, about Shakespeare as a young man with writer's block,
is due to be released Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the figure of James Jones, played by Kris
Kristofferson in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' which was
based on Kaylie Jones' novel about her father and opened earlier
this month, is atypical of the form. Jones is apparently untroubled
by self doubt and creative blocks, and cares as much about his
family as his work. Though, like most writers on screen, he
definitely drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The stereotypical writer in movies, said Morris Dickstein,
Distinguished Professor of English at the Graduate Center of the
City University, ``is a person who stays at home a lot and never
goes off to the office, and becomes very moody at unexpected
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the lack of action in most authors' lives is one reason
filmmakers seem to choose alcoholic writers as subjects _ and, of
course, there has been no shortage of boozing writers to portray.
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald in the 1959 movie ``Beloved Infidel,'' for
instance, and Dorothy Parker in ``Mrs. Parker and the Vicious
Circle'' are only two among many who stagger across the screen.
Drinking makes for ``a much better scene _ whether a cliche or
not,'' said Ivory.
</P>
<P>
   In most films about writers, the artist, by definition a
subversive figure, is somehow punished by failure, both sexual and
commercial, for his outsider status _ something of a German
Romantic notion. ``Henry and June'' (1990) is based on a love
triangle involving the writer Henry Miller, his bisexual wife,
June, and another writer, Anais Nin.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, living in Paris in dire poverty, watches, sometimes with
tears streaming down his face, as June makes love to other men, and
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does have something to do with the status of intellectuals
in our culture,'' said Robert Sklar, professor of cinema studies at
New York University and the author of ``Movie-Made America: A
Cultural History of American Movies.'' In a society that values
enterprise and making money, he said, ``Just living the life of the
writer is a critique of social values. He becomes an ambiguous
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Barton Fink,'' John Turturro, playing a Clifford Odets-like
character, goes to Hollywood to earn money to support his grand
ambitions to found ``a living theater of, about and for the common
man,'' as he puts it. Barton is assigned to write a wrestling
movie. ``Big men in tights, you know the drill,'' the producer
tells him.
</P>
<P>
   Barton seeks the advice of the girlfriend of a Faulkner-like
novelist who is also toiling in the Hollywood fields. ``Bill's
wrestling scenarios are morality tales,'' the woman, played by Judy
Davis, tells Barton. ``He'd have the wrestler protecting an idiot
man-child.'' Finally, Barton gets something down on paper and he
phones his producer. ``I think it's really big _ and important!''
he cries, words most writers have uttered at one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   Dickstein, who is writing a book on the 30s, when many novelists
were lured to Hollywood, said that these films often take the form
of ``the revenge movie, where the writer has been called to
Hollywood and isn't properly used and appreciated, despite the
gigantic amount of money he receives.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer character seems a surrogate for the director who,
too, has inevitably been humiliated by Hollywood. He plays out the
director's own struggle between art and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a sense of failure or opportunism if you go to
Hollywood,'' said Robert Sklar. ``It's a reciprocal disdain.'' In
the 1950 movie ``In a Lonely Place,'' Humphrey Bogart portrays a
writer-turned-Hollywood-hack who is so bitter that when he is asked
to write a screenplay based on a book, he hires a young girl to
read the book to him out loud _ and the girl is murdered.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in almost all movies about writers, Hollywood is a
metaphor for a writer's hell. In ``Barton Fink,'' Barton works in a
dingy hotel room with the wallpaper oozing and peeling ominously
off the walls as he types. At one point, John Goodman, the devil
disguised as an insurance salesman, appears in Barton's doorway
literally engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   The primary punishment for the writer in hell, be it Hollywood
or some other place, is writer's block. ``In `The Shining,'
writer's block leads to insanity,'' said Dickstein. The writer in
the film, played by Jack Nicholson, who has taken a job as the
caretaker of an immense, empty hotel, goes mad and types the same
sentence over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writer's block often seems to be implicitly about impotence,''
Dickstein added. And release from writer's block is often
concurrent with sexual release. In ``Beloved Infidel,'' based on
the book by the gossip columnist Sheilah Graham about her love
affair with Fitzgerald, it only takes a few chaste kisses from her
before Fitzgerald is typing away madly.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the technical difficulties of showing what writers
do, or the self-seriousness of the practitioners, but movies about
writers are often littered with unintentional howlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``An artist should remain poor,'' Cezanne (Vladimir Sokoloff)
says solemnly to his friend, Emile Zola (Paul Muni), in ``The Life
of Emile Zola.'' ``Otherwise his talent, like his stomach, grows
fat and stuffed. I'm sorry, Emile, but I had to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say an author reveals himself subconsciously in his
writings,'' the Sheilah Graham character, played by Deborah Kerr,
says in ``Beloved Infidel.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mrs. Parker and the Vicious Circle,'' Dorothy Parker
recites her poetry to the camera in an incomprehensible drawl,
meant to emphasize her dissoluteness and depression. ``Oh, do you
enjoy Swinburne?'' she asks someone at what is supposed to be a
typical literary cocktail party.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the best howlers of all are in ``Total Eclipse,''
the 1995 film about the love affair between the French poets Paul
Verlaine and Arthur Rimbaud. Leonardo DiCaprio plays Rimbaud as a
bratty teen-ager with grandiose ambitions. ``I want the sun! I want
the sun!'' he cries to Verlaine, played by David Thewlis. ``Do you
understand me! I want the sun!''
</P>
<P>
   The most successful of movies about writers are those that make
fun of the form's cliches, like ``The Shining.'' ``I'm outlining a
new writing project,'' Nicholson says, with a smile that is a
mixture of the bland and the mad. ``And five months of peace is
just what I need.''
</P>
<P>
   Every writer, of course, longs for time to write. And, of
course, the audience senses that it's going to be five long months
of horror.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ``The Shining'' becomes a dark parody of films about
the domestic lives of writers. ``I'm really into my work!''
Nicholson snarls at his wife when she timidly interrupts him. She
ends up paying for her timorous demands on him _ in a big way _
when he axes her to death.
</P>
<P>
   The forthcoming ``Shakespeare in Love'' mocks cliches that
abound in writer films. Shakespeare, played by Joseph Fiennes
(Ralph Fiennes's younger brother), writes frantically with his
quill, scratches his ear while he tries to drum up inspiration and
falls asleep over his desk. ``Where is my play!'' Shakespeare's
producer demands. ``As soon as I find my muse,'' Shakespeare
replies. ``We're at least four acts short, Will, a recipe for
disaster!'' the producer tells him.'' What writer hasn't heard some
version of those words?
</P>
<P>
   When Shakespeare goes to his ``weekly confession'' with an
astrologer-apothecary, he lies down on the couch and complains as
his ``therapist'' says, ``Interesting, interesting,'' and sand
trickles through the hourglass marking the time. ``Words, words,
words,'' Shakespeare moans. And what writer hasn't said that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
