</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WORKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DETAILS COSTS OF RAISING A FAMILY IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With housing and day care consuming half their income,
working parents in Massachusetts earn far less than they need to
cover their families' minimum needs under new standards for
subsistence wages being proposed today.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for example, a single parent of one infant must earn
$47,244 a year to provide adequate food, housing and full-time care
in the home or in day care facilities, according to the study
released by the Women's Educational and Industrial Union in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A family of four with two children, one of preschool age and one
attending school, must earn $42,564. The larger family spends less
for basic necessities because it costs less to care for two older
children, one of them in school, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum standards are well beyond the reach of at least 40
percent of low-wage workers in Massachusetts who take home pay
averaging between $14,000 and $35,000 a year, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Countering the myth that families living outside Boston are
better off, the study found that a subsistence wage for families in
other cities or in rural areas starts around $25,000 and can be
much higher due to high costs of keeping a car running for
transportation to work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The study is the first to document, by geographic area in
Massachusetts, the true costs of raising a family by providing just
enough for rent, basic meals _ no fast food _ child care and
necessary expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The study _ one of seven state studies in a series being
coordinated by Wider Opportunites for Women, a Washington advocacy
group _ highlights the inadequacy of the minimum wage. It also
shows that such measures of income as the federal poverty
guidelines used to determine food stamp eligibility are outdated at
a time welfare reform has required that women who had been on
public assistance enter the work force.
</P>
<P>
   The findings could be an important tool in crafting policies to
help working families, said Mary Lassen, executive director of the
Women's Educational and Industrial Union, an organization
supporting women and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that self-sufficiency isn't achieved through
stop-gap measures or short-term solutions,'' she said. ``Strategies
that are going to create ladders to help families move to
self-sufficiency are going to require efforts on the part of many
constituencies within the Commonwealth.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, US workers are benefiting from this country's
seven-year economic boom. Employers are competing for workers,
especially entry-level and service jobs. The unemployment rate has
reached new lows _ Massachusetts jobless rate was 3 percent in
August.
</P>
<P>
   The WEIU study comes weeks after another study that showed many
working families are, nevertheless, losing ground. The study, by
the Tax Equity Alliance for Massachusetts, or TEAM, showed growing
inequality between low-wage earners and the well-paid. Since the
late 1980s, the bottom 20 percent of all wage earners have seen
yearly incomes decline by 9.3 percent, to $14,299 a year. The top 5
percent saw yearly wages rise 10.7 percent, to $233,110.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deterioration in the quality of life for too many
working families,'' said Jim St. George, TEAM's director. ``If a
recession comes and families still haven't recovered to where they
were in the late 1980s, there'll be a lot of families in really
tough shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic finding in WEIU's study is the huge impact of
day care costs on the family budget.
</P>
<P>
   As more women have entered the work force since the 1970s, child
care issues _ both finding day care and paying for it _ has become
a pressing issue for more and more single- and two-parent families
at a time rent, health care and other expenses are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   The study estimated subsistence wages needed by four types of
families in 40 different geographic areas.
</P>
<P>
   The two-parent family in Boston with one preschool and one
school-age child must pay $985 a month, or $11,820 a year, for
adequate child care _ that is 28 percent of their subsistence wage
of $42,564, according to the study. Child care expenses exceed rent
payments, which are $839 per month.
</P>
<P>
   It is even more difficult for single parents to make ends meet
on one paycheck. Day care for a single parent with one infant is
$1,445, or $17,340 a year. That is 37 percent of a subsistence wage
of $47,244 a year, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   State subsidies were provided in 1996 to care of some 35,000
children in Massachusetts. Yet while the the Legislature added
about $50 million to state funding for child care over the past two
years, 13,000 children remain on waiting lists due to inadequate
resources to meet the growing demand, said Elaine Fersh, executive
director of Parents United, an organization that seeks grassroots
support from parents.
</P>
<P>
   Fersh stressed that the issue of raising a family should be
thought of not in terms of high child care costs but in terms of
the inadequacy of wages to pay for it. ``While we call (state
funding) a child care subsidiary, it really is a payment that
enables somebody to work. Families, to be self-sufficient, need to
make a higher wage to pay for housing and child care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fersh said many more families do not qualify for the subsidies
and are barely able to pay for costly child care.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation is also unappreciated as an issue for families
who lack access to public transportation. Transportation costs for
families who ride Boston subways are below $100 a month, but
families outside the city who drive must spend far more _ about
$277 a month _ to get to work.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted in the early 1960s, federal poverty guidelines are
calculated by multiplying a family's food budget by three _ today,
food costs are far less than a third of household budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal guidelines, at least 10 percent of families are
considered ``poor'' by one estimate, said Laura Russell of WEIU,
who wrote the study with Diana Pearce, professor at the University
of Washington in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The federal guidelines, Russell said, are ``irrelevant to
today's society and economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
