u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-MURDER-PLEA-BOS &LR;      09-22 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-MURDER-PLEA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR DECRIES PLEA DEAL IN SHOOTING OF POLICE OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Gordon Perry pleaded guilty Tuesday to the
August 1997 murder of 24-year-old Epsom Police Officer Jeremy T.
Charron.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plea means that Perry will spend the rest of his
life behind bars with no possibility of parole, it also means he is
spared the ultimate penalty _ death by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   And that has infuriated the governor and the family of the slain
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, who appointed Attorney General Philip
McLaughlin last year, lashed out in a statement: ``If the brutal
murder of a law enforcement officer in the line of duty is not a
case for capital punishment, I don't know what is.''
</P>
<P>
   Charron's parents were not at the Rockingham County Superior
Court hearing, but were outspoken about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon Perry was allowed to decide to plead guilty and save
his life and Jeremy was not given that option,'' said Fran Charron,
Jeremy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction is one of sadness, disappointment, '' said Bob
Charron, Jeremy's father. ``It's my personal feeling and belief
that a grave injustice has been done. We as a society continue to
lose sight of how to punish people for their actions. The judicial
system today compromised itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is pending a judge's approval, which seems likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He entered into this plea bargain to save his life,'' Perry's
lawyer Richard Guerriero said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Superior Court Chief Judge Joseph Nadeau if he had
anything to say, Perry said, ``I'm sorry for what I did and the
pain I caused the Charron family and friends. I hope you all will
accept my apology.''
</P>
<P>
   The court recently ruled inadmissable incriminating statements
made by Perry to a State Police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the status of the case, the status of the evidence
and considering our primary witness was a co-conspirator, and given
the fact that his testimony would be subject to substantial
attack...it was my judgment that (the agreement) was a reasonable
result in the case,'' McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Asst. Attorney General John Kissinger, a prosecutor in the case,
believes ``a jury would have convicted the defendant of the
underlying defense of capital murder. There are always risks
associated with trials and this case is no exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry pleaded guilty to capital murder, a charge of being a
career criminal and four other charges involving theft or robbery,
some of them relating to a Manchester robbery two days before
Charron was shot. The agreement called for sentences totaling 55 to
110 years. Both sides also agreed that Perry would be imprisoned
out of state.
</P>
<P>
   The last execution in New Hampshire was 1939, when Howard Long
of Alton was hanged for the murder of a 10-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Charron was murdered only hours after returning from the
funerals of two state troopers killed in a shooting rampage in
Colebrook. He had stopped to check a parked car at a swimming hole
in Epsom at about 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Perry was behind the wheel and Kevin Paul, 19,
of Concord, was a passenger. Perry got out and shot Charron three
times, then he and Paul fled as Charron fired back before he died,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Perry and Paul stole a pickup truck, fled north
on Interstate 93, robbed a Campton convenience store, and shot at
pursuing police. They were caught in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, accused of robbing the store and shooting at officers
during the chase, agreed in June to testify against Perry in return
for reduced charges. He pleaded guilty to armed robbery and
reckless conduct and was sentenced to 16 to 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Perry had a string of robbery and burglary convictions and had
been paroled 10 weeks before Charron's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Epsom Police Chief Roger Amadon said he, for one, would not
accept Perry's apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon Perry's belated remorse and sympathy will not return
Jeremy to us, nor will it help heal the scars left by his vicious
act of violence,'' Amdadon. ``Mr. Perry took the life of a vibrant
young police officer without any show of emotion or compassion. A
police officer who devoted his life to commitment and dedication
without compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
