<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPINIONS LARGELY UNCHANGED BY CLINTON VIDEOTAPE, POLLS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL,
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE) 
(mk) 
 By MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The release of President Clinton's videotaped grand jury
testimony produced no immediate shifts in public opinion about
Clinton or the issues surrounding his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, according to several polls conducted just after the tape
was televised on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The public is still divided over Clinton's trustworthiness, and
a majority of those polled remain of the opinion that he has lied
under oath about his contacts with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But he continues to receive strong public support for his job
performance. In fact, one poll conducted by Gallup for CNN and USA
Today and one conducted by CBS News showed an increase in the
president's approval rating since the telecast. In the CBS News
poll, 68 percent approved of the way Clinton was doing his job, up
from 59 percent just since the weekend. An ABC News poll showed
Clinton's job approval holding steady at 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Public reaction as to how Clinton had appeared on the videotape
was mixed. Only a quarter of those in an NBC News poll said they
believed that Clinton had told the ``whole truth,'' while 60
percent said they did not. In the Gallup poll, 62 percent said the
president had appeared ``more as someone who is guilty of a crime
and trying to hide something,'' and only 26 percent described his
demeanor as that of someone ``wrongly accused of a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   But while respondents generally felt that the prosecutors had
treated the president ``fairly'' during his testimony, his
avoidance of some questions was deemed ``appropriate.'' Seventy
percent of those questioned by ABC News said he had been right not
to talk about sexual details, and 59 percent said the prosecutors
had been wrong to ask. His anger at repeated questions about his
sexual activity with Ms. Lewinsky was seen as justified by 63
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the CBS News poll, only a fifth of those who watched at least
some of the testimony said it had been more damaging to the
president than expected, and a third said it had been less
damaging. Two-thirds of the viewers said the testimony had had no
effect on their view of him.
</P>
<P>
   But in the NBC News poll, 42 percent said the videotape would
hurt Clinton, while 16 percent said they thought it would help him
and 29 percent said it would have no effect.
</P>
<P>
   The polls were all conducted nationally by telephone on Monday.
NBC News interviewed 508 adults, Gallup 631 adults, and ABC News
523 adults; CBS News interviewed 696 adults who had also been
interviewed over the weekend. The margin of sampling error for each
poll was from four to five percentage points in either direction.
But polls taken on just one day, as these were, are subject to
additional error because of the limited time to reach people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1950EDT &QL; 
