<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      09-22 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CHARGES STARR WITH DISTORTING FACTS AND OMITTING
EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL,
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-POLLS) 
(JT) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and President Clinton's lawyers
complained to Congress Tuesday that Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel, had distorted facts and omitted exculpatory
evidence in his impeachment report against the president.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing letter to the Republican and Democratic leaders of
the House Judiciary Committee, Clinton's lead private attorney,
David Kendall, and the White House counsel, Charles Ruff,
complained that the 445-page Starr report was ``a one-sided and
unfair manipulation of the evidence and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that the ``true goal'' of Starr's report was
``to embarrass the president and inflame the public.'' They warned
the Judiciary Committee, which must decide whether to initiate
impeachment hearings against Clinton, to beware of Starr's
selective and faulty presentation of a case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers said that Starr deliberately omitted any
evidence that might undermine his charges of perjury, obstruction
of justice and witness tampering against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff and Kendall specifically cited the testimony of Monica
Lewinsky in her second appearance before a federal grand jury on
Aug. 20, in which she said that no one ever asked her to lie about
her relationship with Clinton and that she was never promised a job
in exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   Those allegations form the basis of two of the 11 potential
grounds for impeachment cited in Starr's referral to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain now,'' the president's lawyers wrote, ``that the
Office of Independent Counsel has significantly distorted the
testimony of Ms. Lewinsky, quoting it when it suited the OIC's
purposes and downplaying it or ignoring it when it did not.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter continued, ``The OIC ignored all reasonable standards
of fairness in preparing and drafting its referral. The referral is
stunning in its silence about evidence that supports the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCurry, the White House press secretary, pressed the
attack in a briefing in New York, saying that Starr did ``grievous
wrong'' to the president by his selective presentation of facts.
Starr's report ``found room for hundreds and hundreds of salacious
details that, you know, titillated this country and embarrassed
this country in the world,'' McCurry said, ``but it didn't find
room for one sentence from the testimony of Monica Lewinsky, quoted
Tuesday, `I would just like to say that no one ever asked me to lie
and I was never promised a job for my silence.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Charles G. Bakaly III, the spokesman for Starr, declined to
comment on the letter, saying that the issues raised by the White
House and Clinton's lawyers were addressed in the report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not directly quote Ms. Lewinsky's statement to
the grand jury that she had not been asked to lie. Rather, Starr
summarized her testimony by saying, ``Ms. Lewinsky has stated that
the president never explicitly told her to lie. Instead, as she
explained, they both understood from their conversations that they
would continue their pattern of covering up and lying about the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The report likewise does not quote her denial that anyone
promised her help finding a job in exchange for her silence. But in
a footnote to the section describing the job search for Ms.
Lewinsky _ which Starr called evidence of an attempt to obstruct
justice _ the report states: ``The arrangement may not be
explicitly spelled out. In this case, for example, there is no
evidence that Ms. Lewinsky received an explicit proposal where
someone said, `I'll give you a job if you lie under oath.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who chairs the Judiciary Committee,
said that he had received the Kendall-Ruff letter and welcomed
future correspondence from Clinton's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the committee's staff told him the lawyers' central
charge of unfair editing of the evidence ``just is not so.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said that Clinton's lawyers are still
reviewing 3,200 pages of evidence gathered by Starr during his
seven-month investigation of the Lewinsky affair and made public by
Congress on Monday. The official said that the White House likely
would offer further analysis and criticism of the independent
counsel's case when the review is completed later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a brief picture-taking session in New York with
Keizo Obuchi, the Japanese prime minister, said that he had not
read the Starr report or the rebuttals from his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked whether he was paying attention to the coverage of
the release of the videotape of his grand jury testimony or other
materials from the Starr investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much,'' the president replied. ``Believe it or not, I
haven't read the report or my lawyers' replies. I think it's
important that I focus on what I'm doing for the American people
and that's what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
