u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NUKE-NYT &LR;      09-22 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO KEEP RUSSIAN SCIENTISTS FROM AIDING ASPIRING NUCLEAR POWERS
ANNOUNCED  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian and American officials agreed Tuesday on a
program to discourage Russia's nuclear scientists from leaving for
Iraq, Iran or other aspiring nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to create commercial projects in Russia's closed
nuclear cities, which are off-limits to foreigners and Russians
without special permission.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Cold War, the cities produced nuclear material
and weapons for the Soviet nuclear arsenal, but since the breakup
they have fallen on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear workers have found themselves without jobs, and wages
have been delayed for those who are employed. Earlier this month,
nuclear workers demanding back pay demonstrated in front of the
atomic energy ministry here.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, the United States will help the cities start
commercial, non-military ventures. Up to $30 million is to be
provided through the 1999 budget year.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement covers all 10 of the closed cities. The initial
assistance, however, will concentrate on three: Arzamas-16 near the
Volga river city of Nizhny-Novgorod, Chelyabinsk-70 in the Urals,
and Krasnoyarsk-26 in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was signed Tuesday in Vienna by Bill Richardson, the
american energy secretary, and Yevgeny Adamov, the Russian atomic
energy minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot emphasize enough how important it is to us all that
economic hardship not drive Russian nuclear weapon scientists into
employment in places like Iran and North Korea,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists, however, said the program was far too limited
given the scale of the problem, which has been aggravated by the
collapse of the ruble and soaring inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Luongo, a former Energy Department official who heads a
non-profit group focusing on Russian security issues, said it would
take months before the first funds can be dispersed because of
congressional reporting requirements in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said the assistance should be expanded to include, not just
the development of new businesses, but joint efforts to develop
environmental technology and other forms of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, a joint American and Russian panel will pick
the commercial projects that will receive money. American officials
said it was too soon to provide specifics but that the type of
project they had in mind was under way at Arzamas-16, where the
Russians plan to convert a warhead production plant to produce
automotive parts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to investing in commercial ventures, the fund will
be used to train Russian nuclear specialists in business planning.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides also signed a parallel agreement designed to
smooth the way for the United States to purchase uranium removed
from Russian nuclear weapons, another potentially important source
of income for the cash-strapped Russian nuclear complex.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is converting highly enriched uranium from nuclear
warheads into low-enrichment uranium under a 1993 agreement with
the United States. The low-enriched uranium is to delivered to the
United States for use as reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal has snagged over disputes about the terms of sale.
Tuesday's agreement does not resolve all the outstanding
differences, but the Energy Department hopes that it will lead it
commercially-viable arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
