<SLUG> BC-MA-TRIPLE-FATAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE HIGH SCHOOL GIRLS KILLED WHEN CAR SKIDS IN RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER   AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEMBROKE, Mass. _ They were field hockey players, nursing home
volunteers, church lectors, and cherished baby sitters. In the
summer, they played teacher, recruiting neighorhood tots for the
desks of their make-believe schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, on the soggy last morning of summer, they were
victims _ three friends, two of them sisters, killed on a slippery
road, their red, green and blue bookbags lying along rain-soaked
Route 53, just south of St. Thecla's Church.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen M. Clancy and Erin M. Darling, both 17, and Erin's
younger sister, 14-year-old Allison Darling, students at Notre Dame
Academy in Hingham, were killed in the early morning accident.
Police said their car spun out of control and into the path of a
pickup truck driven by an off-duty police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never gave anybody any reason to worry,'' said Edward
Clancy said of his oldest child. ``I mean she never went out on
weekends. It's not like you would worry about her in a car. And I
definitely wouldn't worry about her going off to school. You would
think she's just going up the road to school and that there would
be no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The off-duty officer, police sergeant Richard Simmons, and a
fourth passenger in the car, Shannon Courtney, were being treated
at area hospitals last night.
</P>
<P>
   The 7:03 a.m. crash, which the town's police chief described as
the worst he'd ever seen, touched off heart-rending scenes of grief
across the Notre Dame campus, where young girls in parochial school
plaid skirts wept and received counseling, and in the neighborhoods
of the victims, where friends and relatives carried trays of food
and tried to stifle sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those girls were the kind of kids that you'd want your own
children to emulate,'' said Tina McCabe, who lives across the
street from the Darlings in a handsome neighborhood with basketball
hoops in the driveways and potted flowers on the doorsteps.
``They'd play school in the summer and the little kids would be
their students. They put on plays. You just couldn't ask for a
nicer family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what they're going to do now. Those kids were
their life and to have them taken away like this is just
unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities, relatives and friends gave this account of the
fatal crash that one eyewitness called ``horrifying, horrifying.
The worst accident I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin Darling, Colleen Clancy and Shannon Courtney, all high
school seniors, had been friends for three years, a bond formed at
school and in the carpool their parents established before the
girls learned to drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took turns driving and I can remember when I was in the car
they would ask each other questions about their homework on the way
to school,'' Clancy recalled Tuesday, red-eyed and sipping from a
can of tonic in front of his home. ``We all shared the driving
until they got their licenses and they were all very responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin's sister Allison became the group's youngest member late
last month when she enrolled as a freshman at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, Erin was driving a 1992 Toyota station wagon,
registered to her mother, and after the Darling girls collected
their passengers, Shannon and Colleen, the girls made off for
Hingham, about 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Erin and Shannon sat up front, both wearing seat belts, Allison
and Colleen rode in back. Police are not sure whether they were
wearing belts.
</P>
<P>
   They were traveling north on Route 53 in a moderate to heavy
rainfall, when they hit a slightly inclined patch of road, which
Pembroke Police Chief Gregory Wright described as nearly
stream-like in some rain storms.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Simmons was headed south and, conscious after the
crash, told police that the Toyota hydroplaned, sliding across the
double-yellow line and directly into the path of his pickup. The
nose of the pickup slammed into the Toyota's passenger side.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Tracy, who lives down the street from the scene, said she
knew immediately that the ``slap-like'' sound she heard was a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing else it could have been at that hour in the
morning,'' Tracy said.
</P>
<P>
   At Notre Dame Academy, school officials called teachers out of
their classrooms and into meetings with grief counselors and clergy
who helped them prepare to deliver the news to their homeroom
students. It was met with stunned silence _ and then an avalanche
of grief.
</P>
<P>
   At the homes and in the neighborhoods of the victims, relatives
and friends began attempts to come to grips with how a day that
began with a routine off-to-school commute could deliver such
life-changing horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just the nicest family,'' said Paul Cina, who lives
two doors down from the Darlings and had been summoned home from
work by his wife after the crash. ``The girls babysat for our kids.
The Darlings have always worked for their kids. Their kids are what
they lived for.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Edward Clancy, a state engineer, recited the
academic and civic achievements of Colleen, who was attending
school on an academic scholarship and looked forward to pursuing a
legal career in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``On her learner's permit she had put down that she wanted to be
an organ donor, something I never would have done and I couldn't
believe it,'' Clancy said, between receiving hugs of condolances
from relatives and friends. ``So we called today and we told them
that she would have liked to do that and I think they're working on
that now. She gave to people even in death.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame Academy, renowned for its active student body and
competitive curriculum for girls, draws on 40 communities, and
officials said said most students who have their license drive to
school. There is no bus service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Ellen O'Brien contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8759 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-22 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE) 
 ANALYSIS: CLINTON REMAINS THE MASTER COMMUNICATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
(See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL,(sw) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He began with careful answers about his
understanding of ``the whole truth.'' He ended by saying he wished
he had even more time to answer grand jurors' questions. Throughout
his four hours of sworn testimony broadcast on Monday, President
Clinton dodged and weaved, feinted and bobbed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a spectacle that would have destroyed most politicians,
beamed across television screens with labels warning of its
explicit sexual content and rife with literally incredible details
and denials. It was recorded in the most secret forum in
Anglo-Saxon jurisprudence, then released to the world by the
president's political enemies in the hope that it would damage him
severely.
</P>
<P>
   And yet on Tuesday morning, as he has so often before, Clinton
once again bobbed up, buoyed by a bipartisan _ if sometimes
grudging _ consensus among politicians that after months of
bleeding, the president may have finally had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his life,'' said Alan Simpson, the retired Republican
senator from Wyoming who now directs the Institute of Politics at
the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard. ``His life is
bounding from precipice to precipice like a huge mountain goat,
bridging crevasse after crevasse and people shooting at him with
high-powered rifles and the other side crumbling as he lands, just
like in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting to me is did anybody believe that this man
would testify for four hours and not do well, when it was his
decision to do it?'' Simpson asked.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a big part of Clinton's achievement had to do with
expectations. For days, allies of Kenneth Starr and then
congressional Republicans _ perhaps out of wishful thinking _ had
spread the word that Clinton had lost his cool and raged at his
questioners. Instead, he held his anger mostly in check, and even
seemed broken and humbled at times, as when he confessed, ``I'd
give anything in the world not to have to admit what I've had to
admit today.''
</P>
<P>
   But another part had to do with Clinton himself, and with his
inveterate ability to appear revealing while actually concealing,
to seem to acknowledge even as he technically denies, to control
the terms of discourse even at the hands of dogged prosecutors. In
sum, Clinton is a master communicator and, more than any flat
printed page, the monitor remains his medium.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the president simultaneously testified that he
considered his old friend Vernon Jordan a truthful person and that
he could not remember Jordan's ever telling him that Monica
Lewinsky thought the president might leave the first lady some day.
Jordan testified that he told the president that Ms. Lewinsky
believed just that _ something no ordinary husband would be likely
to forget.
</P>
<P>
   But as the nation long ago learned, Bill Clinton is no ordinary
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good confidence man,'' said William Bennett, the former
education secretary whose new best-selling book, ``The Death of
Outrage,'' bemoans a national moral climate that would overlook
Clinton's misdeeds. ``He's good at what he does, and he wouldn't be
where he is if he weren't very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Bennet added, ``The public likes him.''
</P>
<P>
   So it does. Some overnight polls showed that the president's job
approval ratings held steady or actually rose a bit, even if _ as
the polls also show _ the public does not share his moral code, or
even his highly conditioned view of what constitutes sexual
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a wash,'' said former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas,
summing up the prevailing view. ``He probably helped himself a
little. I told my wife, `He knew that was going to be made public.
He was talking to the people.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is by no means out of trouble. Some of the most
important people he was talking to _ House Republicans _ show no
signs of slowing their review of impeachment proceedings against
him, and few seemed inclined to cut him any slack, much less a deal
on censure or some lesser punishment.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Clinton insisted that it was not his job to be
``particularly helpful'' to Paula Jones' lawyers in their sexual
misconduct suit against him, he once again reminded his adversaries
that he will not make things easy on them, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's opponents keep yearning for the magic bullet, and
they have for years, going way back before Lewinsky,'' said William
Kristol, the Republican theoretician who is editor and publisher of
the Weekly Standard. ``They keep hoping that some deus ex machina
will arrive on stage and rid them of this horrible guy. It hasn't
happened, and it's unlikely that anything's going to show up to do
that work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kristol said, ``The president is not going to
surrender, and his opponents are going to have to do the hard work
and persuade people to move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The public view of the president remains profoundly split, but
hardly undiscerning. An ABC News poll on Monday found that nearly 7
in 10 respondents who had actually watched his testimony found it
evasive, although an identical number felt he was right not to talk
about sexual details.
</P>
<P>
   So once again, Clinton, who staked his political claim on
finding a ``third way'' between liberalism and conservatism, may
have found a way of squaring the circle of truth and falsehood, at
least when it comes to sex. No one who watched the president's
testimony could doubt that he was acknowledging that he had lied to
some of his closest aides about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
Yet even in describing that behavior _ when he was not under oath
and not subject to charges of perjury _ Clinton steadfastly refused
to utter the word ``lie,'' ever sensitive to its political
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is the politicians of both parties, who know Clinton
best and have never especially liked him, who remain most sensitive
to his months of misrepresentations. For Clinton has misled many of
them before, in negotiations over legislation or the budget, and
they are wary to their core.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a history here,'' Bennett said. ``The people who are
paying attention are angrier. The closer you are, the angrier you
are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
