<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-FUSION-ANTIQUES     09-22 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-FUSION-ANTIQUES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANTASIES IN GLASS AWASH IN COLOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: R.I.)   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Toots Zynsky produces fantasy forms in glass that
look as fragile and festive as crepe-paper objects _ ruffled,
puckered, pinched and drenched with color.
</P>
<P>
   She uses a revolutionary technique to create the multicolored
tuliplike works: instead of blowing or casting these pieces, she
fuses thousands of glass threads into entire vessels.
</P>
<P>
   She began exploring this technique in 1982, when she lived in
Manhattan and worked in an experimental workshop, now called Urban
Glass. That year, her pieces caught on: the Corning Museum of Glass
bought the first piece she had ever made out of fused glass
threads, a work showing the threads rolled into a solid mass.
</P>
<P>
   It was introduced at her first solo show, which was held at the
Theo Portnoy gallery. Later, the Museum of Modern Art acquired two
of her glass-thread pieces, and the White House and 40 other
museums also bought her works.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ms. Zynsky (born Mary Ann but called Toots since infancy),
47, is back in New York for her second solo exhibition here,
``Toots Zynsky: Chaotic Fusion,'' at the Barry Friedman gallery in
Manhattan through Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 pieces in the show reveal the radical differences between
her work from a decade ago and from now. The early ones are
monochromatic and incorporate thick glass threads; the later pieces
are multicolored and use hair-fine threads. The pieces range from
$4,500 to $19,500.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, glass was the last thing on Ms. Zynsky's mind in 1971
when she enrolled in art classes at Rhode Island School of Design.
But the freshman courses in art proved disappointing to her so she
switched to glass. She was attracted to the craft because very few
modernists were working in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like walking to the edge of a beach and looking out,''
she said. ``Everything seemed possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zynsky became absorbed in glassmaking at the school. ``If
you wanted to, you woke up at 4 in the morning and went to watch
Dale Chihuly and others blow glass,'' she said. ``There was a real
choreography to blowing glass, a rhythmic motion akin to dancing
that appealed to me. It's very alive. You have to keep moving, you
can't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   She mastered the techniques of the craft _ blowing, fusing,
casting and slumping of heated glass. After graduation she spent
several years helping her husband, Duan Hall, an architect, build a
stone house by hand in Vermont and later running a restaurant while
raising their son, Diau. ``We were hippies and did not worry about
making too much money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the late 1970s, she returned to art, creating barbed-wire
sculpture. She later made blown-glass works wrapped in barbed wire
mesh and called the pieces the ``dust collector series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbed wire inspired me to use hot glass thread,'' she said.
``Both were all about camouflage and hiding, and about them being
the same thing sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, after her marriage had ended, she took her son and
moved to Amsterdam. She has worked there for 15 years and traveled
extensively abroad, picking up ideas for her art along the way. The
chaotic street scene she found in Paris inspired the twisted forms
and explosive coloring in the current show.
</P>
<P>
   The glorious color combinations she saw in Ghana convinced her
to ignore what she had learned in elementary school about mixing
colors. The endless arrays of delicate and brilliant colors that
transfixed her in medieval and Renaissance paintings in Italy are
indelible memories.
</P>
<P>
   Making objects with glass threads goes faster today than it did
when she started. In 1982, a Dutch inventor, Mathijs Teunission Van
Manen, visited her studio to see how she made the pieces. He was
shocked at how much labor pulling threads from glass canes
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than 24 hours, he had mechanized the process,'' she
said. ``He took a bunch of things that he found in my studio _ an
old beat-up drill, a worn-out hacksaw blade, some bearings and
rollers, a bicycle chain and a wheel. And he devised a Rube
Goldberg-like machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she makes far more diverse pieces in a fraction of the time
it once took. And she lays out each one, using threads of varying
colors and lengths, and placing groups of threads side by side in
layered color patches that she then arranges on a board.
</P>
<P>
   To fuse the glass threads, she moves the board to an oven. Then,
at several stages, she takes the glass from the oven, and, in
seconds, shapes the thin softened mass into a vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Next month Ms. Zynsky returns to the United States with her
husband, Ernesto Aparicio, a graphic designer, and their daughter
Julia, 8, to work in Providence near family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernesto needs to be in an urban environment,'' she said. ``I
need to be by the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, she's unsure. ``I don't know where my work will
go,'' she said. ``I've been thinking about some early pieces that
are like very fine net and I was tempted to make one for this show
a few threads thick, something almost impossibly fragile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
