u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      09-22 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS DEAL TO APPEAR BEFORE JUDICIARY PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY AND BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The White House is trying to negotiate a deal with
Congress in which President Clinton would voluntarily testify
before the House Judiciary Committee in exchange for guarantees
that the impeachment process would either be expedited or replaced
by a censure vote, administration and congressional officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials began privately approaching key lawmakers
with the vague offer of Clinton's testimony late last week,
officials said, and the concept gained momentum over the weekend
when Massachusetts Senator John Kerry championed the idea on
national television.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly emboldened group of White House strategists and
their Democratic allies on Capitol Hill believe a historic
appearance by Clinton before Congress, coming either next month or
early next year, would force the Republican leadership towards a
rapid vote on Clinton's fate, one that many Democrats believe the
president would win.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the national airing of Clinton's August grand jury
testimony, many Democrats expressed relief at his performance and
pointed to public opinion polls which showed little momentum for
Clinton's impeachment or resignation and, in one CNN poll,
indicated that his job approval rating jumped to 66 percent. Such
polls, Democrats said privately, strengthen Clinton's bargaining
position as he tries to strike a deal on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a proposal that is still being formed,
Clinton's lawyers and the Judiciary Committee would reach agreement
on a set of facts in the case, including multiple concessions of
wrongdoing on the part of the president in his affair with Monica
Lewinsky and its coverup, according to officials familiar with the
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would then appear before the committee to defend himself
on areas not under agreement, such as perjury and obstruction of
justice allegations, and to argue his case to remain in office,
said the officials, who talked on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Following that appearance, the House would schedule a rapid vote
on impeachment, officials said. The plan would require the Congress
to forego what are now expected to be lengthy impeachment hearings
that could extend well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``An accelerated, streamlined effort to help the country deal
with this in a much more decent way so the nation doesn't feel this
is being exploited for political purposes,'' said Kerry. ``Most
Americans don't have a lot of questions about what happened. Most
people of common sense don't have a lot of questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Several key Republicans have expressed initial interest in the
concept of Clinton's testimony, though they have offered little in
the way of concrete concessions in return. House Speaker Newt
Gingrich telephoned Kerry at a Manhattan restaurant Monday night to
discuss the possibility. And Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said
Tuesday, ``Any time the president comes forward and comes clean in
a formal setting ... it would probably be a positive development.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his telephone conversations with both Gingrich and
Lott, Kerry has held private discussions with senior Clinton aides
over the last two days, including White House Chief of Staff
Erskine Bowles and Capitol Hill liasson Greg Craig, as well as
House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a series of private conversations with colleagues
on the concept,'' Kerry said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
``It's met with considerable interest from some. Others are
skeptical, but we will keep talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the White House, some key aides believe that before
Clinton volunteers his testimony, he must receive some concessions
from Congress or at least an indication of timing and schedules of
congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens if we come up, we do our thing, and we leave, and
they say thank you and go on with what they're doing,'' asked one
senior White House official Tuesday. ``And what framework, what
structure? The right move is to ask what actions we can take to
bring this to closure, but it can't be one-sided, it has to be
bipartisan.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advisers declined to address the issue of testimony or
discuss the specifics of a possible deal Tuesday. Asked about the
prospect of Clinton appearing before a congressional panel, White
House press secretary Michael McCurry said Tuesday, ``What we want
to do is work with Congress to find a course of action that is the
correct one, that will have bipartisan support, that the people of
Congress together agree is the right course for our nation and that
the people of the United States of America will support.''
</P>
<P>
   Added White House communications director Ann Lewis: ``What the
American people want is to get to the end. How do we get to the
end, to allow people to express disapproval for his personal action
while allowing him to continue being president?''
</P>
<P>
   As a variation on the deal, some Democrats are also discussing
the possibility of Clinton testifying before the Judiciary
Committee in exchange for a preordained agreement for a
congressional censure and a sizable fine tantamount to a plea
bargain. The Democrats privately conceded, however, that Clinton is
not in a strong enough position to pose the possibilty to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would depend on whether Republicans were sincerely
interested in ending this embarrassing fiasco sooner rather than
later,'' said Democratic Representative Martin Meehan of
Massachusetts, a member of the Judiciary Committee. Meehan added
that only Gingrich and Lott could convince GOP members of the
Judiciary Committee to agree to such an expedited process.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are dissenters on both sides of the aisle.
Republicans may be loathe to allow Clinton to appear on Capitol
Hill before the November midterm elections, for fear that he may
help his own cause and hurt GOP prospects at the polling booths.
Some Republicans also believe a full airing of charges and a
lengthy hearing could further harm an already weakened president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the entire constitutional issue that Congress
is now facing can be resolved by the single appearance of any one
witness,'' said Representative James E. Rogan, a California
Republican on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J. Hyde of Illinois said he
would ``welcome'' Clinton's appearance before the panel, but that
the Congress would probably not be prepared to begin hearings and
hear testimony until next year, as part of a formal and elaborate
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't invite him because I wouldn't want him to think we
were trying to embarrass him,'' Hyde said, ``But if he wants to
testify we will certainly hear from him.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to recommend in early
October that the full House approve a formal impeachment
investigation of Clinton. If the House approves the inquiry, the
panel would then spend several weeks reviewing Starr's report and
conducting its own investigation in a precursor to hearings.
</P>
<P>
   And even some Democrats have expressed opposition to his
testimony if it ultimately means an expedited process.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Democratic and Republican staffs on the Judiciary
Committee have reached an agreement on how much material to black
out in 12 of the remaining 16 boxes of Starr documents. The panel
is under House orders to decide which of the material to withhold
before it releases the rest, no later than Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The material includes transcripts of grand-jury testimony from
more than 60 witnesses, including Vernon Jordan, Clinton's
confidant; Betty Currie, the president's secretary; and Linda R.
Tripp, the former Lewinsky friend who tipped off Starr to the
illicit affair. The boxes also contain transcripts of the secretly
recorded audiotapes of Tripp's conversations with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, which is deeply divided along partisan lines over
how much of the material to make public, is scheduled to meet
Thursday to renew the debate. However, members of both parties said
the remaining boxes contain no additional damaging information
involving the allegations against Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
