<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-INSPECTORS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING INSPECTIONS LAWS IN NEW YORK CITY SEEN AS INEFFECTIVE AND
USELESS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDY KENNEDY and JOHN SULLIVAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the summer of 1996, an engineer using binoculars
and a high-powered camera inspected the brick facade of a 44-story
office building in midtown and declared it safe, satisfying the
requirements of a city law intended to guard against crumbling
masonry.
</P>
<P>
   But out of the engineer's sight and hidden behind the building's
brickwork, critical metal ties that held the bricks to the walls
were corroding.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years later, on Aug. 10, the ties gave way and a
masonry panel the size of a boardroom table came loose from the
40th floor of the building, showering brick shards onto Lexington
Avenue and punching a jagged hole through the top of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse is perhaps the most dramatic example, but only one
of many, construction experts say, of glaring problems with the
city's 18-year-old effort to require inspections and repairs of
tall buildings.
</P>
<P>
   City officials acknowledge that laws governing facade
maintenance have long allowed for ineffective, sometimes useless,
inspections of buildings. And while the officials have made recent
efforts to strengthen the laws, inspection records and interviews
with city officials, engineers, architects and landlords indicate
that problems persist.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious problem, experts say, is that the laws
encourage visual inspections, which engineers generally perform
with binoculars or cameras with telephoto lenses from the street,
from nearby buildings or from ledges on the building itself. They
are the least expensive inspections and the most widely used by
owners, but they can fail to detect numerous problems that more
comprehensive inspections could catch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the expert say, even when private inspections
detect such problems as loose bricks or telltale cracks, there is
no strong enforcement mechanism to require owners to make repairs.
In some cases the owner simply accumulates fines, sometimes for
more than a year. While the city has the power to seek criminal
charges against the owners, it rarely does.
</P>
<P>
   Even critics of the inspection system stress that it has been
largely successful, leading to repairs of thousands of aging
buildings. Before it, the city had no system for regular facade
inspections. But the critics add that the laws now in place remain
mostly a way of guiding responsible landlords and is ill-equipped
to deal with those who are not. And when the system fails the
results can be catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say they are now trying to fix the flaws. But it
remains unclear whether the changes will address the problems,
which city officials say have existed since the inspections were
mandated in 1980 following the death of a Barnard College student
struck by falling concrete. The laws _ which cover about 10,000
buildings, mostly in Manhattan _ now require inspections every five
years of all exterior facades of buildings taller than 6 stories.
The law primarily rests on the theory that owners will make
necessary inspections and repairs to avoid the potentially huge
costs of liability suits if damage or injuries result from a facade
collapse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BUILDING-INSPECTOR     09-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-INSPECTORS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: facade collapse.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In no real world could the city go out and inspect 10,000
buildings on a regular basis,'' said Gaston Silva, the city's
buildings commissioner. ``That's the responsibility of owning
property in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest collapse, at the headquarters of the brokerage
firm Bear Stearns on Lexington Avenue and 46th Street, the owners
had complied with the inspection law and hired a private engineer,
Raphael Bassan, in 1996 to inspect the facade. Bassan inspected the
building on two days in August 1996, using binoculars and a camera
with a telephoto lens, according to the report he filed with the
city.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Bassan declared the building safe, but he
encouraged the owners to perform periodic inspections of trouble
spots on the building, including caulking around the windows and
brick panels adjacent to the windows.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Aug. 10 of this year, as workers made
waterproofing repairs on the 39th floor, one of the brick panel, a
section 12 feet high and 4 feet wide, came loose. Brick shards
plummeted to Lexington Avenue and two bricks smashed through the
roof of the bus, narrowly missing a woman inside. Silva said in a
recent interview that the corroded ties caused the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   While the accident is still under investigation, recent
inspections of the building have found that several other panels,
each weighing tons, have shifted outward by as much as an inch,
suggesting that more metal ties could be rusted away.
</P>
<P>
   Bassan's inspection met city guidelines, and there is no
indication that it was flawed, city officials said. Construction
experts say it is possible that the building deteriorated in the
two years after he inspected it. In a recent interview, Bassan said
that he saw no problems with the facade that merited a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can put you in front of this wall,'' he said. ``You want to
bang on it with a hammer? You can bang on it with a hammer, and it
will look fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts differ on what type of inspection could have found the
problems at the Bear Sterns building _ some go so far as to say it
would have been necessary to remove bricks to detect the problem
with the metal ties. But they say that for most buildings, a close
inspection from a scaffold can determine far more than a visual
inspection from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sort of like going to the doctor,'' said Rene Testa,
chairman of the civil engineering department at Columbia
University. ``He can look at you from a distance and see a few
things, but he is much more effective if he can touch you and use
some instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has already made some far-reaching changes in the
inspection laws. After a ton of bricks fell from a Madison Avenue
office building last December, closing down parts of one block for
months, the Giuliani administration shepherded a bill through the
City Council that expanded the law to require inspection of all
exterior walls, not just walls facing streets.
</P>
<P>
   Silva, the city's buildings commissioner, said that the city has
also recently assigned a group of inspectors to make random checks
of building facades throughout the city, including smaller
buildings not covered by the facade inspection law.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Silva said he planned to rewrite his own
departmental rules to encourage closer inspections from
scaffolding. Specifically, he plans to delete words from the rules
that refer to visual inspections and add that the city prefers
close facade inspections performed from scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   And within the next few months, the Buildings Department plans
to issue new rules calling for close-up inspections of at least one
specific type of building, terra cotta, on which Silva said visual
inspections through binoculars are likely to miss important
problems.
</P>
<P>
   To put teeth into the changes, Silva said the city plans for the
first time to send its own inspectors to spot-check a percentage of
private inspectors' work, as it does now with plumbing inspections,
for example. For the last several years, he said, ``if something
smelled bad, we would send out an inspector, but he acknowledged
that ``it wasn't terribly well organized.'' Five new building
inspectors will be hired and assigned to the task.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes will only apply the next time a building must be
inspected. And since inspections are only required every five
years, many months will pass before some landlords are force to
make more aggressive efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
