<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE: MUCH ADO, NOT MUCH NEW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis.)  (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL,
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-POLLS) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   APPLETON, Wis. _ Like millions of other Americans on Monday,
Vice President Al Gore watched parts of President Clinton's
videotaped testimony before the grand jury that heard evidence in
the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   And like many of them, Gore said Tuesday that Clinton's answers
to four hours of questions added little to what people already knew
from the report by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent
counsel, which Congress made public last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My overall impression was that it was much ado about not much
new,'' Gore told reporters traveling with him here, where he
appeared with Democratic U.S. Rep. Jay Johnson of New Franken at a
community discussion on public education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has said that he has not read the full Starr report,
on Tuesday added: ``The videotaped testimony was not particularly
new in light of the report that had previously been released, and
the report does not serve as a basis for impeachment. And that
wasn't changed by anything that people saw yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout recent weeks, in which scandal developments have
collided with his campaign efforts around the country for
Democratic candidates, Gore has tried hard to avoid the topic
altogether, a strategy that allows him to demonstrate loyalty to
the president through his policies and not his behavior, an
important distinction for a Democratic presidential hopeful, which
Gore clearly is.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, he has reacted to a question barked at him by a
reporter in close range. But generally, his staff orchestrates
events, like those here at Appleton Central Alternative High
School, with such detailed care that reporters have no opportunity
to bark, lest the barker appear to the audience as rudely
intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, Gore has made a brief statement about the scandal
before the cameras and has granted interviews to local reporters,
as he did last week in New Hampshire, which stages the first
primary each presidential year.
</P>
<P>
   But his talk with reporters on Air Force 2 on Tuesday was the
first of its kind as he agreed to speak on the record, even if
briefly, in the wake of the extraordinary events on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he watched some of the testimony ``as it was aired
live, some of it as it was aired by networks, but mostly I saw
excerpts on the news.'' Aides said Gore had a light schedule on
Monday and watched the testimony from his residence, about two
miles northwest of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   None of Clinton's testimony, Gore predicted, was compelling
enough to change a political equation in which Republicans
generally feel that Clinton should resign or be impeached and
Democrats are generally willing to let him finish his second term.
Gore also said he had not discussed the testimony with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has much effect or changes things very
much,'' Gore said. ``I'm traveling to almost all of the competitive
House races, Senate races and governors' races and almost without
exception, I find people anxious to hear a discussion of the issues
that are at stake in this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with an expectation that the House Judiciary Committee will
vote along party lines to initiate impeachment proceedings, Gore
said he had ``not been involved in an outreach effort to members''
of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to Wisconsin included a reception that raised
$70,000 for Johnson, a first-term House member who is facing Mark
Green, a Republican state assemblyman, in what is considered the
most competitive of Wisconsin's nine House races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
