<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND OBUCHI FAIL TO REACH ACCORD ON CURE FOR JAPANESE
ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton and Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of
Japan met for the first time on Tuesday and struggled to reassure
the markets that they agree on a common strategy to pull the
world's second-largest economy out of a recession that is fueling
economic turmoil on three continents.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly three hours of meetings in New York, the two
leaders emerged with no agreement about what Japan will do about
the trillion dollars in bad debts that have acted like an anchor on
the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Their chief areas of agreement, aides said, were a shared
concern about North Korea, a decision to meet again early next year
and the politically mandatory promise to call each other by their
first names.
</P>
<P>
   While trying to sound upbeat, American officials acknowledge
that they emerged from the meeting with no better sense of how
Obuchi planned to resolve a politically paralyzing debate over the
bank debt that is already threatening the prime minister's loose
grasp on power.
</P>
<P>
   The bad bank debts now overshadow trade disputes and growing
security concerns in the Pacific as the No. 1 issue between the two
countries. The tower of debt has frozen economic activity, forced
Japan to keep insolvent banks afloat and set off waves of turmoil
far beyond Japan's own shores.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief and carefully stage-managed appearance with Obuchi,
Clinton acknowledged that an ``immensely complicated political
situation'' in Japan limited the prime minister's options.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the divisions among the political parties in Japan are
so complex that Obuchi was unable to address Clinton's main
concern: Tokyo's vow to use tens of billions of dollars in public
funds to prop up some of the world's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the two men met, a political deal to merge or nationalize the
virtually insolvent Long Term Credit Bank of Japan, a huge
financial institution, appeared to be unraveling in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister made it clear that they were working very
hard on this legislation, that there are a lot of moving pieces,
and he did not make a commitment,'' Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings with American presidents are always important for
Japanese prime ministers. No matter what the subject of the
session, it is critical for a new Japanese leader to demonstrate
that he can hold his own with the president and fend off, when
necessary, the incessantly demanding Americans.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster the prime minster, the White House planned to fly the
two leaders to the Rockefeller estate in Tarrytown, N.Y., where
they could hold their meeting in a rural setting. But fog kept
their helicopters grounded, and the meeting was held at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel on Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   What made this meeting unusual was that it was also important
for Clinton, at several levels. Without resolving Japan's problems,
Clinton's hopes of calming the world financial turmoil _ a task he
committed himself to in a speech last week at the Council on
Foreign Relations _ would be greatly impaired, if not doomed.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, the session was the latest opportunity for
Clinton to demonstrate that he is focusing on substantive issues
despite the continuing jockeying in Washington over impeachment
proceedings or a possible censure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted to reporters at one point on Tuesday that he
had ignored the televised deluge of testimony and commentary.
``Believe it or not, I haven't read the report,'' he said,
referring to Kenneth Starr's referral to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But as a political diversion, the meeting with Obuchi did not
amount to much.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of progress came as little surprise to the
administration. This was the fourth time in 18 months that Clinton
has urged a Japanese prime minister to act quickly on resolving the
banking crisis that has frozen lending and investment throughout
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the series of running meetings between the two
countries in Tokyo, San Francisco and Washington, there is little
to show in the way of progress _ beyond resentment of American
pressure in Japan and frustration at Japanese intransigence in
Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American strategy for dealing with Japan has been to
coordinate a series of increasingly urgent-sounding warnings _
first from Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Summers, then from
Germany and other European countries, and most recently from the
International Monetary Fund. The problem is how to direct those
critiques.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday and at a press conference on Tuesday,
Obuchi appeared to agree with the broad outlines of the American
strategy: to pump money into viable banks and force the sale of
real estate that has been sitting on the banks' books _ mostly
unsold, because the banks do not want to have to confront how far
prices have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   But striking that deal involves finding common ground among the
strongest political forces in Japan. Among them are banks and
companies that finance the country's political parties,
particularly Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party. And then there are
the opposition leaders, in control of the upper house of
Parliament, who reflect the popular distaste for bailing out badly
run banks and real estate moguls.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi seemed to reflect the difficulty of weaving through that
minefield on Tuesday when he said he was ``neither optimistic nor
pessimistic'' about the chances of getting financial reforms
through parliament. Taking a line from Clinton, he said that ``this
is not only an issue for Japan, but something that has major
implications on economies of Asia as well as the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   In his interview on Monday, Obuchi acknowledged that he had yet
to convince the Japanese public or parliament that the issue went
beyond Japan's domestic interests. But he argued that he had been
underestimated, a point he made obliquely to Clinton on Tuesday
when he noted that he had been compared in the American press to
``cold pizza,'' a slight that clearly annoyed Japanese bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, his aides said, reassured Obuchi that he had eaten cold
pizza the night before in his hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
