<HEADLINE>
THE SELLING OF `FELICITY' (IN A 70-CHANNEL UNIVERSE)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo of billboard advertising WB's ``Felicity'' is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)  
 (Margy Rochlin writes from Los Angeles about film and television.) 
(af)  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Focus groups swooned over the pilot of the WB's ``Felicity.''
Industry analysts _ even executives at rival networks _ declared
``Felicity,'' a new hourlong drama, the only sure hit of an
otherwise unpredictable fall season.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting their latest It Girl, magazine and newspaper editors
rushed to give the kiss-and-hug treatment to the show's star, Keri
Russell, 22, a former Mouseketeer with an innocently open gaze and
angelically backlit blond curls who seems incapable of taking a bad
photograph. The WB couldn't have bought better  &UR; insider &LR;  buzz.
</P>
<P>
   But how do they clue in the rest of the country? How do they let
them know that in a season of female leads who are self-absorbed
whiners, ``Felicity'' is the tale of an intelligent, introspective
and usually obedient rich girl who rejects her parents' plans to
send her to Stanford University and medical school so that she can
follow a tousle-haired hunk she hardly knows to a college in New
York City?
</P>
<P>
   That accomplished, how do they make sure that viewers don't
think the series is about a foolish child of privilege, but about
all that is good and bad about what occurs in the wake of her
blunder?
</P>
<P>
   If the WB were to follow in the footsteps of the big three
networks, the answer to these questions would simply be to
broadcast catchy ``Felicity'' promos in between their most popular
shows. But the upstart network has a problem: not everyone watches
the WB.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a 70-channel universe, your own on-air reach isn't enough
to bring in new viewers; we have to use alternative media,'' said
Garth Ancier, who is the WB's president for programming and
operates in tandem with a marketing staff that has enterprisingly
redefined the term ``alternative media'' to mean anywhere your gaze
might land outside of your television set.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the show makes its debut Tuesday night at 9, the
``Felicity'' advertising campaign may challenge the total
permeation level of last year's Spice Girls, bombarding city
dwellers with close to $5 million worth of billboards, subway
posters and the sides of buses.
</P>
<P>
   If moviegoers assume that their last reminder of the show will
be the ``Felicity'' poster in the foyer and the ``Felicity'' mobile
dangling over the popcorn counter, inside the theater will be a
``Felicity'' trailer with slow-motion footage and an insinuating
theme song by Madonna called ``The Power of Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the carpet-bombing work? If the WB's last two seasons are
any indication, the foundation has been laid for this tactic to
produce results. After all, this was how the WB managed to hook
18-to-34-year-old America on its witty pulp melodrama ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, they did it again, using the image of an
idealistic-looking young man standing alone in a rowboat on a
ripple-free body of water to sell its soul-searching evening soap
``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the WB didn't invent outdoor advertising; cable and
major networks are increasingly reliant on similar methods. But the
WB may be the most sophisticated, detail-consumed practitioner of
this technique.
</P>
<P>
   To CBS, for example, the billboard is a space best filled with a
glorified head shot of, say, the actress Faith Ford, alongside the
title of her new sitcom, ``Maggie Winters.''
</P>
<P>
   To the WB, the same 14 feet by 48 feet is a blank canvas upon
which to suggest as much as it possibly can about Felicity Porter
and the universality of her quest to become her own person.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the slogan: ``She's just made the best mistake of
her life.'' Then there is the dominant illustration of the beatific
Ms. Russell, head aimed slightly heavenward, flanked by two
boyishly good-looking male co-stars whose glances subtly convey
their feelings about her.
</P>
<P>
   One is already smitten; the other appears distracted. There to
communicate all the fears and exciting possibilities that come with
leaving home, a tiny illustration has been placed in an upper
corner: in near-silhouette, a suitcase-lugging Ms. Russell is
depicted before an expansive Manhattan skyline. The skyline was
softened at the edges and given an orangey-golden glow after it was
discovered that a sharp, realistic gray backdrop sent the wrong
message to focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were in trouble when it came out in the research
that people thought she was a teen-age runaway or very `Looking for
Mr. Goodbar,' '' said Bob Bibb, who is the WB's co-executive vice
president for marketing with Lewis Goldstein. Goldstein also noted
that they felt that the girl-before-skyline logo contained such
crucial information that almost every element was tweaked via
digital retouching. Not only was the cityscape made more invitingly
Oz-like but Ms. Russell's pants were changed, her hair brightened
and her worn-out sneakers replaced with platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Originally at NBC, then at Fox, both Goldstein and Bibb moved to
the WB in 1994 along with three other high-level Fox employees,
including Jamie Kellner, now the WB's chief executive officer.
Working out of offices at Warner Ranch, roughly a mile and a half
from the famed Warner Brothers back lot in Burbank, the pair were
inspired by the proximity of their parent company and its Hollywood
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They decided ``to market each of our dramas like a feature
film,'' said Bibb, who hired Rick Frey, a creative director from
Paramount Pictures, to achieve a top-dollar movie elegance. On the
relatively paltry WB budget, the department managed innovative
touches like the installation of black letterbox bands on the
promos and the listing lengthy credits on the posters.
</P>
<P>
   It also hired fashionable photographers like Frank Ockenfels to
produce a black-and-white series of George Hurrell-style portraits
that transformed the WB's roster of cutie-pie headliners into swank
30s-style matinee idols.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these splashy efforts may explain why a cult following
is already poised to rally around the series, even though episode 1
hasn't been broadcast yet. (At least the critics who have lauded
the show's fine writing and quality production values had
 &UR; something &LR;  to base their opinions on.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, good reviews and a worshipful fan base couldn't save
``My So-Called Life,'' an ABC youth drama that was canceled after a
single season (1994-95) and that ``Felicity'' happens to resemble
in style, emotional texture and target audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always ask ourselves, why didn't that work?'' Bibb said
about a show that can serve as a reminder of how even the most
promising product can wither and die. ``What we figured out about
`My So-Called Life' was that it was existing on ABC without any
compatible programming. `Dawson's' exists because of `Buffy,' and
`Felicity' could probably not exist without both of them. Besides,
their promotions never hit the right demographic.''
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago, Goldstein and Bibb and their six-man creative
team could be found in Bibb's modest corner office, watching
``Felicity'' trailers on a television set.
</P>
<P>
   In one, the title character is shown clashing with her father
over her decision to move to Manhattan. As he berates her, Ms.
Russell's eyes slide to one side and her brows knit together in a
way that makes her appear almost maniacal. Although the expression
passes over the actress's face so fleetingly it has to be captured
in freeze-frame, the men still debated whether it helped or hurt
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looks pouty,'' said Bibb, whose primary concern was that
some might see their heroine as ``a brat with a lot of options,''
as opposed to a 17-year-old who is ``trying to break away from a
father who is putting shackles on her and trying to guide her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   To Goldstein, she looked like ``a spoiled daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Lee, vice president for special programming at the
WB, almost hidden behind a thicket of charts and bar graphs,
defended the Look as a quick burst of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfect,'' he kept insisting, until it was agreed that
the Look should stay in. ``You see enough shots of her smiling. It
shows strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this fine-tuning will lead to high Nielsen ratings or
Zeitgeist popularity may not be known for months. But one of the
reasons J.J. Abrams and Matt Reeves, co-creators and co-executive
producers of ``Felicity,'' were attracted to the WB was its
reputation for supporting a show until it was discovered by
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   However, turning their beloved product over to be dissected,
packaged and retailed by Goldstein and Bibb has left them slightly
agog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been through this before,'' said Abrams, who is a
newcomer to television, although both he and Reeves have witnessed
the impact of marketing, for better or worse. (Abrams was one of
the writers on ``Armageddon''; Reeves directed ``The Pallbearer.'')
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone at the ``Felicity'' production office in
Culver City, Calif., Abrams was asked if he was ready to drive
through the streets of Los Angeles surrounded by all things
``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I regret is that there's not a chance of having
people discover `Felicity' for themselves,'' said Abrams, sounding
genuinely conflicted. ``Having said that, I understand the
realities of marketing. The fact is that I love this show and I am
confident about it. But if people get sick of it before they've
even seen it, I'll be upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
