</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO BATTERED BY WORST STORM IN 70 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ Battered overnight by what
meteorologists describe as the strongest storm to hit this
Caribbean island in 70 years, Puerto Rico struggled Tuesday to
begin repairing at least a billion dollars in damage inflicted by
Hurricane Georges, which continued its slow march westward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a major onslaught,'' Gov. Pedro Rossello said
Tuesday morning, as the last traces of the storm were still
pounding the western coast. ``We have severe damage, impassable
roads, no power and a high probability of flooding. We are going to
have to start from zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as residents were cleaning up their homes and businesses,
Georges swept across the neighboring island of Hispaniola,
battering both the Dominican Republic and Haiti. A hurricane watch
may be issued for south Florida as early as Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello described the hurricane, the eighth to strike Puerto
Rico in the past 100 years, as the worst in decades. Local
forecasters said the storm was the most powerful to strike the
island since the San Felipe hurricane of Sept. 13, 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Winds of 115 mph left the island virtually without electricity.
Nearly 80 percent of its 3.8 million residents were without water,
and many also had no telephone service, especially on the southern
coast. In the U.S. Virgin Islands just east of here, similar
problems were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Radio and television stations here said that five people were
killed during the hurricane's passage across Puerto Rico on Monday
night and early Tuesday at a leisurely 14 mph pace, three in a
landslide and two as a result of heart attacks. Police and other
security officials said they could not yet confirm the deaths, but
acknowledged they had received reports that people were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Service in Miami said mountain ranges in
those countries were dissipating some of the storm's strength, but
warned that Georges could regain force once it gets out over the
warm open waters of the Caribbean again.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's future path remains uncertain. Meteorologists said
Georges, a dangerous category 3 storm with winds now at 120 mph,
could strike anywhere from central Cuba to the Bahamas, which along
with Turks and Caicos are already under a hurricane warning.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Feuer, a meteorologist with the Hurricane
Research Division of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, Georges is expected to leave Hispaniola by early
Wednesday morning. Asked if and when it would hit Florida, he said,
``It is very uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a less than 20 percent chance at this point,'' he
said. ``We have no great certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   As a precautionary measure, authorities in Monroe County, Fla.,
which includes Key West and most of the Everglades, declared a
state of emergency and ordered a mandatory evacuation as of
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an island community,'' said Mary Reich, a county
commissioner. ``We're used to these things.'' There are no
hurricane shelters in the Florida Keys, she said, and only one
highway that connects with the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Georges caused extensive damage to housing and public buildings
on the eastern Caribbean islands on Sunday, with 70 percent of the
homes in St. Kitts and Nevis, the smallest country in the Western
Hemisphere, said to be affected. The storm was reported to have
killed three people there and two more in nearby Antigua and
Barbuda.
</P>
<P>
   After an inspection tour Tuesday, Rossello estimated the damage
in Puerto Rico at about a billion dollars. Government officials
said total damages are likely to exceed the cost of Hurricane Hugo,
which struck northeastern Puerto Rico in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has declared both Puerto Rico and the Virgin
Islands to be disaster areas, but the flow of emergency assistance
was slowed because Luis Munoz Marin International Airport here was
still being cleared during the day. American Airlines said,
however, that it expects commercial flights to resume on Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, Rossello and a representative of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency made a swing through the San Juan
metropolitan area, home to about one-third of Puerto Rico's
population. Nearly everywhere they turned, they encountered scenes
of destruction and flooding, combined with instances of rapid
rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   In San Juan, thousands of trees had toppled, taking street
lights and power and other utility lines with them, while near the
eastern suburb of Loiza, a river had overflowed its banks. Streets
were littered with debris, much of it metal signs, shutters and
awnings ripped from windows and walls by the force of the storm.
But residents were already out with brooms, carts and pickup trucks
to haul the rubble away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had had 300 people in shelters during the hurricane, but
that's going to change dramatically,'' said Victor Soto, mayor of
the San Juan suburb of Toa Baja. ``A lot of people here have lost
the roofs on their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest-hit region was said to be the mountainous interior
of the island. There as much as 20 inches of rain fell during
Georges' slow passage across houses of wood and zinc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was much worse than Hurricane Hugo,'' said Juan Marrero,
a resident of the San Juan suburb of Catano, which experienced
extensive flooding. ``Just in the area around where I lived, we've
got more than 30 houses that have no roof anymore. I'm all right,
thank God, except for some damage to the store I own, but those
people have lost everything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges cut off cell phone and phone communication to
the south coast ``This is the worst storm that Salinas has seen in
its history,'' said the mayor of Salinas, Basilio Baerga, on
Tuesday morning, as he was trying to assess the damage to his town.
Baerga said there was at least one death in his town attributed to
Georges _ a blind man who apparently suffered a heart attack as
Georges began hitting this south coast town. He could not provide
further details.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane also damaged the town's popular harbor district
and the town's marina. ``The only thing left is the piling,'' said
67-year-old Bill Williams, who lives on a sailboat docked here.
</P>
<P>
   Many barrio residents took refuge in one of the town's municipal
shelters. ``I lost everything,'' said 46-year-old Onelia Malave of
Barrio Carmen, who rode out the storm at a shelter in the Luis
Munos Rivera school with her three children. ``We have no roof and
everything is wet.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not an easy night at the shelter, however, as heavy rains
flooded rooms, and heavy winds uprooted a huge banyan tree beside
the school. ``That tree has been there since 1925, the year the
school was built,'' said school director Lillian Torres. ``It was a
frightening night.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cayey, in the mountainous part of the island, the lush
vegetation had been turned into greenish-brown confetti by Tuesday
morning. All along highway 1, its main road, houses and businesses
were torn down or turned into twisted hulks of metal and wood.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m., residents seeking to file damage claims had already
formed a long line that wrapped around the municipal stadium, which
was also damaged significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the eye passed over, it was silent. And then you could
hear it coming again. It sounded like a tractor-trailer running
down the highway, said 46-year-old Frank Vega of the storm's
approach. The storm toppled Vega's truck, filled with hay and eggs,
and sent his car sliding into a cement building. ``We got hit
bad,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A warehouse for the town's medical center was also destroyed in
the storm, along with the medicine inside it. Civil Defense
officials were evacuating residents of an old-age home which was
also damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is wet, everything is ruined,'' said Brunilda
Milian, 43, who passed the storm in her wooden home with her
husband and 10 children. The yard behind her house was filled with
the carcasses of dead poultry, which were raised commercially by
her husband. With a machete in hand, he was still trying to
calculate the extent of his loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
