<HEADER>
A8799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LESOTHO-COUP-ART-NYT &LR;      09-22 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LESOTHO-COUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP TO 30 DEAD AS SOUTH AFRICAN TROOPS ENTER LESOTHO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASERU, Lesotho _ South African troops rolled into this tiny
mountainous kingdom early Tuesday morning to put a quick end to
political turmoil that had brought the government to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the invading force met surprisingly heavy
resistance from Lesotho soldiers who oppose the government. They
took to the hills and trained relentless sniper fire on the South
Africans.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day perhaps 30 people were dead, including as
many as 10 South African soldiers. Fighting could still be heard
near the army barracks northeast of this city, where the Lesotho
soldiers had set fire to the tall grass and then escaped into the
craggy hills nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the South Africans tried to lift their wounded into
helicopters near the base, they came under heavy fire and had to
stop the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the South African soldiers also triggered a day
of looting and burning like none other in the history of Lesotho.
By early afternoon, virtually every other building was on fire and
thick plumes of acrid smoke darkened the streets and rose high
above the city. The pavements were littered with what looters had
dropped, a brand-new sneaker here, a pink sofa pillow there. It was
clear that no matter what the outcome of South Africa's action,
much of Maseru had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's action in this country _ a state the size of
Maryland completely surrounded by South Africa _ marked the first
time that President Nelson Mandela's government has taken part in
military intervention beyond its borders. Under apartheid, South
Africa made a name for itself by meddling in its neighbor's
business. But since 1994, South Africa had stuck to a policy of
looking for negotiated solutions to Africa's conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   South African officials said they had sent more than 600
soldiers into Lesotho because they were asked to by the country's
prime minister, Pakalitha Mosisili, who believed a coup was
imminent. For weeks the country had been crippled by
anti-government protesters who believed that the country's August
elections were rigged.
</P>
<P>
   But the presence of South African soldiers here seemed to elicit
nothing but rage among Lesotho citizens. South African-owned
businesses were specifically targeted and cars with South African
license plates were stoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the way to solve our problems,'' said Mohamed
Yunes, who was standing in front of a building he owns on Kingsway
Street here, watching looters breaking windows and setting fires.
``We've never had anything like this before. What are they doing
here? What is their plan? We will all be ruined when they are
through.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's minister for safety and security said at a news
conference in Pretoria that the intervention, under the auspices of
the Southern African Development Community, had been on the drawing
board for weeks and would continue until ``all the parties involved
had agreed that stability had returned.'' Botswana is also supposed
supply troops for the action.
</P>
<P>
   Mufamadi said that six Lesotho soldiers had been killed in the
fighting so far. But later reports counted as many as 17. Army
officials said there had been heavy fighting near the barracks and
the Lesotho dam, which supplies electricity to the country.
</P>
<P>
   At least five civilians have also been reported dead. By
mid-afternoon, a steady stream of refugees, mostly foreigners,
could be seen trying to get across the border into South Africa,
their cars crammed with belongings. On the South African side,
police officers said they would be setting up tents for some of the
refugees in the town of Ladybrand.
</P>
<P>
   Lesotho, an impoverished country greatly dependent on South
Africa, had been in political turmoil since results of elections
were contested by the losing party almost immediately after the
count was in.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Lesotho Congress Party won 79 of 80 Parliament seats.
But a report by a commission of representatives from South Africa,
Botswana and Zimbabwe last week cited ``serious concerns'' about
the voting. It did not however call for new elections. South Africa
has been trying to negotiate between the two parties, but to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the chaos in the country had been escalating.
Anti-government protesters had been hijacking government vehicles
to use them to block traffic downtown. And one army general had
been forced to resign at gun point. But rioting and violence had
been at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the opposition party, Vincent Malebo, condemned
South Africa's action as unwarranted, and a ``heartless'' attempt
by South Africa to beat Lesotho into submission. He also said the
military action was poorly thought out, and had failed to cope with
the burning and looting of shops in Maseru.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly hours went by when there was little sign of a South
African presence in downtown Maseru. Fires roared unattended and
the heat caused glass windows to explode onto the sidewalk. Lesotho
police officers walked by looters without uttering a word.
</P>
<P>
   South African soldiers also appeared stunned by the level of
resistance they encountered. On the road leading to the barracks, a
dozen South African armored vehicles seemed to be patrolling
without much purpose, taking heavy fire from many directions.
Amidst the fire, an armored medical unit was treating a half dozen
wounded soldiers. Three were dead.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wounded soldiers said the Lesotho soldiers had so far
outmaneuvered them. ``They lit all these fires and then they
scattered to the hills,'' the soldier said. ``They are at home in
those hills, we are not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
