u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-SERBS-NYT &LR;      09-22 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-SERBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE SERBS IN BOSNIA REMAIN A POLITICAL FORCE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE O'CONNOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Reassessing what seemed to be a
disaster for the Western strategy to stabilize Bosnia, many foreign
diplomats here are now saying the results of the national election
this month are not as bad as they first thought.
</P>
<P>
   Others still see the results as terrible, but say they now think
the problems may be handled.
</P>
<P>
   Returns from the voting two weekends ago are still preliminary.
But Biljana Plavsic, the Bosnian Serb president on whom the West
placed its hopes for isolating the more nationalistic Serbian
political forces, has conceded defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the presidency of the Bosnian Serb part of the
country is Nikola Poplasen, a man whose hard-line history and
campaign statements made many foreign officials and Bosnian
politicians believe that the Bosnian Serb voters had rejected
moderation by electing him.
</P>
<P>
   Judging Poplasen's support to reveal an intractable vein of
nationalist sentiment among a majority of Bosnian Serbs, many
diplomats reasoned that Western efforts here _ nearly three years
since the war ended, and after more than $3 billion in aid projects
_ had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Poplasen in office there is no point in staying,'' a
Western ambassador said last week. ``It's good-bye and good luck,
at least as concerns the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   But as results come in showing that less hardline politicians
across the country are doing well, there is a belief that Bosnian
voters are more complicated than had been realized and that they
may vote for a militant in one race while voting for moderates in
others.
</P>
<P>
   In the half of Bosnia governed by a federation of Muslims and
Croats, as well as in the election of the national legislature,
unofficial returns indicated that hardline parties were slipping in
support.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a clear change in the mood of despair that
prompted foreign diplomats to say their governments would not be
able to continue their efforts here in any important way.
</P>
<P>
   Four days ago a European official was trying to see how his
country could extract itself from a number projects that it was
financing. But today the official said: ``The initial reaction was
that we had lost the struggle and we should let the Serbs suffer
for a period to see if that made them easier to deal with. Now it
looks as if there may be still something to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially hopeful, say diplomats with access to unofficial
voting results, is that in the Bosnian Serb republic, candidates
who oppose Poplasen's most militant views will probably have a
majority in the legislature, requiring Poplasen to negotiate with
them on the appointment of government ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Results now indicate that the same Bosnian Serbs who supported
Poplasen also voted against the most prominent wartime Bosnian Serb
nationalist still in office, Momcilo Krajisnik. His post as the
Serbian representative on Bosnia's three-member presidency went to
Zivko Radisic, foreign officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Radisic is seen by Bosnian politicians to be far more moderate
and has started to form a coalition with a political party whose
members are predominantly Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people are finally opening their eyes and now want life to
return to normal,'' said Rade Pavlovic, a leader of Radisic's
party, the Serb Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is the emotional bruising from the war, and there is
still fear of the other side,'' he said, ``so you get people voting
for a madman who says he will protect them at the same time they
vote for more moderate politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavlovic is perhaps the most popular man in the bucolic town of
Teslic, an agricultural center three hours' drive from Sarajevo and
a place from which Muslims and Croats were brutally expelled during
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pavlovic's popularity comes from the fact that he tried
to protect minorities from hardline Bosnian Serb officials in
wartime and today is working to help people come home.
</P>
<P>
   Drago Djuric, the owner of a new radio station on the town's
outskirts, said: ``There are people on both sides of Bosnia who
want to make the country work again. They just haven't learned how
to do it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
