<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL HAIL THE FIRST GRAMMARIAN!  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED -They say the man frets over his place in history. Now
we know. Forevermore, Bill Clinton is the Language President,
master of syntax and tense.
</P>
<P>
   All hail the First Grammarian!
</P>
<P>
   This is not such a bad thing, really. If you play close
attention and practice, practice, practice, you too can learn to
talk like a president. At home, at work _ or in front of a federal
grand jury _ this can save you serious heartache.
</P>
<P>
   All you need do is master a few concepts and words. Grab a
pencil. You'll be an amateur Clinton in no time flat.
</P>
<P>
   First, we have to work on your verb tenses, particularly the
present. This trick works best when used with the verb ``is'' and
its conjugations. An example:
</P>
<P>
   In the Paula Jones case, lawyer Bob Bennett told the judge
``there is absolutely no sex of any kind in any manner, shape or
form, with President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   This Clinton defended in his Lewinsky grand jury deposition:
``But that statement in the present tense ... is not inaccurate, if
that's what Mr. Bennett meant. That is, at the time that he said
that, and for some time before, that would be a completely accurate
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   You see the beauty, no? Because Clinton was not having sex in
the present tense _ that is, at the deposition _ technically
Bennett wasn't lying.
</P>
<P>
   Master this trick and you're golden. Imagine that next speeding
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Officer: ``Do you know how fast you were going, buddy?''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo Clinton: ``With all due respect, there's no way I'm
speeding there!''
</P>
<P>
   Completely true. At the precise moment of that locution, you
were stopped!
</P>
<P>
   It works in the future too. Say your boss asks about that big
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Jerko: ``Smithers, where's the Colan gelo presentation? Jerry
will gnaw my leg off if it's late.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Wannabe: ``That's not going to be a problem, sir. Not at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo! It is a problem (begin ital) now (end ital) _ but it's
not going to be, because once snapperhead leaves, you'll get to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true president.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do you have to be an adult to benefit from Clinton's legacy.
One word every 7-year-old should know is ``alone.'' Confronted with
his statement that he and Lewinsky were never alone, Clinton
contorted like so:
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were also a lot of times when, even though no one
could see us, the doors were open to the halls, on both ends of the
halls people could hear. ... So there were a lot of times when we
were alone, but I never thought we were.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, kiddies. Say mom issues this familiar direct order: ``Play
in front of the house. You're not old enough to cross the street
without an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross to your heart's content. The line to use if you're busted?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, ma. I didn't cross (begin ital) alone.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Sure, no adults were within 500 feet _ but there were loads of
'em in nearby houses, any one of whom could've come outside at any
minute to help you cross I-10. They were with you.
</P>
<P>
   In spirit. That's close enough.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton Age, closeness _ to the truth, or an intern _ is
all that counts. This is great news for every horny 17-year-old boy
in America.
</P>
<P>
   Who doesn't recall the frustration of being young and trying
desperately to get to third base with a JV cheerleader _ only to
hear that last-second ``No!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, courtesy of the Language President, comes the perfect
response:
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, Muffy. Please! It's not sexual relations.''
</P>
<P>
   So says Clinton: ``I'll bet the grand jurors, if they were
talking about two people they know, and said they have a sexual
relationship, they meant they were sleeping together, they meant
they were having intercourse together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't words grand?
</P>
<P>
   They turn the truth to putty, and leave even jagged facts silky
smooth. Master words like Clinton, and there's no telling what
you'll get yourself into, or out of.
</P>
<P>
   If you fail, well, take solace. You tried. It's like they say in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Close, but no cigar. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
