u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT &LR;      09-22 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRADE OFFICIAL SAYS CHINA MARKET IS CLOSED TIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A senior American trade official Tuesday criticized
what he called China's unwillingness to open its markets to foreign
companies and accused the Chinese of tightening some restrictions
on foreign businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by the official, David Aaron, undersecretary of
commerce for international trade, reflected what has become an
increasingly tense trade relationship between Beijing and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said China's policies had helped produce a
$1-billion-a-week trade deficit for Americans. He said the United
States would look for new ways to press China into allowing
improved access for American businesses to the nation's 1.2 billion
people if the situation did not improve. ``They have taken this
relationship for granted,'' Aaron said, adding later, ``The list of
barriers is just getting bigger and we're not crossing anything off
the list _ that's the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, who was in Beijing to attend a conference and meet with
Chinese officials, offered hope that the huge trading partners
could ultimately cooperate. But the polite discussions on trade
that surrounded President Clinton's visit here this spring have
evidently given way to exasperation and blunt talk. Aaron
characterized his meetings with the Chinese as ``somewhat somber.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that the Chinese have lots of difficult problems
to face,'' Aaron told a small group of reporters, listing the broad
Asian economic crisis, troubled state-owned enterprises and this
summer's disastrous floods. ``But my job is to make sure that on
that list of problems is this trade deficit and the treatment of
businesses here.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. figures show the trade deficit with China exceeding $50
billion annually, and growing.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's admonitions came after a tense few weeks in which new
American regulations banned imported goods from China that were
packed in untreated wood crates or pallets, a ban that may well
affect more than half of Chinese exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say the new requirements are necessary to
prevent further invasions by the Asian long-horned beetle, which in
the last two years has emerged from Chinese raw-wood packing
material to kill thousands of trees in New York and Chicago. But
Chinese trade officials say the regulations were motivated not by
bugs but by protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unilateral action taken by the United States could impact
the normal development of Sino-American trade,'' China's Ministry
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation said in a statement last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States has for years wanted Beijing to
further open its markets, it had hoped China's stated desire to
join the World Trade Organization would take care of the problem,
since free markets are a condition of membership. But the Chinese
government has apparently accepted that it will not gain admission
to the trade organization now, and the United States has been left
to apply pressure on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said that barriers to American business in China seemed to
be multiplying rather than shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   He said, for example, that authorities here had generally not
let foreign companies develop a distribution network for their
goods, and he complained of China's unwillingness to grant licenses
to foreign companies in such service businesses as insurance. In
the last few years, a number of American companies have established
offices in Beijing, anticipating that such licenses would be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron also complained that the huge Chinese telecommunications
market was mostly off limits to foreign companies and noted that
the government was contemplating banning the few foreign companies
that had indirect investment in that industry.
</P>
<P>
   China has created many more subtle barriers as well, Aaron said,
such as increasingly cumbersome regulations on foreign currency
transactions. He cited a resurgence in counterfeiting that was now
so professional that copycat goods even carried fake Underwriters
Laboratories seals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If WTO isn't moving us toward market access and opening, we're
going to have to find other methods,'' he said, adding that the
Clinton administration was now ``looking at other options.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Aaron was in Beijing to attend a conference on
Chinese energy needs and to talk to officials in preparation for
the annual meeting of the Joint Committee on Commerce and Trade, a
Chinese-American panel, in Washington next month. He said he was
still optimistic that such joint forums could help resolve trade
disputes, at least in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials say the American trade deficit is not nearly
as large as U.S. officials contend, maintaining that it is closer
to $20 billion than $50 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2047EDT &QL; 
