<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONEYWELL-AZR &LR;      09-22 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONEYWELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEYWELL COURTS MINORITY-, WOMEN OWNED FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Rich Jones remembers the small housekeeping service
that was eager to take on more work at Honeywell Inc.'s Phoenix
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Decision making at the giant electronics and aviation systems
company, however, was ticking to a much slower clock. It wasn't
ready.
</P>
<P>
   The small company pushed.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Why not? Give us some reasons, they asked.' And we didn't
have very good reasons,'' Jones recalls with a laugh. ``It was just
the way we did things.''
</P>
<P>
   Today that small business has saved Honeywell significant sums,
says Jones, vice president of supply management in the Space and
Aviation Control division. More importantly, he said, the
experience pushed the giant to respond more quickly to the
companies it deals with.
</P>
<P>
   With benefits like that mind, Honeywell has launched plans to
spend $76 million more with women- and minority-owned businesses by
the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go on ignoring a particular segment of our society
any more than we can go on ignoring a particular part of our
market,'' Honeywell Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Michael
Bonsignore told more than 200 small-business owners last week.
</P>
<P>
   The company invited the women and minority business owners,
mainly from the Phoenix area, to an open house and sessions on
doing business with Honeywell. More than 100 buyers representing
Honeywell offices from Phoenix to Clearwater, Fla., were available
to meet with them.
</P>
<P>
   The company logged contacts between buyers and would-be
suppliers and will track their future meetings and results, Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   Minority-business leaders said the event was the first time
they'd seen a major Valley corporation go to such lengths to
recognize and recruit suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a model for other corporations,'' said David Cavazos,
manager of the Phoenix's small-business assistance office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the head guy says, `This is our goal and go for it,' it
tells the troops they mean business,'' said Joe Castillo, executive
director of the Grand Canyon Minority Supplier Development Council.
</P>
<P>
   Small-business owners hope Castillo is right. Scottsdale-based
Spirit Electronics Inc. has Honeywell as a very small customer now,
President Vickie Wessel said. But when Texas Instruments held a
similar event five years ago, ``we got business out of it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell is the Valley's ninth-largest employer, with 7,500
people working in its Industrial Automation and Control and Space
and Aviation Control divisions here.
</P>
<P>
   The Minneapolis-based company figures it buys $90 million in
goods and services _ 6 percent of its total purchases _ from
minority- and woman-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore wants that share up to 8 percent by 2000. That would
be significantly higher than the average 6.2 percent spent by
companies polled this spring by the National Center for Purchasing
Management's Center for Advanced Purchasing Studies in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate spending with minority suppliers in the Phoenix area
ranges from 3 percent to 11 percent, depending on the industry,
Castillo said. And spending is heading up, he said, as companies
become concerned about their future customers, their staffs'
diversity and ``the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore said Honeywell's drive contradicts what many large
corporations are doing in the effort to be competitive _ slashing
the smallest suppliers off their lists. That affects minority- and
women-owned businesses the most, he said, because they tend to be
newer, less experienced and more thinly capitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has to push back on this tendency to take less
risk with minority suppliers,'' he said. ``Somebody needs to prime
this pump to make sure this whole initiative doesn't go backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell's needs are wide open, Jones said. It has bought
everything from office supplies and catering services to high-tech
products and engineering services from small businesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Phoenix suppliers are not restricted to the Honeywell plants
in their own back yard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with transportation, logistics, they can provide
products and services all over the nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say corporations diversify mainly for the
public-relations effect or to comply with regulations on federal
contractors. But some regard it as good business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Minority- and women-owned companies bring in a fresh voice,
creativity, and breakthrough thinking, Bonsignore said, even to a
battleship-size corporation that he defends as a ``turbo-charged
Stealth battleship.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with companies Honeywell's size, small firms are
fleet-footed, use technology extensively and adapt quickly,
Bonsignore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by interfacing with companies like that, we find that a
lot of their management methods, albeit different from ours, are
contemporary, creative and time- and cost-effective,'' he said.
``And those are lessons we'd like to see reapplied in a big
organization like Honeywell.''
</P>
<P>
   Women and minority-business owners have additional
``institutional hurdles'' that other companies don't face.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can survive in that environment, it seems to me they
can bring a lot of value to helping us go on surviving in an
increasingly complex world,'' Bonsignore said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Jane Larson can be reached at jane.larson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
