<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN GIVES LOUDER VOICE TO RUSSIAN REGIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin gave shape to Russia's new
Cabinet on Tuesday with a decree that created an inner cabinet, or
presidium, made up of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and his six
top deputies. The decree also offered a greater voice to regional
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Under the decree representatives from eight broadly drawn
geographic regions of Russia would fully participate in the
``activities of the government.'' Giving Russia's increasingly
powerful regions a greater role in federal policy making has been a
theme that Yeltsin and Primakov have repeatedly emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's decree elevates to Cabinet status the newly named head
of the Central Bank, Viktor Gerashchenko, and Yuri Osipov, head of
the Russian Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who won a quick confirmation vote 10 days ago in
Parliament, is having trouble assembling a government and finding a
program to pull the country out of its deep economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's naming of Valentina Matviyenko, Russia's current
ambassador to Greece, as deputy prime minister for social issues,
Primakov finally found a candidate willing to take a portfolio that
at least three leading politicians have turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Matviyenko, 49, will be the first woman to serve in a top
government position. She comes to the job with a reputation as a
highly regarded professional diplomat. Her appointment has yet to
be confirmed by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The job was abruptly refused late last week by Vladimir Ryzhkov,
a member of the centrist Our Home Is Russia faction in the
Parliament. Ryzhkov bowed out two days after his appointment became
official with a decree that Yeltsin signed. Ryzhkov's refusal dealt
an embarrassing blow to Primakov's attempt to give his Cabinet a
broad political base and undercut Yeltsin's authority.
</P>
<P>
   News reports said several regional governors had also rejected
job offers, signaling wariness toward a government that is weakened
by internal contradictions over economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons for the growing mistrust toward Primakov is
his excessive orientation toward striking compromises,'' the
Independent Newspaper, a daily here, wrote Tuesday. ``Deputy prime
ministers and Cabinet ministers are being picked at random,
practically from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In reaching for compromise Primakov runs a risk of failing to
put together the team of professionals that he promised when he
took office, the paper said. ``The government is very close to
becoming a discussion club that is supervised by a kind of
minipolitburo in the form of a presidium, or inner Cabinet, stuffed
with governors,'' the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Yuri Maslyukov, a Communist named as first deputy prime
minister in charge of economic policy, Primakov has enlisted Vadim
Gustov, a Communist and governor of the Leningrad region around St.
Petersburg, as his second top lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary deputy from the left-leaning Agrarian party,
Gennady Kulik has been tapped for the agricultural portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has yet to name a finance minister, although acting
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov, a liberal economist, has shown
no signs of leaving his post. Alexander Shokhin, a former economics
minister and leader of the centrist faction, is deputy prime
minister in charge of financial policy. Shokhin, who like Zadornov,
strongly opposes the free-spending policies that Maslyukov
espouses, has been charged with representing Russia in
international financial discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Fyodorov, another free-market reformer and a former
finance minister who returned to the government last spring, is
reported to be remaining as head of tax collection.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview this week Shokhin spoke favorably of
an economic plan put forward this month by Fyodorov, then an acting
deputy prime minister. The two-part strategy called for an easing
of the crushing burden of internal debt and, after January,
installing strict currency controls.
</P>
<P>
   To relieve pressures caused by unpaid salaries, pensions and
other debts, Shokhin said, the government should turn abroad for
help rather than risk inflation by printing money. He acknowledged
that Russia would have difficulty regaining international
creditors' trust, but added that an initial round of talks with the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and representatives
from the European Community had left him hopeful that help might be
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible to find some variants of solving these
problems,'' Shokhin said. ``But I regret to say that we are in time
bind. We are so short of time that we cannot say if we will manage
to come to some agreement by the end of the month.''
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank last week offered Russian banks a plan that
would allow them to pay backed-up debts by dipping into their
reserves and tapping into a small emission of new credits from the
Central Bank. Those banks that did not partake in the plan,
apparently for fear of revealing the extent of their debts, have
been barred from trading their rubles for dollars on the Moscow
Interbank Currency Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
