<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REACT-ART-665     09-22 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REACT-ART-665&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 DEMOCRATS MAKING A CASE FOR SOME FORM OF CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-PANEL,
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-POLL) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and prominent Democrats say they
have opened an aggressive behind-the-scenes campaign to save
President Clinton from impeachment hearings by seeking to build
support among politicians of both parties for the president to be
harshly rebuked by Congress and perhaps pay a large fine.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats involved in the effort said that thus far
there was not much appetite on Capitol Hill, particularly among
Republicans, for short-circuiting the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they said, their strategy involves back-channel
contacts with respected former Republican lawmakers like Bob Dole,
the former Senate Republican leader and his party's nominee for
president in 1996; former President George Bush, and Howard Baker,
also a former Senate Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has begun calling party leaders and Democrats in
Congress to signal that he would be open to a censure deal. ``The
president wants to end this as soon as possible,'' said one adviser
who spoke by telephone to the president. ``He wants to get back to
governing and running the country. If a reasonable deal can be put
on the table, he will accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, most of whom spoke on the condition of anonymity,
say they are advancing several possible forms of a censure, which
would be a formal scolding from Congress. Most options, they say,
involve a large financial penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Democrats involved in the talks described the
appropriate rebuke as a ``sanction'' rather than a censure, and are
pressing for ways to make the punishment harsher, like requiring
that Clinton stand in the well of the Senate as he is being
condemned. They are also discussing the possibility of Clinton
delivering a personal appeal to the House Judiciary Committee, and
agreeing to stop parsing the term ``sexual relations'' in his
public remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said in an interview Tuesday that he discussed the scandal
with Clinton when the two met at the White House on Friday to talk
about his trip to Kosovo, Yugoslavia. But he said that the
president did not raise the possibility of his being an envoy to
help broker a censure deal, and that he was not sure he wanted to
play that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I told the president, `Let the process work,''' said Dole,
explaining that he was not ready to call for censure or impeachment
or anything else. ``We've just had the first tip-off and
everybody's scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   He said censure was ``a dead option right now.'' But while he
said, ``It's pretty difficult to give your former colleagues
advice,'' Dole did not rule out the prospect of a deal, or of his
role brokering one, saying that ``there could be windows of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers said they had sent feelers out to Dole from
people outside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say their most convincing pitch to Republicans to
support a deal is, in the words of Leon Panetta, ``pure politics.''
Panetta, a former Clinton chief of staff who is pushing a censure
option, made this pitch to Republicans: ``You don't want Al Gore to
get into office to have a head start on 2000. What do you gain
politically by continuing to let this run itself out?''
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats also argue that Republicans could appear above
politics and concerned about the well-being of the country if they
pursued a move that would halt a prolonged impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who said he would go along with
a censure and a fine, agreed that the Gore argument to Republicans
could have powerful appeal. ``It's irresponsible to make that
judgment on that basis,'' he said. ``But I'm not naive enough to
think that isn't a significant factor.''
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the effort say they have the tacit approval
of the two Democratic leaders in Congress, Rep. Dick Gephardt and
Sen. Tom Daschle, to explore a possible deal. In fact, Panetta
said: ``Dick Gephardt suggested the idea. He called me up and said
it was something worth pursuing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One person who is deeply involved is a longtime adviser to
Gephardt, Robert Bauer, a Democratic lawyer. At the White House,
officials said, John Podesta, the deputy chief of staff, is the
point person.
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell, the former Senate Democratic leader, said in an
interview Tuesday that two week ago he told Clinton that he was
unable to join his staff as an envoy to Congress to deal with the
scandal but that he would help him informally. Mitchell said he
recently had spoken to several congressional Democrats about
censure and thought there was growing support for such a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did _ it was indefensible,'' Mitchell said. ``But I
think the country should be spared a long-drawn-out ordeal that I
believe in the end should not and cannot end in the president's
being removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the drive for a deal has involved mainly informal
discussions initiated by Clinton's friends and advisers. They
acknowledged that the effort was uphill at best: Before they can
persuade outside Republicans to come on board, Clinton's backers
face a struggle in getting the support of Democrats on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president has not signed on to elements of a
proposed end game. And some Democrats said they feared that Clinton
did not understand that a simple censure would not satisfy even
Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure he's come to terms realistically with what may be
required here,'' said one Democrat who is pushing for a deal.
``It's got to have major teeth in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But former Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York said a simple censure
was appropriate. ``I do favor some device for making clear that we
do not condone his conduct. It's absolutely essential to do that,
and that could be censure,'' he said. ``I do not favor sanctions,
because I do not know what penalty could be put on a man who
already owes $6 million. And what else are you going to do? Flay
him in the marketplace? The public square? That's been done; he's
taken a terrible beating in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole cautioned that he did not expect that there would be a
quick resolution to the scandal or that the president would shrink
from fighting for his survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this rather strong feeling that Clinton's not eager to
leave,'' said the man who took on the president in 1996. ``I don't
see anybody packing over there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
