<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-22 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE RETURNS FIRE WITH SHOT AT STARR REPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House on Tuesday fired back at
independent counsel Kenneth Starr, contending that the prosecutor
selectively omitted testimony favorable to President Clinton in his
impeachment report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans met to determine whether to proceed with
a presidential impeachment inquiry stemming from Starr's report and
to set a timetable for release of more material from the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The White House salvo came one day after the extraordinary
airing of Clinton's grand jury testimony before Starr's
prosecutors. With overnight polls showing that the testimony did
not damage Clinton's job approval rating, the White House went on
the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the top Democrat and Republican on the House
Judiciary Committee, lawyers for President Clinton charged that
Starr's initial report recommending impeachment amounted to a ``one
sided and unfair manipulation of the evidence and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The referral is stunning in its silence about evidence that
supports the president,'' stated attorneys Charles Ruff and David
Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   The president's attorneys complained that Starr's report
excluded Monica Lewinsky's testimony that the president did not ask
her to lie about their sexual affair or try to buy her silence.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's comments were made public Monday when the House
released more than 3,000 pages of supporting documents and evidence
gathered by Starr, including a transcript of Lewinsky's testimony
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to say that no one ever asked me to lie and
I was never promised a job for silence,'' Lewinsky testified.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry, traveling with the president
in New York, said it was ``grossly unfair'' that Starr had not
included that testimony in his summary report, which concluded that
Clinton should be impeached because he lied to the grand jury and
urged others to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also examined whether Clinton's friend Vernon Jordan had
helped Lewinsky obtain a job around the time she was subpoenaed to
testify about their relationship in a sexual harassment case
brought by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that the independent counsel ``found room for
hundreds and hundreds of salacious details that, you know,
titillated the country and embarrassed the country in the world.
But it didn't find room for one sentence in the testimony of Monica
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's deputy counsel, Robert J. Bittman, replied to the
criticism, sending his own letter to Judiciary Committee chairman
Henry Hyde. He said the White House contention was ``so clearly
wrong that the (Ruff-Kendall) letter is obviously an intentional
effort to mislead the committee and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Bittman said the report had noted Lewinsky as saying ``the
president did not expressly instruct her to lie'' but that Clinton
``did suggest misleading cover stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Bittman said that although Lewinsky said she was ``not promised
a job for my silence,'' the report noted that employment assistance
``may not be explicitly spelled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde. R-Ill., said that if the White House is unhappy with Starr
they should direct their complaints to Attorney General Janet Reno
or the three judge federal panel that has authority over the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Hyde and other Republicans on the Judiciary Committee
met to determine what documents to release next now that the most
sensational material, including the widely broadcast videotape of
the president's testimony, has been made public.
</P>
<P>
   The House leadership is expected to meet Wednesday and the
Judiciary Committee Thursday to discuss the next step.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Starr material must be released by next Monday,
according to a resolution passed by the House.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has yet to release former Lewinsky friend Linda
Tripp's now famous taped conversations with her as well as
testimony from a number of others called before the grand jury,
including Clinton's secretary Betty Currie, Clinton friend Jordan
and Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Judiciary Committee have complained that the
process has not been fair, with Republicans overruling any of their
objections to releasing certain testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde denied that he was being partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their (Democrats) strategy is to look for arguments. My
strategy is to smile,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of lawmakers continued to float the idea
that the president might come to Capitol Hill and testify before a
congressional committee about allegations in the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats have quietly talked about cutting a deal where
Clinton might testify, then be censured by Congress instead of
facing prolonged impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Clinton would ``be welcome'' to testify before his
committee. He said that any talk about ``cutting a deal was very,
very premature.''
</P>
<P>
   While many Republicans hoped the release of the Clinton
videotape would build public support for impeachment proceedings,
the overnight polls dispelled such notions.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll found that attitudes toward Clinton
did not change significantly after the broadcast of the videotape.
While the poll found that four out of five respondents believed
that Clinton lied to the grand jury about his sexual relationship
with Lewinsky, 56 percent said he should not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed Clinton's job approval holding steady, with
66 percent of those surveyed giving the president high marks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meeting with Japanese prime minister Keizo Obuchi,
declined to comment on the airing of his videotaped testimony. ``I
don't have any contributions to make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
