<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT &LR;      09-22 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TESTIFIED SHE WAS ASKED TO TAPE JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL,
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-POLL) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contradicting investigators for the Whitewater
independent counsel, Monica Lewinsky told a grand jury in August
that they had asked her to wear a wire to secretly record Vernon
Jordan Jr. and possibly President Clinton, according to a
transcript of her testimony released by the House on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly III, the independent counsel's spokesman, said
Tuesday that the investigators had never suggested that Ms.
Lewinsky secretly record conversations with Clinton or Jordan, and
that he could not explain the discrepancy between his denial and
her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, have
stood by their position since the outset of the Lewinsky inquiry on
Jan. 16, when they initially confronted Ms. Lewinsky with evidence
of possible perjury and obstruction of justice. (The investigators
have not disputed reports that they suggested she secretly record
lower-level employees like Betty Currie, the president's
secretary.)
</P>
<P>
   But in her testimony to the grand jury, Ms. Lewinsky had a
different recollection of that first meeting with the
investigators. The confrontation occurred shortly after she had
been captured on audiotape at a lunch with her Pentagon colleague
Linda Tripp discussing how she would deny a sexual relationship
with Clinton in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, prosecutors urged Ms. Lewinsky to agree to
cooperate with them, Ms. Lewinsky and officials in Starr's office
have said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them what cooperating meant, it entailed, and they
told me that _they had _ first they had told me before about that,
that they had had me on tape saying things from the lunch I had had
with Linda at the Ritz Carlton the other day and they _ then they
told me that I, that I'd have to agree to be debriefed and that I'd
have to place calls or wear a wire to see _ to call Betty and
Jordan and possibly the president,'' Ms. Lewinsky testified before
the grand jury two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky said she told the prosecutors she would not do it.
</P>
<P>
   Plato Cacheris, one of Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers, said he did not
know who had asked Ms. Lewinsky to wear the wire or the precise
nature of the request.
</P>
<P>
   By her account, Ms. Lewinsky was brow-beaten by the prosecutors
to try to reach an agreement to cooperate with them. She testified
she was discouraged from calling her Washington lawyer, Francis
Carter, or her mother, and that while she was free to leave at any
time, she feared she might be arrested. She said she was also told
that the prosecutors were preparing to make a case against her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from Starr's office familiar with the
confrontation have painted a different picture of it. They have
said that, while waiting for Ms. Lewinsky's mother to arrive from
New York, the investigators had gone to dinner with Ms. Lewinsky,
spent time at shopping at a mall, and watched a movie on
television. They also permitted Ms. Lewinsky to call a lawyer in
California, William Ginsburg, and repeatedly told her she was free
to leave at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they tried to reach a quick cooperation
agreement because they knew that a reporter from Newsweek knew
about their inquiry and feared it would become public in a matter
of days. Once it became public, Ms. Lewinsky's utility as a
cooperating witness would sharply decline, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
