<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger sends his regrets
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Have you noticed the interesting relationship Tiger
Woods has with Georgia tournaments? Weird, isn't it? Seems he
either snares them or snubs them. There's no in between.
</P>
<P>
   Woods walks out in 1996 at Callaway Gardens. He wins at Augusta
in 1997. He takes the trophy in May at Atlanta's BellSouth Classic.
Six weeks later, Woods and his International Management Group
announce that he won't be back to defend at the TPC at Sugarloaf in
1999. Because the BellSouth has been switched to April, the week
before the Masters, Woods does not want to make his favorite major
his fourth tournament in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kaplan, the BellSouth's executive director, hardly had time
to celebrate Woods' win in May before the 1999 rug was pulled out
from under him. He got the call from IMG on June 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had barely cleaned up the golf course,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods clearly regrets the situation but apparently did not
realize when making comments about returning to defend that it
would entail playing three straight tournaments before the Masters.
He has an obligation to play Bay Hill as both an IMG client and
Orlando resident. The Players Championship comes the next week,
followed by Atlanta and the Masters. Woods also remembers the
fatigue he felt last year from navigating Sugarloaf and would be
concerned about doing it back to back with hilly Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not me (to miss a defense),'' Woods said, ``but being the
fourth week in a row, that's the main thing. It's just an unusual
situation. If it was in the same time slot as it was last year, I
wouldn't have any problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kite once failed to defend at Atlanta, but that was because
of injury. When Mark Calcavecchia didn't defend at Vancouver last
month, it was because he qualified for a more prestigious
concurrent event, The NEC World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unprecedented, but it's certainly unusual,'' said Bob
Combs, the PGA Tour's senior vice president of public relations and
communications. ``We did speak with (Woods) before his statement
(July 20). We did encourage him to come back. But obviously, in
this instance, he had some compelling reasons not to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed,'' Kaplan said. ``It's kind of out of
character for what normally happens on the PGA Tour. Looking from
his perspective, I realize it would be four tournaments in a row.
But he's a young man. He's going to play a lot more Masters in the
future. . . . This is not something the Tour is happy with. I think
they feel it's a champion's duty to defend.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kaplan still expects to sell out the event _ and, in fact,
did so last year long before Woods committed _ it has made for some
awkwardness. Woods' photo will be used on promotional material, but
tournament organizers will be unable to say, ``Come see Tiger Woods
defend his BellSouth Classic title.'' Interestingly, Kaplan will be
one of the No. 1-tee starters at East Lake next month when Woods
plays in the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger Woods is certainly a part of our tournament history,''
Kaplan said. ``We're not saying he's the defending champion. We're
just saying he's the '98 champion. I don't think from a corporate
standpoint there will be any effect as to whether Tiger Woods is
playing or not playing. I think where it has an effect is on your
individual sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
