<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-KERSEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONE WOMAN'S VOICE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jackie Joyner-Kersee, 36, recently completed a two-decade career
as an Olympic champion track star. She talks about whether female
athletes are better off being coached by men or women:
</P>
<P>
   I can understand both sides, but I feel there are a lot of great
male coaches out there working with females. And they've been very
successful with those females. I don't think they should be
criticized or lose their job because they're not a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Some women might work better with a female coach. I never saw
any difference. Whoever was coaching me, I respected them as my
coach. If I had a concern, I took it to them. I never felt the
people working with me would put me in position to cause me any
harm.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a great coach, you should be able to coach anyone or
anybody. I think Pat Summitt can coach me in basketball. If there
are jobs available and you qualify, I think you should be given
every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to see us get in a battle where we start to fight
among ourselves and our own peers. Some of those males we might be
criticizing are some of the same males that are trying to put us in
position of power and make sure we get those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Louisiana Tech and Georgia. They have done great jobs
with women's basketball programs, and both being coached by males.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
