</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-PREGNANCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pregnancy a big hurdle for athletic careers
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just as Shalonda Enis was ready to tear it up on the
basketball court, her career nearly came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through her sophomore season at Celeste (Texas) High
School, Enis had to leave the team. She was expecting a child, but
waited until the seventh month of her term to tell coaches, friends
and family. She was embarrassed and felt she had let her family
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was over,'' Enis, a sleek 6-foot-1 forward, said.
``It was a disappointment to my family, but they told me that they
would help. They told me that one mistake shouldn't keep me from
doing what I loved. From then on, I didn't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enis took that advice. For seven years _ through the University
of Alabama, where she made All-America, to the ABL's Seattle Reign,
where she was named rookie of the year _ Enis traveled a lonely,
sometimes sorrowful road toward fulfilling her basketball talent
and hoping it would become a way to raise her son.
</P>
<P>
   As career opportunities in athletics arise for women, many are
forced to face questions that never occur to their male
counterparts. Can I start a family and continue playing ball? What
about an unplanned pregnancy?
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, schools, franchises and leagues must balance
consideration for the athlete with the needs of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes, the WNBA's centerpiece player entering the 1997
season, missed much of the regular season while giving birth. She
came back in time to help her team, the Houston Comets, win the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA spun her absence into a positive by showing Swoopes'
family _ son Jordan, husband Eric _ in the stands at games.
</P>
<P>
   When ABL player Carla McGhee, formerly of the Atlanta Glory,
announced last fall that she was sitting out the season because of
her pregnancy, she received the vocal and unqualified support of
the league and the manangement of her team, the two-time champion
Columbus Quest.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Suzie McConnell Serio of the WNBA's Cleveland Rockers is
the mother of four children who have been prominently featured as
part of the league's publicity efforts. In the ABL, Enis has plenty
of company in the mommy brigade, as Taj McWilliams, Yolanda
Griffith and Edna Campbell have generated similar attention for
their roles as parents and players.
</P>
<P>
   It was only this summer that Enis was reunited full-time with
her son, Chase, and moved him into a new home in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised by my grandmother. We're kind of used to taking
care of each other,'' she said. ``Chase has been surrounded by love
all around him. But this is what I've been working toward for so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   But Enis knows how fragile that balance can be and is mindful of
the sacrifices that often have to be made, especially for a single
mother.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing high school, she enrolled at a junior college
and made All-America. In 1995, she moved on to Alabama, and
suddenly the weekend visits home to see Chase were no longer
possible. Even while playing on a tight-knit Crimson Tide team that
was supportive of her situation, the separation at times was
painful.
</P>
<P>
   She has missed hearing Chase's first words, watching him walk
for the first time and seeing him off for his first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him on holidays and during the summer,'' Enis said.
``That was the hardest part of all. There were times when I was
depressed and he felt a million miles away. Talking to him on the
telephone helped me get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
