r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TUREK-TEX     09-22 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TUREK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUREK CONTENT THIS SEASON TO BE STARS' BACKUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roman Turek's age, his standing in the NHL and, maybe, most
important, his agent, say he has to become a No. 1 goalie soon.
</P>
<P>
   But Roman Turek's smile says otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Turek, the Stars' talented 28-year-old backup, has rolled
through training camp and preseason with not so much as a hint of
confrontation with No. 1 goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   While Turek's play has been solid, his demeanor is that of a
role player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, yeah, I want to be a No. 1 goalie. But Eddie is big
name, and he played so well last year,'' said Turek, from the Czech
Republic. ``I am backup, I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Turek has a top-level reputation in the NHL and his
6-foot-3, 190-pound frame has many teams drooling. That led his
agent, Rich Winter, to say this summer, when Turek signed a
one-year contract, that by next season, ``He'll either be the No. 1
in Dallas or he'll be the No. 1 in \Rexpansion\S Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars know full well they might lose Turek next season _
either to the expansion draft, to a potential contract holdout or
to a trade _ so they've prepared by loading up with minor-league
goalies. Longtime Stars No. 3 goalie Manny Fernandez will play with
the Houston Aeros of the International Hockey League this season,
while recently acquired minor-league veteran Mike Bales and rookie
Marty Turco will play for the Stars' IHL affiliate in Kalamazoo,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where we know the things that could happen,
and we want to be best prepared,'' Stars general manager Bob Gainey
said. ``With Roman's \Rone-year\S contract, we know there could be
some options that both sides will have to study.''
</P>
<P>
   Turek was 11-10-1 in 23 games last season, while Belfour
dominated the playing time with 61 appearances and a 37-12-10
record. Belfour earned his starts; he finished with a league-best
1.88 goals against average. Turek had a 2.22 GAA.
</P>
<P>
   But Turek said he knows he could improve his numbers if he could
play on a more consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played best when I played three or four games in a row; you
get in groove,'' he said. ``But playing one game and then sitting
and playing one game and then sitting, that is hard on any
goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Winter is trying to move things along for his
client. Turek will turn 29 on May 21 and is just two years shy of
being eligible for unrestricted free agency. He spent much of his
formative years playing in the Czech Republic and now wants to
follow in the path of a more famous Czech goalie _ two-time NHL
most valuable player Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see in Roman a lot of the same things as Dominik Hasek,''
Winter said. ``And when Dominik Hasek was the backup to Ed Belfour
in Chicago, the only way for him to get his chance was to be traded
\Rto the Buffalo Sabres\S.''
</P>
<P>
   But while all signs say Turek will leave the organization after
this season, Turek said he can't think that far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play more games, I want to get better,'' he said.
``I am better goalie now, and I want to get even better, but I am
backup here. I just want to help.''
Stars reassign six
The Stars yesterday sent six players to their IHL affiliate.
Assigned to the Michigan K-Wings were goalie Mike Bales, defensemen
Frederic Bouchard, Evgeny Tsybuk and forwards Lee Jinman, Marty
Flichel and Jeff Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   The moves bring the Stars' roster to 37 players. They must be
down to 24 by Oct. 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
