<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-SEXUAL-COX     09-22 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SEXUAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Danger zones: Some male coaches pay too much attention
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Diana Nyad was 14, a high school freshman. It was 34
years ago, long before she had become a famous ultra-distance
swimmer going from the Bahamas to South Florida and around
Manhattan Island.
</P>
<P>
   Nyad said she was resting at the house of her coach in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., on the day of the state high school meet when he
ripped off her swimsuit and sexually assaulted her.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again, two years later, in his office, according to
Nyad.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these years later, as I think I'm a pretty together,
fairly happy person in life, I can still get upset and angry, and
even have those little-girl hurt feelings over what happened,''
Nyad, 48, said in a recent interview. ``In a very brief and violent
couple of minutes, probably more like five minutes, he came in and
molested me. I threw up all over the sheets and bled. It was a real
scene. I was shaking. I probably was literally in some state of
shock, with loss of breath and dizziness.''
</P>
<P>
   The target of her accusations is Jack Nelson, a former Olympic
swimmer who went on from Pine Crest School to coach the 1976 Games
women's team and gain induction into the International Swimming
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Nyad, a Fox sports correspondent and National Public Radio
commentator, has spoken often of the alleged incidents, sometimes
in public forums, but has rarely mentioned Nelson by name.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who has not been charged, has heard the accusations
before and denies them, saying Nyad has long suffered from a
fixation with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is really sick,'' Nelson, 66, said in an interview.
``There is absolutely nothing to it. I've been investigated by
everybody known to man. How long does this continue?
</P>
<P>
   ``She is completely and totally known as a great actress. You
follow me? The more times she tells the story, the more dramatic
she gets.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusations illustrate the hot-button issue of how the
situation of adult men coaching young women can turn into something
tawdry.
</P>
<P>
   For Nyad, her story is not unusual. She said some young women
who have heard her tale offer thanks for freeing them from the
shame and isolation from their own experiences with male coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious known case occurred overseas. This summer,
the Irish government concluded that two coaches, including former
Olympic coach Derry O'Rourke, had for decades sexually abused girls
in the country's Amateur Swimming Association. The government
recommended some 100 reforms to protect athletes, and O'Rourke was
sentenced to 12 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Role makes coach an authority figure
</P>
<P>
   By the nature of the position, the coach is the dominant,
controlling authority. Many sports involving women are individual
in nature, not team, and one-on-one attention is common.
</P>
<P>
   The American Swimming Coaches Association is believed to be the
country's only sports federation or association that spells out how
far coaches can go with their athletes. Its code of conduct says:
``A (coach) shall not engage in sexual relations with athletes that
they coach, even of legal age.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the effectiveness of the code is debatable. Six years
since the clause was added, the 5,500-member association hasn't had
a single complaint from an athlete come to its review board. John
Leonard, executive director of the association, confirmed that some
incidents in recent years never were brought before the board,
largely because the swimmer or her parents didn't want to create a
stir.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a young lady is with a male coach, the parents will think
about it and say, `This doesn't make sense (to pursue),''' he said.
``Frequently, it's not a sexual harassment issue, but a . . .
fall-in-love sort of thing. And the parents say, 'No, this isn't
appropriate because it's a 25-year-old coach and a 16-year-old girl
or whatever,' but nobody ever makes an issue out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, University of Florida women's swim coach Mitch Ivey,
then 44, was fired after ESPN reported that he had been sexually
involved with his athletes _ some under the legal age for consent _
and verbally abused others to the point of constituting sexual
harassment. The incidents occurred before Ivey was hired by
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Ivey was 29 when he made advances
toward a 15-year-old on his California club team. The girl said
they began having sex when she was 17, which led to an abortion.
They married when she was 18 _ only to divorce, she said, when she
caught him having sex with a 17-year-old swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 33, Ivey allegedly began a relationship with a
16-year-old swimmer. They got engaged a year later, but she broke
it off after graduating from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ivey was not accused of being sexually involved with
University of Florida swimmers, one told ESPN that he spoke
numerous sexual slurs to her.
</P>
<P>
   And attorney Nancy Hogshead, an Olympian who trained with Ivey's
club team, said this week she was repulsed by Ivey's behavior and
would have left him had she not retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he used me to make his girlfriend jealous,'' she
recalled. ``He was telling her that I was interested in him. He's a
great coach. He got me my Olympic gold medal. But personally . . .
``
</P>
<P>
   She paused, then continued, ``I don't want to finish that
sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said he did nothing wrong and was fired by the university
so it would avoid bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said coaches have become far more aware of crossing the
line than when he began coaching. ``If my memory isn't faulty,
there were a lot more coaches involved with swimmers 30 years ago
than there are now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Essick, former head of U.S. Swimming, acknowledged that the
problem in his sport has not disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff is happening in American society today, and it
probably has happened forever,'' said Essick. ``If the Boy Scouts
of America and the Catholic Church are having those problems, I
don't feel like we're the lone ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Swimming is not alone in the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, two former tennis players at Syracuse University
filed a lawsuit alleging they were sexually harassed by coach Jesse
Dwire. Kirsten Ericson and Dacia Kornechuk are seeking $25 million
each in damages, claiming Dwire insisted on performing full-body
massages on them and repeatedly made inappropriate sexual comments
aimed at initiating a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The university suspended Dwire for three months without pay in
the summer of 1997 for remarks to athletes that violated the
school's sexual harassment and discrimination policies, but a
hearing panel found that other accusations against Dwire were not
violations. Dwire is back on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar suit filed last month, two former North Carolina
soccer players, including 1996 women's player of the year Debbie
Keller, accused coach Anson Dorrance of sexual harassment and other
misconduct. Keller and Melissa Jenings are seeking a combined $12
million in damages against Dorrance, UNC administrators and women's
assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina has been the nation's most dominant women's
soccer program, winning 14 of the 16 NCAA titles contested.
Dorrance is the only coach in the program's 20-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging charge was brought by Keller, a member of the
U.S. women's national team, who accused Dorrance of having made
``uninvited, unauthorized and offensive physical contact'' during
and after her college career. In October 1996, Keller alleged,
Dorrance coerced her into meeting him at a secluded area where he
made an ``uninvited sexual advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorrance has denied the charges, saying, ``I am shocked and
saddened by these allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Former tennis great Billie Jean King is among those who maintain
that male coaches acting inappropriately with young female athletes
is a much greater problem than female coaches involved in lesbian
relationships with athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you it's pervasive,'' she said. ``I know a couple
of tennis situations that are just horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Other alleged victims wouldn't cooperate
</P>
<P>
   Nyad acknowledges that she did not report Nelson when the
alleged incidents occurred. Later, she informed administrators at
Pine Crest and the University of Miami, both times shortly before
Nelson left jobs at the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Former Pine Crest headmaster Bill McMullen confirmed hearing the
allegations from Nyad and refused further comment. Sam Jankovich,
then the Miami athletics director, said he asked Nelson to resign
but declined to say if Nyad's accusations were a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson went on to coach the Fort Lauderdale Swim Team at the
Hall of Fame complex, where he is today.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Swimming officials once spoke to Nyad about her
allegations. ``We were aware of what she had said, but until it
went to a certain point we couldn't do anything,'' said Essick,
adding that other women Nyad alleged to have been involved with
Nelson refused to cooperate with investigators. ``We determined
there wasn't anything we could pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   The swim community wonders why Nyad never filed charges or why
Nelson never responded legally to accuse her of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sue him, because the statute of limitations
has run out,'' Nyad said. ``I looked into a number of loopholes,
but I don't want to spend 10 years of my life in a stupid court
process spending my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said, ``I have a very happy life, and some beautiful
young people who depend on me. I don't need for them to be thinking
of me as something other than their coach.''
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Tim McDermott, says he might have sent Nyad a
cease-and-desist letter several years ago, but he cannot remember
for certain.
</P>
<P>
   As for bringing a lawsuit against her, McDermott said, ``Jack is
not vindictive or nasty. Jack is a very understanding, forgiving
kind of fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
