</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nation can work through scandal, Carter says
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former President Carter said Tuesday that he hopes Congress will
decide quickly how it wants to handle independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's report, but he would not comment on whether he thinks
President Clinton should resign or be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its been a deplorable absorption by the public, the
news media, the Congress and the White House in this unfortunate
circumstance,'' he said in an interview in his office at the Carter
Center in Atlanta. ``My hope is that we'll resolve it (quickly) and
overcome it if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he hasn't discussed the scandal with Clinton since
he visited him in the Oval Office in January, shortly after the
story broke about Clinton's relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. Carter did not elaborate on what they
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he thinks the nation will be able to work through
whatever happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation is so strong, so powerful, so self-assured, so
diverse in its character and its responsibilities that no
peccadillo of a president or mistake of a president, even the one
that resulted in Nixon's (resignation), can seriously and adversely
affect our nation's character or strength,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
