u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONVERGENCE-COX     09-22 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVERGENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wider world for wireless devices
 &HT;    By Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the technology world, hardware _ the ever more
powerful computers, the slimmer hand communicators, the tiny but
potent processors _ get the most attention.
</P>
<P>
   Lost sometimes is the importance of software, which drives,
bolsters, and extends the reach and power of the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence Corp., a small private Norcross software developer,
is a player in the software game, manufacturing a timely product to
enhance a new breed of digital cell phones, as well as text pagers
such as ones being marketed by BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The Telebrowser is a Convergence pet project, which as the name
suggests, empowers the user to access the Internet with a hand-held
device. It capitalizes on the power of the Internet to provide
continuously updated information to keep business people informed
from anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently the system permits a customer armed with a sky
pager to keep up with stock portfolios, movements in company sales,
news developments, announcements by competitors, and even the
approach of a hurricane that could threaten business operations.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Robinson and Robert Frederick, two designers of the
browser, emphasize that the system can be more than a communicator.
It can be an imposing tool as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a weapon for the shark, not just the bystander,'' said
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it different,'' added Frederick, ''is that it can
take action if it is instructed in advance to watch for certain
developments.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Telebrowser software, which is placed within the
company network or at the server can be programmed to watch for
certain signals from the pager, and to look at certain Web sites
for pertinent information.
</P>
<P>
   It can watch for announcements on the business news wire by
competing companies, allied companies or government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   And in two-way applications, the system can contact lawyers,
publicists, executives within moments and print out information on
tiny screens.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers can pull up additional information by typing on tiny
keyboards on the pagers or cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   If programmed to do so, the pagers can tap into the Internet and
pull up very specific kinds of information.
</P>
<P>
   I watched Frederick use his pager to fetch the closing stock
price of a company on a specific day during the summer, and the
answer came back in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   The unique power of the software is the way it guides devices to
look at preassigned areas or databases on the Web, pull up
information and present it in a format that can be reproduced on
hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   The Norcross company's customers are mostly businesses.
Eventually institutions or any organizations that can gain from
being on top of certain kinds of information could become customers
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence's business is part of a global effort, dubbed
Bluetooth, that seeks to establish worldwide standards to permit
seamless communication among wireless devices, partly to extend the
reach of computing.
</P>
<P>
   Harald Bluetooth was a 10th-century king whose great
accomplishment was to unify the country we now call Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   In an approach that may not delight all phone companies and
others who own wires, cables and dedicated channels, Bluetooth
would dramatically facilitate and expand many forms of wireless
communication between devices.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Napier, marketing vice president of Convergence, said,
``Bluetooth will enable mobile professionals as well as consumers
to use each product to its fullest capability and automatically
connect with nearby devices as desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Likewise, manufacturers can focus on their product strengths
and not worry about which cellular or PCS radio technology to
incorporate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluetooth group, convened this year by Intel, encompasses
many manufacturers, including IBM, Ericsson, Nokia and Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   Portable computers stand to be a big beneficiary of the
converging wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   About the company
</P>
<P>
   _ Name: Convergence Corp.
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: 3120 Medlock Bridge Road NW, Norcross
</P>
<P>
   _ Web address: http://www.cvcorp.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Started: January 1997
</P>
<P>
   _ President: Jim Harkins
</P>
<P>
   _ Employees: 12
</P>
<P>
   _ Revenue: $1.2 million (approx.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Product: Software for Internet phone and unrestricted wireless
communication
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
