u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES23-C     09-22 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuba, U.S. in Georges' path
 &HT;    By Shelley Emling
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hurricane Georges, the deadliest storm of this hurricane
season, pounded the island of Hispaniola, shared by the Dominican
Republic and Haiti, and pushed late Tuesday toward Cuba and the
U.S. mainland, threatening to hit South Florida by late Thursday or
early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Packing winds of 120 mph when it slammed into the Dominican
capital of Santo Domingo, Georges was expected to leave Hispaniola
devastated. The two-nation island is home to 15 million people,
many of whom live in substandard housing.
</P>
<P>
   At least 13 deaths have been attributed to Georges during its
surge through the northern Caribbean. On Tuesday, the formidable
storm knocked out power and forced residents into shelters across
the densely populated Dominican Republic, where two people were
killed by downed electrical lines and a third by a collapsing wall.
</P>
<P>
   The storm already had claimed at least 10 lives in the
Caribbean, including five in Puerto Rico, where it left widespread
damage Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expected to issue a hurricane watch some time todayfor
South Florida, where residents packed the stores in search of
supplies such as batteries, flashlights and water.
</P>
<P>
   Georges was expected to weaken somewhat as it moved off the
shore of Hispaniola, but not below hurricane strength. As of 5 p.m.
EDT Tuesday, Georges had sustained winds of 110 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Still, forecasters at the National Hurricane Center predicted
that Georges would pack much less of a punch than Hurricane Andrew,
which caused billions of dollars in damage in densely populated
South Florida in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, workers placed shutters over the windows at City
Hall in Key West, while authorities advised all visitors and
non-residents of the Florida Keys to evacuate the island chain,
whose only connection to the mainland is a two-lane highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate most of the evacuations will occur on
Wednesday,'' said Billy Wagner, an official with the Monroe County
Emergency Management Service. ``Anyone who's got plans to visit the
Keys should postpone them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Caribbean, Georges had paralyzed Santo Domingo, a city of
3 million, by mid-afternoon, flooding streets, uprooting trees, and
whisking away tin roofs and satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials expected a high death toll in Haiti due to
the unsafe living conditions of thousands of desperately poor
Haitians. In Haiti's capital of Port-au-Prince, which is surrounded
by slums, fragile communities of cardboard homes cling to slippery
hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``People die here even when we just get a heavy downpour, one
that's not even a tropical storm, so this could be catastrophic for
us,'' said Michelle Karshan, a spokeswoman for Haiti's President
Rene Preval.
</P>
<P>
   When Tropical Storm Gordon, a much weaker system than Georges,
struck Haiti in 1994, hundreds of people were killed in mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane warnings were posted Tuesday for Haiti, eastern Cuba,
the southwestern Bahamas and the Turks and Caicos islands, and a
hurricane watch was in effect in parts of Cuba and the Bahamas on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and early Tuesday, Georges wreaked havoc across the
northeast Caribbean. With gusts of up to 130 mph, the hurricane
dumped two feet of water in the mountains of Puerto Rico, while
bending palm trees and flipping small aircraft like they were
pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, all of the U.S. territory's 3.8 million people were
without power, and 80 percent of people were without running water,
while more than 25,000 people sought refuge in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The airport in San Juan, Puerto Rico was able to operate Tuesday
for relief flights, but remained closed to other traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting from ground zero,'' Puerto Rico's Gov. Pedro
Rossello said of recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
