</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Some bugs are just nastier
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Chambers
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Surprise: Not all Y2K date problems need to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   By targeting only critical date operations, a Waltham, Mass.,
company enables its customers to save money and quickly repair
mainframe software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional methods require changing 5 to 10 percent of
software code, but only 0.5 percent of code really needs to be
repaired,'' said Benton Burgess, vice president of development for
Data Integrity Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only operations that really need to be fixed are
subtractions, logical comparisons, and sortings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Addition functions for dates and equal date comparisons don't
have to be fixed because they don't need a century value in order
to be correct _ two digits are sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Data Integrity makes PC-based software that investigates
mainframe source code.
</P>
<P>
   The product identifies operations that need to be fixed and
fixes them automatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs run from 7 cents to 14 cents per line of code,''
Burgess said. A large company customer, he noted, recently paid
$200,000 for a 6 million line fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal costs, using other methods, usually run from 70 cents
to $1.60 per line of code, so these guys could have spent upwards
of $6 million to $10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   A second benefit is speed. Another customer, he said, tested his
product against some others and found Data Integrity did in 15
minutes what took its closest competitor 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Data Integrity was founded in 1984. Its customers have included
CitiBank, NationsBank, and the U.S. Department of the Interior. The
company can be reached at 1-888-792-2001 or at its Web site
(http://www.dii2000.com).
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY FOCUS on TECHNOLOGY and TELECOMMUNICATIONS in METRO
ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
