<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-SETTLEMENT-COX     09-22 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SETTLEMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Local firm settles suit around Y2K
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Atlanta company last week paid two Michigan grocers
$250,000 in what is being called the first settlement of a
Y2K-related lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Produce Palace International in suburban Detroit sued
Doraville's Tec America, alleging $65,000 worth of cash registers
and credit card verification machines from that company
malfunctioned when cards bearing the year ``00'' expiration dates
were used to pay for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Tec America, the American subsidiary of Tokyo Electric Co.,
which is part of Toshiba, blamed the glitch on All-American Cash
Register of Inkster, a suburb of Detroit. That company installed
the system in 1995. The statement said Tec America's equipment has
accepted credit cards with 00 expiration dates since May 1997.
Fewer than 24 of the Tec systems are still in use nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with All-American Cash Register could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Yarsike, Produce Palace co-owner, said the system crashed
more than 100 times in the first 500 days after the store opened in
1995. Yarsike and co-owner Sam Katz filed suit in July 1997 asking
for $1.8 million in damages, Yarsike said. Tec America lawyer
Joseph Hoover said the pair asked for as much as $5 million during
negotiations. The trial was to have started Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Produce Palace suit, filed in July 1997, was the first
individual Y2K suit filed in this country, said Dean Morehous,
chairman of the technology practice for the San Francisco offices
of Thelen Reid &AMP; Priest.
</P>
<P>
   Tec attorney Hoover contends the suit is not a Y2K issue. He
said the cash registers malfunctioned because Michigan banks issued
credit cards with 00 expiration dates before most banks, and that
the system's software was not updated soon enough. Hoover said
All-American did a poor job installing the system. Tec America is
suing All-American, which has counter-sued.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 problem, or Y2K, prevents older software and
millions of embedded chips from reading the correct date after Dec.
31, 1999. In an era when memory was scarcer, programmers developed
computer systems that read dates in two digits. Unless fixed, older
systems will read the year 2000 as 00, which they consider to mean
1900.
</P>
<P>
   Produce Palace attorney Brian Parker, a Detroit-area lawyer who
specializes in automobile product liability, said Y2K is nothing
more than a high-tech lemon law matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all Y2K is,'' he said. ``They sold a product that you
didn't tell me was flawed. Now I have losses. People see computers
or technology and think it's confusing, but it's not. Y2K just
means someone screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarsike said the credit card problem usually would cripple the
system for 10 or 15 minutes, backing up checkout lines. The longest
the system was down was one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened continually,'' Yarsike said. ``We eventually
learned to do some things ourselves. Like reboot it and start it
back up. Most of the shutdowns were quick shutdowns, but they were
enough to create aggravation and havoc and things of that nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got attorneys because they wouldn't repair the system,'' he
said. ``We got an attorney and it woke them up.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, Produce Palace sent the system back
to Tec America. Yarsike said Produce Palace bought their new system
from NCR.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
