<HEADER>
A8839 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIL-WAR-MUSICAL-3TA     09-22 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-WAR-MUSICAL-3TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `MUSICAL EVENT' THAT'S BUCKING FOR, YES, A PROFIT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first sing-through of ``The Civil War,'' the
musical extravaganza that opened to enthusiastic audiences and
positive, if qualified, reviews at the Alley Theater here on Sept.
16, took place in the Alley's only rehearsal space, a windowless
room beneath the stage.
</P>
<P>
   It is a space more suitable for a chamber group than for the 28
singers and 9 musicians who crammed it that day in late August,
belting out the sentimental ballads and calculated, 11-o'clock show
stoppers that are the specialty of the composer, Frank Wildhorn.
</P>
<P>
   The room was so full of sound and musical emotion that several
of the performers, hearing the songs sung live for the first time,
were in tears. And it could be said that the scene was emblematic
of the Alley itself, a regional theater so bursting with grand
ambition for national, even international, notoriety that it can't
contain itself.
</P>
<P>
   Its striving has been evident in its recent productions, notably
the world premieres of Tony Kushner's ``Hydriotaphia,'' a
co-production with Berkeley Repertory Theater, where the play is
currently being performed; and ``Not About Nightingales,'' the
early Tennessee Williams play, a well-received collaboration with
England's Royal National Theater and the Moving Theater (founded by
Vanessa Redgrave and her brother, Corin), directed by Trevor Nunn,
for which the Alley is now seeking an appropriate home in New York.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of shows _ serious dramas that add to the
literature _ that have been the bread and butter of American
resident theaters during the past decade as the commercial
viability of such works has diminished. But ``The Civil War,''
which is Broadway-bound and being launched with the kind of
multi-media synergy more characteristic of the Disney company than
of a regional theater, is another animal entirely, a determinedly
middlebrow musical on a grandiose theme with a composer of
commercial pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   (Wildhorn has written dozens of pop anthems for the likes of
Whitney Houston and Natalie Cole, as well as the Broadway and
touring hit ``Jekyll and Hyde'' and the tenaciously lingering
Broadway show ``The Scarlet Pimpernel.'' The lyrics for ``The Civil
War'' were written by Jack Murphy, who has collaborated with
Wildhorn on many songs but never before on a musical.)
</P>
<P>
   At $2 million, ``The Civil War'' is the Alley's biggest
production in its 51-year history. It isn't strictly a book
musical; it's essentially a song cycle with text _ a la Ken Burns _
based on period poems, letters and other documents, and a set
consisting largely of projections by Wendall K. Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   Its songs, including ``I Never Knew His Name,'' a lamentation
crooned by a nurse about a soldier who died as she sat at his
bedside; ``Tell My Father,'' the last words of a dying soldier, and
``River Jordan,'' a gospel chorus about living in slavery, draw on
a variety of American idioms but are largely in a country music
mode, and they tend, like country music, toward gut-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is calling the show ``an epic musical event
encompassing the passion, breadth, romance and emotional power of
America's most defining moment,'' neither standard fare nor
standard promotion for a nonprofit theater.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Livent, the troubled Toronto-based entertainment
company, has turned to an artistic director with a nonprofit
background _ Todd Haimes of the Roundabout Theater in New York _ to
help right itself financially, the Alley's production of ``The
Civil War'' is another clear signal that the traditional divide
between commercial and nonprofit theater production is blurring.
And in Houston as elsewhere, such merging of art and commerce has
become a source of debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a musical and heading it for Broadway seems to me
unnecessary,'' said Ann Holmes, who covered theater for The Houston
Chronicle for 40 years and has written a history of the Alley. ``In
all the arts, all over the country, everything is being dumbed to
death. It's always what they try to do to bring in new crowds, but
in our overall artistic product we're experiencing a lessening,
which is exactly what you're seeing at the Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, not even Ms. Holmes, questions that the Alley's ambition
has been earned. Since the 1989-90 season, its first under the
artistic director Gregory Boyd, the theater has added three
artistic associates _ an eclectic triumvirate of Edward Albee,
Robert Wilson and Wildhorn _ and produced 10 shows a year on its
two stages, an 824-seat auditorium and a 296-seat box with the
audience surrounding the stage (where the Alley recently presented
``Long Day's Journey into Night,'' with Ellyn Burstyn).
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Boyd's programming has featured a wide range of shows,
from Wildhorn's ``Jekyll and Hyde'' and ``Svengali'' to ``The
Greeks,'' a large-scale adaptation of works by Aeschylus,
Sophocles, Euripides and Homer, directed by Boyd, and Wilson's
``Hamlet: a Monologue,'' along with the expected classics and
regional premieres of new plays that have made their names in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, 46, came to the Alley from Stage West, a company in
Springfield, Mass. He spent 11 years as an actor and director at
the Williamstown Theater Festival in the Berkshires and had
previously run the theater program at the University of North
Carolina (where, he is fond of recalling, he taught Michael
Jordan).
</P>
<P>
   A native of Berkeley, Calif., he came to theater consciousness
in the late 1960s, a time when the most influential theater guru in
the Bay Area was William Ball, the energetic artistic director of
the American Conservatory Theater in San Francisco; Ball, Boyd
said, along with ``the Peters _ Hall and Brook'' are his models for
artistic directorship. Like them, he believes that a theater should
use the classics to train a company for a spectrum of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is really mix it up,'' he said. ``I'm
either blessed or cursed with a catholicity of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd is widely given credit for engineering the theater's
rebound from a disastrous decade, which saw the death of its
founding director, Nina Vance, in 1980; the failure and dismissal
of her successor, Pat Brown, who subsequently sued the board for
$20 million (the suit was eventually settled); the abandonment in
mid-construction, when the oil industry went bust, of a 500-seat
proscenium theater on the 15th floor of a parking structure behind
the Alley building, and, in a gruesome tragedy, the murder, in the
theater, of Ms. Brown's managing director, Iris Siff, by a
disgruntled former employee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Vance, a genuine pioneer in the cultural life of the city,
oversaw the theater from its inception in a small dance studio (at
the end of an alley, hence the name), through the move to its
current building, an almost windowless castle-like fortress, in the
late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she earned the status of legend here, along with the
admiration of The New York Times's influential critic, Brooks
Atkinson, and that of the visionary vice president of the Ford
Foundation, W. McNeil Lowry, who called the Alley ``the most
significant professional theater outside New York'' and who was
behind the mammoth grant _ $2.1 million _ in 1962 that spurred the
construction of the new theater. Vance was still running the Alley
at the time of her death, and it floundered for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery has been both artistic _ it won the Tony Award in
1996 for outstanding regional theater _ and, particularly in the
last four years under the guidance of the managing director Paul R.
Tetreault, financial.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Alley's 50th, the company retired a debt that
had climbed to $2.5 million by the time Tetreault came aboard in
1994. And plans are once again under way to complete the new
theater, which would include additional offices and, for the first
time, sufficient rehearsal space.
</P>
<P>
   Subscriptions have held steady at about 17,000, but with a new
marketing plan _ unusually if not uniquely, the Alley has made
heavy use of radio and billboard advertising _ single-ticket sales
have risen some 12 percent, and fundraising has increased to $2.9
million a year ago from $2.2 million in 1994. They support an
annual budget of about $9 million, the 11th largest of any
nonprofit theater in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no great change in the art since I got here,''
Tetreault said. ``To be honest, Greg has always said, `I want the
people who go to the tractor pull and the people who go to the
opera to come to the Alley.' And that's what you get here. Tractor
pull? `The Civil War.' Opera? Robert Wilson.''
</P>
<P>
   What has been missing during Boyd's tenure is the development of
new work by new writers, a failing that Boyd acknowledges, albeit a
bit uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sensitive about the criticism, yes,'' he said. ``But I'm
hip to it as well. I read 500 new plays a year, and 99.99 percent
of them are not good. I see no reason to do a new play just because
it's new. It's like kissing your sister, a virtue, but so what? It
seems to me more worthwhile to take a proven playwright and say,
`Write something for us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His choices are also beholden, he said, to the nature of the
Alley, which maintains one of the country's few repertory companies
and whose identity, Boyd said, ``is as a group of artists, not so
much as a developer of new plays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you need to develop new playwrights,'' he said, ``but you
need to develop actors by doing classical work, by doing our
version of X by Chekhov, or Y by Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Alley is perhaps unique among regional theaters for
its role in its city's cultural establishment. The building sits
downtown in Houston's impressive cultural center, among the mammoth
homes of the symphony, the opera and the ballet, and not far from
where a new music hall and a new baseball stadium are being
constructed as part of the city's planned downtown renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   This is an old theater in a new city; the Alley is considered
mainstream, not fringe, Houston. And theatrically speaking, it
exists in a near vacuum. Houston is the nation's fourth-largest
city, but there are fewer theater companies here than in Seattle,
San Francisco or Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If the Alley does not present ``How I Learned to Drive'' or
``Angels in America'' or ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' Boyd
said, chances are Houstonians will not get to see them.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has left the Alley vulnerable to the charge of being
unadventurous. (A particularly critical article, titled ``Mixed
Review,'' appeared last year in Texas Monthly.) But its defenders
see the theater's programming as both suitable and challenging for
a city that sees itself as growing in sophistication and emerging
nationally as both a business and cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in Houston are pretty good at what they do,
and they're secure in themselves and interested in other people who
are good at what they do,'' said Meredith J. Long, an art dealer
who over the last 40 years has served on the boards of several arts
institutions and is chairman emeritus of the Alley board. ``They
appreciate that the Alley is much more cosmopolitan, that the bill
of fare is constantly at a higher level, that the Alley knows where
it is financially. Greg has been able to bring in highbrow
performances, and his success is not so much from a revenue
standpoint as from the standpoint of increasing audiences. If you
can't get them into the schoolhouse, you can't teach them to read.
A lot of these people are seeing some very tough theater along with
some great entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War'' _ which The Houston Chronicle reviewed as
lacking the impact of a standard book musical but as ``an ambitious
piece whose strengths outweigh its weaknesses'' _ is clearly at the
nexus of this debate. This is largely because of the music of
Wildhorn, 39, a self-described ``frustrated ex-jock'' with a pop
music background and a penchant as a composer, a la Sir Andrew
Lloyd Webber, for critic-proof, audience-pleasing melodies,
swelling arrangements and big voices.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``The Civil War'' includes Linda Eder, the star of
``Jekyll and Hyde'' (who also happens to be Wildhorn's wife) and
Michel Bell, who was last heard on Broadway in ``Show Boat,''
delivering a memorable version of ``Ol' Man River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to be Stephen Sondheim,'' Tetreault said of
Wildhorn, though he compares Wildhorn's aims with those of George
Gershwin, Cole Porter and Richard Rodgers, whose celebrated songs,
whether written for the theater or not, constituted the popular
music of their day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The songs they were writing for the theater transcended
theater,'' Wildhorn said. ``I don't know why in their day it was
O.K. to be a pop writer and now it's not.'' When Rodgers was
writing ``Some Enchanted Evening,'' he said, ``I can't believe he
didn't say to himself, `Boy, that's a pretty good hook.' He didn't
say: `This is getting too melodramatic. I better make it more
obscure.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorn is, admittedly, unmoved by either conventional
theatrical storytelling or the conventional expectations of a
theater audience. ``There's a lot more drama in sports,'' he said.
``The kind of stuff that an audience gives you in a sports event,
or a Bruce Springsteen concert, that's what I love. It's more
visceral and honest to me. I try to do that, write songs that go
right to the heart and transcend the moment onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War,'' he added, ``is by far the most emotional and
dramatic show I've ever written. You don't get back story, or
development. A dying soldier singing to his father? We don't even
have to know the guy's name and we get emotionally involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War,'' which after its Houston run is to make a
brief stop in New Haven in February before its scheduled opening at
the St. James Theater in April, is not the first original Broadway
musical to be developed in a nonprofit theater _ ``Tommy'' came out
of the La Jolla Playhouse and, most famously, ``A Chorus Line'' was
the product of the New York Shakespeare Festival _ but the
calculatedly commercial nature of the production is decidedly new.
</P>
<P>
   The show has the financial backing of the Pace Theatrical Group,
the nation's biggest tour organizer, and the ancillary support of
Atlantic Records, which, in addition to the planned cast album, is
releasing two recordings of the show's music, one featuring country
music stars like Travis Tritt and Trisha Yearwood, the other a
double-CD set featuring a range of performers including Hootie and
the Blowfish, Patti LaBelle and Betty Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   A television special is also in the works. It is a measure of
the show's commercial prospects that Enron, the locally based
energy company, chipped in $200,000, quadrupling its largest annual
contribution to the theater's coffers in exchange for, among other
things, its name above the title during the Houston run.
</P>
<P>
   The cynical view is that the Alley has sold out, that it expects
to collect royalties on ``The Civil War'' for a long time as it
runs on Broadway and tours the country, if not the world; that it
hopes to use the show to create a revenue stream like the $25
million or so that ``A Chorus Line'' produced for Joseph Papp and
the Shakespeare Festival. The Alley denies this, saying that like
all new musicals, this one's prospects are unproven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the reasons for `The Civil War' are all that
financially strategic,'' Tetreault said. ``We have to sell more
than $1.3 million in tickets to break even'' _ more than the Alley
has ever earned from any show. ``It's a mild risk,'' he added,
``though if it takes off, the Alley may have a windfall.''
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, said Boyd, who wrote the book for the show,
is that ``The Civil War'' falls completely within the Alley's view
of itself. The show was conceived as a big event, he acknowledged,
as part of the Alley's 50th-anniversary celebration (even if it
arrived a year late).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pop piece, no question,'' he said. ``But I'm not afraid
of that at all. If all we did was pop musicals, then we could point
a finger at ourselves. Our task is to make it a compelling theater
experience and not just a song cycle of very hooky songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the audience for `Civil War' will come back for Brecht
and Kushner. I have to think that it's all part of a continuum. The
great thing about the Alley right now is that there's nothing we
can't do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
