<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-COX     09-22 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton makes first trip to Capitol Hill since Starr reportBy
Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton visits Capitol Hill today to
honor South African President Nelson Mandela as House leaders
huddle behind closed doors to decide whether to take the next step
to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who will award Mandela a Congressional Gold Medal in
the Capitol Rotunda, has not appeared on the Hill since independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's massive report landed in the hands of the
House Judiciary Committee on Sept 10.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report alleges that Clinton committed perjury,
obstructed justice and abused his powers as president in an attempt
to conceal the relationship he now admits having with Monica
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 10 a.m. ceremony with Mandela, House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, Majority Leader Dick Armey, Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt and the leaders of the Judiciary Committee will meet to
discuss the impeachment review.
</P>
<P>
   A similar meeting two weeks ago produced pledges of
bipartisanship, but no such result is expected today in the
increasingly partisan climate in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican members of the panel, who have been saying
for some time that taking the next step and approving an
impeachment inquiry is ``inevitable,'' predict the matter may go to
the House floor within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, quoting GOP sources and one committee
member _ all speaking on condition of anonymity _ said the
committee could be empowered to go into the material submitted by
Starr earlier this month, as well as any additional evidence that
surfaces in the future. It was unclear whether this would mean that
other House committees _ a panel investigating 1996 campaign
fund-raising by the president, for example _ could bring their own
uncompleted probes under the impeachment umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has set an Oct. 9 target for adjournment, and senior
Republican officials are eager for a floor vote before then, in
part to force rank-and-file Democrats to go on record on the
matter, according to GOP sources quoted by the news service.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers sent a letter Tuesday to the Judiciary
Committee complaining that Starr omitted key portions of Lewinsky's
testimony from his report that substantiated the president's
contention that he never asked Lewinsky to lie on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In that letter, White House Counsel Charles Ruff and David
Kendall, the president's personal attorney, claim that Starr failed
to include Lewinsky's statement to his investigators that Clinton
never told her to lie about their affair nor promised her a job in
exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   Press Secretary Mike McCurry, who was traveling with Clinton in
New York, said the omission shows how ``grossly unfair'' Starr is.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report states: ``Ms. Lewinsky has stated that the
president never explicitly told her to lie.'' But it quickly
discounts that statement by concluding that both the president and
Lewinsky understood from their conversations that they would
``continue their pattern of covering up and lying about the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report does not include the following quotation from
Lewinsky's grand jury testimony: ``No one ever asked me to lie and
I was never promised a job for my silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Most House members have not seized the opportunity to comment on
Monday's release of the videotape of the president's August 17
testimony before a federal grand jury convened by Starr and
thousands of pages of supporting documents.
</P>
<P>
   But key Republicans in the Senate said they would like the House
to move forward with an impeachment inquiry, the
information-gathering stage of the process where hearings would
likely be held.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a call made Sunday by Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.),
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) said the president
should come to Capitol Hill to answer questions about his affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the president comes forward and comes clean in a
formal setting ... it would be a positive development,'' Lott told
reporters. ``The whole thing is demeaning to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee's investigative staff continued to
sift through the remaining 16 boxes of material from Starr, which
could be made public as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) met with Republican
members of his panel Tuesday afternoon to assess the process to
date. Emerging from that meeting, Hyde said the Democratic
assertion of partisanship on the committee ``isn't fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our job, following the mandate, which is to look
at all this stuff and cut out those things that don't really belong
there, for whatever reason, and then release the rest,'' Hyde said.
``It's a difficult job.'' When asked if he was concerned that
Republicans would face a backlash for releasing the salacious
details of the president's affair with Lewinsky, Hyde said he
trusted the public would see the relevance.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee's Democratic spokesman, Jim Jordan, had
a different view of the partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the majority of House Democrats did indeed vote to
release the bulk of the material sent to us by Ken Starr,'' Jordan
said. But those votes were based upon an agreement that the
committee would make all necessary and appropriate redactions, or
editing, to material that was deemed too salacious, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The disputes within the committee have centered on specific
redactions, usually of a highly sexual nature, that have been
proposed by Democrats and rejected by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to Chairman Hyde, I believe that each of
the Democratic members of the committee would strongly dispute his
characterization of the meetings as bipartisan, cooperative or
consultative,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
