<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8845 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIT-ME-FILM-$ADV27-NY     09-22 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIT-ME-FILM-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PASSION IN COLLEGE FOR A MASTER OF PULP FINALLY BEARS FRUIT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Annette Insdorf, director of undergraduate film studies at
Columbia, is writing a book on Krzysztof Kieslowski's films.) 
(af)  
 By ANNETTE INSDORF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I'm basically drawn to defeated, injured, hurt,
barely walking characters,'' said Steven Shainberg, the director of
``Hit Me.'' Little wonder, then, that he would choose a bleak,
gritty Jim Thompson novel, ``A Swell-Looking Babe,'' for his first
feature film.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though decidedly cheerful during an interview, Shainberg
has regarded Thompson as something of a soul mate ever since
college.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he had graduated from Yale in 1985, with a degree in
both English literature and East Asian studies, he had devoured all
of Thompson's work. Within a year, as he tried to carve out a
career as a filmmaker. ``I had five of his books under option for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my then-producing partner, the idea was to do a whole
series of movies from these books, but then I decided to go to the
American Film Institute. It didn't make sense to hold on to the
option for five books if I was committing to film school, so I made
a deal to retain the rights only to a `A Swell-Looking Babe.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Enrolling in the institute's directing program, Shainberg, now
35, went on to make award-winning shorts, including ``The Prom''
and ``The Secretary'' _ both starring Jennifer Jason Leigh and J.T.
Walsh _ as well as music videos. But he kept alive his hope to film
``A Swell-Looking Babe,'' particularly as he watched other
directors turn Thompson novels into film _ ``After Dark, My Sweet''
and ``The Grifters.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the fascination with a writer who, when he died in 1977, had
no novels remaining in print in the United States? Shainberg said
he is drawn by ``the intensity'' of Thompson's ``subjective point
of view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories are always told from a disturbed, passionate and
weird protagonist's perspective _ often violent characters who are
lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit Me'' _ whose script was was written by his longtime
writing partner, the novelist Denis Johnson _ tells the story of
Sonny, a frustrated bellhop in a seedy hotel in Tacoma, Wash.
(Thompson once worked as a bellhop in Ft. Worth).
</P>
<P>
   With dark humor, the film, which opens Oct. 2, recounts how
Sonny, played by Elias Koteas, tries in vain to escape a numbing
life. He is seduced not only sexually _ by a mysterious young
French hotel guest (Laure Marsac) _ but also financially: the
bellhop is lured into ripping off a high-stakes poker game run by
the local crime boss (Philip Baker Hall).
</P>
<P>
   Shainberg first saw Koteas in ``The Adjuster'' (1991), one of
the actor's many collaborations with the Canadian director Atom
Egoyan. ``He plays a character who does not emote at all, a blank
slate,'' Shainberg recalled over an espresso in midtown Manhattan.
``For some reason, I thought, this is an actor with repressed
energy, waiting to bust out.''
</P>
<P>
   After memorable appearances as the impresario of car wrecks in
David Cronenberg's 1996 movie ``Crash,'' and as the demonic
murderer strapped to an electric chair in this year's ``Fallen,''
Koteas is considered to be on the brink of stardom, a view
reinforced by the buzz about his strong performance in Terrence
Malick's forthcoming ``Thin Red Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Shainberg sees little coincidence in the fact that both he and
Malick _ also an AFI graduate _ gravitated toward Koteas. ``Malick
is obviously interested in isolation, desperation and the figure
lost in the landscape,'' he said about the director of the starkly
beautiful ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven.'' ``There's something
about Elias that is conducive to those themes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the juiciness of the role in ``Hit Me,'' Koteas was at
first reluctant to take it; he was ``unsure about playing a
loser,'' he said by phone from Los Angeles. ``But,'' he added,
``the script was unlike anything I've read and, luckily, Steve was
insistent. He let me be free and gave me my wings again.''
</P>
<P>
   Koteas credits Shainberg not only with ``a good ear for the
truth _ he doesn't let actors get actory'' _ but with visual
mastery. ``His camera had its own voice'' Koteas said. ``For an
actor to be part of that landscape revitalizes you.''
</P>
<P>
   Shainberg created a visual landscape that recalls the bleak and
lonely paintings of Edward Hopper. When asked if his ``film noir''
was a kind of ``Hopper noir,'' he replied, ``Yes, but it's also
inspired by Mark Tansey, one of my favorite painters, and Eric
Fischl, whose paintings are very filmic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the look of the movie, I said to the designer, `I want to
make Sonny feel as uncomfortable as possible.' So we used only
synthetic colors in the hotel, colors that don't exist in nature.
In the hallway, he is the only living thing, wearing a jacket the
color of salmon _ a kind of human fish slithering through, running
out of air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Swell-Looking Babe'' attracted him, Shainberg said,
precisely because ``I love moving through long spaces and being
enclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone who hates exteriors _ natural light is
unacceptable to me! _ Thompson's book allowed for total control.''
</P>
<P>
   The very control exerted by the director is what the characters
are missing. Sonny, who is trapped not only by his buddies but
perhaps his destiny, exemplifies for Shainberg that ``there comes a
point for everyone when you finally have to  &UR; do &LR;  something to
change your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But for a lot of people, it won't change,'' he said. ``There's
a kind of dream that movies sell to people: You can start as the
lowliest person and rise to the top. `Hit Me' doesn't sell this
fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the film begins with Thoreau's observation, ``The mass
of men lead lives of quiet desperation.'' Does a bellhop who serves
an endless succession of strangers also serve as the perfect
embodiment of the quotation? Maybe so. But, as Shainberg quipped,
``Who could be more desperate than filmmakers?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
