<HEADER>
A8852 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-2NDTAK     09-22 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the president.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the broadcast of Clinton's testimony before the grand jury,
showing a president ranging from contrite to argumentative, furious
to crestfallen, seemed in fact to strengthen the president.
</P>
<P>
   Polling conducted by Gallup for CNN and US Today showed a
six-point jump in Clinton's job approval rating, to 66 percent,
after the broadcast, compared with 60 percent on Sunday. And CBS
News found that since the telecast, 68 percent of those polled
approved of the way Clinton was doing his job, up from 59 percent
since the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the job approval numbers, however, the public was still
divided over Clinton's trustworthiness, and a majority of those
polled still believe that he lied under oath about his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress also saw the volatility of public opinion in
their own phone calls from constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said that on Thursday and Friday,
phone calls to his office were ``as heavy as I'd ever seen it'' and
running 8 to 1 against the president. But on Tuesday, he said the
calls became ``much more favorable'' to the president. ``It was
significantly changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said he thought little had
changed. ``People who thought the president was a liar felt
vindicated,'' he said. ``People who felt he was being picked on
felt vindicated. And people who hadn't made up their minds were
bored out of their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one Republican took to the Senate floor on Tuesday to
warn his party against even the appearance of partisanship or a
rush to judgment. ``I think it's very important that there be a
real effort on the part of Republicans _ because we Republicans are
in control _ to not press for every bit of advantage,'' warned Sen.
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans fended off any talk of an early deal with the
president, they moved forward with a timetable that would set a
House vote on whether to open an impeachment inquiry for early
October. Impeachment hearings would then be put off until after the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists said the delay would allow their party to
move cautiously before the election _ neither turning off their own
conservative base by being too easy on the president nor appearing
to be too harsh. Because of Clinton's troubles, Republicans are now
expecting to increase their majorities in both the House and the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican House member who is closely monitoring the
elections said that the volatility of the public mood argued for
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is in unchartered waters waiting for the fog to lift
and figure out where they are,'' he said, speaking on condition
that he not be identified. ``No one is willing to make a deal until
they know where they stand. The polls are meaningless. The
president's support is a fraction of an inch deep. Every number
besides his favorable rating is ominous for Democrats. And
Republicans know that misplaying their hand is dangerous too.
Everyone's in a state of suspended animation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
