<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notebook: Pepper irks Europeans
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The LPGA needs more players like Dottie Pepper, whose
competitive fires burn hotter than anyone's in women's pro golf.
But as great as she is to have on your side, she's also can
irritate an opponent. A few members of the European team were
clearly miffed about Pepper's fist-pumping, crowd-inciting tactics
in last weekend's Solheim Cup, which ended in a 16-12 American
victory. On Saturday, before Europe's Marie Laure de Lorenzi was to
chip, Pepper riled up the Muirfield Village crowd after teammate
Juli Inkster clinched her par at the 18th. ``Her behavior is
unprofessional and unnecessary,'' England's Laura Davies said. ``It
nearly spurred us on to victory on the final day. She made a big,
big mistake.'' Pepper, who is 12-4-1 in Solheim matches, said, ``I
wouldn't be the same person if I played without emotion. To me,
it's patriotism.'' It didn't stop several European players from
imagining a likeness of Pepper on a punching bag in the fitness
trailer before Sunday's singles matches. ``I take it as a
compliment. Period,'' Pepper said. ``If that's what it takes, I'm
glad to be their punching bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods concerned about Daly's condition
</P>
<P>
   While it was reported that International Management Group wanted
John Daly to withdraw from the Oct. 8-11 Alfred Dunhill Cup matches
at St. Andrews because of his recent medical problems, he remains
on the U.S. team with Tiger Woods and Mark O'Meara. On Monday,
during an exhibition in Reno with Lee Trevino, Fuzzy Zoeller and
Tom Watson, Daly was joking about his past problems with alcohol,
making reference to several years when he regularly punched his
fists through car windows ``when I was really mad and drunk.''
Woods knows Daly's value if healthy _ they are playing on the same
ground where Daly won the 1995 British Open _ but has concerns
about his health. ``I mean, is this the best time for him to be
playing?'' Woods said. ``Personally, I'm more afraid for him. He's
an extremely nice guy. It's just that we all feel so sorry for
him.'' Woods said he has no problem with Daly as a teammate ``as
long as he goes out there and gives it 100 percent on every shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo apparently has ended his 13-year relationship with
coach David Leadbetter. Leadbetter told GolfWeb that Faldo notified
him of the split with a letter sent to the Leadbetter Golf Academy.
He said Faldo decided to work with Chip Koehlke of the Faldo Golf
Institute. ``It's disappointing when you work so hard with a player
for so many years,'' Leadbetter said. ``. . . . Sometimes you need
a fresh outlook, I suppose. Still, it was a bit of a shock.'' . . .
. David Duval, playing in the Trophee Lancome near Paris on Sunday,
failed to do what Billy Andrade managed the week before in Canada _
spend the weekend in the water at an 18th hole and still win. Duval
double-bogeyed the closing 209-yard par 3 Sunday, losing to Spain's
Miguel Angel Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
