u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-685&AMP;     09-22 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTER PROFIT AT GOLDMAN DECLINES 25 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. said Tuesday that it earned $754 million
before taxes in its fiscal third quarter, a drop of about
one-fourth from the second quarter, as global market turmoil took a
toll on profit and cast doubts on Goldman's own planned public
offering of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Executives acknowledged Tuesday that they were debating whether
to delay the private partnership's much-anticipated initial public
offering, a decision some market analysts look to as a statement on
the stock market's health. If the firm were to delay the offering,
it would suggest that some of the United States' most successful
investment bankers considered it unlikely that financial markets
would significantly recover before year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's six-man executive committee does not have to decide
whether to proceed with the offering until early next month, said
the executives, who spoke on the condition that they not be
identified. It is still scheduled for November. But top company
officials are at least considering the prospect of delaying until
1999, especially since the firm expects its earnings slide to
continue through the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go public if you can't deliver the quarter,'' a
Goldman executive says. ``And you can't fight the tape,'' he said,
alluding to the falling stock prices of financial company rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in financial markets and the stock prices of Goldman
competitors have deteriorated sharply since June, when the 189
partners voted to take the firm public.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's two main peers, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, have seen their stock prices plunge by about half from
their peaks in July. They had been trading at high levels in
relation to earnings, on hopes that profit would continue to grow
quickly, but the reverse is turning out to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldman, Sachs earnings decline is indicative of a broader
Wall Street trend, as Goldman is the first of the big securities
firms to report results.
</P>
<P>
   Many financial companies have suffered losses in emerging
markets since August. But the bigger worry now is the health of
bond markets in advanced economies, a far more important source of
profit. Russia's decision to devalue its currency and default on
some domestic debt has wreaked havoc with prices of debt
securities, and the turmoil shows no sign of easing.
</P>
<P>
   John Thain, Goldman's chief financial officer, said in a
statement that the firm's earnings in some areas, including mergers
and acquisitions advising and asset management, remained robust
through the third quarter, which for Goldman means June, July and
August. But trading and underwriting of new equity and debt issues
took a hit, he said, and the slowdown has continued in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increased volatility in the financial markets, the widening of
credit spreads, a decline in liquidity in certain markets and a
reduction in global equity values have adversely affected many
participants in the financial services sector,'' Thain said. ``We
expect these conditions to negatively impact our fourth-quarter
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Goldman's third-quarter earnings were 25 percent less
than in the second quarter and about 20 percent less than in the
quarter a year earlier, results for the year to date remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of the 1998 fiscal year, the firm
reported pretax earnings of $2.814 billion, compared with $2.447
billion for the corresponding period of 1997. Net revenue for the
first nine months was $7.605 billion and expenses were $4.791
billion. Goldman reports only pretax earnings, as the individual
partners settle their own taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings drop is roughly in line with expectations, said
Raphael Soifer, securities-industry analyst at Brown Brothers
Harriman. But because June and July were relatively strong months,
the 25 percent slump in earnings for the quarter implies a bad
August, he said. And with the slump continuing into September, the
stars are not well aligned for a big Goldman initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``One wonders how one can bring a big IPO into a market this
volatile,'' Soifer said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two other securities companies, Morgan Stanley and Lehman
Brothers, will report results this week. Analysts are expecting
Morgan Stanley to show a similar 25 percent drop in earnings
compared with the second quarter. Lehman Brothers, whose profit
depends more on trading and the bond market than does Morgan's or
Goldman's, is expected to sustain even sharper damage, with
operating earnings falling by about half from the second-quarter
level.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all other brokerage firms and big international banks
are expected to report falling quarterly profit, and in some cases,
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is usually quick to react to changes in market
conditions, and many expect companies to begin laying off workers
in coming weeks. Merrill Lynch and Bankers Trust have already
warned that layoffs are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, who analyzes the securities industry for Salomon
Smith Barney, said that with no quick turnaround for financial
markets in sight, banks and brokerage firms would look for ways to
save money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will look to cut as much fat as they can as soon as they
can,'' he said. But Moszkowski added that some Wall Street houses
overreacted to the 1994 market downturn and dismissed too many
people, making them ill prepared to profit when markets recovered.
``The lesson from 1994, I think, is that they shouldn't be too
quick to cut muscle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
