<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGUY-MARIN-DANCE-$AD     09-22 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGUY-MARIN-DANCE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANGE OF COURSE TOWARD DANCES FOR THE PEOPLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYONS, France _ ``I'm no longer interested in spectacle. I now
want my pieces to deal with what is going on today,'' Maguy Marin,
the experimental French choreographer, said recently over lunch
near Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the conversation was clear: a shift in the
47-year-old choreographer's career. Ms. Marin has moved her
modern-dance troupe, the Compagnie Maguy Marin, from the Parisian
suburb of Creteil to Rillieux-La-Pape, a tougher immigrant suburb
of Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   She has also stopped doing commissioned works for major ballet
companies and is concentrating on her own company, which will
present her 1995 ``Ramdam'' at the Joyce Theater from Tuesday
through Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it was the Lyons Opera Ballet that presented some
of the highly elaborate productions for which she is best-known:
``Cendrillon,'' a doll-house version of ``Cinderella'' seen in New
York in 1987, and ``Coppelia,'' in a modern-dress, mixed-media
staging performed at Lincoln Center Festival '96.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, she said, her emphasis is different. ``I want my
work to be closer to people,'' she said. ``Members of the public
should recognize themselves in my pieces. I want to discard magic
and spectacle. I had a theatrical period, with its field of dreams.
But a dream must also be real, and one must try to blur dream and
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It is back to basics for Ms. Marin, whose early acclaim came
with pared-down pieces like ``May B,'' her terse and brilliant 1981
tribute to Samuel Beckett.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marin, who founded her troupe in 1978, said that as time
went by in her work, ``the performer was taking second place to
production values, and I kept using more dancers and more sets. It
was time to step back and reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, she met her current husband, the composer
Denis Mariotte, who created the scores for recent pieces, including
``Waterzooi,'' performed in 1995 at the Joyce. There, dancers in
her company played toy instruments devised by Mariotte. Although
the tone of the piece was abstract, it was actually a clever and
engaging essay about human emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to start with the abstract in order to work on concrete
things,'' Ms. Marin said. ``If you begin with concrete ideas, you
are closed off. There are more possibilities in the abstract where
things are suggested, not stated. Again, between the dream and
reality, there is something not said, which remains open.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said: ``My subject is always about human
relations. I am not a message choreographer, but I am concerned
with the human condition, especially male-female relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer, however, rarely begins with a defined
subject, except when she is given a commissioned project as in
Lyons Opera Ballet's ``Cendrillon.''
</P>
<P>
   In her own company, she is apt to start on a formal level of
experimenting with movement, especially articulation of isolated
parts of the body. ``Ramdam'' (``Tumult'') consists of two
complementary works in which Ms. Marin and Mariotte experiment with
dancers' vocalizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The springboard for the first piece, `Ram,' is the voice,''
Ms. Marin said. ``The dancers create rhythmic music as they speak
and dance. But you can't always understand them. And you realize
that for all the talk and information in the world, we don't always
hear each other. What do we really know?
</P>
<P>
   ``The dancers wear standard street dress, which doesn't reveal
the inner person, and we hear voices that don't express true
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the `Dam' section, there is more noise. The dancers play
simple instruments. `Ram' is square, `Dam' is more fluid and
explosive. It made me think of a text from a Beckett book, not a
play, where he speaks of how information is distributed and
deformed. The book is `Comment C'est' but because Beckett did not
want any parts of it staged, we could not get the rights to use
excerpts onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in ``May B,'' Ms. Marin's concern was to extend her
company's performing range. ``I wanted more than a dancer, one who
could act and sing and use his or her entire body.''
</P>
<P>
   But about seven years ago, she felt things were going stale.
When she set up a studio in Sainte Foy-les-Lyons, she was contacted
by town authorities in Rillieux-La-Pape, at the opposite end of
Lyons. She agreed to transfer her company there and seek financing
from four other working-class towns and suburbs east of Lyons to do
outreach work in community centers, especially with minority young
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this experience would revitalize us,'' she said.
``Since January, we have given lecture-demonstrations and classes
with people of all ages. Fifteen years ago, I would not have done
this. I would have said I need the time to choreograph. But today,
we have matured and need this contact with the public, especially a
new public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
