</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PANEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL EDITS 16 BOXES, HOPING TO FORESTALL PANDORA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Calif., Ill., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBS, CLINTON-REACT,
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE) 
(jw) 
 BY ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee continued Tuesday to
pick through the 16 remaining boxes of evidence turned over by the
independent counsel, flagging portions that may be too private, too
embarrassing or irrelevant for public viewing.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the committee released transcripts and videotapes of
President Clinton's grand jury testimony, Democratic and Republican
aides were pushing to complete by Thursday their screening of
thousands of pages of other documents, many of which contain
sexually explicit references.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the panel's 37 lawmakers, still nursing their
wounds from last week's partisan thrashing over whether to release
Clinton's videotape, will hunker down in closed session to weigh
the staff's suggested cuts from the new, and much larger, batch of
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Under a House resolution, approved by an overwhelmingly
bipartisan vote, the committee must release all remaining material
by Monday, except for those passages deemed too sensitive or
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers were bracing for another bruising showdown later
this week, as Republicans repeated their calls to release as much
information as possible to allow the public to judge Clinton's
truthfulness. ``The people's right to know is very strong,'' said
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans who have read the material said there were
no bombshells lurking in the transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything new,'' Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif.,
told reporters after a 75-minute meeting among committee
Republicans on Tuesday afternoon. ``I haven't seen anything
remarkable above and beyond'' the accusations leveled in Kenneth
Starr's 445-page report.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members declined to describe in detail the remaining
documents or discuss whether the boxes held material favorable to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the grand jury depositions from central figures like Betty
Currie, Clinton's secretary, as well as the tape-recorded
conversations between Monica Lewinsky and her one-time confidante
Linda Tripp, no doubt will add textured detail to the broad
outlines of what is known about those exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   With the House taking no votes on Tuesday and many lawmakers
still in their districts, about eight or nine Republicans on the
committee met privately to discuss scheduling, procedures and a
summary of the committee staff's suggestions for exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican who heads the committee,
told reporters afterward that aides had made good progress, going
through all but four of the 16 remaining boxes. Starr sent two sets
of 18 boxes to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the aides had agreed on some deletions and disagreed
on others. But lawmakers will review all on Thursday. ``It's
laborious, but we made a lot of progress,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said it was possible that some of the remaining documents
could be made public before Monday's deadline, but other lawmakers
and aides said a release earlier than Monday was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the material forwarded by Starr, the committee
now also has the six-hour deposition Clinton made on Jan. 17 before
lawyers for Paula Jones. Hyde said the committee would review ``the
film of the deposition, probably over the weekend or next week''
and then decide whether to make it public.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said his committee should release
Clinton's deposition in the Jones civil suit, or at least those
parts ``related to Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have long argued that the committee has released more
information than the public needs to judge Clinton's word, and that
the additional disclosures serve only to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde dismissed criticisms that too much or too little
information was being released. ``It's hard to take the temperature
of the public,'' Hyde said. ``We're just doing what we were
mandated to do by the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also held out hope that despite last week's bitter partisan
wrangling, Democrats and Republicans could bridge their differences
and consider the solemn possibility of impeachment proceedings
without rancor. ``I have not given up on bipartisanship,'' Hyde
said.
</P>
<P>
   But other Democrats and Republicans were less sanguine,
expressing fear that the recriminations would only worsen. Canady
shook his head in an interview and said, ``In light of the position
that Democrats have taken _ that even if true, Starr's allegations
don't constitute impeachable offenses _ it'll be impossible to
achieve a consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
