<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-SPENDING-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS MORE MONEY FOR MILITARY READINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week after the nation's military commanders
warned him about growing fiscal strains on the armed services,
President Clinton Tuesday proposed giving the Pentagon an immediate
new infusion of cash and opened the door to a much larger increase
in military spending in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Secretary of Defense William Cohen, Clinton said
he would take ``additional steps'' to plug a series of shortfalls
already envisioned in the Pentagon's $270 billion budget for the
fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Those shortfalls, which commanders told the president were
eroding their readiness to fight and win the next war, have led to
shortages of spare parts for warplanes, cuts in training and
difficulties in recruiting and keeping qualified troops.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton specifically pledged to address each of those readiness
problems and promised to avoid similar problems in the 2000 budget
that the Office of Management and Budget will propose early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commit to you that then men and women of our armed forces
will have the resources that they need to do their jobs,'' Clinton
said in the letter, which Pentagon officials made available on the
condition that they not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The letter did not mention specific figures, but officials at
the Pentagon said the Clinton administration would immediately
propose adding $1 billion to the $4 billion emergency supplement
already proposed for the coming budget.
</P>
<P>
   For the next budget, the president's commitment is less clear. A
spokesman at the White House said Clinton had yet to commit himself
to increasing the overall military budget for 2000, which is set to
grow slightly to $276 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But an administration official said Clinton _ implicitly in the
letter and explicitly in conversations with senior officials at the
Pentagon _ had indicated his support for the first significant
increase in military spending since he took office.
</P>
<P>
   How significant remains to be worked out. The Pentagon's budget
makers have yet to come up with a figure, but analysts have
estimated that an increase could fall between $10 billion and $20
billion, for an increase of 3.5 percent to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The president's pledges came only a week before the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, led by Gen. Henry Shelton, are to appear before the
Senate Armed Services Committee at a special hearing on problems
with the military's readiness. The pledges will give the chiefs
something to use to respond to Republicans who have become
increasingly critical of the administration's military spending,
accusing Clinton of letting the armed forces weaken.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting with Clinton at the National Defense University
last week, the joint chiefs and the unified combat commanders
warned that the increasing duties at home and aboard placed heavy
strains on the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps at a time
when budgets have more or less stayed level with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The readiness strains have led to a series of problems, Pentagon
officials say, from shortages of spare parts to a growing gap
between civilian and military pay that many in the Pentagon believe
is forcing the most qualified troops to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's letter, Clinton wrote, ``Readiness is a perishable
commodity and requires our serious attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Shelton have tried to highlight the shortfalls in
recent months, laying the groundwork for a plea for additional
money. The issue has become more urgent, they have said, because
Congress has refused for two years to agree to close more unneeded
military bases, a step that could save $20 billion over the next
decade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republican aides in the House and the Senate said Tuesday that
they were unaware of the president's letter, though they indicated
that any increase in defense spending was likely to receive broad
support. Already there have been bipartisan calls to increase the
Pentagon's budget for everything from new weapons programs to
improvements in the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how the administration would pay for any increase
in military spending. Another administration official said the $1
billion increase in the immediate future would most likely be
obtained through cuts elsewhere in the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   As for future budgets, Clinton has pledged not to spend any
surpluses until the White House and Congress agree on how to
preserve the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Without the surplus, the balanced-budget agreement would force
the administration to cut spending elsewhere to pay for any
significant increase for the Pentagon, a move that could lead to
fights within the administration and the Democrat Party over
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which has been overtaken by the booming economy,
capped Pentagon spending at about $270 billion this year, but the
caps come off next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Council for a Livable World Education Fund, an advocacy
group in Washington, said in a statement Tuesday that Congress was
using ``anecdotal evidence'' of readiness problems to justify
pork-barrel increases in weapons systems in their home states. The
council added, ``Congress is more interested in preserving local
jobs than helping to solve any readiness problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
