<HEADLINE>
GAME MAKER COOPERATES WITH SEC PROBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ AirTouch Communications has the best cellular
service in greater Los Angeles and L.A. Cellular the worst,
according to a survey by consumer research specialist J.D. Power
and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its annual U.S. wireless customer satisfaction study
released Tuesday, J.D. Power asked 10,249 households in 22 markets
across the country to rate their wireless providers on call
quality, pricing, billing options, customer service and other
categories. The study included results only on providers that hold
10 percent or more market &UR;  &LR; share in a given region. In greater &UR;  &LR; Los
Angeles, only Cerritos-based L.A. Cellular and San Francisco-based
AirTouch qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Based on scores given the two companies by local respondents,
AirTouch scored 101, while L.A. Cellular garnered an 85, making it
the worst performer not only in L.A. but in all of the markets
studied.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, L.A. Cellular thought the results were skewed.
``Our internal reports have always shown us ahead of AirTouch,
PacBell, Sprint and the others,'' said L.A. Cellular spokesman
Steve Crosby. Crosby said that a July survey by another research
group, Emerald Bay Systems Inc., found L.A. Cellular the best
service provider in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to retain our customers, so I don't know. Maybe
this is a study AirTouch paid for or is somehow involved in,''
Crosby said of the J.D. Power report.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Dresch, director of telecommunications market analysis at
J.D. Power, said the study was independently conducted and
financed.
</P>
</TEXT>
