<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-1STLD-     09-22 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-TV-RATINGS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-POLL) 
 REPUBLICANS DISMISS TALK OF LESSER PUNISHMENT FOR CLINTON AS
`PREMATURE'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 12th graf to fix date for Gingrich-Gephardt meeting and for
other minor editing changes.)  
(See also CLINTON, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-PANEL, (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans vowed on Tuesday to press
ahead with their consideration of an impeachment inquiry even
though the broadcast of President Clinton's grand jury testimony
about Monica Lewinsky did nothing to shake his national standing,
and may even have strengthened it.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing that Clinton's job approval ratings had gone
up after the release of his videotaped testimony, White House aides
sent strong signals that the president would accept some kind of
censure, and possibly a fine, to end the threat of impeachment. But
Republicans in both the House and the Senate flatly rejected the
idea of a deal as premature, preferring to see the outcome of the
November elections and whether the Whitewater independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, will follow up with indictments.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the video's release, members of both parties
now consider it inevitable that the House Judiciary Committee will
quickly recommend a full impeachment inquiry. Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., who is chairman of the committee, said on Tuesday that if
the House voted for an inquiry he would like to open hearings
shortly after the midterm election.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde waved off discussion of some lesser punishment for the
president as ``very premature to talk about,'' and indicated that
such negotiations could come only if the House decided to impeach
the president and try him before the Senate. ``That's a decision,
if it ever gets there, for the Senate to make,'' he said. ``But
we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans also widely dismissed any effort to
short-circuit an impeachment inquiry. ''We have a constitutional
process to follow,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the
majority whip. ``I don't think you should say, `Well, here is what
we decided should be the outcome _ it should be impeachment, it
should be censure, it should be reprimand, it should be nothing.' I
don't think we should guess what the solution should be and then
work to build it.''
</P>
<P>
   With manuevering intensifying in Congress, the White House
opened a new counterattack against Starr. Having seen the 3,200
pages of documentation made public by the House Judiciary
Committee, the president's lawyers accused the independent counsel
of distorting the evidence against Clinton in his report citing 11
possibly impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the House Judiciary Committee, David Kendall,
Clinton's private lawyer, and Charles F.C. Ruff, the White House
counsel, said Starr ``ignored all reasonable standards of
fairness'' and left out evidence that supports the President.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, cited the
exclusion of Ms. Lewinsky's statement to a grand jury that ``no one
ever asked me to lie and I was never promised a job for my
silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the charges, Hyde said, ``My staff tells me that's
just not so,'' but added that ``we welcome any correspondence''
from White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Republican dismissal of any deal, the White House and
prominent Democrats also worked feverishly behind the scenes to
craft a punishment for Clinton short of impeachment that could have
appeal within their own party and to respected Republicans outside
Capitol Hill. Over the weekend, Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., suggested
that Clinton should testify before the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said on Tuesday that he would welcome an appearance by
Clinton before his committee, but said the ``orderly procedure''
would be for the president to appear after a formal impeachment
inquiry had begun. Sen. Tom Daschle, the Senate minority leader,
said he was not certain he would recommend that the president take
such a course. ''I have questions about the kind of fair hearing he
would get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia and Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, the House minority leaer, were to meet on Wednesday with
the leaders of the House Judiciary Committee to discuss the next
steps in the Clinton investigation. The deliberations have become
increasingly partisan since the House voted 363-63 to make public
Starr's report, with Democrats accusing the Republicans of seeking
to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the broadcast of Clinton's testimony before the grand jury,
showing a president ranging from contrite to argumentative, furious
to crestfallen, seemed in fact to strengthen the president.
</P>
<P>
   Polling conducted by Gallup for CNN and US Today showed a
six-point jump in Clinton's job approval rating, to 66 percent,
after the broadcast, compared with 60 percent on Sunday. And CBS
News found that since the telecast, 68 percent of those polled
approved of the way Clinton was doing his job, up from 59 percent
since the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the job approval numbers, however, the public was still
divided over Clinton's trustworthiness, and a majority of those
polled still believe that he lied under oath about his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress also saw the volatility of public opinion in
their own phone calls from constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said that on Thursday and Friday,
phone calls to his office were ``as heavy as I'd ever seen it'' and
running 8 to 1 against the president. But on Tuesday, he said the
calls became ``much more favorable'' to the president. ``It was
significantly changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said he thought little had
changed. ``People who thought the president was a liar felt
vindicated,'' he said. ``People who felt he was being picked on
felt vindicated. And people who hadn't made up their minds were
bored out of their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one Republican took to the Senate floor on Tuesday to
warn his party against even the appearance of partisanship or a
rush to judgment. ``I think it's very important that there be a
real effort on the part of Republicans _ because we Republicans are
in control _ to not press for every bit of advantage,'' warned Sen.
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans fended off any talk of an early deal with the
president, they moved forward with a timetable that would set a
House vote on whether to open an impeachment inquiry for early
October. Impeachment hearings would then be put off until after the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists said the delay would allow their party to
move cautiously before the election _ neither turning off their own
conservative base by being too easy on the president nor appearing
to be too harsh. Because of Clinton's troubles, Republicans are now
expecting to increase their majorities in both the House and the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican House member who is closely monitoring the
elections said that the volatility of the public mood argued for
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is in unchartered waters waiting for the fog to lift
and figure out where they are,'' he said, speaking on condition
that he not be identified. ``No one is willing to make a deal until
they know where they stand. The polls are meaningless. The
president's support is a fraction of an inch deep. Every number
besides his favorable rating is ominous for Democrats. And
Republicans know that misplaying their hand is dangerous too.
Everyone's in a state of suspended animation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
