<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neagle content for now to sit, rest ailing shoulder
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ If the parade seems to be passing Denny Neagle by, he'll
just catch up later. His left shoulder is still causing some
discomfort, and given how the rotation has managed, with him making
only two September starts, the left-hander welcomes the extended
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle will work in relief during one of the weekend games with
the New York Mets, at his discretion, in his last tune-up before
the playoffs. He is not 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is, where I got the (cortisone) injection
(Sept. 8), that feels fine,'' he said. ``But now I'm hurting in the
back (of the shoulder) again. It just keeps spreading back and
forth. That's the thing about bursitis, though. The bursa sac
covers that whole area, so it moves around a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle has pitched just 12 innings this month _ a Sept .1
victory over Houston and Thursday's victory over Arizona that gave
the club five 15-game winners. Although he was originally scheduled
to make a final start against the Marlins tonight, manager Bobby
Cox scrambled the rotation for the final week, bringing Kevin
Millwood back from the bullpen to work Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That has allowed Neagle's shoulder to dictate when he works
next. With him relegated to the bullpen for the first round of the
playoffs, the Braves should not have to push to get him to the
mound until the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd be grinding hard (in the last start), trying to get
that 15th win, and that probably put a little more stress on it,''
Neagle said. ``It's not something I'm real concerned about, and
with the way it's all set up now, it feels like a weight's been
taken off my shoulders, so to speak. Now I can pick when I'm going
to throw here in the last few games.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the middle
</P>
<P>
   With seven starts between them in the first 20 games of
September, second baseman Keith Lockhart (strained right hamstring)
and shortstop Walt Weiss (strained left quadriceps) are taking
their own routes to the playoffs. Both will be tested this weekend
to determine if they should be included on the postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart has stepped up his physical regimen to see just what
his hamstring will allow him to do. Beyond light jogging and taking
infield practice, he has done little in the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to take it easy,'' he said. ``If I go and do it
again, it's not like, well, you're 60 percent; it's like, your
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, because he has aggravated his quad injury as many as 10
times this year, does not need to experiment with his mobility. He
is just reserving himself for October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect it to be perfect,'' said Weiss, who first
developed the problem in late May. ``In the postseason, you just go
as hard as you can for as long as you can, and you hope it holds
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   With six games to play, the Marlins have drawn 733,090 fewer
fans at Pro Player Stadium this season, a drop-off of 30 percent. .
. . There have been 11 20-win seasons recorded in the National
League the past eight years. Seven of those belong to Atlanta
Braves, and four of those seven belong to Tom Glavine. . . .
Braves' first baseman Greg Colbrunn entered the Florida series with
seven hits, including two doubles, in his last 14 at-bats and four
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
