<P>
   _ Notes: Smoltz will start, but he won't last much beyond the
third or fourth inning. With the playoffs only six or seven days
off _ depending on site and opponent _ Smoltz is interested only in
a tune-up. Then, he'll let his right elbow rest until the
postseason. He's got hardly anything left to prove, anyway, after
posting an 11-1 record in the second half with a 2.41 ERA. He might
have added another victory if not for his dubious ejection in
Cincinnati on July 29 in a game the Braves eventually won 11-5. He
has faced the Marlins twice this year and beaten them both times,
allowing four runs in 13 innings with 16 strikeouts. Ojala presents
an old challenge for the Braves _ a rookie left-hander. But they
treated him rudely in his first and only start against Atlanta on
Sept. 11 at Turner Field. Ojala gave up five earned runs in four
innings. Gerald Williams' third-inning grand slam was the big blow
in an 8-2 Atlanta victory. Ojala is 1-6 as a starter but deserves
better. He has allowed two or fewer runs in six of his 11 starts,
but the Marlins have scored three or fewer in six of his starts.
</P>
