<SLUG> BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-ROOTS-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHERS MOVE FORWARD INTO THE PAST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   Lyle rexer writes regularly on art and photography for Review
magazine.  
 (af)  
 By LYLE REXER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The photographer Jerry Spagnoli remembers the first
daguerreotype he bought, in a flea market. The image of two girls
seemed to hover over the tarnished silver plate, and the play of
surfaces seemed to capture the vitality of the living subject.
</P>
<P>
   An antiquated process revealed expressive possibilities he
hadn't imagined. He has spent two decades since then exploring
them.
</P>
<P>
   When Jayne Hinds Bidaut saw her first tintype, she was so struck
by its rich creamy tone that she could scarcely believe this
photographic process had been abandoned. She set out to revive it.
For the photographer Dan Estabrook, old albumen prints and tintypes
inspired a fantasy. He imagines planting the ones he makes in flea
markets and antique shops, to be discovered as ``originals'' from a
bygone time that never existed.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of a filmless, digital revolution, photography is
moving forward into its past. Photographers are polishing
daguerreotype plates, coating paper with egg whites, transforming
entire trailers into pinhole cameras and mixing emulsions from
19th-century recipes in order to coax new expressive effects from
old photographic techniques.
</P>
<P>
   So diverse are the artists returning to photography's roots that
the movement is more like a groundswell.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Fuss has rediscovered the pinhole camera and the photogram,
the cameraless photograph made famous by Man Ray. John Dugdale has
given up standard photography to make only blue-toned prints called
cyanotypes, from the simplest developing process. Stephen Sack has
scoured the Bibliotheque Nationale in Paris for stereopticon
images, an early version of 3-D, which he joins together and
rephotographs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best known antiquarian explorers is Joel Peter
Witkin, whose spotty silver prints of staged tableaux, often
involving fantastically masked figures, link photography and the
discovery of the unconscious in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the Smithsonian Institution, the Oakland Museum and
most recently the J. Paul Getty Museum have all mounted major
exhibitions of daguerreotypes, images captured directly on a
silver-surfaced plate. The Getty exhibition ``The Silver Canvas''
demonstrated the range of this early art and hinted at why it is
making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back at these pioneers, today's artists see a way to
restore expression and emotion to an art beguiled by technology,''
says Weston Naef, curator of photography at the Getty. Sarah
Morthland, whose gallery exhibition ``Inventors and Alchemists'' in
May brought together the work of several contemporary artists
exploring old processes, adds: ``They share an attachment to the
photograph as a made thing, rather than as pure image or social
document. They want to hold fast to the art of photography.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the artists have highly personal reasons for choosing
particular processes. When Dugdale, a successful fashion
photographer, lost most of his sight as a result of AIDS, a
large-format camera was the only kind he could manipulate.
</P>
<P>
   To print, he chose the most direct process available: paper
coated with a solution of iron that could be exposed in sunlight
and washed with tap water. The result is a blue-tinted image called
a cyanotype. Fortuitous though it might be, the overall hue lends a
profoundly elegiac quality to his still lifes and portraits of
friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bidaut, whose exhibition opens on Oct. 17th at the
Ricco-Maresca Gallery in Manhattan and may be the first devoted to
contemporary tintypes, had been searching for a way to photograph
insects from her entomological collection. The tintype, an image
captured on a thin, coated plate of iron (there is no tin in it),
provided the detail and dimensionality she wanted. The
image-containing emulsion can often create a raised surface on the
plate. Paper prints simply seemed too flat to her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The past provides an abundance of possibilities for artists in
search of inspiration, if they are willing to get their hands
dirty. Most of the obsolete processes were invented in the early
decades of photography, a hectically experimental period.
</P>
<P>
   The first photogram was probably made around 1802. Louis Jacques
Mande Daguerre made the first daguerreotype around 1835. Cyanotypes
appeared in 1842, the tintype in 1854. Early photographic paper was
made simply by soaking a sheet of paper in salt water and brushing
it with silver nitrate.
</P>
<P>
   When it was discovered that a mix of egg white would make the
paper more sensitive, albumen prints became state of the art. They
held that position for 40 years, until 1895, when gelatin provided
a more stable effect. Methods of taking and printing photographs
multiplied so rapidly that the United States Patent Office threw up
its hands in despair at the applications.
</P>
<P>
   France Scully Osterman and Mark Osterman, present day disciples
of the old methods, have even succeeded in printing photos on
transparent sheets of mica. The Ostermans are to old photography
what Clem Labine and the Old House Journal were to historic
preservation: repositories of arcane knowledge and keepers of the
flame. Through lectures, workshops and their Collodion Journal
(collodion is the material originally used to coat glass-plate
negatives), they have helped hundreds of amateurs and artists
decipher the chemical recipes of old manuals and appreciate the
inventiveness of photographic pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The Ostermans, like Kenneth Nelson of Eastman Kodak, may have
succeeded too well. It is now common to see noncombatants lugging
glass-plate cameras across the fields of Civil War reenactments.
Some are selling their images as originals to rival Mathew Brady's.
</P>
<P>
   It seems a short step to the world of artists like David
McDermott and Peter McGough, who have not only adopted 19th-century
photographic methods, but dress and life style as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The old techniques are heavily hands-on and idiosyncratic. That
is the source of their appeal. It is also the prime reason for
their eclipse. Most became obsolete in a few decades, replaced by
others that were simpler, cheaper and faster and produced more
consistent results. Only the tintype lasted as a curiosity into the
20th century. It was cheaper and easier to view than a
daguerreotype and provided the instant gratification of a Polaroid.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
