<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BAUMAN-COX     09-22 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BAUMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1954: The year Joe Bauman upstaged the aliens (he hit 72)
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSWELL, N.M. _ As he watches Mark McGwire or Sammy Sosa hit
another home run on television, a smile usually appears on Joe
Bauman's wrinkled face, and his mind drifts back 44 years to when
he was briefly the talk of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only the minor leagues,'' says Bauman, organized
baseball's single-season home-run king. ``But it's still something
no one else has done.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa caught and passed Babe Ruth, then Roger Maris.
But the record Bauman set on the windblown fields of the Class C
Longhorn League in 1954 appears unreachable.
</P>
<P>
   Bauman smashed 72 home runs for the Roswell Rockets in just 138
games. He also batted .400, drove in 224 runs, scored 188 and
walked 150 times.
</P>
<P>
   Life magazine and Sports Illustrated photographers recorded the
historic moment when he hit three homers in a season-ending
doubleheader, breaking the minor-league record of 69. But the most
prolific season in minor-league history didn't earn Bauman a trip
to the majors. The 6-foot-5, 245-pound first baseman was 32 and
already had given up hope of making the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, he was back at work at the Texaco service
station he had bought with his baseball savings. The San Francisco
Seals of the Pacific Coast League called, but he couldn't afford to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Soon his record was forgotten, even in Roswell _ the southeast
New Mexico town of 50,000 that has been the Oklahoma native's home
since. An alleged UFO sighting in 1947 was what everyone kept
talking about, not home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``About everyone who saw me play has either moved out of town or
is dead,'' says Bauman, 76. ``A lot of people probably thought I
died, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came McGwire's and Sosa's home-run assault. Now everyone
seems to want to talk to the man who hit 72. The total is as hard
to believe as little men from outer space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm getting more attention now than in 1954,'' Bauman
says. ``Everytime someone hits a home run, another reporter
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries to act like he doesn't want to keep talking about the
old times,'' says Bauman's wife of 56 years, Dorothy. ``But I think
he is kinda enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, there were 36 minor leagues, and the Longhorn League,
which had teams in Texas and New Mexico, was just one rung up from
the bottom among the classifications. Only one of the eight teams
was affiliated with a major-league club and aging minor-leaguers
like Bauman played side by side with raw rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitching wasn't all that great, I'll admit that,'' Bauman
recalls. ``And the ball traveled pretty good in the high altitude.
It was definitely a hitter's league, but the wind usually blew to
left field, not right, which would have helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman's season, however, was no fluke. He hit 50 homers for
nearby Artesia in 1952 and 53 the next year. Then he moved to
Roswell for the 1954 season, lured by a $1,000 bonus that he used
to help buy the service station and a promise of $600 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Bauman started hot and never cooled off. The left-handed hitter
put drive after drive over Fair Park Stadium's 10-foot-high wooden
fence, 329 feet from home plate down the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fence was a holding pen for rodeo bulls, and beyond
that the Eastern New Mexico State Fair rodeo arena. One night,
Bauman hit a shot that cleared the fence, the holding pen and
finally landed in the rodeo arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some spectators told me that,'' Bauman says. ``I couldn't see
it after it went over the fence where they kept the bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   After every trip around the bases at Fair Park, Bauman also got
to make the trip along the grandstand fence. As was the custom in
west Texas and New Mexico, fans celebrated homers by slipping
dollar bils through the holes in the chicken wire for the happy
hitter to collect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to look like Bermuda grass sticking throught the
fence,'' says Bauman, who hit 44 homers at home in 1954 and also
got a free ham for each. ``I don't think I ever got less than $40,
and sometimes a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman would hit a league-record four homers against Sweetwater
on Aug. 31 to give him 68, then he tied the minor-league record on
Sept. 2 with a homer against Midland.
</P>
<P>
   Big Spring had the smallest park in the league, but Bauman went
without a homer there the next two games. Photographers had to
shoot from as close as possible to the batter's box in those days,
and flash bulbs went off every time Bauman swung, often blinding
the hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Only one day was left and the Rockets had a twilight
doubleheader Sept. 5 at Artesia, 43 miles south of Roswell. Many
fans missed the record-breaker, because they were either stuck in
traffic or in line to buy tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Moved to leadoff to get more at-bats, Bauman fouled off three
1-2 pitches from Cuban righthander Jose Gallardo. Then he swung his
35-inch, 34-ounce Louisville Slugger and hit a fastball over the
rightfield fence, 360 feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relief more than anything else,'' Bauman says. ``I
know it wasn't anything like Maris or McGwire must have felt, but
the pressure started to get to me. I wanted it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   After No. 70, Bauman didn't have enough hands or time to grab
all the money stuck through the screen by the crowd of 2,600.
Roswell and Artesia fans all wanted to reward the slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates started to help me collect, then the Artesia
players joined in,'' says Bauman, a big grin engulfing his face at
the recollection. ``We still had a doubleheader to play, and the
umpires wanted to get the game moving. It must have taken us at
least 10 or 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman says he can't remember exactly how much cash was
collected, but he thinks it was about $900. With the loot safely
stored in a large paper sack, Bauman hit two more homers in the
doubleheader nightcap, giving him 10 homers in the season's last
nine games and 72 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulatory telegrams arrived from all over the country,
including one from Ernie Johnson, then a pitcher with the Milwaukee
Braves. Johson had been a teammate at Hartford in 1948, Bauman's
only year in the Braves' farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was a gentle giant, a great guy who could hit a ball a
long way,'' Johnson says. ``But there were a lot of minor-leaguers
in those days and not many spots in the majors. A lot of good
players never really got a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Braves had purchased Bauman's contract from Little
Rock of the Southern Association for $10,000 before the 1948
season. But when he failed to make the AAA team in Milwaukee and
hit only 10 homers in part-time duty at Class A Hartford, the
Braves tried to cut his salary from $600 a month to $400 in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I could make that much selling 24-inch black shoe
strings on a street corner back home in Oklahoma City,'' says
Bauman, who refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
   After the season started, the Braves came back with an offer to
play for the Class AA Atlanta Crackers. But by then Bauman had
signed to play semi-pro ball with a team in Elk City, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd given Elk City my word that I'd play there all season and
wasn't about to go back on my word,'' Bauman says. ``I knew it
would cost me any chance to make the majors, but it was a matter of
principle. Baseball players weren't treated any better than mules
in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman, who had earlier lost four minor-league seasons while he
served in the Navy during World War II, didn't return to the minors
until 1952. He retired because of a bad ankle midway in the 1956
season at age 34 with 337 minor-league homers and a .337 career
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really wanted to retire after 1954,'' Bauman says. ``What
was I going to do for an encore? Hit 73 homers?''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman sold his Texaco station in 1967, then worked for a beer
distributor until retiring. The exterior of the neat, gray bungalow
on West Deming Street he and his wife have lived in for more than
20 years was used when ``Unsolved Mysteries'' filmed an episode
about the Roswell UFO incident.
</P>
<P>
   Roswell hasn't had minor-league baseball since 1959, and the
grandstand at Fair Park Stadium was torn down years ago. Bauman _
who saw his only major-league game in person 50 years ago _ spends
most evenings in his favorite chair in the living room watching
baseball on cable TV. Thanks to McGwire and Sosa, he occasionally
hears his name mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is really jazzed up,'' Bauman says. ``But McGwire and
Sosa would hit them out anyway. They've been great for baseball.
After the (1994) strike, the game was about dead. Now, everyone is
excited about baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of them might finish with 68 homers. I thought 72
was out of reach. But if one of them does it sometime, I'm all for
it. I've never thought what I did should be lumped in with the
major-leaguers anyway. I've always just considered it a
minor-league record. And I don't think it will ever be broken.
That's enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
