</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White making big catches
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even among 100 or so teammates and a dozen coaches,
Georgia Tech's leading receiver Dez White was a lonely young man
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   From the first day of freshman practice, college football was a
struggle, as you'd expect for a receiver who was having a hard time
catching the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking (that) if every practice is like this, I'm
not going to make it,'' White said about his first practice in a
Tech uniform.
</P>
<P>
   What most people didn't know outside the program was that White
never really played receiver in high school at the Bolles School in
Jacksonville. He was a running back whom the coaches sent deep from
time to time because he has such great speed. White was more
comfortable with a ball at his feet than in his hands. His favorite
sport growing up was soccer.
</P>
<P>
   What some of the people inside the Tech program didn't know was
that several days before he got to campus, he had injured his thumb
playing catch with his uncle Adrian Smith, a former New York Giant.
Every time he caught a pass, it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to where I wasn't using my thumb and started dropping
everything,'' White said. ``From then on, my confidence shot down.
The frustrating thing was knowing I could catch the ball and not
being able to.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of his own frustration was that of offensive coordinator
Ralph Friedgen, not known for holding back the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled with it a lot, from a respect standpoint,'' White
said. ``I felt sometimes coach Friedgen was unfair. But now I
realize all the things I did last year have helped me get to this
point. It was adjusting from a high-school coach to a college
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, White was putting his hands up earlier in his
route and concentrating harder on the ball, but nothing seemed to
work.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken sophomore kept his troubles mostly to himself.
But hedid find a source of strength in Marcus Hinton of Athletes
in Action, a campus Christian organization. Several times a week,
Hinton, who played at McEachern High and Clemson, and White would
sit and chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of just keeping on, not giving up,'' White
said. ``I said to myself, `Relax and it'll come.' And it has.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first couple of practices this year , White felt
different, and he played that way. Just a couple practices in, he
made a tough catch up high over two defenders and got some
re-assurance from Friedgen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Great catch,' '' White said and laughed. ``He said,
`If you can make that catch, you should make all of them.' It
wasn't much of a compliment, but you can't expect (much more of
one) from him.''
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of Harvey Middleton and Derrick Steagall,
White was projected as a starter this season, but with injuries to
Mike Sheridan and Jon Muyres in the preseason he has had to be much
more. He has responded by leading Tech with nine catches for 171
yards.
</P>
<P>
   White caught his first touchdown pass, a 24-yarder against New
Mexico State. He made one of his finest catches in that game for a
47-yard gain to move the Tech offense from deep in its territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two catches he made,'' Friedgen said, ``were big time
catches, as good as you'll see in any league.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
