<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public wary of Falcons
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It isn't entirely true that the Falcons have been
ignored in the 16 years since Leeman Bennett was fired. There were
two outbreaks of Falcon Fever, one in 1986, another in 1990. Both
went into immediate remission, and the resulting skepticism remains
the team's single biggest hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   You can offer only so many false clues before the public doubts
every move you make. In 1986, the Falcons tantalized their audience
with a 4-0 start, the linchpin of which was a rousing victory in
Dallas. (How rousing? People actually wrote songs about it.) By
Week 5, the Falcons were selling out Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium,
something they had failed to do in Dan Henning's three previous
seasons. Trouble was, the team still wasn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   The 1986 Falcons won only three more games. Quarterback David
Archer got hurt. Henning's one-back offense was revealed as a
one-trick pony. The Cowboys, foils in what seemed a watershed game,
wound up under .500 for the first time in two decades. In Week 14,
the Falcons played before only 30,397 and managed to lose to 0-13
Indianapolis on a blocked punt. For a franchise that has had few
highs, that was the abject low.
</P>
<P>
   Henning got fired, deservedly. The Falcons could find no one to
take the job _ Dick Vermeil and Terry Donahue said no _ and wound
up promoting Marion Campbell, the defensive coordinator who already
had failed once as a head coach here. When inevitably he failed
again, the Falcons had the chance to start anew. Instead they
dipped again into their past and hired Jerry Glanville.
</P>
<P>
   Glanville did one good thing: He whipped up interest. The
Falcons staged an infamous brawl against Buddy Ryan's Eagles in a
preseason scrimmage, and all of a sudden the Falcons were a hot
ticket again. But familiarity bred contempt. Even though Glanville
took his team to the playoffs in 1991, his methods had begun to
grate. He was gone two years later, replaced by his offensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Married to the run-and-shoot, June Jones had no chance. He
lasted three years. In 1997, the Falcons turned themselves over to
Dan Reeves, an outsider who knows his business. What should have
produced a wave of goodwill was met with raging indifference. Too
many bad moves had left the Falcons overdrawn at the bank of public
forgiveness. Almost on cue, Reeves has built a solid team that
remains distrusted in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   You hear it said that the Falcons can't be taken seriously
unless they win Sunday in San Francisco. That is wrong. They should
be taken seriously now. This is a serious team staffed by serious
players and overseen by serious coaches. Is it a Super Bowl
champion? No. Is it of playoff caliber? Maybe not yet. But it's
getting there.
</P>
<P>
   To lose in San Fran would invalidate nothing. This is not 1986
all over, a quick start built on a mirage. This is not 1990, when
unsoundness was apparent amid the tumult. This is a team that
deserves the benefit of the doubt. Alas, doubt seems overpowering.
The populace clings to its determination not to be fooled again,
even when presented with a team that is, at long last, not fooling
around.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
