<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS23-COX     09-22 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' top run defense faces a test
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Atlanta Falcons defensive tackle Travis Hall flew
past Carolina right guard Corbin Lacina in the second quarter of
the season opener and dropped Panthers running back Fred Lane for a
6-yard loss, Falcons defensive coach Bill Kollar got excited.
</P>
<P>
   Kollar's had a lot to get excited about lately.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has the NFL's No. 1-ranked run defense, allowing just
58.5 yards per game, and the unit is allowing an NFL-low 2.6 yards
per carry. The longest gain has been 9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday at San Francisco, Atlanta (2-0) will place its defense
against a running game different from what it has seen. San
Francisco's Garrison Hearst is more likely to bounce outside and
has more speed than the Panthers' Lane or the Philadelphia Eagles'
Duce Staley. The 49ers (2-0) lead the NFL with 208.5 rushing yards
per game behind Hearst, who is averaging 167.5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   So when No. 1 faces No. 1, something has to give.
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons for the Falcons' success. The Panthers are
No. 24 and Philadelphia is No. 19 in the NFL in rushing. But that
shouldn't take away from the fact that Falcons ends Chuck Smith and
Lester Archambeau, tackles Hall and Shane Dronett, and linebackers
Cornelius Bennett, Jessie Tuggle, Henri Crockett and Craig Sauer
have been very stingy against the run.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons use a scheme called ``gap control.'' The concept
calls for players to drop anchor or rush hard in a specific area
and not give that area up until the play clearly is going away from
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to end up jinxing yourself, but everybody has been
playing better gap control,'' Kollar said. ``Everybody has a better
feel for where they're supposed to be. We want to stop the run and
force the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   They have been good at that lately. The Falcons gave up 118.1
rushing yards per game the first 10 games last season. They've
given up 76 yards rushing per game in eight games since, holding
opposing running backs below 100 yards 10 times in a row. The
Falcons have won eight of those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times in gap defense, you'll see a guy free-lance and
jump into another gap,'' Smith said. ``But we've got respect for
where one another is going to be, and we stay put.''
</P>
<P>
   Attitude means a lot to the Falcons' undersized line. Hall is
the biggest of the Falcons defenders at 6 feet 5, 300 pounds. Smith
(6-2, 265) and Archambeau (6-4, 275) are not as big as some of
their peers, and Dronett (6-6, 295) is not huge. But Archambeau
already has 15 tackles and is tied with middle linebacker Tuggle
for second on the team behind Bennett's 18.
</P>
<P>
   And Smith is plain surly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a mentality; you have to want to play the
run,'' he said. ``A lot of guys just don't want to play the run.
Nobody wants to do the dirty work. You got to attack, run to the
ball. If you can't stop the run, your chances aren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: On Tuesday, the Falcons reached an injury settlement with
former University of Georgia rookie linebacker Brandon Tolbert, a
member of the practice squad, and waived him. Tolbert, bothered by
a hamstring injury, was a seventh-round draft choice by
Jacksonville. The Falcons probably will sign another linebacker to
the practice squad today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
