<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-ROOTS-2ND     09-22 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-ROOTS-2NDTAKE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: a Polaroid.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's artists quickly discover that to exploit the past is to
court the very uncertainty early innovators sought to banish.
</P>
<P>
   When Spagnoli clicks the shutter of a daguerreotype portrait
(demand for them is growing), he can never predict the end result.
The sitter has to hold still for a long exposure, and he uses a
special brace for the purpose. If the plate and emulsion are not
prepared exactly or the mercury-vapor fixing process is badly
timed, a pale-faced subject can appear to have fallen asleep under
a sunlamp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such unpredictability attracted Estabrook to old processes. His
work embraces accident and employs decay in order to dramatize the
distance between spectator and image. In his view, time leaches
meaning from every photograph, renders it a lost object, enabling
us to project onto it our own sentiments and associations.
</P>
<P>
   The stains and imperfections of prints made from gum bichromate
or albumen coatings would have been cropped out by a 19th-century
photographer. Estabrook uses them to emphasize the inevitability of
decay and to heighten the sense of nostalgia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most frequent criticism of old-process photographic art is
that its techniques can be applied to any subject with equally
startling results. Yet the best of these artists choose their
subjects with extreme care. Sack, who appropriates rather than
duplicates an old process, has examined thousands of pairs of
stereopticon images to find a handful that capture for him the way
we imagine and remember places.
</P>
<P>
   Estabrook's 1997 ``Floating Cloth'' appears at first glance to
be an antique image of a pinned drapery, but a closer look reveals
the wires that suspend the cloth, evoking a magician's act and
suggesting photography's origins in a dubious illusionism. Image
and process inform each other. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the early photographers, unpredictability wasn't creative,
it was unprofitable. Given the chemicals involved, it could also be
dangerous. Spagnoli at first hesitated to make daguerreotypes
because one of the main developing agents is deadly mercury vapor.
He began only after he learned that the image could be safely
``fixed'' in a sealed container.
</P>
<P>
   A form of cyanide is another common element in old processes,
and before the danger it posed was fully recognized, many
practitioners would chew on crystals of the stuff in the course of
their work.
</P>
<P>
   The Collodion Journal regularly runs articles on photographic
poisons and their antidotes, complete with excerpts from
19th-century accounts of suicides and horrendous accidental deaths.
Silver burns were so common that collodion photography was called
``the black art.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even such chemical volatility offers the artist a subject.
Spagnoli's 1995 ``Machine for Destroying Daguerreotypes'' is a box
with a peephole containing a cherry blossom and a daguerreotype. As
the flower decays, it gives off gasses that react with the metal
plate to efface the image. It suggests that in art as in life,
beauty and permanence are incompatible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The preoccupation with contingency offers a clue to the deeper
motivations of many of the antiquarian avant-gardists. The widely
variable outcome of old techniques virtually guarantees that each
production is one of a kind and bears, on some level, the indelible
mark of the artist's encounter with a particular set of
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dugdale's recording his world even after he can no longer
see it, these artists seek to present evidence for the individual
in a universe of digital simulacra.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, old methods offer the promise of recovering an
intimacy to photographic communication that mass media have all but
overwhelmed. Individual photographs still mean a lot to people.
Even when these artists play on the desire for meaning, they can't
help honoring it.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Ms. Biduat's tintypes portray classically posed and
draped nudes. She mounts them in antique cases, as they would have
been a century ago. The cases transform them from impersonal works
of art into intimate keepsakes. A few years ago, hunting for these
cases, she discovered one that had been opened so often that it was
marked by fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked myself what picture could have drawn the owner back to
it again and again,'' she says. ``That's the kind of image I want
to make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
