<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-MUSEUM-NYT     09-22 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSEUM IN MEXICO SUDDENLY SHUTS DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With no fanfare and surprisingly little mourning,
a museum that critics had extolled as Mexico's finest forum for
modern art was closed on Sunday, a victim of cost slashing at the
leading television network, Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, the Cultural Center for Contemporary Art, shut its
doors at the spartan but spacious rust-colored building where it
had offered 172 exhibitions over 12 years, including authoritative
retrospectives of Mexican artists like painter Maria Izquierdo and
photographers Manuel Alvarez Bravo and his first wife, Lola.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was created from scratch out of a collaboration
between Emilio Azcarraga Milmo, the billionaire owner of Televisa,
who died last year; his friend Robert Littman, a New Yorker who
directed the museum from its founding, and Paula Cussi, a Mexican
actress whose love affair and eventual marriage to Azcarraga lasted
2{ decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Cultural Center became a respectable stop on the
international circuit, after shows like an affectionate 1987 homage
to Leo Castelli, the New York art impresario, and a 1990 display of
Salvador Dali works from the Reina Sofia National Art Museum in
Madrid. Thriving on ample budgets from Televisa, the museum
accumulated a distinctive collection of works by young artists from
Mexico, the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Although Televisa officials said the center would continue to
operate as a museum-without-walls by lending its collection for
shows in other spaces, considerable confusion seems to surround its
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are completely unclarified to me,'' Littman said. He
said he would pack up the center's collection to store it in a
warehouse at a Televisa complex in a suburb above the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa officials have indicated that the building that housed
the museum, originally a press center for the 1984 World Cup soccer
championships, would be sold or rented for commercial purposes yet
to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   For now, only 15 works from the permanent collection, by
American artists including Edward Ruscha and Brice Marden, will be
hung in the residence of U.S. Ambassador Jeffrey Davidow. The home
is not regularly open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were few protests from Mexican artists, leaders
of Mexico's art world were appalled by Televisa's decision to close
the Cultural Center and dismiss its 120-member staff to save the
$12 million devoted to its annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a divorce where only one party makes the
decision,'' said Raquel Tibol, the longtime art critic for the
weekly magazine Proceso. ``It is an action by a private company
that fails to respect the tacit cultural agreement between a museum
and its public.''
</P>
<P>
   But Televisa officials said they could no longer afford the
Cultural Center under the austerity regimen the company adopted
after the death of Azcarraga, a strong-willed magnate known as the
Tiger, who built his family's business into one of the largest
media empires in the world. A son, Emilio Azcarraga Jean, who is
30, took over the conglomerate after his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cussi had caught the elder Azcarraga's eye in the early days
of her career at Televisa when she was reading horoscopes on the
air. Although she had no expertise in modern art or experience as a
museum curator, he made her chairwoman of the center and appointed
Littman to direct it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paula is a very smart lady and a very quick study,'' Littman
said. ``To stay with Emilio for 25 years, you have to know about
politics, art, entertainment, economics. She was very conversant,
and she spent a lot of time researching.''
</P>
<P>
   As the museum's reputation grew, Azcarraga's support became more
enthusiastic. For most of his lifetime Televisa had a monopoly
hammerlock on television in Mexico, and he was frequently
criticized for producing crass programming to appeal to the lowest
common denominator among Mexican viewers. The Cultural Center
allowed him to show that he could make a sophisticated contribution
to Mexican culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really enjoyed coming to the openings,'' Littman recalled.
``It was an important part of his life. Emilio had many
opportunities to kiss us goodbye, but he never did.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's popularity in Mexico was established in 1988 with a
show that brought together images of the Virgin of Guadalupe,
Mexico's patroness saint. In 1990 Littman organized an exhibition
by Robert Motherwell and other artists from around the world to
illustrate essays of art criticism by Octavio Paz, the Mexican
poet.
</P>
<P>
   But relations between Ms. Cussi and the Azcarraga family cooled
after the death of the elder Azcarraga, from whom she was separated
in 1994. In August 1997 she severed her all her ties to Televisa
when she sold the company shares that he had left her in his will,
for a figure estimated in Mexican press reports at $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Initially the younger Azcarraga made a public pledge in front of
all of Televisa's employees to keep the museum open. But financial
pragmatism, in the wake of a punishing recession in 1995,
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston Melo, a Televisa vice president, said the company was not
planning to sell off the permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling has never been the point,'' Melo said. He said
Televisa was negotiating with public universities and government
museums for shows of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's demise provoked little outcry among Mexican
artists, most of whom remain suspicious of Televisa. But its
closing leaves the cultivation of modern art in Mexico almost
entirely with government museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provided an independent focus on the visual arts,'' Littman
said. ``We didn't have to do a show because the president of Mexico
signed a peace treaty with Lower Slobovia.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tibol, the art critic, said: ``There is absolutely no one
left who can fill the void. No one even aspires to doing it. There
is a spiritual reluctance to barge into the abandoned house that
someone else built.''
</P>
</TEXT>
