<SLUG> BC-MESQUITE-TREES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUNDANT NATIVE MESQUITE IS A BLESSING, OR A CURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things have stirred rural Texans as much as the
centuries-old battle over the pesky mesquite.
</P>
<P>
   Thorny mesquite has been aggressively poisoned and uprooted by
the state's ranchers, who see it as a pasture-ruining water hog.
</P>
<P>
   But the native tree is a blessing to barbecue chefs, furniture
makers and others who appreciate the flavor that its smoke imparts
or who behold strength and beauty in its dark, rich hues.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rob Junell of San Angelo in West Texas, who says the
scrubby trees are about as endearing as ``fire ants with leaves,''
wants to spend millions to destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a group of Texas researchers, artisans and
entrepreneurs called Los Amigos del Mesquite are holding a contest
to find the state's tallest, straightest mesquite so they can use
its seed pods to grow many more.
</P>
<P>
   Junell is seeking $17 million _ $12 million from the state and
$5 million from landowners _ to remove 130 million mesquites and
100 million juniper ash trees in the 950,000-acre North Concho
watershed near his home city.
</P>
<P>
   The trees ``serve as straws sucking water'' from the watershed,
according to an executive summary of a study by the Texas A&AMP;M
Research and Extension Center, the Texas State Soil and Water
Conservation Board and the Upper Colorado River Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing the trees would increase the North Concho River's
watershed stream flow fivefold, recharge underground aquifers and
make water available to West Texans at a fraction of the current
cost, the $86,000 study asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to pull up, poison and chop down the much-maligned
member of the pea family, whose genealogy dates back 50 million
years, are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Antilley has been battling mesquite on his ranch near the
West Texas town of Winters for more than 50 years. Despite a stroke
and two bouts of surgery, he still goes out on weekends to kill
them, his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   But the anti-mesquite forces enjoy a mixed record at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, we've had a USDA-sponsored mesquite eradication
program since the 1950s, when we had 40 million acres of
mesquite,'' said David Miller of Bastrop, whose family has ranched
in the area since the 1850s. ``After 45 years of eradicating
mesquite, we only have 55 million acres left.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fighting mesquite, Miller decided to promote it.
</P>
<P>
   His firm, Texas Woods, is one of a dozen in the state that mills
mesquite logs into flooring tiles for homes, hotels and office
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Four times more stable than oak and twice as hard, mesquite
tiles can be laid in such non-traditional, high-moisture areas as
bathrooms, saunas and boat decks, said Miller, a Baptist minister
and former contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers once urged chainsaw crews to clear mesquite for free,
saving them the expense of doing it themselves. But Miller suggests
that ranchers collect $10 to $15 per cord.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, he said, pay cutters $150 to $300 a cord for the thicker
logs; chip makers pay a fraction of that for the rest. Processed
mesquite floor tile retails for about $7 per square foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas mesquite industry grosses an estimated $25 million a
year, with the bulk in the smoking chip market. But the market for
flooring and furniture is growing, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mesquite is worth $40 per ton as barbecue wood and $2,000 per
ton as a finished floor product,'' said Peter Felker, 51, a plant
physiologist for 24 years at Texas A&AMP;M University-Kingsville.
</P>
<P>
   So what's holding back mesquite?
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everything about it is expensive,'' Miller said. ``It's
hard to harvest, there's a lot of faults (imperfections) in it,
getting a clear board is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Los Amigos researchers are trying to find taller,
straighter specimens among trees that generally are ground hugging
and gnarled, Felker said. Seed pods from the contest's winners, to
be announced Thursday in Corpus Christi, will be used to develop a
tree bred for lumber and furniture use.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said his own father-in-law laughs at the idea of paying
good money for mesquite.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, insisted Claude Watterson, 80, a fourth-generation South
Texas rancher who has struggled against mesquite encroachment for
seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's beautiful wood,'' Watterson said. ``I'd have some
mesquite flooring myself in my house if I could afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
