<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M MIGHT HAVE TO FORFEIT VICTORY, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M officials said yesterday that
they are conducting an investigation into the eligibility status of
fullback D'Andre Hardeman that could result in the Aggies
forfeiting a Sept. 12 victory against Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the issue, said a source with knowledge of the
inquiry, is whether Hardeman should have been declared academically
eligible under NCAA satisfactory-progress rules based on courses he
completed during summer school to regain his eligibility for this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hardeman played in the team's first two games,
questions about his eligibility arose Thursday, athletic director
Wally Groff said. A&AMP;M held Hardeman out of last week's game against
Southern Mississippi. He continues to practice with the team, but
team officials have suspended him until the matter is settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get all the facts, I really can't elaborate on
anything,'' Groff said. ``It could be a day. It could be a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility that No. 17 A&AMP;M might forfeit a 28-7
victory against Louisiana Tech in which Hardeman scored three
touchdowns, Groff said: ``I guess that's always a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M (2-1) plays host to North Texas (0-3) on Saturday, and
Hardeman will not participate in that game, A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum
said. With Hardeman sidelined, the Aggies' depth chart at fullback
shows freshman Ja'Mar Toombs as the starter backed by walk-on Will
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum and Groff acknowledged the possibility that Hardeman, a
senior from Houston, might have played his last game for A&AMP;M but
neither considers that a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman, who rushed for 105 yards and four touchdowns in the
team's first two games, declined to comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a forfeit, players said, would not distract them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already accepted it, whether it does or doesn't
happen,'' quarterback Branndon Stewart said. ``We can still win the
South Division. We can still win the Big 12. It wouldn't be the
forfeiture of a (conference) game.''
</P>
<P>
   But dropping from 2-1 to 1-2 could affect the Aggies in national
rankings and bowl bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought has occurred to me,'' Groff said. ``But I have not
asked about any of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWOOD-MARKETPLACE-     09-22 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWOOD-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: STARWOOD HAS LOST SOME WALL STREET LUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story is now on the business front page. It replaces
FORD-EQUITY-MARKETPLACE, which has been eliminated.) 
(lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the past few years, Barry Sternlicht, chairman and chief
executive of Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide Inc., has
dazzled analysts with his financial acumen, transforming what had
been a sleepy real-estate investment trust into the world's largest
hotel company.
</P>
<P>
   Sternlicht's popularity has waned a good bit on Wall Street
recently, because over the last year Starwood's shares, along with
those of other leisure-time companies, have fallen precipitously.
Yet Sternlicht, who paid $10.2 billion to buy ITT Corp. earlier
this year, has the knack of making into a good deal what
superficially looks bad for Starwood shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   To buy ITT and Westin Hotels LP _ two companies far bigger than
his own _ Sternlicht had to turn to a number of sources, some
exotic, for capital. The collateral he used in exchange for access
to that capital was Starwood stock, and his belief that its price
would continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   The reality that its stock has lost more than 50 percent of its
value in the last year was brought home Tuesday, when Starwood
announced it was unwinding a contract known on Wall Street as a
``forward equity swap arrangement'' with UBS AG, the Swiss bank.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the contract, which Starwood negotiated with
the bank last October and was due to expire on Oct. 10, the company
said it would buy back 2.18 million shares of stock it promised to
the bank for about $130 million, or about $59.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood agreed to buy the shares back by the expiration date at
the price the bank paid, plus interest, if the bank could not sell
them at a profit on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   The news did not help Starwood's stock much. The shares closed
at $32 each, down 12.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   When he borrowed the $130 million, Sternlicht was effectively
gambling that he would never have to issue so many shares to the
bank, because he thought that over the course of the next 12 months
the price of Starwood shares would continue to rise. Given his
reputation, that view was held by a number of analysts on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a number of real-estate investment trust stocks were so
hot last year that some REITs, including Patriot American and
Crescent Financial, struck similar deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were big for a while,'' said Jason Ader, an analyst at
Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. ``They offered REITs a way to access capital to
grow their business without much effort. They were almost making a
bet that the price of the stock would go up.''
</P>
<P>
   The UBS transaction was not the only equity swap deal Sternlicht
negotiated for Starwood. In February 1998, to help finance the ITT
acquisition, the company negotiated a similar deal with Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co., Lehman Brothers and NMS Services Inc. In return for
about $250 million, Starwood agreed to issue the investment banks
4.5 million shares. At the time of that deal, the stock was trading
at about $52 a share.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, Sternlicht said that Starwood was
``evaluating the benefits of an early termination'' of that
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Since no stock was ever issued, and he is repaying the lenders
in cash, Sternlicht can legitimately be seen as borrowing money
from several investment banks, and paying interest on the money.
But analysts said that once fees were included, the borrowing was
probably not very cost-effective, and that ratings agencies might
look twice at what was once promised equity, and is now debt.
</P>
<P>
   Sternlicht was clearly hoping that a rise in Starwood's stock
price would result in the real issuance of less stock than
originally promised.
</P>
<P>
   In part, fears about an impending economic downturn have helped
to hammer Starwood's stock.
</P>
<P>
   But the company remains very optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Starwood said it had received commitments to finance
the repurchase of up to $1 billion of its shares. (The $130 million
of UBS stock it bought back Tuesday is part of that program. An
early unwinding of the Merrill Lynch agreement will presumably be
part of the program too.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Starwood stock represents an extraordinary value,''
Sternlicht said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With assets like Sheraton Hotels, Caesars World and Westin,
people with deep pockets may well agree. A number of analysts said
Tuesday there were rumors that Starwood's sagging stock price might
make the company susceptible to an unsolicited takeover or
leveraged buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gallagher, a Starwood spokesman, declined to comment on the
rumors. But he noted that even at these depressed prices a takeover
would probably cost between $15 billion and $20 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
