</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAL NAMES NEW PRESIDENT IN WAKE OF UNIONS' ACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)  (jw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines' parent company, the UAL Corp., named James
Goodwin, a longtime senior executive, as its new president and
chief operating officer on Tuesday, only a few days after his
predecessor was forced out by the carrier's powerful unions.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment immediately vaulted Goodwin, 54, into the race
to succeed Gerald Greenwald, United's chairman and chief executive,
whose five-year employment contract expires next summer.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodwin's accession is hardly guaranteed. United's board of
directors, scheduled to meet Wednesday in Buenos Aires, has formed
a committee to search outside the company for a new chief executive
and it is not even clear that Greenwald himself would stay on if
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden change in executives presages a period of increasing
uncertainty at United, the country's largest airline as well as the
largest company in which employees hold majority ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 employee stock ownership plan, under which workers
received 55 percent of United's stock in exchange for wage
concessions, expires in 2000 and the company must decide whether to
renew it. The same year, United must also negotiate new contracts
with the International Association of Machinists and the Air Line
Pilots Association, its most influential unions.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the carrier's 19,000 reservation agents voted to
affiliate with the machinists in the most successful union
organizing drive in two decades. They, too, will need a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, who was not available for comment, was most recently
senior vice president in charge of North America, one of several
jobs he has held since joining as an accountant in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim has worked in virtually every aspect of our business and
we are indeed fortunate to have him as our president,'' Greenwald
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his long tenure at United, Goodwin is not well known in
the industry. An executive at the carrier who requested anonymity
described him as a strong operational manager who commands wide
respect within the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he speaks, everyone listens,'' the executive said. ``He
has sort of been the inside guy running the airline for many, many
years.''
</P>
<P>
   And Goodwin appears to have the respect of the unions. ``Our
relations with him in the past have been very positive,'' Kathy
White, a spokeswoman for the pilots' association, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeds John Edwardson, an industry outsider who joined
United in 1994 from the Ameritech Corp. The company had been
grooming him to succeed Greenwald. But Edwardson grew increasingly
unpopular with the pilots' and the machinists' unions, which each
have one seat on United's 12-person board.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned on Friday after it became clear that the two unions
would not support his elevation to chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was a breath of fresh air and he turned out to
be a real disappointment,'' said Karen Asuncion, a United ramp
worker and president of machinists local lodge 1487 near Chicago's
O'Hare Airport.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenwald has a reputation for fairness and is widely
liked by workers, she said, Edwardson was viewed as biased.
``Edwardson always backed management even if the facts leaned
heavily toward the employees,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers praised Goodwin's appointment precisely
because he is an insider.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear was that they would go out and hire some marquee name
who would make Wall Street feel all warm and fuzzy,'' said Mike
Boyd, an airline consultant based in Evergreen, Colo. ``Instead
they picked someone who knows the difference between the smell of
Chanel No. 5 and jet fuel. That is very good because there are a
whole slew of issues facing the airline and they need someone who
doesn't have to have a learning curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Julius Maldutis, a Wall Street airline industry analyst at CIBC
Oppenheimer in New York, agreed. ``He knows all the people and can
calm the ruffled feathers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Goodwin can impress the board that he has enough
breadth and charisma to succeed Greenwald is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Riding four years of record earnings since 1994, airline stocks
have been some of the best performers in recent years. But the
share price of United, which has the largest global network of any
domestic carrier, has lagged behind those of its major competitors.
Some analysts believe investors are wary of the stock because the
Chicago-based company is employee-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, United stock was not hurt by Edwardson's ouster. Rather it
has rallied in recent days, closing Tuesday at $70.25 a share, up
$2 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   United also said that Christopher Bowers, who has been running
its international operations, would succeed Goodwin as senior vice
president for North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
