<P>
   (NYT18) KRASNOYARSK, Russia -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- RUSSIA-LEBED-3,
9-22 -- Managers of the Pikra beer and soft drink plant in the
Russian region of Krasnoyarsk complain that price controls are too
strict. ``The government acts just like it did in the days of
Soviet power, when business people were considered bourgeois
speculators,'' says Yevgeniya Kuznetsova, the president of Pikra.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KRASNOYARSK, Russia -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- RUSSIA-LEBED-2,
9-22 -- In the Russian region of Krasnoyarsk, residents sell
home-grown fruits and vegetables on the street to earn extra
income. Russia's financial crisis has not only rocked Moscow's
political establishment. It has also stirred many of Russia's
far-flung regions to set their own economic course and establish
price controls. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- PEANUT-BAN-2, 9-22 --
Pupils in the lunchroom at Trevor Day School, a private school in
Manhattan. The school banned all peanut foods from the cafeteria
for the lower grades after a mother whose daughter is allergic
began a campaign. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- CLINTON-PANEL, 9-22 --
``It's laborious, but we made a lot of progress,'' Rep. Henry Hyde,
at microphone, says of work by Judiciary Committee Republicans. The
committee continued Tuesday to pick through the 16 remaining boxes
of evidence turned over by the independent counsel, flagging
portions that may be too private, too embarrassing or irrelevant
for public viewing. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- CLINTON-REACT, 9-22 --
George Mitchell, right, the former Senate Democratic leader who is
informally helping the president weather the scandal, thinks there
is growing support among Congressional Democrats for a censure.
``What he did - it was indefensible,'' Mitchell says. ``But I think
the country should be spared a long-drawn-out ordeal that I believe
in the end should not and cannot end in the president's being
removed from office.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- PEANUT-BAN, 9-22 -- The
Epipen is a syringe of epinephrine, used as an antidote to a severe
allergic reaction to peanuts or foods containing them, like peanut
butter. Prodded by worried parents and by the contentions of some
researchers that peanut allergies are on the rise, growing numbers
of public and private schools across the United States have banned
peanut butter from their cafeterias. (G. Paul Burnett/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KRASNOYARSK, Russia -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- RUSSIA-LEBED-1,
9-22 -- Angry at the soaring prices that have stunned Russians,
Alexander Lebed - a former general, presidential hopeful and the
new governor of the Krasnoyarsk region of Siberia - has not just
declared war on inflation, he has tried to make it illegal. ``We
may infringe on the rights of people but it is in their interest,''
Lebed says. ``The strict measures have played their role and soon
will be abolished.'' (James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- YALE-ARCHITECTURE-DEAN,
9-22 -- ``Unlike Louis XIV, Yale is not me'' says Robert Stern, the
new dean of the Yale School of Architecture. Stern, 59, a
traditionalist, has himself had a lifelong love affair with
molding, and there are complaints at Yale that installing the Ralph
Lauren of architecture - the view of his critics - sends the wrong
message about the direction of the school. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- WISCONSIN-POLITICS, 9-22
-- Sen. Russell Feingold, a democrat, has joined his Republican
opponent for the Senate, Rep. Mark Neumann, in curbing campaign
spending. The candidates have promised to limit donations from
political action groups to 10 percent of the total money raised and
are limiting overall spending to $1 per registered voter. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PITTSFIELD, Mass. -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- TEAM-LEAVES-BOS,
9-22 -- Dave Southard, a maintance worker at Wahconah Park, takes a
break before getting the stadium ready for high school football.
New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced last week that his city
had reached a deal in principle with the Mets to move their
single-A minor league club from Pittsfield's 79-year-old ball yard
to a new, $20 million stadium to be built on the site of an
abandoned amusement area on Coney Island. (Frank O'Brien/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- REID-MUSIC-2, 9-22 --
Vernon Reid practicing a dance score that he has been commissioned
to do, called ``Jazz Train,'' at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
Much of the work is pensive and pastoral, gliding between chamber
music and glimpses of the blues. Written for guitar, cello and
fluegelhorn, it's transparent but not simple. (Dith Pran/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- REID-MUSIC-1, 9-22 --
Vernon Reid ventures beyond a range of guitar playing and composing
and into photography and writing plays. Reid, 40, is one of New
York's best-connected musicians. He is doubtless the only player
versatile and personable enough to have made music with Keith
Richards, Public Enemy, Santana, Hootie and the Blowfish, Bill
Frisell and John Zorn. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MEXICO CITY -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- MEXICO-MUSEUM, 9-22 -- A
gallery at the Cultural Center for Contemporary Art, now closed.
The museum shut its doors at the Spartan but spacious rust-colored
building where it had offered 172 exhibitions over 12 years,
including authoritative retrospectives of Mexican artists like the
painter Maria Izquierdo and the photographers Manuel Alvarez Bravo
and his first wife, Lola. (Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- SQUASH-SOUP, 9-22 -- Squash
in all its variations is abundant right now at Greenmarkets. Just
how many squash soups can one city serve? Apparently the number is
infinite, as chefs, inspired no doubt by the presently ubiquitous
butternut squash, present variations on this homey classic. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- NY-WINE-TASTING-2, 9-22 --
No fancy clothes or party manners necessary: taking a break from
errands to sip wine is a growing trend in New York. The city does
not have the vineyards, but it sure has the wine stores, dozens
upon dozens of them, and shrewd customers, after making a few phone
calls and drawing up a little list, can map out a personal wine
trail. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- NY-WINE-TASTING-1, 9-22 --
The wine-tasting season is gathering steam after the summer recess.
Eve Strausman and Laurence Green sampling a bottle at Best Cellars,
which holds a free tasting every night. On Saturdays, the store
pairs wine with food. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1998 -- SPRING-FASHION-2, 9-21 --
Wrapping up a week of earlier showings for spring 1999, American
designers, from marquee names to unknowns, proved with confident
singular collections that they, too, can be trend-setters. From
left, Vivienne Tam's Havana embroidered top, chocolate jams (Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo); Han Feng's rose draped top and smocked
skirt; Mark Eisen's jersey sweater vest, sweater, sweatpant-style
trousers. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
