u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-UNREST-NYT &LR;      09-22 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING A SEXUAL SLUR, MALAYSIAN LEADER CALLS EX-DEPUTY
UNACCEPTABLE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
Tuesday that he once had high hopes that his former deputy, Anwar
Ibrahim, would be his successor. But he said that ``I cannot accept
a man who is a sodomist as leader of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first public statement about the arrest on Sunday of
Anwar, the prime minister said he had interviewed men and women who
said they had had illicit sex with Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 51, was the designated successor to Mahathir, 72, until
he was dismissed three weeks ago. He is now being held under
special government powers intended to prevent subversion.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, Mahathir acknowledged for the first time
that he felt that Anwar had begun to challenge his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to retire,'' he said at a news conference. ``I have
named him successor. What was the need for him to challenge me?''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between the two men grew over the last year as
Malaysia's economy spun into crisis. Mahathir lashed out at world
financial powers, but Anwar took a more orthodox approach in line
with the prescriptions of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   With Anwar's public stature growing, his supporters mounted a
tentative challenge to Mahathir at a congress in June of the
governing party, the United Malays National Organization.
</P>
<P>
   After his removal from office on Sept. 2, Anwar unleashed what
appeared to have been suppressed fury at his mentor, calling him
insane and senile and declaring he was not fit to lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   One response by the government was to arrest a number of Anwar's
allies, including two men who the police said confessed while in
custody to allowing Anwar to sodomize them.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before his arrest, Anwar denied the accusation and
said his friends must have been tortured into making their
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's arrest touched off riots in Kuala Lumpur on Monday,
which were quelled by riot policemen using tear gas and water
cannon. The police said Tuesday that 132 people had been detained.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir defended the police action, saying, ``When you are
dealing with an unruly mob, a certain amount of violence has to be
used.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister asserted that rumors about Anwar's sex life
had been around for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even for me, it took me years to believe the allegations,'' he
said. ``I dismissed it as a false accusation. Subsequently I was
told again about this last year and I said it is just out of sheer
jealousy for my man who is going to be the leader of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he said, he checked for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually interviewed the people he sodomized, the women that
he had sex with, the driver who brought the women to the place
where he met them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WISCONSIN-POLITICS-AR     09-22 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WISCONSIN-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WISCONSIN RACE FOR SENATE, TWO OPPONENTS PUT LIDS ON CAMPAIGN
COFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ With spending on most American political
campaigns seemingly headed toward Pluto, the contest for U.S.
senator in Wisconsin is remarkable for its restraint, including the
almost quaint notion that most of the financial donors in a
Wisconsin election should actually live in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   For Sen. Russell Feingold, a Democrat who sponsored the
unsuccessful recent measure to curb campaign spending, it was a
matter of practicing what he preaches, or risk being called a
hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   For his Republican opponent, Rep. Mark W. Neumann, it was a
chance to underscore his conservative view that Americans can do
the right thing without mandates from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a kind of do-it-yourself reform,'' said Larry
Mackinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, a nonpartisan research group that tracks campaign
spending. ``It's admirable. Can you imagine this happening in New
York?''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have promised to limit donations from political
action groups to 10 percent of the total money raised; vowed that
less than 25 percent of the money raised by individual contributors
will come from out of state; imposed a spending limit of $2,000 of
the candidate's own money, and limited overall spending to $1 per
registered voter.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, who is making the bigger sacrifice _ an incumbent
senator can be a fund-raising machine _ has promised to spend no
more than $3.8 million, less than half of what Paul Wellstone spent
on his successful 1996 Senate race in neighboring Minnesota, a
state with fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann said he would cap his spending at $4.7 million,
justifying the larger sum because Feingold was also using money
raised in his early years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say the Wisconsin contest is the nation's
only statewide race that is sticking to such rules. A Senate
contest in Massachusetts in 1996 between Gov. William Weld, a
Republican, and John Kerry, the incumbent Democrat, produced an
agreement to limit spending. But the final weeks of that campaign,
which Kerry won, dissolved into bitter recriminations, as both
candidates exceeded the spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls published in Wisconsin newspapers have shown
Senator Feingold with a double-digit lead. The Republican Party
says its polls show the race in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The rules imposed by Feingold and Neumann are more stringent
than the terms of the failed campaign finance reform bill, which
Feingold sponsored with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. That bill would
have limited lobbyist contributions to 20 percent of the total sum
a candidate raises, compared with the 10 percent limit in
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, who describes himself as the nation's poorest senator,
with a net worth of $30,000 to $40,000, said he knew that his
advocacy of campaign finance overhaul would mean greater scrutiny
of his own money-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the self-imposed limit, he said, was the
disgust he felt at begging for money like some political
panhandler. ``It made me sick,'' he said. ``You're calling someone
you don't even know and asking them for money.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his Senate staff vehemently opposed the idea of an
incumbent forsaking the chance to raise enough money to blitz radio
and television stations with advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, who tends to the liberal wing of the Democratic Party,
has promised not to use his franking privileges to pay for
mailings. He has also vowed not to cooperate with lobbyists raising
money for advertisements in his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   He asserts that Neumann, on the other hand, has shown little
compunction about benefiting from a windfall of advertisements paid
for with money raised by conservative groups. Feingold noted that
Neumann was running television and radio advertisements on Aug. 11,
a month before his own first commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, a favorite of such groups as the Christian Coalition
and the National Taxpayers Union, meanwhile, asserts that Feingold
has also benefited from advertisements paid for by interest groups,
pointing to spots run recently by the Sierra Club that sharply
criticized the Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these nits, the Wisconsin contest remains a model of
spending restraint, compared with campaigns in most other states.
The state was also the home of the reform-minded Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
   The state has a generally liberal political tradition, but it
has always taken a dim view of excess. Former Sen. William
Proxmire, a Democrat who left office a decade ago, was known for
his Golden Fleece Awards, which highlighted wasteful spending in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Taylor, executive director of the Alliance for Better
Campaigns in Washington, said that vowing to limit campaign
spending was well-intentioned but ``fraught with peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Limiting the money spent by candidates, Taylor said, could
``tilt the playing field to outside interests,'' like business and
union groups, whose advertisements would become even more dominant.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the efforts in Wisconsin were worthy and might show
the nation of new way of electing its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attractive experiment,'' Taylor said. ``The instinct
is to be applauded. But everybody ought to have their eyes open
here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
