<HEADLINE>
2 AGENCIES MAKE ACQUISITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two agencies made acquisitions in health care and in public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowe Healthcare division of the Lowe Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies acquired Grob Health and Science
Inc. in Cambridge, Mass., and renamed the agency Lowe Grob Health
and Science. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Grob Health, with 24 employees, has billings estimated at $16
million from clients like the Boston Scientific Corp. and Medeva
PLC. Lawrence Grob, 48, president, and his wife, Ellen Touart-Grob,
44, chief operating officer, will continue to oversee the agency in
those roles.
</P>
<P>
   And Incepta Group PLC in London _ which owns agencies including
the financial and corporate communications shop Citigate
Communications and the advertising agency Citigate Albert Frank _
acquired another financial and corporate communications agency,
Dewe Rogerson Group Ltd. in London, for an estimated $40 million in
cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Incepta will combine the two public
relations and investor relations agencies to form Citigate Dewe
Rogerson. The combined shop will have 400 employees in 9 offices
around the world and fee income estimated at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   David Wright, 54, chairman of Incepta, was named to the
additional responsibilities of overseeing Citigate Dewe Rogerson,
as chairman, while Anthony Carlisle, a director of Dewe Rogerson
and executive chairman of the London office of Dewe Rogerson, will
become an executive director of Incepta. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
