<SLUG> BC-SUHARTO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUHARTO WEALTH UNDER INQUIRY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The Indonesian government has questioned
former President Suharto about his personal wealth and accusations
that he had billions of dollars in overseas bank accounts,
officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials leading the investigation told reporters on
Tuesday that Suharto would soon provide the attorney general's
office with a report of his wealth to help ``clarify'' news reports
that place his worth at up to $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, who resigned under pressure in May after 32 years in
office, has denied having any holdings overseas and has challenged
critics to substantiate their accusations that he amassed a fortune
through corruption and the granting of business privileges to his
family members and associates.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour meeting with the former president on Monday
evening at his home in central Jakarta, Attorney General Mohammad
Ghalib said the government had no plans to bring charges against
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until there is proof, Suharto is not a suspect,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
