<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: PHILIPPINE AIRLINES TO SHUT DOWN; HIGHER AIR FARES
EXPECTED; WORLD'S LARGEST PASSENGER SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barring a last-minute rescue, Philippine Airlines, Asia's oldest
scheduled carrier, will shut down at midnight Wednesday. This means
passengers who until now have flown the airline's daily nonstop
flight between Los Angeles and Manila, or the thrice-weekly nonstop
flights between San Francisco and Manila, will have to make other
arrangements. But no other arrangements from the United States will
be nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines, for example, has daily flights to Manila
from nine U.S. cities, including New York, Los Angeles and San
Francisco. But all of them connect through Tokyo, which after a
layover of about two hours requires a change of plane and an
additional four and a half hours of flying. Northwest's daily
flight from Memphis, Tenn., to Manila via Tokyo also requires a
stop and a change of plane in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   UAL's United Airlines flew nonstop between San Francisco and
Manila until Feb. 20, when it finally pulled the plug on that
unprofitable route. Now United's Manila-bound passengers have to
fly to Tokyo and connect with another airline _ as do those of
AMR's American Airlines and Delta Air Lines. Continental Airlines'
passengers can fly nonstop to Honolulu from Newark, N.J., Houston
and Los Angeles, and then connect on Continental Micronesia to
Manila after a stop in Guam.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine Airlines has been hurt by a series of strikes, by the
Asian financial crisis and by overly ambitious expansion plans that
have saddled the carrier with $2 billion in debt. ``Demand in Asia
has just dried up, and several airlines there are verging on
bankruptcy,'' said Michael Boult, director of supplier relations
for Rosenbluth International, the large business travel management
company.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbluth and other travel management companies almost never
book clients on struggling airlines, lest they fail and leave
passengers stranded. But they have no problem booking with
Singapore Airlines, Qantas Airways, Air New Zealand, ANA, Cathay
Pacific or Japan Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Boult said that the fire-sale fares offered by many
Asian carriers, in an effort to keep afloat, had led to
``aggressive corporate discounting'' of as much as 25 percent _
even by U.S. and European carriers _ for fares to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 1999 will still be rough going for the weaker Asian
carriers,'' Boult said. ``But there's no doubt in my mind that the
Asian market will rebound in the year 2000,'' although not
necessarily with all the current airlines intact.
</P>
<P>
   Prices on the Rise
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers should prepare themselves for another year of
heavy passenger loads on airlines and high occupancies in business
hotels. And, of course, higher prices for both. A preliminary study
by American Express, released Tuesday, projects an overall increase
of 5 percent to 6 percent for the cost of business travel next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The price increases will again be led by air fares, which will
rise an expected 4 percent to 5 percent, and for hotel rooms, which
will go up 7 percent to 10 percent in New York, Chicago, Los
Angeles and the 22 other top business destinations,
</P>
<P>
   The forecast numbers, based on data from American Express and
other industry sources, could change if current economic turmoil
overseas and stock market instability in the United States
translate into lower demand for business travel. As of now, though,
the company said, it is advising companies ``to brace for another
tough year with few travel bargains.''
</P>
<P>
   A Really Tall Ship
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That behemoth looming over the New York skyline from
Pier 88 beginning Thursday will be neither an apparition nor
something out of a Japanese science fiction film. Instead, it will
be the 109,000-ton, 18-deck, $450 million Grand Princess, the
world's most expensive and biggest passenger ship _ taller than
either Niagara Falls or the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Launched last May, the ship _ owned by Peninsular and Oriental
Steam Navigation Co. _ cruised the Mediterranean until Sept. 11,
before heading to Manhattan. The actress Olivia de Havilland will
formally christen the ship next Tuesday at 10:30 a.m.; the first
marriage in the ship's wedding chapel will be performed Friday at
10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Oct. 4, the ship _ 53 feet too wide to get through the
Panama Canal _ will begin almost eight months of seven-day
Caribbean cruises from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
