<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8941 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HARDEMAN     09-22 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HARDEMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Texas A&AMP;M might have to forfeit its Sept. 12 win
over Louisiana Tech, pending the findings of a university
investigation into the eligibility of fullback D'Andre ``Tiki''
Hardeman.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A senior from Galena Park, Hardeman was placed on indefinite
suspension last week for unspecified reasons and will remain
sidelined Saturday when the Aggies host North Texas at Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before A&AMP;M beat Southern Mississippi 24-6 in
Starkville, Miss., last weekend to improve to 2-1, coach R.C.
Slocum informed Hardeman he was being suspended. University
officials have yet to explain why that action was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much to say,'' A&AMP;M athletic director Wally Groff
said Tuesday, ``other than that we have a situation we're looking
into, and it affects one of our student-athletes. Until we get in
all of the information, we really don't have a comment to make.''
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous source close to the situation has said Hardeman is
mired in an academic problem that has arisen from his summer-school
course work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about satisfactory progress this summer,'' the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cannon, A&AMP;M's sports information director, said that if a
player is suspended for violating team rules, Slocum usually ``will
say it's for breaking team rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I can remember a player just being
suspended indefinitely,'' Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Groff said he first learned about the issue Thursday while
attending a Big 12 athletic directors meeting in Dallas. He gave no
time frame for completion of the university investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could take a day, or it could take a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman has played in two games this season _ a season-opening
23-14 loss to Florida State in the Kickoff Classic at East
Rutherford, N.J., on Aug. 31, and the 28-7 victory over Louisiana
Tech at Kyle Field. In the second game, Hardeman ran for three
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Before being suspended, Hardeman was the Aggies' second-leading
ground-gainer (105 yards) and No. 1 scorer (24 points). Entering
the 1998 season, Hardeman had carried 262 times for 1,490 yards
(5.7 average) and scored 26 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   If it is determined he was academically ineligible at the start
of the season, the Aggies could be forced to forfeit the win over
Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's always that possibility, just like anything
else,'' Groff said.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum admitted Hardeman's absence ``cuts down our options
greatly'' on offense. But other than to confirm the fullback won't
be used Saturday, the coach had little more to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into anything hypothetical, what might
have happened and who is at fault,'' he said. ``I do feel some
frustration. But there are some situations where you can't talk
about some things.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, freshman Ja'Mar Toombs of Kilgore
will start Saturday in place of Hardeman.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies feel that while Hardeman will be missed for whatever
length of time he remains on suspension, there is enough talent to
keep the ship afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not where we want to be, and without Tiki, it will be
tough,'' tight end Dan Campbell said. ``He's what an A&AMP;M running
back is all about. He's tough, and he will run through tacklers.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M has nine games remaining. Should they have to forfeit the
Louisiana Tech win, the Aggies would have to win at least five more
games to qualify for a bowl. According to NCAA guidelines, a team
must have a minimum of six victories against Division I opponents
to qualify for a bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
