<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-985(     09-22 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-985(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW' GERMANS FIND ESCAPE FROM TAINTED PAST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., S.C.)  (jw) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany _ They have grappled with their nation's
history and understand its shame. They see their future with a
self-confidence their parents lacked.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's baby boomers have come of age, a new elite that has
moved into the country's boardrooms and its barracks, worldly,
drawn largely from the former West Germany, and above all striving
for a sense of normality in a land whose elders felt anything but
easy with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls give no clear indication of this generation's
likely voting patterns in national elections on Sept. 27, in which
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, 68, is in the biggest fight of his
political career, against Gerhard Schroeder, 54.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that no politician can afford to ignore this
generation, a broad swath of the 60 million voters. For it will
define the agenda in business, style, the arts and, increasingly,
in politics as a dominant Germany faces a new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an entire generation stretching from 35 to 50 that is
running the country,'' Lt. Col. Carsten Jacobson, 43, a general
staff officer and former tank commander, said at his home near a
lake south of Hanover. ``It is the managers, the political leading
class, the top civil servants.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a generation forged by two key dates: 1968, when a student
revolt in Europe produced a broader sense of its power, and 1989,
when the fall of the Berlin Wall led to German reunification. It is
also a generation that has molded American thinking about how
Germany will brace for a new century _ aware of its own interests
and ready to pursue them, and to assume greater responsibility
within the European and Atlantic alliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether they have overcome their fear of being
German, and the answer is: Yes,'' said J.D. Bindenagel, a senior
U.S. State Department official with long experience in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   German companies are major players in the economies of the
victorious wartime Allies. German soldiers, once barred from
service outside their country, now patrol the Balkans. When
Europeans seek a lead in dealing with the Russian crisis, they turn
reflexively to Bonn. And much of Europe's ability to make its
single currency work will demand German leadership.
</P>
<P>
   As with much of Germany's modern visage, it is a generation with
two profiles: west and east.
</P>
<P>
   Many westerners were born of parents who experienced Nazi
Germany first hand, yet frequently lived in denial of complicity as
they rebuilt their country into Europe's richest. Yet all were
nurtured by the peace, prosperity and self-confidence of the German
economic miracle.
</P>
<P>
   In the former East Germany, the dynamic was different: a
Communist leadership denied not just responsibility for the Nazi
era, but also the individual initiative encouraged in the west _
creating divisions that linger today. But what differentiates
Germany's baby boomers from their American counterparts is the
legacy of the past.
</P>
<P>
   German success, like American success, is measured in snappy
suits and slick cars, exclusive vacations and rich homes. But where
the American collective memory unfolded from victory in World War
II, many Germans of an earlier generation emerged with the
crushing, guilt-laden burden of the Holocaust and defeat.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the new Germans are bolstered by a consensus that
while Germans of their age must prevent history from repeating
itself, time has distanced them from their forebears' guilt. They
are far more ready to assert their interests, sometimes as Germans,
sometimes more as Europeans, in a contradictory world where
globalization has heightened national competition, just as the
conflicts of the post-Cold War era in places like Bosnia and
Albania demand cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Cold War, the soldiers of the former West Germany
were forbidden _ by the Constitution and often by inclination _
from venturing outside the huge land mass patrolled by NATO. When
the Cold War ended, many Germans, including those in the military,
still resisted American insistence that reunification brought new
responsibilities in policing an unruly world.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jacobson was not one of them. ``We are a country at the
crossroads of European history,'' he said. ``We border nine
countries. We are 80 million people. We are a wealthy country and a
magnet to neighbors who are not as wealthy. It's generally felt
that we have a moral burden. But I don't think we have any
alternative but to take an active role.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, though, the emergence of that role took Germany back
to its past and, specifically, to its history in the Balkans, where
Hitler's armies sustained a fascist regime in Croatia. From 1945 to
the mid-1990's, when a German medical unit cautiously deployed to
Croatia, followed by the dispatch of combat troops to Bosnia, the
Balkans represented a taboo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be stupid as a German soldier to go to the Balkans
without knowing what happened there,'' Col. Jacobson said. ``And
since everything in the Balkans is history, there is no nice
gesture to get around that.''
</P>
<P>
   So in late 1997, Col. Jacobson set off for Sarajevo for what
became a seven-month stint as military assistant to a German
two-star general serving under American command of the
international peace force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   It went ``remarkably well,'' he said. Despite historical
mistrust, there were no personal affronts. Indeed, he said, he
discovered that working 24 hours a day with other soldiers in the
multinational force, some from countries that had been invaded by
Nazi Germany, ``Germans were not looked at differently.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found our way back to the choir of nations as
soldiers,'' Col. Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along that route, of course, the United States was a mentor. But
here too, for a newer generation, attitudes toward America have
become more textured as Germans have moved away from being
perceived as Teutonic stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel very German in Britain or the United States,''
said Gabriele Eick, 46, the head of communications at Dresdner
Bank. ``I feel very much at home. I would be embarrassed if people
thought: the typical German.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eick's resume could almost be that of an American high
flier, reflecting a career that for many years unfolded within
German subsidiaries of big American corporations like IBM, A.C.
Nielsen and Burson-Marsteller.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Ms. Eick's career has brought her into a different
and potentially more combative relationship with an important part
of American society: part of her job is to mold the corporate
response to a class-action suit by Holocaust survivors who say
Dresdner and other banks profited from their suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eick was born in the former East Germany in 1952 and her
family fled to the west just a few months before the Berlin Wall
was built in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation grew up on American folk songs,'' she said. ``I
know more American folk songs than German ones. And this is how I
learned a large part of my English. I grew up with a very strong,
positive American orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentiments like these are much different from those of people
like Kohl, whose teen-age years unfolded under the occupation of
French and American forces.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as Hermann Grohe, a 37-year-old member of Parliament in
Bonn put it: ``I meet American legislators with the feeling that
these are representatives of the people in the most important
democracy in the world. But I don't see them as `the victor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere has that been more evident than in the world of
business. German publishing houses have taken huge stakes in
American publishing. Volkswagen owns auto plants from the Czech
Republic to Spain. Daimler-Benz bought Chrysler. SAP, a German
software company, is the fourth largest in the American-dominated
hi-tech world. BMW owns the Rover car company in Britain and has
agreed with Volkswagen to parcel out ownership of Rolls Royce and
Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitive drive was forced on German business by a
changing world. The European single market and the prospect of a
European single currency obliged companies to think in terms of far
wider networks, while the broader dynamics of the auto industry led
the drive for economies of scale as a means of survival in the
global competition. And that, in turn, revolutionized German big
business, creating the readiness not just to advance into global
markets, but also to challenge Germany's stultified labor
practices.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key players in this transformation was Helmut Panke,
52, BMW's industrial relations director, who set up the company's
operation in Spartanburg, S.C., between 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners change because they see a different Germany,'' he
said. ``But Germany and the Germans changed because they have
experienced more of the global network.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that view came from the west, and Matthias Platzeck,
44, the environment minister of Brandenburg, in the east, sees
things differently.
</P>
<P>
   Platzeck was 7 when the Berlin Wall was built, sealing him into
a cocoon of social protection, outright repression and Soviet
domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you learned a second language, it was Russian or Polish,''
Platzeck said. And even now, the sophistication of western Germans
does not extend so easily to the easterners. ``The ability to jump
across the pond is a western thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a world, he said, that treated the Holocaust as ``a side
issue'' and tried to teach its children to glorify the Soviet
Union. And it has left a different legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In eastern Germany, unemployment is twice as high as in the
west, at 20 percent, and it afflicts mainly the 50-plus generation,
the group that in the west gained most from the economic miracle.
The causes for the easterners' joblessness are well known:
reunification brought a wave of Deutschmark capitalism, utterly
destroying industries that had offered artificial full employment.
</P>
<P>
   But, Platzeck said, that same shock wave may have galvanized a
younger generation, forcing members into service industries, the
media and other sectors. ``Unlike in the west, 80 percent of
professional people in eastern Germany who do have jobs have
changed their jobs in the past seven years,'' he said. ``Big
changes are on the way with the European single currency. And
easterners are better armed for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The generational shifts evoke the real subtext driving Germany's
election: How will this new generation propel Europe's economic
powerhouse toward the challenges of the European unity?
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's Social Democratic opponent, Schroeder, is 14 years
younger than the Christian Democratic chancellor and likes to call
himself a Spatgeborene, a word that means ``born late'' and denotes
those whose birth came late enough to avoid all taint of the Third
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   While Schroeder is narrowly ahead in opinion surveys, though,
his personal popularity is equaled by a Christian Democrat of his
generation, Wolfgang Schauble, Kohl's heir apparent. And many
believe that if he won, Kohl would soon hand over to Schauble. In
other words, whatever the outcome on Sept. 27, this is likely to be
Kohl's last election before he bows out.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's choice as economics minister is Jost Stollmann, 43,
an iconoclastic computer millionaire who has angered the Social
Democratic party traditionalists by rejecting their left-wing
economic platform. ``Germany's future,'' Stollmann declared
recently, ``is neither left nor right, not ideological but
pragmatic. It will be a different way, our own German way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
