u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCI-WORLDCOM-RESIGN-N     09-22 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-WORLDCOM-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE FALLOUT FROM A MERGER ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One morning last November, as leaders of Worldcom Inc. and MCI
Communications Corp. held a news conference in New York to announce
their companies' $37 billion merger deal, an executive close to
Worldcom who sat in the audience subtly gestured at the stage and
an extremely subdued Gerald Taylor, MCI's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Jerry,'' the executive said, using Taylor's nickname.
``You can tell he's not going to stick around.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Worldcom completed its acquisition of MCI last
Tuesday, and Taylor, who was to run the new MCI Worldcom Inc.'s
international operations, tendered his resignation before the end
of the week, mere days after the company where he worked for almost
30 years formally disappeared, people close to MCI said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom announced Taylor's resignation Tuesday and said it
would take effect at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday night, Taylor said that he had first
considered leaving MCI after the company agreed to be acquired by
British Telecommunications in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined MCI really as a summer job,'' he said. ``It's time
for new blood there and it's probably time for me to pursue other
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that one of the possibilities he was considering was
joining a small start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   Like the executive at the news conference, most people in the
telecommunications industry did not expect Taylor to remain at the
combined company for long. But the speed of Taylor's departure may
be interpreted as a sign that Bernard Ebbers, who built Worldcom
through acquisitions, does not plan to alter his style of corporate
integration _ which features cost-cutting and major executive
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers, who had been Worldcom's chairman and will be chief
executive of the new company, is known for relying on a tight group
of managers. Executives at Worldcom's targets who find themselves
potentially competing with members of Ebbers' circle generally move
on.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Taylor was not the only senior MCI executive to
announce his resignation Tuesday. Lance Boxer, MCI's chief
information officer, announced that he had agreed to join Lucent
Technologies Inc., North America's biggest maker of
telecommunications gear, as president for communications software.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, 44, said that John Sidgmore, head of Worldcom's Internet
unit, had asked him to stay with MCI Worldcom, but he added that
with the takeover his opportunities for advancement seemed less
than stellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew I wanted to expand and run a new business unit,''
Boxer said Tuesday. ``It wasn't going to be possible in the MCI
Worldcom structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Timothy Price, MCI's president, who is to run MCI
Worldcom's domestic operation, Boxer added, ``The business units
will be run by Tim Price, John Sidgmore and whoever runs the Jerry
Taylor operation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, after MCI and Worldcom announced that Scott
Sullivan, Worldcom's high-powered chief financial officer, would
take over that post in the combined company, Douglas Maine, MCI's
finance chief, left in April to join IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 56, will stay on the MCI Worldcom board, where he will
remain linked to a longtime colleague, Bert Roberts Jr., chairman
of the former MCI and chairman of MCI Worldcom. Executives close to
Roberts say he does not intend to step down anytime soon, but not
many people say they expect Roberts to stay with the company for
the long haul, especially since a majority of the board he is to
lead was appointed by Ebbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
