<HEADLINE>
`RUSH HOUR'S' CHAN FINDS DO-IT-YOURSELF STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ Jackie Chan has a cold.
</P>
<P>
   He caught it after washing his canvas shoes in a hotel room
shower and drying them off naked under the air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny, huh?'' he says. ``I always wash my own shoes. I wash my
own underwear, too. Why? Because if you give it to the hotel, they
charge you $3 for one underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the guy whose new movie, ``Rush Hour,'' just brought in
$33 million over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He's been using the same bar of soap that he picked up in a
Taiwan hotel several stops before reaching San Francisco. He wraps
it up after each use and takes it with him to the next hotel on his
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to see people waste things,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Chan's been like that for more than three decades, ever since he
went from boy to teenager under the tutelage of a tough master at a
Peking Opera academy in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 44 years old but still look very good,'' he says. ``Why?
Because I have very good basic training. My foundation is very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chan comes across as completely sure of himself, he also is
playful. His cold doesn't prevent him from suddenly breaking into
song, in a sweet karaoke voice:
</P>
<P>
   (set ital)Wise men say only fools rush in, but I can't help
falling in love with you.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   He's so pleased with himself that he croons another one.
</P>
<P>
   (set ital)Somewhere over the rainbow, way up high, there's a
land that I heard of once in a lullaby.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a good singer,'' he says. ``For the last 10 years I
listen to a lot of American songs. Why? Because I want to learn
English.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to learn English, he goes on, ``is to have an
American girlfriend. If I don't have an American girlfriend, the
best way is to watch TV, CNN, or listen to CDs, country music.''
</P>
<P>
   There he goes again: (set ital)You are always on my mind, you
are always on my mind.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   He also sings the soul anthem ``War'' with co-star Chris Tucker
in ``Rush Hour,'' but what he really likes to sing are ballads. ``I
like more slow songs. Then I can follow. Then I can listen and
really use the words. Rock, I cannot understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning English, like washing his shoes, is something he does
``for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got all the fame he could possibly handle and probably all
the money, too. ``It's not about the money. Money in the bank is
only zero, zero, zero,'' he says, reaching into the pocket of his
black-and-white jumpsuit and pulling out a money clip. ``Now money
in your pocket, that's real money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to do something today for myself, for my family,
for the Chinese community.''
</P>
<P>
   What he really wants to do right now is ``get back into the
American market.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried it in the early '80s with two ``Cannonball Run''
movies, which starred Burt Reynolds, but the films didn't do too
much for Chan. ``Rumble in the Bronx'' was a U.S. hit in 1994, but
despite the title, the film was a Hong Kong production, with Chan
dubbing his own voice, and so was ``Supercop'' after that.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of the first weekend's box office, it looks as if
``Rush Hour,'' a Hollywood production, has turned the corner for
him.
</P>
<P>
   He's ready to do a sequel, if anybody asks him. ``At the end of
the movie, you see Chris Tucker and me on the plane. Where are we
going? Nobody knows. Maybe plane land in China,'' he says with a
grin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is a Jackie Chan quick change of direction. ``But if it's
no good and nobody call us, that's OK, too. I have my own
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan has his own team of seven stuntmen, and they work out for
three hours every day, wherever his moviemaking takes him _ Los
Angeles, Taiwan, Singapore, Hong Kong. He does not do much weight
training. ``I cannot have huge muscles,'' he says. ``Mostly we
jump, punch, kick.''
</P>
<P>
   He has just published an ``as told to'' book, ``I Am Jackie
Chan: My Life in Action,'' which describes his apprenticeship in
the Peking Opera academy _ Chinese opera includes tumbling and
martial arts, as well as singing. The book also has a filmography
that lists his work as a stuntman on the Bruce Lee films ``Fist of
Fury'' and ``Enter the Dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, the early '70s, he established the style of doing
his own stunts that became his trademark. Now, audiences expect it
from him, even as other action films rely on high-tech computer
graphics for their effects. ``If I make `Jurassic Park,' with
dinosaurs, it's not Jackie Chan anymore. I have to stay in this
kind of style.''
</P>
<P>
   He nearly died as the result of a head injury from falling out
of a tree while making ``Armour of God'' in 1986. Even today, he
does not take stunt-related injuries seriously unless he ends up in
the hospital. For ``Rush Hour,'' there were times he was ``just
hurting a little bit, cutting a little bit,'' but ``mostly blood
comes out a little bit, and I don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
