<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS ARE GRADED ON HOW THEY DEPICT WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Mich., N.Y., Ohio, Calif., Ill.)   (af)  
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An organization of women in advertising is again
grading efforts by Madison Avenue to portray their sex in sales
pitches for products.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon Wednesday at the New York Hilton, the
organization, Advertising Women of New York, will present honors
and dishonors at its second annual event known as the Good, the Bad
and the Ugly Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements labeled good include work for the AT&AMP;T Corp., the
Kellogg Co. and Mastercard International Inc. The campaigns
considered bad are for products as diverse as automobiles, beer and
shampoo. And the most ugly of the ugly ads that present women in
demeaning ways, according to the organization, is a commercial for
a fast-food chain that celebrates a busty blonde running on a
beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we really bent over backwards not to point our
finger at marketers who were still using the outdated, stereotyped
imagery,'' said Toni Lee, co-chairwoman of the Advertising Women of
New York creative committee and an awards judge, ``but this year we
felt we had given them fair warning.''
</P>
<P>
   To supplement the opinions of the judges, the organization asked
women who do not work in advertising to comment on the ads, which
could be viewed on the iVillage Web site (www.iVilliage.com).
</P>
<P>
   N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners in New York, a unit of MacManus Group and
the sponsor of the luncheon, also showed the ads under
consideration to women in focus groups; videotapes of those
sessions will be shown at the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted marketers to hear what women in the marketplace had
to say,'' said Ms. Lee, who is president at TL Communications in
Wilton, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The ads that are being praised portray women as much more
multidimensional than how they were depicted in ads decades ago,
when simplification to the point of condescension was standard. In
many of those early ads, American women were depicted as mindless
housewives whose agenda in life was to scrub kitchen floors, make a
good cup of coffee and have the whitest laundry _ all while wearing
pearls.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the ``good'' ads are suffused with humor, like one
commercial _ a multiple winner at the luncheon _ by the Leo Burnett
Co. in Chicago for the Special K cereal sold by Kellogg. The spot,
which carries the theme ``Reshape your attitude,'' shows men in a
bar, uttering such phrases as ``I will stop asking `Do I look fat
in this?''' and ``I have my mother's thighs. I have to accept
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards _ including a ``Grand Good'' for the commercial and a
``They Get It'' honor for Kellogg _ are especially noteworthy
because as recently as two years ago, the company and Burnett were
criticized by some women for a Special K campaign centered on a
woman admiring herself in a mirror as she modeled a black dress,
apparently a size 2 at most.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg's ``complete advertising about-face is ample evidence
that this leading advertiser not only gets it,'' Ms. Lee said,
``but also gets the fact that they didn't get it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kafer, a spokeswoman for Kellogg in Battle Creek, Mich.,
said the company was pleased with the recognition adding, ``We have
changed our advertising approach based on feedback from women.''
</P>
<P>
   Another winner of a ``good'' award is a commercial for the
Ameritech Corp. cellular telephones, created by the Cliff Freeman &AMP;
Partners unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC in New York. The spot mocks
the propensity of men to buy women gifts like a waffle iron and a
``nice new fluffy bath towel.''
</P>
<P>
   Another praised commercial, for Mastercard, was created by
McCann-Erickson New York, part of the McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising division of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies. The spot describes as ``priceless''
a woman's ability to have the last word with an old boyfriend at a
class reunion.
</P>
<P>
   A second Grand Good Award will be presented to AT&AMP;T and its
agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York, for two
commercials centered on the relationship between mothers and
daughters. One, using the Cyndi Lauper song ``Girls Just Wanna Have
Fun,'' shows a female executive playing hooky from work to take her
three daughters to the beach. The other, using the Frank Sinatra
version of ``Our Love is Here to Stay,'' shows a mother taking her
daughter to college for freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``They Get It'' Award is being given to Purple Moon, a
new media company in Mountain View, Calif., that creates CD-ROMs
and interactive programs for girls. The citation praises the
company for helping girls become comfortable with technology and
recognizing differences between the way girls and boys play.
</P>
<P>
   Luncheongoers who are eager to watch the women of Madison Avenue
bite the hand that feeds them will probably be disappointed,
because the awards, as they did last year, devote less attention to
the bad and the ugly than to the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to embarrass anybody,'' said Nora P. McAniff,
president of Advertising Women of New York, who is also the
publisher of People magazine, which is owned by Time Warner Inc.
``But hopefully it's a learning experience for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   One judge, Caroline Jones, president and creative director at
Caroline Jones Inc. in New York, said that it was important to
criticize as well as to praise because even ``going toward the year
2000, we still see women depicted as sex objects for products
mostly aimed at men.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization wants marketers ``to know that this is not
acceptable in this day and age,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Among the campaigns judged offensive to women are television
commercials for Herbal Essences hair care and shower products sold
by the Clairol unit of the Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. The ads,
created by Kaplan Thaler Group in New York, feature women
simulating sexual arousal to make a pun on the brand's ``organic''
formulas.
</P>
<P>
   Another thumbs down went to the Kay Jewelers retail chain
division of Sterling Jewelers Inc. in Akron, Ohio, and its agency,
Stern Advertising in Pepper Pike, Ohio, for a commercial in which a
woman is ignored by her boyfriend when they encounter the model
Cindy Crawford shopping at a Kay store.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Grand Ugly'' Award will be given to Del Taco Inc. in
Laguna Hills, Calif., for a commercial by Italia/Gal Advertising in
Los Angeles, which promoted a menu item called the Macho Combo
Burrito. As a tanned woman, barely wearing her bikini, runs in slow
motion, an announcer intones, ``If this is your idea of quality
entertainment ... have we got something for you.'' Musclebound men
in crew cuts are then seen head-banging each other interspersed
with beauty shots of the burrito.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of the 21 judges of the awards, Sara Smith, best
summarized why that spot was considered the worst of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``What,'' asked the 11-year-old sixth-grade student from
Davenport, Iowa, ``does a woman in a bikini have to do with
tacos?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
