<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 23
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PHILLY-PAPER-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, September 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, September
6, about a libel suit filed against The Philadelphia Inquirer by a
reporter for the paper, Ralph Cipriano, omitted three words in a
comment made to The Washington Post by Robert J. Rosenthal, the
newspaper's editor. He said, ``There were things we didn't publish
that Ralph wrote that we didn't think were truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-PREDICTONS-NYT (moved on Monday, September 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
21, about predictions misstated the time elapsed since the suicide
of Socrates, who relied on oracles. It was 2,397 years ago, not
1,398.
</P>
</TEXT>
