<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENCER SLUGS HIS WAY INTO YANKS' PLANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shane Spencer can't run as well as Chad Curtis, can't
spray line drives like Tim Raines, doesn't hit the ball as far as
Darryl Strawberry. But what Spencer does have is impeccable timing.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, a veteran of 46 major league at-bats before Tuesday
night, is on a power binge that could propel him into a meaningful
role with the Yankees in the playoffs, which start next week. He
banged two homers and nearly hit two others in the first game of
Tuesday's day-night doubleheader with Cleveland at Yankee Stadium,
seizing the attention of Manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's opened our eyes,'' Torre said after the Yankees won the
first game, 10-4, to improve their record to 108-48. With six games
remaining, including Tuesday night's, the Yankees needed two
victories to tie the single-season club record of 110, set by the
1927 Yankees (who finished 110-44), and three victories to tie the
American League record of 111, set by the 1954 Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's emergence has come just as Strawberry and Raines are
hobbling with minor leg injuries. Strawberry bruised a calf when he
was hit by a pitch on Monday, and Raines has a sore knee. Neither
injury is considered serious, but both players are older and have
histories of leg trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, who played well in the first half of the season and was
rewarded with a three-year contract, has had a miserable second
half, batting just .212 in 189 at-bats with one home run and 13
runs batted in, including a .186 average with runners in scoring
position. Pitches on the outer half of the plate have been a
mystery to him, and his defensive play has suffered of late.
</P>
<P>
   Going into September, the Yankees' post-season lineup figured to
include Raines or Strawberry against right-handed pitchers and
Raines or Curtis against left-handers. But Spencer is crushing the
ball and Curtis is floundering and Torre is watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's swinging the bat now,'' Torre said, referring to
Spencer, ``nobody is swinging the bat better.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Indians' Dave Burba, Spencer slammed a gigantic
410-foot solo home run in the second inning, the second of three
home runs the Yankees hit in the inning. (Tino Martinez hammered a
two-run homer and Scott Brosius homered immediately after Spencer.)
Two innings later, Spencer drove his second home run, to
straightaway center field.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer came within five feet of another home run in the sixth
inning; left fielder David Justice caught the ball at the wall in
left-center field. Then, in the seventh, Spencer unloaded a
towering shot down the left-field line. The ball bent foul by 10 or
15 feet and crashed into the upper deck, prompting some oooohs from
the 14,480 attending the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer also made a running, leaping catch in the second inning
and nearly threw out a runner at second base in the sixth inning,
further confirmation of Torre's belief that Spencer can be at least
adequate in playing the outfield. A week ago, there was some doubt
as to whether Spencer would be part of the 25-man roster. Now the
question is, how may Torre employ a right-handed-hitting outfielder
with a .370 average and an .870 slugging percentage?
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Spencer to Mark McGwire directly would be absurd, but
to put Spencer's binge in perspective: McGwire leads major league
regulars with one home run for every 7.5 at-bats; Spencer had a
homer for every 7.7 at-bats before Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Torre believes in the value of experience, he said, before
adding, ``You try to ride a hot hand when you get in the
post-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, a 28th-round draft pick in 1990, pounded 30 home runs
for Class AAA Columbus in 1997 and put himself into position for
his promotion this year, and most likely onto the post-season
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no control over that,'' Spencer said. ``If I get a
chance to play, I'm just having fun.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
