<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: PRIME-TIME SPINNING; WATERGATE RERUNS; COURT TV KNOWS ITS
NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new prime-time season has just begun, with Nielsen ratings
in for new broadcast network offerings on Sunday and Monday nights.
But the spinning has begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   NBC may have had reason to spin. It finished in fourth place
Monday night in the 40 metered markets measured by Nielsen in
overnight ratings. But that still doesn't explain the news release
NBC issued, with this headline: ```Will and Grace' Debut Tops
Premiere of `Ally McBeal' by 30 Percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will and Grace,'' a new comedy in the 9:30 p.m. time slot
between ``Caroline in the City'' and ``Dateline'' on NBC, had a 9.2
overnight rating (each rating point represents 598,000 homes). But
``Ally McBeal,'' the hourlong Fox hit, had an 11.3 rating overall,
and an 11.5 in the half hour it competed against ``Will and
Grace.'' ``Ally'' was second only to ABC's ``Monday Night
Football.''
</P>
<P>
   The text of the NBC statement said that ``Will and Grace''
outdid the series debut of ``Ally McBeal'' ``in the same time
period last fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the fact that the headline implies a victory in this
year's comparable time periods, the statement is inaccurate even
for last year. In its premiere last fall, on Sept. 8, ``Ally
McBeal'' earned a 9.3 rating. In the episode that ran on the
comparable date last year (Sept. 22), it had a 7.4, which is 24
percent, not 30 percent, lower than the 9.2 ``Will and Grace'' got
in metered markets on Monday night. Even then, it's an odd
comparison: the third episode of ``Ally'' versus the debut of
``Will and Grace''?
</P>
<P>
   The NBC publicist who wrote the release, Mike Nelson, was out of
the office Tuesday and could not be reached for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   NBC may have had reason to gloss over some Nielsen numbers,
since all four of its half-hour sitcoms that had their season
premieres on Monday were down from the ratings the network received
for the same time periods last year, and ``Caroline in the City''
was down by 38 percent, to an 8.3 rating from a 13.4 rating.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, by contrast, had reason to be encouraged. The returning
comedy ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' was up, with a 10.2 rating, even
though it was competing against ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Monday Night
Football.'' A new sitcom, ``The King of Queens,'' got a 9.7
overnight rating. And the new series ``L.A. Doctors'' earned a 10.7
against a 9.0 for ``Dateline,'' which had coverage of President
Clinton's grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The Nixon Hearings
</P>
<P>
   The national fascination with President Clinton's unexpurgated
grand jury testimony on Monday reminded some Americans of an
earlier, equally compelling presidential television event _ the
1974 Watergate hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The History Channel, fittingly, is already on that wavelength.
Tuesday, the cable network announced that it would show the House
Judiciary Committee hearings from 1974, starting next Monday: 25
hours of them in five-hour chunks from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. each day,
and again from 3 p.m. to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Along with committee members who are still involved in
Washington politics, like Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Republican
leader, and Defense Secretary William Cohen, the 1974 clips show a
young lawyer who served as counsel to the committee's Democrats
during those hearings _ Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us had covered anything like this before, and we were
scared,'' Roger Mudd, a History Channel regular who was then the
congressional correspondent for CBS News, said Tuesday. He and Bob
Schieffer, CBS News' current congressional correspondent, will be
the co-anchors for the reruns of the hearings, which will use CBS'
archival footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew what would happen, whether democracy itself would
slip off the edge of the world if you impeached a president,'' Mudd
said Tuesday. ``It was really unknown stuff we were covering.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a journalist living through those years, 1972, 1973 and
1974, no other three years could ever be comparable to those. Every
morning when you woke up, there was something that caused your jaw
to drop. You didn't know from one day to the next how exciting it
would get. You almost couldn't stand it, it was so exciting, but it
was grim and scary at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudd is also kicking off a new monthly series this Friday called
``Great Minds of American History,'' in which he interviews top
historians _ Stephen Ambrose, on World War II and the 1950s; David
McCullough on the early 20th century; James McPherson on the Civil
War; Richard White on the settlement of the American West, and
Gordon Wood on the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to running on the History Channel, these one-hour
episodes will appear on PBS next spring.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who originally wanted to be a professional historian
when he grew up, Mudd has found his niche at the History Channel.
In earning his master's degree in history from the University of
North Carolina, Mudd wrote his thesis on the relationship between
the press and Franklin Roosevelt's top advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I then wanted to work for a newspaper before going on with my
next level of studies,'' he said. He got a job with The Richmond
(Va.) News-Leader, which led to a radio job, which led to
television, and the rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Plugging Away
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of how far Court TV Telecommunications has fallen
off the public radar screen, most newspapers' accounts about which
television networks would be carrying President Clinton's grand
jury testimony on Monday, and later assessments of that coverage,
did not even mention Court TV.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in its heyday, when the nation was obsessed with O.J.
Simpson's murder trial, Court TV was a dominant television force,
both in carrying the trial itself live every day, and in analyzing
and commenting on it between court sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a two-hour show last night replaying segments of the
Clinton testimony and analyzing the specific legal issues,'' Henry
Schleiff, the newly named president of Court TV, said rather
plaintively Tuesday. ``We really put Clinton's testimony under a
microscope, in a way that only Court TV can.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable network also carried Clinton's Aug. 17 videotaped
testimony live as it was being released, just as the all-news cable
networks and the three major broadcast networks did.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's panelists included a number of conservatives _
Mark Braden, former chief counsel of the Republican National
Committee; Jamie Wareham, former director of Lawyers for Dole;
Gilbert Davis, a former lawyer for Paula Jones, and Larry Klayman,
chairman of the conservative foundation Judicial Watch _ as well as
Time magazine's deputy chief of the Washington bureau, Jef
McAllister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five of our own journalists, too, whose job was to
balance the arguments,'' said Sheilagh D'Arcy McGee, the network's
vice president for programming. ``For those tired of all the
partisan arguing and screaming, we are trying to illuminate the
process and the actual legal issues. That's our niche and we will
stick to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schleiff, who technically doesn't start his new job until Oct.
5, will take over a network that has been floundering since Steve
Brill, its founder, sold his interest and departed in February
1997. Court TV was left in the hands of three co-owners who
bickered over its direction and a new president. Finally, Time
Warner and Liberty Media bought out NBC's interest, and last week
hired Schleiff, a lawyer and television executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
