<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ALBRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM ALBRIGHT, 53, COMPOSER OF RAGTIME MUSIC FOR THE ORGAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Albright, a composer, organist and pianist, died on
Sept. 17 at his home in Ann Arbor, Mich. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was liver failure, said his agent, Karen McFarlane.
</P>
<P>
   Albright won special respect for his work in ragtime and organ
music. These might seem quite distinct fields, but,
characteristically, he brought them together. He wrote rags for the
organ, which had probably never had rags written for it before, and
his creative output was nourished by a love of the American
vernacular that he found in ragtime and church music.
</P>
<P>
   He was born on Oct. 20, 1944, in Gary, Ind., and attended the
Juilliard School's preparatory department before going to the
University of Michigan in 1962. There he studied composition with
Ross Lee Finney and George Rochberg and the organ with Marilyn
Mason. He spent the 1968-69 academic year in Paris, attending
Olivier Messiaen's classes at the Conservatory, and then returned
to the University of Michigan, where he completed his graduate
studies and then joined the faculty in 1970. He remained at the
university, eventually becoming chairman of the composition
department.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's discovery of prejazz musical styles _ ragtime and
stride piano _was a revelation. He performed and recorded much of
this music, which provided a crucial model for such early works as
his ``Grand Sonata in Rag'' for piano (1968). As he wrote of this
piece: ``Ragtime, a beautiful, classical, syncopated music from the
turn of the century, has turned out to have a new fascination for
composers nurtured in our century's subsequent modernism.
Imagination, as well as tonality and rhythmic vitality, could run
rampant: why not have fun and sentimentality? It's very
avant-garde!''
</P>
<P>
   He continued to have fun and sentimentality, and to help other
composers along the way. While contributing extensively to the
organ repertory, he also commissioned pieces from diverse
contemporaries that he played on his concert tours of North America
and Europe. His own organ pieces include the Symphony of 1986.
Among other works are mixed-media pieces for the theater,
compositions for instrumental ensembles (usually unconventional
ones) and a 1983 oratorio, ``A Song to David.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a daughter, Elizabeth Mae Albright, of New
York; a son, John Kirk Albright, of Ypsilanti, Mich.; and two
brothers, John B., of Germantown, Md., and Richard, of Morristown,
N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
