<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-UCLA-LADN     09-22 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLI-DIXON GETS THE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From his position on the UCLA sideline, Brian
Poli-Dixon did not hear Freddie Mitchell's femur break in two.
Other players did, but Poli-Dixon was 20 yards away, which seems
like 20 miles when trying to detect slight sounds in a collision
sport.
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later Poli-Dixon heard UCLA trainer Geoff Schaadt
yell, ``Mitchell's down,'' and he figured that meant Mitchell was
out for the game, perhaps a week or two. It wasn't until halftime
that Poli-Dixon learned the unsettling truth: Mitchell had
fractured his left femur, would undergo emergency surgery to insert
a stabilizing rod and two interlocking screws, and would miss the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A few tears later, Poli-Dixon began to see the cruel irony: The
football fates had given as they had taken away. Mitchell's injury
had become his opportunity. A fallen friend had created the chance
of a lifetime for a quiet, skinny sophomore from northeast Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his chance,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of its best playmaker, UCLA needs someone to take
center stage for its potent offense to run at maximum efficiency.
All fingers point to Poli-Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm looking forward to it,'' he said. ``It could be something
somebody put out there for me. Maybe it was meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon does not have Mitchell's charisma, he does not have
Mitchell's quickness and he might not have Mitchell's hands. But in
some respects he's a better prospect _ good enough, in fact, to
draw comparisons to former Bruin J.J. Stokes. Both are 6-5, with
long, graceful strides and possessing what coaches call game speed;
they're as fast as they need to be. Stokes emerged during his
sophomore season and the Bruins hope Poli-Dixon, who has three
touchdowns in two games, will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian has definitely proven he can be a big-play guy,''
offensive coordinator Al Borges said. ``If there is a plus side to
losing Freddie, it's that it gives us a chance to exploit
Poli-Dixon's talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by a mix of hope and belief, UCLA made Poli-Dixon the
starter at split end this week and moved Brad Melsby to backup
flanker behind Danny Farmer. Melsby is strong and surehanded, but
he lacks Poli-Dixon's size and speed and is best suited for the
slot (inside) position when the Bruins use their three-receiver
formation. The big plays _ the post patterns, the out-and-ups, the
quick slants _ will be left to Farmer and Poli-Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmer and I talked about this,'' Poli-Dixon said. ``It's on
us. We've got to do it. We talked about it in Houston, we talked
about it on (Spaulding Field) and in the training room.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans for radical schematic changes, Borges said
Tuesday. Any adjustments in the post-Mitchell passing game will be
too subtle for the fans to notice. (They might be too subtle for
the opponents as well.) Quarterback Cade McNown will disperse the
ball as usual, throwing screens to the running backs, curls to the
tight ends, fades and posts to the receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time you have to make changes is if there's a blatant
weakness filling in,'' Borges said. ``Anytime you lose a guy of
Mitchell's caliber, there are going to be depth problems. I think
we'll be OK as long as we don't lose anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, it's been a difficult week for Poli-Dixon. His
good friend was lost for the year with a broken leg. He hasn't
practiced because of a concussion suffered at Houston (he expects
to play against Miami) and the weight of UCLA's passing game
suddenly has shifted to his lean, sloping shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Is he ready? He'd better be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been myself this week,'' Poli-Dixon said. ``Part of
it may be the concussion, part may be sorrow for Freddie and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I talked to him Sunday, and he said, `You've got to do it
for me.' In the back of my mind, I've got Freddie on my shoulders.
Even though he's not there, I've got his spirit on my shoulders.
I'm playing for him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Note: Hurricane Georges is expected to hit South Florida
later this week. Scheduled to arrive in Miami on Thursday evening,
UCLA is considering alternate travel plans. More information is
expected today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
