<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED AIRLINES' PARENT PICKS INSIDER AS PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   James E. Goodwin, a longtime senior executive, was named
president and chief operating officer of UAL, the parent of United
Airlines, succeeding John Edwardson, who was forced out by the
carrier's powerful unions.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment immediately vaulted Goodwin, 54, into the race
to succeed Gerald Greenwald, UAL's chairman and chief executive,
whose five-year employment contract expires next summer.
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH IN GERMAN MEDIA DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News Corp., and Prince Walid bin
Talal of Saudi Arabia and Mediaset SpA, Italy's largest private
broadcasting company, plan to buy as much as 25 percent of the
Kirch Group, Germany's second-largest media company, for about $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   DOW DROPS, BUT SMALL STOCKS RISE
</P>
<P>
   The Dow industrials fell 36.05 points, or 0.5 percent, to
7,897.20, with Coca-Cola accounting for a third of the drop. The
market as a whole advanced, buoyed by smaller companies and
technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices fell for the first time in five days, and
the yield on the long bond rose to 5.15 percent, from 5.12 percent
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   3COM EARNINGS EXCEED FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding from a loss a year ago, 3Com reported earnings of
$93.7 million, or 26 cents a share, surpassing analysts' estimates
of 20 cents a share, thanks largely to its Palm Pilot portable
computing device. 3Com had disappointed investors in the past as it
worked through a glutted inventory of modems. The company announced
the results after the close of regular stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON AND OBUCHI SEEK AGREEMENT
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan,
meeting for the first time, struggled to reassure financial markets
but failed to reach agreement on a common strategy to pull the
world's second-largest economy out of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. OFFICIAL CRITICIZES CHINA
</P>
<P>
   David Aaron, undersecretary of commerce for international trade,
on a visit to Beijing, criticized what he called China's
unwillingness to open its markets.
</P>
<P>
   FORMER MCI CHIEF RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Taylor, MCI's chief executive who was to run the
international operations of the new MCI Worldcom Inc., has
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   NOMURA TO BUOY AMERICAN UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Nomura Securities said that it would inject $380 million in
capital into its American unit, Nomura Holding America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINE AIRLINES MAY SHUT DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Barring a last-minute rescue, Philippine Airlines, Asia's oldest
scheduled carrier, will shut down Wednesday midnight.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S TAKE ON ADS
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Women of New York will present honors and dishonors
Wednesday at the group's second annual appraisal of how women are
portrayed in sales pitches. Among those considered laudable are two
AT&AMP;T ads by Young &AMP; Rubicam.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIANS TO SETTLE BANK DEBTS
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia said that the Salim and Gajah Tunggal groups had
agreed to settle $7 billion in debts at failed banks they
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   PORTRAYING THE INTERNET IN 3-D
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent Internet pioneers have founded a company called
Invisible Worlds to create a three-dimensional portrayal for those
navigating the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
