<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG AN ADMIRER, JOHNSON BECOMES MCGWIRE'S FOE FOR A DAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Calif., N.Y., Ill., N.D., Wash., Texas)  (jw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Randy Johnson was the awkward one of the two, a tall
campus curiosity as skinny as Jack Sprat with a slingshot of an arm
but the aim of a water gun. Fastballs spraying everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson was the thin man on campus, his teammate at the
University of Southern California back in the early '80s, Mark
McGwire, was the big man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was made for success, and you could see that early on,''
Johnson said just before his Houston Astros played McGwire's
Cardinals Tuesday night. ``I was like 6-foot-10 and 180 pounds. I
threw hard, but I'd usually hit the backstop about every other
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was more polished. I was raw. If someone would have said
Randy will do this or that, no one would have seen it. With Mark,
you saw it. I'm not surprised he is where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Johnson has long since grown into a frame that
uncoils from the mound and comes at batters like a nightmare. And
on Wednesday, the two superstars will face off in a power duel.
Johnson versus McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we both have an admiration for what each other has
done,'' Johnson said. ``I have respect for Mark and what he has
done for baseball. It's amazing what he and Sammy Sosa have brought
about. There are these incredible stories about them, and how they
got to where they are. It's great for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   As unbelievable as McGwire's power has been while he chased and
passed Roger Maris' single-season home run record of 61, reaching
65 before Tuesday night's game against Houston and starter Mike
Hampton, Johnson has displayed surreal numbers as well since coming
to the National League from Seattle in an attention-getting trade
six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He will look to win his seventh consecutive start on Wednesday
in his last action of the regular season. And he will try to grab
it by challenging McGwire. Last year, that strategy failed him as
McGwire, then with the Oakland A's, crushed a Johnson pitch more
than 500 feet in Seattle's Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   In their only meeting of this season, two weeks ago, McGwire
could not catch up to Johnson's fastball. Few batters have since
Johnson arrived from Seattle. In his last six starts, he is 6-0
with a 1.14 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Some have wondered out loud, why now? Why wasn't Johnson this
hot in Seattle (9-10, 4.33 ERA)? There are theories that the
negative air surrounding his contract status in Seattle was
weighing on him, while others believe he was not giving it his best
because of the rift. Whatever the answer, the fresh start has
served him well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that, a new start, but there are other things,'' Johnson
said. ``There are bigger parks in the National League. I've had
shutouts that might not have been shutouts in Seattle because the
Astrodome is bigger. That helps. And I'm also having fun. I'm
feeding off the encouragement of the fans, and I'm focused.''
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety and edginess that crept into Johnson's personality
in Seattle have disappeared as his phenomenal restart to the season
has become a spectacle in its own right. The hype around Johnson's
performance does not come close to matching the swirl of craziness
that has revolved around McGwire, but Johnson has held his own
against his old college teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have gotten to where we are because we worked hard,''
Johnson said. ``I wouldn't be surprised if Mark wins the home run
race, and then comes back and breaks his own record. If there is
one person who will be able to do it, it's him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I face him, I don't isolate on one person. I've never
concentrated on just him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
