u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-MAPS-585&AMP;ADD     09-22 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MAPS-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES FOR THE MOUSE, WHEELS FOR THE JOYSTICK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two prominent Internet pioneers have founded a
company to create a way of navigating the Internet with maps that
portray the relationships between computers and information as
three-dimensional space.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Invisible Worlds Inc., based in Silicon Valley at
Redwood City, is the brainchild of Carl Malamud and Marshall Rose,
both Internet software developers who are credited with helping to
create some of the most widely used technology components of the
global computer network.
</P>
<P>
   The idea underlying the new company is that the current
generation of Internet navigation tools _ portals, search engines
and directories _ make it difficult for users to visualize
dimensions of cyberspace, the virtual universe that has resulted
from the emergence of the Internet and online services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think you should be able to take your mouse or joystick and
drive around the Internet,'' Malamud said. ``One of the reasons the
Web seems so chaotic is there is no way to see it visually.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there are already a number of so-called virtual worlds
and 3-D Internet standards such as Virtual Reality Modeling
Language, or VRML, Malamud said this was the first commercial
effort to build the tools to map the entire Internet.
</P>
<P>
   When it is made available sometime next year, the company's set
of visual rules, known as the Blocks protocol, will make it
possible for computer users to examine locations of and
relationships between Internet computers and network connections
much as they would peruse a map or an atlas.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, users will view the interactive maps using a standard
Web browser. But Malamud said he hoped someday to see the
development of map-viewing software with more powerful
visualization features.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of a standard mapping protocol for the Internet will
be the possibility of creating many different maps based geography,
subject or almost any other concept.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the new company is planning to create two
demonstration maps, one focusing on financial information and the
other on music and media. However, in addition to selling
advertising or possibly even renting metaphorical space in the
areas it maps, Invisible Worlds is hoping that its new protocol
will create a market for tools, service software and map-viewing
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Malamud nor Rose is a novice at creating Internet
standards. Rose is the author of the Post Office Protocol, or POP,
the standard that is used by millions of Internet computer users
for sending and receiving e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Malamud has developed a number of nonprofit projects including
Internet Talk Radio, the first online station, in 1993. He is
probably best known for his campaign to persuade the U.S.
government to publish public records on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   By posting both the entire text of all Security and Exchange
Commission documents and much of the Patent Office database, he
created public demand that in turn forced those agencies to make
documents publicly available on line at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as an economist, Malamud, 39, said that the idea of
mapping the Internet came to him in 1991 while he was working with
the Internet and using computers and routers dispersed around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Because the concept of geographic distance is irrelevant in
cyberspace, which is formed of instantaneous connections, Malamud
began searching for a way to provide the kind of rich, spatially
oriented view of the Internet that maps afford of the physical
world.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although science-fiction writers such as Vernor Vinge, Neal
Stephenson and William Gibson, who coined the term cyberspace in
his 1984 novel ``Neuromancer,'' have all envisioned electronic
worlds emerging from computer networks, Malamud said they did not
inspire the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read a great deal of science fiction,'' Malamud said.
But he did trace his inspiration to the work of writers such as
Thomas Pynchon, whose most recent novel, ``Mason &AMP; Dixon,''
celebrated the role the cartographer can play in defining uncharted
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Vinton Cerf, who invented Internet protocol, the set of
communications rules that made the Internet possible, said mapping
the Internet was an extremely difficult undertaking that had no
certain outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Carl and Marshall are among the most creative network
citizens that we have,'' said Cerf, now an executive at MCI
Worldcom. He said he had abandoned his own experiments with mapping
multiple dimensions of information into a three-dimensional
representation, finding the problem too daunting.
</P>
<P>
   What Malamud found daunting was searching for support. His
three-year odyssey took him from the United States to Japan and
Amsterdam, the Netherlands, and he said he settled on a for-profit
venture only after his bids to form a nonprofit enterprise to
create an Internet atlas failed to win supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Malamud said he decided to come ``home'' to Silicon Valley,
where he has settled into a small office space near several other
start-up companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
