A8983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YALE-ARCHITECTURE-DEA     09-22 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YALE-ARCHITECTURE-DEAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ARCHITECTURAL SHOWMAN TO YALE DEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not so many years ago, Robert A.M. Stern, the
architect, was peacefully reading behind the privet hedge of his
modest East Hampton ranch house _ his architect friends refer to it
as the ranchburger _ which Stern bought after his divorce, when he
overheard a few people passing by his sign out front. ``My God, he
doesn't really live here, does he?'' Stern heard someone say.
</P>
<P>
   Horrified, the man who has designed for Rockefellers,
Rothschilds and Fords waited five minutes for the offenders to
leave, scurried to pull his ``Robert A.M. Stern'' sign from the
grass, then began renovation plans. Today the house is, to no one's
surprise, a classic Stern shingle-style with a big screened porch
and an evocation of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoemaker never has time to make shoes for the children,
let alone for himself,'' said Stern, explaining why he lived in
architectural purgatory for so long.
</P>
<P>
   These days people wonder how Stern, one of the biggest
architectural voices in New York City, has time to make any shoes
at all.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, Stern began his first day as dean of the Yale School
of Architecture, with a mission to haul the floundering institution
back to glory. His 150-member New York firm, Robert A.M. Stern
Associates, has 10 big houses under way, from an East Hampton
shingle to a California Mediterranean for Ivan Reitman, the
director. (They take two years to build and start at $2 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Stern is also at work on a performing arts center in Houston, a
400-unit apartment building in Battery Park City, a residence hall
at Columbia University and public libraries in Nashville, Miami and
Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he is finishing up ``New York 1880,'' the fourth in a
five-volume architectural history of New York City. He is on the
board of Disney, played an important role in luring the company to
Times Square, and is trying to have the 1964 Huntington Hartford
building at 2 Columbus Circle, considered by some architects to
look like a giant shower stall, designated a landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``People associate modernism with commercial crud,'' said Stern,
59. And then, dryly: ``It's very easy to get all the
preservationists to rally if it has molding on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern, a traditionalist, has himself had a lifelong love affair
with molding, and there are complaints at Yale that installing the
Ralph Lauren of architecture _ the view of his critics _ sends the
wrong message about the direction of the school.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern says that ``unlike Louis XIV, Yale is not me'' and
that he will bring in many modernist points of view. His fans
consider him an excellent choice, a tough and decisive
scholar-showman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob has never been short in the chutzpah department,'' said
his longtime friend, Stanley Tigerman, the architect. Friends also
say the appointment will push Stern closer toward the role to which
he aspires, that of architectural statesman, now held by Stern's
onetime Yale professor, Philip Johnson, 92.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was destined for greatness,'' said Johnson, who
added that although Stern's work is ``not my dish of tea,
architecture, like the house of the Lord, has many mansions.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Stern sat still long enough for an interview in his
grand offices at 34th Street and 10th Avenue, with sweeping views
of the Hudson. He was witty and argumentative, thoughtful and glib.
If Stern's calling was politics, he would be a Sunday morning
program's talking head. He often talks in exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   On the redevelopment of Times Square (his firm did an early
master plan): ``People have this romance of Times Square, as if
somehow Bergdorf Goodman used to be there next to the Metropolitan
Museum of Art. Let's get real. This is New York!''
</P>
<P>
   On building houses for rich people: ``We are a capitalist
society. You need a client.''
</P>
<P>
   On the personality of architects: ``To build anything, you have
to think differently. It is fundamentally an arrogant act. That
little drawing becomes 45 stories high. Hundreds of people work in
that building, thousands pass through it. This is not for shrinking
violets. This is not about having a bad season when you pick the
wrong hemline. This is serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern got serious when he was 13 and told his parents he would
be an architect. His inspiration was the sight of Manhattan from
Brooklyn's subways. ``It was like a mountain range of pinnacled
peaks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is uncharacteristically close-mouthed about his Brooklyn
childhood, and about his father, who sold insurance. ``He was not
one of the world's most successful businessmen,'' Stern said.
``Let's not go into it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tigerman tried to explain Stern's reticence: ``My parents were
very poor, so at some level I was embarrassed because I hung out
with rich people. Does that say a lot of good things about me? No.
But you don't talk about it. So he has some frailties. So what?'')
</P>
<P>
   Stern went to Columbia and then the Yale School of Architecture,
where he was Johnson's protege. His first house was a 1967 shingle
in Montauk inspired by Robert Venturi, the post-modernist
architect. He is divorced from Lynn Solinger, a Gimbel, and has one
son. Architecture seems to be his true love.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the swaggering developers, they know about money,'' he
said. ``But you give them a shape. It's a tremendous power.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern had one request: ``Make me funny and charming, but don't
break my fabulous visage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
