u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLER-ARRESTED-NYT &LR;      09-22 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-ARRESTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED KILLER ARRESTED AGAIN IN FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Mass.)  (jw) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ira Einhorn, an anti-establishment leader who has
spent the last 17 years in Europe as a fugitive from justice in the
murder of his girlfriend in Philadelphia in 1977, has been arrested
again in France and faces possible extradition to the United
States, a government official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said of
the government's efforts to persuade France to extradite Einhorn:
``We are very grateful for the help of the French government. We
have never given up.''
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn's lawyers said they would fight the extradition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Einhorn, a lecturer who once held a Kennedy Fellowship
at Harvard University, was convicted in absentia of first-degree
murder in the death of Holly Maddux, whose mummified body was found
in a trunk in Einhorn's closet in his home in Philadelphia. He was
sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After fleeing in 1981, Einhorn lived in Britain, Switzerland,
Spain, Denmark and Sweden, before settling in the French village of
Champagne-Mouton, northeast of Bordeaux. He has denied killing Ms.
Maddux, maintaining that he had been framed.
</P>
<P>
   The case has drawn the attention of the highest levels of the
U.S. government. On a trip to France, Attorney General Janet Reno
discussed it with her French counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Norris Gelman, a lawyer for Einhorn, said in Philadelphia that
several issues would be raised in opposing extradition, including a
challenge to the validity of a new Pennsylvania law that would have
the effect of granting Einhorn a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature cannot grant a new trial,'' Gelman said.
``Only a court can grant a new trial. It violates the separation of
powers. New trials are for the courts, not the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Simon, another lawyer for Einhorn, said in
Philadelphia, ``Under the U.S.-French extradition treaty, the law
that is applied is the law of the country in which the person is
being held.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Simon said, French law requires that a person
tried in absentia, convicted and then arrested ``will be given a
new trial upon the mere asking.''
</P>
<P>
   When Einhorn was first arrested last year and then freed when a
French court refused to allow his extradition, the Pennsylvania law
did not have the provision for a new trial upon the defendant's
request. So the Pennsylvania Legislature passed a law bringing the
state's provision of a retrial on request in line with French law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislative branch has the power to pass laws,'' Simon
said, ``but it is not empowered to grant new trials. That is in the
power of the judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Simon said, Einhorn, if extradited to Pennsylvania, could
find the courts unwilling to grant him a new trial under
legislative edict. He asked, framing the question that would be
raised at the extradition hearing: ``Can the French be confident
that he absolutely will be given a new trial in the same manner
that a Frenchman would be given a new trial?''
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn, now in his late 50s, is a different person to different
people. To Gelman, one of his lawyers, he is a crusading
environmentalist and a brilliant political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   To his followers in Philadelphia, he was a pacifist who
enchanted his audiences with lectures about psychic weapons,
psychedelic drugs and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   But to Ms. Maddux's relatives, who have pressed the Philadelphia
authorities to bring her killer to justice, he is a person whose
jailing would bring them the peace and closure they crave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you can never shake in your life is your
conscience,'' Meg Wakeman, Ms. Maddux's sister, told The
Philadelphia Inquirer this year. ``You can shake the authorities,
you can shake your friends, you can fly from country to country _
on someone else's dime, I might add _ but you just can't get rid of
that conscience. And one of these days, his conscience just might
catch up with him.''
</P>
<P>
   To Philadelphia District Attorney Lynne Abraham he is simply a
murderer who needs to pay the price for his crime. In an interview
on the A&AMP;E cable television network this year, Ms. Abraham said,
``I will hunt him down to the ends of the earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
