<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MANDELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA, AT WHITE HOUSE, SAYS WORLD BACKS CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nelson Mandela, the president of South Africa and
among the planet's foremost moral authorities, gave President
Clinton the kind of emotional endorsement Wednesday night that he
has trouble getting these days from members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House reception, Mandela said that the domestic
debates of the United States were not his business but that his
personal code did not allow him to desert a friend. He said South
Africa, Africa and the entire world supported Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do wish to say that President Clinton is a friend of South
Africa and Africa,'' he said, ``and, I believe, the friend of the
great mass of black people, and the minorities and the disabled of
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that ``we are thinking of you in this difficult and
discouraging time in your life,'' Mandela recalled receiving a
telephone call two days ago from Frederick Chiluba, the president
of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Mandela, I want you to support President Clinton,'
'' Mandela said. ``He was not speaking for himself, and he said so.
He said, `I am speaking for the continent of Africa.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, clearly moved, smiled during Mandela's remarks, and
appeared at one point to wipe away a tear.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela was repeatedly interrupted with applause from an
audience of black religious leaders, presidents of historically
black colleges and members of the Congressional Black Caucus. Black
Americans have been among the president's most loyal supporters
since he acknowledged an inappropriate relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mandela again said he would not ``interfere in the
domestic affairs of this country,'' his audience was laughing,
convinced that he was doing just that. Mandela described the
standing ovation that Clinton received on Monday from the United
Nations General Assembly. ``If you judge from the reaction'' of the
delegates, he said, ``the United States is completely isolated on
this question.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mandela seemed to entertain the possibility that Clinton's
presidency might not survive this scandal. ``If our expectations,
if our fondest prayers and dreams, are not realized,'' he said,
``then we should all bear in mind that the greatest glory of living
lies not in never falling but in rising every time you fall.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Mandela, Clinton thanked him ``for being the
person we'd all like to be _ on our best day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980922.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9120 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BINO-COX     09-22 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A visit to Bill might be just what Georges needs
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I knew I shouldn't be going to see Bill.
</P>
<P>
   I should be going to Home Depot. I should be trying to beat the
storm surge of panic hurricane shoppers. I should be buying anchor
bolts so I'd be ready just in case I have to put those aluminum
panels over the windows in the back of my house.
</P>
<P>
   I shouldn't be driving on Broadway in West Palm Beach, looking
for the storefront shop specializing in occult religious items.
</P>
<P>
   I shouldn't be seeking the counsel of store owner Bill Kennedy.
The last time I spoke to Bill, he sold me something called Luck In
A Hurry Oil and an Alleged Money Drawing Candle.
</P>
<P>
   No, I didn't win the Lotto that week. But maybe I didn't follow
his detailed instructions as carefully as I should have.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm back. Call me an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you got for a hurricane?'' I ask, after walking into
St. Benedict Religious Store.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hurricane?'' Bill says, rubbing his chin thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, to keep one away,'' I say, sparing him the details about
what a chore it is to put up those aluminum panels.
</P>
<P>
   Bill's got stuff for just about everything. There are voodoo
dolls, powders and potions for enemies, and something called Bend
Over Oil for folks you'd like to know better.
</P>
<P>
   I figured he must have some hurricane repellant in the store.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I'm not prone to humoring the occult. But I'm ready to
make an exception.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of immersing myself in the Weather Channel and
its constant scientific nattering, I've had my fill of upper-level
shearing, cones of probability and well-defined eye walls.
</P>
<P>
   I want answers. And I want them now.
</P>
<P>
   Bill gets my hopes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no spirits in the air yet,'' he tells me, looking
out his window.
</P>
<P>
   Bill says hurricanes are basically controlled by one main spirit
who stays in the eye while a crew of other dead spirits swirl
around the outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an army,'' he says. ``Normally, you'll see the
workers floating in the clouds about 24 to 36 hours before it
hits,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do they look like?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``People,'' he says. ``Only bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   But I won't be able to see them, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only certain people can see them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (I had an aunt like that. They let her out on weekends.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But wait a minute, Bill,'' I say. ``That's no help at all. The
scientists will know where the hurricane is going to hit when it's
24 hours away. I need to know now. And if it's coming here, I need
to know if there's something you sell that will make the hurricane
go someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill says he can't help me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody fools with Mother Nature,'' he says. ``The only thing
any human being can do is pray to the god they've been serving.''
</P>
<P>
   Too mainstream occult for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about using some of those blue pellets you have over
there?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bluing'' pellets ($3.50) allegedly ward off evil by
turning your bath water blue before you hop in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Won't work,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would the Seven Holy Spirit Sand, the Black Salt or the
Deliverance Oil _ even in the $12.95 size.
</P>
<P>
   They only work for people problems, not Hurricane Georges
problems, Bill explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you've got nothing!'' I say. ``You can't just start
sprinkling all this stuff in the street and make all these
hurricane spirits go away?''
</P>
<P>
   Bill shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of evil in South Florida,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does that mean?'' I ask. ``You mean, if we get a
hurricane, it's because we deserve it? You're starting to sound
like Pat Robertson.''
</P>
<P>
   I think I've hurt Bill's feelings with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do me a favor, Bill,'' I say, patching things up before
leaving. ``If the spirits start showing up in the clouds, give me a
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I'm going to Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
