<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR to make changes in employee coverages, benefits
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton-based NCR Corp., long considered a
business anomaly with its rich employee benefits program, is
catching up with the times.
</P>
<P>
   Influenced in large part by rising health-care costs, NCR this
week is telling employees and retirees they will be responsible for
part of their health-care costs, starting next year. Among the
changes:
</P>
<P>
   Employees have not had to pay any portion of their health-care
coverage. Starting Jan. 1, individual employees will pay 10 percent
through payroll deduction; employees with dependents will pay for
30 percent of their coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-pocket expenses for generic and brand-name prescription
drugs will go to $10 and $20, up from $5 and $10, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   NCR will cut the number of HMOs to 53, from 70, eliminating HMO
contracts with low enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   The dental deductible for basic and major care (but not
preventive care, which is covered with no deductible) will be
increased to $50 from $20 per individual in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Employees hired on or after Jan. 1 will not longer be offered
retiree medical coverage. Current employees will not have retiree
medical coverage before age 65 unless they meet specific age and
service requirements.
</P>
<P>
   No changes to retiree medical coverage for current retirees age
65 and older were announced.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, NCR spent more than $70 million on medical, dental and
prescription drug benefits for employees and their dependents.
Employers nationally spent more than $262 billion on group health
insurance in 1996, according to the Washington, D.C.-based Employee
Benefits Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, NCR decided to study what similar companies were
doing. ``We found that we're the only company in the technology
industry that was not asking for employee contributions,'' said
spokesman Michael Tarpey. ``Lexis-Nexis, Reynolds &AMP; Reynolds and
Standard Register all ask their employees to contribute to the cost
of medical benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   NCR is making the changes to remain competitive while continuing
to address its employees' needs, Tarpey said, adding that the
company expects to save about $30 million annually with the health
care benefits changes.
</P>
<P>
   Single employees under the NCR Core Plan will contribute on
average $13.25 per month; employees with one dependent, $66 per
month; employees with two or more dependents, $104 per month.
</P>
<P>
   NCR's change in policy follows the trend of companies nationwide
bracing for what they fear will be skyrocketing health-care costs,
said Ken McConnell, a research analyst with EBRI.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Ludwig, secretary/treasurer of the NCR Retiree Assurance
Association, said the changes were not unexpected, especially since
NCR had consulted with employees and retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is fair. Nobody is excited about having to
make contributions to their benefits, but on the other hand, it's
very common,'' said Ludwig, 65, an NCR employee for 42 years before
retiring in 1994. ``NCR for so long had done so much above the
competition and many other companies. Our number one concern is
that the company remain successful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
