<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PAX TV: Poor Nielsen ratings based on bad data
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The first national Nielsen television
ratings for PAX TV came in Tuesday at less than half the network's
estimates, with all its new and rerun prime-time shows rating at
the bottom of the 122-program national list.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson Communications, however, says the numbers don't include
all the households it reaches.
</P>
<P>
   PAX drew an average 0.5 rating for its prime-time programming
for the week of Sept. 14-20, according to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   The number means that half of 1 percent of U.S. homes with TV
sets _ or 529,000 households _ tuned in to the new network.
</P>
<P>
   But West Palm Beach-based Paxson (AMEX: PAX, $9.75), which has
been estimating a 1 to 1.2 average national rating for prime time,
said Nielsen's numbers were incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   The national survey did not count all the areas PAX is serving,
according to Rob Hebenstreit, Paxson vice president of research.
Nielsen's numbers were preliminary and released before Paxson had
verified them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hebenstreit said he had a Nielsen letter in hand that
acknowledged the ratings did not reflect PAX's full coverage. He
would not release the letter, however.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, he said, cited one example of 40 cable systems that
had not been counted in the Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   However, Nielsen spokeswoman Anne Elliot said she was not aware
of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen did not release national numbers for Paxson before this
week because it had difficulty determining where PAX TV was airing,
and when.
</P>
<P>
   Hebenstreit said Paxson wanted the figures released for its
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping that Nielsen's systems were in place,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen measures all networks nightly and weekly, drawing
information from two different groups of metered television sets
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen has been providing overnight ratings of PAX since the
family-oriented network debuted Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   PAX drew a 2.4 overnight rating in the West Palm Beach market
for its first day in existence.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Paxson estimated its ratings at about 1.4
nationally. The latter was an average of the 31 markets Nielsen
measured PAX in, after each market was weighted according to
population.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson has said it needs an average 1 rating 1 percent of
households with televisions over the year to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   All nine of PAX's prime-time shows, including weekend movies,
finished at the bottom of the individual show ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Reruns of Touched by an Angel, Diagnosis Murder and Dr. Quinn,
Medicine Woman finished tied for 114th, with a 0.6 rating. PAX's
original programming was led by Neon Rider, tied for 118th at a 0.4
rating and Flipper: The New Adventures, at 121 with a 0.3 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 rated show for the week was the CBS Sunday night
movie, The Marriage Fool, which drew a 14 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly Nielsen ratings showed that an average 0.3 percent of
people over 2 years old in households with televisions or 738,000
people tuned in to PAX during the week. The percentage of adults 18
to 49 was 0.2, representing 273,000 viewers.
</P>
<P>
   PAX's average prime-time rating of 0.5 percent compared with ABC
at a rating of 8.1; CBS, 7.9; NBC, 7.5; Fox, 6.2; WB, 2.5; and UPN,
1.9.
</P>
<P>
   PAX airs on WPXP-Channel 67 in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson owns, operates or is affiliated with 95 stations in the
nation in markets with more than 76 million TV households.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite M. Plunkett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
