<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cincinnati to become beneficiary of Freedom museum
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Underground Railroad Freedom Center in
Cincinnati will make its public debut this weekend, kicking off a
civil rights lecture series and presenting the first International
Freedom Conductor Award to civil rights crusader Rosa Parks.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ohio celebrates its bicentennial in 2003, the
Freedom Center's planned interactive museum will tell the story of
the Underground Railroad, the clandestine network of abolitionists
who harbored fleeing slaves in pre-Civil War America.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Cincinnati-based center came from the National
Conference for the Community and Justice, formerly the National
Conference of Christians and Jews. The group adopted the
Underground Railroad's timeless civil rights story as a way to
commemorate its 50th anniversary, and is planning the museum as a
way to spread the railroad's message. Construction on the museum is
to begin in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   John Fleming, director of the National Afro-American Museum in
Wilberforce and recently appointed director of the Freedom Center,
said the center will help people understand the contributions of
the Underground Railroad, explain how the secret network ferried
slaves out of the south, and serve as a central clearinghouse of
Underground Railroad information for scholars and preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than showcasing artifacts, the center will take visitors
through the harrowing experience of an escape. Virtual reality
combined with historical accounts of fugitives and those who helped
them will tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not primarily a collecting institution,'' said current
director Ed Ringaud. ``What we're trying to do is become one of the
key partners to the National Park Service on the network.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Congress passed a bill placing Underground Railroad
sites under the protection of the National Park Service. The next
step is to establish the network the bill created and link
Underground Railroad sites to each other and to the Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   While the Freedom Center has no official government ties, it
could help in the effort. The bill's authors, U.S. Reps. Louis
Stokes, D-Cleveland, and Rob Portman, R-Cincinnati, said the
center, working with the National Park Service, would be able to
provide the technological and scholarly resources needed for the
network's base of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ringaud said the museum will have a database of sites and
encourage partons to visit the sites to bring the story to life.
</P>
<P>
   The lecture series and civil rights award help spread the
humanitarian ideals that drove the Underground Railroad and honor
those who still fight for freedom, Ringaud said.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Appeals Judge A. Leon Higginbotham will give the
inaugural lecture on Friday, followed by the presentation of the
International Freedom Conductor Award to Parks on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Higginbotham served as an international mediator for the
1994 elections in South Africa, and was appointed commissioner of
President Clinton's U.S. Commission on Civil Rights in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Parks touched off the contemporary push for civil
rights when she refused to surrender her seat on a Montgomery, Ala.
bus to a white passenger. Her open defiance of the city's Jim Crow
segregation laws sparked a 381-day bus boycott by the city's black
community.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Center will cost an estimated $80 million dollars,
and many local sources have already pledged support, Ringaud said.
Cincinnati will give $6 million and Hamilton County will pay for
the garage-foundation on which the museum will be built.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Center, along with other organizations wanting to
tell the story of the Underground Railroad, could soon be eligible
to share in $24 million from a grant program proposed by U.S. Sen.
Mike DeWine, R-Ohio. The money, added to a federal education bill,
will be distributed over five years to groups dedicated to
educating people about the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations would have to raise 80 percent of their project's
total cost to qualify for the grant. Other government sources could
contribute up to 20 percent of the matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Some preservationists, including Cathy Nelson, state coordinator
the Ohio Underground Railroad Association, said an 80 percent match
is too high for local organizations trying to restore the houses,
roads and other buildings used by the railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a countless number of authentic sites,'' Nelson said.
``I'm not for creating something new. I want to preserve what we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Boesel, a spokesman for DeWine, said the educational
money is just the first step in getting organizations the money
they need to preserve the history of the railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' Boesel said. ``Now that you have
something on the books, it's much easier to go back and get more.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Joyce writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
