<SLUG> BC-WALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recreating history the hard way
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the thousands of slaves who reached Ohio on their way to
freedom in Canada, Anthony Cohen will have traveled almost 800
miles, through forests and rivers, by the time he reaches Dayton,
Ohio on Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, an Underground Railroad historian, is retracing the steps
of slaves who fled to north to freedom in pre-Civil War America.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, 34, left Mobile, Ala., on Sept. 1 and is making his way
to Windsor, Ont. He's due to pass through Oxford, Ohio Nov. 1 and
Dayton Nov. 4, although at this time he has no specific activities
planned to mark his time here.
</P>
<P>
   It's Cohen's second trek along the railroad. In 1996, he
retraced a path from Maryland to Canada. Along the way, he talked
to locals and historians, gathering railroad facts and folklore, as
well as a sense of what it was like to travel such a long distance.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded the last journey in a book due out in February. He
hopes to turn this one into a film documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Zuri Walker, director of Cohen's North Star Foundation, said
Cohen is a marathon runner and is well-prepared for the trip, but
he doesn't have to do it all on foot. He can use any means of
transportation available to fleeing slaves, including boats,
trains, horses and buggies.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who has a B.A. in American Studies from the American
University in Washington, D.C., has advised the National Park
Service on Underground Railroad history. North Star, a non-profit
organization Cohen founded, is devoted to restoring the safe houses
used in the Underground Railroad. North Star is paying for Cohen's
trip through private donations.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Joyce writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
