<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez's HR, steal spark Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A $60 million baseball machine was commandeered by a
reserve catcher with a hero's grin and the gait of a burro. Tuesday
night belonged to Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves mystified by Florida rookie Rafael Medina, who
struck out a career-high eight in seven innings, Perez hit the home
run that determined the game and broke the single-season franchise
record. It was also Perez who stole the first base of his career in
the seventh and then beat one of the best arms in the league to
score a big insurance run.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he had to be refreshed on what the steal sign
was by first-base coach Pat Corrales. Never mind that his homer
cleared the left field wall by the length of his bat. The Braves
beat the Marlins 4-1 on Eddie's night.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking his head, he said, ``I should take off these shoes, put
them in a box and send them right to the Hall of Fame. I should
take the bag with me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' said manager Bobby Cox, ``Eddie was movin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen picked up a pair of two-out RBIs, Michael Tucker
added another and starter Kevin Millwood had enough to win his 17th
game, though he worked just five innings to get it. Millwood
(17-8), destined for the bullpen in the postseason, finished strong
with a third straight victory, allowing only five runs in his last
24 innings (1.88 ERA) while tying Greg Maddux in the victory
column.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that leaves me about 180 wins less than he has in his
career,'' Millwood said. ``I'm even with him right now, but that's
not saying a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen. Amazing,'' said Cox. ``Just amazing. I mean, he's
got the stuff to do it, but it's just amazing your fifth starter
can win that many games in the number of starts he gets (29), which
ain't that many.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's homer in the fifth was the Braves' 208th, breaking the
32-year-old club record. His stolen base in the seventh enabled him
to score the Braves' third run, beating the arm of right fielder
Mark Kotsay, who is tied with Andruw Jones for the major-league
lead with 19 outfield assists. Cox had only allowed Perez to
attempt a steal once in his first 207 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat had to tell me the signal,'' he said. ``Maybe it was the
last chance in my life to get the green light. So I took off, man.
I'm not going to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves bullpen continued its late-season surge with four
scoreless innings and has allowed one earned run in its last 19
innings. Kerry Ligtenberg recorded his 30th save, becoming the
first rookie to reach 30 since Todd Worrell saved 36 for St. Louis
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting to get the numbers I got too,'' said
Ligtenberg, who is unscored on in his last nine appearances. ``When
I got my 15th (on Aug. 1), I was kind of hoping to get to 20 by the
end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
