<HEADLINE>
UP TO 30 DEAD AS SOUTH AFRICAN TROOPS ENTER LESOTHO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for light rewrite with additional information, and to correct
month of elections in 8th graf from August to May)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASERU, Lesotho _ South African troops rolled into this tiny
mountainous kingdom early Tuesday morning to put a quick end to
political turmoil that had brought the government to a standstill.
Instead, the invading force met surprisingly heavy resistance from
Lesotho soldiers who oppose the government. They took to the hills
and brought relentless fire on the South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day perhaps 30 people were dead, including as
many as 10 South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting could be heard near the army barracks northeast of this
city, where the Lesotho soldiers had set fire to the tall grass and
then escaped into the craggy hills nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the South Africans tried to lift their wounded into
helicopters near the base, they came under heavy fire and had to
stop the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the South African soldiers also set off a day of
looting and burning. By early afternoon, every other building
seemed to be on fire and thick plumes of acrid smoke darkened the
streets and rose high above the city. The pavement was littered
with goods the looters had dropped, a brand-new sneaker here, a
pink sofa pillow there. It was clear that no matter what the
outcome of South Africa's action, much of Maseru had been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's action in this country _ a land the size of
Maryland, with a population of 2 million, completely surrounded by
South Africa _ marked the first time that President Nelson
Mandela's government has taken part in military intervention beyond
its borders. Even before the deaths, South Africa's opposition
parties were raising questions about the justification of the
venture in Lesotho (pronounced leh-SOO-too).
</P>
<P>
   Under apartheid, South Africa frequently meddled in its
neighbors' business. But since its first all-race elections in
1994, South Africa had stuck to a policy of looking for negotiated
solutions to Africa's conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   South African officials said they had sent more than 600
soldiers into Lesotho because they were asked to by Prime Minister
Pakalitha Mosisili, who believed a coup was imminent. For weeks the
country had been crippled by protesters who assert that the
country's May elections, won overwhelmingly by the ruling party,
were rigged.
</P>
<P>
   But the presence of South African soldiers here seemed to elicit
nothing but rage among Lesotho citizens. South African-owned
business were singled out for attack and cars with South African
license plates were stoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the way to solve our problems,'' said Mohamed
Yunes, who was standing in front of a building he owns on Kingsway
Street here watching looters breaking windows and setting fires.
``We've never had anything like this before. What are they doing
here? What is their plan? We will all be ruined when they are
through.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's minister for safety and security, Sydney
Mufamadi, said at a news conference in Pretoria that the
intervention, under the auspices of the 14-nation Southern African
Development Community, had been on the drawing board for weeks and
would continue until ``all the parties involved had agreed that
stability had returned.'' Botswana is also supposed to have
supplied troops for the action.
</P>
<P>
   Mufamadi said that six Lesotho soldiers had been killed in the
fighting so far. But later reports counted as many as 17. Army
officials said there had been heavy fighting near the barracks and
the Lesotho dam, which supplies electricity to the country.
</P>
<P>
   At least five civilians have also been reported dead. By
midafternoon, a steady stream of refugees _ mostly foreigners _
could be seen trying to get across the border into South Africa,
their cars crammed with belongings.
</P>
<P>
   A freelance photographer, Greg Marinovich, a Pulitzer Prize
winner, was shot in the leg during the melee, and a South African
Broadcasting Corporation cameraman was also wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Lesotho, an impoverished country that was once a British
protectorate, is greatly dependent on South Africa. The nation had
been in political turmoil since results of elections were contested
by the losing party almost immediately after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Lesotho Congress Party won 79 of 80 Parliament seats.
But a report by a commission of representatives from South Africa,
Botswana and Zimbabwe last week cited ``serious concerns'' about
the voting. It did not however call for new elections. South Africa
has been trying to mediate between the two parties, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the chaos in the country has been intensifying.
Anti-government protesters had been hijacking government vehicles
to use them to block traffic in downtown. And one army general has
been forced to resign at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the opposition party, Vincent Malebo, condemned
South Africa's action as a ``heartless'' attempt by South Africa to
beat Lesotho into submission. He said the military action was
poorly thought out, and had failed to cope with the burning and
looting.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly hours went by when there was looting but little sign
of a South African presence in downtown Maseru. Fires roared
unattended and the heat caused glass windows to explode onto the
sidewalk. Lesotho police officers walked by looters without
uttering a word.
</P>
<P>
   South African soldiers appeared stunned by the resistance they
encountered. On the road leading to the barracks, a dozen South
African armored vehicles seemed to be patrolling without much
purpose, taking heavy fire from many directions. Amidst the fire,
an armored medical unit was treating a half dozen wounded soldiers.
Three others were dead.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wounded soldiers said the Lesotho soldiers had so far
outmaneuvered them. ``They lit all these fires and then they
scattered to the hills,'' the soldier said. ``They are at home in
those hills, we are not. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
