<HEADER>
A9156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-     09-22 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX POUR IT ON DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Very quickly, the opponent changed. The Red Sox went from
worrying about the Devil Rays to worrying about the devilish rain.
One potentially was far more dangerous than the other.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of everything, the Red Sox persevered Tuesday night and
moved a step closer to the playoffs by ripping Tampa Bay, 11-2,
before an underneath-the-overhang assemblage of 20,399 at
rain-swept Fenway Park. The victory dropped Boston's magic number
to 2 for clinching the American league wild-card berth as Toronto
kept pace with a 7-3 victory over the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was a formality after three innings, when Boston
took a 7-0 lead thanks to some truly terrible Tampa Bay pitching in
some truly terrible Boston weather.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, with rain sweeping across the field like a scene
from ``Wuthering Heights,'' the big fear was that the game wouldn't
last the 4 1/2 innings required to make it official. But the
grounds crew kept pounding sand into the pitcher's mound and
infield, the real hard rain never did fall, and the umpiring crew
saw no need to halt play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was pretty harsh,'' said Nomar Garciaparra, who
snapped out of a 2-of-17 skid by going 2 for 3, including his
eighth triple of the season. ``But we've overcome adversity all
year long, and that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The undeniable feel-good story of the night was pitcher Pete
Schourek. In six previous starts, he had pitched well enough to go
0-2 with four no-decisions. Staked to a seven-run lead on a dark
and stormy night against a team going nowhere ... well, he's been
in tougher situations.
</P>
<P>
   He went eight innings, throwing just 91 pitches, an
energy-efficient performance. He yielded a meaningless two-run
homer to Mike Kelly in the fifth and easily could have finished the
game. As it was, his eight innings constituted his longest outing
in almost three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' Schourek said. ``It's a matter of pitch
count for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Added manager Jimy Williams, ``There was no reason for it. We
have a pitch count and he has been through operations before, so
you want to be careful. Why risk it?''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Boston offense, it came, like voting in Chicago,
early and often. The Red Sox picked up three runs in the second off
starter and loser Julio Santana, who added to his impressive
September numbers (0-4, 9.00 ERA) by getting behind virtually every
hitter after a seamless first.
</P>
<P>
   Santana was cuffed for six runs in 2 1/3 innings. In the second,
Darren Bragg snapped an 0-for-9 streak with a two-run double and
eventually scored on a Scott Hatteberg sacrifice fly. Mo Vaughn
knocked in two runs in the third when his single (which easily
could have been scored an error) bounced off first baseman Fred
McGriff and scored Darren Lewis, who had singled, and John
Valentin, who had collected his 44th double of the season. Vaughn's
single extended his hitting streak to 11 games, a season high.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Santana, but his replacement, nano-Red Sox
pitcher Brad Pennington (1996), was even worse. Pennington had just
been called up from Durham Monday; he should have stayed where he
was.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington walked three straight batters, then surrendered an
RBI single to Hatteberg. Mercifully, he was replaced by rookie Mike
Duvall, who can tell his grandchildren that he got Mike Benjamin to
hit into a double play in his very first major league appearance.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, it became a race against the elements. The start
of the game was delayed 29 minutes and the weather worsened in the
middle innings. The umpiring crew said afterward that they almost
stopped play on a couple of occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about it,'' Williams said. ``That's why you
have tarps.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the rain, there was a 17 mile-per-hour wind
blowing all over the place and a temperature of 65 degrees that was
forecast to drop as the night wore on. In other words, there aren't
many more unpleasant conditions under which to play baseball. Or
rugby.
</P>
<P>
   The ridiculousness of the situation was driven home, so to
speak, in the fifth. Tampa Bay second baseman Miguel Cairo lost a
popup in the rain and wind, and two runs scored on what should have
been an easy, inning-ending out. Those two runs made it 10-2 after
five innings, which already seemed like more than long enough, both
in production and endurance. Things quieted down after that, both
in the sky and on the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-98 2359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
